nodes.title: Borgo Medievale
nodes.description: The post-Roman settlement at Alba Fucens became an administrative center ca. A.D. 870 and remained significant as a center in Marsica until ca. 1143. The area was later subsumed by the Duchy of Spoleto.

nodes.title: Tempio Grande at Vulci
nodes.description: A major urban sanctuary at Vulci with a long period of use, stretching from the archaic period into the Roman period.

nodes.title: Consabura/Consabrum
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, likely of Celtic origin, located near Consuegra south of Toledo.

nodes.title: Contestania (region)
nodes.description: Contestania was a region located in the southwest of Hispania Tarraconensis.

nodes.title: Dianium/Hemeroskopeion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 F3 Dianium/Hemeroskopeion

nodes.title: Ebusus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 G3 Ebusus

nodes.title: Ebusus (island)
nodes.description: Ebusus Ins. (modern Ibiza) is an island in the western Mediterranean Sea.

nodes.title: Edeta/Leiria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 E2 Edeta/Leiria

nodes.title: Edetania (region)
nodes.description: Edetania was a region located between the rivers Iberus (Ebro) and Sucro (Iucar). To the west, it was bounded by the mountains of Celtiberia.

nodes.title: Guium?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 inset Guium?

nodes.title: Iamo/Iamna
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 inset Iamo/Iamna

nodes.title: Ildum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 F1 Ildum

nodes.title: Ilici/Helike
nodes.description: The site of Ilici began as a pre-Roman settlement that eventually developed into a Roman municipium. The site continued into the Visigothic and Byzantine periods as a minor urban settlement, controlling a vast territory which reached old Lucentum. The settlement was relocated to the modern site of Elche in the Islamic period.

nodes.title: Iliturgi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 B4 Iliturgi

nodes.title: Isturgi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 A3 Isturgi

nodes.title: Jumilla
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of southeastern Spain, whose ancient name is not known today. Occupation of the area seems to stretch from the bronze age up to modern times.

nodes.title: Libisosa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 C3 Libisosa

nodes.title: Lobetanoi
nodes.description: The Lobetanoi were a pre-Roman tribe of Iberia mentioned only once by Ptolemy. Their homeland is thought to have been located in the mountainous area near Albarracín in the southwest Province of Teruel.

nodes.title: Mago
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 inset Mago

nodes.title: Malaca
nodes.description: A Roman city of Baetica that was perhaps founded by the Carthaginians in the fifth century BC.

nodes.title: Marianus (mountain range)
nodes.description: The modern Sierra Morena mountain range in Spain.

nodes.title: Mentesa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 C3 Mentesa

nodes.title: Olcades?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 A2 Olcades?

nodes.title: Oretana Iuga
nodes.description: The Sierra Morena mountain range.

nodes.title: Oretania/Oretani
nodes.description: A pre-Roman ancient Iberian or Celtic tribe in Extremadura, La Mancha, eastern Andalusia and Murcia. Oretania is a regional name, which associated the area with the ancient people.

nodes.title: Oretum
nodes.description: Oretum was a tributary city of the Oretani that was a part of the conventus of Carthago Nova, according to Pliny the Elder.

nodes.title: Palma
nodes.description: The site of Palma, on the island of Majorca, experienced multiple phases of settlement from Talaiotic to Roman.

nodes.title: Pityussae (islands)
nodes.description: Pityussae Inss., an ancient island group comprised of the islands of Ebusus and Ophiussa.

nodes.title: Pollentia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 inset Pollentia

nodes.title: Saetabis
nodes.description: Saetabis was a town of the Contestani in Hispania Tarraconensis.

nodes.title: Saguntum/Arse
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 E2 Saguntum/Arse

nodes.title: Saltigi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 D3 Saltigi

nodes.title: Sanisera
nodes.description: Sanisera was a Roman settlement of Menorca.

nodes.title: Segobriga
nodes.description: Segobriga was an Ibero-Roman city.

nodes.title: Sexi/Saxetanum
nodes.description: Sexi/Saxetanum (modern Almuñécar) was a Phoenician colony established ca. 800 BC that eventually became a Roman one (Sexi Firmum Iulium).

nodes.title: Sierra de Gádor
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 C5 Sierra de Gádor

nodes.title: Sisapo?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 A3 Sisapo?

nodes.title: Sucro
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 E2 Sucro

nodes.title: Sucro (river)
nodes.description: The Júcar river flows 509 km from its source at Ojuelos de Valdeminguete to the Gulf of Valencia.

nodes.title: Sucronensis Sinus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 E2 Sucronensis Sinus

nodes.title: Suel
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 A5 Suel

nodes.title: Thiar
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 E4 Thiar

nodes.title: Toletum
nodes.description: Ancient Toletum, located on the Tagus river, was the main settlement of the Carpetani. The Romans captured the city in 193 B.C. In 507, Toletum became the capital of the Visigothic Kingdom and in 711 it fell to Muslim invaders. Alfonso VI of León and Castile recaptured the city in 1085.

nodes.title: *Tuci?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 inset *Tuci?

nodes.title: Turdetania (region)
nodes.description: Turdetania was a region located between the Guadiana and the Guadalquivir rivers.

nodes.title: Turia (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 E2 Turia fl.

nodes.title: Valentia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 E2 Valentia

nodes.title: Vergilia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 B4 Vergilia

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 B2 unnamed aqueduct (N Consabura)

nodes.title: Torrecuevas aqueduct
nodes.description: One of five Roman-era aqueducts known from Sexi (modern Almuñécar, Spain). This one is represented by an extant aqueduct bridge located near the source of the Rio Verde, north of Sexi.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 C2 unnamed aqueduct (Segobriga)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 C5 unnamed aqueduct (Rambla de Carcanz, N Sierra de Gador)

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge at Isturgi on the Guadalquivir river
nodes.description: Its ancient name is unknown.

nodes.title: Unnamed Bridge
nodes.description: This archaeologically attested Roman bridge was located east of Salaria on the Guadalquivir river.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Carthago Nova → Acci → Vergilia → Castulo

nodes.description: Carthago Nova → Suel → Map 26

nodes.description: E Segobriga → N to Segontia (Map 25)

nodes.description: Toletum → Caesarobriga → Map 26

nodes.title: Althaia/Cartala
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Istonion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 unlocated Istonion

nodes.title: Libana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 unlocated Libana

nodes.title: Lobeton
nodes.description: A now unlocated site that was the center of the Lobetani in ancient Iberia.

nodes.title: Mastia/Massia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 unlocated Mastia/Massia

nodes.title: Mediolon
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 unlocated Mediolon

nodes.title: Ouarada/Varciliens(...)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 unlocated Ouarada/Varciliens(...)

nodes.title: Ourkesa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 unlocated Ourkesa

nodes.title: Salduba
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Abila M.
nodes.description: A low mountain overlooking the port of Ceuta in North Africa.

nodes.title: Columnae Herculis
nodes.description: The Columnae Herculis (Pillars of Hercules) are the twin promontories that flank the Straits of Gibraltar, namely the rock of Gibraltar on the northern side and a debated southern promontory, likely either Monte Hacho (the ancient Abila Mons) or the Jebel Musa.

nodes.title: Laud (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 28 D3 Laud fl.

nodes.title: Lixus
nodes.description: Lixus was an ancient settlement of Mauretania Tingitana.

nodes.title: Lixus (river)
nodes.description: Lixus fl. (Loukkos River) is a major river of northern Morocco.

nodes.title: Mauretania Tingitana (region)
nodes.description: An ancient region of northwest Africa.

nodes.title: Sala
nodes.description: Sala (modern Chellah, Morocco) was the site of Phoenician and Carthaginian settlement before receiving a Roman colony, Sala Colonia.

nodes.title: Salat (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 28 A5 Salat fl.

nodes.title: Septem
nodes.description: Now the Spanish exclave of Ceuta, Septem is an ancient port whose phases are not entirely clear owing to modern overburden. The city was the seat of a bishopric in the Byzantine period and was the last of Morocco's cities to recognize the authority of the emperor at the time of the Arab conquest.

nodes.title: Septem Fratres Montes
nodes.description: The northern peaks of Jebel Musa, a mountain on the African side of the Strait of Gibraltar that is usually identified as the southern Pillar of Hercules. They share toponomy with, and lie to the west of, the ancient settlement of Septem (modern Ceuta).

nodes.title: Taenia Longa?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 28 D3 Taenia Longa?

nodes.title: Tremuli
nodes.description: A road station mentioned on the Antonine Itinerary (24.1) that was located on the Roman road leading from Tingi to Volubilis.

nodes.title: Volubilis
nodes.description: A town of Mauretania Tingitana and a Roman colony.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: A rural settlement near Tremuli.

nodes.title: Mauretania Caesariensis
nodes.description: Mauretania Caesariensis was the easternmost of the North African Roman provinces, with its capital located at Caesarea (now Cherchell).

nodes.title: Mulucha?/Malva? (river)
nodes.description: The Moulouya River is a river of North Africa that flows from the Atlas Mountains to the Mediterranean Sea.

nodes.title: Portus Sigensis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 29 D1 Portus Sigensis

nodes.title: Siga (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 29 D1 Siga fl.

nodes.title: Assyria (kingdom)
nodes.description: Aššur, later Māt Aššur ('the land of the god Aššur'), grew from a small city-state and important trading center to a powerful, wide-spread empire. At is zenith in the seventh century BC, the Assyrian Empire (883-609 BC) dominated much of the Middle East and the Eastern Mediterranean, stretching from the Persian Gulf in the south to the Mediterranean Sea in the west. Assyria's heartland, an area also referred to as Subartu, roughly corresponds to northern Iraq (Nineveh Governorate) and includes the numerous important cities, especially Aššur (Assyria's traditional religious and administrative capital), Kalhu, Dur-Šarrukin, and Nineveh (the capital of the Assyrian Empire).

nodes.title: Carmania
nodes.description: A province of both the Achaemenid Empire and the Sassanid Empire.

nodes.title: Castellum Tingitanum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 30 B4 Castellum Tingitanum

nodes.title: Iol Caesarea
nodes.description: Iol Caesarea (modern Cherchell, Algeria) is a seaport with Punic and Roman phases.

nodes.title: Nabar? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 30 F3 Nabar? fl.

nodes.title: Tipasa
nodes.description: Tipasa was an ancient Punic trading-post conquered by Rome and turned into a strategic base for the conquest of the kingdoms of Mauritania.

nodes.title: Zucchabar
nodes.description: Zucchabar was an ancient city of Mauretania Caesariensis with Punic origins. The modern Algerian community of Miliana lies atop and around the largely unexcavated ancient site. Epigraphic evidence indicates that the Roman emperor Augustus established a veteran colony there.

nodes.title: Gedrosia
nodes.description: Gedrosia was a mountainous region covering parts of what is today southeastern Iran and southwestern Pakistan.

nodes.title: Aqueduct at Castellum Tingitanum
nodes.description: Its ancient name is unknown.

nodes.title: Kalon Oros
nodes.description: The Kalon Oros is mentioned in the Periplus Maris Erythraei and has been identified by modern scholars with the modern Jebel Akhdar in Oman.

nodes.title: Kish
nodes.description: Kish is an island in the Persian Gulf.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 30 F3 unnamed bridge (S Rusguniae (2): el Kounitra and Oued el Hamiz)

nodes.title: Nabataea (region)
nodes.description: Nabataea was an ancient region of Arabia inhabited by the Nabataeans. This region covers parts of northern Arabia and the Southern Levant, lying between Arabia and Syria, and stretching from the Euphrates river to the Red Sea.

nodes.title: Persicus Sinus/Erythr(ae)um Mare
nodes.description: The Persian Gulf is located in Western Asia between Persia and the Arabian Peninsula.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 30 B4 no. 4 (N Castellum Tingitanum)

nodes.title: Zagrus M.
nodes.description: The Zagros Mountains.

nodes.title: Alexandria in Carmania
nodes.description: A now unlocated city that was founded by Alexander the Great, perhaps in 324 B.C.

nodes.title: Anamis/Andanis/Ananis (river)
nodes.description: Anamis/An(d)anis fl. was a river located in Carmania.

nodes.title: Aradarum/Hardea/Ardea
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 unlocated Aradarum/(H)Ardea

nodes.title: Arai
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

nodes.title: Archedotis/Arciotis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 unlocated Archedotis/Arciotis

nodes.title: Badis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 unlocated Badis

nodes.title: Caumatis/Kanate/Kanthatis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 unlocated Caumatis/Kanate/Kanthatis

nodes.title: Charadrai
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

nodes.title: Kophanta/Kophas
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 unlocated Kophanta/Kophas

nodes.title: Kophanta
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 unlocated Kophanta (1)

nodes.title: Parsika (mountain)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 unlocated Parsika M.

nodes.title: Portospana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 unlocated Portospana

nodes.title: Salmous
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 unlocated Salmous

nodes.title: Semiramis (mountain)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 unlocated Semiramis M.

nodes.title: Soxotai
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

nodes.title: Zetis
nodes.description: Zetis was an ancient city of Carmania, although its location can no longer be determined.

nodes.title: Cemetery at Ain bou Merzoug
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 F4 Ain bou Merzoug

nodes.title: Abbeyknockmoy abbey
nodes.description: A ruined Medieval Cistercian abbey founded in 1190.

nodes.title: Kercado tumulus
nodes.description: A dolmen that is still covered by its original cairn, the Kercado tumulus was built ca. 4600 B.C. and remained in use for approximately 3,000 years.

nodes.title: Alignements du Manio
nodes.description: An alignment of menhirs that form a rectangular area.

nodes.title: Sarvestan Palace
nodes.description: The Sassanid Palace at Sarvestan is an elite building of the fifth century A.D. It is located approximately 90 km southeast of Shiraz.

nodes.title: Investiture relief of Ardashir I
nodes.description: A rock-cut relief depicting the investiture of Ardashir I, ca. A.D. 226-242. This relief is the earliest Sasanian monument at Naqš-e Rustam.

nodes.title: Termas romanas de Santa María
nodes.description: Remains of Roman baths at Antequera in Spain.

nodes.title: Termas romanas de las Bóvedas
nodes.description: The Roman Baths of Las Bóvedas are near the mouth of the Guadalmina River.

nodes.title: Hochdorf Chieftain's Grave
nodes.description: Tumulus covering a rich Celtic burial of ca. 530 BC.

nodes.title: Silver Mine at Thorikos
nodes.description: A silver mine at Thorikos. A schematic map of the mine is carved into the rocks at the site.

nodes.title: Church of San Primitivo
nodes.description: The so-called Church of San Primitivo in Monte Compatri. The church's bell tower was converted to a defensive tower around 1200.

nodes.title: Fonte dell'Acqua Paola
nodes.description: The Fontana dell'Acqua Paola or Il Fontanone stands on the Ianiculum near the church of San Pietro in Montorio. It was built in 1612 to mark the end of the Acqua Paola aqueduct after it had been restored by Pope Paul V.

nodes.title: Bagras Castle
nodes.description: Bagras Castle is located in Turkey's İskenderun district in the Amanus Mountains. The tenth-century castle was rebuilt in the twelfth century.

nodes.title: Za'ini
nodes.description: Za'ini is a (walled?) city in Gurgum that is mentioned in inscriptions of the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC). Its current location is unknown.

nodes.title: Theater of Zeugma
nodes.description: The remains of the ancient theater at Zeugma

nodes.title: Anduarsalia
nodes.description: A fortress in the vicinity of Til-garimmu fortified by the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) against Urarṭu.

nodes.title: Luhsu
nodes.description: A fortress in the vicinity of Til-garimmu fortified by the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) against Urarṭu.

nodes.title: Abusir Pharos tomb
nodes.description: A tomb that seems to imitate the famous lighthouse of Alexandria.

nodes.title: Gurgum (kingdom)
nodes.description: The Neo-Hittite kingdom of Gurgum (Hittite Karkuma, Luwian Kurkuma, Aramaic grgm) was located north of the Amanus mountains. Gurgum, whose capital was Marqasi (modern Maraş), is known from Akkadian, Aramaic, Hittite, and Luwian sources.

nodes.title: Marqasi (province)
nodes.description: Gurgum (kingdom) became an Assyrian province after Sargon II captured its capital Marqasi in 711 BC.

nodes.title: Tabālu (province)
nodes.description: In 713 BC, Tabal (together with the reigion Bit-Purutaš) was conquered by the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) and established as an Assyrian province. However, by 711 BC, Assyria lost control over the region of Tabālu.

nodes.title: Sam'alla (province)
nodes.description: The eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Shalmaneser V (r. 726-722 BC) conquered Sam'al and its territory and established the city as the administrative capital of an Assyrian province named after it.

nodes.title: Paqarhubuni (region)
nodes.description: Paqarhubuni is a region between the kingdoms of Gurgum and Kummuhu, possibly in the vicinity of modern Gaziantep or Kızkapanlı.

nodes.title: Carnac megaliths
nodes.description: Carnac (Breton: Karnag) is a site in southern Brittany known for the so-called Carnac stones, a massive complex of Neolithic menhir stones.

nodes.title: Poulnabrone dolmen
nodes.description: The Poulnabrone dolmen is a portal tomb in County Clare, Ireland, dating between 4200 and 2900 BC.

nodes.title: Capocorb Vell
nodes.description: At Capocorb Vell are the remains of a Talaiotic settlement dating to the later second millennium BC.

nodes.title: Noarus (river)
nodes.description: The Noarus was a river in the territory of the Scordisci.

nodes.title: Tuscan Archipelago
nodes.description: A chain of islands between the Ligurian Sea and Tyrrhenian Sea.

nodes.title: Beitin
nodes.description: A settlement which originally dates to the Chalcolithic period.

nodes.title: Monte Nuxi
nodes.description: A proto-nuragic settlement on Monte Nuxi that covered approximately one hectare. The remains of various built springs are evident.

nodes.title: Pecile at Hadrian's Villa
nodes.description: An artificial terrace surrounding a large pond, 30 m wide x 116 m long, located at the western end of Villa Adriana.

nodes.title: Kasta tomb
nodes.description: A tumulus of Macedonian or Roman date located in the hinterland of Amphipolis. The tomb was discovered in 2012 and first entered in 2014.

nodes.title: Sepulcrum Hirtii
nodes.description: The tomb of Aulus Hirtius, consul in 43 B.C., was discovered beneath the northwest corner of the Palazzo della Cancelleria in Rome in 1938.

nodes.title: Curiae Veteres
nodes.description: The earliest sanctuary of the curiae at Rome, located at the northeastern corner of the Palatine Hill. Tacitus identifies the structure as one point of the Palatine pomerium.

nodes.title: Gazandži (Kazana)
nodes.description: Gazandži is a village at the Turkish-Armenian border location south of Armavir, on the right bank of the river Arasse, approximately 9 km northeast of Iğdir. Here a cylindrical stone with a building inscription of the Urartian king Argišti I., son of Minua (8th century BCE) was found.

nodes.title: Potter's workshop
nodes.description: Shop no. 29 located in the commercial area along the via dei Sepolcri outside the Porta Ercolano at the northwest corner of Pompeii. Archaeological excavation in 2012 and 2013 undertaken by the École française de Rome in coordination with Ministero per i Beni e le attività cultural demonstrated that, at the time of its destruction, the shop was occupied by a potter.

nodes.title: Castellammare della Bruca
nodes.description: A fortified medieval settlement that succeeds the acropolis of ancient Velia.

nodes.title: West House at Vasiliki
nodes.description: The West House is an architectural complex built as an annex to a large building, the Red House, in an Early Minoan settlement at Vasiliki on Crete.

nodes.title: Grave Circle B
nodes.description: Grave Circle B is a burial complex of shaft and cist graves located 130 meters west of the Lion Gate at Mycenae. It was used for the burials of elite families between approximately 1625 and 1550 BC.

nodes.title: Portara on Naxos
nodes.description: The Portara is the 26-foot-tall doorway of an unfinished Ionic temple of the Late Archaic Period on the island of Naxos.

nodes.title: Çatalhöyük
nodes.description: A Neolithic and Chalcolithic settlement of southern Anatolia, inabited ca. 7500 B.C. to 5700 B.C. In July 2012, it was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

nodes.title: Unnamed Place
nodes.description: An unnamed ancient place

nodes.title: Koukonesi
nodes.description: Koukonesi (or Koukonisi) is a small, coastal island in the Moudros harbour of Lemnos where important archaeological evidence for Bronze Age commerce has been discovered.

nodes.title: Esterzili
nodes.description: The Domu de Orgia at Esterzili is the largest nuragic "megaron" structure thus far discovered in Sardinia.

nodes.title: So-called Oratory of Phalaris
nodes.description: A small, rectangular Greek temple-type building dated to the first century B.C. and located in the upper agora of Agrigento, on the Poggetto di San Nicola. The name "Oratory" comes from its later use as a Christian chapel.

nodes.title: Iberia (modern region/peninsula)
nodes.description: The Iberian Peninsula, the westernmost portion of the continent of Europe, bounded in the northeast by the Pyrenees Mountains, in the east and south by the Mediterranean Sea, the west by the Atlantic Ocean, and the north by the Bay of Biscay.

nodes.title: Theater of Zea
nodes.description: Visible remains of a Hellenistic theater located to the west of the Zea Harbor in Piraeus, dating ca. 200 B.C.

nodes.title: Tower of the Winds
nodes.description: Also known as the Horologion of Andronikos Kyrrhestes, the Tower of the Winds is an octagonal Pentelic marble clocktower located in the "Roman" Agora that functioned as a horologion.

nodes.title: Theatrum Marcelli
nodes.description: Theatrum Marcelli (Theater of Marcellus) is an ancient Roman theater in the Circus Flaminius. Augustus completed its construction and dedicated it in 12 BC.

nodes.title: Santi Giovanni e Paolo
nodes.description: An ancient Christian basilica on the Caelian Hill in Rome that was built in AD 398 by will of a senator known as Pammachius. The basilica was located over the home of two Roman soldiers, John and Paul, who had been martyred under Julian in AD 362. The church was thus called the Titulus Pammachii.

nodes.title: Clivus Scauri
nodes.description: A street that ascended from the depression between the Palatine and the Caelian hills.

nodes.title: Case Romane del Celio
nodes.description: An archaeological area beneath the basilica of the martyrs John and Paul that has been explored by means of excavation, revealing a series of Imperial period domestic remains dating between the second and fourth centuries A.D.

nodes.title: Basilica of San Clemente al Laterano
nodes.description: The eleventh-century Basilica of San Clemente al Laterano is a Roman Catholic basilica dedicated to Clement I. It sits atop a three-tiered series of architectural remains stretching back to the Republican period. The earliest phase is represented by the foundations of a building destroyed by the fire of A.D. 64.

nodes.title: Mont'e Prama
nodes.description: A locality near Cabras, Sardinia, where, in 1974, the cache of monumental prehistoric stone sculptures known as the "Giants of Mont'e Prama" was discovered.

nodes.title: Kirkbride
nodes.description: A Roman fort at Bowness on Solway on the Stanegate.

nodes.title: Agora of Corinth
nodes.description: The Agora of ancient Corinth.

nodes.title: Tagisken Plateau
nodes.description: A plateau in modern Uzbekistan near the Aral Sea containing two burial sites dating to the first millennium BCE.

nodes.title: Roman arch at Capera
nodes.description: A quadrifons arch at Capera.

nodes.title: Mithraeum at Vindovala
nodes.description: A temple sacred to Mithras located at the Roman fort of Vindovala (Rudchester) on Hadrian's Wall.

nodes.title: Via Amerina
nodes.description: A Roman road begun ca. 241 B.C. that connected Veii and Ameria.

nodes.title: Janiculum
nodes.description: This hill is located outside of the ancient city of Rome to the west of the Tiber and is not considered one of the Seven Hills of Rome. From an early stage the Janiculum was connected to the city by fortifications and a bridge over the Tiber. It also was the site of important water-powered mills in the Roman Empire.

nodes.title: Piazza d'Oro at Hadrian's Villa
nodes.description: One of the largest and most luxurious complexes of Villa Hadriani. It is situated at the northern end of the Villa, and consists of a vast building, with a vaulted, octagonal vestibule to the north, a cenatio to the south, and a central quadriporticus, down the middle of which runs a canal.

nodes.title: Proposed location of Artulu 2 (Kayseri)
nodes.description: Another proposed location of ancient Artulu is at or in the vicinity of modern Kayseri.

nodes.title: Garden and Pool Complex at Petra
nodes.description: Garden terrace and monumental pool with island pavilion dates to the Nabataean/Early Roman periods, 9 BCE-c. 200 CE. Formerly called the "Lower Market."

nodes.title: Temple of Claudius
nodes.description: A large classical-style Roman temple built shortly after the conquest of Britannia in A.D. 43 by the emperor Claudius. Its remains lie beneath Colchester Castle.

nodes.title: Feliginates
nodes.description: An ancient people of Umbria whose territory is now unlocated.

nodes.title: Mausoleum of Clesippus Geganius
nodes.description: The ruins of a first century B.C. Roman tomb along the Via Appia at Mesa di Pontinia.

nodes.title: Subura
nodes.description: Subura (or Suburra) refers to an area of ancient Rome, although the precise spatial definition of this area is unclear. In the earliest instances, this toponym may refer to the valley lying between the Oppian and the Caelian. As such it corresponds to one of the four urban regions known as the "Servian" regions. In later times the Subura referred to a part of the Augustan regio IV which was known as a densely populated area between the Esquiline, Quirinal, Viminal, and Cispian hills and had a rough and seedy reputation.

nodes.title: Via Olevano Romano columbarium
nodes.description: A late republican to early imperial columbarium along the Via Praenestina. The columbarium is of rectangular plan and was last used during the early Flavian period.

nodes.title: Mausoleo della Conocchia
nodes.description: A Roman mausoleum dating most likely to the second century.

nodes.title: Phylakopi
nodes.description: A major Bronze Age settlement on Melos with evidence for continuous occupation from the third millennium BC until the twelfth century BC, Phylakopi provides important information about the Cycladic civilization.

nodes.title: Temple of Castor and Pollux, Cora
nodes.description: The Temple of Castor and Pollux at Cora was originally built between the fourth and the second centuries B.C. The partially extant architrave carries an inscription of the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Abu Ballas Trail
nodes.description: Caravan route connecting the Dakhleh Oasis with Gilf Kebir in the Libyan Desert, used from the third millennium BCE through the Roman period. The site of Abu Ballas was likely a way station along the road.

nodes.title: Theatrum Pompei
nodes.description: Rome's first permanent theater, located in the Campus Martius. The complex was completed under the second consulship of Pompeius Magnus in 55 B.C.

nodes.title: Zou
nodes.description: At Zou are the remains of a palatial building of the Minoan period, built during MM IIIB.

nodes.title: Maroni
nodes.description: At Maroni Vournes in southern Cyprus, the remains of a large ashlar building of the thirteenth century BC have been excavated.

nodes.title: Pass of the Alpes Graiae
nodes.description: A pass west of Segusio

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Burdigala → Lugdunum (Map 17)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Divona → S

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Divona → Segodunum → SE

nodes.title: Fexitoialum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 unlocated Fexitoialum

nodes.title: Primuliacum
nodes.description: Now unlocated, Primuliacum was located in southwestern Gaul.

nodes.title: Agatha
nodes.description: Agatha (modern Agde), also known as Agatha Tyche, was a colonial foundation of ca. 525 B.C. The colony was founded by Phocaean Greeks from Massilia.

nodes.title: Ambrussum
nodes.description: A Pre-Roman and Gallo-Roman oppidum located along the Roman Via Domitia.

nodes.title: Andusia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 B1 Andusia

nodes.title: Apta Iulia
nodes.description: Once the most important town of the Gallic Vulgientes, Romans destroyed the site ca. 125 BC and Iulius Caesar re-founded it as Apta Iulia.

nodes.title: Arauris (river)
nodes.description: The ancient Hérault River

nodes.title: Blasco Ins.
nodes.description: Blasco Ins. is a small, volcanic island located close to the Cap d'Agde.

nodes.title: Cabellio
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 E2 Cabellio

nodes.title: Canteduc Roman Quarry
nodes.description: A limestone quarry at Nîmes that is often referred to by the name of the hill into which it was cut. It is located just west of the Temple of Diana and north of the terminus of the Rue de la Càrriere Romaine. Modern structures have been built in and around the quarry and access is gated, but some of the excavated cliff faces are still visible from the terminus of the Rue du Rempart Romain.

nodes.title: Carpentorate/*Forum Neronis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 E1 Carpentorate/*Forum Neronis

nodes.title: Col. Arausio
nodes.description: Founded as Colonia Julia Firma Secundanorum Arausio in 35 B.C.

nodes.title: Col. Baeterrae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 A3 Col. Baeterrae

nodes.title: Druentia (river)
nodes.description: Called the Durance (French), a tributary of the Rhone.

nodes.title: Estel Roman Quarry
nodes.description: A limestone quarry from which was sourced the stone used in the construction of the Pont du Gard. The quarry was excavated in the late 1990s and early 2000s on a site 600-700 meters northeast of the aqueduct bridge.

nodes.title: Forum Domitii
nodes.description: Forum Domitii was a market created prior to the foundation of Narbonne along the Via Domitia.

nodes.title: Gallicum Mare
nodes.description: The Gulf of Lion, or Sinus Gallicus.

nodes.title: Gaujac
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 D1 Gaujac

nodes.title: Glanum
nodes.description: Glanum was a Celtic oppidum that became a Roman city; it was eventually abandoned in the third century AD.

nodes.title: Lattara
nodes.description: A walled port city inhabited by Gauls, Etruscans, and Massalian Greeks.

nodes.title: Ledus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 B2 Ledus fl.

nodes.title: Lunel-Viel
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 C2 Lunel-Viel

nodes.title: Metapinum? Ostium
nodes.description: Metapinum? Ostium, the mouth of the Rhone river.

nodes.title: Nemausus
nodes.description: Nemausus (modern Nîmes) was the ancient capital of the Volcae Arecomici and later a Roman colony.

nodes.title: Rhodanousia
nodes.description: An important pre-Roman and Roman settlement along the western reaches of the Rhône river.

nodes.title: Rhodanus (river)
nodes.description: The river now known as the Rhône is the second longest river in Gaul.

nodes.title: Sextantio
nodes.description: Sextantio was a Celtic settlement at a ford on the Ledus fl. and later became a Gallo-Roman town.

nodes.title: Tarusco
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 D2 Tarusco

nodes.title: Taurus/Volcarum Stagna
nodes.description: The coastal lagoons of Languedoc

nodes.title: Theline/Col. Arelate/Constantina
nodes.description: An ancient settlement located at modern Arles in France.

nodes.title: Ucetia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 C1 Ucetia

nodes.title: Ugernum
nodes.description: Ugernum was a waypoint on the Via Domitia located on the right bank of the Rhodanus fl.

nodes.title: Ura Fons
nodes.description: The Ura Fons was a source of water for ancient Nemausus.

nodes.title: Vasio
nodes.description: Vasio (modern Vaison-la-Romaine) was the civitas capital of the Vocontii and eventually received Roman status by the late first century BC.

nodes.title: Vindalium?
nodes.description: Vindalium? is a site in Gallia Narbonensis where Domitius Ahenobarbus defeated the Allobroges (121 BC).

nodes.title: Vocontii
nodes.description: The Vocontii were a Gallic people living to the east of the Rhone river.

nodes.title: Volcae Arecomici
nodes.description: A Gallic people of the Languedoc. Their chief town was Nemausus.

nodes.title: Vulgientes
nodes.description: The Vulgientes were a Celtic people in Gallia Narbonensis.

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct at Baeterrae
nodes.description: An aqueduct supplying Baeterrae from the north.

nodes.title: Nîmes aqueduct
nodes.description: Supplied Nemausus with water from the mid-first to sixth centuries AD.

nodes.title: Pont d'Ambroix
nodes.description: A bridge over the Vidourle and road station on the Via Domitia.

nodes.title: Pont du Gard
nodes.description: The Pont du Gard is an ancient Roman aqueduct bridge that crosses the Gardon River near the town of Vers-Pont-du-Gard in the south of France. It was enrolled as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1985.

nodes.title: Pont Flavien
nodes.description: A Roman bridge that carries the Via Julia Augusta across the Touloubre river.

nodes.title: Pont Julien
nodes.description: A bridge that spans the river known as the Cavalon (French), once part of the Via Domitia

nodes.title: Centuriation around Baeterrae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 A3 unnamed centuriation (around Col. Baeterrae)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 A3 unnamed centuriation (around Agatha)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 C2 unnamed centuriation (around Rhodanousia (St-Gilles))

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 D1 unnamed centuriation (around Col. Arausio, Vasio and Carpentorate (Orange B))

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 D2 unnamed centuriation (around Col. Arelate (Orange C))

nodes.title: Alaunium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 A2 Alaunium

nodes.title: Alb(i)um Intimilium/Albintimilium
nodes.description: Alb(i)um Intimilium/Albintimilium (modern Ventimiglia) was the main settlement of the Ligurian tribe of the Intemelii. In the 2nd century BC it came under control of the Roman Republic. Albintimilium became a municipium in 89 BC in the tribus Falerna. In the same period the city walls were built, with several towers. The city flourished in the early Imperial period, with baths, an acqueduct and a theater. In the 6th and early 7th century it was a Byzantine kastron, coming under control of the Longobards in 641. During the 7th and 8th century the Roman city was slowly abandoned in favour of a smaller hilltop settlement focused around the Cathedral.

nodes.title: Album Ingaunum/Albingaunum
nodes.description: The fourth century B.C. capital of the Ingauni Ligures sided with Carthage during the Punic War but was reduced by Lucius Aemilius Paullus Macedonicus in 181 B.C. A treaty was struck with Rome; the city received Roman citizenship in 45 B.C.

nodes.title: Alebaece Reiorum Apollinarium/Apollinaris Reiorum/Reii
nodes.description: Alebaece Reiorum Apollinarium/Apollinaris Reiorum/Reii was the capital of the tribe of the Reii.

nodes.title: Cemenelum
nodes.description: An oppidum that was the capital of the Vediantian Ligures; later became a municipium of the tribus Claudia.

nodes.title: Col. Forum Iulii
nodes.description: Col. Forum Iulii (modern Fréjus) was a Roman military colony, most likely founded by Iulius Caesar, that served as a major naval base.

nodes.title: Costa Bellene/Ballene (Capo Don?)
nodes.description: A Roman mansio on the via Iulia Augusta. An Early Christian complex (basilica, baptistery, cemetery) developed nearby and lasted until the Middle Ages.

nodes.title: La Galère
nodes.description: An ancient Greek village on the east end of the island of Porquerolles discovered through archaeological survey in the 1980s and dating to the first century BCE. Its ancient name is unknown.

nodes.title: Gallinaria (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Ligurian Sea.

nodes.title: Glanate
nodes.description: Glanate was originally a Ligurian settlement that became a Roman town after the annexation of Provence.

nodes.title: Ingauni
nodes.description: An ancient people, localized in Liguria (BAtlas 16 F1 Ingauni)

nodes.title: Intemelii
nodes.description: The Intemelii were a tribe of Liguria.

nodes.title: Lero (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 D2 Lero Ins.

nodes.title: Ligusticum Mare
nodes.description: Ligusticum Mare (Ligurian Sea).

nodes.title: Lucus Bormani
nodes.description: A Roman settlement on the coast of Liguria.

nodes.title: Planasia/Lerina (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 D2 Planasia/Lerina Ins.

nodes.title: Pomponiana?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 B3 Pomponiana?

nodes.title: Reii
nodes.description: A Celtic-Ligurian tribe of Gallia Narbonensis.

nodes.title: *Kuzzurak
nodes.description: A place (city or land) in Anatolia mentioned in a Neo-Assyrian query to the sun-god (reign of Esarhaddon [r. 680-669 BC]).

nodes.title: Uargin
nodes.description: A fortress in the vicinity of Til-garimmu fortified by the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) against Musku (Phrygia).

nodes.title: Ad Duodecimum
nodes.description: A station (statio) located in the territory of the Batavians between Grinnes and Noviomagus.

nodes.title: Via Statilia tombs
nodes.description: Late Republican chamber tombs (ca. 100 B.C.) located at the intersection of the modern Via Statilia and Via di Santa Croce in Rome.

nodes.title: Arch of Marcus Aurelius at Tripoli
nodes.description: A quadrifons arch at ancient Oea (modern Tripoli) that commemorates Roman victories over the Parthians in A.D. 161.

nodes.title: Temple of Talamonaccio
nodes.description: An Etruscan temple of the fourth century BCE, associated with the ancient settlement of Telamon. It lies on Mount Talamonaccio, across the bay from the modern village of Talamone, north of Orbetello, Italy.

nodes.title: Aetokremnos
nodes.description: A rock shelter thought to be the oldest Cypriot settlement, with evidence for human activity already in the Epipalaeolithic.

nodes.title: Unnamed dam near Jumilla, Spain
nodes.description: Remains of a Roman dam located about 15km SSE of Jumilla in modern Spain.

nodes.title: Temple to Nefertari at Abu Simbel
nodes.description: The smaller of the two temples at Abu Simbel, dedicated to the goddess Hathor and the deified queen Nefertari. The temple was relocated between 1964 and 1968 to prevent its submersion under Lake Nasser after the construction of the Aswan High Dam.

nodes.title: Camp celtique de la Bure
nodes.description: A Gallo-Roman settlement of a commercial nature located on the Meurthe river. Archaeological evidence for earthworks, as well as ritual activity, has been discovered. The Gallo-Roman ramparts, in a later phase, make use of marble sculpture as spolia.

nodes.title: 'Akkaz
nodes.description: Formerly an island but now part of the harbor infrastructure of Kuwait City: Shuwaikh Port.

nodes.title: al-Qusur
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 93 E4 al-Qusur

nodes.title: Arakia? (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 93 G4 Arakia? Ins.

nodes.title: Babylonia
nodes.description: An ancient Akkadian region in Mesopotamia.

nodes.title: Dez/Hithite/Hudhud/Koprates? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 93 E2 Dez/Hithite/Hudhud/Koprates? fl.

nodes.title: Dilmun (region)
nodes.description: An ancient region near the Persian Gulf that likely encompassed Bahrain, Kuwait, Qatar, and the eastern portion of Saudi Arabia.

nodes.title: E-kara/Icarus (island)
nodes.description: Failaka Island in the Persian Gulf.

nodes.title: Eridu
nodes.description: Eridu was an ancient city of Sumeria and perhaps one of the first true cities. The site is settled from ca. 5300 B.C. onward. Eridu was located approximately Located 12 km southwest of Ur and was the southernmost of a conglomeration of Sumerian cities that grew up around temple complexes.

nodes.title: Euphrates (river)
nodes.description: The longest river of Western Asia, the Euphrates flows from the Kara Su and the Murat Su to the confluence with the Tigris river.

nodes.title: Failaka/Tell Khazne
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 93 E4 Failaka/Tell Khazne

nodes.title: [Girsu]/Tello(h)
nodes.description: A Sumerian city-state.

nodes.title: Isin
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 93 B2 Isin

nodes.title: Jebel Khayabir/Alexandria?/Antiochia?/Spasinou Charax?/Karkh Maisan?/[Astarabad Ardashir]?
nodes.description: Close to Ǧabal Ḫayabir in Iraq, this site was an important mercantile center of southern Mesopotamia and capital of Characene. The ancient site is located close to Ǧabal Ḫayabir.

nodes.title: Karun/Pasitigris? (river)
nodes.description: The Karun river flows from the Zard-Kuh mountains to the Persian Gulf.

nodes.title: Kharg
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 93 G4 Kharg

nodes.title: Larsa
nodes.description: Larsa was an important city of ancient Sumeria. It was a center of the cult of Utu, the sun god.

nodes.title: Marad
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 93 A1 Marad

nodes.title: Mesene/Characene/Shad Bahman/Maisan
nodes.description: Mesene/Characene/Shad Bahman/Maisan was a kingdom within the Parthian Empire founded ca. 127 BC under Aspasine.

nodes.title: Nippur/Nufar/‘Hippareni’
nodes.description: An ancient Sumerian settlement whose ruins lie at Nuffar in modern Iraq. Under various names it persisted as a settlement throughout the periods of Greek and Roman engagement in Babylonia.

nodes.title: Shaur/Choaspes?/Eulaeus?/Uknu? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 93 E2 Shaur/Choaspes?/Eulaeus?/Uknu? fl.

nodes.title: Roman walls, Novaria
nodes.description: A segment of the Roman defensive wall.

nodes.title: Daskalio
nodes.description: An island of the Cyclades that is now uninhabited. The Cambridge Keros Project identified a large Bronze Age settlement on the island.

nodes.title: Tomba della Medusa (Roma)
nodes.description: A Roman chamber tomb now located on the grounds of the Policlinico Umberto I hospital in Rome.

nodes.title: Theater of Pyrrhus
nodes.description: The Hellenistic theater at Dodona is linked to the reign of Pyrrhus in the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Vasconum saltus
nodes.description: A forest, now unlocated, in the territory of the Varduli.

nodes.title: Enlil Gate
nodes.description: The Enlil Gate is one of Babylon's eight city gates and it is situated on the northwestern side of the inner city, directly north of the Bāb-Lugalerra quarter. King Nebuchadnezzar II built the gate ca. 575 B.C.

nodes.title: King's Gate
nodes.description: The King's Gate is one of Babylon's eight city gates and it is situated on the western side of the inner city, directly west of the nu-x-ù quarter. King Nebuchadnezzar II built the gate ca. 575 B.C.

nodes.title: Šūhi Canal Gate
nodes.description: The Neo-Babylonian kings Nabopolassar (r. 625–605 BC) and Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC) constructed an outer wall around the eastern side of Babylon. That mudbrick wall is reported to have had 120 towers and 5 entrances, including the Šūhi Canal Gate. This access point to the city was probably located on the northeastern stretch of the wall.

nodes.title: Giššu Gate
nodes.description: The Neo-Babylonian kings Nabopolassar (r. 625–605 BC) and Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC) constructed an outer wall around the eastern side of Babylon. That mudbrick wall is reported to have had 120 towers and 5 entrances, including the Giššu Gate. This access point to the city was probably located on the southeastern stretch of the wall.

nodes.title: Sun of the Gods Gate
nodes.description: The Neo-Babylonian kings Nabopolassar (r. 625–605 BC) and Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC) constructed an outer wall around the eastern side of Babylon. That mudbrick wall is reported to have had 120 towers and 5 entrances, including the Sun of the Gods Gate. This access point to the city was probably located on the southern stretch of the wall.

nodes.title: Ešiddukišara
nodes.description: The temple of the god Nabû, Ešiddukišara (“House of the Director of the Universe”), was located in the Tuba district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of three temples in that part of Babylon.

nodes.title: Nuraghe S'Urachi
nodes.description: A nuragic site near San Vero Milis in west central Sardinia, occupied from the Late Bronze Age into the Roman period.

nodes.title: Fossa Traiana
nodes.description: The Fossa Traiana (Channel of Trajan) describes a canal of ca. 45 m width connected with the artificial harbors at Portus. Despite the name, its origins may lie in the Claudian harbor works. The cutting of the channel created an artificial island between Ostia and Portus, the so-called Isola Sacra.

nodes.title: Forum Iulium
nodes.description: The Forum Iulium (or Forum of Caesar, Forum Caesaris) is a forum built by Iulius Caesar and dedicated ca. 46 B.C. The main cult of the forum is that of Venus Genetrix.

nodes.title: House of Sallust
nodes.description: The House of Sallust (VI 2,4) is a domus in Pompeii that assumes its final form around the second century B.C.

nodes.title: tribus Esquilina
nodes.description: The tribus Esquilina was one of the four urban tribes of Rome, which were reportedly created under the reign of Servius Tullius.

nodes.title: House of the Small Fountain
nodes.description: A Samnite-type house located on the Via di Mercurio (VI, 8, 23). The house derives its conventional name from a mosaic fountain located at the rear of the peristyle.

nodes.title: Roman villa at Verige Bay
nodes.description: A Roman villa rustica located in the bay of Verige, dating from the first century B.C. through the sixth century A.D. The villa's ruins lie within Croatia's Brijuni National Park.

nodes.title: Temple of Minerva Medica
nodes.description: The so-called Temple of Minerva Medica is, in fact, a nymphaeum located along the line of the Anio Vetus aqueduct; it most likely dates to the fourth century AD.

nodes.title: Via Claudia Nova
nodes.description: A Roman road built in AD 47 in order to connect the Via Caecilia with the Via Claudia Valeria.

nodes.title: Via Claudia Valeria
nodes.description: A portion of the Via Valeria connecting Aternum and Corfinium. A Claudian milestone (CIL 9.5973) records the construction taking place in AD 48/9 and that the road ran from Cerfennia to the mouth of the Aternus river (modern Pescara).

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Aeclanum
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater located at Aeclanum.

nodes.title: Crypt and church of San Lussorio
nodes.description: The Romanesque church of San Lussorio dates to the early twelfth century.

nodes.title: Madānu Canal Gate
nodes.description: The Neo-Babylonian kings Nabopolassar (r. 625–605 BC) and Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC) constructed an outer wall around the eastern side of Babylon. That mudbrick wall is reported to have had 120 towers and 5 entrances, including the Madānu Canal Gate. This access point to the city was probably located on the eastern stretch of the wall.

nodes.title: Egišhurankia
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Bēlet-Ninūa, Egišhurankia (“House of the Ordinances of Heaven and Underworld”), was located in the Bāb-Lugalerra district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of three temples in that part of Babylon. Egišhurankia seems to have been located near Imgur-Enlil, along the northern wall.

nodes.title: Ebursasa
nodes.description: The temple of the god Šara, Ebursasa (“House of Beautiful Jars”), was located in the Bāb-Lugalerra district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of three temples in that part of Babylon.

nodes.title: Vicus Victoris
nodes.description: The Vicus Victoris was located in Regio XII, according to CIL 6, 975, and may have been located near the porta Ardeatina.

nodes.title: Ara della Regina
nodes.description: A fourth to third century BC sanctuary at Tarquinia

nodes.title: Roman baths at Vertillum
nodes.description: The remains of baths at the Gallo-Roman site of Vertillum.

nodes.title: Great City Baths at Salona
nodes.description: The so-called Great City Baths at Salona or Great Thermae were built in the second or beginning of third century A.D.

nodes.title: Temple of Seti I
nodes.description: The Temple of Seti I at Abydos is also known as the "Great Temple of Abydos".

nodes.title: Temple of Ramesses II
nodes.description: The Temple of Ramesses II at Abydos in Egypt.

nodes.title: Aliphera sanctuary
nodes.description: Pausanias observed sanctuaries of both Asclepius and Athena at Aliphera, as well as an altar of Zeus Lecheates.

nodes.title: Theater of Cyrene
nodes.description: The Greek theater of Cyrene was constructed in the sixth century BCE and transformed into a Roman amphitheater in the second century CE.

nodes.title: Phourni
nodes.description: A Minoan necropolis located near Mount Juktas that was in use from the Early Minoan II to Late Minoan IIIC periods.

nodes.title: Sklavokampos
nodes.description: A Late Minoan structure that first excavated in the 1930s. The Sklavokampos complex contained at least 17 rooms and yielded a range of evidence, including at least 39 sealings.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Su Valsu
nodes.description: A Middle Bronze Age nuraghe located southwest of Florinas in Sardinia.

nodes.title: Pons Neronianus
nodes.description: A bridge across the Tiber river built either by Caius or Nero in order to connect the western part of the Campus Martius with the Campus Vaticanus.

nodes.title: Meta Sudans
nodes.description: A large fountain located southwest of the Flavian Amphitheater and completed under Domitian (ca. A.D. 96). Four of Rome's Augustan regions converged at this point (I, III, IV, X); it is possible that Regio II also intersected the other four regiones at this place.

nodes.title: Mount Kedros
nodes.description: Mount Kedros is a mountain of Crete located southwest of the Ida massif (1,777 m (5,830 ft) asl).

nodes.title: Thrypti
nodes.description: Thrypti, a mountain range of eastern Crete.

nodes.title: Torre Caetani
nodes.description: A Medieval tower located on Tiber Island.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Montélu
nodes.description: The Sanctuary of Montélu lies to the west of Chassenon. The building, only partially excavated, is of an octagonal plan and oriented to the cardinal points.

nodes.title: Roman castrum at Pyrgi
nodes.description: The Roman castrum at Pyrgi seems to re-use, in a direct fashion, elements of the preceding Etruscan city plan, although covering a smaller area.

nodes.title: Dinka Settlement Complex
nodes.description: A small frontier settlement dated to the Neo-Asssyrian period, located in the Peshdar Plain near the banks of the Lesser Zab River.

nodes.title: Ferresanus Portus
nodes.description: A Roman military harbor facility, attested by name in a Latin inscription dating to 144 CE, on the island of Farasan in the Red Sea. The exact location of the facility is not known; the inscription was found in a context of reuse.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Su Casteddu
nodes.description: Nuraghe Su Casteddu is a trilobate nuraghe in Sardinia.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Bruncu Maduli o Bruncu Madugui
nodes.description: A Middle Bronze Age nuraghe and a proto-nuragic village located on the plain known as Giara di Gestur.

nodes.title: Melone del Sodo
nodes.description: Etruscan tumulus-type tombs of the seventh through fourth centuries B.C. located near Cortona, Italy, in località Il Mulino.

nodes.title: Amphitheater of Durrës
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater of Durrës dates to the reign of Trajan.

nodes.title: Poggio Gramignano villa romana
nodes.description: Poggio Gramignano, Lugnano in Teverina.

nodes.title: Villa Redenta
nodes.description: An ancient suburban villa outside of Spoletium, occupied from the Augustan period to the third century A.D. The remains are on the grounds of the modern Villa Redenta complex.

nodes.title: Orticello, Spello
nodes.description: A suburban villa outside Hispellum at the base of Mount Subasio, near a road linking the Via Flaminia to Perusia and Asisium.

nodes.title: Linguella Roman villa
nodes.description: A multi-phase villa on the island of Elba.

nodes.title: Great Palace of Constantinople
nodes.description: Palace complex constructed by Constantine I in 330 CE that served as the primary residence of the Eastern Roman/Byzantine Emperors until 1081 CE. Use of the palace declined beginning in the 11th century, and it had been abandoned by the time of the Ottoman conquest of Constantinople in 1453. Most of the structure was demolished in the early Ottoman period. The Sultan Ahmed Mosque was built on the primary site of the palace in the early 17th century.

nodes.title: Sultanahmet Camii
nodes.description: The Sultanahmet Camii (The Blue/Sultan Ahmed Mosque) was built on the primary site of the Great Palace of Constantinople between 1609 and 1616 during the rule of Ahmed I.

nodes.title: Boothby Roman fort
nodes.description: A Roman fortlet that was part of the Stanegate system, dating to the late first to second centuries.

nodes.title: Nether Denton Roman fort
nodes.description: A Roman fort site at Nether Denton that was identified via cropmarks. The fort formed part of the Stanegate frontier system, and thus pre-dates Hadrian's Wall. It was abandoned ca. 122.

nodes.title: Villa of L. Crassius Tertius
nodes.description: The Villa of L. Crassius Tertius at Oplontis (modern Torre Annunziata in Italy) was discovered in 1974, approximately 250m east of the Villa of Poppaea.

nodes.title: Cala Minnola, Levanzo, Province de Trapani
nodes.description: A productive site connected with fish processing the production of fish sauce.

nodes.title: So-called Grotta Fragapane
nodes.description: A large and rich Early Christian necropolis on the Via Sacra in Agrigento, dated to the fourth century A.D.

nodes.title: Temple of Athena at Paestum
nodes.description: A Late Archaic Doric Temple of Athena (ca. 500 B.C.) at Paestum.

nodes.title: Forum of Paestum
nodes.description: The forum of Roman Paestum stands north of the Hera sanctuary and measures ca. 57 x 150 meters. It occupies the site of the Greek agora and was surrounded with a peristyle of re-used Doric columns. Tabernae stood at its south side and baths funded by M. Tullius Venneianus stood to the southwest. A triple-podium structure - lararium? - stands on the western side.

nodes.title: Lake Tana
nodes.description: Lake Tana is the source of the Blue Nile and the largest lake in Ethiopia.

nodes.title: Panagia Aggeloktisti
nodes.description: An eleventh century Christian church in Kiti, Cyprus, built atop the remains of a fourth century church.

nodes.title: Fauces Garamanticae
nodes.description: The Garamanticae Fauces, or Valley of the Garamantes. Modern Wadi el-Agial.

nodes.title: Garama Metropolis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 36 C5 Garama Metropolis

nodes.title: Garamantes
nodes.description: The Garamantes, a Saharan People, living in Fezzan region of Libya cited: BAtlas 36 C4

nodes.title: Austuriani
nodes.description: A Confederation of Libyan peoples, cited: BAtlas 37 C3 Austuriani

nodes.title: Tautamei?
nodes.description: Tautamei, A Libyan People, thought (by Mattingly) to be a sub-people of either the Nasamones or Macae, cited: BAtlas 37 C2

nodes.title: Apollonia/Sozousa
nodes.description: Apollonia was an ancient city in the Cyrenaica and a port of Cyrene. The city was one of the five cities of the Libyan Pentapolis in Cyrenaica.

nodes.title: Barke
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 B1 Barke

nodes.title: Berenice
nodes.description: The modern city of Benghazi, Libya, began as the Greek colony of Euesperides ca. 525 BC. The city was later renamed Berenice in honor of Berenice of Cyrene, the queen of Ptolemy III Euergetes.

nodes.title: Cyrenaica (region)
nodes.description: An ancient region (the environs of the city of Cyrene) that lies in the eastern part of modern Libya.

nodes.title: Cyrene
nodes.description: An ancient Greek city founded in eastern Libya ca. 630 B.C., Cyrene later became part of the Roman empire (ca. 74 B.C.). The site was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 1982.

nodes.title: Darnis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 D1 Darnis

nodes.title: Nasamones
nodes.description: The Nasamones were a nomadic tribe of northern Libya.

nodes.title: Paliouros
nodes.description: Paliouros was a village of the Marmaridae that was located near a temple sacred to Heracles.

nodes.title: Phaia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 E1 Phaia

nodes.title: Plateia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 E1 Plateia

nodes.title: Plateia? Ins.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 E1 Plateia? Ins.

nodes.title: Ptolemais/Barkes Limen
nodes.description: An ancient capital of Cyrenaica, Ptolemais was probably named after Ptolemy III Euergetes. The city was founded in either the seventh or sixth century BC.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Coast road Berenice → Ptolemais

nodes.title: Cyrene - Apollonia Road
nodes.description: Cyrene → Apollonia

nodes.title: Addua (river)
nodes.description: The Adda river is a river in northern Italy and a tributary of the Padus fl. (Po river).

nodes.title: Ad Figlinas
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 D5 Ad Figlinas

nodes.title: Ad Fonteclos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 F4 Ad Fonteclos

nodes.title: Ad Tarum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 G4 Ad Tarum

nodes.title: Agunia (river)
nodes.description: Agunia fl. (Agogna river) is a river of northern Italy and a tributary of the Padus fl. (Po river).

nodes.title: Alba Pompeia
nodes.description: Alba Pompeia (modern Alba) was a Celtic and Ligurian settlement that entered into the Roman sphere during the late Republican period. In Imperial times Alba was the birthplace of Pertinax.

nodes.title: Amalune (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 B3 Amalune fl.

nodes.title: Andes
nodes.description: Andes is said to be the birthplace of the poet Vergil.

nodes.title: Aquae Statiellae
nodes.description: Aquae Statiellae (modern Acqui Terme) was an ancient settlement in Liguria.

nodes.title: Augusta Bagiennorum
nodes.description: Augusta Bagiennorum was a chief settlement of the Bagienni, a Ligurian tribe. A Roman colony was established at the site in the time of Augustus. Remains of structures are found to the northeast of the modern town of Bene Vagienna, Italy.

nodes.title: Augusta Praetoria
nodes.description: Augusta Praetoria (modern Aosta) was a settlement of the Salassi conquered by Rome in 25 B.C. From 24 B.C. a colony of 3,000 Roman military veterans occupied the city of Augusta Praetoria Salassorum and it became the capital of the province Alpes Graies from 11 B.C.

nodes.title: Augusta Taurinorum
nodes.description: Augusta Taurinorum (modern Turin), the settlement of indigenous Celto-Ligurian peoples, was re-settled as a Roman veteran colony in 28 BC.

nodes.title: Bedriacum
nodes.description: Bedriacum was an ancient town of Cisalpine Gaul located between Verona and Cremona that was the site of two battles during the 'Year of the Four Emperors' (A.D. 69).

nodes.title: Benacus (lake)
nodes.description: Benacus L. (Lake Garda) is the largest lake in Italy.

nodes.title: Bergomum
nodes.description: Originally a center of the archaic Golasecca culture, Bergomum became a municipium of the tribus Voturia. In 452 Attila captured and razed the city.

nodes.title: Betuctelum? (river)
nodes.description: The Lys flows from the Lys Glacier of the Monte Rosa massif to converge with the river Dora Baltea as a righthand tributary at Pont-Saint-Martin.

nodes.title: Brixellum
nodes.description: An ancient Roman town in the plain of the Po river.

nodes.title: Brixia
nodes.description: An ancient settlement. Modern Brescia in Italy.

nodes.title: Canalicum
nodes.description: A Roman road station on the via Iulia Augusta, attested in several itineraries.

nodes.title: Carreum Potentia
nodes.description: Carreum Potentia (Regio IX) is the site of a Roman colony, perhaps planted during the Gracchan period, on a site that preserves, perhaps, its pre-Roman name.

nodes.title: *Civitas Camunnorum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 G2 *Civitas Camunnorum

nodes.title: Clastidium
nodes.description: Clastidium was an ancient town in Cisalpine Gaul where Marcus Claudius Marcellus won the spolia opima in 222 B.C.

nodes.title: Clesus (river)
nodes.description: A major river and tributary of the Po river of northern Italy.

nodes.title: [Comacina] (island)
nodes.description: A small island in Lake Como.

nodes.title: ‘Comeli magus’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 E3 ‘Comeli magus’

nodes.title: Cremona
nodes.description: Cremona is a city of Cisalpine Gaul located on the Po river. The Romans established a colony of 6,000 settlers there after 225 B.C. Cremona was the first Latin colony placed north of the Po river.

nodes.title: Dertona
nodes.description: A city founded in the second century B.C. at the junction of the Via Postumia and Via Aemilia Scauri which merged to become the Via Julia Augusta.

nodes.title: Duria (Bautica) (river)
nodes.description: Duria (Bautica) fl. (Dora Baltea) is a river of northern Italy that is a tributary of the Padus fl. (Po river).

nodes.title: Duria (river)
nodes.description: One of two tributaries of the Po river named Duria, the modern Dora Riparia.

nodes.title: Eporedia
nodes.description: A Roman military outpost during the Roman invasion of the Dora Baltea ca. 100 B.C., Eporedia was assigned to Regio XI.

nodes.title: Eupilis L.
nodes.description: Eupilis L. (Lake of Pusiano)

nodes.title: Fidentia
nodes.description: Fidentia (modern Fidenza) began as a Roman castrum and in 41 BC it became a municipium. The settlement is located along the Via Aemilia, between Parma and Placentia.

nodes.title: Florenti(ol)a
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 F4 Florenti(ol)a

nodes.title: Forum Fulvii Valentinum
nodes.description: Forum Fulvii Valentinum was a small Roman settlement in Liguria that was established by M. Fulvius Flaccus (cos. 125 B.C.) along the Via Fulvia, a road running from Dertona to Hasta Pompeia.

nodes.title: *Forum Germanici
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 A4 *Forum Germanici

nodes.title: Gabellus/*Secia (river)
nodes.description: Gabellus/*Secia fl. (Secchia river) is a tributary of the Po river.

nodes.title: Genua
nodes.description: Genua was an ancient settlement of Liguria that came to be destroyed by Carthage in 209 BC. Thereafter it received Roman municipal privileges and was rebuilt.

nodes.title: Hadra (river)
nodes.description: The Arda is a right tributary of the Po River in northern Italy.

nodes.title: Hasta
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 D5 Hasta

nodes.title: Incia (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 G4 Incia fl.

nodes.title: Insubres
nodes.description: A Gallic tribe of Northern Italy, giving their name to the region of Insubria.

nodes.title: Iria/Forum Iulii Iriensium
nodes.description: Iria/Forum Iulii Iriensium (modern Voghera) was located along the road from Placentia to Dertona. An Augustan colony was established there (colonia Forum Iulium Iriensium) that was then destroyed in the first century AD.

nodes.title: Ir(i)a (river)
nodes.description: The Scrivia river is a tributary of the Po river.

nodes.title: Iria (river)
nodes.description: Iria fl. (Staffora river) is a river of northern Italy that flows from the Ligurian Apennines to the Padus fl. (Po river).

nodes.title: Lambrus (river)
nodes.description: Lambrus fl. (Lambro river) is a river of Lombary and a tributary of the Padus fl. (Po river).

nodes.title: Larius/Comacinus L.
nodes.description: Larius/Comacinus L. (Lake Como)

nodes.title: Laus Pompeia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 E3 Laus Pompeia

nodes.title: Libarna
nodes.description: Libarna was a Roman city located in Liguria.

nodes.title: Liguria (region)
nodes.description: Liguria is a coastal region of northwest Italy.

nodes.title: Mantua
nodes.description: Mantua (modern Mantova) is a city of Etruscan origin that received Roman citizenship in 49 B.C.

nodes.title: Mediolan(i)um
nodes.description: A Celtic settlement and crossroads, later a Western Roman capital. Now modern Milan, Italy.

nodes.title: Mincius (river)
nodes.description: The Mincio river is a tributary of the Po river.

nodes.title: Mutina
nodes.description: Ancient Mutina (originally the Etruscan town Mutna), was first inhabited by Villanovans and later by Ligurians and the Gaulish Boii. The Boii sieged the city in 218 BC and later Mutina was re-established as a Roman colony (183 BC). It was an important city and played a role in the civil wars during the last decades of the Roman Republic.

nodes.title: Novaria
nodes.description: A Roman municipium with an orthogonal plan.

nodes.title: Nure (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 F4 Nure fl.

nodes.title: Ollius (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 F2 Ollius fl.

nodes.title: Olonna (river)
nodes.description: The Olona river flows through the provinces of Varese, Milan and Pavia and empties into the Lambro meridionale.

nodes.title: Orgus (river)
nodes.description: Orgus fl. (Orco river) is a river of northern Italy and a tributary of the Padus fl. (Po river).

nodes.title: Pagus Ambitrebius
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 E4 Pagus Ambitrebius

nodes.title: Parma
nodes.description: The site of a Bronze Age terramare settlement, Parma was re-founded first by Etruscans and later by the Romans when a colony was established there in 183 B.C. The city was rebuilt by Augustus and was eventually sacked by Attila.

nodes.title: Parma (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 G4 Parma fl.

nodes.title: Pedo(na)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 A5 Pedo(na)

nodes.title: Placentia
nodes.description: Placentia (modern Piacenza) was an ancient site with Gallic and Etruscan occupation before the Roman conquest of 218 B.C. The city persisted into Late Antiquity.

nodes.title: Pollentia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 B4 Pollentia

nodes.title: Porcibera (river)
nodes.description: A river, flowing from the Apennines and emptying in the Ligusticum Mare near Genua.

nodes.title: Regium Lepidum
nodes.description: Regium Lepidum (modern Reggio Emilia) was founded by M. Aemilius Lepidus in either 187 or 175 B.C.

nodes.title: Ricina
nodes.description: A Roman road station along the Via Aemilia Scauri on the Mediterranean coast of Italy, thought to have been located in the vicinty of modern Recco.

nodes.title: Sabini
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 G2 Sabini

nodes.title: Sesites (river)
nodes.description: A river of northwestern Italy and a tributary of the Po river.

nodes.title: Sirmio
nodes.description: Modern Sirmione on Lake Garda.

nodes.title: Statielli
nodes.description: A tribe of Liguria whose territory was located on the northern slopes of the Apennines in the Bormida valley.

nodes.title: Tanarus (river)
nodes.description: Tanarus fl. (Tanaro river) is a 276 km-long river in northern Italy that flows from the Ligurian Alps to the Padus fl. (Po river).

nodes.title: Tannetum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 G4 Tannetum

nodes.title: Tarus (river)
nodes.description: Tarus fl. (Taro river) is a tributary of the Po river in northern Italy.

nodes.title: Ticinum
nodes.description: An ancient city of Gallia Transpadana, Ticinum lay along the line of the ancient Via Aemilia. Today Ticinum is the modern city of Pavia.

nodes.title: Ticinus (river)
nodes.description: Ticinus fl. (Ticino) is a left-bank tributary of the Padus fl. (Po river) in northern Italy.

nodes.title: Transpadana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 C3 Transpadana

nodes.title: Trebia (river)
nodes.description: A river of Liguria and Emilia-Romagna and one of the four main right-bank tributaries of the river Po.

nodes.title: Trident(i)um
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 I1 Trident(i)um

nodes.title: Vada Sabatia
nodes.description: An ancient settlement that began as a second century B.C. Roman military outpost.

nodes.title: Veleia
nodes.description: Veleia was an ancient Ligurian settlement (regio VIII).

nodes.title: Verbanus L.
nodes.description: Verbanus L. (Lake Maggiore).

nodes.title: Vercellae
nodes.description: Originally a captial of the Libici, a tribe of Ligurians, Vercellae became an important Roman municipium.

nodes.title: Verona
nodes.description: Verona was an ancient settlement that became a Roman colonia in 89 BC and a municipium in 49 BC.

nodes.title: Victoriolae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 I4 Victoriolae

nodes.title: Victumulae
nodes.description: A settlement of the Celtic Insubres located in the territory of Vercellae.

nodes.title: Vitricium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 B2 Vitricium

nodes.title: Unnamed Roman aqueduct at Eporedia
nodes.description: According to PECS, the Roman aqueduct at Eporedia originates "at the Viona stream on the slopes of the Mombarone".

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct at Augusta Bagiennorum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 B4 unnamed aqueduct (Augusta Bagiennorum)

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct at Alba Pompeia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 C4 unnamed aqueduct (Alba Pompeia)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 D4 unnamed aqueduct (Dertona)

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge at Lévérogne
nodes.description: According to the Barrington Atlas directory, an ancient group of bridges crossing the river Duria (Bautica) is found at Villeneuve/Leverogne to the west of Aosta.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 B2 unnamed bridge (at Vitricium)

nodes.title: Pont-Saint-Martin (bridge)
nodes.description: A Roman segmental arch bridge in the Aosta Valley in Italy that dates to the first century BC. The bridge spans 31.4 m across the Betuctelum to the NNW of Eporedia.

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge at Bard
nodes.description: The so-called "Ponte di Bard" located at Bard, to the southeast of Vitricium.

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge
nodes.description: An unnamed bridge over the Ir(i)a fl., north of Libarna.

nodes.title: Roman bridge at Clastidium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 E3 unnamed bridge (at Clastidium)

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge
nodes.description: An unnamed bridge over the Nure fl., southeast of Placentia.

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge
nodes.description: An unnamed ancient bridge over the Incia fl., near S. Ilario d’Enza.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 A4 unnamed centuriation (*Forum Germanici)

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 B3 unnamed centuriation (Augusta Taurinorum W Rivarolo Canavese)

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 C3 unnamed centuriation (Vercellum (W))

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 E3 unnamed centuriation (Laus Pompeia)
