nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 H4 unnamed centuriation (Mutina)

nodes.title: Carystum
nodes.description: An oppidum of the Statielli/Statellati, where the Romans defeated Ligurian tribes in 173 BC.

nodes.title: Adouli
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 4 A2 Adouli

nodes.title: Adoulitikos Kolpos
nodes.description: Adoulitikos Kolpos (The Gulf of Zula)

nodes.title: Aethiopia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 4 A3 Aethiopia

nodes.title: Alalaiou (islands)
nodes.description: Alalaiou Inss., the modern Dahlak Archipelago in the Red Sea, comprised of 126 islands.

nodes.title: Arabicus Sinus/Erythr(ae)um/Rubrum Mare
nodes.description: Arabicus Sinus/Erythr(ae)um/Rubrum Mare (The Red Sea) is an inlet of the Indian Ocean located between Africa and Asia.

nodes.title: Astapous (river)
nodes.description: Astapous fl. (Blue Nile or Amharic or an-Nīl al-Azraq (النيل الأزرق‎ an-Nīl)) is a major river of Africa and a tributary of the Nile river. Its source is Lake Tana in Ethiopia.

nodes.title: A(u)xoume
nodes.description: Present-day Aksum in Ethiopia. The center of the Aksumite Kingdom, a maritime trading power that flourished from the first to the tenth centuries AD. The city was listed as UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1980.

nodes.title: Aualites Sinus
nodes.description: Aualites Sinus (The Gulf of Aden).

nodes.title: Azanium Mare/Barbarikon Pelagos
nodes.description: Azanium Mare/Barbarikon Pelagos (The Arabian Sea).

nodes.title: Bracheia/Prasodes Thalassa
nodes.description: Bracheia/Prasodes Thalassa was a part of the Indian Ocean described by Ptolemy lying off the coast of east Africa

nodes.title: Camarum (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 4 B2 Camarum Ins.

nodes.title: Chelonitis (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 4 B2 Chelonitis Ins.

nodes.title: Deire
nodes.description: Deire is located on a promontory (modern Ras Siyyan) on the western side of the Bab-el-Mandeb strait, located between the Red Sea and the Gulf of Aden.

nodes.title: Ad Idicem
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 A4 Ad Idicem

nodes.title: Ad Rubiconem
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 C4 Ad Rubiconem

nodes.title: Devade Islands
nodes.description: The modern Farasan Islands.

nodes.title: Ad Silarum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 B4 Ad Silarum

nodes.title: Ad Sinnium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 B4 Ad Sinnium

nodes.title: Aemilia
nodes.description: Aemilia was a region (Regio VIII) of northern Italy.

nodes.title: Altinum
nodes.description: Altinum was the capital of the Veneti of northern Italy. The site was destroyed by Attila in AD 452.

nodes.title: Aprusa (river)
nodes.description: Aprusa fl. (Ausa River)

nodes.title: Ariminum
nodes.description: Ariminum (Rimini) is a Roman colony founded on the Adriatic coast in 268 BC.

nodes.title: Diosko(u)rides (island)
nodes.description: Socotra is an island in the Arabian Sea. It is the eponymous island of the Socotra archipelago and comprises approximately 95% of the landmass in said archipelago. Human activity on the island begins in the Lower Paleolithic. In Graeco-Roman times, the island appears as "Dioskouridou" in the Periplus of the Erythraean Sea.

nodes.title: Ariminus (river)
nodes.description: A river of eastern Italy that flows from the Monte dei Frati to the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Astagus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 B1 Astagus fl.

nodes.title: At(h)esis (river)
nodes.description: The Adige River is the second longest river in Italy. It flows from the Alps to the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Atrianorum Paludes
nodes.description: Lagoons of the Po (Padus) river delta near (H)Atria

nodes.title: Auraei
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 A2 Auraei

nodes.title: Bedesis (river)
nodes.description: The Ronco river is a tributary of the Montone river, located in Romagna, northern Italy.

nodes.title: Boi(i)
nodes.description: A later Iron Age Gallic tribe, the Boii enter Italy as part of the 'Gallic Invasion' of Italy in 390 BC. They made the Etruscan city of Felsina their new capital, Bononia (Bologna). The Romans defeated them decisively at Mutina.

nodes.title: Cadianum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 A2 Cadianum

nodes.title: Caesena
nodes.description: An Umbrian and Etruscan city on the Savio river that passed into Roman control in the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Castello del Tartaro
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 A2 Castello del Tartaro

nodes.title: Classis
nodes.description: A military port near Ravenna, established by Octavian by 12 B.C. as headquarters for the Roman fleet in the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Claterna
nodes.description: Claterna was a Roman a town of Gallia Cispadana, located along the Via Aemilia between Bononia and Forum Cornelii.

nodes.title: Compitum ad Confluentes
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 C4 Compitum ad Confluentes

nodes.title: Faventia
nodes.description: A Roman city on the Via Aemilia.

nodes.title: Felsina/Bononia
nodes.description: A city of the Po Plain with important cultural phases related to Etruscan, Celtic, and Roman culture. Important evidence for the Iron Age Villanovan culture has been found in Bononia and its vicinity. The Romans established a Latin colony of 3000 settlers at Bononia in 189 BC. After changing hands several times following the fall of the Western Roman Empire, Bologna became an important Medieval center.

nodes.title: Forum Cornelii
nodes.description: An ancient city founded by Lucius Cornelius Sulla as a colony ca. 82 BC.

nodes.title: Forum Gallorum
nodes.description: A town on the Via Aemilia that was the site of a battle waged between M. Antonius and Hirtius and Pansa during the siege of Mutina.

nodes.title: Forum Livii
nodes.description: A town of Gallia Cispadana located on the right bank of the Montone river.

nodes.title: Forum Popilii
nodes.description: Forum Popilii on the Via Aemilia was founded in 173 BC by M. Popilius Laenas.

nodes.title: *Hadriani
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 C3 *Hadriani

nodes.title: (H)Atria
nodes.description: (H)Atria (modern Adria) was a Venetic and, later, Etruscan settlement. The city itself is likely a sixth century BC foundation.

nodes.title: Hostilia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 A2 Hostilia

nodes.title: Iulia Concordia
nodes.description: Iulia Concordia (Concordia Sagittaria) was established by the Romans in 42 BC at the intersection of the Via Annia and the Via Postumia.

nodes.title: Liquentia (river)
nodes.description: The Livenza river is a river of northern Italy that flows into the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Exusta/Katakekaumene Inss.
nodes.description: Exusta/Katakekaumene Inss. are a group of islands located in the Red Sea. The ancient names Exusta and Katakekaumene refer to the volcanic nature of these islands, one of which is identifiable as the modern Jabal al-Tair Island.

nodes.title: Meduacus Maior (river)
nodes.description: The Brenta river flows from near Trentino to the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Opitergium
nodes.description: Opitergium (modern Oderzo) is a settlement of the Veneti along the Piave river located at a junction of the Via Postumia.

nodes.title: Ostium Volane
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 C3 Ostium Volane

nodes.title: Padus/Eridanus (river)
nodes.description: The Po river of northern Italy flows from the Cottian Alps (Alpes Cottiae) to the Adriatic Sea. It is the longest of Italy's rivers.

nodes.title: Padusa
nodes.description: A marshy region on the river Eridanus.

nodes.title: Patavium
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of the Veneti, Patavium became a Roman municipium in 45 BC. It was the birthplace of several famous Romans including Titus Livius, Valerius Flaccus, Asconius Pedianus and Thrasea Paetus.

nodes.title: Plavis (river)
nodes.description: A river of northern Italy that flows from the Alps to the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Ravenna
nodes.description: A city of northern Adriatic Italy that served as the capital of the Western Roman Empire from A.D. 402 until 476.

nodes.title: Retron (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 A1 Retron fl.

nodes.title: Rhenus (river)
nodes.description: The Reno river in northern Italy

nodes.title: Rubico (river)
nodes.description: A river in northeastern Italy that served, during the late Roman Republic, as the southern boundary of the province of Cisalpine Gaul and which Caesar famously crossed with an army in 49 BCE thereby precipitating the Roman Civil War. Its modern location is debated (see "Connections" and "Details" sections).

nodes.title: Hippalon Pelagos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 4 D3 Hippalon Pelagos

nodes.title: Sapis (river)
nodes.description: Sapis fl. (Savio river)

nodes.title: Scultenna (river)
nodes.description: The Scultenna, the modern Panaro river, is a tributary of the Po river in northern Italy.

nodes.title: Septem Maria (Station)
nodes.description: A station on the Via Popillia in the Po river delta (also known as Septem Maria)

nodes.title: Septem Maria (Po River Delta)
nodes.description: The Po (Padus) river delta.

nodes.title: Silarus (river)
nodes.description: The Sillaro river.

nodes.title: Silis (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 C1 Silis fl.

nodes.title: Spina
nodes.description: An Etruscan port city at the mouth of the Po river on the Adriatic Sea, most likely founded at the end of the sixth century B.C.

nodes.title: Homeritai
nodes.description: A tribe of southern Arabia Felix, occupying territory that is now part of Yemen.

nodes.title: Tarvisium
nodes.description: Tarvisium (Treviso) is a settlement located in the plain of the Silis river, not far from the Via Claudia Augusta.

nodes.title: Vatrenus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 A4 Vatrenus fl.

nodes.title: Vicetia
nodes.description: Vicetia (modern Vicenza) as a settlement of the Veneti in northern Italy.

nodes.title: Vicus Varianus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 B3 Vicus Varianus

nodes.title: Vitis? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 B4 Vitis? fl.

nodes.title: Indicum Mare
nodes.description: The Indian Ocean.

nodes.title: Kinnamomophoros Chora
nodes.description: Strabo dubs the territory around around Cape Guardafui as the "Land of Cinnamon".

nodes.title: Kokkonatou (islands)
nodes.description: The Socotra archipelago in the Indian Ocean was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2008 on account of its biodiversity.

nodes.title: Malichou islands
nodes.description: A group of 10 major volcanic islands located in the Red Sea.

nodes.title: Mari(a)ba
nodes.description: Capital of the Sabaean kingdom.

nodes.title: Notou Keras/Aromata Pr.
nodes.description: Cape Guardafui is a headland in the northeastern Bari province of Somalia.

nodes.title: Oreine (island)
nodes.description: Oreine Ins. (Dissei) is an island in the Red Sea.

nodes.title: Ptolemais Theron
nodes.description: Ptolemais Theron was an ancient marketplace on the Red Sea, the precise location of which is now unknown.

nodes.title: Pyraloi (islands)
nodes.description: The Lamu Archipelago is located in the Indian Ocean near the northern coast of Kenya.

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct at Vicetia
nodes.description: An aqueduct supplying Vicetia (modern Vicenza in Italy)

nodes.title: Ravenna Aqueduct
nodes.description: Supplied Ravenna with water from the Bedesis fl.

nodes.title: Sap(p)har
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 4 B3 Sap(p)har

nodes.title: Nuraghe Unia
nodes.description: A well-preserved monopteral nuraghe located in northwestern Sardinia.

nodes.title: Amphitheater of Anazarbos
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater located south and outside the city walls at Anazarbos (modern Dilekkaya in Turkey).

nodes.title: Phaneromeni Burials (Chiliomodi)
nodes.description: A monumental sarcophagus of archaic date was excavated in situ in 1984 at a place known today as Phaneromeni in the eastern part of modern Chiliomodi's (Greece) village territory. Its location provides evidence for the urban extent of ancient Tenea.

nodes.title: Roman Mausoleum at Palio Scholeio (Chiliomedio)
nodes.description: A monumental Roman mausoleum, originally installed over a Hellenistic cemetery, was excavated in 2017 at a site known as "Old School" to the south of modern Chiliomedio in Greece. Its location helps indicate the extent and date of cemeteries at the ancient site of Tenea.

nodes.title: Temple of Hera, Olympia
nodes.description: The Temple of Hera at Olympia, also known as the Heraion, is a peripteral temple in the northwest corner of the Altis precinct that is dedicated to Hera. Built ca. 600-590 B.C., the Heraion is the oldest temple at Olympia and one of the earliest known examples of the Doric order in Greece.

nodes.title: Choragic Monument of Lysicrates
nodes.description: The Choragic Monument of Lysicrates is a round structure erected in 334 BC in Athens to honor the victory of a choregos in a dramatic competition.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Armungia
nodes.description: A single-tower nuragic site; the diameter of the tower measures ca. 12 meters.

nodes.title: Ponte Brabaciera
nodes.description: A second century Roman bridge on the Riu Brabaciera.

nodes.title: Matzanni
nodes.description: A sanctuary that includes a Punic temple built in white limestone, a nuraghe, and a sacred well.

nodes.title: Jebel Barkal
nodes.description: Jebel Barkal is a mountain that, ca. 1450 BC, was considered the limit of the New Kingdom empire of the Egyptian Pharaoh Thutmose III. Numerous archaeological sites connected with Nubia and the Kingdom of Kush surround Jebel Barka, all of which are listed on the UNESCO World Heritage list.

nodes.title: Inveravon
nodes.description: Site of a small Roman fort on the Antonine Wall.

nodes.title: Civitas Leonina
nodes.description: The Civitas Leonina or Leonine City is a portion of the city of Rome on the left bank of the river Tiber around which Pope Leo IV commissioned the construction of the Leonine Wall in the ninth century AD. This followed the Saracen sack of Rome in AD 846.

nodes.title: Ophryneion
nodes.description: Ophryneion was an ancient city of the northern Troad. It lay between Rhoteum and Dardanus. The site is located about 1.5 km north-east of the village of İntepe (previously known as Erenköy) in Çanakkale Province, Turkey.

nodes.title: Palaio Pretorio
nodes.description: The ruins of a colonnaded structure in marble, perhaps a temple; a well / cistern is also observed by Sealy.

nodes.title: Palaiokhori
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 B3 Palaiokhori

nodes.title: Parakoila
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Parakoila

nodes.title: Pelinnaion M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C4 Pelinnaion M.

nodes.title: Pergamum
nodes.description: An important ancient settlement, located at modern Bergama in Turkey. It was first described in Xenophon's Anabasis and was later used as a treasury under Lysimachus. Pergamum became the administrative capital and principal city of the Attalid kingdom and dynasty (282-133 BCE) and was briefly the first capital of the Roman province of Asia. It later was a seat of a Christian bishopric and is listed in Revelation as one of the seven churches of Asia. It was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2014 under "Pergamon and its Multi-Layered Cultural Landscape".

nodes.title: Petra
nodes.description: An ancient coastal settlement on the island of Lesbos, situated around and atop a volcanic neck.

nodes.title: Phalakrai
nodes.description: Phalakrai, Summit of Ida Mons, cited: BAtlas 56 D2

nodes.title: Phanai
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 B5 Phanai

nodes.title: Phanai Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C5 Phanai Pr.

nodes.title: Philadelpheia
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Asia Minor, modern Alaşehir, Turkey.

nodes.title: Phocaea
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Asia Minor, modern Foça in Turkey.

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Phonias

nodes.title: Phyrites (river)
nodes.description: The Phyrites river is a tributary of the Cayster.

nodes.title: Pteleos L.
nodes.description: A lake of the Troad, mentioned by Strabo following his discussion of the grove of Hector.

nodes.title: Pyrra
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Pyrra

nodes.title: Rhoiteion
nodes.description: An ancient city located in the northern part of the Troad.

nodes.title: Sandalium? (island)
nodes.description: An islet near Lesbos, the modern Garbias.

nodes.title: Sardianon Pedion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 F4 Sardianon Pedion

nodes.title: Sardis/Hyde?
nodes.description: Sardis was the capital of the Lydian Empire located in western Turkey. In 188 B.C. Sardis became a part of the Attalid kingdom and thus it passed with the territory of Attalus III to Rome in 133 B.C.

nodes.title: Satnioeis (river)
nodes.description: A minor river of the southern Troad.

nodes.title: Scamander (river)
nodes.description: A river of the Troad (modern Karamenderes River).

nodes.title: Selles
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Selles

nodes.title: Sigeion
nodes.description: Sigeion was located in the northwest part of the Troad at the mouth of the Scamander river.

nodes.title: Simoeis (river)
nodes.description: A tributary of the Scamander in the Troad.

nodes.title: Skala Polykhnitou
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Skala Polykhnitou

nodes.title: Skala ton Loutron
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 D3 Skala ton Loutron

nodes.title: Skepsis
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of the Troad.

nodes.title: Skoteino
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Skoteino

nodes.title: Smintheion
nodes.description: Homer mentions the temple of Apollo Smintheus as the shrine where Chryses was priest. The second century B.C. remains of an Ionic sanctuary with an adjacent town are located in the southwestern Troad near modern Gülpinar.

nodes.title: Smyrna/Eurydikeia
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Asia Minor, modern Izmir in Turkey.

nodes.title: Stratonicaea/Hadrianopolis
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Lydia, located near modern Siledik in Turkey.

nodes.title: Tantalos M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C4 Tantalos M.

nodes.title: Tarti
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C4 Tarti

nodes.title: Temnos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 E4 Temnos

nodes.title: Tenedos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C2 Tenedos

nodes.title: Tenedos (island)
nodes.description: An island located in the Aegean Sea 5 km off the coast of Troas.

nodes.title: Teos
nodes.description: An ancient Ionian settlement of Asia Minor, located at modern Siğacik in Turkey.

nodes.title: Tes Kores to Gephyri
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C5 Tes Kores to Gephyri

nodes.title: Thebes Pedion
nodes.description: A fertile plain of Mysia, located south of Mount Placius.

nodes.title: Thymiana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C5 Thymiana

nodes.title: Thyateira
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Asia Minor, located at modern Akhisar in Turkey.

nodes.title: Thymbras Pedion
nodes.description: A plain located south of Troy.

nodes.title: Thymbrios (river)
nodes.description: A small river of the Troad and tributary of the Scamander.

nodes.title: Traron
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C1 Traron

nodes.title: Trianta
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Trianta

nodes.title: Troas (region)
nodes.description: Troas (or the Troad) is an historical region that occupies the Biga peninsula in northwestern Asia Minor.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C2 unnamed aqueduct (Ilium)

nodes.title: Roman Aqueduct at Mytilene
nodes.description: A large aqueduct that supplied the city of Mytilene from the west. Some parts of it are preserved.

nodes.title: Ain el-Sabil
nodes.description: Roman/late antique settlement, with visible remains of streets and mud-brick structures, including a church, two pigeon towers, and possibly residential units. Largely unexcavated.

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge
nodes.description: The remains of a bridge of Byzantine or Turkish construction located northwest of Sardis.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Unnamed route or road

nodes.title: Sardis-Thyateira Road
nodes.description: An ancient road connecting Sardis and Thyateira.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 F4 unnamed tumulus (6 clusters in Korou Pedion)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 G4 unnamed tumulus (4 clusters in Sardianon Pedion/Katakekaumene)

nodes.title: Aigiroessa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 unlocated Aigiroessa

nodes.title: Apolloniacharax
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 unlocated Apolloniacharax

nodes.title: Ardynion
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Karseai/Karseis/Kerasai/Kerateis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 unlocated Karseai/Karseis/Kerasai/Kerateis

nodes.title: Kleandria
nodes.description: Now unlocated, Kleandria was a settlement of the Troad located 60 stadia from Kale Peuke.

nodes.title: Mernouphyta
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 unlocated Mernouphyta

nodes.title: Oios ho Hermaites
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 unlocated Oios ho Hermaites

nodes.title: Pedasos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 unlocated Pedasos

nodes.title: Philetaireia
nodes.description: An ancient place whose precise location is unknown today, but it was somewhere on the foot of Mt. Ida.

nodes.title: Zeus Hyperdexios, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 unlocated Zeus Hyperdexios, T.

nodes.title: Aegaeum Mare
nodes.description: The Aegean Sea is the largest body of water between Greece and Asia Minor and an embayment of the Mediterranean Sea.

nodes.title: Aigila/Ogylos (island)
nodes.description: Aigila/Ogylos Ins. (Antikythera) is an island in the Aegean Sea located between Crete and the Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Cyclades Islands
nodes.description: An island group in the Aegean Sea composed of over 200 islands.

nodes.title: Palaiokastro
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 57 B6 Palaiokastro

nodes.title: Achaea/Achaia (region)
nodes.description: An ancient Greek region on the northern coast of the Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Ag. Eirene
nodes.description: Ayia Irini, located on Keos, was occupied from the Late Neolithic until the Mycenaean period. The site was extensively excavated under J.L. Caskey.

nodes.title: Ag. Helene
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Ag. Helene

nodes.title: Ag. Ioannes
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 H4 Ag. Ioannes

nodes.title: Ag. Kyriake
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Ag. Kyriake

nodes.title: Aigai
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Achaia in the Peloponnese. Modern Akrata.

nodes.title: Aigeira
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C1 Aigeira

nodes.title: Aigion
nodes.description: A city-state of ancient Achaea that numbered as one of the 12 Achaean cities. The city was located 30 stades from Rhypae, and 40 stades from Helice.

nodes.title: Akrokorinthos
nodes.description: Akrokorinthos (Acrocorinth) was the acropolis of ancient Corinth.

nodes.title: Alipheira
nodes.description: Pausanias notes that Alipheira was mostly abandoned when Arcadians were merged into Megalopolis.

nodes.title: Alphe(i)os (river)
nodes.description: The longest river of the Peloponnesus.

nodes.title: Amyklai
nodes.description: Amyklai was an ancient settlement located near Sparta in the plain by the Eurotas river to the east of the Taygetus mountains.

nodes.title: Angathia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Angathia

nodes.title: Apollo Korythos, T.
nodes.description: A multi-phase sanctuary of Apollo that begins in the archaic period. Pausanias visited the sanctuary and observed two cult statues of the god. One of these, sacred to Apollo Corynthus, was of wood. The other, sacred to Apollo Argeotas, was of bronze.

nodes.title: Arachnaion (mountain)
nodes.description: A mountain of the Argolid with a higher western peak (Profitis Ilias, 1199 masl) and a lower eastern peak (Mavrovouni or Arna, 1139 masl). Material from the Mycenaean, Archaic, and Classical periods has been found on the western peak and identified with altars of Zeus and Hera described by Pausanias. Aeschylus mentions its use as a signal station.

nodes.title: Araxos
nodes.description: Cape Araxos separates the Gulf of Patras from the Ionian Sea.

nodes.title: Arcadia
nodes.description: The ancient region of Arcadia comprised the highlands at the center of the Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Argolicus Sinus
nodes.description: A gulf on the east of the Peloponnese that opens into the Aegean Sea.

nodes.title: Argolis
nodes.description: Argolis (also known as 'the Argolid') occupied the eastern part of the Peloponnese; comprising primarily the Argolid peninsula and the coastal region lying to the east of Arcadia, and north of Laconia.

nodes.title: Argos
nodes.description: Argos was a city of ancient Greece that reached its cultural highpoint under Pheidon in the seventh century BC.

nodes.title: Aroania (mountain)
nodes.description: Aroania M. is the third highest mountain of the Peloponnese (2,355 m asl).

nodes.title: Asea
nodes.description: Asea was a town of Arcadia, located in the district Maenalia. Lying near the frontier of Laconia, Asea was to be found along the road from Megalopolis to Pallantium and Tegea. Asea participated in the foundation of Megalopolis and many of its inhabitants relocated there.

nodes.title: Asinaeus/Coronaeus Sinus
nodes.description: Asinaeus/Coronaeus Sinus (the Messenian Gulf).

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Asklepios at Epidauros
nodes.description: A major sanctuary complex, with extensive surviving archaeological remains, located approximately 8km from the ancient city of Epidauros in Greece. A UNESCO World Heritage Site.

nodes.title: Aspis (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Saronic Gulf.

nodes.title: Bassai
nodes.description: The Temple of Apollo Epikourios (often Latinized as Epicurius) at Bassae is an innovative mid-5th century B.C. Doric temple in Arcadia. The temple preserves the oldest Corinthian capital yet found. It was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 1986.

nodes.title: Belbina (island)
nodes.description: A small island in the Saronic Gulf, some 10 miles from the promontory of Sounion.

nodes.title: Bolinaios (river)
nodes.description: A river located in northern Achaea that drains into the Gulf of Corinth.

nodes.title: Chelonatas Sinus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 A2 Chelonatas Sinus

nodes.title: Corinthia
nodes.description: Corinthia was a region of ancient Greece associated with the city-state Corinth.

nodes.title: Corinthiacus Sinus
nodes.description: The Gulf of Corinth.

nodes.title: Corinthus/Korinthos
nodes.description: The ancient Greek and Roman city of Corinth, located in the Peloponnese, Greece. Also known today as Archaia Korinthos and not to be confused with the nearby modern town.

nodes.title: Cyllenius Sinus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 A2 Cyllenius Sinus

nodes.title: Cyparissius Sinus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 A2 Cyparissius Sinus

nodes.title: Cythera (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 inset Cythera Ins.

nodes.title: Dine
nodes.description: The whirlpool Dine, located in the Argolic Gulf, is discussed by Pausanias in a discussion of the flow of water in the Argolid.

nodes.title: Diolkos
nodes.description: The Diolkos was a paved tract near ancient Corinth that allowed boats to portage the Isthmus of Corinth. It was in use from ca. 600 B.C. until ca. A.D. 50.

nodes.title: Dorion
nodes.description: A fortified hilltop settlement overlooking the Soulima Valley in northern Messenia. Dorion appears in the Catalogue of Ships in Homer's Iliad.

nodes.title: Dyme
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B1 Dyme

nodes.title: Emborio
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Emborio

nodes.title: Ephyra? (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Ephyra? Ins.

nodes.title: Epidauros
nodes.description: Epidauros is located on a small peninsula on the eastern coast of Peloponnesus.

nodes.title: Epidauros Limera
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 E4 Epidauros Limera

nodes.title: Epitalion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 A2 Epitalion

nodes.title: Eurotas (river)
nodes.description: Eurotas fl. (Evrotas) is the principal river of Laconia.

nodes.title: Gatheai
nodes.description: Gatheai was a town of Arcadia in the district of Cromitis, along the river Gatheatas.

nodes.title: Gatheatas? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C3 Gatheatas? fl.

nodes.title: Geraistos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 H2 Geraistos

nodes.title: Geraistos Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 H2 Geraistos Pr.

nodes.title: Geronteon (mountain)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C2 Geronteon M.

nodes.title: Halieis
nodes.description: An ancient Greek harbor city in the Argolid (across from the modern village of Porto Cheli) that was abandoned toward the end of the fourth century BCE. Excavated remains include fortification walls (as early as the eighth c. BCE), a city with an orthogonal street plan, an industrial quarter, and domestic architecture with evidence for agricultural processing. Parts of the city are now under water due to a rise in sea levels.

nodes.title: Heraion (Argolis)
nodes.description: The Argive Heraion was a major ancient sanctuary sacred to Hera located in the Argolid.

nodes.title: Hierakia (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 F4 Hierakia Ins.

nodes.title: Hydroussa/Hydrea (island)
nodes.description: An island of the Aegean Sea between the Saronic and Argolic gulfs.

nodes.title: Ichthys Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 A2 Ichthys Pr.

nodes.title: Ioulis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G2 Ioulis

nodes.title: Ipnoi? M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G2 Ipnoi? M.

nodes.title: Isthmia
nodes.description: Isthmia was an ancient city located on the Isthmus of Corinth and was the site of a major sanctuary sacred to Poseidon, as well as the site of the panhellenic Isthmian games.

nodes.title: Isthmos
nodes.description: The Isthmus of Corinth is a narrow land bridge connecting the Peloponnese peninsula to the Greek mainland.

nodes.title: Ithome M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B3 Ithome M.

nodes.title: Kalaureia (island)
nodes.description: An island near the coast of Troezen in the Peloponnesus.

nodes.title: Polonnaruwa
nodes.description: An ancient city of the Kingdom of Polonnaruwa dating ca. AD 1070. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1982.

nodes.title: House of the surgeon
nodes.description: The so-called "House of the Surgeon" is considered to be one of the oldest domus in Pompeii. (VI, 1, 10, 23)

nodes.title: Aphrodite sanctuary at Lokroi Epizephyrioi
nodes.description: The worship of Aphrodite is significant in the colonial city of Lokroi Epizephyrioi.

nodes.title: Centocamere at Lokroi Epizephyrioi
nodes.description: The so-called "Centocamere" is an urban complex within the city walls dating to the fourth and third centuries B.C. This complex is laid out a organized city blocks separated by planned streets.

nodes.title: Cistern
nodes.description: A Roman period cistern of Olbia on Sardinia.

nodes.title: Tomb of Caius Cartilius Poplicola
nodes.description: The Tomb of Caius Cartilius Poplicola, dating to ca. 30-20 B.C., is a monumental tomb outside the Porta Marina of Ostia. Poplicola was a prominent citizen of Ostia.

nodes.title: Catacombs of Trypiti
nodes.description: The rock-cut Catacombs of Milos date from the first to fifth centuries.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Tlos
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Tlos preserves 34 rows of seating.

nodes.title: Vicus Censorius
nodes.description: A street located on the Tiber Island that connected the Pons Cestius and Pons Fabricius. It is cited on the so-called "Capitoline Base".

nodes.title: Temple E at Selinus
nodes.description: A fifth century B.C. Doric temple, sacred to perhaps Hera or Dionysus, located on the eastern hill at Selinus.

nodes.title: Temple of Demeter at the Sanctuary of Demeter Malophoros, Selinus
nodes.description: The Temple of Demeter was used for the worship of Demeter (Malophoros), goddess of fertility, grain and agriculture. Built in the seventh century BC, the temple was used continuously until its abandonment ca. 250 BC

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Guildhall, London
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater of London, now beneath the Guildhall Art Gallery, was discovered in 1988.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Paestum
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Paestum was built ca. 50 B.C., making it one of the earliest extant amphitheaters.

nodes.title: Roiate
nodes.description: A fortified pre-Roman center connected with the Aequi. The ancient name of the site is unknown.

nodes.title: Pyramid of Cestius
nodes.description: An ancient pyramid-shaped tomb built for Caius Cestius (ca. 18-12 BC), a magistrate and member of the Septemviri Epulonum. The tomb stands at the fork of the ancient Via Ostiensis and was later incorporated into the city's fortifications.

nodes.title: Sep. Eurysacis
nodes.description: The tomb of a baker, M. Vergilius Eurysaces, built at the point where the via Labicana and the via Praenestina exit from Rome's walls to the east. The tomb dates to the later Republican period (ca. 50-20 B.C.).

nodes.title: Coastal Tower 16b (Old Mawbray)
nodes.description: Coastal Tower 16b, part of the Hadrian's Wall Coastal defences

nodes.title: Nazzano Romano
nodes.description: Nazzano Romano was the site of an Etruscan settlement covering some 7 hectares and dating between the eighth and fifth centuries B.C.

nodes.title: Erechtheion
nodes.description: The Erechtheion is a temple on the north side of the Athenian Acropolis dedicated to Athena Polias and other deities and heroes; the temple is of the Ionic order with several distinctive features, including its famous caryatid porch.

nodes.title: Basilica and convent of S. Ippolito
nodes.description: An important paleochristian complex located in the area of Portus.

nodes.title: So-called Caesareum of Cyrene
nodes.description: A large architectural complex on the east side of the acropolis ridge in Cyrene that was probably built at the beginning of the first century AD and used as a gymnasium, but was later repurposed as forum in Flavian times, when the rooms north of the complex were levelled in order to build a large basilica. Various ruins can still be seen, including the podium of a temple in the central area, possibly dedicated to Dionysos. A fragmentary inscription referring to the "portico of Caesar", found over the inner side of the porch, made the place known as Caesareum.

nodes.title: Temenos of Athena
nodes.description: Area on the north-east side of the Piana di Himera, delimited by walls and containing four religious buildings (temples A, B, C and D), probably dedicated to Athena. The foundations are still visible in the archaeological site of Himera.

nodes.title: Ramesseum
nodes.description: The funerary temple of Ramesses II, built within the area known as the Ipet-isut, "The Most Selected of Places", along the Nile River.

nodes.title: Eshnunna
nodes.description: An ancient Sumerian and Akkadian city in the Diyala Valley (modern Tell Asmar in Diyala Province, Iraq).

nodes.title: Tuttul
nodes.description: Tuttul was a Bronze Age city that is associated with the archaeological site of Tell Bi'a located in the Raqqa Governorate of northern Syria. The tell lies near the confluence of the Balikh and Euphrates rivers.

nodes.title: Aqua Augusta (Naples)
nodes.description: The Aqua Augusta (Naples), also known as the Acquedotto romano del Serino, is a complex aqueduct system supplying Roman-period sites in the Bay of Naples. The aqueduct system was built between ca. 33 and 12 B.C. It supplied a number of Campanian centers, including Pompeii, Herculaneum, and Puteoli.

nodes.title: Hellenistic-Roman theater at Sarno
nodes.description: An ancient theater.

nodes.title: Poggio del Molino
nodes.description: A Roman villa overlooking the Tyrrhenian sea located within the former territory of Populonia.

nodes.title: Dún Ailinne
nodes.description: An ancient ceremonial site located in County Kildare, Ireland. The circular enclosure once covered ca. 13 ha.

nodes.title: Qasr al-Abd at Tyrus
nodes.description: A Hellenistic palace constructed in the second century CE at the southern end of the Tyrus/'Iraq al-Amir site.

nodes.title: Upper Chambers at Kalhu
nodes.description: This ornately-decorated, elevated building might have been the residence of Sammu-ramat (the legendary Semiramis) in the palace of her son Adad-nārārī III (r. 810-783 BC) at Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud). Because these rooms were built noticeably higher than the surrounding area, its first excavator Austen Henry Layard believed that he had uncovered part of an upper floor of an Assyrian palace and, therefore, referred to this area as the “Upper Chambers.”

nodes.title: Sceilg Mhichíl
nodes.description: A monastic complex on Skellig Michael established in the seventh century A.D. and enrolled as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1996.

nodes.title: Villamassargia, Nuraghe di Santu Pauli
nodes.description: A nuragic complex situated atop a low hill near Villamassargia, Sardinia.

nodes.title: Su Carroppu
nodes.description: A Neolithic rock-shelter settlement.

nodes.title: Vicus sandalarius
nodes.description: A street in regio IV, the Vicus Sandalarius ("street of the sandal-makers"), likely was located north-east of the Templum Pacis. The magistri of the Vicus sandalarius dedicated an altar to Augustus in 2 B.C. Augustus also dedicated a statue to Apollo in the same street. In later times many of the city's bookshops were located there.

nodes.title: Necropolis of Ponte Messato
nodes.description: A pre-Roman and Roman period necropolis on the outskirts of Teramo.

nodes.title: Via Ciminia
nodes.description: The Via Ciminia was a Roman road that left the Via Cassia and continued toward the Ciminian hills. Its course likely ran from Sutrium to near Viterbo.

nodes.title: Compitum Acilii
nodes.description: The Compitum Acilii was a crossroads in the city of Rome. It was most likely the intersection of the Vicus Cuprius and another street on the Carinae.

nodes.title: Mahabodhi Temple
nodes.description: One of the four main Buddhist pilgrimage sites, identified as the place where Gautama Buddha attained Enlightenment. The first temple on the site was built by Emperor Asoka in the third century B.C., and the present temple dates from the fifth or sixth centuries. It is one of the earliest Buddhist temples built entirely in brick, still standing in India, from the late Gupta period. The site was largely abandoned from the twelfth-eighteenth centuries. It was named a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2002.

nodes.title: Stadium of Delos
nodes.description: Stadium in the settlement of Delos, constructed in the early 3rd century BCE.

nodes.title: Anmurru
nodes.description: A fortress in the vicinity of Til-garimmu fortified by the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) against Urarṭu.

nodes.title: Kammanu/Meliddu (kingdom)
nodes.description: A kingdom in eastern Anatolia, whose capital is classical Melitene (modern Arslantepe). Meliddu, which is sometimes referred to as Kammanu, was conquered by the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II and its territory was given to Kummuhu.

nodes.title: Tabālu (region)
nodes.description: Tabal is a region in the eastern and southeastern part of the central Anatolian high plateau (roughly the area of Cappadocia) and it is divided into several principalities (including Bīt-Purutaš) and city-states.

nodes.title: Hilakku (region)
nodes.description: Hilakku is a mountainous region near Tabālu and Que in the Cilician plain. Its exact location is still debated among scholars. Nevertheless, Hilakku has been tentatively identified as being in the area of Bolkar Dağları or in that of Göksu-Tal, in the western part of Cilicia, that is, in the classical Cilicia Tracheia/Cilicia Aspera.

nodes.title: Que (kingdom)
nodes.description: Country in the Cilician Plain (Cilicia Pedias) that is known from first-millennium-BC Neo-Assyrian, Neo-Babylonian, Hebrew, Aramaic and Hieroglyphic Luwian sources.

nodes.title: Sam'alla (kingdom)
nodes.description: Sam'alla (šmʾl; also known as Bīt-Gabbāri and yʾdy) was a small Aramean kingdom/city-state during the first half of the first millennium BC. It is named after its capital city Sam'al (modern Zincirli Höyük).

nodes.title: Tablis
nodes.description: A place located between Lugdunum Batavorum and Noviomagus.

nodes.title: Tomb of Publius Vesonius Phileros
nodes.description: An aedicula tomb built near the Porta Nocera ca. A.D. 25-50 by Publius Vesonius Phileros for himself, his patroness Vesonia, and his friend Marcus Orfellius Faustus. A later added inscription shows a falling out between the two friends.

nodes.title: Saqqarah
nodes.description: A pharaonic necropolis serving the ancient Egyptian city of Memphis. It was most active during Early Dynastic and Old Kingdom Egypt. The step pyramid complex of the Third Dynasty Pharaoh Djoser is the best preserved and most well known structure of the site.

nodes.title: Exomvourgo
nodes.description: A mountain on the island of Tinos with archaeological evidence for habitation beginning in the Late Bronze Age and concluding with the remains of a Venetian fortress.

nodes.title: Tawern Roman temple complex
nodes.description: This reconstructed (in-situ) temple complex stands on a hill called Metzenberg, just to the southwest of modern Tawern in Germany. A partially excavated Gallo-Roman vicus lies at the foot of the hill, closer to town.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Cádiz
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Cádiz was one of the largest in the Roman world, accommodating some 20,000 spectators. It dates originally to the first century B.C. In the thirteenth century it was incorporated into a fortress built by King Alfonso X of Castile.

nodes.title: Arco de los Blanco
nodes.description: A Roman gateway.

nodes.title: Harbor at Lechaion
nodes.description: The ancient harbor of Lechaion on the eastern side of the Gulf of Corinth.

nodes.title: Terrace of the Lions at Delos
nodes.description: Nine white marble lions arranged in a single row along a terrace facing the sacred lake. The pathway marks an entry point into the city from the Bay of Skardana towards the shrine of Leto.

nodes.title: Church of the Acheiropoietos
nodes.description: A fifth century A.D. Byzantine church.

nodes.title: Church of St. Nicholas Orphanos
nodes.description: A fourteenth century AD church in Thessalonica

nodes.title: Castellaccio di Capo Ripa
nodes.description: A Hellenistic fortified site (?oppidum) near Capranica (Viterbo).

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Carmo
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Carmo could accommodate 18,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Alcázar del rey Don Pedro
nodes.description: A fortification at Carmona built by Pedro I of Castile.

nodes.title: Re-Buried Hellenistic Temple and Workshops
nodes.description: Excavations on site of post office at 49 Ben Ami St. revealed Hellenistic remains, including a dedication to Zeus Soter on behalf of Antiochos VII by a courtier (SEG XIX 9094). This inscription was associated with Hellenistic architecture of a temple-like character. Nearby workshops also uncovered.

nodes.title: City gate at Patara/Arsinoe
nodes.description: An extant gate of Patara on the south-west coast of Lycia.

nodes.title: Bouleuterion
nodes.description: A Bouleuterion complex at Nicopolis in Epirus.

nodes.title: Jaén
nodes.description: A Spanish city located in Andalusia that once belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Jaén.

nodes.title: Villa of Agrippa
nodes.description: The so-called Villa (or baths) of Agrippa on Planasia Ins. (modern Pianosa) is the putative location of exile for Agrippa Postumus, grandson of Augustus.

nodes.title: Son Bou Basilica
nodes.description: A three-aisled Paleochristian basilica of the fifth century A.D. located in the village of Son Bou in Menorca, Spain.

nodes.title: House of the Ara Maxima
nodes.description: The House of the Ara Maxima, located on the Via del Vesuvio, is also known as the House of Pinarius and the House of Narcissus (VI, 16, 15-17).

nodes.title: House of Trebius Valens
nodes.description: The House of Aulus Trebius Valens (III,2,1) is an atrium-style house in Pompeii that lies on the north side of Via dell'Abbondanza. It was first excavated in 1913.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: East Midlands: Verulamium → Londinium → Durobrivae → Col. Lindum → Petuaria

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: East Anglia: Branodunum → Venta →Col. Camulodunum → Londinium

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Wales and the Marches: Kanovium → Deva → Viroconium → Ariconium → Venta → ‘Bornio’ → Moridunum

nodes.title: Rha/Attila (river)
nodes.description: The modern Volga river is the longest river in Europe.

nodes.title: Via Domitia
nodes.description: The Via Domitia connected Italia and Hispania and was built ca. 118 BC by Cnaeus Domitius Ahenobarbus around the time Colonia Narbo Martius (Narbonne) was founded.

nodes.title: Asia Minor
nodes.description: An ancient region, coincident with a peninsula of the continent of Asia. It is bounded on the south by the Mediterranean Sea, on the west by the Aegean Sea, and on the north by the Black Sea. Today it is part of the territory of the modern country of Turkey.

nodes.title: Moridunum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 unlocated Moridunum

nodes.title: Abonouteichos/Ionopolis
nodes.description: A coastal town of Paphlagonia.

nodes.title: Amastris/Sesamos
nodes.description: An ancient settlement on the Black Sea coast in Asia Minor, modern Amasra in Turkey.

nodes.title: Amnias (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 D2 Amnias fl.

nodes.title: Billaios (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 C2 Billaios fl.

nodes.title: Bithynion/Claudiopolis/Hadriana
nodes.description: An ancient settlement in Bithynia, modern Bolu in Turkey.

nodes.title: Cappadox? (river)
nodes.description: The ancient Cappadox river may be identified with the modern watercourse known as the Delice River (Turkish: Delice Irmağı). This river is a tributary of the Kızılırmak River (the ancient Halys).

nodes.title: Elaios (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 B2 Elaios fl.

nodes.title: Gangra
nodes.description: Also known as Germanicopolis or Germanopolis. An ancient settlement in Paphlagonia, modern Çankırı in Turkey.

nodes.title: Heraclea
nodes.description: An ancient settlement on the Black Sea coast of Asia Minor at modern Karadeniz Ereğli in Turkey. It is often referred to as Heraclea Pontica (or Heraclea in Pontus) to distinguish it from other cities with the same name.

nodes.title: Iustiniani Pons
nodes.description: The Bridge of Justinian or Sangarius Bridge is a Late Roman bridge built by the emperor Justinian I across the Sangarius river. The bridge's original span was ca. 430 m.

nodes.title: Kales (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 B2 Kales fl.

nodes.title: *Kobara
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 D3 *Kobara

nodes.title: Krateia/Flaviopolis/*Agrippeia?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 C3 Krateia/Flaviopolis/*Agrippeia?

nodes.title: Atlanticus Oceanus
nodes.description: Atlanticus Oceanus (The Atlantic Ocean) likely derives its name from Atlas, one of the Titans of Greek mythology. The Atlantic Ocean covers ca. 20% of the surface of the Earth.

nodes.title: Lykos (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 B2 Lykos fl.

nodes.title: Mariandynoi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 A3 Mariandynoi

nodes.title: Mariandynus Sinus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 A2 Mariandynus Sinus

nodes.title: Paphlagonia (region)
nodes.description: The ancient region as defined in the Barrington Atlas (BAtlas 86 C2 Paphlagonia)

nodes.title: Pompeiopolis/Sebaste
nodes.description: Pompeiopolis/Sebaste, in Paphlagonia, was founded under Pompeius in 64 B.C. in the valley of the Amnias river.

nodes.title: Prusias ad Hypium/Kieros
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 B3 Prusias ad Hypium/Kieros

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 B3 unnamed aqueduct (Prusias ad Hypium)

nodes.title: Atlas Mon(te)s
nodes.description: A major mountain range, located in northwest Africa (primarily modern Morocco).

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Dia → Heraclea → Tieion → Amastris → Abonouteichos → Sinope

nodes.title: Apatouros Kolpos
nodes.description: Apatouros Kolpos (Taman Bay) is a shallow bay or gulf on the east coast of the Strait of Kerch.

nodes.title: Cimmerius Bosp(h)orus
nodes.description: A strait between the modern Black Sea and Sea of Azov.

nodes.title: Kimmerikon
nodes.description: Kimmerikon was an ancient Greek colony in the Crimea located on the Kerch peninsula. The city was founded by Milesian colonists in the fifth century BC.

nodes.title: Korokondamitis/Opissas Limne
nodes.description: Korokondamitis/Opissas Limne (Taman Bay)

nodes.title: Myrmekion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 L2 Myrmekion

nodes.title: Myrmekion Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 L2 Myrmekion Pr.

nodes.title: Nymphaion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 K2 Nymphaion

nodes.title: Ain el-Gedida
nodes.description: Roman/late antique settlement, with substantial remains of an industrial area, a church complex, and a mud-brick temple reused as a ceramic workshop.

nodes.title: Baetica
nodes.description: Hispania Baetica was a Roman senatorial province that beings with the Augustan restructuring of the provinces in 27 B.C. The provine was bounded by the Anas river in the west and the Sierra Morena mountains to the north.

nodes.title: Albanum Mare
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 88 H3 Albanum Mare

nodes.title: Albanos (river)
nodes.description: The Samur river.

nodes.title: Alontas (river)
nodes.description: A major river of the Northern Caucasus that flows from Georgia to the Caspian Sea.

nodes.title: Triumphal Arch of Orange
nodes.description: A triumphal arch most likely built during the reign of Augustus to honor veterans of the Gallic Wars and Legio II Augusta.

nodes.title: Theater of Pergamon
nodes.description: The Greek Theater of Pergamon dates ca. 225 -200 B.C.

nodes.title: Church of the Saviour, Thessaloniki
nodes.description: The Church of the Saviour, Thessaloniki is a fourteenth century Byzantine church.

nodes.title: Church of Saint Panteleimon
nodes.description: The Church of Saint Panteleimon (Thessaloniki) is a late Byzantine church.

nodes.title: Gyaur-Kala, Merv
nodes.description: The fortifications of the ancient city of Gyaur Kala in the Merv Oasis.

nodes.title: Hagia Sophia, Thessaloniki
nodes.description: A church to Saint Sophia dating originally from the third century A.D.

nodes.title: Valle dei Templi
nodes.description: The "Valle dei Templi" of Agrigento is an archaeological site in Sicily located on a ridge, as opposed to the false suggestion of the conventional name, outside modern Agrigento.

nodes.title: Scheggia Pass
nodes.description: The Scheggia Pass marks the division between the Central and Northern Apennines in northern Umbria. Its elevation is 632 meters above sea level.

nodes.title: Syreanos
nodes.description: An ancient sanctuary of Zeus attested in inscriptions found on "the upland plain of Makas Alan between the [Phrygian] cities of Kotiaeion (Kiitahya) and Nakoleia (Seyitgazi)" in modern Turkey (Drew-Bear). Its precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Tautaendia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 unlocated Tautaendia

nodes.title: Trikomia 3
nodes.description: One of several "Trikomiai" attested in the ancient Greek and Roman world. This presumed settlement cannot be located today, but probably lay in what is today the country of Turkey, somewhere between Dorylaion (Eskişehir) and Pessinous (Ballıhisar).

nodes.title: Ancyra
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 63 B1 Ancyra

nodes.title: Andabalis
nodes.description: Andabalis was a settlement of southern Cappadocia located northeast of Tyana.

nodes.title: Arg(ai)os Mons
nodes.description: Mount Hasan, Hasan Dağı in Turkish, is an inactive stratovolcano and the second highest peak in Anatolia.

nodes.title: Gallograecia (region)
nodes.description: A region in Hellenized Galatia.

nodes.title: Garsaura/Col. Claudia Archelais/Koloneia
nodes.description: Originally known as Garsaura, this place was a key settlement of the strategia of Garsaouritis. King Archelaus refounded it and named it after himself. Under the Roman emperor Claudius the site received colonial status. The settlement is located at an oasis to the southeast of Tuz Gölü and some 225 km south of Ancyra.

nodes.title: Taouion/Tabia
nodes.description: The main settlement of the Galatian tribe of the Trocmi, it was inhabited from the fourth millennium BCE.

nodes.title: Trokmoi
nodes.description: An ancient Celtic people who likely migrated into Anatolia in the early third century BCE.

nodes.title: Villa Palmati
nodes.description: Jones describes this place as the site of an 'imperial stud farm' that produced race horses.

nodes.title: *Zizima
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 63 A4 *Zizima

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 63 A4 unnamed mine (near *Zizima)

nodes.title: Karissa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 63 unlocated Karissa

nodes.title: Laskoria/Lassora
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 63 unlocated Laskoria/Lassora

nodes.title: Mithridation
nodes.description: Described by Strabo as a "walled fortress" "which Pompey gave to Bogodiatarus".

nodes.title: Oukena/Oukaina
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 63 unlocated Oukena/Oukaina

nodes.title: Posdala
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 63 unlocated Posdala

nodes.title: Rastia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 63 unlocated Rastia

nodes.title: Tetrapyrgia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 63 unlocated Tetrapyrgia

nodes.title: Mut el-Kharab
nodes.description: The settlement of Mut el-Kharab, located in Egypt's Dakhleh Oasis. A temple to the god Seth was built at this location.

nodes.title: Anisa
nodes.description: Anisa was an ancient settlement of Cappadocia that was inhabited in Hellenistic, Roman, and Byzantine times.

nodes.title: Antitaurus Mons
nodes.description: A mountain range of SE Turkey, extending N of the Taurus mountains.

nodes.title: Argaeus (mountain)
nodes.description: Erciyes Dağı in Turkish. A massive volcanic mountain, the highest peak of the Antitaurus range. Commonly depicted on coins from Cappadocia.

nodes.title: Ariaratheia
nodes.description: An ancient settlement in Asia Minor, located at modern Pınarbaşı (former Aziziye/Azizie) in Turkey.

nodes.title: Armenia Minor
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 64 G2 Armenia Minor

nodes.title: Capotes? M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 64 H1 Capotes? M.

nodes.title: Cappadocia (region)
nodes.description: A region that stretched from Lake Tatta in the east to the upper Euphrates River and from the Black Sea southward to Cilicia.

nodes.title: Dascusa
nodes.description: A fortress in Armenia Minor on the river Euphrates, some 75 Roman miles from Zimara.

nodes.title: Gauraina
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 64 E3 Gauraina

nodes.title: Palace of Sennacherib
nodes.description: The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib built a magnificent royal residence in the citadel of Nineveh. This extensive architectural complex was given the Sumerian ceremonial name Egalzagdinutukua, which means "Palace Without a Rival." A small portion of the once-grand Assyrian palace is still visible today.

nodes.title: Kidmuri Temple
nodes.description: The bīt Kidmuri is one of the temples located in the citadel of Nineveh. Its Sumerian ceremonial name is not preserved in extant cuneiform sources. Although the temple's exact location remains unknown, it is generally believed to have been between the temple of the goddess Ištar (Emašmaš) and the Citadel Gate (East Gate).

nodes.title: Akītu-Temple of Ištar
nodes.description: The New Year’s House (or Akītu Temple) of Nineveh's tutelary deity Ištar appears to date back at least to the Middle Assyrian period (reign of Tukultī-Ninurta I). Its Sumerian ceremonial name is not preserved in extant cuneiform sources. This temple's exact location remains unknown and it is certain whether Ištar's Akītu Temple was located in the citadel or in the lower town.

nodes.title: Palace of Ashurbanipal
nodes.description: The Neo-Assyrian king Ashurbanipal built a grand royal residence in the citadel of Nineveh. It was located north and east of the temples of the god Nabû (Ezida) and the goddess Ištar (Emašmaš), and it was constructed on the site of an older, smaller palace. Ashurbanipal referred to this palace as the bīt redûti ("House of Succession"); in scholarly literature, it is often referred to as the "North Palace." A small portion of the once-grand Assyrian palace is still visible today.

nodes.title: Handuru Gate
nodes.description: Most 7th-century B.C. Assyrian inscriptions record that Nineveh had eight south- and east-facing gates: the Handūru Gate was the first of these. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Šarur-mušamqit-ayyāb-šarri ("The God Šarur Is the One Who Cuts Down the King's Enemy"). This unlocated gate is now generally thought to have been located near southwest corner of the city.

nodes.title: Mašqû Gate
nodes.description: Nineveh's western wall had seven (or eight) gates: the Mašqû Gate was the northernmost one. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Ea-mušēšir-kuppīya, which means "The God Ea Is the One Who Properly Directs (Water Flow into) My Cisterns."

nodes.title: Step Gate of the Palace
nodes.description: Nineveh's western wall had seven (or eight) gates: the Step Gate of the Palace was the second gate from the northern city wall. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it sometime between 694 and 691 B.C. and he gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Libūr-ēpissa, which means "May Its Builder Endure." The gate is still unlocated, but, based on its everyday name Akkadian name mušlālum ša ēkalli ("Step Gate of the Palace"), it must have led up to Sennacherib's Palace on the citadel, perhaps up to the harem or its northern section.

nodes.title: Quay Gate
nodes.description: Nineveh's western wall had seven (or eight) gates: the Quay Gate was the fourth gate from the northern city wall. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Mušēribat-miširti-dadmē, which means "The One Who Brings in Income from the Settlements."

nodes.title: Step Gate of the Armory
nodes.description: Nineveh's western wall had seven (or eight) gates: the Armory Gate (later Step Gate of the Armory) was the fifth gate from the northern city wall. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial names Pāqidat-kalāma ("The One Who Regulates Everything") and Lū-dāri-bānûša ("May Its Builder Live Forever").

nodes.title: Citadel Wall of Nineveh
nodes.description: The citadel of Nineveh was surrounded by a thick mud-brick wall. When the 7th-century B.C. king Sennacherib made Nineveh the capital of the Assyrian empire, that wall was rebuilt and strengthened; its base was reinforced with limestone blocks along its southern stretch.

nodes.title: Ponte d'Augusto
nodes.description: A Iulio-Claudian bridge located in Ariminum.

nodes.title: Arx of Cosa
nodes.description: The citadel of the ancient city and location of its Capitolium.

nodes.title: Comitium of Poseidonia/Paestum
nodes.description: The comitium is a component of a monumental forum complex constructed at Paestum after the city became a Latin colony in 273 B.C.

nodes.title: Arch of Trajan at Benevento
nodes.description: A triumphal arch built in honor of Trajan at Beneventum; it marks the Trajanic extension of the Via Appia.

nodes.title: Archiepiscopal Chapel of Ravenna
nodes.description: A private, early Christian oratory in Ravenna, Italy, erected by Peter II as archbishop in A.D. 495.

nodes.title: Ešasurra
nodes.description: The temple of the god Išhara, Ešasurra (“House of the Womb”), was located in the Šuanna district (modern Ishin Aswad) of Babylon. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, this was one of two temples in that part of the city, which was located in the southern part of the eastern half of Babylon.

nodes.title: tribus Tities
nodes.description: An early Roman tribal division said to date from the time of Romulus.

nodes.title: Public administration buildings
nodes.description: The administration buildings on Pompeii's forum were built before 80 B.C. and renovated following the earthquake of A.D. 62. The central building is generally regarded as the tabularium.

nodes.title: Temple of Vespasian
nodes.description: The "Temple of Vespasian" (VII, 9, 2), also referred to as Aedes Genii Augusti, is situated between the Temple of the Lares Publici and the Building of Eumachia on the eastern side of the forum of Pompeii. Its precise attribution is still a matter of debate.

nodes.title: Temple of Fortuna Augusta
nodes.description: A Corinthian order temple in Pompeii dedicated to Fortuna Redux and likely dating to the late first century BC (VII, 4, 1).

nodes.title: House of the Dioscuri
nodes.description: A large and well-appointed house that takes its name from frescoes of Castor and Pollux (VI, 9, 6).

nodes.title: House of Apollo
nodes.description: Located on the Via di Mercurio, the so-called House of Apollo draws its name from a cycle of frescoes of the myth of Apollo found at the rear of the garden. One M. Herenullius Communis, whose name appears on a ring found in 1830, may have been the owner (VI, 7, 23).

nodes.title: House of the Baker
nodes.description: House in Pompeii (VI,3,3) that most likely dates from the second century BC and experienced extensive remodeling after the earthquake of AD 62.

nodes.title: So-called Tempio di Venere e Cupido
nodes.description: The so-called Temple of Venus and Cupid at Rome is part of the complex of buildings associated with the Sessorian palace. The structure's modern assignation is owed to the discovery of a fragmentary statue of Sallustia Orbiana in the guise of Venus Felix. Sallustia Orbiana was the wife of Alexander Severus. The statue is now held in the Museo Pio Clementino in the Vatican Museums.

nodes.title: Canopus at Hadrian's Villa
nodes.description: The Canopus garden is set at the principal entrance to Hadrian's Villa. An imposing waterway occupies all its length.

nodes.title: Formello villa and mausoleum
nodes.description: A Roman villa in the territory of Blera of which a cistern and a mausoleum remain.

nodes.title: Verlamion

nodes.title: Via Collatina

nodes.title: Via Tiburtina

nodes.title: Gibil Gabib
nodes.description: Gibil Gabib is an archaeological site on a high mountain (615 m asl) in Sicily with evidence for long-range occupation stretching from prehistoric times to the Hellenistic period.

nodes.title: Ponte Rotto necropolis
nodes.description: The Ponte Rotto necropolis is associated with the Etruscan city of Vulci.

nodes.title: Tagisken South
nodes.description: Saka necropolis with burials from the 7th-5th century BCE on the Tagisken plateau.

nodes.title: Cantiano

nodes.title: Stadium at Aizanoi
nodes.description: The Stadium at Aizanoi is adjacent to the theater.

nodes.title: Roman baths at Oescus

nodes.title: Pont Serme

nodes.title: Arian Baptistry

nodes.title: Circus of Col. Tarraco
nodes.description: The Roman circus of Tarragona dates from the reign of Domitian. The circus measures ca. 325 meters in length and ca. 100 to 115 meters in width.

nodes.title: Gimtu

nodes.title: Arch of Constantine

nodes.title: Temple of Maharraqa

nodes.title: Obelisk of Theodosius
nodes.description: Obelisk of Theodosius is an ancient Egyptian obelisk created at Karnak under Thutmoses III (1479–1425 BC) that was transported to Constantinople by the Roman emperor Theodosius I and re-erected in late the fourth century AD.

Located near the modern city of Казанлъ̀к (Kazanlak) in Bulgaria, the site was excavated in the 1940s and subsequently submerged by the filling of the Koprinka reservoir.
