nodes.description: An ancient settlement, described by Strabo as lying "on the left of the Pontus, between Naulochus and Odessos, near Mount Haimos". Its modern location is uncertain, although it may correspond to a fortified settlement on the St. Athanasius Cape near modern Byala in Bulgaria.

nodes.title: Oboulensioi
nodes.description: The Oboulensioi were an ancient people of Moesia Inferior.

nodes.title: Acesinus? (river)
nodes.description: The Inhulets River is a right tributary of the Dnieper River that flows through the Ukraine.

nodes.title: Ak-Mechet'
nodes.description: A major Scythian kurgan of the 5th c. BC partially excavated in 1885.

nodes.title: Borysthenes (river)
nodes.description: The Dnieper River.

nodes.title: Charax
nodes.description: Charax was a Scythian, and later, Roman, fortress founded on the Ai-Todor promontory near ancient Chersonesus in the third century BC.

nodes.title: Chersonesos
nodes.description: Chersonesos was an ancient Greek colony founded in the southwestern part of the Crimean Peninsula, ancient Taurica. Settlers from Heraclea Pontica established the site in the sixth century B.C.

nodes.title: Coretus Sinus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 23 H2 Coretus Sinus

nodes.title: Danuvius/Istros/Hister (river)
nodes.description: The Danube river.

nodes.title: Dort Oba
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 23 H3 Dort Oba

nodes.title: Gerros (river)
nodes.description: The Molochna River is a river of south Ukraine that flows from Zaporizhia Oblast, Ukraine, to the Azov Sea.

nodes.title: Kerkinitis?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 23 G3 Kerkinitis?

nodes.title: Neapolis
nodes.description: An important Scythian settlement, capital of the late Scythian state on the Crimean peninsula.

nodes.title: Panskoye 1
nodes.description: Panskoye 1 was an agricultural settlement in the Crimea founded by by Chersonesus in the late fourth century BC.

nodes.title: Peukes/Hieron Stoma
nodes.description: The southernmost mouth of the Danube river, described by Strabo as "hieron stoma" or the "holy mouth".

nodes.title: Psilon Stoma/Thiagola
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 23 C3 Psilon Stoma/Thiagola

nodes.title: Taurike Chersonesos
nodes.description: The Crimean Peninsula, located in the northern Black Sea.

nodes.title: Tyras (river)
nodes.description: The Dniester river flows from Ukraine to the Black Sea.

nodes.title: Chaika
nodes.description: Settlement in western Crimea, probably founded by Chersonesus in the fourth century BCE. The city was destroyed in the second century BCE by the Scythians, who established a trading center on the same site that lasted until the first centuries CE.

nodes.title: Hermonaktos Kome
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 23 unlocated Hermonaktos Kome

nodes.title: Ad Lippos/Appos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F4 Ad Lippos/Appos

nodes.title: Aquae Flaviae
nodes.description: Aquae Flaviae (modern Chaves, Portugal).

nodes.title: Astura (river)
nodes.description: Astura fl. (Esla river)

nodes.title: Asturia (region)
nodes.description: Asturia is a region of the Atlantic coast of northern Iberia.

nodes.title: Asturica (Augusta)
nodes.description: Asturica (Augusta) was the capital of the Conventus Asturum. An Augustan colony was established in 14 B.C.

nodes.title: B(a)edunia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F2 B(a)edunia

nodes.title: Boreios/Gallicus/Cantabricus Oceanus
nodes.description: The Bay of Biscay.

nodes.title: Bracara Augusta
nodes.description: With settlement from the Neolithic onwards, Bracara Augusta was established as a civitas in 20 B.C. In the third century A.D. Diocletian advanced the settlement to the capital of the administrative area known as Conventus Bracarensis, forming part of the Roman province of Gallaecia.

nodes.title: Brevis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 C2 Brevis

nodes.title: Brigaecium/Brigeco
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F2 Brigaecium/Brigeco

nodes.title: Arienzo
nodes.description: A villa of the second century AD that was destroyed by a flood in the fourth century.

nodes.title: Bir Ftouha basilica
nodes.description: An Early Christian pilgrimage complex and baptistry at Carthage.

nodes.title: Porta Romanelli
nodes.description: A section of ashlar masonry fortification walls, including a gate, at Tarquinii.

nodes.title: Banditaccia necropolis, Caere
nodes.description: The Etruscan necropolis of Caere, a UNESCO World Heritage site.

nodes.title: Monterozzi necropolis
nodes.description: The Monterozzi necropolis is an Etruscan necropolis located to the east of Tarquinia. The necropolis contains about 6,000 graves.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Florentia
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Florentia was built between 124 and 130.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Nicopolis
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Nicopolis incorporates both Greek and Roman architectural practices in its construction.

nodes.title: Small Roman theater at Vendeuil-Caply
nodes.description: Site of the small Roman theater on Le Mont Châtelet.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Mogontiacum
nodes.description: The site of the Roman theater in Mainz.

nodes.title: Roman Theater at Bosra
nodes.description: The Roman Theater at Bosra dates to the second century A.D.

nodes.title: Madrasa Gumushtakin
nodes.description: Center of the Madrasa Gumushtakin in the Ancient City of Bostra.

nodes.title: Roman aqueduct bridge
nodes.description: An aqueduct bridge crossing a small ravine, built of brick and now encrusted with stalactites.

nodes.title: Torre di Mercurio
nodes.description: A tower associated with Pompeii's fortification wall that is also sometimes designated as "Tower XI".

nodes.title: Skellig Michael
nodes.description: An island in the Atlantic Ocean located just west of the coast of Ireland.

nodes.title: Via Campana?
nodes.description: A road located on the right bank of the Tiber leading to the Campus Salinarum romanarum and sharing the first part of its course with the Via Portuensis.

nodes.title: Via Flavia
nodes.description: An ancient Roman road that connected Tergeste to Dalmatia and followed the course of the Istrian coast. The road was built during the reign of emperor Vespasian.

nodes.title: Su Mulinu
nodes.description: A nuragic complex with three phases of occupation and construction, beginning as early as the sixteenth century B.C.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Perdu Cossu
nodes.description: A monopteral nuraghe located near Norbello, Sardinia.

nodes.title: Tomb of Trebius Iustus
nodes.description: A Late Antique hypogeum tomb discovered in 1911 and dedicated to Trebius Iustus and Honoratia Severina.

nodes.title: Pons Fabricius
nodes.description: The Pons Fabricius (sometimes referred to as the Ponte dei Quattro Capi) is a first century BC bridge in Rome that spans part of the Tiber from the area of the Circus Flaminius to the Tiber island.

nodes.title: Basilica of Santa Maria in Trastevere
nodes.description: The Basilica di Santa Maria in Trastevere is a titular minor basilica located in the Trastevere district of Rome, Italy.

nodes.title: Vaticanus Mons
nodes.description: A hill located across the Tiber from Rome's traditional seven hills, the Vaticanus Mons now lies within the territory of Vatican City.

nodes.title: Velia
nodes.description: The Velia, no longer extant, was a spur stretching from the north side of the Palatine Hill toward the Oppian Hill.

nodes.title: Archaeological area of Macchia Grande
nodes.description: The archaeological area of Macchia Grande provides archaeological evidence for multiple phases of human occupation from the Villanovan period to the Roman Imperial period.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater of Italica
nodes.description: The amphitheater of Italica, built in the second century A.D., was one of the largest in the Roman world and could accommodate an estimated 25,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Hispania Citerior
nodes.description: Province of the Roman Republic in the Iberian peninsula. In the first century BCE Augustus incorporated Hispania Citerior into the new province of Hispania Tarraconensis.

nodes.title: Italia, Regio I
nodes.description: One of the administrative regions from Augustus's division of Italy, comprising Latium and Campania. Described by Pliny the Elder in Book III of his Natural History.

nodes.title: Macedonia (Archaic and Classical kingdom)
nodes.description: Founded by the Argead dynasty, the kingdom of Macedonia was originally located on the political, social, and cultural periphery of Greece. It was allied with the Persian Empire, and the Macedonian king Alexander I supplied troops to fight the Athenian/Spartan alliance at the Battle of Platea in 479 BCE. Thereafter Macedonia became increasingly part of the Greek political world, which culminated in Philip II's subjugation of the majority of Greece after the Battle of Chaeronea in 338 BCE. Alexander III ("the Great') expanded Macedonian control over the entirety of the Persian Empire. After Alexander's death in 323 BCE the kingdom was fought over by his successors who declared themselves kings in 306 BCE, effectively ending the unified kingdom.

nodes.title: Great Mosque of Aleppo
nodes.description: The Great Mosque of Aleppo, also known as the Umayyad Mosque of Aleppo, is the largest and one of the oldest mosques in the city of Aleppo, Syria.

nodes.title: Jebel Akhdar (Oman)
nodes.description: Coordinates after GeoHack.

nodes.title: Jebel Shams
nodes.description: Jebel Shams (Arabic: جبل شمس‎, (mountain of sun) rises to 2,818 m (9,245 ft) asl and is the highest summit of the Al Hajar Mountains in Oman.

nodes.title: Mains Rigg signal tower
nodes.description: The Mains Rigg signal tower was revealed by excavations (1928; 1971-2) to measure 6.5 m square.

nodes.title: Tomb of the Volumnii and Palazzone necropolis
nodes.description: A hypogeum-type tomb located in Ponte San Giovanni, a suburb of Perugia. The tomb is generally dated to the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Casa del Diavolo
nodes.description: A Roman villa (second to fourth centuries A.D.) located near ancient Forentum.

nodes.title: Fayyum (oasis)
nodes.description: Large depression (not a true oasis) west of the Nile River containing arable land watered by the flooding of the Nile. Inhabited from the Mesolithic period, the Fayyum contains the earliest evidence of farming in Egypt. The water levels of the Fayyum's lake varied significantly until a land reclamation project during the 12th dynasty implemented artificial water controls. During the Ptolemaic and Roman periods, the Fayyum was administered as the Arsinoite Nome.

nodes.title: Quartier du Stade at Delos
nodes.description: Neighborhood surrounding the stadium in the settlement of Delos, constructed during the Hellenistic period.

nodes.title: Bīt-Purutaš (kingdom)
nodes.description: A kingdom located in northern Tabal, in the vicinity of modern Kayseri. This area was briefly under Assyrian control during the reign of the eighth-century-BC king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC).

nodes.title: Que (province)
nodes.description: Que became an Assyrian province during the reign of the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Shalmaneser V (726-722 BC).

nodes.title: Arch of Augustus (Fano)
nodes.description: A city gate in the form of a triumphal arch with three vaults. The gate marks the entry of the via Flaminia into the city.

nodes.title: Cardo Maximus
nodes.description: The Cardo Maximus of Saepinum.

nodes.title: Decumanus maximus of Carsulae
nodes.description: The Decumanus maximus of Carsulae.

nodes.title: Basilica of Carsulae
nodes.description: The civic Basilica of Carsulae is located on the forum.

nodes.title: Arch of Trajan at Ancona
nodes.description: An arch erected to honor Trajan between A.D. 100 and 116.

nodes.title: Mausoleum of the Julii
nodes.description: The mausoleum of the three Julii brothers, ca. 40 B.C.

nodes.title: Porte de Mars
nodes.description: The Porte de Mars is a Roman triumphal arch in Reims, France, that dates from the third century A.D.

nodes.title: Hypogeum of Ħal-Saflieni (Malta)
nodes.description: A prehistoric, subterranean temple; named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1980.

nodes.title: Lamiospito Tholos Tomb, Dimini
nodes.description: Late Helladic III B tholos tomb on the west foot of the Neolithic hill settlement.

nodes.title: Topazios (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Red Sea. The island is noted by Pliny as a source of topaz.

nodes.title: Bernashivka
nodes.description: Site of a settlement from the Neolithic Cucuteni-Trypillia culture, located on the left bank of the Dniester River.

nodes.title: Morgantina, House of Ganymede
nodes.description: The House of Ganymede at Morgantina is a peristyle house with mosaic floor pavements. The earliest phase of the house belongs to the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Ekklesiasterion of Morgantina
nodes.description: The monumental central staircase in the agora of Morgantina has been identified as the Ekklesiasterion. They date after the middle of the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Albinia Roman villa
nodes.description: The remains of a villa rustica near Orbetello, found to have construction in opus latericium.

nodes.title: Theater of Stratos
nodes.description: The Theater of Stratos dates to the late fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: Habuba Kabira (South)
nodes.description: The southernmost of two associated settlements located on the western bank of the Euphrates, and one of the only examples of large-scale residential architecture from the Late Uruk period. Rescue excavations were conducted at the site before it was inundated by the Tabqa Dam Reservoir in the early 1970s.

nodes.title: Angkor Wat
nodes.description: The principal temple of Angkor, the capital city of the Khmer empire, Angkor Wat was constructed in the 12th century CE. Angkor was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage site in 1992.

nodes.title: Temple of Dionysos at Teos
nodes.description: A Temple of Dionysos in the Ionic order begun in the Hellenistic period.

nodes.title: Thermae Diocletiani
nodes.description: Public baths near the Viminal Hill in Rome constructed under Diocletian from 298-306 CE.

nodes.title: Isis Tomb
nodes.description: Now lost, the so-called "Isis Tomb" was excavated at Vulci in the 19th century. Based on finds evidence, the tomb is traditionally dated ca. 625 to 550 B.C. Its traditionally assigned name is likely a misnomer, based on a contemporary identification of a bronze bust as representing the Egyptian goddess Isis. The subsequent back-filling of the tomb and uncareful recording at the time have caused the tomb's location to be lost to us.

nodes.title: Ponte di Diocleziano, San Lazzaro di Fossombrone
nodes.description: The so-called "Ponte di Diocleziano" in the local comune of San Lazzaro di Fossombrone was a Roman bridge along the Via Flaminia in the valley of the Metaurus river. The Roman bridge was completely destroyed during the Second World War.

nodes.title: Tagisken North
nodes.description: Late Bronze-early Iron Age necropolis on the Tagisken plateau used throughout the first half of the first millennium BCE.

nodes.title: Catacombs of San Senatore
nodes.description: A Christian catacomb located at the fifteenth mile of the Via Appia in use from the late third century A.D. until the Middle Ages.

nodes.title: Cercadilla
nodes.description: A Late Roman palace complex connected with the emperor Maximian.

nodes.title: Nea Kameni
nodes.description: In the present-day caldera, Nea Kameni is the larger of the two volcanogenic islands formed over the last two millennia. It is a geological successor of Cameini, and was likely formed before, or during, the major period of volcanic activity in 1866-1870.

nodes.title: Mikro Kameni
nodes.description: Mikro Kameni is a non-extant island that was formed in the Santorini caldera some time before 1851, when it was attested in the Admiralty Chart of Robert Graves, HMS Volgae. It was joined to Nea Kameni at some point after this, probably in the major period of volcanic activity in 1866-1870.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Appiu
nodes.description: A nuragic complex in northwest Sardinia.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Volaterrae
nodes.description: The archaeological remains of an amphitheater were discovered at Volterra in 2015. Preliminary work suggests that the structure measured ca. 70 x 90 meters and had three tiers of seats that could accommodate 8,000 to 10,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Portone necropolis at Volaterrae
nodes.description: The so-called Portone necropolis is a major Hellenistic necropolis outside the walls of Volaterrae.

nodes.title: Eurmeiminanki
nodes.description: The ziggurat of the god the god Nabû at Borsippa. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eurmeiminanki means "House which Gathers the Seven (Me's) of Heaven and Underworld."

nodes.title: Eulmaš
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Ištar at Agade.

nodes.title: Elugalgalgasisa
nodes.description: The ziggurat of the god Sîn at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Elugalgalgasisa means "House of the King who Lets Counsel Flourish". The platform temple was originally built during the Early Bronze Age and was then restored in the sixth century B.C. by King Nabonidus.

nodes.title: Ekinu
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Aya at Sippar. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ekinu means "House, Bed-Chamber."

nodes.title: Eigikalamma
nodes.description: The temple of the god Lugal-Marda at Marad. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eigikalamma means "House, Eye of the Land."

nodes.title: Ebabbar
nodes.description: The temple of the god Šamaš at Sippar. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ebabbar means "Shining House."

nodes.title: Insula 104 at Hierapolis
nodes.description: A well-excavated residential section of the Phrygian city of Hierapolis, dated to the proto-Byzantine period (ca. 2nd century CE).

nodes.title: Pago Triopio
nodes.description: The Pago Triopio is a monumentalized area located near the mausoleum of Caecilia Metalla between the second and fourth mile of the Via Appia. The residence of Herodes Atticus was located here.

nodes.title: Columbarium of the freedmen of Augustus
nodes.description: An early imperial columbarium tomb on the Via Appia.

nodes.title: Tomba del Timpano
nodes.description: A rock-cut tomb of the sixth and fifth centuries B.C.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Viminacium
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Viminacium could accommodate roughly 12,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Casinum
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Casinum was built thanks to the patronage of Ummidia Quadratilla in the first century.

nodes.title: Civitas Camunnorum amphitheater
nodes.description: The ruins of a Roman amphitheater.

nodes.title: Temple B
nodes.description: A temple vowed by Q. Lutatius Catulus at the battle of Vercellae (30 June, 101 B.C.). The sanctuary is a tholos-type temple and was sometimes referred to as 'aedes Catuli'.

nodes.title: Porta Leoni
nodes.description: A Republican gate of Verona dedicated by P. Valerius, Q. Caecilius, Q. Servilius and P. Cornelius.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Uthina
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Uthina dates to the reign of Hadrian and seated about 16,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Tomb of Thutmes I and Hatshepsut (KV20)
nodes.description: KV20 may be the earliest tomb cut in the Valley of the Kings. It was first the tomb of Thutmose I, although he was later re-interred in KV38. KV20 was adapted to accommodate both her and her father.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Cumae
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater at Cumae in Campania.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Kodros, Neleus and Basile at Athens
nodes.description: A sanctuary located between the Phaleron gate and the Itonian gate of Athens.

nodes.title: Gymnasium at Akragas
nodes.description: An architectural complex in the upper agora of Akragas (modern Agrigento) dedicated to Hermes and Heracles that was probably used as gymnasium. It appears to have been built in Hellenistic time and renovated in the Augustan period.

nodes.title: Tomb of Theron
nodes.description: Theron was a fifth century B.C. tyrant of Akragas. A tomb located near the Porta Aurea of the city is traditionally referred to as being that of the tyrant.

nodes.title: tribus Velina
nodes.description: The tribus Velina was one of the later rural tribes which was established in Rome in 241 B.C.

nodes.title: Lacus Curtius
nodes.description: The Lacus Curtius is an area in medio foro connected with the earliest phases of Rome's occupation. By the late Republican period it had become a small basin set inside a paved area. Livy relates the famous episode of the Sabine Mettius Curtius in relation to his description of the site.

nodes.title: Vicus Sobrius
nodes.description: A street in Rome mentioned by Festus.

nodes.title: Via Flaminia
nodes.description: A major Roman road connecting Rome and Ariminum, by way of Narnia and Nuceria. The road was begun under the censorship of Caius Flaminius Nepos in 220 B.C.

nodes.title: Giza
nodes.description: The site of Giza encompasses the Giza Necropolis, a large archaeological site famous for its pyramid complexes and monumental sculpture.
nodes.featureTypes: sanctuary, cemetery, pyramid, tomb, settlement, architecturalcomplex

nodes.title: Apollo Cynneius
nodes.description: Sanctuary of Apollo Cynneius near or in Temnos, destroyed by Prusias II in 155 BCE. Its precise location is unknown today but certainly lies within Barrington Atlas Map 56 grid E4.

nodes.title: Camp of Diocletian at Palmyra
nodes.description: Camp of Diocletian in the Ancient City of Palmyra. Coordinates determined by eye in Google Earth in November 2012, following description in UNESCO World Heritage List.

nodes.title: Temple of Nabu at Palmyra
nodes.description: A temple dedicated to the Babylonian god of wisdom.

nodes.title: Shalmaneser Gate
nodes.description: The “Shalmaneser Gate” gave access from the lower town of Kalhu to the citadel. This entrance, which was flanked by a pair of inscribed stone lions, was located on the east citadel wall, just north of the Nabû temple Ezida. This gate, which its excavators named after the ninth-century-BC Assyrian ruler Shalmaneser III (r. 858–824 BC), is assumed to have been the main east citadel gate, especially since a road ran between it and the armory (Fort Shalmaneser) located in the southwest corner of the city.

nodes.title: Temple of Thelsae
nodes.description: A well-preserved Roman period temple located in modern Dmeir, Syria. The sanctuary was later converted into a fortification.

nodes.title: Temple of Jupiter Anxur
nodes.description: A late Republican sanctuary of the city of Terracina that is typically dated ca. 100-70 B.C.

nodes.title: Amphitheater of Pompeii
nodes.description: The Amphitheater of Pompeii is the earliest known surviving example of a Roman amphitheater. It was built between 80 and 70 B.C.

nodes.title: Review Palace
nodes.description: An Assyrian armory was built to the south of the citadel at Nineveh. The ruins of the 7th-century B.C. architectural complex are directly below the modern settlement built on top of Nebi Yunus, the site's smaller mound.

nodes.title: Palace of Naqi'a
nodes.description: The influential Neo-Assyrian queen Naqi’a built a royal residence for her son Esarhaddon in the citadel of Nineveh. This palace, which may have served as a summer residence for the Assyrian king and his mother, remains unlocated. It is certain from contemporary Akkadian inscriptions that the palace was constructed near the Sîn-Šamaš temple, but the exact location of that temple is not known.

nodes.title: Aššur Gate
nodes.description: Most 7th-century B.C. Assyrian inscriptions record that Nineveh had eight south- and east-facing gates: the Aššur Gate was the second of these. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial names Lilbur-iššak-Aššur ("May the Vice-Regent of the God Aššur Endure") and Libūr-iššak-Aššur ("May the Vice-Regent of the God Aššur Stay in Good Health").

nodes.title: Sennacherib Gate
nodes.description: Most 7th-century B.C. Assyrian inscriptions record that Nineveh had eight south- and east-facing gates: the Sennacherib Gate was the third of these. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Sāpin-gimir-nakirī, which means "The One Who Flattens All Enemies." During the reign of Sennacherib's grandson, the gate was renamed the Ashurbanipal Gate.

nodes.title: Šamaš Gate
nodes.description: Most 7th-century B.C. Assyrian inscriptions record that Nineveh had eight south- and east-facing gates: the Šamaš Gate was the fourth of these. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Enlil-mukīn-palêya, which means "The God Enlil Is the One Who Makes My Reign Firm."

nodes.title: Mullissu Gate
nodes.description: Most 7th-century B.C. Assyrian inscriptions record that Nineveh had eight south- and east-facing gates: the Mullissu Gate was the fifth of these. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial names Ištar-zāninki-kurbī ("O Ištar Bless the One Who Provides for You!") and Ša-Sîn-ahhē-erība-manzalti-ereqqi-kinnī-palêšu ("Make Sennacherib's Dynasty as Firm as the Position of the Wagon Constellation!").

nodes.title: Barhalzi Gate
nodes.description: Nineveh's western wall had seven (or eight) gates: the Barhalzi Gate was the sixth gate from the northern city wall. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it sometime between 694 and 691 B.C. and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Anum-nāṣir-napištīya, which means "The God Anu Is the Protector of My Life."

nodes.title: Desert Gate
nodes.description: Nineveh's western wall had seven (or eight) gates: the Desert Gate was the southernmost gate along that stretch of wall. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it sometime between 695 and 691 B.C. and he gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Kadrê-Tēme-u-Sumuʾel-qerebša-irrub ("The Presents of the People of Tēma and Sumuʾel Enter Through It").

nodes.title: Royal Road of Nineveh
nodes.description: As part of transformation of Nineveh’s lower town at the beginning of the 7th century B.C., the Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib created a broad royal road that ran all the way through the city. That fifty-two-cubit-wide road, whose ancient ceremonial name is not known, is still unlocated, but it is generally thought to have run north from the Aššur Gate, east past the armory and the citadel, to the Sîn Gate (formerly the Gate of the Gardens).

nodes.title: Khosr River
nodes.description: The Khosr River was a tributary of the Tigris River that ran directly through the center of the Assyrian city Nineveh. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib reinforced its banks with large stone blocks to prevent it from flooding or damaging the citadel wall.

nodes.title: Conventus Bracaraugustanus
nodes.description: The Conventus Bracaraugustanus or Conventus Bracarus was a sub-provincial administrative district of the Roman empire located in the northwestern part of the Iberian Peninsula, in Gallaecia. Its capital was located at Bracara Augusta.

nodes.title: Roman Circus (Bosra)
nodes.description: The Roman circus of Bosra dates to the third century.

nodes.title: Temple of Apollo at Corinth
nodes.description: The second temple of Apollo at Corinth whose reconstructed remains are visible on the site today. The structure dates ca. 540 B.C.

nodes.title: Mithraeum at Vulci
nodes.description: A mithraeum was discovered at Vulci in 1975 during excavations of a Roman aristocratic house. The shrine was well preserved with two tauroctony scenes dating to the third century. The site was destroyed in the fourth century A.D.

nodes.title: Puig de Sa Morisca
nodes.description: A first millennium B.C., pre-Roman settlement of Majorca.

nodes.title: So-called Temple of the Dioscuri
nodes.description: Temple in the acropolis of Cyrene, probably built around the VII century BC

nodes.title: So-called Temple of Cybele
nodes.description: Recently discovered temple in the acropolis of Cyrene

nodes.title: So-called Temple of Aphrodite
nodes.description: Temple in the acropolis of Cyrene

nodes.title: Monument at Ain bou Merzoug
nodes.description: Unlabeled feature captured from the Barrington Atlas

nodes.title: Unnamed spring supplying Tubusuctu via aqueduct
nodes.description: Unlabeled feature captured from the Barrington Atlas

nodes.title: Unnamed spring supplying Thuburbi Minus via aqueduct
nodes.description: Unlabeled feature captured from the Barrington Atlas

nodes.title: Spring at Ain-el-Hamera
nodes.description: Unlabeled feature captured from the Barrington Atlas

nodes.title: San Nicola in Carcere
nodes.description: San Nicola in Carcere is a titular church in Rome's historical district (rione) Sant'Angelo, close to the Forum Boarium. The twelfth century church is built atop the remains of Roman temples of the Forum Holitorium and incorporates their remains into its structure.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Pan at Paneas
nodes.description: The Paneion at Caesarea Philippi, a sanctuary site dedicated to Pan centered around a natural cave and spring site on the southwestern slopess of Mount Hermon. The sanctuary was first built in the Hellenistic period (before 200 BCE). A temple to Augustus was constructed in front of the cave during the reign of Herod the Great in 19 BCE, and the site was further expanded through 220 CE.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater, Córdoba
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater of Córdoba.

nodes.title: Cerreto Sannita
nodes.description: A Samnite temple dedicated to Flora.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Asusa
nodes.description: A nuraghe standing on a modest hill (502 meters above sea level) on the Brabaciera river. The nuraghe originally had two towers with an intermediary courtyard.

nodes.title: Adoni
nodes.description: A Late Bronze age nuragic complex composed of a central tower, a quadrilobate bastion, and a village.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Rumanedda
nodes.description: A nuraghe located near Tottubella in the territory of Sassari.

nodes.title: Sa Mandra Manna
nodes.description: A fortified site in Sardinia with megalithic architecture.

nodes.title: Erek Dağ
nodes.description: Erek Dağ is a mountain in the Van Province in eastern Anatolia. It is the second-highest peak of the province of Van, rising to 3200 meters above sea level.

nodes.title: Acropolis of Cumae
nodes.description: The Acropolis of Cumae was used across multiple periods, beginning with the foundation of the Greek colony in the eighth century B.C.

nodes.title: Esquilinus Mons
nodes.description: The Esquiline Hill is one of the seven hills of Rome. The eastern section of the hill lay outside the Servian Wall, and served as a pauper's cemetery during the archaic and Republican periods.

nodes.title: Grotta Porcina tumulus
nodes.description: A rock-cut tumulus of the first half of the sixth century B.C.

nodes.title: Macchia delle Valli, Vetralla
nodes.description: A rock-cut Etrusco-Roman sanctuary sacred to Demeter that was discovered during rescue excavations in 2006 following looting activity. The sanctuary, set in a grove, remained in use until the second century A.D.

nodes.title: Vigna Parrocchiale archaeological area
nodes.description: A complex of civic and sacred buildings in the urban area of ancient Caere, including the so-called "elliptical building".

nodes.title: Sha'ar Hagolan
nodes.description: A Neolithic settlement of the Yarmukian culture, located on the northwestern bank of the Yarmuk River approximately 1.5 km south of the Sea of Galilee. At 20 hectares, it is one of the largest known Neolithic settlements in the Near East.

nodes.title: Orcia (river)
nodes.description: The Orcia originates on Monte Cetona and is a major tributary of the Ombrone.

nodes.title: Abbazia di Sant'Antimo
nodes.description: The Abbey of Sant'Antimo was a Benedictine monastery located in the comune of Montalcino, Italy, about 9 km from the line of the Via Francigena. The abbey grew around the site of an oratory to Saint Anthimus, whose relics may have been relocated here in the eighth century. The site was formerly occupied by a Roman villa.

nodes.title: Pons Sublicius
nodes.description: The Pons Sublicius is traditionally held to be the earliest Roman bridge across the river Tiber. The textual tradition assigns its construction to the king Ancus Marcius in 642 B.C. It crossed the Tiber near the Forum Boarium just downstream from the Tiber Island.

nodes.title: Castle of Serravalle
nodes.description: The Castle of Serravalle is a twelfth century castle located in Bosa, province of Oristano, Sardinia. It is connected with the Tuscan Malaspina family.

nodes.title: Forum Augusti
nodes.description: The Forum of Augustus at Rome was dedicated in 2 BCE, to the northeast of Julius Caesar's Forum. It contained the Temple of Mars Ultor.

nodes.title: Pano Mantilaris
nodes.description: Site of a late Bronze Age settlement near the modern village of Alassa, southern Cyprus.

nodes.title: Paliotaverna
nodes.description: Site of a late Bronze Age settlement near the modern village of Alassa, southern Cyprus.

nodes.title: Filitosa
nodes.description: Filitosa is a megalithic site in southern Corsica that was in use from the Neolithic period until Roman times. A number of menhirs have been discovered at the site.

nodes.title: Araghju
nodes.description: A prehistoric site of the Torrean civilization in Corsica.

nodes.title: Lago di Castiglione
nodes.description: An ancient caldera lake near Gabii (ancient name unknown) that has been drained and filled in modern times.

nodes.title: Su Nuraxi di Barumini
nodes.description: A nuragic site in Barumini, Sardinia that was named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1997

nodes.title: Mausoleum of Lucilius Peto
nodes.description: A tumulus-type tomb discovered in 1887 belonging to the military tribune M. Lucilius Peto of the gens Lucilia.

nodes.title: Sep. Scipionum
nodes.description: A family tomb of the Cornelii Scipiones near the Porta San Sebastiano in use from the third century B.C. to the first century A.D.

nodes.title: Peshawar
nodes.description: Ancient Peshawar was a capital of the Gandharan kingdom from the second century AD, when it was known as Purushapura.

nodes.title: Via Hadriana
nodes.description: A Roman road established by Hadrian running from Antinoopolis to Berenice. The road was completed in AD 137.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Volsinii
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Volsinii dates to the second half of the first century A.D. It measures ca. 86 x 69 meters.

nodes.title: Black Pyramid
nodes.description: The pyramid of the Middle Kingdom Pharaoh Amenemhat III.

nodes.title: Gorkhatri
nodes.description: A complex in Peshawar, constructed as a caravanserai in the 16th century CE. The site itself seems to go back much earlier (to perhaps the 3rd century CE) and may be mentioned in early travelers' accounts.

nodes.title: Roman baths of Ebora
nodes.description: The Roman baths of Ebora were in use during the second and third centuries. The archaeological site was discovered in 1987.

nodes.title: Novaya Beden'ga I
nodes.description: Hillfort site in the watershed between the Volga and Sviyaga rivers. The site shows signs of habitation in the Late Scythian period (1st-3rd centuries CE) and the Hunnish period (4th-6th centuries CE).

nodes.title: Pupinia
nodes.description: The tribus Pupinia was one of the oldest rural tribes of ancient Rome. Festus indicates that its name is derived from an area lying between Tusculum and Rome.

nodes.title: Villa di Faragola
nodes.description: A Late Roman villa site near Ausculum.

nodes.title: Gymnasium at Olympia
nodes.description: The Gymnasium of Olympia was a practice and training field constructed in 250 BC for male Hellenic athletes competing in the Olympic Games.

nodes.title: Library of Hadrian at Athens
nodes.description: The Library of Hadrian is located on the north side of the Acropolis, immediately north of the Roman Agora. The complex was built by the Roman emperor Hadrian in A.D. 131/2 and subsequently destroyed during the Herulian sack of Athens in A.D. 267.

nodes.title: Temple of Apollo at Thermos
nodes.description: A temple to the Apollo built in the late seventh century B.C. atop the ruins of the previous megaron in Thermos.

nodes.title: So-called East Church in Apollonia
nodes.description: A Christian church located in the ancient city of Apollonia (Cyrenaica) built approximately in the fifth century A.D., probably on earlier Hellenistic foundations. The site was excavated in 1922 and shows a three-aisled nave with transept at the eastern end, and a single apse. Traces of the mosaic floor are still visible.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Burnum
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater associated with the legionary establishment of Burnum.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Salona
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Salona.

nodes.title: Dragoncello
nodes.description: Dragoncello is a modern district of Rome's metropolitan area where archaeological evidence for a series of late republican villas was uncovered. At least four in number, these villa rustica sites have evidence for domestic production.

nodes.title: Basilica of Lechaion
nodes.description: The basilica of Lechaion was dedicated to Leonides, the bishop of Athens. It is one of the most important early Byzantine monuments in the Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Sanctuary at Leben
nodes.description: Leben is known for the sanctuary of Asclepius.

nodes.title: Nymphaeum at Cupra Marittima
nodes.description: The nymphaeum at Cupra Marittima was associated with a Roman villa.

nodes.title: Theater at Phoinike
nodes.description: The Greek Theater at Phoinike in Epirus.

nodes.title: Agora of the Italians
nodes.description: A Hellenistic and Roman complex on the island of Delos, the so-called "Agora of the Italians" was likely built by Roman merchants. Its precise function is debated.

nodes.title: Temple of Iuno Moneta at Signia
nodes.description: The remains of the Temple of Iuno Moneta on the acropolis of Segni support the later (tenth century) church of St. Peter.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Sutri
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Sutri likely dates to the reign of Augustus.

nodes.title: Church of the Holy Apostles
nodes.description: A fourteenth century church at Thessalonica.

nodes.title: Prata Mucia
nodes.description: The so-called Prata Mucia was a meadow granted to the Roman Republican hero Mucius Scaevola in recognition of his heroism in the face of the invasion of Lars Porsena of Clusium.

nodes.title: Pagus Ianiculensis
nodes.description: Pagus Ianiculens is a name for a district of the Transtiberim during the Republican period. The name is attested in two inscriptions of ca. 100 B.C., one of which was found in an opus signinum pavement near the church of Santa Maria dell'Orto.

nodes.title: S. Porphyrius
nodes.description: The oldest Orthodox church in Gaza, sacred to the fifth century Saint Porphyrius whose tomb lies within the church.

nodes.title: Mahalliba
nodes.description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources; the modern site is Maḥālib.

nodes.title: Pyramid of Amenemhat III
nodes.description: Pyramid and tomb of Pharaoh Amenemhat III of the Twelfth Dynasty.

nodes.title: Villa of Diomedes
nodes.description: A suburban villa of Pompeii located outside the Herculaneum gate, the Villa of Diomedes was excavated between 1771 and 1774 and named after the tomb of Marcus Arrius Diomedes which faces the entrance on the opposite side of the road.

nodes.title: Africa Proconsularis (late Roman province)
nodes.description: The late Roman province of Africa Proconsularis, within the Diocese of Africa.

nodes.title: Mauretania Tingitana (late Roman province)
nodes.description: A late Roman province within the diocese of Hispaniae.

nodes.title: Aqueduct south of Djebel Zid
nodes.description: An aqueduct connected to areas of centuriation north of Segermes

nodes.title: Cuicul
nodes.description: A Berbero-Roman town of North Africa (modern Djémila in Algeria). Sometimes labeled on maps and in travel information as "Curculum".

nodes.title: Djebel Taya
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 G3 Djebel Taya

nodes.title: Hippo Regius
nodes.description: Hippo Regius (modern Annaba in Algeria) was a colony established by Phoenicians from Tyre as early as the twelfth century BC.

nodes.title: Mauretania
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 B4 Mauretania

nodes.title: Numidia (region)
nodes.description: Numidia was an ancient region of North Africa. From the late third century B.C. to 40 B.C. the territory was controlled by the ancient kingdom of the Numidians. It later became a Roman client state. Numidia was located in what is now Algeria, as well as parts of Tunisia and Libya in the Maghreb. In pre-Roman terms the polity was divided between the Massylii in the east and the Masaesyli in the west.

nodes.title: Rusicade/Thapsus
nodes.description: Rusicade/Thapsus was the port of Cirta and a Roman colonia, located at the mouth of the small river Thapsus.

nodes.title: Saldae
nodes.description: Founded by Numidian Berbers, the settlement of Saldae (modern Béjaïa, Algeria) was a minor port during phases of Carthaginian and Roman occupation. The Roman emperor Vespasian established a veteran colony there, at a time when Saldae was part of the province of Mauretania Caesariensis.

nodes.title: Thapsus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 F3 Thapsus fl.

nodes.title: Thubursicum Numidarum
nodes.description: Thubursicum Numidarum (now Khamissa, Algeria) is an indigenous site that became a Roman municipium by A.D. 100 (Municipium Ulpium Traianum Augustum Thubursicu).

nodes.title: *Tiddis
nodes.description: *Tiddis (or Castellum Tidditanorum) was a Roman city located in the Constantine Province in Algeria.

nodes.title: Tubusuctu
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 B3 Tubusuctu

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 B3 unnamed aqueduct (Tubusuctu)

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 F3 unnamed aqueduct (Rusicade and spring)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 F4 unnamed aqueduct (from Ain bou Merzoug to Cirta)

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 H3 unnamed aqueduct (Hippo Regius)

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct supplying Thubursicum Numidarum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 H4 unnamed aqueduct (Thubursicum Numidarum)

nodes.title: Mausoleum of Quintus Lollius Urbicus
nodes.description: Quintus Lollius Urbicus served as a governor of Britannia between 139 and 142. His career is detailed on a pair of inscriptions from his hometown of Tiddis. His mausoleum is located at Tiddis.

nodes.title: Unnamed tunnel on the aqueduct supplying Saldae
nodes.description: An aqueduct tunnel, near Saldae, sometimes referred to as the Nonius Datus tunnel.

nodes.title: Ad Piscinas
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 unlocated Ad Piscinas

nodes.title: Ad Villam Serviliana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 unlocated Ad Villam Serviliana

nodes.title: Turres
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 unlocated Turres

nodes.title: Ain-el-Hamera
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 F4 Ain-el-Hamera

nodes.title: Ain Ouassel
nodes.description: Ain Ouassel or Ain Wassel is a rural archaeological site dated to the early Byzantine period. The site contained a mix-use farm.

nodes.title: Avitta Bibba
nodes.description: Avitta Bibba was a settlement located in the Roman province of Africa Proconsularis.

nodes.title: Carthago
nodes.description: The ancient city of Carthage, located in modern Tunis (Tunisia).

nodes.title: Fundus Aufidianus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 E3 Fundus Aufidianus

nodes.title: Hermaia Akra/Mercurii Pr./Kalon Akroterion?
nodes.description: Cap Bon is a peninsula of northeastern Tunisia.

nodes.title: *Matar
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 E2 *Matar

nodes.title: Municipium Aurelium Commodianum/Thibiuca?
nodes.description: An ancient city whose site is now known as Henchir-Zouitina in modern Tunisia.

nodes.title: Musti
nodes.description: Musti was a Roman municipium located along the road from Carthage to Tebessa.

nodes.title: Naraggara
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 B4 Naraggara

nodes.title: Pheradi Maius
nodes.description: Pheradi Maius was a civitas of Africa Proconsularis. The archaeological site is today located near the village of Sidi Khelifa, Tunisia.

nodes.title: Sicca Veneria
nodes.description: Sicca Veneria was an important Punic and Roman city located in what is now Tunisia.

nodes.title: Simitthu
nodes.description: A city of Africa Proconsularis, Simitthu is especially noted for its marble quarries.

nodes.title: Thabraca
nodes.description: Thabraca was a maritime city of Numidia located at the mouth of the river Tusca.

nodes.title: Thagaste
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 A4 Thagaste

nodes.title: Thagura
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 B4 Thagura

nodes.title: Thizika
nodes.description: Thizica was a civitas in the Roman province of Africa Proconsularis.

nodes.title: Thuburbo Minus
nodes.description: A settlement in Africa Proconsularis, mentioned in the Itinerarium Antonini and the Tabula Peutingeriana.

nodes.title: Thuburbo Maius
nodes.description: An ancient settlement with extensive archaeological remains, located north across the river Kebir from the modern city of El Fahs in Tunisia.

nodes.title: Thugga/Tokai?
nodes.description: Thugga/Tokai? (Dougga) is an ancient site in Tunisia with a rich heritage that includes Numidian-Berber, Punic, ancient Roman, and Byzantine phases. The city's Roman phase is particularly well preserved and UNESCO listed the site as a World Heritage Site in 1997.

nodes.title: Tusca (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 C3 Tusca fl.

nodes.title: Uchi Maius
nodes.description: Uchi Maius was a township of Africa Proconsularis where Marius settled veterans. It did not achieve the status of colonia until the third century.

nodes.title: Uthina
nodes.description: Uthina was a town in the province of Africa Proconsularis with Roman colonial status.

nodes.title: Uticensis Sinus
nodes.description: The Gulf of Tunis

nodes.title: Vicus Augusti?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 D3 Vicus Augusti?

nodes.title: Zucchari(...)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 E4 Zucchari(...)

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct supplying Thuburbi Minus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 E3 unnamed aqueduct (Thuburbi Minus)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 F3 unnamed aqueduct (Carthago)

nodes.title: Aqueduct east of Djebel Zid
nodes.description: An aqueduct connected to areas of centuriation north of Segermes

nodes.title: Marble quarry near Simitthus
nodes.description: An unnamed marble quarry near Simitthus (modern Chemtou, Tunisia). The marble variety is known as marmor numidicum or giallo antico.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Hippo Regius → Thagaste → Naraggara → Sicca Veneria → Musti → Membressa → Sicilibba → Ad Pertusa → Carthago

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Musti → Sicca Veneria → Naraggara → Thagura → Map 31

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 C4 unnamed waterwheel (Chemtou, near Simitthu)

nodes.title: Sacra Via
nodes.description: The Sacra Via (Sacred Way) is one of Rome's oldest urban streets and its main sacred route, extending from the top of the Velia (summa Sacra Via) to the Forum Romanum.

nodes.title: Italia Suburbicaria
nodes.description: A vicariate of the Roman empire instituted by Constantine I. It was centered in south-central Italy.

nodes.title: Usi
nodes.description: A fortress in the vicinity of Til-garimmu fortified by the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) against Musku (Phrygia).

nodes.title: Roman theater at Suessa Aurunca
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Suessa Aurunca was built in the first century A.D. and then restored under Antoninus Pius. Amedeo Maiuri initiated excavations at the theater site in the 1920s. The excavation was not completed until 2003.

nodes.title: Ras Siyyan
nodes.description: A peninsula in the Obock Region of Djibouti located on the Bab-el-Mandeb strait between the Red Sea and the Gulf of Aden.

nodes.title: La Lône arcade, Nimes aqueduct
nodes.description: A segment of the Nimes aqueduct.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Santa Sarbana
nodes.description: A nuragic complex in Silanus, Sardinia, dating to the period ca. 1500-1000 BC.

nodes.title: Doulopolis
nodes.description: A community within the territory of Colophon. Although there is some controversy as to its status, the name suggests that the community was founded by slaves (or other dissidents) who supported Aristonikos against Rome between 133 and 130/129 BCE. It seems to have been reabsorbed by Colophon at an undetermined point after 130/129. Its location is unknown today.

nodes.title: So-called Central Church in Apollonia
nodes.description: A three-aisled basilical church, with an external apse, situated near the centre of the ancient settlement of Apollonia (Cyrenaica), about half way between the East and West churches. The building has a narthex, a small western atrium and a range of added rooms along the north flank. The mosaics have been dated around the sixth century AD, but the building seems to have been built in earlier times (possibly fifth century AD).

nodes.title: Washing Wells Roman Fort
nodes.description: The site of a Roman fort has been identified via aerial photos. It is situated in agricultural land on Dunston Hill overlooking the River Tyne, 3 miles southwest of Newcastle and ca. 1 km southeast of Whickham.

nodes.title: Roman theater of Herculaneum
nodes.description: The Roman theater of Herculaneum was constructed during the Augustan period. The theater was discovered first in 1709 while a well was being dug.

nodes.title: Kınık Höyük
nodes.description: An archaeological site in southern Cappadocia. Inhabited from the Late Bronze Age through the Middle Iron Age, Kınık Höyük was an important settlement in the Kingdom of Tuwana.

nodes.title: Odeon
nodes.description: The Odeon (VIII, 7, 19) is a small roofed theater in Pompeii. It was built between 80 and 75 BC, under commission by two public officials, C. Quinctius Valgus and Marcus Porcius.

nodes.title: Aral Sea
nodes.description: The Aral Sea, a large lake of Asia, is a remnant of the ancient Paratethys Sea. It was once one of the largest lakes in the world.

nodes.title: Samnite Palaestra
nodes.description: The so-called "Samnite Palaestra" (VIII, 7, 29) lies behind the temple of Isis. A dedication in the Oscan language dates to the second half of the second century BC.

nodes.title: House of the Ceii
nodes.description: A Roman house in Pompeii (I, 6, 15), also known as the House of L. Ceius Secundus. It is also referred to as the House of Fabia and Tyrannus.

nodes.title: House of the Lararium of Achilles
nodes.description: The so-called "House of the Lararium of Achilles" (I ,6 ,4) lies on the Via dell'Abbondanza. Excavated in 1912 and 1913, it is also known as the "House of the Ilion Sanctuary".

nodes.title: House of the garden of Hercules
nodes.description: The so-called "House of the Garden of Hercules" (II, 8, 6) is an example of an early "rowhouse" atrium building (third-second centuries BC) that was renovated in the first century BC.

nodes.title: Necropolis of Porta Nola
nodes.description: An area with three tombs located outside the Porta di Nola.

nodes.title: Kinneil
nodes.description: The site of a Roman fortlet on the Antonine Wall. The fortlet measures ca. 21.5 x 18.5 m, covering an area of ca. 0.04 ha.

nodes.title: Beltany
nodes.description: At Beltany in County Donegal, Ireland, is a Neolithic stone circle monument comprised of 64 menhirs. The monument dates ca. 1400-800 BC.

nodes.title: Altaqû
nodes.description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources, Altaqû is equated with biblical Elteqeh and modern Tel aš-Šallāf.

nodes.title: Levant (region)
nodes.description: A large historical region of the Eastern Mediterranean. Exact definitions of the region's borders vary, but in general the term "Levant" refers to the eastern littoral of the Mediterranean Sea, comprising the modern countries of Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, and Israel.

nodes.title: Tsarëv Kurgan
nodes.description: A funerary mound on the bank of the Volga River in Samara Oblast', Russia, south of Volzhskiy.

nodes.title: The "Auditorium site" at the Auditorium Parco della Musica (Rome)
nodes.description: An Early Republican to Middle Imperial elite complex along the Via Flaminia in the outskirts of Rome.

nodes.title: Porta Vesuvio
nodes.description: The so-called "Porta Vesuvio" was damaged in the earthquake of A.D. 62.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Santa Barbara
nodes.description: A nuragic site located on Monte Manai in Sardinia.

nodes.title: Roman Amphitheater at Syracuse
nodes.description: A Roman Amphitheater at Syracuse, Sicily, that was in use from the first through third centuries. The structure measured ca. 140 x 119 meters.

nodes.title: Gabbutūnu
nodes.description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources; the modern site is Gibbetôn. An alternative name is Raʾs Abī Ḥamīd.

nodes.title: Girmua
nodes.description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources; the modern site is Ǧirwān/Jerwan.

nodes.title: So-called Theatre 3
nodes.description: A Roman theatre on the acropolis ridge of Cyrene, conventionally numbered "3".

nodes.title: San Felice Roman villa
nodes.description: The villa site is located approximately 1 km. south of the presumed ancient course of the Via Appia.

nodes.title: Cathedral of the Holy Cross at Aghtamar
nodes.description: Armenian church built on the island of Aghtamar by King Gagik I Artsruni between 915-921 CE.

nodes.title: Akdamar Island
nodes.description: The second largest of the four islands in Lake Van, in eastern Turkey.

nodes.title: Ponte di Apollo, Punicum
nodes.description: A Roman bridge.

nodes.title: Hadrian's Wall (Cumbrian Coast)
nodes.description: Line of Roman fortifications along Cumbrian Coast running from western terminus of the stone wall commonly referred to as Hadrian's Wall at Maia (Bowness-on-Solway) in the north to Gabrosentum (Moresby) in the south.

nodes.title: Cabu Abbas
nodes.description: A nuragic complex near Olbia, in the province of Sassari.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Cuccurada
nodes.description: A nuragic complex composed of the nuraghe itself, a large wall, and a megalithic structure.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Zuras
nodes.description: A later nuragic site, in use from the fourteenth to the twelfth centuries BC.

nodes.title: Casteddu de Fanaris
nodes.description: A Late Bronze Age nuragic site.

nodes.title: Monte Catalfaro
nodes.description: A rocky plateau located north-east of modern Mineo, overlooking Catania, that was inhabited from prehistoric times to the Middle Ages.

nodes.title: Pigades
nodes.description: A Late Bronze Age settlement and sanctuary.

nodes.title: House of the Ancient Hunt
nodes.description: A well-appointed atrium house with Fourth Style wall paintings (VII,4,48).

nodes.title: Lupanar
nodes.description: The Lupanar (or Lupanare Grande) (VII, 12, 18–20) is located east of the forum at the intersection of Vico del Lupanare and Vico del Balcone Pensile. It is the largest of Pompeii's brothels.

nodes.title: Doric temple
nodes.description: A temple of the Doric order (VIII,7,30-34) located in the so-called Triangular Forum of Pompeii.

nodes.title: Hyctanis (river)
nodes.description: A river in Carmania mentioned by both Pliny and Strabo.

nodes.title: Fonteblanda
nodes.description: A planned Etruscan settlement in the Albegna valley along the line of the Via Aurelia founded, perhaps, ca. 570 B.C. The site offers evidence for iron working.

nodes.title: Great Bulmore
nodes.description: Site of a suburban Roman settlement on the bank of the river Usk, 2 km. north-east of the legionary fortress at Caerleon.

nodes.title: Paduline villa
nodes.description: A Roman villa located on the Bruna river that was in use from the third century B.C. until the fifth century A.D.

nodes.title: Thracian Tomb of Kazanlak
nodes.description: A fourth century BC Thracian tomb near the ancient city of Seuthopolis discovered in 1944 and inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1979.

nodes.title: Fortunatae Insulae? (Madeira Islands)
nodes.description: The modern, Portugeuse archipelago of Madeira seems to have been identified by some ancient authors with the "Fortunatae Insulae" or "Blessed Islands".

nodes.title: Afyonkarahisar Castle
nodes.description: Afyonkarahisar Castle is a Late Bronze Age fort (ca. 1350 B.C.) and may be the site of the Hittite settlement known as Hapanuwa.

nodes.title: Barcombe Hill Roman Signal Station
nodes.description: A Roman signal station on Barcombe Hill, overlooking the Stanegate and Vindolanda.

nodes.title: Tabard Square Temple Complex
nodes.description: A Romano-Celtic temple complex located near the junction of Stane Street and Watling Street in modern Southwark.

nodes.title: Tell Habuba Kabira
nodes.description: The northernmost of two associated settlements located on the western bank of the Euphrates, showing signs of habitation from the Late Uruk period through the Middle Bronze Age. Rescue excavations were conducted at the site before it was inundated by the Tabqa Dam Reservoir in the early 1970s.

nodes.title: Angkor
nodes.description: The capital city of the Khmer empire, founded in the late 9th century by Yasovarman I (889-901). The city was sacked in 1431 by invaders from the Ayutthaya kingdom, and was abandoned except for the temple of Angkor Wat, which remained a Buddhist shrine.

nodes.title: Zakros
nodes.description: A Minoan site in eastern Crete and the location of a Bronze Age palatial center.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater of Asisium
nodes.description: In the Porta Perlici of Assisi are the remains of a first century A.D. Roman amphitheater.

nodes.title: Bouleuterion of Onchestos
nodes.description: The Bouleuterion of Onchestos has been identified adjacent to the Temple of Poseidon.

nodes.title: Theater at Letoon
nodes.description: An ancient theater associated with the Letoon, a sanctuary of Leto near the ancient city Xanthos in Lycia. The theater is located on the Roman agora, to the the north of the acropolis.

nodes.title: Triconch Palace at Butrint
nodes.description: The so-called Triconch Palace.

nodes.title: Arènes de Cimiez
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater of the second century that was enlarged during the course of the third, the so-called Arènes de Cimiez measures 67 by 56 meters.

nodes.title: Porta Venere
nodes.description: One of the six gates of the Roman period fortification wall.

nodes.title: Hippodrome at Ptolemais/Barkes Limen
nodes.description: The Hippodrome at Ptolemais/Barkes Limen (Cyrenaica, Libya).

nodes.title: Amphitheatre of El Jem
nodes.description: Third century A.D. Roman amphitheater; declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1979.

nodes.title: Basilica of Hildeguns
nodes.description: A basilica dating to the time of the Vandals.

nodes.title: Murus Servii Tullii
nodes.description: The Republican city wall of Rome.

nodes.title: Necropolis of Montessu
nodes.description: The Necropolis of Montessu is located near Villaperuccio, Sardinia. It is the site of about 40 domus de Janas tombs and dates to the third millennium B.C.

nodes.title: Dún Aonghasa
nodes.description: A prehistoric fort in the Aran Islands of County Galway, Ireland, dating ca. 1100 BC.

nodes.title: Porta Solestà
nodes.description: The Porta Solestà is one of the gates of Ascoli Piceno.

nodes.title: Neapolis
nodes.description: After the sacking of Jerusalem, Vespasian settled Roman veterans on a new town site located between Mt. Gerizim and Mt. Ebal. The new Roman colony was built on the site of Mabartha.

nodes.title: Oneuatha/*Anabatha
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 F1 Oneuatha/*Anabatha

nodes.title: Pacida (river)
nodes.description: The Kishon River flows from the Gilboa mountains to the Mediterranean Sea.

nodes.title: Ras el-'Ain
nodes.description: An ancient settlement in the southern part of modern Lebanon, known by various names in antiquity.

nodes.title: Paneas/Caesarea Philippi
nodes.description: An ancient settlement at the southwest foot of Mount Hermon, located in the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights, just across the Lebanese border.

nodes.title: Phoenice (region)
nodes.description: Ancient Phoenicia.

nodes.title: Samaria (region)
nodes.description: The ancient region of Samaria.

nodes.title: Samaria/Sebaste
nodes.description: Samaria/Sebaste was an ancient city of Iudaea. In 30 B.C. it passed under the control of Herod the Great and was renamed Sebaste in honor of the emperor Augustus.

nodes.title: Sarepta/Makra Kome
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B3 Sarepta/Makra Kome

nodes.title: Scythopolis/Nysa
nodes.description: A settlement located at the juncture of the Jordan and Jezreel valleys, Scythopolis/Nysa had important Egyptian through Roman phases.

nodes.title: Sidon/Col. Aurelia Pia
nodes.description: Sidon/Col. Aurelia Pia is an ancient maritime city and Phoenician metropolis

nodes.title: Stratonos Pyrgos/Caesarea
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 A4 Stratonos Pyrgos/Caesarea

nodes.title: Sychem
nodes.description: An ancient settlement in the Levant, attested Biblically and in ancient Egyptian documents and the Amarna letters. Scholars associate this settlement with the archaeological site of Tel Balata, which is located in the modern West Bank and has seen attention from archaeologists since the early 20th century.

nodes.title: Thelseai
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 E2 Thelseai

nodes.title: Tiberiadis Mare/Gennesar Lacus
nodes.description: The Sea of Galilee, also known as the Sea of Tiberias, is the largest freshwater lake in Israel.

nodes.title: Tiberias
nodes.description: Tiberias was founded by Herod Antipas ca. 20 BC.

nodes.title: Tyrus/Col. Septimia Severa
nodes.description: The ancient city of Tyre (modern es-Sur on the coast of Lebanon). A UNESCO World Heritage Site, in part because of its "important archaeological remains, mainly from Roman times."

nodes.title: ‘Valle Diocletiana’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 F2 ‘Valle Diocletiana’

nodes.title: Vallis Alba
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 F2 Vallis Alba

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct (at Gaba Philippi)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B4 unnamed aqueduct (Gaba Philippi)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 C2 unnamed aqueduct (Berytus)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: A Roman bridge located in what is now Lebanon that crosses the Litani River (Leontes). The bridge is located in the vicinity of Nahr Abou Assouad, approximately 10 km north of Tyre.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B3 unnamed mole (so-called Agger Alexandri)

nodes.title: Archelais
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 G2 Archelais

nodes.title: Ashdod/Azotos (Mesogeios)
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of the Philistines.

nodes.title: Ashqelon/Ascalon
nodes.description: Ashqelon/Ascalon was an ancient city in coastal Palestine, located midway between Azotus and Gaza. It became independent in 104 B.C. and remained the only free city in Palestine. Strabo refers to it, while Pliny calls it a free city (oppidum libera).

nodes.title: Azotos Paralios
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F2 Azotos Paralios

nodes.title: Beer Sheva/Berosaba
nodes.description: Tel Be'er Sheva is an archeological site in southern Israel that is believed to be the location of the remains of the biblical town of Beersheba.

nodes.title: Beth Dagon
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F1 Beth Dagon

nodes.title: Beth Govrin/Eleutheropolis
nodes.description: Govrin/Eleutheropolis was a Roman city founded on the site of Betaris.

nodes.title: Eboda
nodes.description: Known today as Avdat, this ruined city was founded by the Nabateans in the Negev desert in what is today southern Israel. It flourished into Byzantine times. Along with three other ancient settlements, it was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005.

nodes.title: Ekron/Akkaron
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F2 Ekron/Akkaron

nodes.title: En Boqeq
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 G3 En Boqeq

nodes.title: Gaza
nodes.description: An important ancient settlement on the coast of Palestine.

nodes.title: Gazara
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F2 Gazara

nodes.title: Gophna
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 G2 Gophna

nodes.title: Hebron
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 G2 Hebron

nodes.title: Hierichous
nodes.description: An ancient site in the Jordan valley with occupation beginning ca. 11,000 years BP. The tell of Hierichous (Jericho) has more than 20 settlement horizons, ranging from Natufian Hunter-Gatherers to modern.

nodes.title: Idumaea
nodes.description: Idumaea or the kingdom of Edom was an historical region of the Levant located south of Iudaea and the Dead Sea.

nodes.title: Ierusalem/Hierosolyma/Col. Aelia Capitolina
nodes.description: The city of Jerusalem.

nodes.title: Ioppe
nodes.description: Ioppe (Jaffa) is an ancient port city in Iudaea.

nodes.title: Iordanes (river)
nodes.description: Iordanes fl. (the Jordan river).

nodes.title: Iudaea (region)
nodes.description: Iudaea was an historical region of the Levant located in the mountainous southern part of the Land of Palestine, roughly corresponding to the southern West Bank. The region's name derives from the biblical tribe of Judah and the associated Kingdom of Judah (ca. 934 until 586 BC).

nodes.title: Lachish
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F2 Lachish

nodes.title: Lydda/Diospolis/Georgioupolis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F2 Lydda/Diospolis/Georgioupolis

nodes.title: Malatha
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 G3 Malatha

nodes.title: Mampsis
nodes.description: The Nabataean city of Mampsis or Memphis (Ancient Greek: Μέμφις) was an important station on Incense Road.

nodes.title: Masada
nodes.description: Masada is a natural fortress in the Iudaean desert that overlooks the Dead Sea. It was the site of the standoff between Jewish rebels and the Roman army in A.D. 73. Herod the Great built a palace atop the citadel during his reign. Roman camps and siege works are still visible at the site, which is listed on the UNESCO World Heritage List.

nodes.title: Negev
nodes.description: The Negev is a desert and semidesert region of southern Israel.

nodes.title: Palaestina (region)
nodes.description: A region at the southeastern coast of the Mediterranean Sea, encompassing the coastal plain between Phoenicia and Gaza. The region's name derives from the Hebrew Plšth, "the land of the Philistines."

nodes.title: Pegai/Antipatris/Arethousa?
nodes.description: Pegai/Antipatris/Arethousa? was a city built by Herod the Great and named for his father-in-law, Antipater.

nodes.title: Phasaelis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 G1 Phasaelis

nodes.title: Saltus Constantinianus?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 E3 Saltus Constantinianus?

nodes.title: Saltus Gerariticus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F3 Saltus Gerariticus

nodes.title: Sobata
nodes.description: Sobata or Shivta is an ancient city in the Negev Desert located some 43 km southwest of Beersheba. The site was enrolled as a UNESCO World Heritage site, together with Haluza, Mamshit, and Avdat, in June 2005.

nodes.title: Thala
nodes.description: Thala (Tell Halif) is a small tell located in the northeastern Negev desert, near the modern town of Lahav. The site shows signs of habitation from the Chalcolithic through the Medieval and Ottoman periods.

nodes.title: Thamara?

nodes.title: Andium? (island)
nodes.description: The island of Jersey is the largest of the Channel Islands in the English Channel.

nodes.title: Fanum Martis/Civitas Coriosolitum
nodes.description: Fanum Martis/Civitas Coriosolitum (modern Corseul) was a major Gallo-Roman settlement, closely associated with the extra-urban sanctuary of Mars at Haut Bécherel. Fanum Martis/Civitas Coriosolitum was the chief town of the Coriosolites and was likely founded ca. 10 BC.

nodes.title: Lisia?/Silia? (island)
nodes.description: Lisia?/Silia? Ins. is the island of Guernsey which shows evidence for prehistoric habitation. During the Roman period there is evidence of both settlement and trading activity.

nodes.title: Noviomagus Lexoviorum
nodes.description: Noviomagus Lexoviorum, located at the confluence of the Orbiquet and Touques rivers, was the chief settlement of the Lexovii.

nodes.title: The Nunnery
nodes.description: A Roman fort on the island of Alderney in the English Channel. Its ancient name is unknown.

nodes.title: Olina (river)
nodes.description: The Orne river, located in in Normandy within northwestern France, drains into the English Channel.

nodes.title: Osismii
nodes.description: A Celtic tribe in Aremorica.

nodes.title: Le Pinnacle
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 7 D2 Le Pinnacle

nodes.title: Riduna (island)
nodes.description: The northernmost of the Channel Islands.

nodes.title: St-Peter-Port
nodes.description: St-Peter-Port is a port city on the island of Guernsey.

nodes.title: Sena (island)
nodes.description: Sena Ins. (modern Île de Sein).

nodes.title: Titos (river)
nodes.description: Titos fl. (Trieux river) is a river of Brittany.

nodes.title: Uxantis (island)

nodes.title: Vorgium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 7 C3 Vorgium

nodes.title: Dibon
nodes.description: Dibon was the capital of the ancient Moabite kingdom.

nodes.title: Khirbet et-Tannur
nodes.description: Located some 70 km from Petra, Khirbet et-Tannur is the site of a well-preserved, open-air Nabataean sanctuary.

nodes.title: Madaba
nodes.description: Madaba has a long settlement history. During the Roman period the city was part of the Trajanic province of Arabia.

nodes.title: Mortuum Mare/Asphaltitis L.
nodes.description: The modern "Dead Sea", which is bordered by Israel, Jordan, and the West Bank.

nodes.title: Nebo Mons
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 71 B2 Nebo Mons

nodes.title: Petra
nodes.description: Capital city of the Nabataeans located on the slope of Mount Hor.

nodes.title: Amman/Philadelpheia
nodes.description: An ancient settlement in northwest Jordan (modern Amman) received a Macedonian settlement and the name of Philadelphia from Ptolemy II Philadelphos (285-246 BC). The modern Amman, Jordan.

nodes.title: Tyrus
nodes.description: Hellenistic and Roman settlement in the Jordan Valley. The site contains a large palace, the Qasr al-Abd, dated to the second century CE.

nodes.title: Olympos (mountain on Cyprus)
nodes.description: A mountain located on the northeast tip of the island of Cyprus and mentioned by Strabo. One of several mountains scattered throughout the Greek world known by this name. Not to be confused with the main peak of the Trogodos mountains, which is today called "Mount Olympus" and lies in the center of the island.

nodes.description: Located on Cyprus, Paphos has been inhabited since the Neolithic period and was an important cult center of Aphrodite.

nodes.title: Koroneia

nodes.title: Ainesisphyra/Ennesyphora/Nesus
