nodes.title: Antipyrgos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: None

nodes.title: Gonia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: None

nodes.title: Libya Inferior (region)
nodes.description: An ancient coastal region of North Africa between Alexandria in Egypt and Darnis (modern Derna in Libya).

nodes.title: Marmarica
nodes.description: Marmarica was an ancient region of the North African coast between Cyrenaica and Aegyptus.

nodes.title: Oasis Parva
nodes.description: The Bahariya Oasis is a depression and oasis located in the Western Desert of Egypt approximately 370 km from Cairo.

nodes.title: Zeszes/Oasis Parva
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: None

nodes.title: Aegyptium Mare
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 D1 Aegyptium Mare

nodes.title: Alexandria
nodes.description: The ancient port city in Egypt's Nile Delta, founded by Alexander the Great in 332/331 BCE.

nodes.title: Bolbitinon Stoma
nodes.description: The second western-most ancient mouth of the Nile river, located in the western Delta, near Rosetta.

nodes.title: Bolbitinos (river)
nodes.description: Bolbitinos fl. (Rosetta branch of the Nile river).

nodes.title: Bousiris
nodes.description: Bousiris was a city of Lower Egypt near the Phatnitic mouth of the Nile river and was considered one of the possible birthplaces of Osiris.

nodes.title: Bousiritikos? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 E4 Bousiritikos? fl.

nodes.title: Boutikos potamos
nodes.description: An ancient canal of the Egyptian delta, with its western end on the Canopic branch of the Nile at Hierakonpolis and its eastern end at Pelusium (modern Tell el-Farama), deviating from an east-west line between the two at Bouto (modern Kom el-Farain).

nodes.title: Bouto
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 D2 Bouto

nodes.title: Canopus
nodes.description: An ancient Egyptian city of the Nile river delta. Canopus was located in the seventh nome (Menelaites) on the western bank at the mouth of the westernmost branch of the Nile.

nodes.title: Clysma
nodes.description: Clysma as an ancient port at the northern end of the Gulf of Suez.

nodes.title: Deir Abou Menas
nodes.description: An ancient Christian pilgrimage site that grew into an active town centered around the monastery complex devoted to Saint Menas who is said to have been buried there. The town reached its peak as the most visited pilgrimage site in Egypt during the sixth century AD.

nodes.title: Kanope Ins.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 C2 Kanope Ins.

nodes.title: Kanobikon Stoma
nodes.description: The western-most ancient mouth of the Nile river, located just east of the city of Canopus. It was fed by the Canopic (Kanobikos) branch of the Nile and emptied into the Canopic Gulf (Kanopikos Kolpos).

nodes.title: Kanobikos (river)
nodes.description: The western-most ancient branch of the Nile river in the Delta, terminating in the Mediterranean via the "Canopic mouth" (Kanobikon Stoma).

nodes.title: Kynopolis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 E3 Kynopolis

nodes.title: Mareia
nodes.description: Mareia is a Late Antique settlement in Egypt, with remains of harbor and industrial installations, baths, shops, a funerary church, and a large basilica.

nodes.title: Mendesion Stoma
nodes.description: The third eastern-most ancient mouth of the Nile river.

nodes.title: Metelis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 C2 Metelis

nodes.title: Naucratis
nodes.description: Naucratis was a city of the Nile river delta, located on the Canopic branch. Capital of Ptolemaic Egypt, Naucratis was the site of permanent Greek habitation from the sixth century BC onward.

nodes.title: Nilus (river)
nodes.description: The Nile is a major river of northeastern Africa and is generally acknowledged as the longest river in the world, measuring some 6,650 km (4,130 miles) from source to mouth.

nodes.title: Pelousiakos (river)
nodes.description: Pelousiakos fl. (the now-defunct Pelusiac branch of the Nile river).

nodes.title: Pelousiakos Kolpos
nodes.description: Pelousiakos Kolpos (Jūnah aţ Ţīnah)

nodes.title: Pelousiakon Stoma
nodes.description: The easternmost ancient mouth of the Nile River, fed via the now-defunct "Pelusiakos potamos" branch of the river and emptying into the "Pelousiakos Kolpos", a bay on the Mediterranean near the ancient settlement of Pelusium/Pelousion.

nodes.title: Pharos
nodes.description: The Pharos lighthouse of Alexandria, one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World, was built under the Ptolemies between 280 and 247 BC.

nodes.title: Phatnitikon Stoma
nodes.description: The middle mouth of the Nile river in antiquity and a part of the Nile Delta.

nodes.title: Pikrai Limnai
nodes.description: The Small Bitter Lake is a salt water lake in the Sinai.

nodes.title: Pikrai Limnai
nodes.description: The Great Bitter Lake is a salt water lake in the Sinai.

nodes.title: Schedia/Chaireon/Menelais?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 C2 Schedia/Chaireon/Menelais?

nodes.title: Sebennytikon Stoma
nodes.description: The third western-most ancient mouth of the Nile river.

nodes.title: Sebennytos
nodes.description: Sebennytos was an ancient city of Lower Egypt located on the Sebennytic branch of the Nile river. It was the capital of Lower Egypt's twelfth nome (the Sebennyte nome).

nodes.title: Santorini Archipelago
nodes.description: The islands of the Santorini archipelago, inhabited until the Late Bronze Age, were formed by modern and historic volcanism.

nodes.title: S. Gennaro
nodes.description: A minor settlement

nodes.title: Kolonos Agoraios
nodes.description: The hill flanking the Athenian Agora to the west, site of the Doric temple of Hephaestus.

nodes.title: Mura Greche
nodes.description: The so-called "Mura Greche" are remains of the later third century B.C. fortifications of Neapolis.

nodes.title: Roman theater of Neapolis
nodes.description: The Roman theater of Neapolis is a structure of the first century B.C. that is built atop the pre-existing fourth century B.C. Greek theater.

nodes.title: Tunni
nodes.description: Tunni is a mountain in Tabal. Inscriptions of the ninth-century-BC Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC) refer to it as "the mountain of silver."

nodes.title: Timur
nodes.description: Timur is a walled city in Que that is mentioned in royal inscriptions of the Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824).

nodes.title: Grotto of the Sibyl
nodes.description: A cave discovered by Amedeo Maiuri in 1932 and connected in the historical tradition with the Cumaean Sibyl. The site features in the sixth book of Virgil's Aeneid.

nodes.title: Poliochne
nodes.description: A Bronze Age settlement on the island of Lemnos, Poliochne pre-dates Troy I and shows influence from the Greek mainland during Early Helladic II (ca. 2500 BC). Mycenaean horizons have also been identified.

nodes.title: Stravomyti
nodes.description: Stravomyti is a Neolithic cave site with evidence for cultic activity. It is located on the slopes of Mt. Juktas in Crete.

nodes.title: Kephala
nodes.description: A Neolithic site and cemetery on Keos.

nodes.title: Kalavasos-Tenta
nodes.description: Kalavasos-Tenta is a neolithic settlement in Cyprus.

nodes.title: *Via Curia
nodes.description: A Roman road connecting Reate (Rieti) with Interamna Nahars (Terni).

nodes.title: Hala Sultan Tekke
nodes.description: A major Late Bronze Age settlement occupied the site of Hala Sultan Tekke, which later became an important Sufi Islamic shrine associated with Umm Haram.

nodes.title: Tırmıl Tepe Höyüğü
nodes.description: An unexcavated mound on the outskirts of modern Mersin in Turkey. Archaeological surface survey yielded pottery dating from the Calcolithic to the Medieval periods. Atop the mound lie the much-depleted ruins of a possibly medieval fortification. Tırmıl Tepe Höyüğü numbers among the proposed locations of ancient Kundu/Kyinda.

nodes.title: Basilica Julia
nodes.description: The Basilica Julia was built on the south side of the Forum Romanum in 46 B.C. on the site of the former Basilica Sempronia.

nodes.title: Upper Agora
nodes.description: The Upper Agora at Sagalassos is in use from the Hellenistic period onward.

nodes.title: Roman baths at Sagalassos
nodes.description: The Roman baths at Sagalassos date to the early part of the first century A.D.

nodes.title: Castra Bonnensia
nodes.description: The Roman legionary base at Bonna.

nodes.title: Roman city wall of Zaragoza
nodes.description: The Roman city wall of Zaragoza was begun under Tiberius, although work continued through the third century. The wall once stretched some 3,000 meters and had 120 defensive towers.

nodes.title: Circus at Calagurris
nodes.description: The Circus at Calagurris is located to the northeast of the city and could have accommodated 20,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Theater of Priene
nodes.description: Greek theater just below the agora in the Ionian city of Priene

nodes.title: Theater at Leuke
nodes.description: The theater is located at the north-east end of Kouphonesi. It was a stone-built building that could accommodated ca. 1000 spectators.

nodes.title: Temple of Augustus
nodes.description: The Temple of Augustus in Pula is a Roman temple that dates to the time of Augustus. The tetrastyle Corinthian temple sites a high podium.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Augusta Bagiennorum
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Augusta Bagiennorum

nodes.title: Roman theater at Sparta
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Sparta dates to the late first century B.C.

nodes.title: Kaminia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Kaminia

nodes.title: Kaphyai
nodes.description: Kaphyai or Caphyae was an ancient settlement of Arcadia in Greece located northwest of the lake of Orchomenus.

nodes.title: Karthaia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G2 Karthaia

nodes.title: Karystos
nodes.description: Karystos was a Greek polis located on the south coast of Euboea.  It is included in Homer's "catalogue of ships" in the Iliad and its name is also thought to be attested in Linear B documents.

nodes.title: Kastri
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G2 Kastri

nodes.title: Kato Komia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 H4 Kato Komia

nodes.title: Kenchreai
nodes.description: The ancient Saronic Gulf port of Corinth (near modern Kechries in Greece).

nodes.title: Keos (island)
nodes.description: One of the islands of the Cyclades.

nodes.title: Keryneia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C1 Keryneia

nodes.title: Koresia/Arsinoe
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G2 Koresia/Arsinoe

nodes.title: Korone
nodes.description: Korone was located on the west coast of the Messenian Gulf at the foot of Mount Mathia.

nodes.title: Korphos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Korphos

nodes.title: Kranae (island)
nodes.description: Kranae is an island off the coast of Gytheio.

nodes.title: Kyllene
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 A2 Kyllene

nodes.title: Kyllene (mountain)
nodes.description: A mountain in Arcadia (Greece), still known as Kyllene today.

nodes.title: Kythera
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 inset Kythera

nodes.title: Kythnos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G3 Kythnos

nodes.title: Habıbuşağı (İzoli)
nodes.description: Habıbuşağı (İzoli) was an Urartian fortress situated near Kömürhan, at the left shore of the river Euphrates in the Elazığ Province of eastern Turkey. Today it is covered by the reservoir behind the Karakaya dam. Habıbuşağı is best known on account of a rock inscription of the Urartian king Sarduri II, son of Argišti (eighth century BCE) which reports the expedition of Sarduri to this region. Habıbuşağı is, in fact, the westernmost known fortress of the Urartian kingdom.

nodes.title: Via Flaminia militare
nodes.description: The Via Flaminia Militare, or Via Flaminia Minor, was a road constructed by Gaius Flaminius in 187 BCE that connected Arretium and Bononia.

nodes.title: Capitolium of Cosa
nodes.description: The so-called Capitolium temple of the Latin colony of Cosa.

nodes.title: Cardo Maximus (Apamea)
nodes.description: The Cardo Maximus of Apamea in Syria is the site of the so-called "Great Colonnade", a portico that flanks the road for some 2 kilometers.

nodes.title: Aššur-mušalbir-palê-šarri-ēpišīšu-nāṣir-ummānīšu
nodes.description: The Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) surrounded his new capital Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") with a rectangular-shaped, 16,280-cubit-long inner and outer city wall. The name of the city wall (dūru) was Aššur-mušalbir-palê-šarri-ēpišīšu-nāṣir-ummānīšu ("The God Aššur Is the One Who Prolongs the Reign of Its Royal Builder (and) Protects His Troops") according to some Akkadian royal inscriptions, but Aššur-mulabbir-palê-šarri-ēpišīšu-nāṣir-perʾīšu ("The God Aššur Is the One Who Prolongs the Reign of Its Royal Builder (and) Protects His Offspring") according to other texts written in the name of Sargon II.

nodes.title: Khorsabad Gate 4
nodes.description: This undecorated gate is the southernmost city gate of the southeast wall of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

nodes.title: Khorsabad Citadel Gate B
nodes.description: This decorated gate was the principal entrance to the citadel of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

nodes.title: Šamaš Gate
nodes.description: The Šamaš Gate, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Šamaš-mušakšid-ernittīya ("The God Šamaš Is the One Who Makes Me Triumph"), is the first of the eight city gates of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") listed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) in inscriptions recording the construction of his new capital. This gate is the first of the east-facing entrances to the city.

nodes.title: Enlil Gate
nodes.description: The Enlil Gate, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Enlil-mukīn-išdī-alīya ("The God Enlil Is the One Who Establishes the Foundation of My City"), is the third of the eight city gates of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") listed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) in inscriptions recording the construction of his new capital. This gate is the first of the north-facing entrances to the city.

nodes.title: Ea Gate
nodes.description: The Ea Gate, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Ea-muštēšir-nagbīšu ("The God Ea Is the One Who Keeps Its Spring(s) in Good Order"), is the seventh of the eight city gates of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") listed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) in inscriptions recording the construction of his new capital. This gate is the first of the south-facing entrances to the city, but its precise location remains unknown.

nodes.title: Bēlet-ilī Gate
nodes.description: The Bēlet-ilī Gate, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Bēlet-ilī-murappišat-talittīšu ("The Goddess Bēlet-ilī Is the One Who Increases Its (Animals’) Offspring"), is the eighth of the eight city gates of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") listed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) in inscriptions recording the construction of his new capital. This gate is the second of the south-facing entrances to the city, but its precise location remains unknown.

nodes.title: Fosso Marangone
nodes.description: A small stream that flows into the Tyrrhenian Sea. It now lies in the territory of the municipalities of Allumiere, Civitavecchia, and Santa Marinella and forms the geographical boundary between the latter two. The watercourse originates at Poggio Ombricolo.

nodes.title: Khorsabad Residence M
nodes.description: The eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) had several royal residences constructed in the citadel of his new capital, Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad). Residence M, which has constructed on the western side of the citadel, is presumed to have been for one of the highest officials of the Assyrian Empire. Since no inscriptions were discovered in the ruins of the building, the owner/principal occupant of the this Assyrian palace is not known.

nodes.title: Khorsabad ziggurat
nodes.description: The eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) had a temple-tower built on the palace terrace of his new capital, Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad). The ziggurat was located at the northern end of the temple sector, which was accessible from Sargon’s palace, through the Courtyard XV.

nodes.title: Via Aemilia Scauri
nodes.description: A Roman road connecting Rome to Placentia begun by Marcus Aemilius Scaurus in 115 B.C.

nodes.title: Mithraeum
nodes.description: Temple of Mithras at Roman fort of Housesteads (Vercovicium)

nodes.title: Acquapendente
nodes.description: The modern Acquapendente was settled in pre-Roman times but is known historically from the Middle Ages onward.

nodes.title: Maes Howe
nodes.description: Maes Howe is a Neolithic chambered cairn and passage grave on Mainland, Orkney, Scotland.

nodes.title: Sublanuvium
nodes.description: Sublanuvium was an ancient station (statio) along the Via Appia, located between Aricia and Ad Sponsas. While its precise location is unknown, the site is located at the twentieth milestone of the Appia.

nodes.title: Unnamed Pass
nodes.description: An unnamed pass in the Alpes Cottiae near Vesulus Mons

nodes.title: Hagia Sophia
nodes.description: A major paleochristian, then Byzantine, church in Istanbul; subsequently an Islamic mosque, and today a museum.

nodes.title: Roman villa of Ammaia
nodes.description: The Roman villa of Ammaia dates to the first century.

nodes.title: Bañuela (peak)
nodes.description: Bañuela is the highest peak of the Sierra Morena (Spain), measuring 1,332 m (4,370 ft) above sea level.

nodes.title: Cisterns of La Maalga
nodes.description: A group of 15 large cisterns constructed during the late Punic era as a water supply for the city of Carthage.

nodes.title: Samnite House
nodes.description: The so-called "Samnite House" is a domus in Herculaneum that originally dates to the second century B.C., making it one of the oldest buildings discovered at the site.

nodes.title: Tomb of Cuccumella
nodes.description: An archaic tumulus-type tomb at Vulci.

nodes.title: Tomb of the Dolphin
nodes.description: An early Hellenistic painted tomb at Vulci.

nodes.title: Tino (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Ligurian Sea designated as part of a UNESCO World Heritage Site, Tino is connected with the life of the seventh century AD Christian Saint Venerius.

nodes.title: Nuraghe la Prisciona
nodes.description: A nuragic site of northeast Sardinia, occupied from the fourteenth until the ninth century BC. At its height the complex covers ca. five hectares.

nodes.title: Lucus Furrinae
nodes.description: The Lucus Furrinae or Syrian Sanctuary is a sanctuary site on the Janiculum Hill in Rome. The first known construction at the site took place during the late first century CE and it remained in use until the mid-fourth century CE.

nodes.title: Library of Celsus
nodes.description: The Library of Celsus is a library and monumental tomb in Ephesus which was constructed ca. 110-120 CE.

nodes.title: Temple of Artemis at Ephesus
nodes.description: The Temple of Artemis, the central element of the extramural sanctuary of Artemis at Ephesus, was considered one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.

nodes.title: Roman cistern at Largo Zucchi
nodes.description: The Roman cistern at Largo Zucchi dates to the second century A.D. It was discovered in 1957 and had an original diameter of ca. 6.90 meters.

nodes.title: Odeon at Kom el-Dikka
nodes.description: The Odeon at Kom el-Dikka, used both for entertainment and academic functions, was built in the center of ancient Alexandria in the fourth century CE and rebuilt between the end of the fifth and beginning of the sixth century CE.

nodes.title: Arch of Septimius Severus
nodes.description: The Arch of Septimius Severus is situated at the northwest corner of the Forum Romanum. It was dedicated in A.D. 203 and serves to commemorate the Parthian victories of Emperor Septimius Severus and his two sons against the Parthians (194/195 and 197–199).

nodes.title: Temple district at Hattusa
nodes.description: An area of the upper city of Hattusha with the remains of up to 30 temples.

nodes.title: Theater of Sagalassos
nodes.description: The Theater of Sagalassos dates to the later second century.

nodes.title: Odeion at Sagalassos
nodes.description: The Odeion at Sagalassos occupies a terrace that is north of the Lower Agora and downslope from the Upper Agora.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Herakleia
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Herakleia dates to the time of Hadrian and remained in use until the fourth century. Its remains came to light in 1968.

nodes.title: Forum and basilica at Venta
nodes.description: The forum-basilica at Venta date to the first and second centuries A.D. and are of the so-called "principia" type. The basilica measures ca. 54.6 x 20.1 m and was of the Corinthian order.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Noviodunum
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Noviodunum was only discovered in 1996 and likely dates to the second century A.D. The arena measures ca. 50 x 36 meters.

nodes.title: Square Castan at Besançon
nodes.description: A square containing architectural remains of the Roman city.

nodes.title: Teatro Clunia
nodes.description: A Roman theater initially constructed during the reign of Tiberius.

nodes.title: Périgueux Roman amphitheater
nodes.description: The Périgueux Roman amphitheater dates to the first century.

nodes.title: Temple of Augustus, Barcelona
nodes.description: The Temple of Augustus dates to the second century A.D.

nodes.title: Roman theater of Zaragoza
nodes.description: Dating to the first century, the Roman theater of Zaragoza accommodated about 6,000 spectators.

nodes.title: The Temple of Athena Polias at Priene
nodes.description: The temple of Athena at Priene, built by the architect Pytheos, is an especially good example of the Late Classical form of the Ionic order.

nodes.title: Théatre Gallo-Romains
nodes.description: The so-called Théatre Gallo-Romains could accommodate some 6,600 spectators.

nodes.title: Theater at Heraclea Minoa
nodes.description: The Theater at Heraclea Minoa dates to the late fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: Pula Arena (Roman amphitheater)
nodes.description: The Pula Arena is a Roman amphitheater dating to the first century.

nodes.title: Philistia (region)
nodes.description: A region in the southern Levant inhabited by the Philistines in the Iron Age. The Philistine Pentapolis comprised Ashdod, Ashkelon, Gaza, Ekron, and Gath.

nodes.title: Bent Pyramid
nodes.description: A pyramid built by Pharaoh Sneferu (ca. 2600 BC). Representative point location based on OpenStreetMap.

nodes.title: Red Pyramid
nodes.description: The third pyramid built by Pharaoh Sneferu.

nodes.title: Abbazia di San Vincenzo al Volturno
nodes.description: An historic Benedictine monastery located in the Province of Isernia, near the source of the river Volturno.

nodes.title: Via Portuensis?
nodes.description: The Via Portuensis is an ancient Roman road that connected Rome and Portus. It proceeded along the right bank of the Tiber river, starting from the Pons Aemilius. In the first part of its course it is identical to the Via Campana.

nodes.title: Ager Romanus
nodes.description: The rural hinterland of the ancient city of Rome.

nodes.title: Jerwan Aqueduct
nodes.description: The Assyrian king Sennacherib had an aqueduct constructed between 703 and 690 B.C. near the ancient city of Girmua. The structure is part of the "Khinnis [Canal] System." The identification of the structure's builder is confirmed by means of several inscriptions.

nodes.title: Temple G at Selinus
nodes.description: Remains of an octastyle Doric temple begun in the sixth century B.C. but left unfinished.

nodes.title: Tanitikon/Saitikon Stoma
nodes.description: The second eastern-most ancient mouth of the Nile river.

nodes.title: Taposiris Megale
nodes.description: A Ptolemaic city and temple built by Ptolemy II between 280 and 270 BC.

nodes.title: Akanthonpolis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 E1 Akanthonpolis

nodes.title: Arsinoites/Krokodeilopolites Nomos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 D2 Arsinoites/Krokodeilopolites Nomos

nodes.title: Dionysias
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 C2 Dionysias

nodes.title: Haueris
nodes.description: Hawara is an archaeological site located south of Crocodilopolis. It lies at the entrance to the depression of the Fayyum oasis.

nodes.title: Hermopolites Nomos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 D4 Hermopolites Nomos

nodes.title: Labyrinthos
nodes.description: Labyrinthos is a name applied by Greek authors, notably Herodotus and Strabo, to describe a monumental funerary temple at Hawara.

nodes.title: el-Lahun
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 D2 el-Lahun

nodes.title: Libykon Oros
nodes.description: Mountains that border the Nile river valley to the west.

nodes.title: Memphis
nodes.description: A city and capital of Ancient Egypt that remained an important center for most of Egyptian history.

nodes.title: Moeris (lake)
nodes.description: Moeris Lacus (Lake Moeris) was an ancient lake in the northwestern part of the Fayuum Oasis in Egypt; its surviving modern remnant is Birket Qarun.

nodes.title: Takyris
nodes.description: Takyris is an ancient royal Egyptian necropolis located in the desert on the west bank of the Nile.

nodes.title: Tomis (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 D3 Tomis fl.

nodes.title: Phchet
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 E1 Phchet

nodes.title: Berenike he Nea Potamos/ Berenike he Nea
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 unlocated Berenike he Nea (Potamos)

nodes.title: Nestou Epoikion
nodes.description: An ancient village or region in the Arsinoite nome in Egypt, mentioned in documentary papyri, whose precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Aelana/Aila
nodes.description: The city of Aqaba on the Red Sea.

nodes.title: Aelaniticus Sinus
nodes.description: The Gulf of Aqaba.

nodes.title: Arabia Eudaemon
nodes.description: Arabia Eudaemon or Arabia Felix was a term used by ancient geographers to describe the southern part of the Arabian Peninsula, now Yemen.

nodes.title: Arabia Petraia
nodes.description: A province on the frontier of the Roman empire from the second century AD, Arabia Petraia comprised parts of the former kingdom of Nabataea, as well as southern Syria, the Sinai, and the northwestern part of the Arabian peninsula. Its capital was Petra.

nodes.title: Heroopoliticus Sinus
nodes.description: Heroopoliticus Sinus (The Gulf of Suez)

nodes.title: Horeb Mons, Mon.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 76 D4 Horeb Mons, Mon.

nodes.title: Jebel Moneijah
nodes.description: Jebel Moneijah was the site of a Nabatean sanctuary in the Southern Sinai.

nodes.title: Nabataei
nodes.description: The Nabataei or Nabataeans were an ancient people who lived in the Southern Levant and northern Arabia.

nodes.title: Sinai
nodes.description: The Sinai Peninsula is bounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the north and the Red Sea to the south.

nodes.title: Syna M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 76 D4 Syna M.

nodes.title: Tineida
nodes.description: The ancient village of Tineida, in Egypt's Dakhleh Oasis.

nodes.title: Choirokoitia
nodes.description: The prehistoric settlement at Choirokoitia, in Cyprus. The site was inhabited from the seventh to the fourth millennium B.C. and was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1998.

nodes.title: Gebel el-Muzawaka
nodes.description: The Greek and Roman period necropolis at Gebel el-Muzawaka, in Egypt's Dakhleh Oasis.

nodes.title: Abydos/Ebot
nodes.description: Ancient Egyptian city and burial place of its first kings. Primary cult place of the god Osiris.

nodes.title: Antinoopolis
nodes.description: An ancient city in Egypt established by Hadrian in A.D. 122 in honor of Antinous. The city stood on the east bank of the Nile, opposite Hermopolis.

nodes.title: Diospolis Mikra
nodes.description: The capital of the seventh Nome of Upper Egypt, located on the west bank of the Nile.

nodes.title: Hermopolis Magna/Schmun
nodes.description: The capital city of the Hermopolite nome (the fifteenth Nome of Upper Egypt). The ancient Egyptians called the site Khmun after the group of eight divinities (Ogdoad) that represented the primordial world.

nodes.title: Lykopolis/Siout
nodes.description: A city of the west bank of the Nile, Lykopolis/Siout was the capital of the Thirteenth Nome of Upper Egypt (Lycopolites Nome) around 3100 B.C.

nodes.title: Makhareg
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 77 E1 Makhareg

nodes.title: Makhareg Gharb
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 77 E1 Makhareg Gharb

nodes.title: Panopolis/Schmin
nodes.description: Capital city of the ninth (Chemmite) nome of Upper Egypt.

nodes.title: Ptolemais Hermiou/Psoi
nodes.description: A city founded by Ptolemy I Soter as the capital of Upper Egypt.

nodes.title: This
nodes.description: The capital city of the first dynasties of ancient Egypt. While the precise location of the ancient site is unclear, mainstream scholarly thought places it near ancient Abydos and modern Girga.

nodes.title: Catacomb of Ponziano
nodes.description: A Paleochristian catacomb at the second mile of the via Portuensis. The catacomb is noted for containing the original tombs of Pope Anastasius I and his son Pope Innocent I.

nodes.title: Temple of Amun at Jebel Barkal
nodes.description: Large temple dedicated to the Amun located at the base of Jebel Barkal. Designated temple B500, the structure was likely constructed by the Napatan king Piankhi in the 8th century BCE.

nodes.title: Cave di Fosso del Drago
nodes.description: A tuff quarry along the line of the via Tiberina.

nodes.title: Mdina
nodes.description: Mdina, Malta, has ancient origins, being occupied perhaps as early as 4000 BC. The site was first fortified by the Phoenicians ca. 700 BC.

nodes.title: Fosse Way
nodes.description: Fosse Way was a Roman road connecting Isca Dumnoniorum and Lindum Colonia.

nodes.title: Maroneia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 unlocated Maroneia

nodes.title: Rharion Pedion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 unlocated Rharion Pedion

nodes.title: Tripyrgia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 unlocated Tripyrgia

nodes.title: Acharna
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 D2 Acharna

nodes.title: Ag. Triada
nodes.description: An ancient Minoan administrative center located in south-central Crete, Ag. Triada (or Hagia Triada) was excavated in the early twentieth century by the Scuola Archeologica Italiana di Atene.

nodes.title: Aigaion Antron
nodes.description: A cave on Crete sacred to the Minoans that may be the Diktaean cave, the putative site of Zeus' birth in Greek mythology.

nodes.title: Aigaion
nodes.description: A mountain range in eastern Crete, known today as Dikti (Dicte).

nodes.title: *Aina?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 C2 *Aina?

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 C2 Allaria?

nodes.title: Amyklaion?
nodes.description: Amyklaion? (the archaeological site of Kommos) was a Bronze Age port and settlement in southern Crete.

nodes.title: Andros (island)

nodes.title: Asterousia M.
nodes.description: The Asterousia Mountains are a range of southern Crete that separate the Mesara Plain from the Libyan Sea.

nodes.title: Atabyrion M.
nodes.description: The highest mountain on Rhodes (1,215 meters above sea level).

nodes.title: Aulon/Alonion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 C2 Aulon/Alonion

nodes.title: Berekynthos

nodes.title: Chalke
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 F3 Chalke

nodes.title: Chalke Island
nodes.description: An island west of Rhodes (modern Halki).

nodes.title: Creta (island)
nodes.description: The island of Crete is the largest of the Greek islands and the fifth-largest island in the Mediterranean Sea.

nodes.title: Creticum Mare
nodes.description: The Sea of Crete is the sea located south of the Aegean Sea, north of the island Crete, and south of the Cyclades islands.

nodes.title: Diktynnaion
nodes.description: A sanctuary located at Menies bay in Chania, Crete, with remains ranging in date from Hellenistic period to Late Antiquity.

nodes.title: Dimastos? (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 F3 Dimastos? Ins.

nodes.title: Donakea?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B4 Donakea?

nodes.title: Drepanon Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B2 Drepanon Pr.

nodes.title: Dreros
nodes.description: An ancient Greek settlement near modern Neapoli in the Lasithi region of Crete (about 15km northwest of Agios Nikolaos).

nodes.title: Eileithyias Antron
nodes.description: The Cave of Eileithyia on Crete is an ancient sanctuary sacred to the goddess of childbirth. The shrine was active during Neolithic, Minoan, and Mycenaean phases.

nodes.title: Eleutherna
nodes.description: Eleutherna was an ancient polis on Crete, some 25 km from Rethymno.

nodes.title: Eltynia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 D2 Eltynia

nodes.title: Eschatiota?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 A4 Eschatiota?

nodes.title: Gortyn(a)
nodes.description: The Roman capital of Creta et Cyrenaica province, then Creta, and later seat of the Archbishop of Crete, Gortyna was a thriving community from the Geometric period to the Middle Byzantine period. The first traces of urban settlement date from the Archaic period. The ancient Greek law code known as the "Gortyn Code" was discovered there in 1884.

nodes.title: Gyaros (island)
nodes.description: Gyaros is an island in the Aegean Sea, located to the south of Andros. The geographer Strabo visited the island in 29 B.C.

nodes.title: Gyras M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B4 Gyras M.

nodes.title: Harmedon? (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 D5 Harmedon? Ins.

nodes.title: Heraklion
nodes.description: Heraklion was the harbor city of ancient Knossos, and was later re-founded by the Arab conquerors.

nodes.title: Hermaia? Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B2 Hermaia? Pr.

nodes.title: Heteireia? (island)
nodes.description: Nisís Áyios Evstáthios

nodes.title: Hierapytna

nodes.title: Hippokoronion? M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B2 Hippokoronion? M.

nodes.title: Ialysos
nodes.description: Ialysos was an ancient city located on the north coast of the island of Rhodes. Together with Lindus and Kamiros it was one of the three ancient cities of Rhodes.

nodes.title: Ida(ion) M.
nodes.description: Ida(ion) M. is the highest mountain on Crete at 2,456 m (8,058 ft) above sea level.

nodes.title: Idaion Antron
nodes.description: A sacred cave on Crete where it was believed Rhea hid Zeus to protect him from Cronus. Archaeological evidence indicates use as a shelter or dwelling as early as the Late Neolithic period, with religious activities taking over in the Bronze Age and continuing through the Roman period.

nodes.title: Inatos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 D3 Inatos

nodes.title: Itanos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 F2 Itanos

nodes.title: Iytos M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 D2 Iytos M.

nodes.title: Kalamyde
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 A2 Kalamyde

nodes.title: Kamiros
nodes.description: An ancient city of Rhodes, with evidence for Mycenaean occupation. From the eighth century BC a Greek settlement flourished, with a temple dedicated to the goddess Athena on its acropolis. The Hellenistic phase of the site followed the tenets of Hippodamian planning. The city was twice destroyed by earthquakes (226 and 142 BC).

nodes.title: Kantanos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 A2 Kantanos

nodes.title: Karpathos (island)
nodes.description: Karpathos, part of the Dodecanese, lies between Crete and Rhodes in the southern Aegean Sea.

nodes.title: Karphi
nodes.description: An archaeological site in the Dikti Mountains of Crete that was the location of a post-Bronze Age 'refuge' settlement of Minoan and Mycenaean peoples.

nodes.title: Kasos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 G2 Kasos

nodes.title: Kasos (island)
nodes.description: Southwest of Karpathos, Kasos is the southernmost island of the Dodecanese.

nodes.title: Kastri
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 D2 Kastri

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B3 Kaudos?

nodes.title: Kavousi Kastro
nodes.description: An archaeological site (ancient name unknown) overlooking the Gulf of Mirabello in eastern Crete, not far from the modern town of Kavousi and the ancient site now known as Azoria (q.v.). BAtlas 60 E2 Kavousi (sic).

nodes.title: Kimolos (island)
nodes.description: Kimolos Ins. (Kimolos) is an island in the Aegean Sea that is part of the Cyclades.

nodes.title: Kisamos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 A2 Kisamos

nodes.title: Kisamos?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B2 Kisamos?

nodes.title: Knosos/Col. Iulia Nobilis Cnosos
nodes.description: A major ancient settlement of Crete located some 5 km southeast of Heraklion, Knossos was occupied from the Neolithic period to the time of the Roman empire.

nodes.title: Kome
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B4 Kome

nodes.title: Korion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 C2 Korion

nodes.title: Korykiai (islands)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 A1 Korykiai Inss.

nodes.title: Korykos Pr.
nodes.description: The westernmost of the two pairs of peninsulae of northwestern Crete (with the other being the Rodopos Peninsula).

nodes.title: Kriou Metopon
nodes.description: Cape Krios (Akra Krios), the southwestern corner of the island of Crete.

nodes.title: Kydonia
nodes.description: An ancient settlement on Crete inhabited since the Neolithic period, Kydonia has been a major center of Minoan, Greek, and Byzantine civilization.

nodes.title: Lagousa (island)
nodes.description: The island of Kardiotissa in the Aegean Sea.

nodes.title: Lappa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B2 Lappa

nodes.title: Lasaia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 C3 Lasaia

nodes.title: Lato
nodes.description: Lato was an ancient city of Crete, a Dorian city-state located on Mirabello Bay. The principal ruins date to the fifth and fourth centuries B.C. and the city was destroyed ca. 200 B.C.

nodes.title: Lato pros Kamara
nodes.description: Lato pros Kamara was the port of ancient Lato.

nodes.title: Leben
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 C3 Leben

nodes.title: Lera
nodes.description: An ancient cave sanctuary on the Akrotiri peninsula of Crete.

nodes.title: Leuka M.
nodes.description: Leuka M., a mountain range of Western Crete, located in the Chania prefecture.

nodes.title: Leuke
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 F3 Leuke

nodes.title: Leuke (island)
nodes.description: Leuke, now Koufonísi, is a small, rocky island southeast of Crete that in antiquity was a center for the production of the purple dye derived from from the gastropod Murex trunculus.

nodes.title: Lindos
nodes.description: Lindos is an ancient city located on the island of Rhodes.

nodes.title: Lissos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 A2 Lissos

nodes.title: Lykastos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 D2 Lykastos

nodes.title: Lyktos
nodes.description: An ancient settlement on Crete, located just east of modern Xydas/Xidas, with which it is sometimes conflated. The city is mentioned in Homer and seems to have flourished in Hellenistic and Roman times, at least.

nodes.title: Mallia
nodes.description: Mallia is a site on the northern coast of Crete that was the location of a major Minoan palatial center of the Middle Bronze Age.

nodes.title: Mese (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 A1 Mese Ins.

nodes.title: Minoa
nodes.description: Minoa, an ancient settlement, was located on the Gulf of Mirabello.

nodes.title: Mithymna?

nodes.title: Mokhlos

nodes.title: Oliaros (island)
nodes.description: Oliaros Ins. (modern Antiparos) is an inhabited island in the southern Aegean Sea and part of the Cyclades.

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 D2 Omphalion

nodes.title: Oreioi
nodes.description: The Oreioi were a league of states centered in the mountains of western Crete.

nodes.title: Pantomatrion/Agrion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 C2 Pantomatrion/Agrion

nodes.title: Paraskeues to Petali
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 C4 Paraskeues to Petali

nodes.title: Prinias (Patela)
nodes.description: An Iron Age settlement on the Patela plateau north of the modern village of Prinias; its ancient name is uncertain. The site is notable for its occupation from the end of the Bronze Age through to the Archaic period, as well as for the monumental architecture and Orientalizing sculpture of its Buildings ('Temples') A and B.

nodes.title: Phaistos
nodes.description: An ancient settlement on Crete where occupation began ca. 3000 B.C., Phaistos was a major center of the Minoan civilization and continued to be a Greek city of the first millennium B.C.

nodes.title: Phalanna?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 C2 Phalanna?

nodes.title: Phalasarna
nodes.description: An ancient harbor town located on the northwest coast of Crete.

nodes.title: Phoinikous Limen
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B2 Phoinikous Limen

nodes.title: Phoinix
nodes.description: Phoinix was an ancient coastal city of western Crete that served as the port of inland Anopolis and also of later Aradena.

nodes.title: Phoinix?

nodes.title: Pholegandros (settlement)

nodes.title: Pholegandros (island)
nodes.description: Pholegandros is an island in the Aegean Sea located in the southern part of the Cyclades.

nodes.title: Polyrrenia

nodes.title: Rhodos (island)
nodes.description: The island of Rhodes has an area of some 1,400 square km and sits 18 km from the coast of Asia Minor. The island has been inhabited by humans since the Neolithic period.

nodes.title: Seriphos (island)
nodes.description: Seriphos is an island of the western Cyclades. The island was settled by the third millennium B.C. The island was a member of the Delian League.

nodes.title: Sikinos (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 D5 Sikinos Ins.

nodes.title: Siphnos (island)
nodes.description: The island of Siphnos has been inhabited since the Neolithic period and was a major center of Cycladic civilization.

nodes.title: Syros (island)
nodes.description: Syros is an island in the Cyclades in the Aegean Sea. Human settlement on Syros began at least 5,000 years ago with the so-called Kastri culture.

nodes.title: Tenos (island)
nodes.description: Tenos Ins. (Tinos) is an island in the Aegean Sea and part of the Cyclades archipelago.

nodes.title: Zeus Atabyrios, T.

nodes.title: Temple of Hera I (the "Basilica")
nodes.description: An Archaic Doric temple probably dedicated to Hera in the central urban sanctuary of Paestum/Poseidonia.

nodes.title: Terrace and altar of M. Nonius Balbus
nodes.description: Marcus Nonius Balbus of Nuceria was an important civic patron of Herculaneum. Balbus was a praetor and proconsul of Crete and Cyrene and served as tribune of the plebs in 32 B.C. This architectural complex near the Suburban Baths included the terrace as well as an honorific statue and altar.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Ferentium
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Ferentium dates to the early Imperial period.

nodes.title: Hellenistic theater at Dion

nodes.title: Tomb of P. Numisius Ligus

nodes.title: Roman theater at Helikore/Nicaea

nodes.title: Roman theater at Ostia
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Ostia was built under the patronage of Marcus Agrippa.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Iguvium
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Iguvium is located within the Guastuglia archaeological area and dates to the late republican period.

nodes.title: Villa di Nerone

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Teate

nodes.title: Arch of Septimius Severus

nodes.title: Pompey's pillar

nodes.title: Catacombs of Kom el Shoqafa

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Vindonissa

nodes.title: Roman theater at Ferentinum
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Ferentinum is today poorly preserved.

nodes.title: Roman theater of Fourvière

nodes.title: Ostia Synagogue
nodes.description: The ancient synagogue located in Ostia Antica is one of the oldest known synagogues in the world. The structure's earliest phase dates to the reign of Claudius and it continued in use until the fifth century.

nodes.title: Gallo-Roman vicus at Dalheim

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Falerio Picenus

nodes.title: Roman theater at Falerio Picenus

nodes.title: Roman theater at Teate
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Teate measures 80 meters in diameter.

nodes.title: Serapeum of Alexandria
nodes.description: The Serapeum in Alexandria was a temple to Serapis erected by Ptolemy III in the third century B.C. It was destroyed in A.D. 391.

nodes.title: Acarnanian League
nodes.description: The Acarnanian League was a tribal confederation of the Acarnanians that later transformed into a league by the 5th century BCE. The league was incorporated into the Roman province of Achaea following the battle of Actium in 31 BCE.

nodes.title: Palace of Adad-nārārī III
nodes.description: The Assyrian king Adad-nārārī III (r. 810-783 BC) constructed a palace for himself at Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud). This royal residence, whose walls were covered with white plaster and painted with geometric and floral motifs, was built immediately to the south of the palace of his great-grandfather Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC).

nodes.title: Gula temple (Kalhu)
nodes.description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the goddess Gula. Although its location is not known, the Gula temple at Kalhu is thought to have been part of the Ninurta temple complex (in the northwest corner of the citadel), east of the Šarrat-niphi temple and north of the Kidmuri temple.

nodes.title: Šarrat-niphi temple (Kalhu)
nodes.description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the goddess Šarrat-niphi (an aspect of Ištar).

nodes.title: Mortuary Temple of Amenhotep III
nodes.description: Temple constructed in the Theban Necropolis during the 18th Dynasty.

nodes.title: Porta Collina
nodes.description: The Porta Collina was a gate in Rome's Servian Wall located on the Quirinal Hill. At the Porta Collina the Via Salaria and the Via Nomentana divided. Some remains of the gate were identified in 1872 on the Via Venti Settembre beneath the Italian Ministry of Finance.

nodes.title: Praedia Galbana
nodes.description: A suburban tract of land located southwest of the Aventine Hill that would come to be the location of the Horrea Galbae.

nodes.title: Caupona and Domus of L. Vetutius Placidus and Ascula
nodes.description: Thermopolium with a marble counter (I.8.8), connected to a private house (I.8.9) in Regio I, insula 8 in Pompeii. The walls of the house show extensive decoration in third style.

nodes.title: House of the Four Styles
nodes.description: The House of the Four Styles or Casa dei Quattro Stili (I.8.17) is noted for having examples of all four style of Pompeian wall paintings.

nodes.title: Temple of Dakka
nodes.description: An ancient temple relocated in the 1960s before the completion of the Aswan dam.

nodes.title: Dolmen de Kerhenry
nodes.description: A Neolithic tomb.

nodes.title: Kermario alignments
nodes.description: A complex comprised of 1029 megaliths arranged in 10 rows.

nodes.title: Ménec alignments
nodes.description: A complex comprised of 11 rows of megaliths covering an area of 1,165 x 100 meters.

nodes.title: Petit-Ménec alignments
nodes.description: An alignment of megaliths located east of Kerlescan.

nodes.title: Anaktoron at Pantalika
nodes.description: The Anaktoron is an enigmatic megalithic building associated with the prehistoric Sicilian settlement of Pantalica; its polygonal blocks may date to the 12-11th c. B.C., but the current form of the building seems to be the result of Byzantine reconstruction.

nodes.title: Roman Aqueduct at Moria
nodes.description: The remains of a 26 km aqueduct that supplied Mytilene. The best preserved section measures some 170 m. long.

nodes.title: Necropolis of Pantalica
nodes.description: A large, rock-cut necropolis of over 5,000 tombs dating from the thirteenth to the seventh centuries BC.

nodes.title: Pontic rock-cut tombs
nodes.description: A number of monumental, rupestral tombs at ancient Amaseia (modern Amasya in Turkey) among which 5 large ones are mentioned by Strabo and attributed to the kings. Mount Harşena and the Rock-tombs of the Pontic Kings were submitted to the Tentative World Heritage Lists in 2005 by the Permanent Delegation of Turkey to UNESCO.

nodes.title: Monte Inici
nodes.description: A mountain of Sicily located just south of the Golfo di Castellammare.

nodes.title: Thorikos Residential and Production District
nodes.description: The residential and production district of Thorikos features the remains of a number of classical period houses and a silver refinement center.

nodes.title: Ruines Romaines de Mazelles
nodes.description: The remains of three significant Roman buildings on the river Cher.

nodes.title: Andelos reservoir
nodes.description: A reservoir that functioned as part of the water supply of Andelos.

nodes.title: Aphrodision
nodes.description: Located outside the city walls of Pergamon, this temple, according to an inscription (OGIS 273-9), was supposedly the site of a victory of Attalos I over the Tolistogi, Galatians, and Antiochus Hierax. it was likely later destroyed by Philip V.

nodes.title: Phrygia (kingdom)
nodes.description: Phrygia was an ancient kingdom of west-central Anatolia, developing around Gordion beginning in the ninth century BCE. According to Strabo, the Cimmerians defeated and overran the Phrygian kingdom in the seventh century BCE.

nodes.title: Porta Palatina
nodes.description: A surviving turreted gateway of the Roman circuit wall of Augusta Taurinorum.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Mannu, Olmedo
nodes.description: A single-tower nuraghe built in the later second millennium B.C.

nodes.title: Caspingium
nodes.description: A Roman settlement, now unlocated, of Germania Inferior. The Tabula Peutingeriana places it along the military road connecting Noviomagus and Lugdunum Batavorum.

nodes.title: Isthmia Fortress
nodes.description: A Byzantine fortress erected in the fifth century CE that includes three gates and 21 towers.

nodes.title: Simi
nodes.description: A Middle Minoan sanctuary located on the slopes of Mount Dikte in Crete.

nodes.title: Castellaccio Europarco
nodes.description: A villa and a number of burials located along the Via Laurentina, dating from the fourth century BC to the second century AD.

nodes.title: Arslantepe (Melid)
nodes.description: Arslantepe became an important center in the Late Chalcolithic period. With the decline of the Hittite empire, the site became the center of an independent Luwian Neo-Hittite state (Kammanu). The state became a tributary of the Assyrian empire under Tiglath-Pileser I (1115-1077 BC) and it was sacked by Sargon II in 712 BC.

nodes.title: Church of Saint Alexander Nevsky, Jerusalem
nodes.description: The nineteenth century Russian Orthodox church preserves within it remains of Constantine's original fourth century church of the Holy Sepulchre.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Nuraddeo
nodes.description: A Middle Bronze Age nuragic site with a central tower standing ca. 14 m. tall near Suni, Sardinia.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Sant'Imbenia
nodes.description: A nuragic complex near Alghero, Sardinia, composed of a main, central tower flanked by two minor towers and a bastion, and surrounded by a village. The complex dates from the Middle Bronze Age onwards.

nodes.title: Theatre of Apollonia
nodes.description: The theatre of the ancient city of Apollonia, situated just outside the city wall, on the east side. The construction appears to be late Hellenistic, with half of the seats cut out of the rock on the elevation of the acropolis, and the other half built up.

nodes.title: So-called West Church in Apollonia
nodes.description: A large architectural complex that includes a three-aisled church with a projecting western apse, a small atrium, a baptistery, and other structures built up against the inner face of the western stretch of the city wall of Apollonia.

nodes.title: Tunnel of Eupalinos
nodes.description: A sixth century B.C. aqueduct on Samos, the Tunnel of Eupalinos is an amphistomon, meaning it was excavated simultaneously from each terminus. The tunnel measures 1,036 m in length.

nodes.title: Nichoria
nodes.description: Located in Messenia, Nichoria was a site with important Bronze Age and Iron Age phases.

nodes.title: Accu Sa Pira Nuraghe
nodes.description: A monopteral nuraghe located near Quartu Sant'Elena.

nodes.title: Treasury of Atreus
nodes.description: A Bronze Age tholos tomb with a corbeled dome and monumental ashlar facade on the Panagitsa Hill at Mycenae.

nodes.title: Domus of Vespasia Polla
nodes.description: A Roman domus traditionally associated with Vespasia Polla, mother of the emperor Vespasian.

nodes.title: Roman arch at Spoletium
nodes.description: The so-called "Arch of Drusus and Germanicus" at Spoleto.

nodes.title: Tigellio Roman villa
nodes.description: An elite villa dated to the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Tergeste
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Tergeste dates to the late first century A.D.

nodes.title: Roman baths at Sexi/Saxetanum
nodes.description: The Roman baths at Sexi/Saxetanum date to the first century.

nodes.title: Unnamed Aqueduct at Sexi/Saxetanum
nodes.description: One of five aqueducts known from Roman-era Sexi. This one is represented by an aqueduct bridge whose extant remains parallel the SO-02 between the Ctra. de Málaga - Velilla and the Carrera de la Concepcion in modern Almuñécar, Spain.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Tipasa
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater at Tipasa.

nodes.title: Temple of Herakles, Cora
nodes.description: The Temple of Herakles at Cora was built during the 80s B.C. The temple is tetrastyle in its plan and built following the Etrusco-Italic temple tradition.

nodes.title: Abu Ballas
nodes.description: A sandstone peak approximately 200 kilometers southwest of the Dakleh Oasis containing extensive pottery remains dated from the 3rd millennium BCE through the Roman period. Abu Ballas was likely a way station along a caravan route connecting the Dakhleh Oasis with Gilf Kebir.

nodes.title: tribus Stellatina
nodes.description: The tribus Stellatina was a later rural tribe of ancient Rome which was established in 387 B.C.

nodes.title: tribus Teretina
nodes.description: Established in 299 B.C., the tribus Teretina was one of the later rural tribes of ancient Rome.

nodes.title: Sepulcrum Pansae
nodes.description: The tomb of the consul Gaius Vibius Pansa Caetronianus (43 B.C.) was located in the Campus Martius of Rome according to both literary and epigraphic testimony. Its precise location has not been determined.

nodes.title: Chiesa di Sant'Ilario a Port' Aurea
nodes.description: A sixth-, seventh-, and eighth-century Christian church located near the Port' Aurea of Benevento built during the Longobard period. The church was built atop Imperial remains and was an apsidal hall.

nodes.title: Arco del Sacramento
nodes.description: A Roman arch of the second century A.D. that faced on to the forum of Beneventum.

nodes.title: Grange stone circle
nodes.description: Grange stone circle or Lios na Grainsi is the largest stone circle in Ireland, consisting of 113 stones and was built ca. 2100 BC.

nodes.title: Mochlos archaeological site
nodes.description: A multi-period settlement site in use by a number of civilizations dating ca. 3100 B.C. to A.D. 1200.

nodes.title: Casa della Regina Carolina
nodes.description: A domus at Pompeii partially excavated in the nineteenth century.

nodes.title: Khorsabad Gate 1
nodes.description: This decorated gate is the northernmost city gate of the northeast wall of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

nodes.title: Khorsabad Gate 2
nodes.description: This undecorated gate is the southernmost city gate of the northeast wall of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

nodes.title: Khorsabad Gate 3
nodes.description: This decorated gate is the northernmost city gate of the southeast wall of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

nodes.title: Egalgabarinutukua
nodes.description: The palace of the eighth-century-BC Assyrian Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) at Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad), Egalgabarinutukua ("Palace That Has No Equal"), was constructed between 717 BC and 706 BC. This royal residence was constructed on a high, mud-brick terrace located within the city’s citadel, which was located against the northwestern stretch of the city wall. This large, ornately-decorated palace complex consisted of over two hundred rooms (including chapels to the deities Ea, Sîn, Ningal, Adad, Šamaš, and Ninurta) and courtyards, as well as a ziggurat.

nodes.title: Khorsabad Residence J
nodes.description: The eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) had several royal residences constructed in the citadel of his new capital, Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad). Residence J, which has constructed on the western side of the citadel, is presumed to have been for one of the highest officials of the Assyrian Empire. Since no inscriptions were discovered in the ruins of the building, the owner/principal occupant of the this Assyrian palace is not known.

nodes.title: Ningal temple (Khorsabad)
nodes.description: As part of the palatial complex of Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad), the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) constructed six temples, including one to the goddess Ningal.

nodes.title: Adad temple (Khorsabad)
nodes.description: As part of the palatial complex of Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad), the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) constructed six temples, including one to the god Adad.

nodes.title: Šamaš temple (Khorsabad)
nodes.description: As part of the palatial complex of Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad), the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) constructed six temples, including one to the god Šamaš.

nodes.title: Theater of Orchomenus
nodes.description: A theater of the late fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: Eetioneia Hellenistic gateway
nodes.description: A fortified gateway protecting the mouth of the Piraeus harbor.

nodes.title: Ponte Sereno
nodes.description: A bridge near Ferentinum (modern Ferentino in Italy) that is traditionally dated to A.D. 260 or after. A substructure in polygonal masonry supports the bridge.

nodes.title: Tell Um Hammad Sharqi
nodes.description: Archaeological site on the banks of the Zerqa River with signs of habitation in the Early Bronze Age I-II and IV. The eastern portion of the larger Tell Um Hammad site is called Um Hammad Sharqiya; the western section is Um Hammad al-Gharbi. The two may have been linked as a single village in the Early Bronze Age IV.

nodes.title: Necropolis of Porta Vesuvio
nodes.description: A necropolis of Pompeii located outside the so-called "Porta Vesuvio".

nodes.title: Castellum aquae
nodes.description: A building in Pompeii serving as the distribution point of water originating from the Acquedotto Serino, Claudio or Augusteo. The structure is also referred to as Castellum Divisorium.

nodes.title: Central Baths
nodes.description: A bath complex (IX, 4, 5-18) located at the intersection of the Via Stabiana and Via di Nola that was built following the earthquake of AD 62.

nodes.title: tribus Suburana (Succusana)
nodes.description: The tribus Suburana (also called Succusana) was an urban tribe of Rome, reportedly established by Servius Tullius.

nodes.title: Triangular Forum
nodes.description: A triangular plaza with an Ionic propylon that was surrounded by 95 Doric columns. A Doric order temple sits in the forum.

nodes.title: Mahabalipuram
nodes.description: This group of sanctuaries was carved out of rock along the Coromandel coast in the seventh and eighth centuries. The Group of Monuments at Mahabalipuram is a UNESCO World Heritage site.

nodes.title: Circus Gai et Neronis
nodes.description: Circus Gai et Neronis was originally built as a private race course for the emperor Caius. In the fourth century AD the north side of the circus was destroyed in order to make room for the first basilica of St. Peter.

nodes.title: Hamaxitos
nodes.description: Hamaxitos was a Greek city in the southwestern Troad which was considered to mark the boundary between the Troad and Aeolis. Its territory included the temple of Apollo Smintheus.

nodes.title: Hekatonnesoi (islands)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 D3 Hekatonnesoi Inss.

nodes.title: Hephaistia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 A2 Hephaistia

nodes.title: Herakles, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 A2 Herakles, T.

nodes.title: Hermeios Sinus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 D4 Hermeios Sinus

nodes.title: Hermus (river)
nodes.description: The Gediz River, the second largest of Anatolia's rivers, flows into the Aegean Sea.

nodes.title: Hiera
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Hiera

nodes.title: Hypaipa
nodes.description: Hypaipa or Hypaepa is an ancient city of Lydia located at the foot of Mount Aipos.

nodes.title: Ida (mountain)
nodes.description: Ida M. is a mountain of northwestern Turkey standing to 5,820 ft (1,774 m) above sea level.

nodes.title: Ilieon Kome
nodes.description: The "VIllage of the Ilians" located on the slopes of Karatepe in Asiatic Turkey.

nodes.title: Ilium/Troia
nodes.description: An ancient city of northwest Anatolia with occupation ranging from the Bronze Age to the Roman period. Troy features as the central setting of Homer's Iliad.

nodes.title: Ionia (region)
nodes.description: The coast of Asia Minor between Aeolis and Caria.

nodes.title: Issa?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Issa?

nodes.title: Kabaki
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Kabaki

nodes.title: Kabeireion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 A2 Kabeireion

nodes.title: Kallikolone M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C2 Kallikolone M.

nodes.title: Kalydnai/Lagusae Inss.
nodes.description: Kalydnai/Lagusae Inss., a small island group of the northern Aegean Sea.

nodes.title: Kaminia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 A2 Kaminia

nodes.title: Kardamyle?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C4 Kardamyle?

nodes.title: Karini
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Karini

nodes.title: Kastri
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Kastri

nodes.title: Kebren
nodes.description: Kebren was an ancient settlement of the Troad.

nodes.title: Khontro Bigli
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Khontro Bigli

nodes.title: Kilbianoi (Ano)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 G5 Kilbianoi (Ano)

nodes.title: Kilbianoi (Kato)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 G5 Kilbianoi (Kato)

nodes.title: Killaion (mountain)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 D4 Killaion M.

nodes.title: Klazomenai (earlier)
nodes.description: The initial, mainland site of the city, located to the southwest of modern Urla Iskelesi in Turkey. Pausanias reports that the city relocated to an island in the Bay of Smyrna, for which see "Klazomenai (later)."

nodes.title: Klazomenai (later)
nodes.description: A town in Lydia that, according to Pausanias, moved from an initial, mainland site thought by scholars to have been southwest of modern Urla Iskelesi to an island in the Bay of Smyrna (modern Klazümen). This place resource represents the later city; see also "Klazomenai (earlier)."

nodes.title: Koddinou Petra
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 E4 Koddinou Petra

nodes.title: Koila
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C4 Koila

nodes.title: Koja Dag
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Koja Dag

nodes.title: Kokkinos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 A2 Kokkinos

nodes.title: *Kokylion?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C2 *Kokylion?

nodes.title: Kolonai
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C2 Kolonai

nodes.title: Korou Pedion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 F4 Korou Pedion

nodes.title: Kouphi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Kouphi

nodes.title: Koutlougouni
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Koutlougouni

nodes.title: Lamponia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C2 Lamponia

nodes.title: Lapsarna
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 B3 Lapsarna

nodes.title: Laris(s)a?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 E4 Laris(s)a?

nodes.title: Larisa/Ptolemais?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C2 Larisa/Ptolemais?

nodes.title: Larissai Petrai
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Larissai Petrai

nodes.title: Latom
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C4 Latom

nodes.title: Lekton/Lectum
nodes.description: The Lekton promontory (modern Cape Baba or Baba Burnu) is the the westernmost point of Asia Minor.

nodes.title: Lemnos (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 A2 Lemnos Ins.

nodes.title: Lesbos (island)
nodes.description: Lesbos is an island of the northeastern Aegean Sea and was named for the son of Lapithos, the descendant of Deucalion and Helen.

nodes.title: Leukai
nodes.description: Leukai was an ancient harbor city on the north shore of the Gulf of Smyrna.

nodes.title: Lithi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 B5 Lithi

nodes.title: Lydia/Maionia (region)
nodes.description: Lydia was a region in Western Asia Minor, situation between Ionia on the west, Caria on the south, Phrygia on the east, and Mysia on the north. It was home to an Iron Age kingdom (q.v), and gave its name to a succession of administrative areas of the Roman empire and other states.

nodes.title: Makara
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Makara

nodes.title: Malia (promontory)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 D3 Malia Pr.

nodes.title: Managros
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 B5 Managros

nodes.title: Manna
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Manna

nodes.title: Megalos Lakkos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 B3 Megalos Lakkos

nodes.title: Melaina Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 B4 Melaina Pr.

nodes.title: Meletos/Smyrnaeus Sinus
nodes.description: The Gulf of İzmir

nodes.title: Messon
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Messon

nodes.title: Meter Plastena, T.
nodes.description: A large, rock-cut Hittite monument located on Mount Sipylus at the locality of Akpınar. The relief depicts a seated figure who is positioned in a niche.

nodes.title: Metokhi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 B5 Metokhi

nodes.title: Milingos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C5 Milingos

nodes.title: Moria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 D3 Moria

nodes.title: Mosychlos M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 A2 Mosychlos M.

nodes.title: Myrina
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 A2 Myrina

nodes.title: Myrina/Sebastopolis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 D4 Myrina/Sebastopolis

nodes.title: Mysia (region)
nodes.description: A region of northwestern Asia Minor.

nodes.title: Mytilene
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 D3 Mytilene

nodes.title: Nagos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C4 Nagos

nodes.title: Nakrason (or Nakrasos)
nodes.description: An ancient settlement whose precise location is unknown. Modern scholars place it variously at Bakir, Maltepe, or İlyaslar in modern Turkey.

nodes.title: Naulochon/Smyrna/Palaia Smyrna
nodes.description: An ancient settlement located on the gulf of Smyrna, east of the town of Bayraklı (some 4 km north of Izmir, Turkey). Archaeological evidence indicates that the earliest Hellenic evidence dates to the eleventh or tenth centuries B.C.

nodes.title: Neandria
nodes.description: Neandria was a Greek city in the south-west of the Troad region of Anatolia.

nodes.title: Neonteichos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 E4 Neonteichos

nodes.title: Caermote Roman fort
nodes.description: The earthwork remains of a first century A.D. Roman fort and a possible second century fortlet.

nodes.title: Palace of Ardashir
nodes.description: A castle built in A.D. 224 by King Ardashir I of the Sassanian Empire, the Palace of Ardashir is located 2 km north of Gor.

nodes.title: Vieil-Évreux Roman Baths
nodes.description: The Vieil-Évreux Roman Baths of the second and third centuries A.D. have four architectural phases that have been identified.

nodes.title: Garni temple
nodes.description: The Garni Temple dates to the first century A.D. and was sacred to the Armenian sun god Mihr.

nodes.title: Pyramid of Senusret II
nodes.description: Senusret II was a pharaoh of the Twelfth dynasty of ancient Egypt.

nodes.title: Amasya castle
nodes.description: Amasya Castle or Harşene Castle, is a fortress located in Amasya in northern Turkey.

nodes.title: Spring at Amphiareion
nodes.description: The spring at the healing sanctuary at Amphiareion and a site of votive deposits in the form of coins. It still flows today.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Iuno Gabina
nodes.description: The Sanctuary of Iuno Gabina at Gabii.

nodes.title: Vicus Alexandri
nodes.description: A settlement at the third milestone of the Via Ostiensis.

nodes.title: Vicus Augustanus Laurentium?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 Vicus Augustanus Laurentium?

nodes.title: Villa Hadriani
nodes.description: The Villa of Hadrian (Villa Adriana in Italian) is a sprawling archaeological complex at Tivoli, Italy. The villa complex was designed and used by the emperor Hadrian in the second century A.D.

nodes.title: Villa Maxentii
nodes.description: A complex on the Via Appia constructed by Maxentius in the early fourth century A.D.

nodes.title: Villa Neronis
nodes.description: The Villa Neronis was a rural villa of the emperor Nero, likely built early in his reign (perhaps before AD 60).

nodes.title: Villa Pamphili
nodes.description: The church of San Pancrazio was founded in the sixth century A.D. by Pope Symmachus. It stands beyond the Porta San Pancrazio on the Ianiculum. Below the church is a massive catacomb referred to as S. Pancrazio or Ottavilla.

nodes.title: Villa Torlonia
nodes.description: A Jewish catacomb discovered in 1919 on the grounds of the Villa Torlonia park in Rome.

nodes.title: Aqua Alexandrina
nodes.description: The Aqua Alexandrina was an ancient Roman aqueduct that carried water 22.4 km from Pantano Borghese to the Baths of Alexander in the Campus Martius. It was in use from the third to the eighth century AD.

nodes.title: Aqua Alsietina
nodes.description: The Aqua Alsietina was an aqueduct built by Augustus that drew water from the lacus Alsietinus (Lago di Martignano) and conducted it to Rome.

nodes.title: Aqua Anio Novus
nodes.description: Aqua Anio Novus is an ancient aqueduct supplying the city of Rome. Begun by Caius in A.D. 38, it was completed and dedicated by Claudius in A.D. 52.

nodes.title: Aqua Anio Vetus
nodes.description: Aqua Anio Vetus, an aqueduct serving Rome and built originally during the third century BC. The Anio Vetus carried water to Rome from the Aniene near Vicovaro.

nodes.title: Aqua Antoniniana
nodes.description: The Aqua Antoniniana was a branch of the Aqua Marcia that carried water to the Baths of Caracalla.

nodes.title: Aqua Appia
nodes.description: The earliest of Rome's aqueducts, the Aqua Appia was constructed in 312 BC by the censor Appius Claudius Caecus. The aqueduct runs a course of 16.4 km, entering Rome at the Porta Maggiore. Frontinus estimated the daily volume at 75,537 cubic meters.

nodes.title: Aqua Claudia
nodes.description: The Aqua Claudia was one of the four great aqueducts of the ancient city of Rome. It was begun by Caius in A.D. 38 and completed by Claudius in A.D. 52.

nodes.title: Aqua Marcia
nodes.description: The Aqua Marcia was the longest of Rome's 11 aqueducts.

nodes.title: Aqua Tepula
nodes.description: The Aqua Tepula was an aqueduct built in 126 BC by the censors G. Servilius Caepio and L. Cassius Longinus.

nodes.title: Aqua Traiana
nodes.description: The Aqua Traiana was an aqueduct built by Trajan and inaugurated in AD 109.

nodes.title: Aqua Virgo
nodes.description: The Aqua Virgo was one of the 11 aqueducts supplying the city of Rome and was completed by Marcus Agrippa in 19 BC. The aqueduct was later revitalized by Pope Adrian I in the eighth century.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 unnamed aqueduct (Vicus Augustanus)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 unnamed aqueduct (Lavinium)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C4 unnamed aqueduct (Antium)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 A2 unnamed bridge (Ad Turres)

nodes.title: Pons Aemilius
nodes.description: The Pons Aemilius was the first stone bridge across the Tiber river at Rome (241 B.C.). Its remains are known today as the 'Ponte Rotto'.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 unnamed bridge (Cessati Spiriti)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 unnamed bridge (Ad Sponsas)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 unnamed canal group (Portus)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 unnamed canal (SE Ostia)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 unnamed canal (Villa Domitiani, from Albanus L.)

nodes.title: Emissarium of Lake Nemi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 unnamed canal (from Nemorensis L.)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D4 unnamed canal group (SW Forum Appii)

nodes.title: Unnamed canals
nodes.description: unnamed canal group (NW Pomptinae Paludes)

nodes.title: Cemeteries around Caere
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 A2 no. 1 (cemeteries around Caere)

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge over R. Quartaccio
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 A2 no. 2 (bridge over R. Quartaccio)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 no. 4 (bridge over R. Arrone)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 no. 6 (bridge over Cremera fl.)

nodes.title: Villa delle Grotte at Grottarossa
nodes.description: A villa with beginnings in the early Republican period, continuing in use to the middle Imperial period.

nodes.title: Unnamed villas and a tomb near Pons Mulvius
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 no. 9 (villas (2) and tomb near Pons Mulvius)

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge in the Piazza Eugenio Biffi
nodes.description: The remains of an ancient Roman bridge in the present Piazza Eugenio Biffi in Rome. This bridge is thought to have spanned the Almo river.

nodes.title: Unnamed temple
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 no. 12 (temple at EUR)

nodes.title: Ponte di Vallerano
nodes.description: The Ponte di Vallerano is a second century Roman bridge that carried the via Ostiensis across the fosso di Vallerano.

nodes.title: Ponte di Malafede
nodes.description: A Roman bridge that is no longer extant. Quilici notes that the bridge was destroyed both by the Second World War and by urbanization that followed in the post-war period. Blake publishes a photo of E. B. van Deman and indicates that the bridge was built in peperino and of "indeterminate date". She compares the Ponte di Malafede with the construction of the Via Appia viaduct that lies just beyond Ariccia, a structure that was Augustan in its date.

nodes.title: Ponte Ladrone
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 no. 16 (bridge (Ponte Ladrone))

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: A tuff quarry located at Castelporziano, to the east of Ostia Antica.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C1 no. 18 (tomb near Nomentum)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 19 (villa near S. Sinforosa)

nodes.title: Cemetery of Gordianus, Epimachus, Apronianus
nodes.description: A burial ground for the the Christian martyrs Gordianus, Epimachus, and Apronianus at the seventh mile of the Via Latina.

nodes.title: Parco delle Tombe di via Latina
nodes.description: A cluster of Roman Imperial tombs along the Via Latina excavated in the nineteenth century.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 27 (bridge on Via Labicana)

nodes.title: Quarries at Aquae Albulae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 29 (quarries at Aquae Albulae)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 30 (tombs near Villa Adriana)

nodes.title: Roman bridges at Tibur
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 32 (bridges at Tibur (2))

nodes.title: Unnamed forts near Aefula
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 33 (forts near Aefula)

nodes.title: Ponte Ceccara
