nodes.description: The Ponte Ceccara, also referred to as the ponte di Terra, is a Republican period bridge located on the fosso di Passerano along the Via Praenestina. It is located within the modern comune of Zagarolo, some 30.5 km southeast of the center of Rome.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 38 (bridge (Ponte dell’Acqua Nera))

nodes.title: Ponte Amato
nodes.description: The bridge known as Ponte Amato carries the Via Praenestina near Gallicano.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 41 (villa near Praeneste)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 no. 45 (villa at Albanus L.)

nodes.title: Roman Villa at Lago di Nemi
nodes.description: A Roman Villa on the shores of Lago di Nemi.

nodes.title: So-Called Tomb of Clodius
nodes.description: The so-called Tomb of Clodius along the Via Appia near Castel Gandolfo.

nodes.title: Unnamed temple near Solforata
nodes.description: An ancient temple located near Solforata, between Lavinium and the Alban Lake in modern Italy.

nodes.title: Ponte di Mele
nodes.description: A Roman bridge along the Via Appia.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 no. 56 (temple at Algidus M.)

nodes.title: Unnamed Roman villa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 no. 57 (villa near Norba)

nodes.title: Ponte Tre Ponti
nodes.description: A Roman bridge located along the Via Amerina outside Civita Castellana.

nodes.title: Roman villa near Setia
nodes.description: The platform, including cryptoporticus, of a republican period villa originally dating to the first century B.C. with evidence for second century A.D. renovations.

nodes.title: Abellinum
nodes.description: Abellinum was a settlement of the Hirpini in Campania.

nodes.title: Acerrae
nodes.description: Acerrae was an ancient Oscan city of Campania, perhaps originally named Akeru. The Romans granted it civitas sine suffragio in 332 BC.

nodes.title: Acqua Claudia
nodes.description: A Roman villa at Anguillara Sabazia that may have been built in order to take advantage of mineral springs. The villa dates to the Late Republican period but has only been partially excavated. A large hemicycle with ambulatio is extant; this feature may have been coordinated with the villa's garden.

nodes.title: Ad Flexum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Ad Flexum

nodes.title: Ad Medias
nodes.description: Ad Medias was a mutatio on the ancient Via Appia. It was located at the halfway point of the so-called Decennovium.

nodes.title: Ad Turres Albas
nodes.description: Ad Turres Albas lay on the Via Severiana, midway between Circeii and Astura.

nodes.title: Aenaria/Pithekoussai (island)
nodes.description: Aenaria/Pithekoussai Ins. (modern Ischia) is a volcanic island located in the northern part of the Bay of Naples.

nodes.title: Al(l)ifae
nodes.description: An ancient town of either Oscan or Samnite origin situated in the Volturno river valley.

nodes.title: Aletrium
nodes.description: A Hernican hill town that formed part of a sixth century B.C. defensive league against Volscian and Samnite aggression and allied itself to Tarquinius Superbus. Rome eventually took Aletrium in 306 B.C.; by the first century B.C. the site was a Roman municipium.

nodes.title: Alfedena
nodes.description: A Samnite settlement occupying a strategic location in the valley of the Sangro river.

nodes.title: Antinum
nodes.description: A town of the Marsi in the valley of the Liris river.

nodes.title: Apollo et Nymphae Nitrodes, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E4 Apollo et Nymphae Nitrodes, T.

nodes.title: Aquae Caeretanae
nodes.description: Therapeutic springs located near Caere.

nodes.title: Aquinum
nodes.description: Aquinum was a municipium by the time of Cicero. It was thought to be the place of birth for the satirist Juvenal and the emperor Pescennius Niger.

nodes.title: Arpinum
nodes.description: An ancient center that originated as early as the seventh century B.C. that became a civitas sine suffragio in 305 B.C. Arpinum was the birthplace of Caius Marius and Marcus Tullius Cicero.

nodes.title: Arx Fregellana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Arx Fregellana

nodes.title: Astura
nodes.description: Astura was once a coastal island of Latium and is now a small peninsula at the southeastern edge of the Bay of Antium.

nodes.title: Atella (Campania)
nodes.description: A city of Campania located between Capua and Neapolis.

nodes.title: Atina
nodes.description: Atina was a Samnite hill town with a polygonal masonry fortification wall.

nodes.title: Aurunci
nodes.description: The Aurunci were an Italic tribe of south Italy. Their territory was incorporated into the Roman territory in the fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: Avernus L.
nodes.description: A volcanic crater lake located in the Phlegraean Fields, Lake Avernus served a major ritual role for ancient Romans and Greeks as they viewed it as an entrance to Hades.

nodes.title: Baiae
nodes.description: A Roman seaside community on the Bay of Naples that included thermal springs.

nodes.title: Bauli
nodes.description: Bauli (near modern Bacoli) was an ancient settlement of the Campi Phlegraei.

nodes.title: Beneventum/Maleventum
nodes.description: Beneventum/Maleventum (modern Benevento) was an ancient city of Campania of Samnite origin.

nodes.title: Boscoreale
nodes.description: A settled area of Campania that is especially well known for the Roman country villas of the first century BC that were destroyed by the eruption of Vesuvius in A.D. 79.

nodes.title: Bovianum
nodes.description: Bovianum was a Samnite center and the capital of the Pentri tribe. It received Roman municipium status ca. 87 B.C. By the late first century A.D. it was occupied by veterans of Legio XI and known as the "colonia Bovianum Undecimanoruin".

nodes.title: Buca
nodes.description: Buca was an ancient settlement of the Frentani.

nodes.title: Caiatia
nodes.description: A Samnite town that eventually became a Roman municipium of the tribus Falerna ca. 89 B.C.

nodes.title: Caieta
nodes.description: Caieta was a town of ancient Latium located on the Tyrrhenian Sea coast between Tarracina and Formiae.

nodes.title: Callifae?
nodes.description: A city of the Samnites that, according to Livy, was captured by the Romans in Republican times. Probably at or in the vicinity of modern Roccavecchia di Pratella in Italy.

nodes.title: Calatia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Calatia

nodes.title: Cales
nodes.description: Cales was an ancient city of Campania of Ausonian origins. The Romans captured the town in 335 B.C. and established a colony there.

nodes.title: Calor (river)
nodes.description: A river of Samnium and a major tributary of the Volturno river.

nodes.title: Campania
nodes.description: Campania was a region of southern Italy.

nodes.title: Campi Phlegraei
nodes.description: The Campi Phlegraei (Phlegraean Fields) is a large caldera (13 km wide) in the Bay of Naples region of Italy. In total, the the area comprises 24 craters, although a good portion of the caldera now lies under water. The area was important in Greek and Roman times; the Greeks established their first mainland colony at Cumae within the Campi Phlegraei.

nodes.title: Campochiaro
nodes.description: An Italic sanctuary sacred to Hercules located in località Civitella in the comune of Campochiaro. The site is to be connected with the Pentrian Samnites.

nodes.title: Capreae
nodes.description: Settlement on the island of Capreae.

nodes.title: Capreae (island)
nodes.description: An island of the Bay of Naples off the Sorrentine Peninsula that has, since the time of the Roman Republic, been a popular seaside resort area. The emperor Tiberius maintained twelve villas on the island.

nodes.title: Capua
nodes.description: An important ancient city of Campania with Villanovan and Etruscan origins.

nodes.title: Carecini Supernates
nodes.description: The Carecini Supernates were a tribe of Samnites.

nodes.title: Carsioli
nodes.description: An ancient settlement along the Via Valeria, Carsioli was established as a Latin colony in the territory of the Aequi ca. 298 BC.

nodes.title: Casilinum
nodes.description: A settlement located in the border region between the ager Falernus and the ager Campanus, north of Capua.

nodes.title: Casinum
nodes.description: A Volscian hilltop settlement that became a Roman colony in 312 B.C.

nodes.title: Caudium
nodes.description: A city of Samnium located between Capua and Beneventum. In 321 B.C. the Samnites under C. Pontius encamped there before defeating the Romans at the battle of the Caudine Forks.

nodes.title: Cerfennia
nodes.description: A settlement of the Marsi and a Roman road station on the Via Valeria.

nodes.title: Circeii 1
nodes.description: Circeii received a Latin colony ca. 390 B.C. The remains on the site include an enclosure wall built in polygonal masonry. "Circeii 1" refers to the earlier Roman colony founded at the eastern side of Monte Circeo. The settlement eventually moved to the western side of the peninsula.

nodes.title: Circeii 2
nodes.description: A port on the Tyrrhenian coast. In myth, the site was considered to be one of the stopping points of the hero Odysseus.

nodes.title: Clanius (river)
nodes.description: A river of Campania that likely flowed into the Tyrrhenian Sea near Liternum.

nodes.title: Cumae/Kyme (Campanian)
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Campania, Cumae was the first Greek colony established on the Italian mainland in the eighth century BC.

nodes.title: Damecuta
nodes.description: An Imperial villa excavated by A. Maiuri in the 1930s, Damecuta was connected to the Iulio-Claudian emperors. The construction of later Medieval and Bourbon fortifications on the site significantly damaged the ancient remains. The Medieval Damecuta tower stands atop part of the Roman villa.

nodes.title: Decennovium
nodes.description: Decennovium refers to a 19-mile stretch of the Via Appia from the Forum Appii to Tarracina that continued through the paludes Pontinae.

nodes.title: Diana Tifatina, T.
nodes.description: The Fanum Dianae Tifatinae located on the slopes of Mt. Tifata in Campania.

nodes.title: Dikaiarcheia/Puteoli
nodes.description: A maritime city of Campania situated on the Phlegrean Peninsula. The settlement started as a Greek colony and became a Roman colony under the name Puteoli in 194 B.C.

nodes.title: Epomeus M.
nodes.description: The highest mountain on the island of Ischia.

nodes.title: Eumorfiana? Ins.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D4 Eumorfiana? Ins.

nodes.title: Fabrateria Vetus
nodes.description: Fabrateria Vetus was a Volscian settlement that surrendered to Rome in 424 B.C.

nodes.title: Fagifulae
nodes.description: Fagifulae was a center of the Pentrian Samnites.

nodes.title: Falernus Ager
nodes.description: The Ager Falernus comprised the northern portion of Campania from the Massican hills to the Vulturnus river. The area was celebrated for its fertility and, in particular, for its wines.

nodes.title: Ferentinum
nodes.description: A Hernican town along the Via Latina that the Romans captured in 364 B.C. Later in the Republican period (after 195 B.C.) the city received Roman municipal status.

nodes.title: Formiae
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of likely Greek origin along the Via Appia. Cicero was assassinated near Formiae (now Formia) in 43 B.C.

nodes.title: Forum Popillii
nodes.description: An important town of the Ager Falernus, not to be confused with Forum Popili, the modern Polla.

nodes.title: Fratte
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Fratte

nodes.title: Fregellae
nodes.description: Fregellae was a city of Latium Adjectum that became a Roman colony in 328 B.C., but was subsequently captured by the Samnites; a Roman presence was re-established in 313 B.C. Loyal to Rome during the Second Punic War, Fregellae revolted in 125 B.C. and the site was razed.

nodes.title: Frentani
nodes.description: An Italic people of eastern Italy occupying a territory between the Apennines and the Adriatic seaboard, the Frentani had a close cultural connection with the Samnites.

nodes.title: Frusino
nodes.description: Frusino (modern Frosinone) was a town in Latium along the Via Latina that was originally a Volscian settlement.

nodes.title: Fucinus L.
nodes.description: A lake of ancient Italy, site of a major battle of 89 BC. Flood and drainage controls were attempted by both Claudius and Hadrian. The Torlonia family drained the lake in the nineteenth century.

nodes.title: Fundi
nodes.description: Fundi achieved civitas sine suffragio after the Latin War in 338 B.C.

nodes.title: Gallinaria Silva
nodes.description: An evergreen thicket of the area around Cumae.

nodes.title: Gaurus M.
nodes.description: An eruptive volcanic vent in the Phlegraean Fields.

nodes.title: Grottacce
nodes.description: At Grottacce are the remains of a Roman seaside villa or villa maritima.

nodes.title: Herculaneum
nodes.description: An ancient Roman town of Campania destroyed by the eruption of Mt. Vesuvius in A.D. 79. Named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1997.

nodes.title: Herculis Petra
nodes.description: An islet in the Gulf of Naples.

nodes.title: Imeus (mountain)
nodes.description: Imeus Mons is the name given in the Peutinger Table to a pass that leads from the Fucine lake to the territory of the Peligni; the Via Valeria crossed the pass which is now known as the Forca Caruso.

nodes.title: Interamna Lirenas
nodes.description: A Latin colony founded ca. 312 B.C. along the Via Latina. The site was sacked by Samnites (ca. 294 B.C.) and subsequently by Hannibal (212 B.C.). It received Roman municipal status in 90 B.C.

nodes.title: ‘Invinias’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 ‘Invinias’

nodes.title: ‘Iovis Lareni’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F1 ‘Iovis Lareni’

nodes.title: Latium (region)
nodes.description: The territory of the Latins.

nodes.title: Latium Adiectum
nodes.description: A region of ancient Italy characterized as an area of Latin colonial expansion; also referred to as Latium Novum.

nodes.title: Lautulae
nodes.description: Lautulae is a narrow pass (saltus) located above Terracina in Latium.

nodes.title: Liris/Clanis (river)
nodes.description: The Liris river (modern Liri) is one of the principal rivers of central Italy.

nodes.title: Lucrinus (lake)
nodes.description: A small lake near Lake Avernus.

nodes.title: Lucus Feroniae
nodes.description: A sanctuary of Feronia located at a spring on the via Appia near Tarracina.

nodes.title: Malborghetto
nodes.description: The hamlet of Malborghetto, located on the ancient Via Flaminia, is traditionally linked with Constantine the Great and his visions of victory that occurred prior to the battle of Saxa Rubra on 28 October A.D. 312. The quadrifons arch, dating to the fourth century, marks the intersection of the Via Flaminia and the Via Tiberina.

nodes.title: Marruvium
nodes.description: Ancient Marruvium was the principal city of the Italic tribe of the Marsi.

nodes.title: Massicus
nodes.description: Mons Massicus, a mountain ridge of ancient Italy, in the territory of the Aurunci, at the border of Latium and Campania.

nodes.title: Melpis (river)
nodes.description: The Melfa river flows through Lazio, originating from the Monti della Meta and joining the Liri river near San Giovanni Incarico.

nodes.title: Minturnae
nodes.description: Originally an Ausonian town that fought against Rome in 314 B.C., Minturnae became a colony in 296 B.C. The site is located on the Garigliano river (ancient Liris) and served an important economic function. The Via Appia passes through the city.

nodes.title: Misenum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Misenum

nodes.title: Monte S. Croce
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Monte S. Croce

nodes.title: Monte Vairano
nodes.description: At Monte Vairano are the remains of a fortified center of the Pentrian Samnites.

nodes.title: Mura di S. Stefano
nodes.description: A second century A.D. Roman villa built atop an earlier villa rustica.

nodes.title: Nuceria (Alfaterna)
nodes.description: Nuceria (Alfaterna) (modern Nocera Inferiore) is an ancient settlement in Campania. In pre-Roman times this was the chief settlement of the Sarnus river valley.

nodes.title: Oplontis
nodes.description: An ancient place (modern Torre Annunziata in Italy), lying between Pompeii and Herculaneum and buried by the eruption of Vesuvius in 79 CE. Its ancient name is known only from Peutinger's Roman Map.

nodes.title: Palazzo a Mare
nodes.description: The site of one of the twelve villas of Tiberius, and perhaps the largest, on the island of Capreae.

nodes.title: *Pallanum
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of the Frentani located on Monte Pallano.

nodes.title: Palmaria (island)
nodes.description: The second largest of the Pontine Islands, the modern Palmarola.

nodes.title: Paludes Minturnenses
nodes.description: The Marshes of Mintumae were located near the mouth of the river Liris.

nodes.title: Panapio/Punicum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 A1 Panapio/Punicum

nodes.title: Pandataria (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Pontine archipelago of the Tyrrhenian Sea, Pandataria is volcanic in origin and is best known, in historical terms, as the place to which Augustus banished Julia the Elder, his daughter, in 2 BC and to which Tiberius banished Agrippina the Elder in AD 29.

nodes.title: Parthenope/Neapolis
nodes.description: Founded as Parthenope by Greeks in the eighth century B.C., the site eventually gave rise to Neapolis in the sixth century B.C. and was one of the most prominent cities of Magna Graecia.

nodes.title: Pentri
nodes.description: The Pentri were a major tribe of Oscan-speaking Samnites; their chief center was Bovianum Undecumanorum.

nodes.title: Picentinus Ager
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Picentinus Ager

nodes.title: Samnite Sanctuary at Pietrabbondante
nodes.description: An ancient sanctuary on the slope of Monte Saraceno in the modern Italian comune of Pietrabbondante.

nodes.title: Pithekoussai
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E4 Pithekoussai

nodes.title: Pompeii
nodes.description: An ancient city of Campania destroyed by the volcanic eruption of Mt. Vesuvius in A.D. 79, Pompeii was named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1997.

nodes.title: Pomptinae Paludes
nodes.description: The Pomptinae Paludes (Pontine Marshes) is an area of former marshland in Latium.

nodes.title: Pomptinus Ager
nodes.description: Pomptinus Ager (Pomptine plain) is a region in Latium lying between Albanus M. and the Tyrrhenian coast.

nodes.title: Pons Campanus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Pons Campanus

nodes.title: Pontia
nodes.description: A settlement on Pontia Ins. The largest of the Pontine Islands, Pontia lies 33 km south of Cape Circeo on the Italian mainland.

nodes.title: Pontiae (islands)
nodes.description: An archipelago in the Tyrrhenian Sea off the west coast of Italy.

nodes.title: Privernum
nodes.description: A Volscian center that Rome reportedly destroyed in the late fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: Prochyta (island)
nodes.description: Procida is one of the Flegrean Islands located between Cape Miseno and the island of Ischia.

nodes.title: Punta Chiarito
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E4 Punta Chiarito

nodes.title: Punta Eolo
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D4 Punta Eolo

nodes.title: Puteolanus Sinus/Crater
nodes.description: Also called the Bay of Naples, the Puteolanus Sinus is a gulf located on the southwestern coast of Italy. It opens west to the Mediterranean Sea and is bordered on the east by Mt. Vesuvius and the south by the Sorrentine Peninsula.

nodes.title: Pyrgi
nodes.description: Pyrgi is an ancient Etruscan port city on the Tyrrhenian coast of Italy. A Roman colony was established at the site by 191 B.C. In 1964 the bi-lingual 'Pyrgi Plaques' were discovered during the course of excavations.

nodes.title: Saepinum
nodes.description: An ancient town of Samnium captured by the Romans in 293 B.C., located on the road between Beneventum and Corfinium.

nodes.title: Salernum
nodes.description: A city of Campania with Osco-Etruscan origins that became a Roman colony in 197 B.C.

nodes.title: Saltus Vescinus/Mefineis? M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Saltus Vescinus/Mefineis? M.

nodes.title: Samnium (region)
nodes.description: Samnium is the Latin name for a region of south and central Italy inhabited by the Samnites. The geographic limits of this region prior to sustained Roman contact are poorly defined. With the Augustan reorganization of Italy, the pre-Roman Samnium is subdivided among three of the Augustan regions.

nodes.title: S. Benedictus
nodes.description: A monastery originally established by St. Benedict of Nursia in A.D. 529/530.

nodes.title: S. Rocco
nodes.description: The San Rocco villa was built during the second quarter of the first century B.C. It was initially a simple villa rustica and it was later enlarged substantially.

nodes.title: S. Sebastianus
nodes.description: San Sebastiano in the territory of Alatri originates in the late fifth century.

nodes.title: S. Vincenzo al Volturno
nodes.description: S. Vincenzo al Volturno is a multi-period settlement. In pre-Roman times a phase of Samnite occupation has been identified. By the fifth century A.D. the site was occupied by a large agricultural estate (villa) that was abandoned in the later fifth century, only to be replaced by a Christian church.

nodes.title: Sarno
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Sarno

nodes.title: Sarnus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Sarnus fl.

nodes.title: Sebethus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Sebethus fl.

nodes.title: Sidicini
nodes.description: The Sidicini were a people of ancient Italy; their territory bordered that of the Campani and the Samnites.

nodes.title: Sinonia (island)
nodes.description: A small island that is part of the Pontine Islands.

nodes.title: Sinues(s)a/Sinope
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Sinues(s)a/Sinope

nodes.title: Sora
nodes.description: An ancient city of Latium located in the valley of the Liris river that likely had Volscian origins. The Romans captured the city in 345 BC and later established a colony there in 303 BC after the Second Samnite War.

nodes.title: Speluncae
nodes.description: An ancient grotto, associated with the nearby Villa Tiberii, at the modern Italian town of Sperlonga.

nodes.title: Stabiae
nodes.description: An Oscan and Roman settlement located on the bay of Naples.

nodes.title: Suessa Aurunca
nodes.description: The ancient center of the Aurunci, Suessa Aurunca was abandoned in 337 B.C. for a more favorable site (modern Sessa) where a Latin colony was established in 313 B.C.

nodes.title: Sulmo
nodes.description: A chief settlement of the Peligni that was ravaged by the Carthaginians during the Second Punic War.

nodes.title: *Supinum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 *Supinum

nodes.title: Surrentum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Surrentum

nodes.title: Taburnus M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G3 Taburnus M.

nodes.title: Tarracina(e)/Anxur
nodes.description: A strategic Volscian city that had come under Roman control by 509 B.C.; a Roman citizen colony was established there in 329 B.C. The site is particularly notable for the remains of the terraced sanctuary of Iuppiter Anxur.

nodes.title: Teanum Sidicinum
nodes.description: Teanum Sidicinum (modern Teano) was the capital of the Oscan-speaking Sidicini tribe. The city likely submitted to Rome after 334 B.C.

nodes.title: Telesia
nodes.description: An ancient Samnite city located in the valley of the Calor river.

nodes.title: Terventum
nodes.description: Terventum was the site of a Roman municipium established in the territory of the Pentrian Samnites.

nodes.title: Tifata M.
nodes.description: A mountainous region of central Italy known to be densely wooded with oak trees.

nodes.title: Tifernus (river)
nodes.description: The Tifernus (modern Biferno) is a river of Molise that flows from near Bojano to the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Tifernus M.
nodes.description: Tifernus M. (Monti Matese), a mountain chain that straddles Campania and Molise in the central-southern Apennines.

nodes.title: Treba
nodes.description: Treba (modern Trevi nel Lazio) was originally a settlement of the Aequi.

nodes.title: Trebula Balli(ni)ensium
nodes.description: An ancient city of Campania that became enfranchised in the Roman system in the late fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: The Sanctuary of Vastogirardi
nodes.description: A sanctuary of the Pentrian Samnites on the flanks of Monte Capraro, north of the modern Italian village of Vastogirardi.

nodes.title: Venafrum
nodes.description: Venafrum was an ancient town of Campania.

nodes.title: Verulae
nodes.description: Verulae is an ancient city that became a Roman municipium in 90 B.C.

nodes.title: Vesuvius M.
nodes.description: A stratovolcano located in the Gulf of Naples, Vesuvius stands to an elevation of 1,281 m (4,203 ft). It is notable in historical terms for its eruption of AD 79 in which numerous settlements, including Pompeii and Herculaneum, were destroyed.

nodes.title: Vietri
nodes.description: Modern Vietri sul mare is the likely site of ancient Marcina, an Etruscan settlement in the ager Picentinus located 120 stades from Pompeii. It later came to be inhabited by Samnites.

nodes.title: Villa Iovis
nodes.description: A 7,000 m² palatial villa built atop the island of Capreae by the Roman emperor Tiberius.

nodes.title: Villa Tiberii
nodes.description: A coastal villa at Sperlonga associated with the Roman emperor Tiberius.

nodes.title: Volsci
nodes.description: The Volsci (Volscians) were an Italic tribe of central Italy during the first millennium B.C. They inhabited parts of southern Latium and were bounded by other tribes, including the Aurunci, Samnites, and Hernici.

nodes.title: Volturnum
nodes.description: Volturnum was located at the mouth of the Volturno river.

nodes.title: Volturnus (river)
nodes.description: The Volturno river flows 175 km from the Apennines to the Tyrrhenian Sea at Castel Volturno.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D3 unnamed aqueduct (Tarracina(e))

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 unnamed aqueduct (Casinum)

nodes.title: Aqueduct (Venafrum)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 unnamed aqueduct (Venafrum)

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge over the Volturnus river on the Via Domitiana
nodes.description: An unnamed bridge located along the Via Domitiana.

nodes.title: Ponte Latrone
nodes.description: A Roman bridge on the Volturno river located near Capriati.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 unnamed bridge (Ponte Sfondato, E Teanum Sidicinum)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G3 unnamed bridge group (Via Appia from Caudium to Beneventum)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D2 unnamed canal (from Fucinus L., near Pitonia?)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D3 unnamed canal (in Pomptinae Paludes)

nodes.title: Centuriation (Frusino)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D2 unnamed centuriation (Frusino)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D3 unnamed centuriation (Fundi)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D3 unnamed centuriation (Pomptinus Ager)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D3 unnamed centuriation (Tarracina(e))

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 unnamed centuriation (Aquinum)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 unnamed centuriation (Formiae)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 unnamed centuriation (Forum Popilii)

nodes.title: Unnamed centuriation (Cales)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 unnamed centuriation (Cales)

nodes.title: Unnamed centuriation (Teanum Sidicinum)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 unnamed centuriation (Teanum Sidicinum)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 unnamed centuriation (Trebula Balli(ni)ensium)

nodes.title: Centuriation (Venafrum)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 unnamed centuriation (Venafrum)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 unnamed centuriation (Pompeii)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G3 unnamed centuriation (Caudium)

nodes.title: Unnamed centuriation
nodes.description: Traces of centuriation connected with the Roman phase(s) of Saepinum.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 unnamed centuriation (Abellinum)

nodes.title: Abolani
nodes.description: The Abolani number among the 53 peoples of Latium Vetus that Pliny the Elder records as having perished without leaving a trace (interiere sine vestigiis).

nodes.title: Accienses
nodes.description: The Accienses number among the 53 peoples of Latium Vetus that Pliny the Elder records as having perished without leaving a trace (interiere sine vestigiis).

nodes.title: Allia (river)
nodes.description: The Allia river was a tributary of the Tiber, but is now unlocated. It joined the Tiber some 18 km (11 miles) north of Rome and was most famous as the site of a battle in which the Romans were defeated by Brennus and the Gauls ca. 387 B.C.

nodes.title: Ameriola
nodes.description: An ancient town of Latium that was a member of the Latin League.

nodes.title: Amitinum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Amitinum

nodes.title: Apiolae
nodes.description: An ancient city of Latium that led the Latin resistance against Tarquinius Priscus.

nodes.title: Arcanum
nodes.description: Arcanum was the location of an estate that belonged to Quintus Cicero. it was located between Aquinum and Arpinum.

nodes.title: Bolani
nodes.description: The Bolani were the people of Bola, an ancient city of Latium. Its foundation is ascribed by Virgil to the kings of Alba.

nodes.title: Bubetani
nodes.description: The Bubetani number among the 53 peoples of Latium Vetus that Pliny the Elder records as having perished without leaving a trace (interiere sine vestigiis).

nodes.title: Caenina
nodes.description: Caenina was an ancient town of Latium.

nodes.title: Cameria
nodes.description: An ancient city of Latium that is noted by Pliny the Elder as one of the lost cities of central Italy.

nodes.title: Capitulum Hernicum
nodes.description: A Hernican town that still existed in Pliny's time, Capitulum Hernicum received colonists under both Sulla and Iulius Caesar.

nodes.title: Carventum
nodes.description: Carventum was an ancient city of Latium, listed by Dionysius as one of the thirty states of the Latin League.

nodes.title: Castrum Invi
nodes.description: An Italic site located at the mouth of the Incastro river and in the territory of Ardea.

nodes.title: Cominium Ocritum
nodes.description: Cominium Ocritum was a Samnite stronghold captured in 291 BC by Quintus Fabius Maximus Gurges.

nodes.title: Coras M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Coras M.

nodes.title: Corbio
nodes.description: Corbio was an ancient city of Latium located on the northeastern flank of the Alban Hills, although its precise location is no longer secure. This Latin city is said to have fallen to the Aequi and then been the subject of contention between the Aequi and the Romans, ultimately recaptured by the latter after Cincinnatus' victory at Mons Algidus in 458 B.C.

nodes.title: Corioli
nodes.description: Corioli was an ancient city of Latium connected in the tradition with C. Marcius Coriolanus. The location of Corioli is no longer known.

nodes.title: Ebutiana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Ebutiana

nodes.title: Hortenses
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Hortenses

nodes.title: Lanuenses
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Lanuenses

nodes.title: Laterium
nodes.description: A villa of Q. Tullius Cicero located in the territory of Arpinum, near Cereatae.

nodes.title: Latinienses
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Latinienses

nodes.title: Longula
nodes.description: Longula was an early settlement of Latium Vetus, although its location is no longer known. A Volscian city, Longula was first taken by the Romans in 493 B.C. under the consul Postumus Cominius. It subsequently changes hands several times during the fifth and fourth centuries B.C. It likely lay between Ardea and Antium.

nodes.title: Lucanum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated *Lucanum

nodes.title: Macrales
nodes.description: The Macrales number among the 53 peoples of Latium Vetus that Pliny the Elder records as having perished without leaving a trace (interiere sine vestigiis).

nodes.title: Manates
nodes.description: The Manates number among the 53 peoples of Latium Vetus that Pliny the Elder records as having perished without leaving a trace (interiere sine vestigiis).

nodes.title: Munienses
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Munienses

nodes.title: Octulani
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Octulani

nodes.title: Olliculani
nodes.description: The Olliculani number among the 53 peoples of Latium Vetus that Pliny the Elder records as having perished without leaving a trace (interiere sine vestigiis).

nodes.title: Pedum
nodes.description: Pedum was an ancient city of Latium that was part of the Latin League. Located between Tibur and Praeneste, its precise location is now unknown. Some suggest that modern Gallicano is the site of the ancient city.

nodes.title: Petrinus Vicus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Petrinus Vicus?

nodes.title: Pollusca
nodes.description: Pollusca was an early city of Latium Vetus connected with Longula and Corioli. These three cities were captured by Coriolanus in 488 BC. The location of Pollusca is no longer known.

nodes.title: Querquetulani
nodes.description: An ancient tribe of Latium Vetus enumerated by Pliny the Elder as having disappeared by the first century.

nodes.title: Romulea
nodes.description: Now unlocated, Romulea was captured by the Romans during the Third Samnite War.

nodes.title: Salutaris Pagus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Salutaris Pagus

nodes.title: Sassula
nodes.description: Now unlocated, Sassula was a city of Latium captured by the Romans in 354 B.C.

nodes.title: Scaptia
nodes.description: Scaptia, now unlocated, was an ancient town of Latium from which the tribus Scaptia derived its name.

nodes.title: Septem Pagi
nodes.description: Septem Pagi refers to a community of South Etruria located on the Tiber's right bank that was absorbed by Rome at an early date.

nodes.title: Sisolenses
nodes.description: The Sisolenses number among the 53 peoples of Latium Vetus that Pliny the Elder records as having perished without leaving a trace (interiere sine vestigiis).

nodes.title: Tellena
nodes.description: Tellena was a prominent city of ancient Latium that factors in the early history of the city of Rome. Its location is no longer certain.

nodes.title: Tifata (Latium)
nodes.description: Tifata is a site in Latium listed as defunct by the elder Pliny. Palmer notes that Festus (43 L) raises the question of an identically named Roman curia.

nodes.title: Tolerium
nodes.description: Tolerium was an ancient city that was a part of the Latin League. Antonio Nibby supported associating its location with Valmontone.

nodes.title: Tucianus Pagus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Tucianus Pagus

nodes.title: Ulmanus Pagus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Ulmanus Pagus

nodes.title: Velienses
nodes.description: The Velienses number among the 53 peoples of Latium Vetus that Pliny the Elder records as having perished without leaving a trace (interiere sine vestigiis).

nodes.title: Venetulani
nodes.description: The Venetulani number among the 53 peoples of Latium Vetus that Pliny the Elder records as having perished without leaving a trace (interiere sine vestigiis).

nodes.title: Verrugo
nodes.description: Verrugo was a Volscian settlement at the borders of Latium. Its location is now uncertain.

nodes.title: Vescia
nodes.description: Vescia was a city of the Ausones that is now unlocated. It became involved in the Latin War and Rome destroyed the city in 314 B.C.

nodes.title: Via Popilia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 unlocated Via Popilia

nodes.title: Via Vitularia
nodes.description: A Roman road, now unlocated, near Arpinum.

nodes.title: Vicus Esquilinus
nodes.description: Vicus Esquilinus is a district connected with Cales in Campania.

nodes.title: Vicus Palatius
nodes.description: A district or small extra-urban settlement, mentioned in an inscription, that seems to have been connected with the Roman colonial foundation at Cales in Campania.

nodes.title: Vimitellari
nodes.description: The Vimitellari number among the 53 peoples of Latium Vetus that Pliny the Elder records as having perished without leaving a trace (interiere sine vestigiis).

nodes.title: Ad Calorem
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 A2 Ad Calorem

nodes.title: Ad Fluvium Bradanum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 C3 Ad Fluvium Bradanum

nodes.title: Aecae
nodes.description: An ancient town of Apulia that in legend was reported to have been founded by Diomedes. In the third century B.C. the Roman general Quintus Fabius Maximus captured the town after the battle of Cannae.

nodes.title: Aeclanum
nodes.description: An ancient settlement in Samnium that came to be associated with the Hirpini.

nodes.title: Aequum Tuticum/Equus Tuticus
nodes.description: Aequum Tuticum/Equus Tuticus was an ancient Oscan town. The settlement was located near the intersection of the Via Traiana and the Via Herculia in the territory of the Hirpini.

nodes.title: Agropoli
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 A4 Agropoli

nodes.title: Alburnus Portus
nodes.description: A port at the mouth of the river Silarus that derived its name from Alburnus mons.

nodes.title: Aquilonia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 B2 Aquilonia

nodes.title: Aufidus (river)
nodes.description: The Aufidus is the longest of the rivers in Apulia.

nodes.title: Ausculum
nodes.description: Ausculum (Ascoli Satriano) was a settlement of the Daunians.

nodes.title: (B)Aletium
nodes.description: (B)Aletium (Alezio) was a Messapic center that had ties to the Iapyges, according to Pliny. Saracens destroyed the site ca. A.D. 1000.

nodes.title: Barium
nodes.description: A city of the Peucetii that came under Roman control in the third century BC.

nodes.title: Bradanus (river)
nodes.description: A river of Lucania which flows into the Gulf of Tarentum.

nodes.title: Brundisium/Brentesion
nodes.description: A Greek and Roman port, terminus of the Via Appia.

nodes.title: Butuntum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 E2 Butuntum

nodes.title: Caelia
nodes.description: A town of the Peucetii in Apulia.

nodes.title: Caelia
nodes.description: Caelia (Ceglie Messapica) was a Messapic site of south Italy that received Greek colonists after 700 B.C.

nodes.title: Calabria
nodes.description: Ancient Calabria comprised the southern part of Apulia and the Salento peninsula.

nodes.title: Cannae
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Apulia on the Aufidus river. Nearby the Roman army suffered a major defeat at the hands of the Carthaginians in 216 B.C. during the Second Punic War.

nodes.title: Canusium
nodes.description: A center of the ancient Daunians, Canusium became allied to Rome in 318 B.C. It received municipal status in 88 B.C.

nodes.title: Castrum Minervae/Athenaion/Limen Aphrodites
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of the Sallentini in Apulia. Legendary history held that this was the spot where Aeneas first landed in Italy, thus the assignation 'Limen Aphrodites' or 'Portus Veneris'.

nodes.title: Casuentus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 D3 Casuentus fl.

nodes.title: Cavallino
nodes.description: Cavallino was an ancient center of the Messapii.

nodes.title: Cerbalus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 C2 Cerbalus fl.

nodes.title: Choirades Nesoi
nodes.description: A small archipelago composed of two islands - San Pietro and San Paolo - in the gulf of Taranto.

nodes.title: Chones
nodes.description: Chones, an ancient Lucanian tribe.

nodes.title: Compsa
nodes.description: Compsa was a city of the Hirpini, located near the sources of the Aufidus river.

nodes.title: Daunii
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 B2 Daunii

nodes.title: Diria?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 F3 Diria?

nodes.title: Diomedeae Islands
nodes.description: An Adriatic archipelago north of Mons Garganus.

nodes.title: Diomedis Campi
nodes.description: The name assigned by some writers, including Livy, to the plain of Canusium, in which the battle of Cannae was fought in August of 216 BC.

nodes.title: Egnatia/Gnathia
nodes.description: Egnatia/Gnathia was an ancient city of the Messapii in southern Italy.

nodes.title: Ergitium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 B1 Ergitium

nodes.title: Fertur (river)
nodes.description: Fertur fl. (Fortore river)

nodes.title: Fioccaglia di Flumeri
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 B2 Fioccaglia di Flumeri

nodes.title: Forentum?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 C2 Forentum?

nodes.title: Furfane
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 C2 Furfane

nodes.title: Garganou Kolpos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 B1 Garganou Kolpos

nodes.title: Gargani Pr.
nodes.description: Promontory of the Garganus Mons

nodes.title: Garganus Mons
nodes.description: A massif and promontory of Apulia.

nodes.title: Genusia
nodes.description: Genusia, modern Ginosa, was a city of the Peucetii located to the west of Tarentum.

nodes.title: Grumentum
nodes.description: Grumentum was an ancient settlement of Lucania, likely inhabited since the sixth century B.C. The site played a role in the Second Punic War and later became a bishopric in the fourth century A.D.

nodes.title: *Grumum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 E2 *Grumum

nodes.title: Temple of Hera at Foce del Sele
nodes.description: A sanctuary at the mouth of the Sele river in Italy with an octastyle temple dedicated to the Argive Hera.

nodes.title: Hera temple
nodes.description: The so-called 'Tavole Palatine' is the site of the ruins of a sixth century B.C. Doric temple sacred to Hera and associated with the city of Metapontum.

nodes.title: Herdoniae/Ardaneae/Civitas Serdonis
nodes.description: Herdonia was an ancient city of Apulia located along the via Minucia. The city was the site of two major engagements of the Second Punic War (212 and 210 B.C., respectively), both of which were Carthaginian victories. The city's extensive remains have been investigated by the Belgian Institute since the Second World War.

nodes.title: Hirpini
nodes.description: The Hirpini were an ancient Samnite people of central Italy.

nodes.title: Ionios Kolpos/Tarentinus Sinus
nodes.description: Ionios Kolpos/Tarentinus Sinus (Gulf of Taranto) is a gulf of the Ionian Sea.

nodes.title: Karbinai?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 G3 Karbinai?

nodes.title: Larinum
nodes.description: A settlement of Apulia that originated with the Samnites and Frentani and later came under Roman influence. During the Second Punic War, the Romans defeated Hannibal at Larinum. The settlement eventually gained Roman municipal status.

nodes.title: Lucania (region)
nodes.description: An ancient region of south Italy stretching from the Tyrrhenian Sea to the Gulf of Taranto.

nodes.title: Luceria/Noukeria (Apoulon)
nodes.description: Luceria/Noukeria (Apoulon) was originally a Daunian city. It was named as a Colonia Togata in 320 B.C. and came to play a significant role in the Second Punic War. Constans II sacked the town in A.D. 663.

nodes.title: Lupia(e)
nodes.description: A settlement of the indigenous Messapii that was refounded under Roman influence in the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Manduria
nodes.description: Manduria was a key Messapic center. Archidamus III, king of Sparta, fell there in 338 B.C. while leading the army of Taras.

nodes.title: Matera
nodes.description: Matera is an ancient settlement in the Basilicata region of Italy where human occupation is evident beginning from 9,000 years BP.

nodes.title: Merinum
nodes.description: An ancient city placed in the Gargano and discussed by Pliny the Elder.

nodes.title: Mesagne
nodes.description: A center of the Messapii in Apulia.

nodes.title: Messapii
nodes.description: The Messapii were an ancient Indo-European people occupying the Salento peninsula in southeast Italy.

nodes.title: Metapontum
nodes.description: An important city of Magna Graecia, Metapontum was located on the Gulf of Tarentum. The Achaeans were responsible for its foundation, perhaps as early as the eighth century B.C.

nodes.title: Moio della Civitella
nodes.description: A fortified outpost (phrourion) of the city of Velia/Elea.

nodes.title: Neretum
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of the Messapii in Apulia captured by the Romans in 269 BC. The Trajanic extension of the Via Appia ran through the site.

nodes.title: Paestanus Sinus
nodes.description: A gulf of the Tyrrhenian Sea.

nodes.title: Peucetii
nodes.description: The Peucetii were an ancient tribe of Apulia in southern Italy.

nodes.title: Pons Aufidi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 C2 Pons Aufidi

nodes.title: Pontecagnano
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 A3 Pontecagnano

nodes.title: Poseidonia/Paestum
nodes.description: A major Greco-Roman center of south Italy, Poseidonia/Paestum was originally founded by Greeks from Sybaris in the seventh century BC, who named the settlement Poseidonia. After the Pyrrhic war, the city became a Latin colony named Paestum ca. 273 BC.

nodes.title: ‘Rudas’/‘Budas’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 D2 ‘Rudas’/‘Budas’

nodes.title: Rudiae
nodes.description: An ancient Messapic town, Rudiae was the birthplace of the poet Ennius.

nodes.title: Sallentini
nodes.description: Sallentini were a tribe of an ancient Apulia, the 'heel' of the booth of the Italian peninsula. They spoke the Messapian language.

nodes.title: Sallentinum/Iapygia
nodes.description: Cape Leuca, known as Sallentinum and Iapygia in ancient sources, is a headland that forms the extreme southeastern point of Italy and separates the Gulf of Tarentum from the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Aristanis
nodes.description: A Byzantine site in western Sardinia, made important by the location of a bishopric there by Torcotorio in AD 1070; now the modern city of Oristano.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Santu Antine
nodes.description: A nuragic structure dating originally ca. 1,600 to 1,450 BC.

nodes.title: Mortuary Temple of Senwosret III
nodes.description: Mortuary temple constructed for Senwosret III, a pharaoh of the 12th Dynasty in Egypt.

nodes.title: Via Herdonitana
nodes.description: A Roman road connecting Herdonia and Ausculum.

nodes.title: Via Aurelia Aeclanensis?
nodes.description: A road in Apulia leading from Aeclanum toward Vibinum. The Via Aurelia Aeclanensis? intersects the Via Herculia.

nodes.title: Via Tiberina
nodes.description: An ancient Roman road.

nodes.title: Tomb of Priscilla
nodes.description: A Roman tomb along the Via Appia that belonged to one Priscilla, wife of Titus Flavius Abascanto, a freedman of the emperor Domitian.

nodes.title: Villa of the Papyri
nodes.description: A suburban villa located northwest of Herculaneum that was originally owned by Lucius Calpurnius Piso Caesoninus.

nodes.title: Villa of the Mysteries
nodes.description: A Roman villa located northwest of Pompeii.

nodes.title: Gallo-Roman Structure at Moissac
nodes.description: A Gallo-Roman structure including hypocaust and other remains of a bath, located beneath the later Church of Saint Martin in modern Moissac, France. The bath may have belonged to a villa of the fourth-fifth centuries CE.

nodes.title: Unnamed Roman bridgehead
nodes.description: Ancient bridgehead west of Milecastle 27 (Hadrian's Wall), providing link to Cilurnum.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Fortuna Primigenia
nodes.description: The Sanctuary of Fortuna Primigenia at Praeneste is a terraced sanctuary of monumental proportions. The phase visible today dates to the late second century B.C.

nodes.title: Second Temple, Jerusalem
nodes.description: The so-called "Second Temple" in Jerusalem stood on the northern edge of the Dome of the Rock and was destroyed in A.D. 70 during the Roman siege.

nodes.title: Great Mosque of the Umayyads
nodes.description: The Great Mosque of the Umayyads is located in the old city of Damascus and is one of the largest and oldest mosques in the world. It was completed in 715.

nodes.title: Roman Theatre of Orange
nodes.description: The Roman Theatre of Orange was built early in the first century A.D.

nodes.title: Theater at Xanthos
nodes.description: The Greek theater (second century BC) was renovated following a Roman design following the earthquake of A.D. 141.

nodes.title: Tyre Hippodrome
nodes.description: The Tyre Hippodrome dates to the second century.

nodes.title: Ancient Stadium of Rhodes
nodes.description: The Hellenistic Stadium on the Acropolis of Rhodes.

nodes.title: Temple of Apollo Pythios
nodes.description: The Hellenistic Temple of Apollo Pythios on the Acropolis of the city of Rhodes.

nodes.title: Temple of Zeus at Olympia
nodes.description: The Temple of Zeus at Olympia was built in the second quarter of the fifth century B.C. Libon of Elis served as architect.

nodes.title: Roman Temple of Évora
nodes.description: The Roman Temple of Évora, also referred to as the Temple of Diana, is a Roman temple of the first century A.D.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Brixia
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Brixia was built during the Flavian period.

nodes.title: San Salvatore monastery
nodes.description: A monastery founded in A.D. 753 by Desiderius, future king of the Lombards. Located in modern Brescia, Italy.

nodes.title: Tomb of Cyrus the Great
nodes.description: The Tomb of Cyrus the Great is located about 1 km southwest of the palaces at Pasargadae. It is typically dated to ca. to 559-529 B.C.

nodes.title: Gastaldaga area and the Episcopal complex
nodes.description: A Longobard complex in Cividale del Friuli.

nodes.title: Byzantine arcosolia
nodes.description: Byzantine tombs at the site belong to the sixth century when the Temple of Concordia was converted into a Christian church.

nodes.title: Lower Agora
nodes.description: The lower agora of the ancient city of Agrigentum contains shops, a sacred area, and the gymnasium complex.

nodes.title: Catacombs of Generosa
nodes.description: A Paleochristian catacomb located at the sixth mile of the via Portuense.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Losa
nodes.description: A nuraghe near Abbasanta, Sardinia. The original phase of the site dates to the fifteenth through thirteenth centuries B.C., while the enclosure wall dates to the thirteenth and twelfth centuries B.C. The site saw diminished activity in the Iron Age; the eighth and seventh centuries B.C. show evidence for funerary activity.

nodes.title: Gird-i Bazar
nodes.description: Archaeological site in the Peshdar Plain with remains dated to the Neo-Assyrian period. The site is part of a larger frontier settlement known as the Dinka Settlement Complex.

nodes.title: Shrine of Venus Cloacina
nodes.description: The Sacrum Cloacina was a small shrine dedicated to Venus Cloacina, patron divinity of the sewer, and was located near the Tabernae novae in the Forum Romanum. The foundation of the sacellum is extant while images of its likely elevation are found on Roman coins.

nodes.title: tribus Voltinia
nodes.description: The tribus Voltinia (or Votinia) was an older rural tribe of ancient Rome.

nodes.title: Skinburness
nodes.description: Milefortlet 9, Skinburness

nodes.title: Casiana
nodes.description: A fortress (phrourion) and settlement near Apamea on the Orontes river. The precise location is unknown today.

nodes.title: Porta Maggiore
nodes.description: The Porta Maggiore is the ancient Porta Praenestina, an early Imperial gate preserved in the later third century walls built by Aurelian.

nodes.title: The Great Pyramid
nodes.description: The Great Pyramid of Khufu was built ca. 2580–2560 B.C. during the 4th dynasty of ancient Egypt. It initially stood to a height of 146.5 meters (481 feet).

nodes.title: Walls
nodes.description: Approximate linear extent of the ancient city walls

nodes.title: Martyrion
nodes.description: Unknown

nodes.title: Sebasteion
nodes.description: The Sebasteion at Aphrodisias was a temple complex dedicated to Aphrodite and the Iulio-Claudian emperors that was financed by local patrons. It was built between ca. AD 20 and 60. The complex was excavated in 1979-81.

nodes.title: Akkad
nodes.description: Akkad (Māt-Akkadî) is the name of a historical region of central Mesopotamia (northern Babylonia). During the Sargonic/Akkadian Period (ca. 2334-2113 B.C.), its capital was the city of Agade, which may have been located somewhere near the confluence of the Diyala and Tigris Rivers. In cuneiform texts of the first millennium B.C., the term Māt-Akkadî was used for the name of the region roughly comprising the northern half of Babylonia, now modern-day central Iraq.

nodes.title: Hatti (region)
nodes.description: In Assyrian and Babylonian texts of the first millennium BC, Hatti is a purely geographical term referring to North Syria, the area roughly covered by Syro-Hittite states west of the Euphrates River.

nodes.title: Fortified Port Settlement on Cape St. Athanasius
nodes.description: An ancient settlement with fortifications and port facilities located on the modern Cape St. Athanasius near Byala in Bulgaria.

nodes.title: Roman wall, Gijon
nodes.description: A Roman fortification wall that dates initially to the third or fourth century.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Toscono
nodes.description: A single tower nuraghe standing ca. 7.25 meters.

nodes.title: Baqa
nodes.description: An unlocated city/town in the kingdom of Suhu, probably not far from Alu-eššu, Qaqqar-aradātu, and Ribaniš.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Porcarzos
nodes.description: A complex nuraghe surrounded by a quadrilobate bastion.

nodes.title: Santa Maria dell'Orto
nodes.description: The church of Santa Maria dell'Orto is a Roman Catholic church located in Rome's Trastevere district. Its foundation is traced to 508.

nodes.title: Esagila
nodes.description: The temple of the god Marduk at Babylon. The Sumerian ceremonial name Esagil(a) means "House, Whose Top is High."

nodes.title: Panjakent
nodes.description: The easternmost city of Sogdiana, inhabited from the fifth-ninth centuries CE.

nodes.title: Ishkhani (monastery)
nodes.description: A church and monastery in Tao-Klarjeti, first constructed in the 7th century.

nodes.title: Sarissa
nodes.description: Sarissa was a Hititite site of the second millennium BC. Its remains are located at Kuşaklı, Turkey. Excavations have recovered a substantial archive of Hittite texts.

nodes.title: Pauli Stincus
nodes.description: A Punic farm site occupied from the fourth to the second century B.C.

nodes.title: Achaea Phthiotis
nodes.description: Achaea Phthiotis was a historical region of ancient Greece in southeastern Thessaly.

nodes.title: Aetolia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 A3 Aetolia

nodes.title: Amphiareion
nodes.description: The Amphiareion of Oropos was an ancient sanctuary dedicated in the fifth century BC to the hero Amphiaraos and located in the hills southeast of the port of Oropos.

nodes.title: Apollo, T.
nodes.description: The oracular shrine of Apollo Koropaios.

nodes.title: Asopos (river)
nodes.description: A river of Boeotia and northern Attica that marked the border between the cities of Thebes and Plataea.

nodes.title: Atrax
nodes.description: An ancient Greek polis in Pelasgiotis in Thessaly. The site is located in modern Greece, immediately south of the Peneios river and 2.5 km west of a small village named Κάστρο (Kastro), which is within the municipality of Larissa.

nodes.title: Azoros
nodes.description: Azoros was a citty belonging to the tripolis of the Perrhaebi.

nodes.title: Boeotia
nodes.description: A region of central Greece inhabited since prehistoric times.

nodes.title: Calydon
nodes.description: An ancient Greek city of Aetolia that derives its name from its founder Calydon, son of Aetolus.

nodes.title: Cicynethus (island)
nodes.description: A small island in the Pagasitic Gulf.

nodes.title: Delphi
nodes.description: The ancient pan-Hellenic sanctuary of Delphi in Greece, seat of the oracle of Apollo.

nodes.title: Demeter, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 D3 Demeter, T.

nodes.title: Demetrias (Magnesian)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 D2 Demetrias

nodes.title: Dirphys M.
nodes.description: Highest point (1745 meters) on the island of Euboea

nodes.title: Eleutherai
nodes.description: A city of northern Attika at the boundary of Boeotia, Eleutherai is one of the best preserved ancient fortresses in Attika.

nodes.title: Euboea (island)
nodes.description: Euboea is the second largest Greek island by area and is separated from the Greek mainland by the Euripus Strait.

nodes.title: Euenos (river)
nodes.description: The Euenos (modern Evinos) is a river of western Greece that flows into the Gulf of Patras.

nodes.title: Eurymenai
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 D1 Eurymenai

nodes.title: Eutresis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 E4 Eutresis

nodes.title: Gla
nodes.description: A large Bronze Age fortification of the Mycenaean civilization, Gla dates ca. 1300 B.C.

nodes.title: Glisas
nodes.description: Glisas was an ancient town of Boeotia located northeast of Thebes. Glisas is included in the Homeric catalogue of ships.

nodes.title: Gomphoi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B2 Gomphoi

nodes.title: Haliartos

nodes.title: Helleniko
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 F2 Helleniko

nodes.title: Hestiaiotis
nodes.description: Hestiaiotis was a region of northwestern Thessaly and a part of the Thessalian tetrarchy. It roughly corresponds to the modern Trikala regional unit.

nodes.title: Homolion
nodes.description: Homolion or Homolium was a polis of ancient Magnesia located in ancient Thessaly. Homolion was situated at the foot of Mount Homole near the edge of the vale of Tempe.

nodes.title: (Hypo)Chalkis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B4 (Hypo)Chalkis

nodes.title: Iolkos
nodes.description: Iolkos was an ancient city located in Magnesia, Thessaly, Greece.

nodes.title: Kallipolis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 C3 Kallipolis

nodes.title: Kasthaneia
nodes.description: A settlement in Thessaly mentioned by Herodotus, Kasthaneia is most likely at the site of modern Keramidi.

nodes.title: Kephissos (river)

nodes.title: Larisa Kremaste/Pelasgia
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Achaea Phthiotis, located in the area of the modern town of Pelasgia in Greece.

nodes.title: Larissa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 C1 Larissa

nodes.title: Lefkandi
nodes.description: A coastal village on the island of Euboea known especially for rich Bronze Age and Iron Age material.

nodes.title: Lelant(i)on Pedion
nodes.description: A plain on the island of Euboea located between Chalcis and Eretria.

nodes.title: Leuktra
nodes.description: Leuktra was a settlement located in ancient Boeotia. It was located along the road leading from Thespiae to Plataea, somewhere in the vicinity of the modern town. In 371 B.C. the Thebans defeated the Spartans in a celebrated battle near the site.

nodes.title: Lidorikion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 C3 Lidorikion

nodes.title: Lilaia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 D3 Lilaia

nodes.title: Magnesia (region)
nodes.description: A coastal region of Thessaly, including the long, narrow peninsula stretching into the Aegean on the southeast. Magnesia gives its name to the modern Greek regional unit.

nodes.title: Makra Kome
nodes.description: An ancient settlement and fortification in the upper Spercheios river valley, located near modern Varibopi in Greece.

nodes.title: Maliacus Sinus
nodes.description: Maliacus Sinus (Malian Gulf) is a gulf of the Aegean Sea in eastern central Greece. The gulf is located in the region of Phthiotis.

nodes.title: Mauragani

nodes.title: Methone (Magnesian)

nodes.title: Metropolis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B2 Metropolis

nodes.title: Molykreion?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B4 Molykreion?

nodes.title: Naupactus
nodes.description: Originally a city of the Ozolian Locrians, Naupactus eventually fell to Athens; under Macedonian rule Philip II ceded it to the Aetolians.

nodes.title: Nea Pleuron
nodes.description: Second site of the ancient Greek city of Pleuron, built after the destruction of the original location in the 3rd century BCE. This second site boasts significant excavated remains and is located on the southern slope of Mount Aracynthus near modern Kato Retsina.

nodes.title: Oichalia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B3 Oichalia

nodes.title: Olizon
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 E2 Olizon

nodes.title: Onchestos
nodes.description: Onchestos was located northwest of Thebes and was the site of an ancient cult of Poseidon. Prior to the Macedonian period the Boeotian confederacy met here.

nodes.title: Orchomenos/Orchomenus
nodes.description: The so-called "Boeotian Orchomenos", located in the vicinity of the Byzantine church of Panaghia Skripou. The longer, modern title is used to distinguish this settlement from another Greek site with the same ancient name located in Arcadia in the Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Ossa (mountain range)
nodes.description: A mountain range in central Greece (between Olympus and Pelion), important in Greek mythology. Several ancient cities and a shrine to the Muses were located on its western slopes.

nodes.title: Pagasaeus/Demetriacus Sinus
nodes.description: The Pagasetic Gulf.

nodes.title: Palaia Pleuron
nodes.description: Original location of the ancient city of Pleuron, which was reportedly destroyed in the 3rd century BCE. There is debate concerning its location. After the destruction, a new site was selected for the city. It is known as "Nea Pleuron" (q.v.).

nodes.title: Panormos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 F2 Panormos

nodes.title: Parnassus M.
nodes.description: A mountain of central Greece located north of the Gulf of Corinth. In Greek mythology Parnassus was sacred to Apollo and was the home of the Muses.

nodes.title: Pelasgiotis

nodes.title: Sciathus (island)

nodes.title: Thermopylae
nodes.description: Thermopylae is the name of a narrow pass leading from Thessaly into Locris. It was the site of a pivotal battle during the Graeco-Persian wars in 480 BC.

nodes.title: Thisbe
nodes.description: Thisbe was an ancient town of Boeotia located on the southern flank of Mt. Helicon.

nodes.title: Trikka

nodes.title: Xyniai

nodes.title: Xynias L.

nodes.title: Aeolis
nodes.description: Sometimes defined as covering the entrance of the Hellespont to the mouth of the Hermus river, Aeolis was region centered on the North West coast of Asia Minor and some islands, notably Lesbos. Herodotus lists the eleven ancient cities of Aeolis as Cyme, Lerisae, Neon Teichos, Temnos, Cilla, Notion, Aegiroessa, Pitane, Aegaeae, Myrina, and Gryneia. He also claims that Smyrna was once an Aeolian city, but was taken by the Ionians at an unspecified date.

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 B5 Elinta

nodes.title: Emporio
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C5 Emporio

nodes.title: Erythrai
nodes.description: Erythrai was one of the twelve Ionian cities of Asia Minor. It is located on a small peninsula that extends into the Bay of Erythrae.

nodes.title: Garbias
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Garbias

nodes.title: Gargara
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 D2 Gargara

nodes.title: Gentinos?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C2 Gentinos?

nodes.title: Gergis
nodes.description: A city of the Troad in the territory of Lampsacus that Strabo describes as being "rich in vines".

nodes.title: Gergitha?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 F3 Gergitha?

nodes.title: Gryneion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 E4 Gryneion

nodes.title: Gyges
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 F4 Gyges

nodes.title: Crypta Balbi
nodes.description: The Crypta Balbi, mentioned by name only in the Regionary Catalogues, most likely refers to a vaulted passageway built in the Campus Martius by the proconsul Lucius Cornelius Balbus in 15 BC, who also dedicated a theater there in the same year.

nodes.title: Ianus Quadrifons
nodes.description: A quadrifrons triumphal arch at Rome that is located at a crossroads in the area of the Velabrum and the Forum Boarium. It dates to the early fourth century AD; its construction employed spolia and it likely honored either Constantine I or Constantius II.

nodes.title: Roman theater of Aspendos
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Aspendos dates ca. AD 155 and is perhaps the best preserved example of a Roman theater building.

nodes.title: Hippodrome of Constantinople
nodes.description: The Hippodrome was the great racetrack of the city of Constantinople and was connected to the no longer extant imperial palace. At about 450 m in length, the Hippodrome once accommodated about 100,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Agios Elias Doric temple
nodes.description: The Doric temple at Agios Elias, above Asea in Arcadia, dates to ca. 500 B.C.

nodes.title: Torre Astura
nodes.description: A Medieval coastal fort of the Frangipani.

nodes.title: Barcombe Hill Roman Quarry
nodes.description: Two quarry faces to the southwest of the summit of Barcombe Hill, near Vindolanda. Findspot of RIB 3373.

nodes.title: Coombe Crag Roman Quarry
nodes.description: Evidence of Roman quarrying activity was discovered at Coombe Crag, a site some 350 meters south of the line of Hadrian's Wall. The quarry was used as a source of building materials for the Wall and at least eight inscriptions were identified on the sandstone cliff.

nodes.title: Arco Etrusco
nodes.description: The so-called "Arco Etrusco" is one of the gates of ancient Perusia. The gate dates originally from the third century B.C. when it was one of seven gates in the Etruscan wall. In 40 B.C. it was refashioned under Augustus.

nodes.title: Porta Eburnea
nodes.description: The so-called Porta Eburnea or the Arco della Mandorla is an ancient gate of the Etruscan walls of Perusia.

nodes.title: Shadwell Roman Bathhouse
nodes.description: A second to fourth century A.D. Romano-British bathhouse that was excavated in 2002. Findspot of RIB 3012.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 B4 unnamed bridge (Eupatoria, over Iris)

nodes.title: Chabak(t)a
nodes.description: An unlocated place in Pontus that was the site of a mint.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 unlocated Metropolis

nodes.title: Philyreis Ins.
nodes.description: An ancient island or island group, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

nodes.title: Akampsis (river)
nodes.description: Akampsis fl. (Çoruh River)

nodes.title: Amaseia
nodes.description: Amaseia (modern Amasya) was a naturally fortified settlement in the Pontic mountains near the Black Sea. It served as the capital of the kingdom of Pontus from ca. 300 BC to 183 BC.

nodes.title: Comana Pontica/Hierocaesarea
nodes.description: An ancient city of Pontus.

nodes.title: Halys (river)
nodes.description: The Kızılırmak river, the ancient Halys River, is a major river of Asia Minor that flows into the Black Sea.

nodes.title: Iris (river)
nodes.description: Iris fl. (Yeşilırmak River) is a river of Asia Minor that flows into the Black Sea.

nodes.title: Korax? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 F1 Korax? fl.

nodes.title: Lykos (river)
nodes.description: Lykos fl. (Kelkit River or Kelkit Çayı)

nodes.title: Via Aurelia
nodes.description: An ancient Roman road begun ca. 241 B.C. by the censor C. Aurelius Cotta.

nodes.title: Aswan Quarry Landscape
nodes.description: Quarry region around the town of Aswan in Upper Egypt.

nodes.title: Ness of Brodgar
nodes.description: Ness of Brodgar is an archaeological site near Loch of Harray, Orkney. The site covers 2.5 hectares.

nodes.title: Standing Stones of Stenness
nodes.description: The Standing Stones of Stenness is a Neolithic monument on the mainland of Orkney, Scotland, generally dated to the third millennium BC.

nodes.title: Barnhouse Settlement
nodes.description: The Barnhouse Settlement is a Neolithic village of approximately 15 houses located adjacent to the Loch of Harray, Orkney Mainland, Scotland.

nodes.title: Vapheio Tholos Tomb
nodes.description: The Vapheio Tholos Tomb is a Mycenaean tholos built around 1500 BC that is assumed to have held an elite burial or burials. It is best known for the two golden Minoan-style cups it housed.

nodes.title: Guglia di Marcello
nodes.description: The so-called "Guglia di Marcello" or "Aguglia d'Agosta" is a Roman funerary monument located along the ancient via Pompei that once connected Syracuse and Messina. It dates to the period from the first century B.C. to the first century A.D.

nodes.title: Roman Theater of Baelo
nodes.description: A Roman theater in Baelo that dates to the reign of Claudius.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater of Col. Tarraco
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater in Tarragona built in the first century A.D. The structure was renovated under Elagabalus.

nodes.title: Maison Carrée
nodes.description: A well preserved Roman temple built ca. 16 B.C. and dedicated to Caius and Lucius Caesar.

nodes.title: Piercebridge Roman Bridge
nodes.description: A Roman bridge that carried Dere Street across the River Tees in northern England.

nodes.title: Pons Probi
nodes.description: The Pons Probi across the Tiber is attested in the Notitia and, according to Platner and Ashby, was likely built under Emperor Probus in the third century AD.

nodes.title: Mausoleum of Romulus
nodes.description: Tomb of Valerius Romulus (ca. AD 292/295 – 309), son of Maxentius, along the Via Appia.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Cuccuru Ibba
nodes.description: A pre-nuragic village of the Ozieri culture and later nuraghe located in the Laguna di Santa Gilla.
