nodes.description: A milecastle situated on Hadrian's Wall.

nodes.title: Milecastle 65 (Tarraby)
nodes.description: A milecastle situated on Hadrian's Wall.

nodes.title: Mortuary Temple of Merenptah
nodes.description: Mortuary temple of the Nineteenth Dynasty in the Theban Necropolis.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Nuracale
nodes.description: A quadrilobate nuragic complex located in the territory of Scano di Montiferro.

nodes.title: Bath city walls
nodes.description: The circuit walls of Aquae Sulis, enclosing an area of some 23 ha, began in the Roman period and were later reinforced in the Anglo-Saxon and Medieval periods. Various remains are visible at points along the original circuit.

nodes.title: Casa della statuetta indiana
nodes.description: The so-called "Casa della statuetta indiana" (I.8.5) lies on the Via dell'Abbondanza. Excavated between 1930 and 1935, it was named for the fine ivory statuette (thought by some to depict Lakshmi) found inside. The house has a slightly irregular floor plan with some rooms added to the structure from adjacent properties.

nodes.title: Taberna Pomaria di Felix
nodes.description: A fruit shop in Pompeii (I, 8, 1) with an entrance on to the Via dell'Abbondanza.

nodes.title: Pistrinum of Betitius Placidus
nodes.description: A small shop located in Regio I of Pompeii (I, 8, 7).

nodes.title: Pont de Bornègre
nodes.description: A Roman aqueduct bridge connected to the Roman aqueduct of Nîmes.

nodes.title: Ezida
nodes.description: The temple of the god Marduk as Tutu, later of the god Nabû, at Borsippa. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ezida means "True House."

nodes.title: Eniggidrukalamasuma
nodes.description: The temple of the god Nabû of the ḫarû as at Borsippa. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eniggidrukalamasuma means "House which Bestows the Scepter of the Land."

nodes.title: Ekišnugal
nodes.description: The temple of the moon god Nanna/Suen/Sîn at Ur from the third to first millennium B.C. Over the course of its long history, it was rebuilt (and expanded) numerous times. A few of its more famous builders were Narām-Sîn of Agade, Ur-Nammu of Ur, and Nebuchadnezzar II of Babylon.

nodes.title: Eanna
nodes.description: The temple of the god Anu and the goddess Ištar at Uruk. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eanna means "House of Heaven."

nodes.title: City walls of Sabucina
nodes.description: The fortification walls of the Classical city.

nodes.title: Roman baths of Coriovallum
nodes.description: The site of Coriovallum is known for its well-preserved bath complex. These baths were first built ca. A.D. 40 and then re-built during the reign of Hadrian. They remained in use until the fourth century.

nodes.title: Villa del Pastore
nodes.description: A large villa at Stabiae covering more than 17,000 square meters.

nodes.title: Villa del fondo Ippolito Zurlo
nodes.description: A Roman villa located in the contrada Giuliana at Boscoreale on a side street of via Grotta II. The site was excavated by Vincenzo De Prisco in 1897 and subsequently reinterred.

nodes.title: Villa of Asellius
nodes.description: A Roman villa excavated at Boscoreale in 1903 and 1904 under the supervision of Vincenzo De Prisco and located on the property of one Giuseppe De Martino. Wall paintings and artifacts were recovered from the site and it was subsequently reinterred. Records as to its precise location are less than optimal.

nodes.title: Jensberg Celtic oppidum
nodes.description: Site of the Celtic wall protecting the oppidum from south-west.

nodes.title: Temple complex
nodes.description: A Gallo-Roman sanctuary with an enclosed precinct that was linked to the oppidum.

nodes.title: Moab
nodes.description: A mountainous strip of land in Jordan that was also the location of the kingdom of Moab, with its capital at Dibon.

nodes.title: Spolverino, Alberese
nodes.description: An archaeological site of the Roman period connected with the fluvial harbor of Rusellae.

nodes.title: Diyālā
nodes.description: A place from the TAVO Index

nodes.title: Torre del Papito
nodes.description: A Medieval tower in Rome's Largo Argentina.

nodes.title: Casa dei Crescenzi
nodes.description: A structure in Rome built between 1040 and 1065 by one Niccolò, son of Crescenzio and Teodora, in order to control the Ponte Emilio, on whose transit the family charged a toll. The building incorporates ancient spolia.

nodes.title: Tumulo di Montecalvario
nodes.description: An Etruscan tomb located at Castellina in Chianti in Italy.

nodes.title: Chassenon Roman amphitheater
nodes.description: Remains of a Roman amphitheater at Chassenon.

nodes.title: Caesareum of Alexandria
nodes.description: Hellenistic temple constructed by Cleopatra VII and dedicated to Julius Caesar, and later rededicated by Augustus to himself. In 13 BCE Augustus relocated two obelisks from Heliopolis to the site. The temple was converted to a Christian church in the mid-4th century.

nodes.title: Portus Cosanus
nodes.description: The harbor of the Latin colonial city of Cosa in south Etruria.

nodes.title: Villa della Colonne
nodes.description: A late Republican and early Imperial villa in the ager Cosanus noted for its turreted enclosure wall.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 E3 unnamed unlabeled ((15 monuments))

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1-C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Flaminia (20))

nodes.title: Ponte Spiano
nodes.description: The so-called Ponte Spiano is a Roman bridge located along the Via Flaminia in the modern comune of Sigillo.

nodes.title: Ponte Grosso
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1-C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Flaminia (20))

nodes.title: Ponte Manlio
nodes.description: The Roman bridge known as "Ponte Manlio" carried the Via Flaminia across the Bosso torrent, whose main channel is now some hundreds of meters to the south. This is a well-preserved Roman vaulted arch bridge that dates to the second century B.C.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1-C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Flaminia (20))

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1-C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Flaminia (20))

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1-C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Flaminia (20))

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1-C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Flaminia (20))

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1-C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Flaminia (20))

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1-C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Flaminia (20))

nodes.title: Ponte del Toro
nodes.description: A Roman arched bridge on the Via Flaminia near modern Terni.

nodes.title: Ponte di Augusto
nodes.description: A Roman arched bridge located near Narni built originally in the Augustan period that remained in use until A.D. 1055.

nodes.title: Ponte Calamone
nodes.description: A Roman bridge near Narnia that was built over the river Nera ca. 27 B.C.

nodes.title: Ponte Fonnaia
nodes.description: The Roman bridge at Ponte Fonnaia carried a branch of the Via Flaminia over the river Naia. It is located north of modern Acquasparta in Umbria.

nodes.title: Ponte di San Giovanni de Butris
nodes.description: The remains of a Roman bridge along the Via Flaminia that have been incorporated into the thirteenth-century church of San Giovanni de Butris.

nodes.title: Villa Marittima della Tagliata
nodes.description: A maritime villa of the first century A.D. adjacent to the port of Cosa.

nodes.title: Cima tumulus
nodes.description: A rock-cut Etruscan tomb dating to the second half of the seventh century B.C.

nodes.title: Tumulo del tesoro
nodes.description: An Etruscan tumulus of the seventh century B.C.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Uchi Maius
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater located at Uchi Maius (modern Henchir ed-Douâmis).

nodes.title: Temple of Zeus at Nemea
nodes.description: A partially reconstructed Doric temple, dating to the 4th century BCE.

nodes.title: Asklepieion of Messene
nodes.description: The Asklepieion in Ancient Messene is a sanctuary of Asklepios, the Greek god of healing, constructed in 214 BC. The complex includes civic as well as sacred buildings

nodes.title: Cencelle
nodes.description: A Medieval settlement that, according to textual sources, was founded in 854 by Pope Leo IV in order to provide a more secure position for the citizens of Centumcellae (Civitavecchia). Situated along the ancient VIa Aurelia, Cencelle occupies a defensible hill positioned between the Melledra and Mignone rivers. The site chosen for the Medieval city likely occupies the former site of an Etruscan oppidum.

nodes.title: Torre del Pascolaro
nodes.description: The ruins of a Medieval tower in South Etruria.

nodes.title: Temple of Vesta at Tibur
nodes.description: The Temple of Vesta in Tivoli dates to the early first century B.C. It was once situated on the acropolis of the ancient city. Its ruins now lie within the grounds of the Villa Gregoriana.

nodes.title: Anfiteatro di Bleso
nodes.description: The "Anfiteatro di Bleso" is a second century A.D. Roman amphitheater at Tibur (modern Tivoli in Italy).

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Thibiuca
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater located at ancient Thibiuca (modern Henchir Bou Cha).

nodes.title: Basilica of Santa Pudenziana
nodes.description: A palaeo-Christian church dedicated to St. Pudentiana located in Rome and, perhaps, the earliest site of Christian worship in the city. The church is located along the Via Urbana, which follows the course of the ancient vicus Patricius.

nodes.title: Clelia Roman Villa
nodes.description: A Late Roman villa and necropolis located at modern Imola in Italy.

nodes.title: Munychia
nodes.description: A hill in the Piraeus and the site of extensive fortifications in the Classical and Hellenistic periods.

nodes.title: The Athenaeum of Hadrian (Rome)
nodes.description: The Athenaeum of Hadrian was located in regio VII near the Capitoline Hill in Rome. Founded by the Emperor Hadrian, it was designated for the promotion of literary and scientific studies and named after the city of Athens. Excavations connected to the Metro C line revealed a complex in the vicinity of the modern Piazza Venezia that has been identified as the site of the Athenaeum.

nodes.title: Alişar Höyük
nodes.description: A settlement with occupation from the Chalcolithic period (fourth millennium B.C.) until the Phrygian period (first millennium B.C.).

nodes.title: Via Popilia (in Aemilia)
nodes.description: A road from Ariminum up the Adriatic Coast toward what is now Venice.

nodes.title: tribus Sergia
nodes.description: An older rural tribe of ancient Rome.

nodes.title: Eumachia Building
nodes.description: Located on the east side of Pompeii's forum (VII, 9, 1), the so-called Eumachia building is a large, public building financed by Eumachia, a public priestess of Venus in Pompeii during the middle of the first century AD.

nodes.title: Ekklesiasterion at Poseidonia/Paestum
nodes.description: The seat of the popular assembly of Poseidonia/Paestum, the Ekklesiasterion was built ca. 480-470 B.C. and could accommodate, at most, 1,700 persons. The structure retained its function after the Lucanian conquest but was abandoned, buried, and built over after the Roman conquest.

nodes.title: "Basilica" of San Vitale
nodes.description: A church (but not a basilica) in Ravenna, Italy, established by Bishop Ecclesius in 526 AD and consecrated ca. 547 AD.

nodes.title: Roman Theater of Minturnae
nodes.description: A theater constructed in Minturnae under Augustus or Tiberius, and further embellished under Hadrian.

nodes.title: Es Trepucó
nodes.description: Es Trepucó, Minorca, is the site of a Talaiotic village that dates from 1500 to 1300 BC.

nodes.title: Litana Silva
nodes.description: The Litana Silva was a forest located in Gallia Cispadana in the territory of the Boii. It was the site of the defeat of the Roman consul L. Postumius Albinus in 216 BC. Its precise location is uncertain, but it probably lay somewhere in the flat land south of the Po river in Italy.

nodes.title: Santuario nuragico di Santa Vittoria
nodes.description: A nuragic site near Serri, Sardinia, with a later phase of Christian re-use.

nodes.title: House of the Gilded Cupids
nodes.description: A Roman domus that once belonged to Cn. Poppaeus Habitus (VI 16,7).

nodes.title: Temple of Asclepius
nodes.description: The Temple of Asclepius (VIII, 7, 25) in Pompeii is located at the intersection of the Via del Tempio di Iside and the Via Stabiana. It is also referred to as the Temple of Jupiter Meilichius.

nodes.title: Ourima/Antiochia ad Euphratem/Arulis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 F2 Ourima/Antiochia ad Euphratem/Arulis

nodes.title: Pagrae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 C4 Pagrae

nodes.title: Pordonnium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 G1 Pordonnium

nodes.title: Pyramos (river)
nodes.description: The modern Ceyhan river in southern Turkey. Its modern mouth is well to the east of its ancient location, which was to the west of Magarsa and much inland from the modern coast.

nodes.title: Samosata
nodes.description: An ancient city located on the West bank of the Euphrates river, established perhaps as early as the Hittite period. Its ruins, known in modern times as Samsat (Turkey), were submerged following the construction of the Atatürk Dam in the early 1990s. The modern village of Samsat was relocated and is not coincident with the ancient site.

nodes.title: Seleukeia epi tou Zeugmatos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 G2 Seleukeia epi tou Zeugmatos

nodes.title: Zeugma
nodes.description: An ancient settlement whose site is located in the Gaziantep province of modern Turkey, at the modern village of Belkis (a.k.a. Kavunlu). The majority of the ancient remains were covered by water in the year 2000, due to the construction of the Birecik Dam.

nodes.title: Zeus Madbachos, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 D4 Zeus Madbachos, T.

nodes.title: Onchae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 unlocated Onchae

nodes.title: Basilica di Santa Balbina all'Aventino
nodes.description: The basilica of Santa Balbina is a paleo-Christian basilica in Rome, located on the "little Aventine".

nodes.title: Domus Cilonis
nodes.description: The house of Lucius Fabius Cilo, praefectus urbi in 203, consul in 193 and 204, and a close friend of the emperor Septimius Severus. The house was a gift of the Severans and appears on the Severan marble plan. Its site is now occupied by the basilica of Santa Balbina on the "little Aventine".

nodes.title: Caelius Mons
nodes.description: The Caelian Hill in Rome.

nodes.title: Domus Aurea
nodes.description: A sprawling palace complex begun by Nero after A.D. 64 that aimed to connect the Esquiline, Caelian, and Palatine hills.

nodes.title: Tor de' Schiavi
nodes.description: The Tor de' Schiavi is a medieval tower (thirteenth century) built atop the remains of the octagonal hall of the Villa Gordiani.

nodes.title: Kerlescan alignments
nodes.description: A complex of 555 megaliths arranged in 13 rows.

nodes.title: Crucuno stone rectangle
nodes.description: A rectangle of 21 menhirs ranging in height from 0.91 m to 2.4 m.

nodes.title: Ka'ba-ye Zartosht
nodes.description: A stone monument located in the Naqsh-e Rustam compound.

nodes.title: Temple of Mater Matuta at Satricum
nodes.description: A sanctuary dedicated to Mater Matuta that was in use between the seventh and fifth centuries B.C.

nodes.title: Post-Archaic necropolis at Poggio dei Cavallari
nodes.description: A necropolis located along a road that once led to the Mater Matuta sanctuary composed of approximately 50 tombs.

nodes.title: Belverde Necropoli della Cavetta
nodes.description: The Cavetta necropolis at Pantalica includes tombs and rock-cut houses of the prehistoric and later periods.

nodes.title: Kral Kaya Mezarları
nodes.description: Elite Hellenistic rock-cut tombs of the Pontic kingdom.

nodes.title: Altar at the temple of Amphiaraos
nodes.description: An altar located to the east of the temple of Amphiaraos.

nodes.title: Theater at Thorikos
nodes.description: The largely preserved classical theater at Thorikos is dated ca. 525-480 B.C.

nodes.title: La Granède, Millau
nodes.description: An oppidum located on the headland of the Larzac, overlooking the valley of the Tarn river.

nodes.title: Esiskur
nodes.description: The New Year's (Akītu) temple of the god Marduk outside Babylon. The Sumerian ceremonial name Esiskur means "House of the Sacrifice."

nodes.title: Enunmah
nodes.description: The ḫilṣu-building of the goddess Ningal inside the Egišnugal temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Enunmah means "House of the Exalted Prince."

nodes.title: Ekarzagina
nodes.description: The temple of the god Ea within the Esagil(a) complex at Babylon. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ekarzagina means "Pure Quay"or "Quay of Lapis Lazuli."

nodes.title: Ehulhul
nodes.description: The temple of the god Sîn at Harran. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ehulhul means "House which Gives Joy."

nodes.title: Egipar
nodes.description: The Giparu-House at Ur was the temple of the high-priestess of the moon-god.

nodes.title: Ebabbar
nodes.description: The temple of the god Šamaš at Larsa. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ebabbar means "Shining House."

nodes.title: Eamaškuga
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Ningal at Kissik. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eamaškuga means "House, Pure Sheepfold."

nodes.title: Monterfil II at Corseul
nodes.description: Remains of the commercial quarter of the Gallo-Roman settlement.

nodes.title: Stoa in the sanctuary of Zeus Lykaios
nodes.description: A 62 m long stoa, probably of the fourth century BC.

nodes.title: Grave Circle A at Mycenae
nodes.description: Grave Circle A encloses a royal cemetery within the walls of the citadel of Mycenae; inside it are six shaft graves constructed around 1600 BC.

nodes.title: Amphithéâtre Gallo-Romain
nodes.description: The ruins of the Roman amphitheater Saint-André-sur-Cailly are located in the hamlet of Bout Levé.

nodes.title: Acropolis of Eretria
nodes.description: The Acropolis of Eretria became the site of the settlement during the Middle Helladic period.

nodes.title: Temple of Apollo Daphnephoros
nodes.description: The Temple of Apollo Daphnephoros at Eretria dates originally to the late archaic period.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Amman/Philadelpheia
nodes.description: A second century Roman theater at Amman that could seat 6,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Sacred Way at Iuppiter Latiaris, T.
nodes.description: The sacred processional street on Monte Cavo.

nodes.title: "Ponte Sanguinario" at Spoletium
nodes.description: The "Ponte Sanguinario" at Spoleto is a late republican to early imperial Roman bridge. The remains of the bridge are now below street level in the Piazza della Vittoria, not far from the Porta San Gregorio.

nodes.title: Industrial area at Sexi/Saxetanum
nodes.description: Extensive archaeological evidence of the fish processing industry is evident at Sexi/Saxetanum.

nodes.title: Temple of Apollo at Hierapolis
nodes.description: The Temple of Apollo at Hierapolis, built during the Hellenistic period.

nodes.title: Thermes de Cluny
nodes.description: A Gallo-Roman bath complex of the third century CE at Lutetia (modern Paris).

nodes.title: Mine on Euboea
nodes.description: One of a group of mines on Euboea Ins.

nodes.title: Pimentel, Necropoli di S'Acqua Salida e di Corongiu
nodes.description: A necropolis of the second millennium B.C.

nodes.title: Noddule nuragic complex
nodes.description: A multi-period settlement site with occupation stretching from ca. 4000 B.C. to the fourth century A.D.

nodes.title: House of the Red Walls
nodes.description: A domus excavated in 1832 and 1882. It is noted for its late-stage wall decoations that may call upon public monuments for inspiration.

nodes.title: House of Marcus Lucretius
nodes.description: The House of Marcus Lucretius was excavated in 1846 and 1851.

nodes.title: Khorsabad Gate 5
nodes.description: This undecorated gate is the southernmost city gate of the southwest wall of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

nodes.title: Khorsabad Gate 6
nodes.description: This decorated gate is the northernmost city gate of the southwest wall of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

nodes.title: Khorsabad Gate 7
nodes.description: This undecorated gate is the southernmost city gate of the northwest wall of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

nodes.title: Khorsabad Citadel Gate A
nodes.description: This decorated gate is located on the western wall of the citadel of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

nodes.title: Mullissu Gate
nodes.description: The Mullissu Gate, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Mullissu-muddišat-ḫiṣbi ("The Goddess Mullissu Is the One Who Restores Abundance"), is the fourth of the eight city gates of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") listed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) in inscriptions recording the construction of his new capital. This gate is the second of the north-facing entrances to the city.

nodes.title: Anu Gate
nodes.description: The Anu Gate, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Anu-mušallim-epšēt-qātīya ("The God Anu Is the One Who Makes My Undertakings Successful"), is the fifth of the eight city gates of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") listed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) in inscriptions recording the construction of his new capital. This gate is the first of the west-facing entrances to the city.

nodes.title: Ea temple (Khorsabad)
nodes.description: As part of the palatial complex of Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad), the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) constructed six temples, including one to the god Ea.

nodes.title: tribus Aemilia
nodes.description: The tribus Aemilia is counted among the twenty-one oldest rural tribes of Rome. Its location is uncertain.

nodes.title: tribus Aniensis
nodes.description: The tribus Aniensis was one of the later rural tribes of Rome and was organised in 299 B.C.

nodes.title: Thermopolium of Vetutius Placidus
nodes.description: The house and thermopolium of Vetutius Placidus (I,8,8) opens directly onto the south side of the Via dell'Abbondanza.

nodes.title: Claudia
nodes.description: A Roman rural tribe that was one of the most ancient of Rome's gentes. The gens Claudia traced its history to the earliest days of the Roman Republic. Appius Claudius Sabinus Regillensis, in 495 B.C., was the first of its members to hold the consulship.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Col. Augusta Raurica
nodes.description: The theater at Augusta Raurica is one of the best preserved Roman theaters north of the Alps.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Malaca
nodes.description: The remains of the first century B.C. Roman theater are located adjacent to the Alcazaba of Málaga. The theater is not completely excavated, although epigraphic data places it in the Augustan period. Its abandonment came in the third century.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Isis at Dion
nodes.description: The sanctuary of Isis at Dion dates to the second century A.D.

nodes.title: Theater at Telmessos
nodes.description: The ancient Theater at Telmessos with 1,500 seats dates to the latter days of the Pergamene empire.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Helvia Ricina
nodes.description: Helvia Ricina flourished under Augustus and Tiberius and its theater is the largest in Picenum.

nodes.title: Mausoleum of Lucius Pomponius Grecinus
nodes.description: A Roman funerary monument of the first century B.C. that is traditionally associated with the prefect Lucius Pomponius Grecinus.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Antium
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Antium is most likely built in the second half of the first century.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Cales
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Cales dates to the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Roman Forum at Thugga
nodes.description: The Roman Forum at Thugga is large, covering more than 900 square meters.

nodes.title: Roman theater
nodes.description: The theater at Thugga dates to 168 or 169 and could accommodate 3500 spectators.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Carthage
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Carthage was built around the middle of the second century A.D. It was re-discovered in 1904.

nodes.title: Odéon at Carthage
nodes.description: The theater and odéon of Roman Carthage stood in the northeast of the city, some three blocks from the cardo maximus.

nodes.title: Carthage military harbor
nodes.description: The cothon at Carthage was divided into a rectangular merchant harbor and an inner protected harbor reserved for military use.

nodes.title: Ancient theater of Kourion
nodes.description: The Ancient theater of Kourion was first built in the second century B.C. It remained in use until the fourth century.

nodes.title: Theater of Miletus
nodes.description: The Theater of Miletus was built in four phases between ca. 300 and ca. 133 B.C.

nodes.title: Casa di Properzio
nodes.description: The so-called "Casa di Properzio" at Assisi is a Roman domus located near the southern curtain of the ancient city walls. The decorations date the house to the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Helorus
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Sicily that was likely a colonial foundation of Syracuse.

nodes.title: Helorus (river)
nodes.description: Helorus fl. (Tellaro), a river of southeast Sicily.

nodes.title: (H)Enna
nodes.description: The origins of (H)Enna are unclear. Some sources claim it was founded by Syracuse in 664 B.C. but the archaeological record suggests it is likely a Hellenized Sikel settlement.

nodes.title: Heraclea Minoa
nodes.description: An ancient Greek city of the south coast of Sicily located at the mouth of the Halykos river. Founded by Selinus in the sixth century BC, the site was abandoned in the first century AD.

nodes.title: Heraia M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Heraia M.

nodes.title: Herbessos?
nodes.description: Herbessos was a town of the Siculi (the modern Montagna di Marzo near Piazza Armerina, Sicily).

nodes.title: Hereum/Cymbe
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F5 Hereum/Cymbe

nodes.title: Hexapyla
nodes.description: A sanctuary located north of Syracuse.

nodes.title: Hiera (Hephaistou) (island)
nodes.description: One of the Aeolian Islands utilized in antiquity mostly for its natural resources. Ancient Romans exploited resources including wood, alum, and sulfur.

nodes.title: Hiera/Maritima (island)
nodes.description: The second largest of the Aegadian Islands, Marettimo in Sicily.

nodes.title: Himera
nodes.description: A colony on the north shore of Sicily founded in 649/8 BC by the Myletidai.

nodes.title: Himeras (river)
nodes.description: Himeras fl. (modern Grande or Imera Settentrionale) is a river of Sicily that flows into the Tyrrhenian Sea.

nodes.title: Himeras (river)
nodes.description: Himeras fl. (modern Salso or Imera Meridionale) is a river of Sicily. Two ancient rivers named Himeras cause some confusion, as one (modern Fiume Grande) flowed south to north emptying into the Tyrrhenian Sea while the other flowed north to south, emptying into the Gulf of Gela.

nodes.title: Hippana
nodes.description: Ancient settlement in the western part of Sicily, probably founded in the seventh century B.C.

nodes.title: Hybla Gereatis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F3 Hybla Gereatis

nodes.title: Hybla Heraia
nodes.description: Hybla Heraia (modern Ragusa) was an indigenous center of ancient Sicily that came into contact with Greek and, later, Roman and Byzantine cultures.

nodes.title: Hyblaei Colles
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F4 Hyblaei Colles

nodes.title: Hykkara?
nodes.description: A settlement of the Sicani on the northern coast of Sicily, conquered by the Athenians in 415 BC.

nodes.title: Hypsas (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Hypsas fl.

nodes.title: Ietas
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Ietas

nodes.title: Imachara?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E3 Imachara?

nodes.title: Inykon?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 B2 Inykon?

nodes.title: Iurato
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E5 Iurato

nodes.title: Kakyron?
nodes.description: A fortified city, north of Licata, located on the western side of Sicily that was founded by the Sicani in the eighth century B.C.

nodes.title: Kale Akte
nodes.description: Kale Akte was the site of a Sikel center that received an Ionian colony. The precise location of the ancient settlement is unknown, although it is placed in the area of Marina di Caronia.

nodes.title: Kaprianon?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C4 Kaprianon?

nodes.title: Kasmenai
nodes.description: Kasmenai was founded as a colony of Syracuse in 643 B.C.

nodes.title: Katane/Catina
nodes.description: The colonial city of Katane (modern Catania) was founded by Chalcidian Greeks sometime after the foundation of Leontini in 730 B.C.

nodes.title: Lakkios
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G4 Lakkios

nodes.title: Leontini
nodes.description: A Greek colonial city founded by Naxians in 729 B.C., Leontini was reduced by Hippocrates of Gela in 498 B.C. Following the Sicilian Expedition, the city became subject to Syracuse. In Roman times it may have been of little importance and was destroyed by the Saracens in A.D. 848.

nodes.title: Letojanni
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G3 Letojanni

nodes.title: Lilybaeum
nodes.description: Lilybaeum (modern Marsala) is located at the extreme westernmost point of Sicily. Lilybaeum was a Punic settlement that was conquered by the Romans in 241 B.C.

nodes.title: Lilybaeum Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 A3 Lilybaeum Pr.

nodes.title: Lipara (settlement)
nodes.description: A Greek colony and long-time settlement on the island of the same name, located to the north of Sicily in the Tyrrhenian Sea. Modern Lipari.

nodes.title: Lipara (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Tyrrhenian Sea, north of Sicily. Modern Isola Lipari.

nodes.title: *Logariana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F4 *Logariana

nodes.title: Longane
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G2 Longane

nodes.title: Longaricum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Longaricum

nodes.title: Lykos (river)
nodes.description: The ancient Lykos river is now considered as three separately named courses: the Grande, the Delia, and the Arena.

nodes.title: Maestro
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F5 Maestro

nodes.title: Makron Akron
nodes.description: A promontory/peninsula on the eastern end of Sicily.

nodes.title: Maktorion?

nodes.title: Mazara
nodes.description: An ancient settlement located on the western coast of Sicily.

nodes.title: Megara Hyblaia
nodes.description: Megara Hyblaia was an ancient Greek colony in eastern Sicily founded in the eighth century B.C.

nodes.title: Melita
nodes.description: A capital town founded by Carthaginians.

nodes.title: Melita/Malta (island)
nodes.description: The island of Malta, located in the Mediterranean Sea between Sicily and Libya.

nodes.title: Menai
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F4 Menai

nodes.title: Monte Castello di S. Angelo Muxaro
nodes.description: At Monte Castello di S. Angelo Muxaro are remains of a Sikan center (ninth to fifth centuries B.C.).

nodes.title: Monte Gibel Gabel
nodes.description: An archaeological site located ca. 5 km south of Caltanissetta, Sicily, situated on a 615-meter high mountain plateau. Excavations during the twentieth century under Dinu Adameșteanu revealed evidence for the Bronze Age Castelluccio culture, with indigenous occupation continuing until at least the sixth century B.C.

nodes.title: Monte Grande
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Monte Grande

nodes.title: Monte Lavanca Nera
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Monte Lavanca Nera

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Monte Manganello

nodes.title: Monte Maranfusa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Monte Maranfusa

nodes.title: Monte Navone
nodes.description: Monte Navone rises 754 m above sea level in Sicily's Enna province. Archaeological remains of a settlement pre-dating Greek colonisation were discovered on the summit that have been correlated with the Sikel site of Hybla Erea.

nodes.title: Monte Pecoraro
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C2 Monte Pecoraro

nodes.title: Monte Pietroso di Camporeale
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Monte Pietroso di Camporeale

nodes.title: Monte Polizzo
nodes.description: An ancient hilltop settlement of Sicily dated ca. ninth to fourth centuries B.C.

nodes.title: Monte Scurzi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F2 Monte Scurzi

nodes.title: Monte Turcisi
nodes.description: Monte Turcisi is the site of Greek fortifications located in the province of Catania, Sicily. This military outpost was likely of Syracusan dependence.

nodes.title: Montelungo
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Montelungo

nodes.title: Montevago
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Montevago

nodes.title: Montevergine di S. Anna
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Montevergine di S. Anna

nodes.title: Morgantina
nodes.description: An indigenous Sicilian site founded by the Morgeti, according to Strabo, Morgantina was eventually defeated by Syracuse and thus, in turn, passed into Roman hegemony in the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Motya
nodes.description: A small island in the Stagnone Lagoon of western Sicily, Motya has evidence for quite ancient settlement, including a significant Punic phase. The settlement on the island was destroyed by Syracuse in 379 BC. At one point the island was connected to the mainland via a causeway.

nodes.title: Motyon?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Motyon?

nodes.title: Mura Pregne
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D3 Mura Pregne

nodes.title: Muratore di Castellana Sicula
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E3 Muratore di Castellana Sicula

nodes.title: Mutyce
nodes.description: Ancient settlement on the southern side of the Hyblean Mountains, between Syracuse and Camarina.

nodes.title: Mylae
nodes.description: An ancient Greek settlement on the north-east coast of Sicily, located at the base of a peninsula that juts into the Tyrrhenian Sea. A colony of Zancle, it was probably founded in the eighth or seventh century BC. In 260 BC, during the First Punic War, the Romans won their first major naval battle against the Carthaginians in the waters off Mylae.

nodes.title: Myttistraton
nodes.description: An ancient Greek city in the central part of Sicily, near modern Marianopoli, known for its fortifications.

nodes.title: Narasette
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Narasette

nodes.title: Naulochos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G2 Naulochos

nodes.title: Naustathmus Portus?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G5 Naustathmus Portus?

nodes.title: Naxos (settlement)
nodes.description: Naxos was the earliest Greek settlement in Sicily, according to Thucydides who places its foundation in 734 BC.

nodes.title: Neaition/Netum
nodes.description: Neaition/Netum was an ancient town in Sicily that likely became subject to Syracuse after 263 B.C.

nodes.title: Nebrodes M.
nodes.description: Nebrodes M. are a major mountain range on the island of Sicily.

nodes.title: Noai?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F3 Noai?

nodes.title: Oanis (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F5 Oanis fl.

nodes.title: Omphake?
nodes.description: Omphake? was an ancient Sikanian center that came into conflict with the Greek colony of Gela.

nodes.title: Ortomosaico di Giarratana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F4 Ortomosaico di Giarratana

nodes.title: Ortygia (island)
nodes.description: A coastal island of Sicily that became the center of ancient Syracuse.

nodes.title: Pagliuzza
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D3 Pagliuzza

nodes.title: Palikoi/Palicorum Stagna
nodes.description: A pair of boiling lakes in Sicily, whose effervescence was attributed to the divine agency of the Palikoi.

nodes.title: Pan(h)ormus
nodes.description: First founded in 734 BC by the Phoenicians as Ziz, Pan(h)ormus (modern Palermo) was an important ancient city of the Greek, Roman, and Arabic civilizations.

nodes.title: Pantalica
nodes.description: Archaeological area near Sortino, in Sicily, famous for its large rocky necropolis. The place was occupied from the 13th century BC to the Byzantine period. Formerly identified with the ancient settlement of Herbessos, it is now more often associated with Hybla Gereatis.

nodes.title: Parthenicum
nodes.description: Ancient settlement on the north-west side of Sicily, thought to be in the area of modern Partinico, near Palermo.

nodes.title: Patti Marina
nodes.description: A third century A.D. Roman villa near Messina in Sicily that was perhaps the center of an ancient latifundium.

nodes.title: Pelorus/Regium (promontory)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 H2 Pelorus/Regium Pr.

nodes.title: Phalarion?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Phalarion?

nodes.title: Philosophiana
nodes.description: An ancient settlement not far from Piazza Armerina, in the municipality of Mazzarino. Archaeological finds suggest it was inhabited from the early Roman Imperial period to the third century A.D., when it was abandoned. The site was then re-occupied during the Middle Ages.

nodes.title: Phintias
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Phintias

nodes.title: Phoenicusa (island)
nodes.description: One of the Aeolian Islands, Phoenicusa shows evidence for Bronze Age occupation, as well as activity during the Greek and Roman periods.

nodes.title: Phorbantia (island)
nodes.description: Phorbantia Ins. (modern Levanzo) is the smallest of the Aegates Inss.

nodes.title: Piano dei Casazzi
nodes.description: A small, fortified hilltop with evidence of nearby Sikel tombs. The Greek fortifications have been speculatively attributed to Hippokrates of Gela (ca. 495 B.C.).

nodes.title: Piano della Città
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Piano della Città

nodes.title: Piano della Clesia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Piano della Clesia

nodes.title: Roman Villa and Medieval Settlement at Piazza Armerina
nodes.description: The so-called "Villa Romana del Casale" (of Roman date) and the nearby settlement of Piazza Armerina, which seems to have been occupied by survivors from the villa site after it was destroyed in an earthquake in the early middle ages. The villa is listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, in part because of its famous mosaics.

nodes.description: Ruins of a Roman-era villa/estate (ancient name unknown) at modern Burmarrad, Malta.

nodes.title: Sabucina
nodes.description: Sabucina was a major indigenous center in central Sicily that was wealthiest in the sixth and fifth centuries BC; it may have been connected with sulfur mining.

nodes.title: Saraceno di Favara
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Saraceno di Favara

nodes.title: Scicli
nodes.description: Scicli is the site of settlement beginning in the third millennium BC. The town of Scicli is believed to have been founded by Sicels ca. 300 BC.

nodes.title: Segesta/Egesta
nodes.description: A center of the Elymian people in northwestern Sicily.

nodes.title: Selinous/Lanaricus (river)

nodes.title: Selinus
nodes.description: A Greek colonial city located on the southern coast of Sicily, Selinus was said to have been founded as a colony of the city of Megara Hyblaia.

nodes.title: Settefrati
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D2 Settefrati

nodes.title: Sicilia (island)
nodes.description: Sicily is the largest island in the Mediterranean Sea and has been the site of human habitation since ca. 8,000 BC. In historical terms Sicily has seen important settlement activity connected to numerous culture groups - Punic, Carthaginian, Greek, Roman, Vandalic, Ostrogothic, Byzantine, Arabic, and Norman.

nodes.title: Siculum Fretum
nodes.description: A strait separating the eastern tip of Sicily and the southern tip of Calabria in the south of Italy.

nodes.title: Syracusae/Syrakousai

nodes.title: Tauromenium

nodes.title: Timpone Rasta
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 B3 Timpone Rasta

nodes.title: Torre del Filosofo
nodes.description: The so-called "Torre del Filosofo" was a structure on Mt. Etna that may have been built by the Roman emperor Hadrian in honor of the Greek philosopher Empedocles as local legend held that he once climbed the mountain and died by falling into the volcano.

nodes.title: Traiectus

nodes.title: Triokala?
nodes.description: Ancient Triokala was a fortified site in western Sicily that was allied to Carthage during the second Punic War.

nodes.title: Trogilos

nodes.title: Kallipolis

nodes.title: Kamikos

nodes.title: Buduntini
nodes.description: Buduntini, the only freshwater lake in Sardinia.

nodes.title: Caput Tyrsi
nodes.description: A Roman-era road station located at modern Buddusò on the island of Sardinia, presumably associated with the source of the Thyrsos river.

nodes.title: Caralis
nodes.description: A city with its origins in a Phoenician settlement of the seventh century BC, Caralis comes under Roman control in 238 BC during the Punic Wars. Florus refers to it as urbs urbinum, or capital of Sardinia

nodes.title: Cornus

nodes.title: Corsi
nodes.description: The Corsi were an ancient tribe occupying a region of ancient Sardinia that is now known as Gallura.

nodes.title: Cuniculariae (islands)
nodes.description: The modern archipelago of Maddalena off northern Sardinia is comprised of seven main islands and numerous other small islets.

nodes.title: Hydata Hypsitana/Forum Traiani
nodes.description: Hydata Hypsitana/Forum Traiani (modern Fordongianus) was a Roman settlement in Sardinia along the road from Tibula to Othoca.

nodes.title: Hydata Lesitana
nodes.description: An ancient thermal site with both nuragic and Roman remains. Now the community of Benettuti on the island of Sardinia.

nodes.title: Iglesias
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 Iglesias

nodes.title: Ilienses
nodes.description: The Ilienses were an important people of the interior of Sardinia who were never subjugated to Roman authority.

nodes.title: Insani M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B2 Insani M.

nodes.title: Is Bangius
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 Is Bangius

nodes.title: *Kaidros (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B2 *Kaidros fl.

nodes.title: Rotunda of Galerius
nodes.description: A brick rotunda of the fourth century AD ordered by the emperor Galerius for use as either a tomb or temple; later incorporated into the Christian Church of Agios Georgios. Listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1988

nodes.title: Madonna del Parto
nodes.description: Madonna del Parto is a Christian church at Sutri, dating to the thirteenth and fourteenth centuries. The rock-cut sanctuary repurposes a Mithraeum dating to the first and second centuries.

nodes.title: Leonforte
nodes.description: A modern Sicilian town in the province of Enna, thought to be located in the area of the ancient settlement of Assorus.

nodes.title: Alu-eššu
nodes.description: An unlocated city/town in the kingdom of Suhu, probably not far from Baqa, Qaqqar-aradātu, and Ribaniš.

nodes.title: Yabi
nodes.description: An unlocated city/town in the kingdom of Suhu, probably not far from Hurzē (Korsote).

nodes.title: Yāduru
nodes.description: An unlocated city/town in the kingdom of Suhu that is located in the territory of the city Ukalāya.

nodes.title: Ešuzianna
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Anat at Anat (Anatho). The Sumerian ceremonial name Ešuzianna means "House, True Hand of Heaven."

nodes.title: Halatu
nodes.description: An unlocated well in the middle Euphrates region, near the city Ḫindānu.

nodes.title: Stadium at Laodicea ad Lycum
nodes.description: The ancient Stadium at Laodicea ad Lycum dates initially to the later first century A.D.

nodes.title: Krasnyĭ mai͡ak
nodes.description: Late Scythian burial site on the Lower Dnieper River containing burials dated to the 3rd century BCE-2nd century CE.

nodes.title: Tell 'Ali
nodes.description: A small site on the left bank of the Lower Zab where an archive of ca. twenty-five Middle Assyrian texts was discovered. The town was situated more or less where travellers from Aššur to the cities Nuzi and Arrapha would have crossed the Lower Zab. Tell 'Ali is identified with ancient Atmannu.

nodes.title: Tell Bazmusian
nodes.description: A site on the right bank of the Lower Zab that was excavated by Iraqi archaeologists in 1956–58. Tell Bazmusian, whose ancient name is not known, is one of the largest archaeological sites in the Ranya Plain (Sulaymaniyah Governorate, Iraq). The city was occupied from the sixth millennium BCE to the ninth century CE. A small group of Middle Assyrian tablets were discovered in a pit outside the city’s temple. Tell Bazmusian is now submerged under Lake Dukan.

nodes.title: North Palace at Deir el-Ballas
nodes.description: Royal palace in the Upper Nile in use from the Second Intermediate Palace to the early New Kingdom.

nodes.title: Ponte Sodo
nodes.description: A rock-cut tunnel (cuniculus) at the northwest margin of ancient Veii.

nodes.title: Dura-Europos synagogue
nodes.description: The Dura-Europos synagogue is one of the oldest known synagogues in the world. According to an Aramaic inscription, its final phase of construction took place in A.D. 244. It was uncovered during excavations in 1932.

nodes.title: Basilica of Thyrsos
nodes.description: A fifth or sixth century AD (Early Christian) triple-aisled basilica including mosaic floors.

nodes.title: Campo Valdés Roman Baths, Gijón
nodes.description: Roman baths dating from the first to fourth centuries.

nodes.title: Villa Carmiano
nodes.description: A villa rustica of about 400 square meters that was discovered at Stabiae in 1963. The site was reinterred in 1998.

nodes.title: Domus of the Lararium
nodes.description: The so-called "Domus of the Lararium" in Assisi was discovered at a depth of 7 meters beneath the Palazzo Giampè. The surviving remains are those of a well-appointed domus with floor mosaics and wall paintings. The domus, dating to the second half of the first century. B.C. and the first decades of the first century. A.D., was comprised of at least 13 rooms and a peristyle.

nodes.title: Sese Grande
nodes.description: The "Sese Grande" or "Sese del Re" is a prehistoric tomb on the island of Pantelleria. Sesi are megalithic tomb structures of the second millennium B.C. that are connected with the Sesiote culture.

nodes.title: Bruncu Campulongu Nuraghe
nodes.description: A nuragic site.

nodes.title: Is Calas
nodes.description: A nuragic complex located near Monte Nai, Sardinia.

nodes.title: Trajanic harbor
nodes.description: The hexagonal Trajanic harbor basin at Portus was built between 100 and 112. Its maximum diameter is approximately 716 meters.

nodes.title: Küçük Ağrı Dağı
nodes.description: A peak of the Ararat massif, known as Little Ararat.

nodes.title: Porta all'Arco
nodes.description: The Porta all'Arco is a city gate of Volterra. Later incorporated into Medieval walls, the gate originates in the fourth and third centuries B.C.

nodes.title: Roman Odeion at Corinth
nodes.description: The Roman Odeion at Corinth dates to the first century A.D.

nodes.title: Macedonian palace at Pella
nodes.description: The Macedonian palace at Pella, now only partially excavated, occupied an area of perhaps 60,000 square meters. The palace consisted of up to seven large architectural groupings.

nodes.title: Necropolis at Archontiko
nodes.description: A cemetery used by Macedonians in the area of Pella from the Early Iron Age to the Early Hellenistic Period.

nodes.title: Acamantis
nodes.description: Acamantis, named for the hero Acamas, was an Attic tribe or phylai created by the reforms of Cleisthenes. It included the demes of Cholargos, Eiresidai, Hermos, Iphistiadai, Kerameis, Kephale, Poros, Thorikos, Eitea, Hagnous, Kikynna, Prospalta, and Sphettos.

nodes.title: Tomb Garden of Theodoros at Smyrna
nodes.description: A funerary garden attested in text carved on a marble block from the settlement of Smyrna

nodes.title: Rousolakos
nodes.description: A Minoan site in eastern Crete.

nodes.title: Bodhgaya
nodes.description: A town in India traditionally identified as the place in which Gautama Buddha attained enlightenment. One of the four main Buddhist pilgrimage sites, it is home to the Mahabodhi Temple, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

nodes.title: Hosios Loukas
nodes.description: A tenth century walled monastery in Boeotia, Greece.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Piscu
nodes.description: A multi-phase nuragic complex dating between 1400 and 1000 BC.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Santu Milanu
nodes.description: A single-tower nuraghe with a quadrilobate bastion.

nodes.title: Church of Sant'Urbano alla Caffarella
nodes.description: A tenth century church built on the site of a Roman structure that was either a temple or a tomb dating ca. AD 160.

nodes.title: Icknield Street
nodes.description: Icknield Street was a road of Roman Britain running from Fosse Way to Templeborough.

nodes.title: Metchley Fort
nodes.description: A Roman fort built in the area of modern Birmingham, England, soon after the Roman invasion of A.D. 43. The fort, about 200 square meters in area, was in use periodically until its abandonment ca. A.D. 120.

nodes.title: Basiluzzo
nodes.description: An islet that is part of the Aeolian Islands.

nodes.title: tribus Collina
nodes.description: An early urban tribe of the city of Rome, reportedly established by Servius Tullius.

nodes.title: Temple of Jupiter
nodes.description: The Temple of Jupiter (VII,8,1) in Pompeii sits at the north end of the forum. It was built in the middle of the second century BC.

nodes.title: Forum baths
nodes.description: A bath complex adjacent to Pompeii's forum that was built after 80 BC (Reg VII, Ins 5, 2, 5, 7, 24). The baths are publicly financed by the duovir Lucius Caesius and the aediles Caius Occius and Lucius Niraemius.

nodes.title: Clepsydra of the Oropos Amphiareion
nodes.description: The Oropos Amphiareion clepsydra is a hydraulic inflow clock serving the Sanctuary of Amphiaraus. Situated on the southeast bank of the sacred spring of Amphiaraus, this inflow hydraulic clock dates to the 4th century BCE.

nodes.title: Jandial Temple
nodes.description: Jandial is the site of a semi-Classical temple of Ionic Greek design constructed in the first or second centuries BCE. It is the farthest east of any known Hellenic temple.

nodes.title: Hellenistic Balaneion, Amathous
nodes.description: A circular public bath building dating to the Hellenistic period in the agora of Amathous.

nodes.title: Strata Diocletiana
nodes.description: A Roman road built in the third century AD under the emperor Diocletian that ran along the limes Arabicus of the eastern Roman empire.

nodes.title: Monumental complex of Sant'Ilario a Port' Aurea
nodes.description: An architectural complex associated with the nearby Longobard church of Sant'Ilario. The complex included a monastery and is built atop Roman Imperial remains.

nodes.title: Great Temple of Petra
nodes.description: The Great Temple of Petra is one of the major archaeological and architectural components of central Petra. It is located to the south of the Colonnaded Street and southeast of the Temenos Gate and covers 7560 square meters.

nodes.title: Temple of the Winged Lions
nodes.description: The Temple of the Winged Lions is a colonnaded temple built in Petra in order to honor the Arabian goddess al-Uzza.

nodes.title: Symbra
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 unlocated Symbra

nodes.title: Adana/Antiochia ad Sarum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 G3 Adana/Antiochia ad Sarum

nodes.title: Aleion Pedion
nodes.description: Aleion Pedion (the Aleian Plain) in Cilicia.

nodes.title: Mersin-Yumuktepe
nodes.description: A tell known today as "Yumuktepe" is located at modern Mersin in Turkey. Excavations there, beginning in the 20th century, have provided evidence for continuous and/or successive human settlement beginning in the Neolithic period. Scholars believe that the names "Ingirâ" (found in Akkadian sources) and "Anchiale(ia)" (found in Greco-Roman sources) are to be associated with the site.

nodes.title: Anemurium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 B4 Anemurium

nodes.title: Calycadnus (river)
nodes.description: The most important river of Cilicia Tracheia.

nodes.title: Charadros
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 B4 Charadros

nodes.title: Cilicia Pedias
nodes.description: A region of southern Asia Minor, "Flat Cilicia". This region is described as "well-watered" and fertile. It was bounded by the Taurus and Anti-Taurus Mountains and the Mediterranean Sea.

nodes.title: Cilicia Tracheia
nodes.description: A region known as "Rough Cilicia" in southern Asia Minor.

nodes.title: Cilicius Aulon
nodes.description: The sea passage between Anemurium and Cyprus.

nodes.title: Corycus
nodes.description: Corycus was an ancient city in Cilicia Trachaea.

nodes.title: Cybistra
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 E1 Cybistra

nodes.title: Cydnus (river)
nodes.description: A river of ancient Cilicia.

nodes.title: Dağpazarı
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 C3 Dağpazarı

nodes.title: Elaioussa/Sebaste
nodes.description: Elaioussa/Sebaste was an ancient Roman city in Asia Minor founded in the second century BC.

nodes.title: Hyde?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 D2 Hyde?

nodes.title: Iconium/Claudiconium
nodes.description: Iconium/Claudiconium (modern Konya) was an important city in Lycaonia that later became part of the Roman province of Galatia.

nodes.title: Kilikiai Pylai
nodes.description: The Cilician Gates, a pass through the Taurus Mountains connecting Cilicia to the Anatolian Plateau, by way of the gorge of the Gökoluk River.

nodes.title: Lauzadeai
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 B3 Lauzadeai

nodes.title: Mallos/Antiochia ad Pyramum
nodes.description: Mallos/Antiochia ad Pyramum was an ancient coastal city of Cilicia.

nodes.title: Platanistes
nodes.description: Strabo characterizes this stretch of rugged/rocky coastline (παράπλους τραχὺς) as lying between Charadros (modern Yakacık in Turkey) and Anamourion (Eski Anamur).

nodes.title: (P)Saros/Sinarus/Koiranos (river)
nodes.description: (P)Saros/Sinarus/Koiranos fl. (Seyhan River)

nodes.title: Regma/Rogmoi
nodes.description: Regma/Rogmoi (also Rhegma) is an ancient lake or lagoon formed by the Cydnus river in Cilicia, approximately 5 km from Tarsus.

nodes.title: Seleucia ad Calycadnum/Tracheia
nodes.description: A city founded by Seleucus Nicator between 296 and 280 BC.

nodes.title: Tarsus/Antiochia ad Cydnum
nodes.description: An important city and river port on the Cydnus river located in Cilicia Pedias.

nodes.title: Taurus (mountain range)
nodes.description: The Taurus Mountains in southern Turkey, the modern Toros Dağları.

nodes.title: Tyana/Col. Aurelia Antoniniana
nodes.description: An ancient city of Cappadocia that was the capital of the Neo-Hittite kingdom in the first millennium B.C.

nodes.title: Tynna/Dana?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 F1 Tynna/Dana?

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 F1 unnamed aqueduct (Tyana)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 G3 unnamed bridge (over (P)Saros fl. at Adana)

nodes.title: Kundu/Kyinda
nodes.description: Kundu is mentioned in Akkadian royal inscriptions of the seventh-century-BC Assyrian king Esarhaddon. In Classical times, Strabo describes Kyinda as a fortress where Macedonian kings deposited treasure. Eumenes reportedly captured the treasure when he revolted against Antigonus. The site is now unlocated.

nodes.title: Aigai(ai)/Aegeae
nodes.description: Aigai(ai)/Aegeae (modern Yumurtalık, Turkey) is an ancient city in Cilicia.

nodes.title: Alexandria ad Issum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 C3 Alexandria ad Issum

nodes.title: Amanikai Pylai/Ciliciae Portae
nodes.description: A pass through through the Taurus Mountains, the modern Karanlik Kapi.

nodes.title: Amanus (mountain range)
nodes.description: A mountain range located along the Cilician-Syrian border. Today known as the Nur Daǧları.

nodes.title: Amphipolis/Tourmeda/Nikatoris?
nodes.description: An ancient settlement in Syria on the Euphrates river. Its precise location is not known, although various suggestions have been made by modern scholars.

nodes.title: Anazarbos/Caesarea/Ioustin(ian)oupolis
nodes.description: Anazarbos or Anazarbus was an ancient city of Cilicia; its extensive multi-period archaeological remains are located adjacent to the modern village of Dilekkaya in the Kozan district of Turkey's Adana province. Anazarbos became the capital of Cilicia Secunda in the later Roman empire. The city was rebuilt in 527 following an earthquake and destroyed by Mamluk forces in 1374.

nodes.title: Antiochia/Theoupolis
nodes.description: A city founded ca. 300 BC by Seleucus I Nicator, a successor of Alexander the Great. Antioch was a great trading center and numbered as one of the four cities of the Syrian tetrapolis. Justinian I renamed the city 'Theoupolis' in the sixth century AD.

nodes.title: Arianodum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 F1 Arianodum

nodes.title: Beroia
nodes.description: The ancient city of Aleppo, located in modern Syria, where extensive elements of Hittite, Hellenistic, Roman, Byzantine, Ayyubid, and Umayyad architecture are incorporated into the urban fabric of the modern city. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1986.

nodes.title: Callicome
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 E4 Callicome

nodes.title: Carrhae
nodes.description: Carrhae is a major settlement of Upper Mesopotamia from the Bronze Age onward. The earliest mentions of the site are found in the Ebla tablets (ca. 2300 B.C.).

nodes.title: Cilca Novum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 E1 Cilca Novum

nodes.title: Cilicia
nodes.description: An ancient region, stretching along the southern coast of Asia Minor as far north as the Taurus mountains and westward from the Amanus mountains to the river Melas or, according to some ancient commentators, all the way to the coastal city of Korakesion (modern Alanya in Turkey)

nodes.title: Ciliza/Urmagiganti
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 E3 Ciliza/Urmagiganti

nodes.title: Commagene
nodes.description: Commagene was a region between the Euphrates river and the Taurus Mountains.

nodes.title: Cyrrus/Hagioupolis
nodes.description: Seleucid kings (either Seleucus I Nicator or Antiochus I Soter), likely founded Cyrrhus in the first half of the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Doliche
nodes.description: An ancient city of Asia Minor (modern Dülük in Turkey).

nodes.title: Europos
nodes.description: An ancient city that was part of the Mitanni, Hittite, and Neo-Assyrian Empires (Kargamiš in Hittite; commonly Carchemish). The site was occupied as early as the Neolithic and Chalcolithic periods; evidence for Early Bronze Age cist tombs begins ca. 2400 BC. It was a key commercial center during the time of Ebla and Mari. The Mitanni controlled the site from the sixteenth to the fourteenth centuries and was conquered by Šuppiluliuma ca. 1350 B.C. A famous battle, attested in the Bible, was fought at the site in 605 BC between the Babylonian army under Nebuchadnezzar II and that of the Egyptian Pharaoh Necho II.

nodes.title: Germanikeia
nodes.description: An ancient city located in the northern Syrian region of Commagene mentioned. Modern Maraş.

nodes.title: Hierapolis/Bambyke
nodes.description: Hierapolis/Bambyke was an ancient settlement of Commagene. The city was also a center for the worship of the Syrian goddess Atargatis.

nodes.title: Hydatos Potamoi/Seleukeia Pieria
nodes.description: The capital city of Seleucus I Nicator, established ca. 300 BC.

nodes.title: Imma
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 D4 Imma

nodes.title: Issicus Sinus
nodes.description: Issicus Sinus (the Gulf of İskenderun) is a gulf of the Levantine Sea.

nodes.title: Karmalas? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 B1 Karmalas? fl.

nodes.title: Koryphe Oros
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 D4 Koryphe Oros

nodes.title: Mopsou(h)estia/Seleukeia pros to Pyramo
nodes.description: Mopsou(h)estia/Seleukeia pros to Pyramo was an ancient settlement in Cilicia Pedias (now modern Yakapınar, Turkey).

nodes.title: Nastae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 F1 Nastae

nodes.title: ‘Octacuscum’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 F1 ‘Octacuscum’

nodes.title: Orontes (river)
nodes.description: The Orontes River is one of the chief rivers of the Levant.

nodes.title: London Mithraeum
nodes.description: A temple sacred to Mithras in Londinium that was discovered in 1954. The visible remains of the temple do not sit on the original site, but have been reassembled at Temple Court, Queen Victoria Street, London.

nodes.title: Casa dei Grifi
nodes.description: A late Republican domus of the Palatine Hill that was later consumed by the substructures of the Domitianic wing of the Flavian palace. The Casa dei Grifi preserves important wall paintings that are transitional from the First to the Second Pompeian style. Giacomo Boni discovered the domus in 1912.

nodes.title: Mnajdra Megalithic Temple (Malta)
nodes.description: Megalithic temple complex of the fourth millennium BC.

nodes.title: Picentino (river)
nodes.description: A river of Campania that is connected to the now-lost settlement of Picentia and the Picentinus Ager.

nodes.title: So-called Arch of Hadrian (Capua)
nodes.description: The remains of a triple arch in opus latericium marking the pomerium of Capua. It is perhaps originally constructed under the Flavians.

nodes.title: Catacombs of Domitilla
nodes.description: A Christian catacomb located on the via Ardeatina.

nodes.title: İşhan
nodes.description: A village in Turkey, the site of a late antique Georgian church constructed in the 7th century.

nodes.title: Walls of Timoleon
nodes.description: The Greek fortifications of Gela that are credited to Timoleon of Corinth.

nodes.title: Via Aemilia
nodes.description: The Via Aemilia was a major Roman trunk road of northern Italy and connected Placentia and Ariminum. Its construction began in 187 BC under M. Aemilius Lepidus.

nodes.title: Abbotsbury Castle
nodes.description: Abbotsbury Castle is an Iron Age hill fort located on Wears Hill in Dorset, England.

nodes.title: Incastro River
nodes.description: The Incastro is a river of Latium that drains the waters originating from the Lago di Nemi. Its ancient name is unknown.

nodes.title: Incheville
nodes.description: A Celtic hilltop settlement (oppidum).

nodes.title: Boviolles
nodes.description: Gallo-Roman hilltop settlement

nodes.title: Porta Asinaria
nodes.description: The Porta Asinaria is a gate of the Aurelian Walls on the Caelian Hill, located immediately southwest of the Porta S. Giovanni.

nodes.title: Majorca (island)
nodes.description: Majorca is the largest island in the Balearic Islands archipelago in the western Mediterranean Sea.

nodes.title: Ses Païsses
nodes.description: Ses Païsses was a Talaiotic settlement of the Bronze Age on the island of Majorca.

nodes.title: Circus Flaminius
nodes.description: Located in the southern Campus Martius, the Circus Flaminius is a large area built by C. Flaminius Nepos in 221 B.C. Various games, including the ludi plebeii, ludi Taurii, ludi saeculares, were celebrated here. The circus was also a place of popular assembly.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Arrubiu
nodes.description: A Middle Bronze Age nuragic site (ca. 1500 BC) near Cagliari, Sardinia.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Albucciu
nodes.description: A nuragic village dating ca. 1600 BC.

nodes.title: River Gelt Roman Quarry
nodes.description: A Roman quarry on the River Gelt near Brampton, Cumbria.

nodes.title: Gremanu
nodes.description: A 7-hectare nuragic settlement and sanctuary.

nodes.title: Tomb of T. Claudius Secundus
nodes.description: A Roman tomb along the Via Appia.

nodes.title: Valley of the Kings
nodes.description: A valley in Egypt where Pharaonic burials took place from the sixteenth to the eleventh centuries B.C. (Eighteenth to the Twentieth Dynasties).

nodes.title: So-called Theatre 2
nodes.description: The ruins of an ancient theatre in Cyrene, known as "Theatre 2".

nodes.title: Via Annia
nodes.description: The Via Annia was a Roman consular road in Cisalpine Gaul that connected (H)Atria to Aquileia. The praetor Titus Annius Rufus constructed the road in 131 BC.

nodes.title: Cuccuru Nuraxi
nodes.description: A nuragic site near Cagliari, Sardinia.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Vignamarina
nodes.description: A single-tower nuraghe with an associated village.

nodes.title: Lutibu
nodes.description: Lutibu is a fortified city in Sam'alla that is mentioned in royal inscriptions of the Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC). It is often identified with Sakçagözü (Coba Höyük), which is ca. 20 km northeast of Sam'al (Zincirli Höyük).

nodes.title: Ellibir
nodes.description: A fortress in the vicinity of Til-garimmu fortified by the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) against Kasku.

nodes.title: Šindarara
nodes.description: A fortress in the vicinity of Til-garimmu fortified by the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) against Kasku.

nodes.title: Uršu/Waršuwa
nodes.description: Uršu/Waršuwa was an Assyrian trading colony (kārum) located on the route between Aššur and Kaneš. This important city is attested in Eblaite and Sumerian sources, including an inscription of Gudea of Lagaš that describes the rebuilding of the temple of the god Ningirsu at Girsu; numerous Old Assyrian and Old Babylonian texts; and Hittite sources, for example, the annals of king Hattusili I, a literary composition generally referred to as ‘The Siege of Uršu,’ a treaty between the Hittite king and Sunassura of Kizzuwatna, and a land grant to a nobleman (Sahurunuwa).

nodes.title: Mausoleum of Lucius Sempronius Atratinus
nodes.description: A first-century B.C. circular funerary monument at Gaeta.

nodes.title: Perrotte Aqueduct tunnel, aqueduct of Nimes
nodes.description: The aqueduct tunnel known as the Tunnel de la Perrotte stretches for more than 60 meters.

nodes.title: Acquedotto Anio Novus Ponte S. Antonio
nodes.description: The Ponte S. Antonio carried the Anio Novus aqueduct.

nodes.title: Circus at Mirobriga
nodes.description: The Roman circus at Mirobriga has been dated to the third century.

nodes.title: Theater at Delphi
nodes.description: The theater at Delphi near the Temple of Apollo.

nodes.title: The Siphnian Treasury
nodes.description: Treasury building erected by the citizens of the island city of Siphnos at Delphi in the late Archaic period, famous for its caryatid columns.

nodes.title: Stadium of Delphi
nodes.description: The Stadium of Delphi was perhaps built in the later fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: Kom Wasit
nodes.description: Archaeological site in the province of Beheira in the Western Delta, inhabited from the Roman through the Early Islamic periods. Along with the nearby site Kom el-Ahmer, it has been identified as a possible location of Metelis, the capital of the Metelite Nome.

nodes.title: Pyramid of Pepi I at Saqqarah
nodes.description: One of the pyramids at Saqqarah in Egypt. Pepi I was a pharaoh of the Sixth Dynasty and reigned from ca. 2332–2287 B.C.

nodes.title: Torre d'en Galmés
nodes.description: Torre d'en Galmés was a Talaiotic settlement of Bronze Age Minorca and was established ca. 1400 BC.

nodes.title: Arkalochori cave
nodes.description: A Bronze Age cave sanctuary on Crete known for the votive deposits of Bronze Age weapons recovered by archaeology.

nodes.title: S. Maria a Vico
nodes.description: A town founded as Vicus Novanensis, later named simply Ad Novas, along the Via Appia.

nodes.title: Santeramo
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 E3 Santeramo

nodes.title: Silarus (river)
nodes.description: The Sele river.

nodes.title: Silvium
nodes.description: Silvium (modern Gravina in Puglia) was founded as a Greek colony. It was a town on the frontier of the Peucetii.

nodes.title: Stournoi/Austranum?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 G3 Stournoi/Austranum?

nodes.title: *Tamarus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 A2 *Tamarus fl.

nodes.title: Tanager (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 C4 Tanager fl.

nodes.title: Taras/Tarentum/Neptunia
nodes.description: A Greek colonial city founded in 706 B.C.

nodes.title: Termitito
nodes.description: An ancient city of Lucania.

nodes.title: Trimerus (island)
nodes.description: The largest of the Diomedeae Islands in the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Trivici Villa?
nodes.description: A settlement of Samnium, within the territory of the Hirpini, that lay close to the frontiers of Apulia. The site is described only by Horace in his famous trip to Brundisium.

nodes.title: Turenum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 D2 Turenum

nodes.title: Turris Caesaris
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 F3 Turris Caesaris

nodes.title: Uria
nodes.description: An ancient city of the Messapii.

nodes.title: Uzentum/Ouxenton
nodes.description: Uzentum/Ouxenton (Ugento) was an ancient city in the territory of the Salentini with both Messapic and Roman phases.

nodes.title: Valetium/Balesium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 H3 Valetium/Balesium

nodes.title: Venusia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 C3 Venusia

nodes.title: Veretum/Baris
nodes.description: Veretum/Baris was a town of Calabria, in the territory of the Sallentines.

nodes.title: Vescellium?
nodes.description: Vescellium was a settlement of the Hirpini.

nodes.title: Vibinum/Vibarna
nodes.description: Vibinum/Vibarna was an ancient settlement in Campania that opposed Rome during the Samnite Wars.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 F4 unnamed aqueduct (Tarentum from springs near Satyrion (aqua nymphalis))

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge
nodes.description: An ancient bridge, known as "Ponte Rotto", over the Calore Irpino river along the Via Appia between Beneventum and Aeclanum.

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge

nodes.description: Sublupatia was a statio on the Via Appia but is now unlocated.

nodes.title: Ursentini
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 unlocated Ursentini

nodes.title: Aprustum
nodes.description: Aprustum was an interior town of Bruttium.

nodes.title: Arocas (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 46 E4 Arocas fl.

nodes.title: Bruttii
nodes.description: An ancient Italic people of extreme southern Italy, the Bruttii inhabited an area that roughly corresponds to the modern Calabria.

nodes.title: Carcinus (river)
nodes.description: The Corace river empties into the Gulf of Squillace.

nodes.title: Caulonia
nodes.description: Caulonia was founded by Achaean colonists in the eighth and seventh centuries BC.

nodes.title: Cocynthum (promontory)
nodes.description: A promontory located between Caulonia and the sinus Scylacius.

nodes.title: Euonymus (island)
nodes.description: One of the Aeolian Islands with occupation evidence beginning ca. 1200 B.C.

nodes.title: Temple of Hera Lacinia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 46 F3 Hera, T.

nodes.title: Kaulonia
nodes.description: Kaulonia is an Achaean colony of Magna Graecia founded in the eighth or seventh century BC.

nodes.title: Lacinium (promontory)
nodes.description: The Capo Colonna, the ancient Promunturium Lacinium, is a cape of Calabria located near Crotone.

nodes.title: Leucopetra (cape)
nodes.description: Leucopetra Pr. (Punta di Pellaro) in Calabria is the extreme southwestern point of mainland Italy.

nodes.title: Lokroi Epizephyrioi
nodes.description: Locri is a town and comune in the province of Reggio Calabria, Calabria, in southern Italy. Epizephyrian Locris was founded ca. 680 BC near modern Capo Zefirio, by the Locrians, apparently under the Opuntii (East Locrians) from the city of Opus, but also including Ozolae (West Locrians) and Lacedaemonians.

nodes.title: Lucani
nodes.description: An ancient Oscan-speaking population of south Italy.

nodes.title: Melpes (river)
nodes.description: A river of Lucani that flows into the Tyrrhenian Sea.

nodes.title: Nerulum?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 46 C2 Nerulum?

nodes.title: Oenotri
nodes.description: An ancient Italic population occupying a portion of southwestern Italy from Poseidonia/Paestum to Calabria. Their name may derive from the Greek 'oinos' meaning wine.

nodes.title: Petelia
nodes.description: Petelia was an ancient city on the coast of Bruttium in southern Italy. Petelia remained allied to Rome during the Second Punic War.

nodes.title: Pyxous/Buxentum (settlement)
nodes.description: An ancient coastal settlement of south Italy, modern Policastro Bussentino.

nodes.title: Pyxous (river)
nodes.description: An ancient river of southern Italy, the modern Bussento.

nodes.title: Rhegion/Regium
nodes.description: A site with settlement origins in the Bronze and Iron ages, Rhegion was eventually colonized by Chalcis in either 730 or 743 BC.

nodes.title: Rouskiane
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 46 E2 Rouskiane

nodes.title: Scyllaceus Sinus
nodes.description: Scyllaceus Sinus (modern Gulf of Squillace) is an inlet of the Ionian Sea along the Calabrian coast of Italy.

nodes.title: Scylletium/Scolacium
nodes.description: Scylletium/Scolacium was an ancient settlement in Bruttium located on the Gulf of Squillace.

nodes.title: Siris
nodes.description: Siris was an ancient Greek colonial city of Magna Graecia situated at the mouth of the Siris (modern Sinni) river. The city was founded by Ionian Greeks between 690 and 660 BC.

nodes.title: Siris/Semnus (river)
nodes.description: The Siris/Semnus fl. (modern Sinni) is a river of south Italy flowing through the region of Basilicata.

nodes.title: Strongyle (island)
nodes.description: One of the eight Aeolian Islands, Strongyle Ins. is one of the three active volcanoes in Italy.

nodes.title: Sybaris/Thurii/Copia
nodes.description: Sybaris was an ancient city of Magna Graecia founded as an Achaean colony as early as 720 B.C. on a plain drained by both the Crati and Sybaris rivers.

nodes.title: Temesa/Tempsa
nodes.description: An ancient city located on the west coast of Bruttium, just north of the Gulf of Hipponium.

nodes.title: Traeis (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 46 E2 Traeis fl.

nodes.title: Velia/Elea
nodes.description: The ancient city of Elea / Velia was said to have been founded by Phocaean Greeks in the sixth century B.C. and then became an ally of Rome in the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Vibonensis Sinus
nodes.description: The Gulf of Saint Euphemia.

nodes.title: Untitled

nodes.title: Polites, T.
nodes.description: A heroon located near Temesa that, according to Strabo, was dedicated to Polites, one of the companions of Odysseus.

nodes.title: Semuncla
nodes.description: A road station during the Roman period, attested by the Antonine Itinerary. Its exact location is not known today, but may have been in the Upper Sinni Valley in southern Italy.

nodes.title: Taurianos Skopelos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 46 unlocated Taurianos Skopelos

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G3 Acium

nodes.title: Acrae
nodes.description: Akrai, an ancient city of Sicily, originated as a colony founded by Syracuse in 664 B.C., making it the first of the city's three colonial foundations.

nodes.title: Acrillae
nodes.description: A Greek colony founded in Sicily ca. 598 B.C., Acrillae was an important economic center. In 213 B.C. the Roman consul M. Claudius Marcellus fought an engagement against the Syracusans there.

nodes.title: Ad Fluvium Lanaricum

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 B3 Ad Olivam

nodes.title: Adranon?

nodes.title: Adranon
nodes.description: Adranon was a settlement founded ca. 400 B.C. on the western slopes of mount Aetna.

nodes.title: Aegates (islands)
nodes.description: The Egadi Islands, a small group of mountainous islands northwest of Sicily.

nodes.title: Aeoliae (islands)
nodes.description: A volcanic archipelago in the Tyrrhenian Sea composed of eight islands.

nodes.title: Aetna M.
nodes.description: An active stratovolcano on the east coast of Sicily (known today as Mount Etna).

nodes.title: Agathyrnum
nodes.description: An ancient city of Siceliote origin on the north coast of Sicily.

nodes.title: Agyrium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F3 Agyrium

nodes.title: Aigousa (island)
nodes.description: Aigousa Ins. - meaning 'goat island' - is an island west of Sicily that was the scene of a major naval engagement of the First Punic War.

nodes.title: Akragas/Agrigentum
nodes.description: An ancient city on the island of Sicily, now known as Agrigento. A UNESCO World Heritage Site.

nodes.description: The Roman theater at Petra.

nodes.title: Mithraeum at Segontium
nodes.description: A mithraeum was excavated at Segontium (modern Caernarfon) in 1959, ca. 137m from the east corner of the Roman auxiliary fort. The site was abandoned in the late fourth century A.D.

nodes.title: Temple of Hercules Victor
nodes.description: A monopteros in the Forum Boarium at Rome built in the late second century BC, perhaps by L. Mummius Achaicus.

nodes.title: Sacred Area of S. Omobono
nodes.description: An archaeological area in the Forum Boarium comprising an ancient ritual precinct with twin temples ranging in date from the Archaic period through the time of the Roman Empire. The Medieval church dedicated to S. Omobono stands atop the remains of one of the two ancient temples.

nodes.title: Oenoanda bridge
