nodes.description: An Ottoman bridge at Oinoanda on the Xanthos river. A Latin inscription found nearby suggests an earlier Roman bridge existed at the site.

nodes.title: Villa del Río Roman bridge
nodes.description: A Roman bridge along the Via Augusta.

nodes.title: Adad Gate
nodes.description: The Adad Gate is one of Babylon's eight city gates and it is situated on the western side of the inner city, directly west of the nu-x-ù quarter. King Nebuchadnezzar II built the gate ca. 575 B.C.

nodes.title: City Wall of Dura-Europos
nodes.description: The fortified wall encircling the city of Dura-Europos built primarily of locally-quarried ashlar limestone blocks. Built ca. 150 BCE, the walls were breached in 256 CE and went out of use thereafter.

nodes.title: Eastern Outer Wall of Babylon
nodes.description: The Neo-Babylonian ruler Nabopolassar (r. 625–605 BC) started planning and constructing an outer wall around the eastern side of Babylon. This massive mudbrick brick wall, together with its protective quay wall and a wide moat, remained unfinished at the time of Nabopolassar’s death. His son and successor Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC) finished the work started by his father. Traces of Babylon’s once-impressive eastern outer wall are still visible today.

nodes.title: Via Severiana
nodes.description: The Via Severiana was a coastal route running from Ostia to Terracina, a distance of ca. 80 Roman miles.

nodes.title: Mount Juktas
nodes.description: Mount Juktas is mountain of north-central Crete, noted for being the location of an important Minoan peak sanctuary.

nodes.title: Torre dei Capocci
nodes.description: The Torre dei Capocci, together with the Torre dei Graziani, was built in the twelfth century by the Arcioni family as a monumentalized entrance to the Esquiline.

nodes.title: Torre dei Graziani
nodes.description: The Torre dei Graziani is a twelfth-century tower on the Esquiline Hill in Rome.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Urbs Salvia
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Urbs Salvia.

nodes.title: Priniatikos Pyrgos
nodes.description: Priniatikos Pyrgos is located on a limestone headland jutting out into the southwest corner of the Gulf of Mirabello in East Crete. Ongoing survey and excavation in the vicinity is producing evidence of occupation from at least the Late Neolithic down through the Late Roman and Byzantine periods. Whatever ancient names may have been applied to these settlements are as yet unknown.

nodes.title: Tumulus MM
nodes.description: A funeral mound of the latter eighth century BC, possibly associated with the Phrygian king Gordias.

nodes.title: So-called House of the Mosaic Columns
nodes.description: Suburban villa outside the Herculaneum gate in Pompeii

nodes.title: Wittenham Clumps
nodes.description: Wittenham Clumps describes a group of small hills in the Thames Valley where archaeological remains of Iron Age hill forts have been identified.

nodes.title: Porticus Octaviae
nodes.description: A porticus in the area of the Circus Flaminius, the Porticus Octaviae was dedicated by Augustus sometime after 27 B.C. in honor of his sister, Octavia Minor. The porticus replaced the Porticus Metelli. It was restored twice after major urban fires in A.D. 80 and 203.

nodes.title: Ninurta-mukīn-temmēn-ālišu-ana-labār-ūmē-rūqūti
nodes.description: The Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) surrounded his new capital Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") with a rectangular-shaped, 16,280-cubit-long inner and outer city wall. The name of the outer/lower city wall (šalḫû) was Ninurta-mukīn-temmēn-ālišu-ana-labār-ūmē-rūqūti ("The God Ninurta Is the One Who Establishes the Foundation of His City for (All) Days to Come") according to some Akkadian royal inscriptions, but Ninurta-mukīn-temmēn-adušši-ana-labār-ūmē-rūqūti ("The God Ninurta Is the One Who Establishes the Foundation of the Wall for (All) Days to Come") according to other texts written in the name of Sargon II.

nodes.title: Adad Gate
nodes.description: The Adad Gate, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Adad-mukīn-ḫegallīya ("The God Adad Is the One Who Establishes My Prosperity"), is the second of the eight city gates of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") listed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) in inscriptions recording the construction of his new capital. This gate is the second of the eastward-facing entrances to the city.

nodes.title: Ištar Gate
nodes.description: The Ištar Gate, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Ištar-mušammeḫat-nišīšu ("The Goddess Ištar Is the One Who Makes Its People Flourish"), is the sixth of the eight city gates of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") listed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) in inscriptions recording the construction of his new capital. This gate is the second of the west-facing entrances to the city, but its precise location is uncertain.

nodes.title: Castellina del Marangone
nodes.description: A small fortified coastal settlement in Etruria occupied from the tenth century B.C. to the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Khorsabad Palace F
nodes.description: The armory (ekal māšarti) of Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad) was located in the lower city, adjacent to the southern stretch of the southwest wall. No inscriptions of the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) record the construction of "Palace F," although several objects of that ruler were discovered there.

nodes.title: Khorsabad Residence L
nodes.description: The residence of Sîn-aḫu-uṣur, brother of the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) and grand vizier of the Assyrian Empire, was constructed in the citadel of Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad), near the royal palace Egalgabarinutukua ("Palace That Has No Equal"). "Residence L" was largest of the four royal residences (J, K, L, and M) built in Dūr-Šarrukīn's citadel.

nodes.title: Khorsabad Residence K
nodes.description: The eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) had several royal residences constructed in the citadel of his new capital, Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad). Residence K, which has constructed on the western side of the citadel, is presumed to have been for one of the highest officials of the Assyrian Empire, possibly even Sargon’s heir designate Sennacherib.

nodes.title: Nabû temple (Khorsabad)
nodes.description: The eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) had a temple to the god Nabû, the god of scribes, built in the citadel of his new capital, Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad). Building H is the largest temple in Sargon’s newly-constructed city and it was built on a platform in the western side of the citadel, rather than on the palace terrace. The Nabû temple was connected to the temple district, which formed part of Sargon’s royal residence, by a stone bridge.

nodes.title: Sebetti temple (Khorsabad)
nodes.description: A temple dedicated to the Sebetti, the divine seven, was excavated by Iraqi archaeologists in 1957. This temple at Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad) is located just west of the citadel, near Citadel Gate A and City Gate 7.

nodes.title: Sîn temple (Khorsabad)
nodes.description: As part of the palatial complex of Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad), the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) constructed six temples, including one to the god Sîn.

nodes.title: Ninurta temple (Khorsabad)
nodes.description: As part of the palatial complex of Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad), the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) constructed six temples, including one to the god Ninurta.

nodes.title: Tomb of Senwosret III
nodes.description: The tomb of Senwosret III, a pharaoh of the 12th Dynasty in Egypt.

nodes.title: Church of Saint Demetrius
nodes.description: A seventh century AD church dedicated to the patron saint of Thessalonica; the present basilica stands on the site of a precursor with phases beginning in the fourth century AD.

nodes.title: Necropolis at Sutrium
nodes.description: Numerous rock-cut tombs are evident at Sutri, most dating from the Hellenistic period and later. In archaeological terms the tombs are poorly understood.

nodes.title: Castrum Rauracense
nodes.description: A Late Roman fortress located on the southern bank of the Rhine adjacent to Augusta Raurica.

nodes.title: Spring at Temple of Apollo
nodes.description: Across a small river from the temple

nodes.title: Villa del Cortijo de los Vila at Alameda
nodes.description: Roman villa at Alameda, located near the modern town cemetery. It is also known as the “Finca del Moral”.

nodes.title: Regio VIII, Pompeii
nodes.description: The so-called Regio VIII, an archaeological subdivision located in the southwestern section of Pompeii, contains a theatre, a sanctuary dedicated to Venus, and a mix of residential, administrative, and commercial structures.

nodes.title: Aegyptus (Roman imperial province)
nodes.description: The Roman province of Egypt (Aegyptus) was established in 30 BC after the defeat of Marcus Antonius and Cleopatra VII at the Battle of Actium.

nodes.title: Abu Gariya
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 78 D4 Abu Gariya

nodes.title: Mons Claudianus
nodes.description: A mountain (modern Jabal Faţīrah in the Egypt's eastern desert). Site of Roman-era mining and military activities.

nodes.title: Klaudianon
nodes.description: A Roman and Late-antique fort and quarry at Mons Claudianus (modern Jabal Faţīrah) and in the associated Deir Wadi Umm Hussein in Egypt's eastern desert. It is often referred to in scholarly literature and the press simply as "Mons Claudianus" because of its location. Excavations at the site are notable in part for the recovery of a large textual archive that details the operations and daily life of soldiers and workers at the site.

nodes.title: Aethusa (island)
nodes.description: One of the Pelagie Islands in the Mediterranean Sea, used as a naval base by the Romans during the Punic Wars.

nodes.title: Africa (region)
nodes.description: The region of modern North Africa to which the Romans referred as "Africa", effectively the majority of same with the exception of Egypt, later truncated to correspond to the Roman province of the same name.

nodes.title: Africum Mare
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 1 D3/F3 Africum Mare

nodes.title: Ain Labakha
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 79 D2 Ain Labakha

nodes.title: Balat
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 79 inset Balat

nodes.title: Bashendi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 79 inset Bashendi

nodes.title: el-Deir
nodes.description: el-Deir (also known as Deir el-Munīra) is the site of a Roman fort and necropolis in Egypt's Kharga Oasis.

nodes.title: Esotero (Oasis)
nodes.description: The modern Dakhla (Dakhleh) Oasis in Egypt's western desert.

nodes.title: Exotero (Oasis)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 79 D2 Exotero (Oasis)

nodes.title: Qasr al-Gib
nodes.description: A late Roman fort in Egypt's Kharga Oasis

nodes.title: Hibis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 79 D3 Hibis

nodes.title: Hindaw
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 79 inset Hindaw

nodes.title: Jmr-t
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, centered on the temple to Amun Nakht, located at modern Ain Birbiyeh/Birbibya, in Egypt's Dakhleh Oasis: BAtlas 79 inset Jmr-t

nodes.title: *Kalamon
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 79 inset *Kalamon

nodes.title: Kellis
nodes.description: Roman/late antique settlement, with substantial remains of public religious buildings, including a large temple, residential areas, tombs, and three churches.

nodes.title: Mothis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 79 inset Mothis

nodes.title: Oasis Magna/Thebaidos
nodes.description: Kharga: one of the large oases of Egypt’s Western Desert.

nodes.title: el-Qasr
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 79 inset el-Qasr

nodes.title: *Sioua
nodes.description: "Sioua" is the Greek reconstruction of an ancient toponym (found in Egyptian sources: S·t-wȝḥ) that encompassed some part of the western end of the Dakhla Oasis in Egypt (certainly the site now known as Deir al-Haggar was included, and possibly also Amheida).

nodes.title: Qasr al-Sumayra
nodes.description: A late Roman fort in Egypt's Kharga Oasis.

nodes.title: *Thenete/Ten(...)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 79 inset *Thenete/Ten(...)

nodes.title: Trimithis
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of at least Roman and Late Antique date, situated in the Dakleh Oasis at a site now called Amheida.

nodes.title: Umm al-Dabadib
nodes.description: A late-Roman fortified settlement in Egypt's Kharga Oasis.

nodes.title: Alpes (mountains)
nodes.description: The Alps are one of the great mountain ranges of Europe stretching some 1,200 km. (750 miles).

nodes.title: Abaton
nodes.description: An ancient site designated as the burial place of Osiris-Serapis.

nodes.title: Akathartos Kolpos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 80 inset Akathartos Kolpos

nodes.title: Apa Phoibammon, Mon.
nodes.description: The seventh century monastery of St. Phoibammon was built on the upper terrace of the temple of Hatshepsut at Deir el-Bahri.

nodes.title: Aphrodites Nesos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 80 G4 Aphrodites Nesos

nodes.title: Berenice/Berenike
nodes.description: An ancient port city on the west coast of the Red Sea in modern Egypt.

nodes.title: Cataracta Prima
nodes.description: The First Cataract of the Nile is located at Aswan.

nodes.title: Contra Apollonos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 80 B4 Contra Apollonos

nodes.title: Coptos
nodes.description: An ancient settlement on the Nile river (modern Quft/Qift in Egypt) that flourished from pre-dynastic times through late antiquity.

nodes.title: Diospolis Magna/Thebai
nodes.description: Diospolis Magna/Thebai was known in ancient Egypt as Waset, "City of the Sceptre". The site was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1979.

nodes.title: Eileithyiaspolis
nodes.description: Eileithyiaspolis is a city of Upper Egypt on the eastern bank of the Nile river. The site was occupied from the Neolithic period onwards. Its ancient name was most likely Nekheb.

nodes.title: Elephantine
nodes.description: A fortified settlement located just before the First Cataract of the Nile. During the Second Intermediate Period, Elephantine marked the southern border of Egypt.

nodes.title: Hermonthis
nodes.description: An important town of the Egyptian Middle Kingdom that was enlarged during the Eighteenth Dynasty.

nodes.title: Karnak
nodes.description: A large temple complex in Egypt, associated with the ancient site of Thebes and Luxor and inscribed together with them on the UNESCO World Heritage list.

nodes.title: Latopolis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 80 B3 Latopolis

nodes.title: Lepte Akra
nodes.description: Lepte Akra (Cape Banas, Egypt (رأس بناس))

nodes.title: Memnon Colossi
nodes.description: Two seated, colossal statues of the Pharaoh Amenhotep III at a site on the west bank of the Nile river.

nodes.title: Memnonia
nodes.description: An archaeological site in the Theban Hills on the West Bank of the Nile river opposite Luxor, Egypt. The location is best known for the Mortuary Temple of Ramesses III.

nodes.title: Myos Hormos?
nodes.description: Myos Hormos was a port on the Red Sea built by the Ptolemies in the third century BC.

nodes.title: Pathyris/Aphroditopolis (settlement)
nodes.description: Pathyris/Aphroditopolis is known especially for its necropolis where material ranges in date from the Predynastic Period to the Middle Kingdom. In the 160s BC Ptolemy VI Philometor established a military outpost at the site that was destroyed in the first century BC.

nodes.title: Syene
nodes.description: The ancient city of Swenett in Egypt, called Syene by the Greeks.

nodes.title: Ambos
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Abona (river)
nodes.description: The River Avon, Bristol.

nodes.title: ‘Abone’
nodes.description: ‘Abone’ or Abonae was a Roman port located on the Avon (Abona) river, now Sea Mill, Bristol, Great Britain.

nodes.title: Alauna?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 F2 Alauna?

nodes.title: Ancaster
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 G2 Ancaster

nodes.title: ‘A(n)dros’ Ins.
nodes.description: ‘A(n)dros’ Ins., referred to as Edrou Heremos by Ptolemy was perhaps originally a coastal island, but is now connected to the mainland by a narrow strip of land, thus forming a peninsula.

nodes.title: Aquae Sulis
nodes.description: An ancient Roman thermal spa and site of the Temple of Sulis Minerva.

nodes.title: Ariconium
nodes.description: A site in Roman Britain located some 20 km northwest of Gloucester along the road leading towards the Wye valley. Numismatic evidence suggests possible Roman military presence.

nodes.title: Atrebates
nodes.description: The Atrebates were a Belgic tribe of Gaul and Britain prior to the Roman conquest.

nodes.title: Bignor
nodes.description: A Roman-style courtyard villa located 9 miles northeast of Noviomagus Regentium (modern Chichester).

nodes.title: Bououinda (river)
nodes.description: The River Boyne follows a course of some 112 km from Trinity Well, Newberry Hall, near Carbury, County Kildare to the Irish Sea.

nodes.title: Bourton-on-the-Water
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 F3 Bourton-on-the-Water

nodes.title: Brading
nodes.description: At Brading on the Isle of Wight, the remains of a Roman winged corridor type villa, consisting of three blocks, were excavated between 1881 and 1900. The villa was occupied between the second and fourth centuries A.D. The villa is known for its mosaic pavements.

nodes.title: Bray
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 A1 Bray

nodes.title: Calleva
nodes.description: Calleva Atrebatum (known as Silchester Roman Town) was an Iron Age oppidum and Roman town in Britannia. It was the civitas capital of the Atrebates tribe.

nodes.title: Camerton
nodes.description: Site of a small Romano-British town.

nodes.title: Cantiaci
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 H3 Cantiaci

nodes.title: Chedworth
nodes.description: A large Roman-style villa in Britain, dating from the second to fourth centuries A.D.

nodes.title: Chesterton-on-Fosse
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 F2 Chesterton-on-Fosse

nodes.title: Col. Camulodunum
nodes.description: Col. Camulodunum (Colchester) was the pre-Roman capital of the Trinovantes; it received a Roman city after the annexation of Britannia.

nodes.title: Col. Lindum
nodes.description: An Pre-Roman Iron Age settlement of Britain that became the site of a Roman colony after A.D. 71; its full name was Domitiana Lindensium.

nodes.title: Condate
nodes.description: A settlement along Watling Street, roughly midway between Deva and Mamucium.

nodes.title: Corieltauvi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 F2 Corieltauvi

nodes.title: Cornovii
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 E2 Cornovii

nodes.title: Crococalana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 G1 Crococalana

nodes.title: Deceangli
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 D1 Deceangli

nodes.title: Demetai
nodes.description: An Iron Age Celtic people who inhabited modern Pembrokeshire and Carmarthenshire in south-west Wales.

nodes.title: Deva
nodes.description: Deva or Deva Victrix (modern Chester) was a legionary base in Britannia. It was originally founded by the Legio II Adiutrix in the AD 70s and completed by the Legio XX Valeria Victrix.

nodes.title: Dorchester-on-Thames
nodes.description: Dorchester-on-Thames was the site of a Roman vicus, although its name is no longer known.

nodes.title: Dorn
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 F2 Dorn

nodes.title: Drumanagh
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 A1 Drumanagh

nodes.title: Durno(no)varia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 E4 Durno(no)varia

nodes.title: Durobrivae
nodes.description: Roman town at present day Rochester, cited: BAtlas 8 H3 Durobrivae

nodes.title: Durocobrivis
nodes.description: Durocobrivis (Dunstable) was a Romano-British station along Watling Street.

nodes.title: Durocornovium
nodes.description: Durocornovium (Wanborough, Wiltshire) was a vicus on the Ermine Street.

nodes.title: Durotriges
nodes.description: The Durotriges were a Celtic tribe of pre-Roman Britain.

nodes.title: *Durovernum
nodes.description: Durovernum Cantiacorum, modern Canterbury, was the site of a pre-Roman oppidum and, then, post A.D. 43 of a Roman fort.

nodes.title: Engleton
nodes.description: The site of a Roman villa that was excavated in 1937.

nodes.title: Farningham
nodes.description: A concentration of no fewer than three villas, possibly forming a settlement, situated ca. 2.5 km NE of the substantial early villa at Lullingstone.

nodes.title: Gosbecks
nodes.description: The Gosbecks farm site is the location of a Romano-Celtic temple. The shrine measures 100 meters square and a pre-Roman enclosure lies within the later temenos. The pre-Roman site was likely sacred to the war-god Camulos. Camulos was later synchronized with the Roman god Mars, although evidence for the worship of Mercury was also discovered at the site.

nodes.title: Isca
nodes.description: Isca Dumnoniorum was a Roman site that was the likely base of Legio II Augusta.

nodes.title: Isca
nodes.description: Roman legionary fortress at present-day Caerleon. Base of Legio II Augusta from ca. A.D. 75-300. Also known as Isca Augusta and Isca Silurum.

nodes.title: Ischalis?
nodes.description: Ischalis? is mentioned by Ptolemy, but its precise location remains debated. One possible location is the 'Charterhouse Roman town' site, while another is at Gatcombe, Somerset.

nodes.title: Iska (river)
nodes.description: The River Exe flows into the English Channel at Lyme Bay.

nodes.title: Kanovium/Conovium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 D1 Kanovium/Conovium

nodes.title: Kantion Akron
nodes.description: Kantion Akron (South Foreland) is a chalk headland on the coast of southeast England.

nodes.title: Korinion/Cironium
nodes.description: Korinion/Cironium (also referred to as Corinium Dobunnorum) was the second largest town of Roman Britain.

nodes.title: Lactodorum
nodes.description: Lactodorum was a fortified Roman settlement along Watling Street covering an area of ca. 11.25 ha.

nodes.title: Lagentium
nodes.description: Roman Lagentium (modern Castleford) is the site of a series of forts, beginning with a Flavian fort that was later replaced by a second-century fort. The site of the fort was occupied from ca. A.D. 80 to 150 while the vicus remained occupied until the fourth century.

nodes.title: ‘Lavobrinta’?
nodes.description: ‘Lavobrinta’? was a Roman fort on the east bank of the Severn river.

nodes.title: *Letocetum
nodes.description: *Letocetum was an important military post near the junction of Watling Street and Icknield Street.

nodes.title: Lindinis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 E4 Lindinis

nodes.title: Londinium/Augusta
nodes.description: Roman London was established ca. A.D. 43.

nodes.title: Cataracta Secunda
nodes.description: The Second Cataract (or Great Cataract) was located in Nubia. It is now submerged under Lake Nasser.

nodes.title: Hierasykaminos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 81 C2 Hierasykaminos

nodes.title: Ikhmindi
nodes.description: A sixth century BC settlement on the Nile in Lower Nubia.

nodes.title: Premis
nodes.description: Qasr Ibrim is an archaeological site in Lower Nubia. The site has a long history of occupation stretching from the eighth century B.C. to 1813.

nodes.title: Pselchis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 81 C2 Pselchis

nodes.title: Tachompso
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 81 C2 Tachompso

nodes.title: Manduessedum
nodes.description: At Manduessedum are the remains of a Roman settlement dating from ca. A.D. 60 to the early fifth century. A first-century A.D. military camp dates ca. A.D. 70.

nodes.title: Margidunum
nodes.description: Margidunum was a large settlement along the Fosse Way that began as a Roman fort during the mid-first century A.D. and was abandoned ca. A.D. 70.

nodes.title: Roman Tomb at Mersea
nodes.description: A Roman barrow tomb on Mersea Island.

nodes.title: Mona (island)
nodes.description: Mona Ins. (Isle of Anglesey or Ynys Môn) is an island off the northwest coast of Wales.

nodes.title: *Moridunum
nodes.description: *Moridunum (Carmarthen) was the civitas capital of the Demetae in Roman Wales.

nodes.title: Newgrange
nodes.description: Newgrange is a prehistoric monument in County Meath, Ireland, built ca. 3200 BC.

nodes.title: Newport Roman Villa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 F4 Newport

nodes.title: Noviomagus
nodes.description: In Britannia, Noviomagus was the capital of the Regni. According to the Antonine Itinerary, Noviomagus was the first road station along the road from London to Durovernum.

nodes.title: Ouergionios Okeanos
nodes.description: The Celtic Sea is a region of the Atlantic Ocean off the south coast of Ireland.

nodes.title: Pennocrucium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 E2 Pennocrucium

nodes.title: *Petuaria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 G1 *Petuaria

nodes.title: Portus Dubris
nodes.description: Portus Dubris (modern Dover) was a key commercial site for trade across the English Channel and was a key site connected with the A.D. 43 Roman invasion of Britain.

nodes.title: Ratae
nodes.description: Ratae Corieltauvorum (modern Leicester) was a settlement in Britannia.

nodes.title: Reg(i)noi
nodes.description: The Reg(i)noi were a British Celtic kingdom and later a civitas of Britannia.

nodes.title: Rutupiae
nodes.description: The Roman fort at Rutupiae was erected at the location where the Claudian landings took place in A.D. 43.

nodes.title: Sabrina (river)
nodes.description: Sabrina fl. (River Severn) is the longest river in the United Kingdom.

nodes.title: Segontium
nodes.description: A Roman fort at present day Caernarvon. The first Roman fort was built under Agricola ca. A.D. 77 and the site was occupied by Romans until ca. 338.

nodes.title: Shepton Mallet
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 E3 Shepton Mallet

nodes.title: Silures
nodes.description: The Silures were a tribe of South Wales.

nodes.title: Spinis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 F3 Spinis

nodes.title: Tamesis (river)
nodes.description: The River Thames.

nodes.title: Tamion?
nodes.description: Tamion? (modern Cardiff, Wales). A series of Roman forts occupied the same site in Cardiff, located on a river terrace adjacent to the River Taff, and represent continuous occupation from the late 50s AD until the late fourth century.

nodes.title: Tara
nodes.description: Tara is an archaeological site comprising a number of ancient monuments. Tradition holds that the site was the seat of the High King of Ireland.

nodes.title: Templebrough
nodes.description: At Templebrough an archaeological sequence of three superimposed Roman forts and a vicus were discovered. The first fort dates ca. A.D. 43.

nodes.title: Trinobantes
nodes.description: The Trinobantes were a Celtic tribe of Pre-Roman Britain.

nodes.title: ‘Tripontio’
nodes.description: A fortified Roman town along the line of Watling Street.

nodes.title: Uxacona
nodes.description: A Roman site with evidence for a series of ditched enclosures of the first century.

nodes.title: Vagniacis
nodes.description: Vagniacis was a small Roman site of the first to fifth centuries with likely specialized religious functions. A series of five temples are situated within a temenos along the Watling Street at Springhead.

nodes.title: Vectis (island)
nodes.description: Vectis Ins. (the Isle of Wight)

nodes.title: Venonis
nodes.description: Venonis was a Roman site located at the intersection of Watling Street and Fosse Way in Britannia.

nodes.title: Venta
nodes.description: Venta was a Roman town in what is now Wales. Established ca. A.D. 75, Venta served as an administrative and mercantile center for the defeated Silures tribe.

nodes.title: ‘Vernemeto’
nodes.description: According to the Antonine Itinerary, ‘Vernemeto’ was located 13 Roman miles north of Ratae Coritanorum (Leicester) along the Fosse Way.

nodes.title: Verulamium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 G3 Verulamium

nodes.title: Viroconium
nodes.description: Viroconium was a large and prosperous city of Roman Britain.

nodes.title: Abounkis
nodes.description: A settlement of Aethiopia located between the Second Cataract and Syene on the left bank of the Nile river.

nodes.title: Pide
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 81 unlocated Pide

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct(s) at Dolaucothi, Wales
nodes.description: A group of Roman-era aqueducts (a "leat system" in regional parlance and the archaeological literature for the area), probably supplying the gold mining works at Dolaucothi.

nodes.title: Alana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 82 D3 Alana

nodes.title: Astaboras (river)
nodes.description: Astaboras fl. (Atbarah River) flows over 800 km from near Lake Tana to the Nile in northern Sudan. The Tekezé river is a tributary of the Atbarah.

nodes.title: Cataracta Quarta
nodes.description: The Fourth Cataract of the Nile is located in the Manasir Desert. Since 2008 it has been flooded by the Merowe Dam.

nodes.title: Cataracta Quinta
nodes.description: The Fifth Cataract of the Nile river is located near the confluence of the Nile and Atbarah Rivers.

nodes.title: Cataracta Tertia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 82 A2 Cataracta Tertia

nodes.title: Meroe
nodes.description: Meroë is an ancient city located on the east bank of the Nile river near Shendi, Sudan. The city was a center of the kingdom of Kush.

nodes.title: Napata
nodes.description: Napata was a Nubian city-state located on the west bank of the Nile River and founded in the fifteenth century B.C.

nodes.title: Bonchis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 82 unlocated Bonchis

nodes.title: Baclanaza
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 83 B3 Baclanaza

nodes.title: Egra/Meda'in Salih
nodes.description: An ancient settlement located in the Hejaz of modern Saudi Arabia.

nodes.title: Iathrippa
nodes.description: Iathrippa was an oasis settlement along the Incense Road. From the Roman period until the advent of Islam the site was the seat of influential Iudaeo-Arabian tribes. Iathrippa would become an important center of Islam. Muhammad fled here from Mecca in 622 and the site was renamed Al-Madīna. It remained a key center until 656. It is the site of Muhammad's grave and a place of Muslim pilgrimage.

nodes.title: Ap(p)enninus M.
nodes.description: The Apennine Mountains extend ca. 1,200 km (750 miles) along the length of peninsular Italy.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Unnamed route or road

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 I3 unnamed lighthouse group (Portus Dubris)

nodes.title: Gold Mines at Dolaucothi, Wales
nodes.description: Known now as the "Dolaucothi Gold Mines" or "Ogofau Gold Mine," this was a major gold mining and ore processing site in the Roman period.

nodes.title: Bata/Patous
nodes.description: Bata/Patous was an ancient Greek colony on the Black Sea.

nodes.title: Gorgippia/Sindikos Limen
nodes.description: Gorgippia/Sindikos Limen was a sixth century B.C. colony founded by Pontic Greeks on the site of Sinda.

nodes.title: Hypanis (river)
nodes.description: Hypanis fl. (modern Southern Bug River) flows into the Black Sea.

nodes.title: Maeotis
nodes.description: Maeotis, known in antiquity as a lake, is the modern Sea of Azov and is the shallowest of the world's seas.

nodes.title: Poritos (river)
nodes.description: The Mius River flows into the Sea of Azov.

nodes.title: Rhombites Elasson (river)
nodes.description: Rhombites Elasson fl. (Lesser Rhombites) is the modern Kirpili River.

nodes.title: Rhombites Megas (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 84 D2 Rhombites Megas fl.

nodes.title: Tanais
nodes.description: Tanais (located near modern Nedvigovska) was a city of the third century B.C. founded on the banks of the Tanais river by Bosporanian Greeks.

nodes.title: Tanais (river)
nodes.description: The modern Don River.

nodes.title: Torikos/Pagras Limen/Heptalou Limen
nodes.description: Torikos/Pagras Limen/Heptalou Limen (modern Gelendzhik) was a Greek trading outpost on the Black Sea known to the Romans as Pagrae.

nodes.title: Hertichei
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 84 unlocated Hertichei

nodes.title: Pollina
nodes.description: Modern town in Sicily, near Cefalù, that has been associated with the ancient settlement of Apollonia.

nodes.title: Tomb of the Winged Demons
nodes.description: The so-called Tomb of the Winged Demons (Sovana, Italy), a third-century BC Etruscan tomb located in the Poggio Felceto necropolis.

nodes.title: Roman baths at Gaujac
nodes.description: The Roman baths at Gaujac were begun ca. A.D. 20.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Albano Laziale
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Albano Laziale is generally dated to the mid-third century A.D.

nodes.title: Roman cistern
nodes.description: A large Roman cistern at Albano Laziale.

nodes.title: Lateran Basilica, Palace, and Castra Nova equitum singularium
nodes.description: Site of a basilica and palace from early Roman imperial times, as well as an military installation built by Septimius Severus for the Roman imperial cavalry bodyguard. Now the site of the Archbasilica of St. John Lateran (rebuilt in the 16th century): Complesso dei San Giovanni in Laterano (Basilica, Palazzo Apostolico Lateranense, edifici annessi) Holy See; listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1990.

nodes.title: Catacomba di San Giovanni
nodes.description: Ancient catacombs in the city of Siracusa, built between AD 315 and 360. The main gallery re-purposes parts of an earlier aqueduct.

nodes.title: Biblis
nodes.description: A spring located in the territory of Miletus.

nodes.title: South Palace at Deir el-Ballas
nodes.description: Two-story palace near the western bank of the Nile used as an administrative center from the Second Intermediate Period to the early New Kingdom.

nodes.title: Forum Traiani
nodes.description: Imperial forum constructed at Rome under Trajan between 105-112 CE.

nodes.title: Bath-Gymnasium Complex at Sardis
nodes.description: Bath/gymnasium complex containing a palaestra and a synagogue that was developed in the 3rd century CE.

nodes.title: Tomb of Seuthes III
nodes.description: An elaborate tomb located near Kazanlak, Bulgaria. The Tomb of Seuthes III, who was King of the Odrysian Kingdom from ca. 331 to ca. 300 BC, is found in the Valley of the Thracian Rulers.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Artemis Limnatis at Messene
nodes.description: A sanctuary on the slopes of Mount Ithome and within the city walls of ancient Messene in the Peloponnese. It was developed beginning in the 4th-3rd centuries BCE.

nodes.title: Dilmun Burial Mounds
nodes.description: The Dilmun Burial Mounds, a cultural landscape inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage site in July 2019. This landscape includes tombs dispersed in at least 21 archaeological sites in western Bahrain. These tombs date between 2050 and 1750 B.C. In all there are more than 11,774 burial mounds.

nodes.title: Madinat Hamad 2 Burial Mound Field (Karzakkan)
nodes.description: A necropolis of the early Dilmun culture, dating to the second millennium B.C.

nodes.title: San Nicola di Trullas
nodes.description: A Medieval church on the island of Sardinia that is dated to 1133.

nodes.title: Avenches Roman amphitheater
nodes.description: The Avenches Roman amphitheater.

nodes.title: Porta Pretoria (Albano Laziale)
nodes.description: The principal gateway of Castra Albana.

nodes.title: Mochlos (island)
nodes.description: Mochlos is an island in the Gulf of Mirabello, although in antiquity it was likely connected to the Cretan mainland. The island is the site of an ancient Minoan settlement.

nodes.title: Agora of Halaesa
nodes.description: The agora of the ancient city of Halaesa (second century B.C.), now within the archaeological area of Alesa Arconidea, Sicily.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Sa Bosa
nodes.description: The remains of a nuraghe near an industrial zone near Sassari.

nodes.title: Theater at Stymphalos
nodes.description: The remains of a rock-cut theater at Stymphalos.

nodes.title: Royal Tombs of Vergina
nodes.description: The Macedonian royal necropolis at Vergina.

nodes.title: Kavuncu
nodes.description: Kavuncu is a modern settlement situated near Van in the southeast of Turkey. Here a cylindrical stone (probably a column base) with an inscription of the Urartian king Minua, son of Išpuini (9/8th century BCE) was found (CTU I A 5-53 B).

nodes.title: Theater of Ephesus
nodes.description: The Theater of Ephesus sits at the foot of the Panayir mountains. It could host up to 25,000 spectators.

nodes.title: New Nisa
nodes.description: The tell site of New Nisa is part of the Parthian fortress of Nisa, designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

nodes.title: Old Nisa
nodes.description: The tell of Old Nisa is part of the Parthian fortress of Nisa, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

nodes.title: Theater at Alinda/Alexandria ad Latmum
nodes.description: The Roman Theater at Alinda could accommodate about 5,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Yazılıkaya
nodes.description: A sacred rock-cut sanctuary of the Hittites. The sanctuary was in use from the late sixteenth century B.C. Many of the reliefs date reigns of Tudhaliya IV and Suppiluliuma II in the late thirteenth century B.C.

nodes.title: Heroön
nodes.description: The so-called Heroön at Sagalassos dominates the Upper Agora in the northwest sector of the city.

nodes.title: Palace of the Shirvanshahs
nodes.description: A fifteenth-century palace built by the Shirvanshahs in Baku, Azerbaijan.

nodes.title: Newport Arch city gate
nodes.description: The remains of a third century A.D. city gate.

nodes.title: Multangular Tower
nodes.description: The Multangular Tower at York once stood at the west corner of the Roman legionary fortress.

nodes.title: Roman forum of Col. Clunia (Sulpicia)
nodes.description: The Roman forum of Col. Clunia (Sulpicia) dates to the Imperial period. It is equipped with a rectangular basilica and a small tribunal in addition to shops. The paved decumanus enters the square through a gate.

nodes.title: San Roque Theatre - Carteia
nodes.description: The Roman theater of Carteia.

nodes.title: "Western Theater" at Laodicea ad Lycum
nodes.description: Digitized by eye in Google Earth on 13 July 2012 at an eye altitude of 683m. Dates are general settlement dates, following Foss and Mitchell in BAtlas.

nodes.title: Roman theater of Stobi
nodes.description: The Roman theater of Stobi dates to the second century.

nodes.title: Arch of the Sergii
nodes.description: A Roman triumphal arch at Pula commemorating Lucius Sergius Lepidus and the family of the Sergii for service at the Battle of Actium in 31 BC.

nodes.title: Malo rimsko kazalište (Roman theater)
nodes.description: The Roman theater in Pula dates to the first century.

nodes.title: Temple of Artemis Orthia
nodes.description: An Archaic temple dedicated to Artemis Orthia within the sanctuary of this goddess at Sparta. The site contained rich deposits of votives and masks.

nodes.title: Underground Shrine (Paestum)
nodes.description: A small, underground tomb-like structure located in the agora of Paestum, thought to be either a shrine or a heroon.

nodes.title: Porta Marina tower of Poseidonia/Paestum
nodes.description: The so-called Porta Marina of Paestum is a gate in the Hellenistic fortifications and is located along a main street axis leading to the port of the city.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of the Public Lares
nodes.description: A sanctuary located on the east side of Pompeii's forum (VII, 9, 3), the Sanctuary of the Public Lares was likely built after AD 62. The sanctuary measures ca. 18 x 21 m and centers on an open central courtyard.

nodes.title: Mensa Ponderaria
nodes.description: The Mensa ponderaria (VII,7,31) was an official public office adjacent to the forum of Pompeii wherein weights and measures were regulated. This location was in use from the late second century BC.

nodes.title: Temple of Khonsu at Karnak
nodes.description: New Kingdom temple to the god Khonsu, constructed by Ramesses III and expanded by Ptolemy III Euergetes.

nodes.title: Absheron (peninsula)
nodes.description: A peninsula in the South Caucasus, extending approximately 60 km into the Caspian Sea.

nodes.title: Mausoleum of Lucius Munatius Plancus
nodes.description: A Roman mausoleum that is associated with Lucius Munatius Plancus.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Grumentum
nodes.description: Grumentum's amphitheater (first century B.C.) is the only known example in Lucania. The arena measures ca. 62.5 by 60 meters.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Frusino
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Frusino measures ca. 78 by 57 meters.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Al(l)ifae
nodes.description: Remains of a Roman amphitheater dating to the later first century A.D.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Telesia
nodes.description: A Late Republican Roman amphitheater at Telesia.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Simitthu
nodes.description: The poorly preserved remains of an amphitheater that had likely been abandoned by the fifth century.

nodes.title: Tomb of Tutankhamun (KV62)
nodes.description: The rock-cut tomb of the Egyptian pharaoh Tutankhamun (r. ca. 1332-1323 BC), discovered by Howard Carter in 1922.

nodes.title: Public baths at Saepinum
nodes.description: The public baths at Saepinum are located along the decumanus and date to the first and second centuries.

nodes.title: Basilica at Saepinum
nodes.description: The Basilica at Saepinum is positioned at the intersection of the cardo and the decumanus.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Carsulae
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Carsulae dates to the Augustan period, pre-dating the amphitheater.

nodes.title: Forum of Carsulae
nodes.description: The Forum of Carsulae is supported by terraces and it includes the basilica and a twin sanctuary, in addition to tabernae.

nodes.title: So-called twin sanctuary
nodes.description: A double sanctuary on the forum of Carsulae. It is no longer clear to which gods these temples belonged.

nodes.title: Roman arch
nodes.description: A triumphal arch located in the civic forum.

nodes.title: Roman arch
nodes.description: The Roman arch that stands at Musti (Tunisia).

nodes.title: Forum of Suasa
nodes.description: The Forum of Suasa measures 50 x 100 meters and was surrounded by a portico.

nodes.title: House of the Cryptoporticus at Vulci
nodes.description: A well-appointed Roman domus with a large, well-preserved cryptoporticus. The earliest phase belongs to the late second and early first century B.C. with subsequent modifications during the early Imperial period.

nodes.title: Castel Sant'Angelo
nodes.description: The Mausoleum of Hadrian, also known as the Castel Sant'Angelo, is an Imperial tomb on the banks of the Tiber river.

nodes.title: Via Aurelia
nodes.description: A Roman road.

nodes.title: Ponte Nepesino
nodes.description: A bridge along the Via Amerina.

nodes.title: Ponte Romano di Parco dei Medici
nodes.description: The ruins of a second-century A.D. Roman bridge at Magliana Vecchia.

nodes.title: Mouseion Hill
nodes.description: A hill located near the acropolis of Athens. Pausanias discusses fortifications in the hellenistic period; later the Philopappos Monument was built at the summit.

nodes.title: Mithraeum at Fertőrákos
nodes.description: A well-preserved Mithraeum with modern stone vault above ground and site below in Fertőrákos, Hungary at the site of ancient Scarbantia

nodes.title: Capitolinus Mons
nodes.description: The smallest of Rome's hills and one of its most important, the Capitoline served as the citadel (arx) of the city and as the site of its poliadic temple.

nodes.title: Arcus Argentariorum
nodes.description: A commemorative arch located in the Velabrum dedicated to the Severan emperors in AD 204 by the local association of money-changers (argentarii) and merchants (negotiantes). It was later incorporated into the church of S. Giorgio al Velabro.

nodes.title: Polygonal masonry wall
nodes.description: An extant segment of a Polygonal masonry wall in Caiazzo.

nodes.title: Poseidon?, T.
nodes.description: Poseidon?, T. a sanctuary of Poseidon on the island of Samos.

nodes.title: Pothaia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 D4 Pothaia

nodes.title: Priene/‘Lince’?
nodes.description: Priene/‘Lince’? was an ancient Greek city of Ionia on an escarpment of Mycale Mons.

nodes.title: Proespera
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 C2 Proespera

nodes.title: Psaropyrgos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 A4 Psaropyrgos

nodes.title: Pyrgos Kheimarrou
nodes.description: A Hellenistic fortification and tower in southeastern Naxos.

nodes.title: Rhakhes
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 C2 Rhakhes

nodes.title: Rheneia (settlement)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 A3 Rheneia

nodes.title: Rheneia (island)
nodes.description: A Cycladic island just west of Delos in the Aegean Sea. It consists of two parts linked by a narrow isthmus.

nodes.title: Samiopoula
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 D2 Samiopoula

nodes.title: Samos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 D2 Samos

nodes.title: Samos (island)
nodes.description: The island of Samos.

nodes.title: Selinous (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 E2 Selinous fl.

nodes.title: Skalia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 D3 Skalia

nodes.title: Skanderion Pr.
nodes.description: Cape Skandari is the northernmost point of the island of Kos.

nodes.title: Sounion Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 A3 Sounion Pr.

nodes.title: Sporades (archipelago)
nodes.description: An archipelago off the east coast of Greece in the Aegean Sea consisting of 24 islands.

nodes.title: Stratonikeia
nodes.description: An ancient city in Caria founded by Antiochus I Soter, according to Strabo. The city had several phases, including a period of Rhodian influence, before coming under the umbrella of Roman administration. The city was elaborately embellished with monumental programs of public art and architecture.

nodes.title: Sykia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 D4 Sykia

nodes.title: Syme
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 F4 Syme

nodes.title: Syme (island)
nodes.description: An island located off the coast of Caria, some 24 km north of Rhodes.

nodes.title: Syrie (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 inset Syrie Ins.

nodes.title: Teutloussa (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 F4 Teutloussa Ins.

nodes.title: Thera
nodes.description: An ancient settlement located atop the modern Messavouno mountain on the island that shared its name in antiquity (modern Thira/Santorini).

nodes.title: Thera (island)
nodes.description: An island of the southern Aegean Sea, Thera is the southernmost of the Cyclades. The island's present form is the result of a Middle Bronze Age volcanic eruption that destroyed a Minoan settlement on the island.

nodes.title: Therasia (island)
nodes.description: Therasia is the the second largest island of the Santorini Archipelago. It was separated from Thera by the Thera eruption.

nodes.title: Therasia?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 A5 Therasia?

nodes.title: Therma/Asklepieis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 C2 Therma/Asklepieis

nodes.title: Thia? (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 A5 Thia? Ins.

nodes.title: Tralles/Dia/Seleuceia ad Maeandrum/Kaisareia
nodes.description: Tralles/Dia/Seleuceia ad Maeandrum/Kaisareia was an ancient city founded by Argives and Trallians that then fell under the sway of the Persian Empire and, later, Hellenistic kings.

nodes.title: Tsoko
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 E2 Tsoko

nodes.title: Tsikalario
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 A3 Tsikalario

nodes.title: Xerokambos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 D3 Xerokambos

nodes.title: Zeus Melosios, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 B3 Zeus Melosios, T.

nodes.title: Prinas (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 6 E5 Prinas fl.

nodes.title: Sacae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 6 C2 Sacae

nodes.title: Sagapa Stoma
nodes.description: Sagapa Stoma is the western mouth of the Indus river.

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct at Ephesus (Aqua Iulia?)
nodes.description: The longest and most recently-constructed Roman aqueduct in the province of Asia, measuring 36.5 km from its source in the hills south of Ephesus to the metropolis itself. The aqueduct was first commissioned by the emperor Hadrian in 122-126, and it portions of it remained in use into the medieval period. In modern times, it is known as the Değirmendere Aqueduct, after the nearby Kenchrios river (modern Değirmendere).

nodes.title: Sinthon Stoma
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 6 B5 Sinthon Stoma

nodes.title: Sogdiana
nodes.description: Sogdiana was a wide region of the Achaemenid Empire lying between the Oxus (Araxes) and Iaxartes rivers.

nodes.title: Taxila
nodes.description: An ancient city with the ruins of the Gandhāran city of Takṣaśilā, an important Hindu and Buddhist center. (cited: BAtlas 6 C3 Taxila)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 D2 unnamed bridge (at Neokhorion on Samos)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 A5 unnamed cemetery (on Therasia)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 D3 unnamed fort (on Akrite)

nodes.title: Unnamed fort on Nisyrion Inss.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 E4 unnamed fort group (on Nisyrion Inss.)

nodes.title: unnamed quarry (on Mykonos)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 A3 unnamed quarry (on Mykonos)

nodes.title: Achaia (settlement)
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, said by Strabo to have been located in Areia (i.e., in or near the modern province of Herat, Afghanistan). Its precise location is unknown.

nodes.title: Arius L.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 6 unlocated Arius L.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Hot springs located on Nisyros.

nodes.title: Cholbesina
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Condigramma
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Daroakana
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Gorys/Gorya
nodes.description: An ancient settlement in the Hindu-Kush, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Indikomordana
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Margania
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Memaceni
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

nodes.title: Oxeiana
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Oxeianoi
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

nodes.title: Panda
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Asopos (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 unlocated Asopos fl.

nodes.title: Pasikai/Paskai
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

nodes.title: Dimastos M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 unlocated Dimastos M.

nodes.title: Tarmia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 unlocated *Tarmia

nodes.title: Scythae/Sagae/Sacae
nodes.description: The Scythians. An ancient people of Central Asia, mentioned frequently in Greek and Roman sources. Their place of origin and territory is the subject of much scholarly debate; the territory likely changed over time.

nodes.title: Trybaktra
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Aizanoi
nodes.description: Aizanoi was an ancient Roman city located in western Anatolia.

nodes.title: Akroenos/[Akroinos]
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 E4 Akroenos/[Akroinos]

nodes.title: Antiochia/Col. Caesarea
nodes.description: An ancient city in Pisidia.

nodes.title: Apollo, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 E4 Apollo, T.

nodes.title: Dindymos M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 C4 Dindymos M.

nodes.title: Dorylaion
nodes.description: Dorylaion was an important city in the north of Phrygia (modern Eskişehir in Turkey).

nodes.title: Eiokome
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 D3 Eiokome

nodes.title: Gordion/Vindia?
nodes.description: The capital city of ancient Phrygia, the ruins of Gordion are located near the modern village of Yassıhüyük about 10km east of the Turkish city of Polatlı.

nodes.title: Kadoi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 B3 Kadoi

nodes.title: Kastolou Pedion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 A4 Kastolou Pedion

nodes.title: Kotiaeion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 C3 Kotiaeion

nodes.title: Midaion
nodes.description: A city in Phrygia named after its legendary founder, king Midas.

nodes.title: Nakoleia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 E3 Nakoleia

nodes.title: Penkalas (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 C3 Penkalas fl.

nodes.title: Pessinous/Iustinianoupolis
nodes.description: An ancient city of Asia Minor, today Ballıhisar in Turkey.

nodes.title: Tembris (river)
nodes.description: The modern Porsuk River.

nodes.title: Temnos M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 A3 Temnos M.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An unnamed spring and aqueduct serving Colonia Caesarea

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 E2 unnamed bridge (S Dorylaion, between city and hot springs)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 F5 unnamed bridge (three in aqueduct NE Antiochia)

nodes.title: Adoreus M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 unlocated Adoreus M.

nodes.title: Kastollos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 unlocated Kastollos

nodes.title: Kobedyle
nodes.description: A settlement mentioned in ancient sources that cannot be precisely located today. It was probably located in the area of modern Turkey called Burçak Ovası (ancient Kastolou Pedion), northeast of Philadelpheia (modern Alaşehir).

nodes.title: Governor's Palace at Kalhu
nodes.description: This beautifully-decorated Assyrian palace is located just north of the Nabû temple Ezida, in the southeast quarter of the citadel of Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud). The building likely served as the office and/or residence of several important individuals in the administration of the Assyrian Empire, probably including the governor of Kalhu. Numerous cuneiform tablets were discovered in three rooms north of the central courtyard. Because many of those Akkadian texts relate to the activities of several governors, British excavators in the 1950s dubbed the building the "Governor's Palace."

nodes.title: Kalhu ziggurat
nodes.description: The temple-tower of the god Ninurta, which was started by the ninth-century-BC Assyrian ruler Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) and completed by his son and successor Shalmaneser III (r. 858–824 BC), is still the most prominent feature of Kalhu (modern Nimrud). This multi-staged ziggurat, whose remains are now a pyramid of eroding mud-brick, was constructed in the northwest corner of the citadel, next to Kalhu's principal sanctuary, the Ninurta temple.

nodes.title: Ninurta temple (Kalhu)
nodes.description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. The most important of those was dedicated to the god Ninurta, the patron deity of city, which Ashurnasirpal had constructed between his palace and the ziggurat, a building also consecrated to Ninurta.

nodes.title: Ea-Damkina temple (Kalhu)
nodes.description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the god Ea and the goddess Damkina. Although its location is not known, the Ea-Damkina temple at Kalhu is thought to have been situated within the Ninurta temple complex, in the northwest corner of the citadel.

nodes.title: Kidmuri temple (Kalhu)
nodes.description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the divine Kidmuri (probably a collective name for a group of gods).

nodes.title: Central Building at Kalhu
nodes.description: Near the middle of the citadel of Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud), the ninth-century-BC Assyrian king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) constructed a building with a grand, south-facing entrance. This building, constructed east of the southeast corner of the Northwest Palace, might have been one of the temples built by Ashurnasirpal II when he made Kalhu the administrative capital of the Assyrian Empire. Alternatively, the Central Building might have served as a palace.

nodes.title: Al-Khazneh
nodes.description: An elaborate, rock-cut monument at Petra built ca. 100 BC to AD 200 known as "Al-Khazneh" or "The Treasury". The Nabatean structure, originally used as a tomb, dates to the reign of Aretas IV Philopatris.

nodes.title: Synagogue at Aḥmadiah (Aḥmadiya, Ahmadiyye)
nodes.description: Remains of a synagogue in the Golan with Greek and Hebrew Inscriptions

nodes.title: Bitti, Complesso di Romanzesu
nodes.description: A 7-hectare nuragic complex.

nodes.title: Seruci
nodes.description: A nuragic complex including a central nuraghe and an associated village.

nodes.title: Nuraghe s'Ulimu
nodes.description: A two-tower nuraghe located near Ulassai in the province of Nuoro.

nodes.title: Qaqqar-aradātu
nodes.description: An unlocated city/town in the kingdom of Suhu, probably not far from Alu-eššu, Baqa, and Ribaniš.

nodes.title: Enamhe
nodes.description: The temple of the gods Adad and Apla-Adad at Anat (Anatho). The Sumerian ceremonial name Enamhe means "House of Plenty."

nodes.title: Uqaya
nodes.description: This unlocated land/region is presumably near the kingdom of Suhu, in the middle Euphrates region.

nodes.title: Martu
nodes.description: An unlocated well in the middle Euphrates region, near the city Ḫindānu.

nodes.title: Suhu
nodes.description: The kingdom of Suhu was situated on the middle Euphrates and stretched from the northwestern border of Babylonia in the south to Hindanu in the north. During the 9th and 8th centuries B.C., its rulers held authority over the cities Anat (Anatho), Suru, Rahi-ilu, and even Mari. Approximately thirty Akkadian inscriptions of its rulers Šamaš-rēša-uṣur and Ninurta-kudurrī-uṣur were discovered in the region of Haditha in the early 1980s, prior to the construction of the Haditha dam, which flooded the region; many of Suhu's cities are now underwater.

nodes.title: Vejano
nodes.description: Vejano, located in the Province of Viterbo, is located on the Mignone river approximately 60 km northwest of Rome. While the most visible monument on the site today is the fifteenth century castle known as "La Rocca", the site has a long settlement history reaching back to the Bronze Age.

nodes.title: Tropaeum Traiani (monument)
nodes.description: A war memorial near the ancient settlement of Tropaeum Traiani (modern Adamclisi)

nodes.title: Forum of Vulci
nodes.description: The forum of the ancient town, dating to the Roman period.

nodes.title: Forum of Roman Corinth
nodes.description: The Roman forum of ancient Corinth.

nodes.title: Roman theater of Lokroi Epizephyrioi
nodes.description: A Roman theater of the first century B.C. built on the site of the fourth century B.C. Greek theater.

nodes.title: Etruscan acropolis at Volaterrae
nodes.description: The multi-phase acropolis of Etruscan Volaterrae has numerous important phases, beginning in the Archaic period. The monumental site continued to develop and grow during the Hellenistic period. It was identified archaeologically only in the nineteenth century. In the twentieth century it was the subject of major investigations under M. Cristofani and, later, M. Bonamici.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Volaterrae
nodes.description: The Roman theater of Volaterrae was built during the during the Augustan period under the consulship of Aulus Caecina Severus.

nodes.title: Turris Mamilia
nodes.description: The Turris Mamilia was a tower in Rome's Subura that was part of the sacred rites of the Equus October.

nodes.title: Avitta Bibba amphitheater
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater located in the modern Siliana Governorate of Tunisia.

nodes.title: Zababa Gate
nodes.description: The Zababa Gate is one of Babylon's eight city gates and it is situated on the eastern side of the inner city, directly east of the TE.E quarter. King Nebuchadnezzar II built the gate ca. 575 B.C.

nodes.title: Ehursagtilla
nodes.description: The temple of the god Ninurta, Ehursagtilla (“House Which Exterminates the Mountains”), was located in the Šuanna district (modern Ishin Aswad) of Babylon. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, this was one of two temples in that part of the city, which was located in the southern part of the eastern half of Babylon. The building was rebuilt by the Neo-Babylonian king Nabopolassar (r. 625–605 BC).

nodes.title: Kullab
nodes.description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, Kullab was one of the six city districts of the eastern half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained four temples.

nodes.title: TE.E
nodes.description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, TE.E (read as either Tê or Kisīri) was one of the six city districts of the eastern half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained one temple and two daises.

nodes.title: Gardens of Maecenas
nodes.description: The Gardens of Maecenas or "Horti Maecenatis" were extensive, planned gardens laid out on Rome's Esquiline Hill by Caius Cilinius Maecenas in the mid-30s B.C. These formal gardens occupied what had previously been the agger of the Servian walls and the adjacent necropolis that had an unsavory reputation. Following the death of Maecenas, the gardens became imperial property.

nodes.title: North Palace at Babylon
nodes.description: The Neo-Babylonian king Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC) constructed a new royal residence for himself at Babylon. This grand palace was constructed north of the so-called “South Palace,” the traditional royal residence of the kings of Babylon. The building, which is referred to as the “new palace” (ēkallu eššu) in Achaemenid-period texts, is generally called the “North Palace,” “Nordburg,” and “New Palace.”

nodes.title: Marduk Gate
nodes.description: The Marduk Gate is one of Babylon's eight city gates and it is situated on the eastern side of the inner city, directly east of the Kullab quarter. King Nebuchadnezzar II built the gate ca. 575 B.C.

nodes.title: Emah
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Ninmah/Bēlet-ilī, Emah (“Exalated House”), was located in the Ka-dingirra district (modern Kasr) of Babylon. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, this was one of four temples in that part of the city, which was located in the northern part of the eastern half of Babylon. Emah was rebuilt by the Assyrian king Ashurbanipal (r. 668–ca. 631 BC) and the Babylonian king Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC).

nodes.title: Eridu
nodes.description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, Eridu was one of the six city districts of the eastern half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained thirteen temples (including Esagila) and the ziggurat Etemenanki. Eridu is also a name of Babylon itself.

nodes.title: Ka-dingirra
nodes.description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, Ka-dingirra was one of the six city districts of the eastern half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained four temples. Ka-dingirra is also a name of Babylon itself.

nodes.title: New City/Newtown
nodes.description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, New City (ālu eššu) was one of the six city districts of the eastern half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained two temples and one dais. This city quarter dates back to the late Old Babylonian Period (as demonstrated by a commercial archive excavated in the Merkes).

nodes.title: Tuba
nodes.description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, Tuba was one of the four city districts of the western half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained three temples.

nodes.title: Mount Fumaiolo
nodes.description: A mountain of the northern Apennines (elevation 1,408 m; 4,619 ft) from which the Tiber River originates.

nodes.title: Maşat Höyük
nodes.description: A Bronze Age Hittite center ca. 100 km east of Boğazkale/Hattusa.

nodes.title: Arsham
nodes.description: An ancient fortress located somewhere between Mosul and modern Zakho; its precise location is unknown today.

nodes.title: Bagni di Nerone
nodes.description: The so-called "Baths of Nero" are located near the Porta a Lucca in Pisa.

nodes.title: Temple of Al-Lat at Palmyra
nodes.description: A temple sacred to the goddess Al-Lat in Palmyra. The earliest shrine on the site was constructed in the mid-first century BCE, and was greatly expanded during the second century CE. The temple was closed and its altar destroyed during the 380s CE.

nodes.title: So-called House of the Doric Peristyle
nodes.description: A large private house in Cyrene.

nodes.title: Via Julia Augusta
nodes.description: A road begun in 13 BC by Augustus that was, in effect, a merging of the Via Postumia and the Via Aemilia Scauri.

nodes.title: Mura Messapiche
nodes.description: Well-preserved remains of the ashlar fortification walls at Manduria.

nodes.title: *Atuna (kingdom)
nodes.description: A kingdom in Tabal mentioned in royal inscriptions of the Assyrian kings Tiglath-pileser III (r. 744-727 BC) and Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC).

nodes.title: *Atuna
nodes.description: *Atuna is the capital of the kingdom *Atuna in Tabal.

nodes.title: Jauṣa[...]
nodes.description: The partially preserved kingdom Jauṣa[...] is mentioned together with the city Hubušnu and Mount Mulî in a royal inscription of the Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC).

nodes.title: Jā' (region)
nodes.description: A region on Cyprus (Akkadian Jadnana). The eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II states that seven kings of Jāʾ, a region of Jadnana, sent him tribute.

nodes.title: Harrua
nodes.description: Harrua is a Quean fortress located on the Cilician plain. In the eighth century BC, perhaps only for a short time, Phrygia controlled the territory in which Harrua is was located. The Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705), after his armies defeated the Phrygian king Midas (= Mitâ of Musku), restored Harrua to Que, which was then a province of the Assyrian Empire.

nodes.title: Lamena (mountain)
nodes.description: A mountain in Que, probably in the region of Kozan or north of Adana, mentioned in royal inscriptions of the Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC).

nodes.title: Falerna
nodes.description: A rural tribe of Rome, which was established in 318 B.C.

nodes.title: Villa della Cecchignola
nodes.description: A Roman villa that was, in antiquity, located along the via Ardeatina, perhaps at the ninth mile. Excavations by Carlo Fea (1828) and twentieth century excavations (1939) recorded the villa on the land of the Cecchignola (formerly a property of the Torlonia family). The precise location of the archaeological site is today unknown.

nodes.title: Kara-Tepe
nodes.description: A Buddhist monastery constructed near the city of Tarmita/Termez in the early second century CE.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater of Venusia
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater dating to the first and second centuries.

nodes.title: Azeia
nodes.description: A settlement in Troas whose precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Silwan necropolis
nodes.description: Iron Age cemetery located on the eastern slope of the Kidron Valley, containing burials dated from the 9th-7th centuries BCE.

nodes.title: Aetolian League
nodes.description: Based in Aetolia in central Greece, the Aetolian League was founded in the Hellenistic period to counter the power of Macedon and the Achaean League. It was allied with Rome in the First Macedonian War (215-205 BCE), but later was opposed to the republic in Rome's war against Antiochos (192–188 BCE). After Rome's victory in 188, the Aetolian League was fully subordinate to Rome.

nodes.title: Achaean League (Second)
nodes.description: Established in 280 BCE, the second Achaean League was centered in the northern and central Peloponnese. Allied to Rome in the Second Macedonian War (200-196 BCE), the league extended its control over all of the Peloponnese. In the Third Macedonian War (171–168 BCE) the League's relationship with Rome deteriorated; in ca. 146 BCE this led to open warfare, which resulted in the defeat and dissolution of the league.

nodes.title: Naga ed-Deir
nodes.description: The necropolis associated with the unlocated city This (Thinis), capital city of the unified Egyptian kingdom in the Early Dynastic period. The necropolis stretches for 1.5 kilometers and contains thousands of burials from the Predynastic period through the early Coptic period, with particularly large numbers of burials from the Predynastic period (ca. 3800–3200 BCE) and the late Old Kingdom-First Intermediate Period (ca. 2300–2061 BCE).

nodes.title: Rabaçal Roman villa
nodes.description: A fourth-century AD Roman villa located in Rabaçal, Portugal, near the site of Conimbriga.

nodes.title: Massyli
nodes.description: A confederation of Berber tribes living in Numidia.

nodes.title: Nigris (river)
nodes.description: Nigris fl. (Djedi river) is a wadi in Algeria that is also one of the largest rivers of the Sahara.

nodes.title: Thamugadi
nodes.description: A Roman colonial town founded in the Aurès Mountains of Algeria by the Emperor Trajan around AD 100. The city's full name was Colonia Marciana Ulpia Traiana Thamugadi. Trajan named the city in commemoration of his mother Marcia, eldest sister Ulpia Marciana, and father Marcus Ulpius Traianus.

nodes.title: Vatari?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 34 F2 Vatari?

nodes.title: Zarai
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 34 D2 Zarai

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct supplying Diana Veteranorum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 34 E2 unnamed aqueduct (Diana Veteranorum)

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct supplying Lambaesis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 34 E2 unnamed aqueduct (Lambaesis)

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct supplying Thamugadi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 34 E2 unnamed aqueduct (Thamugadi)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 34 D3 unnamed feature group (forts along Nigris fl.)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Gemellae → Ad Piscinam? → Tfilzi → Lambaesis

nodes.title: Siuddurusi Praesidium)/Siuddurusi Psidium)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 34 unlocated Siuddurusi P(rae)sidium)

nodes.title: Velefi
nodes.description: An ancient settlement or road station attested in the Peutinger Map, but otherwise unknown and unlocateable. The map places it together with several other unlocated places on a route in modern Algeria between Gadifaula (modern Ksar Sbehi) and Vatari (which might be modern Fedj es Siouda).

nodes.title: Abrotonum/Sabratha
nodes.description: The westernmost of the "three cities" of Tripolis, Abrotonum/Sabratha was founded ca. 500 B.C. by the Phoenicians. The city was part of the Numidian Kingdom of Massinissa before becoming a Roman city.

nodes.title: Cidamus
nodes.description: Cidamus (modern Ghadamès, Libya) became allied to Rome after Lucius Cornelius Balbus prevailed against the Garamantes in 19 BC.

nodes.title: Ghirza
nodes.description: Ghirza is the site of a Roman town in Libya.

nodes.title: Laguatan
nodes.description: A confederation of Libyan peoples, cited: BAtlas 35 F3 Laguatan

nodes.title: Macae
nodes.description: Macae, Libyan Tribe, cited: BAtlas 35 F3

nodes.title: Meninge
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 35 C1 Meninge

nodes.title: Meninx/Lotophagitis/Girba Ins.
nodes.description: Meninx/Lotophagitis/Girba Ins. (modern Djerba) is the largest island of North Africa.

nodes.title: Neapolis/Lepcis Magna
nodes.description: Originally a Phoenician colony founded ca. 1100 B.C., Lepcis Magna became a prominent Roman city and birthplace of the emperor Septimius Severus.

nodes.title: Oea
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 35 F2 Oea

nodes.title: Syrtis Minor
nodes.description: The Gulf of Gabès.

nodes.title: Tacape
nodes.description: Tacape (modern Gabès) was a commercial city located on the Lesser Syrtis.

nodes.title: Tipasa
nodes.description: An ancient settlement and emporion.

nodes.title: Tisavar
nodes.description: A Roman fortlet in Tripolitana (modern Ksar Ghilane in Tunisia).

nodes.title: Tripolitana (region)
nodes.description: The historical region of coastal Libya and Tunisia around Sabratha, Oea, and Lepcis Magna

nodes.title: Zliten
nodes.description: A coastal villa known especially for its polychrome gladiatorial mosaics.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 35 E2 unnamed aqueduct (Sabratha)

nodes.title: Unnamed earthwork in the Tebaga Gap
nodes.description: The so-called "Tebaga clausura", a Roman earthwork located northeast of Bezereos at Tebaga in Tunisia.

nodes.title: Temple F at Selinus
nodes.description: Temple F at Selinus is a Doric temple located on the site's so-called "East Hill". Dedicated either to Athena or Dionysus, the temple dates to the middle of the sixth century B.C. The non-canonical ground plan of 6 x 14 columns gives the temple an elongated aspect.

nodes.title: Roman bath at Volaterrae
nodes.description: A bath complex located adjacent to the theater of Volaterrae.

nodes.title: House of the cithara player
nodes.description: The so-called "House of the cithara player" (I,4,5 and 25) opens both on to the Via Stabiana and the Via dell'Abbondanza. One of the largest aristocratic homes in Pompeii, it was formed from two adjoining properties.

nodes.title: House of Octavius Quartio
nodes.description: The House of Octavius Quartio or the House of Loreius Tiburtinus (II,2,2).

nodes.title: Porta Nocera
nodes.description: A city gate of Pompeii located at the southern terminus of Strada di Porta Nocera.

nodes.title: tribus Arnensis
nodes.description: The tribus Arnensis was one of the later rural tribes of Rome, which was established in 387 B.C.

nodes.title: Porta Nola
nodes.description: A city gate located at the eastern terminus of the Strada di Nola. In antiquity, the gate was known as Porta Urbulana.

nodes.title: tribus Camilia
nodes.description: The tribus Camilia is one of the sixteen oldest rural tribes of Rome.

nodes.title: tribus Claudia
nodes.description: The tribus Claudia was the twenty-first rural tribe.

nodes.title: Watling Street
nodes.description: A Roman road in Britain.

nodes.title: Dere Street
nodes.description: Dere Street is a Roman road in northern Britain and Scotland, also known as the Via Regia. Dere Street connected Eburacum with Veluniate.

nodes.title: So-called Palace of the Dux
nodes.description: A large building complex located on the western hill of Apollonia, probably built between the fifth and sixth centuries A.D. Its position and size, the presence of a chapel with a reliquary, and some public rooms led Goodchild to identify it as the residence of the Dux.

nodes.title: Ta' Ħaġrat Temple Complex
nodes.description: Ta' Ħaġrat is a megalithic temple complex on the island of Malta (ca. 3600-3000 B.C.), included in the UNESCO World Heritage List.

nodes.title: Via Latina
nodes.description: A Roman road running southeast from Rome toward Campania.

nodes.title: Vicus Iugarius
nodes.description: An ancient street that led from the Forum Romanum to the porta Carmentalis, passing between the basilica Iulia and the temple of the Castors.

nodes.title: Stadium at Anazarbos
nodes.description: A stadium south of the city proper at Anazarbos (modern Dilekkaya in Turkey)

nodes.title: Temple of Zeus at Cyrene
nodes.description: The Doric Temple of Zeus at Cyrene

nodes.title: Agade
nodes.description: Agade was the capital of the Akkadian state, which was the dominant military and political force in southern Mesopotamia ca. 2334-2113 B.C. Agade (also known as Akkad and Akkade) is mentioned in cuneiform texts from the late third millennium B.C. to the Neo-Babylonian period. The exact location is still unknown and debated among scholars, many of whom place it along or east of the Tigris River, between Samarra and Baghdad.

nodes.title: Cuarto Roble
nodes.description: A fortified Roman villa within the territory of Norba Caesarina. Re-occupation occurred during the Islamic period in Spain.

nodes.title: Temple of Vesta at Rome
nodes.description: The Temple of Vesta, located at the east end of the Forum Romanum.

nodes.title: Temple C at Selinus
nodes.description: The so-called Temple C at Selinus is a Doric temple that dates to the second half of the sixth century B.C.

nodes.title: Tall-e Bakun
