nodes.description: Prehistoric archaeological site located 3 km south of Persepolis. The site consists of two mounds (Tall-e Bakun A and B).

nodes.title: Kythnos (island)
nodes.description: Kythnos is an island in the Aegean Sea and one of the Cyclades.

nodes.title: Lacedaemon/Laconia
nodes.description: Lacedaemon/Laconia is a region comprising the south-eastern part of the Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Laconicus Sinus
nodes.description: Laconicus Sinus is a gulf located in the southeastern Peloponnese of Greece.

nodes.title: Ladon (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B2 Ladon fl.

nodes.title: Ladon/Selleis (river)
nodes.description: A 70-km long river in the Peloponnese that is a tributary to the river Alfeios. The Ladon flows from its sources on the western slope of the Aroania mountain and joins the Alfeios some 3 km southeast of the village of Tripotamia.

nodes.title: Larisos (river)
nodes.description: An ancient river of the northern Peloponnese that was considered to constitute the western border of the region of Achaia.

nodes.title: Lechaion
nodes.description: The port of ancient Corinth.

nodes.title: Leontion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B1 Leontion

nodes.title: Lepreon
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B3 Lepreon

nodes.title: Lerna
nodes.description: Lerna was an ancient settlement on the east coast of the Peloponnesus. Extensive Bronze Age layers were excavated in the twentieth century by J. L. Caskey.

nodes.title: Loukou
nodes.description: A villa of Roman Imperial date, attributed to Herodes Atticus and his heirs. The modern name comes from the nearby Moni Loukous, or monastery of Loukou (St. Luke?), which may sit above an early Christian church.

nodes.title: Lykaion (mountain)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B3 Lykaion M.

nodes.title: Lykosoura
nodes.description: A city of Arcadia and home of the cult of Despoina

nodes.title: Mainalion (mountain)
nodes.description: The tallest in Arcadia, Mainalion is part of the Menalon mountain range of the Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Mainalion Pedion
nodes.description: The Mainalion Pedion was a plain located in central Greece.

nodes.title: Malea Pr.
nodes.description: Cape Maleas is a cape located in the southeast of the Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Marmarion
nodes.description: An ancient settlement and associated marble quarries on the island of Euboea.

nodes.title: Melos (settlement)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Melos

nodes.title: Melos (island)
nodes.description: Melos is a volcanic island in the Cyclades and in prehistoric times served as an important source of obsidian in the Aegean Sea. Substantial remains of Bronze Age and Greco-Roman civilizations have been excavated on the island.

nodes.title: Menelaion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C3 Menelaion

nodes.title: Messene
nodes.description: Capital of Messenia

nodes.title: Messenia
nodes.description: Messenia was the southwestern district of the Peloponnesus. It was bounded on the east by Laconia, on the north by Elis and Arcadia, and on the south and west by the sea.

nodes.title: Methone/Mothone (Messenian)
nodes.description: An ancient settlement sited at Homeric Pedasos on the Messenian peninsula.

nodes.title: Minoa Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 E4 Minoa Pr.

nodes.title: Mycenae
nodes.description: Mycenae was an ancient settlement of the Argolid, with the earliest occupation evident ca. 2900 B.C. As the eponymous site of the Mycenaean culture of the Aegean Bronze Age, the site flourished as a fortified citadel during the mid to late second millennium B.C. In the first millennium B.C., the site experienced a revival of fortunes, although by Strabo's time the settlement had vanished.

nodes.title: Myrtoion Mare
nodes.description: Myrtoion Mare (Myrtoan Sea) is a part of the Mediterranean Sea lying between the Cyclades and the Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Nauplia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 D2 Nauplia

nodes.title: Neda (river)
nodes.description: A river of Greece, rising on the slopes of Mt. Lykaion and flowing west to empty into the Gulf of Kyparissia just south of the modern village of Giannitsochori.

nodes.title: Nemea
nodes.description: Nemea, located north of Argos, was the site of the Panhellenic Games and the Sanctuary of Nemean Zeus.

nodes.title: Olenos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B1 Olenos

nodes.title: Olygyrtos (mountain)
nodes.description: Olygyrtos M. is a mountain located at the point where the reigons of Arcadia, the Corinthia and the Argolid intersect in the northeastern Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Olympia
nodes.description: Ancient sanctuary of Zeus and home of the ancient Olympic games.

nodes.title: Oneon (mountain)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 D2 Oneon M.

nodes.title: Orchomenos
nodes.description: The so-called "Arcadian Orchomenos", located near a modern village in the Peloponnese that, until the 1960s, was known as Kalpaki.

nodes.title: Oryx(is) (mountain)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C2 Oryx(is) M.

nodes.title: Palaiokhori
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 H4 Palaiokhori

nodes.title: Pamisos (river)
nodes.description: The principal river of Messenia.

nodes.title: Panormos (settlement, port)
nodes.description: An ancient settlement presumed to have been co-located with a harbor (limen) mentioned by Pausanias as lying 15 stadia east of the Rhion Pr. (modern Rio in Greece), on the north coast of the Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Panormos (harbor)
nodes.description: An ancient harbor (limen) on the north coast of the Pelopnnese, mentioned by Pausanias as lying 15 stadia to the east of the Rhion Pr. (modern Rio in Greece).

nodes.title: Parnon M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 D3 Parnon M.

nodes.title: Patra(e)
nodes.description: Patra(e) (modern Patras) is an important ancient center with settlement beginning in the Late Helladic period. Patras played a leading role in the foundation of the second "Achaean League" and was the site of a Roman colony after 146 BC.

nodes.title: Pelekoudi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 H4 Pelekoudi

nodes.title: Pellene
nodes.description: Pellene was an ancient settlement in Achaea allied with Sparta during the Peloponnesian War.

nodes.title: Peloponnesus/Peloponnesos/Peloponnese
nodes.description: The large peninsula protuding into the Mediterranean Sea that constitutes the southern part of Greece. It is largely separated from mainland Greece on the north by the Corinthian Gulf, joining it only in the northeast via the narrow Isthmus of Corinth.

nodes.title: Pelos Pyrgaki
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Pelos Pyrgaki

nodes.title: Pherai
nodes.description: An Archaic period to Roman period settlement located near Kalamata, Messinia in the Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Phigaleia
nodes.description: Phigaleia was an ancient city in the southwestern part of Arcadia in Greece.

nodes.title: Phleious
nodes.description: An ancient city located in the valley of the river Asopos.

nodes.title: Pollonia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 H4 Pollonia

nodes.title: Probatas
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Probatas

nodes.title: Rema
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 H4 Rema

nodes.title: Ribari
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Ribari

nodes.title: Samikon/Samia
nodes.description: A town of Triphylia in ancient Elis.

nodes.title: Saronicus Sinus
nodes.description: The Saronic Gulf (also called the Gulf of Aegina) is a part of the Aegean Sea that delimits the eastern side of the isthmus of Corinth.

nodes.title: Sicyon/Demetrias
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 D2 Sicyon/Demetrias

nodes.title: Sidero
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G2 Sidero

nodes.title: Skandeia
nodes.description: Pausanias locates Skandeia on the coast of the island of Cythera, some 10 stades from the inland settlement of Cythera.

nodes.title: Sparta
nodes.description: Sparta was a prominent city-state (polis) of ancient Greece.

nodes.title: Sta Glastria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Sta Glastria

nodes.title: Stoloi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Stoloi

nodes.title: Stymphalos
nodes.description: Stymphalos was a small but wealthy city of ancient Arcadia.

nodes.title: Sythas (river)
nodes.description: An ancient river of the northern Peloponnese (modern Trikaliotikos) that was considered to constitute the eastern border of the region of Achaia.

nodes.title: Tainaron (settlement)
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, located near the tip of a southern peninsula of the Peloponnese, known also by the name "Tainaron" in antiquity (modern Cape Matapon in Greece).

nodes.title: Tainaron Pr.
nodes.description: Tainaron Pr. (Cape Matapan) is the southernmost point of mainland Greece.

nodes.title: Taygetos M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C3 Taygetos M.

nodes.title: Tegea
nodes.description: Tegea was an ancient city of Arcadia. It is especially noted for its sanctuary dedicated to Athena Alea.

nodes.title: Tenea
nodes.description: Tenea was an ancient city of the Corinthia famous for its sanctuary of Apollo. Scholars have long believed it is to be located in the area of modern Chiliomodi in Greece. Recent scientific excavations have identified the general extent of a large, multi-period cemetery zone to the east and south of the modern town, as well as an extensive bath complex of Roman date.

nodes.title: Therapne
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C3 Therapne

nodes.title: Tholos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G2 Tholos

nodes.title: Thouria
nodes.description: Thouria is a settlement of the Peloponnese, with archaeological evidence ranging in date from the Bronze Age to the Roman period. The nature of the archaic and classical polity is debated in the sources.

nodes.title: Tiryns
nodes.description: A fortified Mycenaean center in the Argolid that flourished between 1400 and 1200 B.C.

nodes.title: Touthoa (river)
nodes.description: An ancient river of the northwest Peloponnese, described by Pausanias as flowing into the Ladon at the border of Thelpusian and Heraian territory (i.e., prior to the Ladon's confluence with the Alpheios).

nodes.title: Treis Ammoundas
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G2 Treis Ammoundas

nodes.title: Tria Pigadia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 H4 Tria Pigadia

nodes.title: Trikrana Ins.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 E3 Trikrana Ins.

nodes.title: Triphylia
nodes.description: Triphylia was a region of the western Peloponnese located north of the Alpheius river and south of the Neda river.

nodes.title: Trit(a)ia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B2 Trit(a)ia

nodes.title: Troizen
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, located in the Peloponnese.

nodes.title: Zeus, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G2 Zeus, T.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Zeus Lykaios
nodes.description: The sanctuary of Zeus Lykaios on Mt. Lykaion.

nodes.title: Achaia (spring)
nodes.description: An ancient spring said by Pausanias to be near Dorion in Messenia, its precise location is unknown.

nodes.title: Achaiai
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 unlocated Achaiai

nodes.title: Amymone
nodes.description: A river and homonymous spring mentioned by Pausanias in the vicinity of Lerna. Its precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Arantia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 unlocated Arantia

nodes.title: Arene
nodes.description: A spring that Pausanias places at Lepreon. Its precise location is not known today.

nodes.title: Bryseai
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Laconia whose precise location cannot be determined today. It was mentioned by both Homer and Pausanias. Pausanias places it at the foot of the Taleton Akra, a peak of the Taygetos range.

nodes.title: Chalkis
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Chelydorea (mountain)
nodes.description: An ancient peak in Arcadia (Greece) whose precise location is not known today. Pausanias names it and associates it with Kyllene.

nodes.title: Epaioi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 unlocated Epaioi

nodes.title: Ephyra
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Euoras
nodes.description: An ancient place in the Taygetos mountain range, described by Pausanias as being near a peak called Taleton. Its precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Eurykydeion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 unlocated Eurykydeion

nodes.title: Hagno (spring)
nodes.description: A spring on Mount Lykaion, mentioned by Pausanias and associated in his narrative with the sanctuary of Zeus Lykaios. The exact location of the spring is uncertain today.

nodes.title: Ionaion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 unlocated Ionaion

nodes.title: Keleai
nodes.description: According to Pausanias, Keleai was the site of the tomb of Aras, as well as that of Dysaules of Eleusis.

nodes.title: Kretea
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 unlocated Kretea

nodes.title: Kynortion (mountain)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 unlocated Kynortion M.

nodes.title: Makistia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 unlocated Makistia

nodes.title: Onchiakon
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 unlocated Onchiakon

nodes.title: Phoinikous
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Pontinos (river)
nodes.description: A river of the Argolid, near Lerna, mentioned by Pausanias. Its precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Pontinos (mountain)
nodes.description: A mountain peak mentioned by Pausanias whose precise identity and location can not be determined today. Pausanias places it in Argolis, above Lerna and reports that a ruined sanctuary of Athena Saitis was to be found at its summit in his day.

nodes.title: Taleton Akra
nodes.description: A peak in the Taygetos range, mentioned by Pausanias. Its precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Thaumasion (mountain)
nodes.description: An ancient peak whose precise location is not known, but which Pausanias implies was part of the Mainalion range in Achaia.

nodes.title: Aegina (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Saronic gulf that is surrounded by Attica, Megaris, and Epidaurus.

nodes.title: Agrai
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B3 Agrai

nodes.title: Aigina (settlement)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 A3 Aigina

nodes.title: Anagyrous
nodes.description: Anagyrous was a deme of ancient Attica.

nodes.title: Temple of Aphaia on Aegina
nodes.description: An ancient sanctuary on the island of Aegina, dedicated to the autochthonous deity Aphaia.

nodes.title: Artemis, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 D3 Artemis, T.

nodes.title: Artemis Brauronia
nodes.description: A sacred site in Attica dedicated to Artemis Brauronia. The sanctuary is active from the Middle Bronze Age period, although a gap in activity stretches from the Final Bronze Age to the eighth century B.C.

nodes.title: Athenae
nodes.description: A major Greek city-state and the principal city of Attika. Modern Athens in Greece.

nodes.title: Temple of Athena Skiras on Salamis
nodes.description: This sanctuary, reported by Herodotus, is thought to have been located on the modern Cape Arapis in the northeast part of the island of Salamis, just north of the modern naval base. It is not to be confused with the Temple of Athena Skiras in Phaleron, reported by Pausanias.

nodes.title: Attica
nodes.description: Historical region of Greece, centered on the Attic peninsula.

nodes.title: Boudoron
nodes.description: A settlement on the island of Salamis that was sieged by Cnemus in 429 BC.

nodes.title: Choma?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B3 Choma?

nodes.title: Dekeleia
nodes.description: A deme of Attica located 120 stades from Athens. Dekeleia ceded its autonomy under Theseus to form the city-state of Athens.

nodes.title: Demeter, T.
nodes.description: The Sanctuary of Demeter at Eleusis in Attica was the site of the celebration of the Eleusinian mysteries, observed from the Archaic period to Late Antiquity.

nodes.title: Eleusis
nodes.description: Eleusis, located some 22 km west of Athens, was the site of the cult of Demeter and the sanctuary in which the Eleusinian Mysteries were celebrated from the Bronze Age to the Roman Imperial period.

nodes.title: Eretria
nodes.description: Eretria was an ancient polis located in Euboea.

nodes.title: Euboicus Sinus
nodes.description: The Gulf of Euboea is an arm of the Aegean Sea.

nodes.title: Hagnous
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C3 Hagnous

nodes.title: Halai Araphenides
nodes.description: A deme of Attica, located on the eastern shore north of Brauron. The site was known in antiquity for its sanctuary dedicated to Artemis Tauropolos.

nodes.title: Halipedon
nodes.description: A swampy plain that was located to the north of the main harbour of the Piraeus.

nodes.title: Herakleion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C2 Herakleion

nodes.title: Hydroussa (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B3 Hydroussa Ins.

nodes.title: Hymettos M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C3 Hymettos M.

nodes.title: Ikarion
nodes.description: An ancient settlement and deme of Attica.

nodes.title: Ilissos (river)
nodes.description: Ilissos fl. is a river of Athens, Greece, that was originally a tributary of the Kifissos River. The Ilissos is now, for the most part, channeled below ground.

nodes.title: Kantharos Limen
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B3 Kantharos Limen

nodes.title: Kikynna?
nodes.description: A deme of ancient Attica that belonged to the phyle of Acamantis.

nodes.title: Kophos Limen
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B3 Kophos Limen

nodes.title: Laureion
nodes.description: A mining region of Attika famous in antiquity for its silver mines. These mines were one of the chief sources of revenue for the Athenian state.

nodes.title: Marathon
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C2 Marathon

nodes.title: Marathonian Pedion
nodes.description: The plain of Marathon.

nodes.title: Mikron Helos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C2 Mikron Helos

nodes.title: Mounichia Limen
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B3 Mounichia Limen

nodes.title: Nemesis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 D2 Nemesis

nodes.title: Oinoe (Marathon)
nodes.description: Attic paralia deme of the phyle of Aiantis.

nodes.title: Paiania Hypenerthen
nodes.description: A deme located to the east of Mt. Hymettus. The site is located on the eastern outskirts of modern Liopesi.

nodes.title: Pallene
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C2 Pallene

nodes.title: Pan kai Nymphai, T.
nodes.description: A small cave located northeast of Vari in Attica, Greece, that was used as a shrine dedicated to Apollo, Pan, and the Nymphs form the sixth to second centuries BC.

nodes.title: Patroklou Charax (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C4 Patroklou Charax Ins.

nodes.title: Peiraieus/Piraeus
nodes.description: The ancient, fortified port settlement (and deme) of ancient Athens.

nodes.title: Pentelikon/Brilessos (mountain)
nodes.description: Pentelikon/Brilessos is a mountain to the northeast of Athens that was famous for its fine-grained marble.

nodes.title: Phabra (island)
nodes.description: The island of Fleves in the Saronic Gulf.

nodes.title: Phaleron Limen
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B3 Phaleron Limen

nodes.title: Phaleron
nodes.description: Phalerum was a port of ancient Athens, located approximately 5 km southwest of the Acropolis of Athens, on the Saronic Gulf.

nodes.title: Phreatto?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B3 Phreatto?

nodes.title: Plakoto (settlement)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B2 Plakoto

nodes.title: Plakoto fort
nodes.description: Described by Ober as a "signal tower and small fortification", Plakoto fort is situated at the northern edge of the Thriasian plain.

nodes.title: Temple of Poseidon at Sounion
nodes.description: The hexastyle temple of Poseidon at Sounion was built ca. 444-440 B.C. atop the ruins of an Archaic period temple.

nodes.title: Probalinthos
nodes.description: An ancient deme of Athens in the plain of Marathon.

nodes.title: Prospalta
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C3 Prospalta

nodes.title: Psyttaleia (island)
nodes.description: An island located in the Saronic Gulf.

nodes.title: Rhamnous
nodes.description: Rhamnous was an ancient settlement of Attica adjacent to the Euboean Strait.

nodes.title: Salamis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B3 Salamis

nodes.title: Salamis (island)
nodes.description: Salamis is the largest island of the Saronic Gulf.

nodes.title: Soros
nodes.description: The tumulus (burial mound) of the Athenian dead at Marathon.

nodes.title: Sounion
nodes.description: The fortified port settlement at Sounion served the Athenian grain ships originating in Euboea and was the site of the sanctuary of Poseidon, among others.

nodes.title: Tanagra
nodes.description: Tanagra was an ancient settlement of Boeotia.

nodes.title: Tetrapolis
nodes.description: A district of northeastern Attica that included the cities of Marathon, Probalinthus, Tricorythus, and Oenoe.

nodes.title: Thorikos
nodes.description: Thorikos was a deme of Attika. A significant Mycenaean prescence existed at the site during the Bronze Age.

nodes.title: Thymaitadai
nodes.description: Ancient deme-site in the city of Athens, located in modern Keratsini, a western suburb of Piraeus.

nodes.title: Trikorynthos
nodes.description: Trikorynthos was an ancient deme of Attica.

nodes.title: Vari
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C3 Vari

nodes.title: Zea Limen
nodes.description: The main naval harbor of the Peiraeus with 196 ship sheds.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C4 unnamed fort (on Patroklou Charax)

nodes.title: Akte Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B3 Akte Pr.

nodes.title: Eetioneia Pr.
nodes.description: A fortified promontory located on the western side of the main port of Piraeus.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C3 unnamed quarry group (on Hymettos M.)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An mine or quarry from a group on Pentelikon M.

nodes.title: Mine of Laureion
nodes.description: An Athenian lead or silver mine

nodes.title: Makra Teiche
nodes.description: The Makra Teiche or "Long Walls" of Athens were built in the middle of the fifth century B.C. and connected Athens to its ports at Piraeus and Phalerum. They were destroyed by the Spartans after the Athenian surrender in 403 B.C., and rebuilt during the beginning of the Corinthian War, which started in 395 B.C. The walls were ultimately destroyed by Sulla during his siege against Athens in 86 B.C.

nodes.title: Aulon
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 unlocated Aulon

nodes.title: Bambideios
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 unlocated Bambideios

nodes.title: Drymos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 unlocated Drymos

nodes.title: Hyperakria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 unlocated Hyperakria

nodes.title: Antinoeion at Hadrian's Villa
nodes.description: A sacred precinct at the western end of Villa Hadriani, comprising two temples at opposite (north and south) ends of a plaza or garden, and (on the western edge of this complex) a small colonnaded hemicycle. Here, Hadrian may have planned to build a large, semi-circular temple-tomb for Antinous, in place of which his successors built the colonnaded hemicycle.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Aphrodite Paphia
nodes.description: A major sanctuary to Aphrodite on Cyprus; activity is found as early as the 3rd millennium BCE.

nodes.title: Public Bath of Pella
nodes.description: The Public Bath at Pella is a bathing complex constructed and continuously renovated between the 4th and the 1st centuries BCE.

nodes.title: Persian and Hellenistic Administrative Building (PHAB), Tel Kedesh
nodes.description: The Persian and Hellenistic Administrative Building was constructed at Tel Kedesh by the Persians in the mid-4th century BCE and was in use through the middle Hellenistic Period (around 143 BCE).

nodes.title: Grove of Asklepios at Kos
nodes.description: Mentioned in ancient sources, this sacred grove in the ancient sanctuary of Asklepios located on the Aegean island of Kos cannot be precisely located today.

nodes.title: Funerary Chamber of Manlia Felicitas
nodes.description: A subterranean funerary chamber with three frescoes walls depicting animal and vegetal life, located around the third mile of the Via Appia.

nodes.title: Polygonal wall of Signia
nodes.description: The circuit wall of ancient Signia realized in polygonal masonry.

nodes.title: Santi Quattro Coronati
nodes.description: Santi Quattro Coronati is an early Christian basilica on Rome's Caelian Hill begun by Pope Miltiades in the fourth century A.D.

nodes.title: Sobek temple, Qaşr Qārūn
nodes.description: A Ptolemaic temple to the god Sobek.

nodes.title: Northwest Palace at Kalhu
nodes.description: An impressive and ornately-decorated palace constructed at Kalḫu (modern Nimrud, biblical Calah) by the ninth-century-BC Assyrian ruler Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC), likely completed between 865 and 869 BC. This multi-winged palatial complex served as the primary residence and chief administrative center of the Assyrian Empire until Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) moved the imperial capital to Dūr-Šarrukīn in 706 BC. The Northwest Palace, the name given to it by its excavators (since it was built in the northwestern part of Kalḫu’s citadel), remained in use until the very end of the Assyrian Empire (612 BC). The southern half of the building also functioned as the burial place of prominent royal women, including Mullissu-mukannišat-Ninua, the wife of Ashurnasirpal and the mother of Shalmaneser III.

nodes.title: Stonehenge
nodes.description: An ancient formation of stones set in a field near Salisbury (Wiltshire County, England).

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Segobriga
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Segobriga dates to the Flavian period. It measures approximately 75 by 65 meters and could seat 5,500 spectators.

nodes.title: Arch of Augustus at Aosta
nodes.description: The Arch of Augustus at Aosta is a commemorative arch dedicated to Augustus ca. 25 BC following victories over the Salassi.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheatre, Charterhouse
nodes.description: An amphitheater stood to the west of the lead mining settlement at Charterhouse Roman Town.

nodes.title: Roman civil amphitheater at Carnuntum
nodes.description: Located outside the city wall, the Roman amphitheater at Carnuntum dates to the later second century. It could accommodate some 13,000 spectators. The amphitheater likely went out of use by the fourth century.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Lupia(e)
nodes.description: The precise date of the Roman theater at Lecce is uncertain, but it is generally assigned to the Augustan period.

nodes.title: Roman Amphitheater at Mérida
nodes.description: The Amphitheatre of Mérida was inaugurated in 8 B.C.

nodes.title: Roman Circus at Mérida
nodes.description: The Roman Circus at Mérida dates ca. 20 B.C.

nodes.title: Aquincum Military Amphitheater
nodes.description: The Aquincum Military Amphitheater dates to the reign of Antoninus Pius.

nodes.title: Diavolino II tomb
nodes.description: An Etruscan tomb of the seventh century B.C.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Fiesole
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Fiesole dates to the first century.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Falerii
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Falerii was excavated in 1829.

nodes.title: Falerii Novi amphitheater
nodes.description: The Falerii Novi amphitheater is located north of the city walls.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Vendeuil-Caply
nodes.description: The larger of the two Roman theaters at Vendeuil-Caply was located at the northwest angle of the cardo and the decumanus.

nodes.title: Theater at Philippi
nodes.description: The initial phase of the Theater at Philippi dates to just after 356 B.C. when Philip II conquered the city.

nodes.title: Temple of Apollo at Metropolis
nodes.description: A peripteral Doric temple built in the mid-6th c. BCE and destroyed by fire in the 2nd c. BCE. The temple faces east, and was built of mudbrick on foundations of local sandstone, with sandstone column drums and a terracotta roof. A 4th c. BCE dedicatory inscription found in the cella attests the worship of Apollo. The structure was discovered in 1994 following the activity of looters.

nodes.title: Temple of Jupiter, Damascus
nodes.description: The Temple of Jupiter in Damascus was begun during the rule of Augustus and completed during the rule of Constantius II.

nodes.title: The Great Altar at Pergamon
nodes.description: A monumental altar built during the reign of king Eumenes II.

nodes.title: Temple of Trajan at Pergamon
nodes.description: The Temple of Trajan at Pergamon, also referred to as the Traianeum, was dedicated to Trajan and Zeus Philios and completed during the reign of Hadrian.

nodes.title: Palace of Diocletian
nodes.description: A third century A.D. fortified palace built by the emperor Diocletian.

nodes.title: Church of Panagia Chalkeon
nodes.description: An eleventh century A.D. Byzantine church in Thessaloniki.

nodes.title: Capitolium of Brixia
nodes.description: The Capitolium of Brixia was built in A.D. 73.

nodes.title: Sultan Kala
nodes.description: A fortified area at Merv covering some 400 hectares.

nodes.title: Erk Kala
nodes.description: Erk Kala, founded in the sixth century B.C., was at the center of Merv.

nodes.title: Qatna
nodes.description: A city in western Syria first settled in the Early Bronze Age III (ca. 2700-2600 BCE). In the Middle Bronze Age (2000-1600 BCE), it became a major trading center and the capital of a regional kingdom. In the Late Bronze Age Qatna the city became a vassal of first the Mitanni Kingdom, then the Neo-Hittite Empire and Egypt. The city's acropolis was abandoned in the Late Bronze Age I, though the surrounding area remained inhabited. It was resettled in the 10th century BCE as part of the Aramaean kingdom of Hamath, but was sacked by the army of Sargon II in 720 and ultimately abandoned in the 6th century BCE.

nodes.title: Alaca Höyük
nodes.description: A Neolithic and Hittite settlement located to the northeast of Boğazkale.

nodes.title: Hattusa
nodes.description: The Late Bronze Age capital of the Hittite empire (near modern Boğazkale in Turkey). The site was enrolled as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1986.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Salamis/Konstantia
nodes.description: Salamis remained an important city of Cyprus during the Roman period and the theater is one part of a complex of monumental architecture there.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Trier
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Trier dates to the reign of Antoninus Pius and was renovated under Constantius Chlorus. The arena measures ca. 71 x 47.5 meters.

nodes.title: Porta Nigra
nodes.description: The so-called "Porta Nigra" is a surviving Roman city gate that dates to ca. A.D. 186-200. It was enlisted as part of the "Roman Monuments, Cathedral of St. Peter and Church of Our Lady in Trier" UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1986.

nodes.title: Temple of Trajan at Italica
nodes.description: A sanctuary dedicated to Trajan in the 'urbs nova' of Italica that flourished under the patronage of Hadrian.

nodes.title: Haltwhistle Burn Roman Fortlet and Camp
nodes.description: Site of Roman fortlet and temporary camp. The fortlet guarded the crossing of the Burn by the Stanegate. It pre-dates the construction of Hadrian's Wall, which passes 0.5 km to the north.

nodes.title: Caer y Twr
nodes.description: Caer y Twr is the site of a Roman period hill fort in Anglesey, Wales.

nodes.title: Royal Palace of Qatna
nodes.description: A large palace constructed in about 1600 BCE in Qatna, an important Bronze Age city in Syria.

nodes.title: Royal Hypogeum at Qatna
nodes.description: Tomb VI at Qatna, known as the Royal Hypogeum, is a tomb complex located approximately 12 meters below the Royal Palace of Qatna. The tomb consists of a long corridor and 4 burial chambers, and contained approximately 20 burials.

nodes.title: Quirinal Hill
nodes.description: One of the hills of Rome, comprised of several smaller peaks. According to tradition its first inhabitants were Titus Tatius and the Sabines; during the Republic the hill was a mostly residential area.

nodes.title: Doric temple of Segesta
nodes.description: The Doric temple of Segesta is an incomplete (6 x 14) temple of the Doric order begun in the 420s B.C.

nodes.title: Kothon
nodes.description: The Kothon harbor is an artificial port basin of the Punic phase of the island, dating to the sixth century B.C.

nodes.title: Queen's pyramid
nodes.description: There are three satellite pyramids, typically referred to as "Queen's pyramids", associated with the pyramid of Menkaure on the Giza plateau.

nodes.title: Porta Gemina at Asculum
nodes.description: A city gate of the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Asculum
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Asculum was discovered during excavations in 1932. The structure dates to the first century A.D.

nodes.title: Forum of Segobriga
nodes.description: The Forum of Segobriga is traditionally dated to the early Iulio-Claudian period when Segobriga became a municipium.

nodes.title: Theater at Segobriga
nodes.description: Construction of the Roman Theater at Segobriga began under Tiberius and was completed during the Flavian period.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Rusellae
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Rusellae dates to the first century.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater of Martigny
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater of Martigny likely dates to the reign of Trajan.

nodes.title: Porta Praetoria at Aosta
nodes.description: A gate of the city wall of the Augustan colony, ca. 25 B.C.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Aosta
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Aosta likely dates to the first century A.D. Its remains are englobed within Medieval structures.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Aosta
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Aosta dates ca. 25 B.C.

nodes.title: Heidentor
nodes.description: A triumphal monument built at Carnuntum between A.D. 354 and 361, perhaps by Constantius II.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Carthago Nova/Col. Urbs Iulia
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Cartagena dates to the first century.

nodes.title: Lucera Castle
nodes.description: A castle originally built by Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor in AD 1233.

nodes.title: Monumental entrance arch at Mérida
nodes.description: The so-called "Arch of Trajan".

nodes.title: Aquincum Civil Amphitheater
nodes.description: The Aquincum Civil Amphitheater is the smaller of two Roman amphitheaters located in Budapest, Hungary. It was built between ca. A.D. 250 and 300.

nodes.title: Arch of Septimius Severus at Lepcis Magna
nodes.description: The Arch of Septimius Severus at Lepcis Magna dates ca. A.D. 203.

nodes.title: Basilica of Septimius Severus
nodes.description: The Basilica of Septimius Severus belongs to the Severan Forum at Lepcis Magna.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at *Moridunum
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Moridunum is located in Carmarthenshire. It is one of only seven surviving Roman amphitheaters in Britain.

nodes.title: Pietrera tomb
nodes.description: An Etruscan tholos tomb of the seventh century B.C. at Vetulonia.

nodes.title: Mura dell Arce
nodes.description: The so-called "Mura dell Arce" of Vetulonia served as the sixth- and fifth-century B.C. fortifications of Etruscan Vetulonia. These are massive walls built in megalithic technique using limestone.

nodes.title: Belvedere tomb
nodes.description: An Etruscan tomb of the seventh century B.C.

nodes.title: Pian di Civita, Tarquinii
nodes.description: The Pian di Civita was the ancient urban area of Tarquinia.

nodes.title: Tomb of the Shields and Chairs, Caere
nodes.description: The so-called Tomb of the Shields and Chairs at Caere dates ca. 520 - 500 B.C. The organization of this tomb is similar to that of the Tomb of the Capitals and the Tomb of the Cornice. It has a short dromos and a large vestibule. In the vestibule are two seats carved from the tuff bedrock as well as a series of hanging shields carved in relief.

nodes.title: Tomb of the Five Chairs, Caere
nodes.description: An Etruscan tomb at Caere dated ca. 625-600 B.C.

nodes.title: Porta di Giove, Falerii
nodes.description: A Roman gate in the city's defensive wall.

nodes.title: Theater of Tegea
nodes.description: The remains of the Hellenistic theater of Tegea are to be found beneath the tenth century A.D. Middle Byzantine church of Palaia Episkopi.

nodes.title: Acropolis of Circeii
nodes.description: The polygonal masonry walls of the Acropolis of Circeii enclose an area of approximately two hectares. The walls likely date to the middle republican period.

nodes.title: Tuvixeddu Punic necropolis
nodes.description: A Punic necropolis near Caralis in Sardinia.

nodes.title: Pozzuolo necropolis
nodes.description: A necropolis of Etruscan Veii.

nodes.title: Santa Maria in Cosmedin
nodes.description: A minor basilica church in Rome, Italy. Tradition holds that the church was founded in the sixth century to serve the Greek community at Rome. The beginnings of the present edifice lie in the eighth century.

nodes.title: San Giorgio in Velabro
nodes.description: A church dedicated to St. George located in Rome's Velabrum. Legend connects the church's location with the spot where the Roman she wolf found the abandoned twins, Romulus and Remus.

nodes.title: Hercules Cubans
nodes.description: A shrine that is located on the Tiber's right bank, according to the Regionary Catalogues.

nodes.title: Temple of Poseidon at Isthmia
nodes.description: The Poseidon sanctuary at Isthmia lies 16 km to the east of Corinth. The initial phase belongs to the seventh century BC, although the sanctuary was destroyed ca. 470 BC and rebuilt in 440 B.C.

nodes.title: Graeco-Roman theater at Isthmia
nodes.description: A theater founded ca. 390 B.C. with subsequent Hellenistic and Roman renovations.

nodes.title: Basilica Manastirine
nodes.description: An important extra-mural Christian site at Solina. The site includes the basilica and the cemetery of Manastirine, associated with a Christian martyr.

nodes.title: Shunet ez Zebib
nodes.description: A large mudbrick structure located at Abydos in Upper Egypt that dates to the Second Dynasty (ca. 2700 B.C.) of ancient Egypt.

nodes.title: Osireion
nodes.description: The Osireion at Abydos is located to the rear of the temple of Seti I. It is an integral part of Seti I's funeral complex and was built to resemble an 18th Dynasty Valley of the Kings tomb.

nodes.title: Cybele sanctuary
nodes.description: A temple sacred to Cybele located at Neuss am Rhein.

nodes.title: Temple of Demeter
nodes.description: A Doric temple ascribed to Demeter with origins in the fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: Cava d’Ispica
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F5 Cava d’Ispica

nodes.title: Cave di Barone
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 B3 Cave di Barone

nodes.title: Cave di Cusa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 B3 Cave di Cusa

nodes.title: Cena
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C4 Cena

nodes.title: Centuripae
nodes.description: A city of the indigenous Sikels, Centuripae allied itself with Athens during the expedition against Syracuse.

nodes.title: Cephaloedium
nodes.description: An city founded on an imposing promontory on the northern coast of Sicily.

nodes.title: *Chalae?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 *Chalae?

nodes.title: Charybdis
nodes.description: Charybdis was a sea monster that was rationalized in the form of a whirlpool located in the Strait of Messina.

nodes.title: Chrysas, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E3 Chrysas, T.

nodes.title: Cignana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Cignana

nodes.title: Cittadella
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G5 Cittadella

nodes.title: Colle Madore
nodes.description: Colle Madore is an archaeological site connected with the Sicanians.

nodes.title: Colle Rotondo
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C4 Colle Rotondo

nodes.title: Cosconiana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Cosconiana

nodes.title: Cossyra (settlement)
nodes.description: A harbor settlement on the island of the same name.

nodes.title: Pantelleria (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Strait of Sicily with human occupation dating back at least 35,000 years, Pantelleria has evidence for Bronze Age, Punic, Roman, Medieval, and modern phases. The Romans first acquired the island in 255 B.C. They called it Cossyra.

nodes.title: Cozzo Cicirello
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Cozzo Cicirello

nodes.title: Cozzo Matrice
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E3 Cozzo Matrice

nodes.title: Cozzo Mususino
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E3 Cozzo Mususino

nodes.title: Cozzo Sannita
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D3 Cozzo Sannita

nodes.title: Cozzo Spolentino
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Cozzo Spolentino

nodes.title: Crimisus (river)
nodes.description: A river of western Sicily.

nodes.title: Cusumano
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Cusumano

nodes.title: Cyanes Fons
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G4 Cyanes Fons

nodes.title: Cyane (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G4 Cyane fl.

nodes.title: Cyclopum Scopuli Tres
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G3 Cyclopum Scopuli Tres

nodes.title: D(a)edalium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 D(a)edalium

nodes.title: Dianae Fons?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F5 Dianae Fons?

nodes.title: Didyme (island)
nodes.description: One of the Aeolian Islands with Greek occupation from the fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: Drepanum
nodes.description: Drepanum, the modern Trapani, Sicily, is an ancient port city. The archaeological remains of the ancient city are meager. During the First Punic War, Hamilcar fortified the site. The Roman Republic lost a naval engagement near Drepanum in 249 B.C. but then prevailed in the battle of the Egadi islands in 241 B.C. The city was likely of censorial status thereafter.

nodes.title: Durrueli di Realmonte
nodes.description: A Roman villa rustica dating to the first century A.D. located in the Punta Grande beach, in the territory of Realmonte, province of Agrigento, Sicily.

nodes.title: Eknomos?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Eknomos?

nodes.title: Elymi
nodes.description: The Elymians were an indigenous people inhabiting western Sicily during the Bronze Age and the first millennium BC.

nodes.title: Emporion Segestanon
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 B2 Emporion Segestanon

nodes.title: Engyon
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F3 Engyon

nodes.title: Entella
nodes.description: Entella was an ancient city in the interior of Sicily, situated on the left bank of the river Hypsas.

nodes.title: Epipolai
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G4 Epipolai

nodes.title: Erikodes/Ericusa (island)
nodes.description: One of the Aeolian Islands; the island is the site of the extinct Montagnola volcano.

nodes.title: Eryx
nodes.description: An ancient, indigenous settlement of western Sicily, likely inhabited by the Elymians.

nodes.title: Eryx M.
nodes.description: Mount Eryx is a mountain of western Sicily. The mountain is mentioned by numerous ancient authors; notably in the Aeneid Virgil discusses it in relation to Venus Erycina.

nodes.title: Euboia?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F4 Euboia?

nodes.title: Euryelos
nodes.description: A fortress built by Dionysius the Elder 9 km west of Syracuse, in the modern hamlet of Belvedere (Sicily).

nodes.title: Feudo Nobile
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Feudo Nobile

nodes.title: Fiumedinisi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G2 Fiumedinisi

nodes.title: Fontana Calda di Butera
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Fontana Calda di Butera

nodes.title: Francavilla di Sicilia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G3 Francavilla di Sicilia

nodes.title: Gaulos (island)
nodes.description: The island called Gozo in modern times, part of the country of Malta.

nodes.title: Gela
nodes.description: A Greek colony of Sicily founded by Rhodians and Cretans ca. 688 B.C. The oikists were the Rhodian Antiphemos and the Cretan Entimos.

nodes.title: Gela(s) (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Gela(s) fl.

nodes.title: Gemelli Colles
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D3 Gemelli Colles

nodes.title: Geraci
nodes.description: A fourth century A.D. Roman villa with mosaic pavements. The villa may have extended to some 10,000 square meters in area.

nodes.title: Roman Villa at Għajn Tuffieħa, Malta
nodes.description: Ruins at this ancient site include a Roman-era bath complex and extensive mosaics. Its ancient name is unknown.

nodes.title: Gioiosa Vecchia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F2 Gioiosa Vecchia

nodes.title: Grancifone
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Grancifone

nodes.title: Grattauli
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Grattauli

nodes.title: Grotta Regina
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C2 Grotta Regina

nodes.title: Halaesa
nodes.description: Halaesa is located on the north coast of Sicily between between Kalakta and Kephaloidion. The city was founded in 403 B.C. by Archonides of Herbita. The city sided with Rome during the First Punic War and was made "libera et immunis". By the Augustan period it had become a municipium.

nodes.title: Halicyae
nodes.description: A town of the Elymians located between Lilybaeum and Entella.

nodes.title: Haluntium
nodes.description: An ancient settlement located between Tyndaris and Calacte. Some authors ascribe the foundation of the site to the Acarnanians.

nodes.title: Halykos (river)
nodes.description: The Halykos (modern Platani) is the fifth longest river in Sicily.

nodes.title: Santa Cristina
nodes.description: A nuragic sanctuary centered on a sacred well that was in use from ca. 1200 to 700 BC.

nodes.title: Temple of the Oxus
nodes.description: The Temple of the Oxus is a Seleucid-era temple situated within the citadel of Takhti-Sangin, a Graeco-Bactrian town between the Vakhsh and Panj rivers.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Murtas
nodes.description: A single-tower nuraghe dating between 1500 and 1200 B.C.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Perda su Luaxiu
nodes.description: A nuraghe located near Quartu Sant'Elena.

nodes.title: Cadmea
nodes.description: The acropolis / fortress of Thebes. The fortress was destroyed by Alexander the Great in 335 B.C. and later rebuilt by Cassander in 316 B.C.

nodes.title: Temple of Artemis at Sardis
nodes.description: A large temple dedicated to Artemis at the city of Sardis in western Asia Minor. A sanctuary to Artemis was constructed on the site during the Persian Era (ca. 547-334 BCE), and construction on a new temple on the site began during the third century BCE. The temple was never fully completed. A small church was built on part of the site in the 5th century CE, but the structure declined from the 7th century onwards, and many of its stones were reused or burned.

nodes.title: Mithraeum at Poetovio
nodes.description: The third of five shrines sacred to Mithras found near the site of Poetovio.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Sopron
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Sopron dates to the later first century A.D.

nodes.title: Halberg Mithraeum
nodes.description: A natural cave in the side of the Halberg hill was enlarged for the use of the Mithras cult.

nodes.title: Temple of Athena at Sounion
nodes.description: The Temple of Athena at Sounion (ca. 470 B.C.) with its L-shaped colonnade was built on the site of an earlier temple (sixth century B.C.) at the same location.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Phrontis(?)
nodes.description: The site of a shrine assumed to honor to the hero Phrontis.

nodes.title: Milecastle 37 (Housesteads)
nodes.description: One of the milecastles along Hadrian's Wall, approximately 400 meters to the west of Housesteads Roman fort (Vercovicium)

nodes.title: Theban necropolis
nodes.description: Collective name for the complex of tombs and temples on the western bank of the Nile, opposite the city of Thebes/Luxor. The necropolis was used for royal and elite burials throughout the Pharaonic period.

nodes.title: Gaziantep
nodes.description: Gaziantep, also referred to as Antep, is located in southeastern Turkey. The site has a long history of settlement that begins in the Neolithic period. The site has a significant Hittite presence. Some scholars suggest it is the site of the Hellenistic city of Antiochia ad Taurum.

nodes.title: Sheikh Abd el-Qurna
nodes.description: A necropolis located on the West Bank at Thebes in Upper Egypt that is now part of the archaeological area of Deir el-Bahari.

nodes.title: Nizzetti
nodes.description: A hamlet in Sicily, located near Acireale, that is the findspot of antiquities possibly related to the ancient settlement of Acium.

nodes.title: Mausoleum of Helena
nodes.description: An ancient tomb located on the ancient Via Labicana (now along the Via Casilina) that was built by Constantine I and used as the tomb for his mother, Helena.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Is Paras
nodes.description: A trilobate nuragic complex of the fifteenth century BC.

nodes.title: Phalarium
nodes.description: A fortress named after Phalaris, a tyrant of Acragas and located near the Himera River.

nodes.title: Kom el-Dikka
nodes.description: Part of the ancient city of Alexandria where the Roman theater and baths are located.

nodes.title: Church of Saint Martin at Moissac
nodes.description: A Christian church built, at least in part, atop the ruins of a Gallo-Roman building that include a hypocaust.

nodes.title: Porta Trasimena
nodes.description: The Porta Trasimena or Arco di San Berni is a third century B.C. gate in the Etruscan wall of Perusia.

nodes.title: Suburbium Toletanum
nodes.description: The location of the Late Roman and Visigothic suburbium beyond the Roman circus. Transition from suburban villas to a large-scale Visigothic expansion, which included various churches and the Praetorium, or Royal Palace. Destroyed during the ninth century. Excavations carried out in the early 2000s.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Poddinosa
nodes.description: A single-tower nuraghe located near Dorgali (NU).

nodes.title: Stadium-garden at Hadrian's Villa
nodes.description: A garden at the Villa Hadriani imitating the shape of a stadium, situated between the Three Exedras' Hall (to the west) and the Winter Palace (to the east), with a semi-circular nymphaeum at its southern end.

nodes.title: Fundus Albianus
nodes.description: An estate located in the Pagus Ambitrebius mentioned on the Tabula alimentaria Traianea.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Lupia(e)
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Lupia(e), modern Lecce, was built in the late first and early second centuries A.D.

nodes.title: So-called Area X in Berenike
nodes.description: The ruins of a small building (possibly first century AD) with a shrine, in the archaeological site of Sidi Khiribech, in Berenike. According to some archaeologists, it might have been connected to the adjacent Area A, and constitute together a single unit. In other interpretations, it is an independent sacred space.

nodes.title: Church in Sidi Khiribech
nodes.description: Ruins of a church likely built around the fifth century AD, on the summit of the low hill of Sidi Khiribech in Berenike. The character of the building and its position has suggested to some archaeologists a defensive as well as a religious purpose.

nodes.title: Irno (river)
nodes.description: The Irno river is a river of Campania that flows into the Tyrrhenian Sea. While its ancient name is unknown, the river valley is the site of first millennium B.C. settlement and also the site of numerous clay beds exploited for pottery production.

nodes.title: Temple of Ba'al at Palmyra
nodes.description: Temple of Ba'al in the ancient city of Palmyra. Coordinates determined by eye in Google Earth in November 2012, following description in UNESCO World Heritage List.

nodes.title: Agora of Palmyra
nodes.description: Agora of the Ancient City of Palmyra. Coordinates determined by eye in Google Earth in November 2012, following description in UNESCO World Heritage List.

nodes.title: Irru
nodes.description: A nuragic shrine with a sacred well.

nodes.title: Manor House Roman villa
nodes.description: The site of a Roman corridor villa with a separate bathhouse. Three phases dating from the late first century AD into the fourth century. It possibly forms part of a complex with the villa uncovered ca. 250 meters to the south and east.

nodes.title: Archaic compound (Gabii)
nodes.description: An archaic compound with evidence for ritual dining that has been identified by its excavators as a "regia".

nodes.title: Madhukeshwara temple
nodes.description: A Shiva temple at Banavasi in India whose foundation may date as early as the 7th century CE.

nodes.title: Greek Theater at Syracuse
nodes.description: Rock-cut theater of Greek form at Syracuse, Sicily, probably in use from the 5th c. BC to the Late Roman period.

nodes.title: Lagash
nodes.description: Lagash was an important Sumerian city of the late third millennium B.C.

nodes.title: Regio III, Pompeii
nodes.description: The so-called Regio III, a largely unexcavated archaeological subdivision located in the northeastern section of Pompeii, contains a mix of residential and commercial structures.

nodes.title: Abbey of Monte Cassino
nodes.description: A multi-period hilltop settlement with evidence for ancient terrace construction that now supports an abbey of the Benedictine order.

nodes.title: Basilica at Aspendos
nodes.description: The remains of a Roman Basilica at Aspendos.

nodes.title: Parco archeologico Griso-Laboccetta
nodes.description: An Archaic to Hellenistic sanctuary sacred to Demeter.

nodes.title: Church of St. George
nodes.description: One of of a group of eleven rock-hewn monolithic churches located in Lalibela, a city in the Amhara Region of Ethiopia. The church likely dates to the twelfth or thirteenth century.

nodes.title: Ekklesiasterion/Theater at Metapontum
nodes.description: A building complex located in the city's agora, the Ekklesiasterion/Theater is dated ca. 625-300 B.C.

nodes.title: Santa Maria Sopra Minerva
nodes.description: A first century B.C. temple dedicated to Minerva by Gneus Caestius and Titus Caesius Priscus, who were two of the Assisi's quattuorviri. The temple was converted to the church of Santa Maria Sopra Minerva in 1539.

nodes.title: Basilica of St. Francis of Assisi
nodes.description: A papal basilica begun ca. AD 1228.

nodes.title: Gallo-Roman amphitheater at Montbouy
nodes.description: The Gallo-Roman amphitheater at Montbouy dates to the early Imperial period.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Luna
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Luna was built in the second century, perhaps during the Antonine period.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Lixus
nodes.description: The ruins of a Roman amphitheater at Lixus, one of only a few such structures known in Berber North Africa.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Mactaris
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Mactaris dates to the second century.

nodes.title: Capitolium at Mactaris
nodes.description: The Capitolium temple at Mactaris likely dates to the reign of Marcus Aurelius.

nodes.title: Palace of Mausolos at Bodrum
nodes.description: The fortified Palace of Mausolos at Bodrum.

nodes.title: Luxor Temple
nodes.description: An ancient Egyptian temple initially built ca. 1400 B.C.

nodes.title: Stifone
nodes.description: Evidence of a Roman shipyard has been discovered at the locality of Stifone within the comune of Le Mole of the town of Narni. This shpiyard was connected to an artificial canal dug adjacent to the river Nera.

nodes.title: Spring south of Djebel Zid
nodes.description: Unlabeled feature captured from the Barrington Atlas

nodes.title: Mastaba of Ptahshepses at Abusir
nodes.description: The mastaba-style tomb of Ptahshepses, vizier to the Fifth Dynasty Pharaoh Nyuserre Ini. Following the intial elite burials in the Old Kingdom, the mastaba became a funerary site for new burials during the Late Period.

nodes.title: Bouleuterion at Aspendos
nodes.description: The Bouleuterion at Aspendos dates to the early second century.

nodes.title: Pyramid of Khafre
nodes.description: The Pyramid of Khafre is the second-largest of the ancient Egyptian Pyramids at Giza and served as the tomb of the pharaoh Khafre (Chefren), of the Fourth Dynasty of ancient Egypt.

nodes.title: Odeon
nodes.description: Unknown

nodes.title: Stadium
nodes.description: The stadium at Aphrodisias dates to the later first century A.D. and is thought to be part of a comprehensive program of monumental construction undertaken at the site. The stadium's form is unusual and scholars assign it to a category referred to as στάδιον ἀμφιθέατρον (an "amphitheatral stadium").

nodes.title: Hadrianic Baths
nodes.description: Unknown

nodes.title: Ancient Greek theater at Palazzolo Acreide
nodes.description: The theater at ancient Akrai.

nodes.title: Shore Temple of Mahabalipuram
nodes.description: The so-called "Shore Temple" of Mahabalipuram is a granite-built tomb at the Mahabalipuram UNESCO World Heritage Site. It dates to the eighth century CE.

nodes.title: Rhotanos (river)
nodes.description: The Tavignano is a river of Corsica that flows into the Tyrrhenian Sea near Aléria.

nodes.title: Sacrum Pr. (promontory)
nodes.description: An ancient cape, identified with the Corsican islets now known as the Îles Finocchiarola, which extend from a small, northeastern promontory of the island into the Tyrrhenian Sea.

nodes.title: Sardoum Mare
nodes.description: The name given by the ancients to the part of the Mediterranean sea adjoining the island of Sardinia on the west and south.

nodes.title: Soubasanoi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 D3 Soubasanoi

nodes.title: Titianoi
nodes.description: A people settled on the coast of south-western Corsica (area of modern Tizzano).

nodes.title: Titianos Limen
nodes.description: A settlement on the coast of south-western Corsica, in the territory of the Titianoi.

nodes.title: Vanacini
nodes.description: The name of an ancient people inhabiting the northeastern portion of Corscia

nodes.title: An unnamed bridge
nodes.description: A bridge located north of Usel(l)is in western Sardinia

nodes.title: Decimomannu Roman bridge
nodes.description: The remains of a stone, arched Roman bridge at Decimomannu, to the west of Assemini, Sardinia. Three of the original six arches survive today. The bridge may originally have been as much as 160 meters in length. R.J. Rowland considered it to be of Iulio-Claudian date.

nodes.title: Unnamed Roman bridge
nodes.description: An unnamed bridge, located northeast of ‘Luguidunec’.

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge (E Fundus Moddol(...))
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B3 unnamed bridge (E Fundus Moddol(...))

nodes.title: Unnamed Roman bridge
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B3 unnamed bridge (NW Ussana)

nodes.title: Unnamed quarry
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B1 unnamed quarry (on Errebantion Akron)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 unnamed quarry (W Terr'e Frucca)

nodes.title: Fundus Palladii
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 unlocated Fundus Palladii

nodes.title: Heraion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 unlocated Heraion

nodes.title: Iolaia
nodes.description: The name of an indigenous tribe of Sardinia as reported by ancient authors including Pausanias.

nodes.title: Skapitanoi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 unlocated Skapitanoi

nodes.title: Aous (river)
nodes.description: A river that flows from the Pindus mountains to the Adriatic Sea; the modern Vjosë or Aoös.

nodes.title: Apollonia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 B3 Apollonia

nodes.title: Carmo
nodes.description: Carmo was a town in Hispania Ulterior.

nodes.title: Carteia/Calpe/Karpessos
nodes.description: A Phoenician and Roman town in Spain located on the Bay of Gibraltar. The site played a strategic role in the Punic Wars, and was given the rights of a Latin colony in 171 BC.

nodes.title: Casal da Várzea
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 B2 Casal da Várzea

nodes.title: Cilniana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 F5 Cilniana

nodes.title: Cilpe/*Lacilbula?
nodes.description: Cilpe/*Lacilbula? was an Ibero-Roman settlement in Baetica.

nodes.title: Corduba/Col. Patricia
nodes.description: Corduba/Col. Patricia (modern Córdoba, Andalusia) is an ancient site where prehistoric, Punic, Roman, Visigothic, and Muslim phases of occupation are known. The city's historic center was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1984.

nodes.title: Ebora
nodes.description: A Roman city with likely Celtic roots and a long, subsequent architectural history, the historic center of modern Évora in Portugal was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 1986.

nodes.title: Emerita Augusta
nodes.description: An ancient settlement (modern Mérida, Spain).

nodes.title: Gadeira/Gades/Col. Augusta Gaditana
nodes.description: Gadeira/Gades/Col. Augusta Gaditana (modern Cadiz, Spain) is an ancient city of Spain and one of the oldest continuously occupied cities of Europe. Its origins may be Phoenician (Gadir (Phoenician: גדר)).

nodes.title: Glaukou? Akra
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 D5 Glaukou? Akra

nodes.title: Herakleios Porthmos/Gaditanum Fretum
nodes.description: The Strait of Gibraltar, a narrow strait that connects the Atlantic Ocean and the Mediterranean Sea and separates Europe from Africa.

nodes.title: Herculis Ins.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 D4 Herculis Ins.

nodes.title: Hispalis/Col. Romula
nodes.description: Hispalis/Col. Romula (modern Seville, Spain).

nodes.title: Ilipa Magna
nodes.description: Ilipa Magna was located on the right bank of the Baetis river. It is now the modern Alcalá del Río. In antiquity it was notable for silver mines located nearby.

nodes.title: Italica
nodes.description: A city in Spain founded in 206 B.C. by Publius Cornelius Scipio Africanus as a site at which to settle Roman soldiers wounded in the Battle of Ilipa.

nodes.title: (Iulia) Myrtilis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 C4 (Iulia) Myrtilis

nodes.title: Kal(l)ipous (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 B3 Kal(l)ipous fl.

nodes.title: Ligustinus (lacus)
nodes.description: The so-called Guadalquivir Marshes (Marismas del Guadalquivir) are a region of wetlands located on the lower Guadalquivir River. In antiquity these wetlands included a lagoon and an estuary known as Lacus Ligustinus. Silting gradually transformed the lake into wetlands.

nodes.title: Londobris (island)
nodes.description: Londobris Ins., the modern Berlenga Grande Island, is the largest of the islands of the Berlengas Archipelago.

nodes.title: Metellinum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 E3 Metellinum

nodes.title: Mirobriga
nodes.description: Miróbriga (also known as Mirobriga Celticorum) is an ancient Roman town located near the village Santiago do Cacém, Portugal. The site shows evidence of Iron Age occupation beginning in the ninth century B.C. and continuing through to the time of the Roman colonization of Lusitania.

nodes.title: Munda (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 F4 Munda fl.

nodes.title: Munda (river)
nodes.description: Munda fl. (Mondego River) is a river of Lusitania.

nodes.title: Norba/Col. Norbensis Caesarina
nodes.description: An Roman settlement, modern Cáceres in Spain.

nodes.title: Olisipo
nodes.description: Olisipo (modern Lisbon, Portugal).

nodes.title: Paisoula
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 D4 Paisoula

nodes.title: Phosphoros/Lux Dubia (sanctuary)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 D5 Phosphoros/Lux Dubia, T.

nodes.title: Proserpina
nodes.description: A Roman-era reservoir and dam northwest of modern Mérida in Spain, which was tapped to supply Emerita Augusta (modern Mérida) via aqueduct.

nodes.title: Regina
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 E3 Regina

nodes.title: Salacia (Imperatoria)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 B3 Salacia (Imperatoria)

nodes.title: Salduba (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 F5 Salduba fl.

nodes.title: Salsum (river)
nodes.description: The Guadajoz river.

nodes.title: Scallabis/Praesidium Iulium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 B2 Scallabis/Praesidium Iulium

nodes.title: Singilis (river)
nodes.description: Singilis fl. (Genil river) is a tributary of the Baetis/Certis fl. (modern Guadalquivir).

nodes.title: Tagus (river)
nodes.description: The Tagus river is the longest river on the Iberian Peninsula.

nodes.title: Tróia
nodes.description: The site of a large Roman town located on the Troia peninsula on the left bank of the Sado river.

nodes.title: Urgapa?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 F4 Urgapa?

nodes.title: Urius (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 D4 Urius fl.

nodes.title: Vettones
nodes.description: Vettones, a pre-Roman Celtic population of the Iberian peninsula.

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct supplying Augusta Emerita
nodes.description: The so-called "Acueducto de los Milagros" (miraculous aqueduct) that supplied Augusta Emerita from the Lago de Proserpina north of the city. A small portion of the impressive aqueduct bridge still stands in Mérida.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 D2 unnamed bridge (at Ad Sorores)

nodes.title: Alcántara Bridge
nodes.description: A six-span stone bridge over the Tagus river, also known as the Puente Trajan.

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge over the river Guadiana near Metellinum
nodes.description: An unnamed Roman bridge over the river Guadiana near Metellinum.

nodes.title: Bardili Turduli
nodes.description: An ancient people of southwest Portugal.

nodes.title: Tema/Thema
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 unlocated Tema/Thema

nodes.title: Gerontis Arx
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 unlocated Gerontis Arx

nodes.title: Acci/Col. Iulia Gemella
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 B4 Acci/Col. Iulia Gemella

nodes.title: Anticaria
nodes.description: An ancient Roman town mentioned in the Antonine Itinerary and by the Ravenna Cosmographer. Modern Antequera in Spain.

nodes.title: La Argentera
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 G2 La Argentera

nodes.title: Aurgi/Orongis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 B4 Aurgi/Orongis

nodes.title: Baliares/Gymnesiae Inss. (Maior et Minor)
nodes.description: Baliares/Gymnesiae Inss. (Maior et Minor) (The Balearic Islands) is an island group of the western Mediterranean Sea, located to the east of the Iberian peninsula. In modern geographical terms, the four largest islands of the group are Majorca, Minorca, Ibiza, and Formentera, but the latter two are also part of the Pityussae island group of antiquity.

nodes.title: Baliaricum Mare
nodes.description: The Balearic Sea or Iberian Sea: coastal waters to the south and east of the Iberian Peninsula.

nodes.title: *Bocchori
nodes.description: *Bocchori was an ancient settlement at the northern extreme of the island of Majorca.

nodes.title: Buñola
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 inset Buñola

nodes.title: Cabanes
nodes.description: The remains of a Roman arch consisting of two columns supported by a square base.

nodes.title: Caesarobriga
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 A2 Caesarobriga

nodes.title: Capraria (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 inset Capraria Ins.

nodes.title: Carpetania
nodes.description: Carpetania is the territory of the Carpetani, a powerful tribe of the Iberian interior that clashed with Hannibal during the Second Punic War.

nodes.title: Carthago Nova/Col. Urbs Iulia
nodes.description: Carthago Nova/Col. Urbs Iulia (modern Cartagena, Spain) was originally an indigenous settlement that was subsequently refounded first as a Punic site Qart Hadasht ("New City") in 228 BC and later as a Roman city.

nodes.title: Castulo
nodes.description: An Ibero-Roman settlement of Baetica that was inhabited beginning in the Neolithic period. It is noted for the silver mines of the Sierra Morena.

nodes.title: Colubraria? (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 F2 Colubraria? Ins.

nodes.title: Colubraria/Ophiussa (island)
nodes.description: Colubraria/Ophiussa Ins. (modern Formentera) is an island of the Balearic Islands in the western Mediterranean Sea.

nodes.title: Palace of Nebuchadnezzar II
nodes.description: The Neo-Babylonian king Nebuchadnezzar II constructed for himself a large and ornately decorated palace, the ruins of which are still visible today. This extensive architectural complex was located in the Kadingirra district of Babylon, which is situated just south of the Ishtar Gate, east of the processional street Ay-ibūr-šabû, north of the Lībil-hengalla canal, and west of the Euphrates River. Several Akkadian inscriptions of Nebuchadnezzar II record the construction of this building.

nodes.title: Khufu's ship
nodes.description: The sealed burial pit adjacent to the Great Pyramid contained a remarkably well preserved Old Kingdom ship that has been interpreted as the solar barge of the pharaoh Khufu.

nodes.title: Colombarone
nodes.description: An archaeological site that preserves remains of a Late Roman settlement along the Via Flaminia.

nodes.title: Herculaneum Gate
nodes.description: The "Herculaneum Gate" was a city gate of Pompeii located at the northern terminus of the Via Consolare. The gate originally incorporated three passageways.

nodes.title: Temple of Portunus
nodes.description: A tetrastyle temple dedicated to the god Portunus and dating to the late second century or early first century BC.

nodes.title: Pyramid of Userkaf
nodes.description: A Fifth Dynasty pyramid at Saqqarah.

nodes.title: Sippar-Amnanum
nodes.description: Sippar-Amnanum, located at modern Tell ed-Der, was an ancient city of the Old Babylonian period and the sister city of Sippar.

nodes.title: Sam'al
nodes.description: A Hittite and Aramaean city located at Zincirli Höyük in the Anti-Taurus mountains. The site appears in Neo-Assyrian sources as Samʾalla and Aramaic texts as šmʿl (also yʾdy). It is identified with the modern site of Zincirli.

nodes.title: Archaic agora of Thasos
nodes.description: The agora of the ancient city. The site was located near the center of the city's shoreline and was surrounded by stoas and public buildings.

nodes.title: Listercombe Bottom
nodes.description: The site of a Roman villa discovered ca. 1760 and excavated in 1930. It lies ca. 2.5 km SE of Chedworth Roman villa.

nodes.title: Barnwood Roman cemetery
nodes.description: Site of Romano-British inhumation and cremation cemetery.

nodes.title: Ermin Street
nodes.description: A branch Roman road (Margary 41) running from Calleva Atrebatum (modern Silchester) to the legionary fortress at Col. Glevum (Gloucester). Not to be confused with the major north-south road named Ermine Street (Margary 2).

nodes.title: Rusahinili
nodes.description: Rusahinili (modern Toprakkale) was an ancient fortress of Urartu built by Rusa I.

nodes.title: Trakhtemyrivsʹke horodyshche
nodes.description: A Scythian-period (seventh-sixth centuries BCE) hillfort site on the right bank of the Dnieper River, consisting of a large fortified territory (Velyki Valky) surrounding a smaller acropolis (Mali Valky).

nodes.title: Belvedere Temple, Orvieto
nodes.description: A fifth century B.C. temple that was likely sacred to Tinia.

nodes.title: Knowth
nodes.description: Knowth is a Neolithic passage grave of Brú na Bóinne in the valley of the River Boyne in Ireland. The site, covering almost a hectare, is comprised of a central, large mound (Site 1) and 17 smaller satellite tombs.

nodes.title: Dowth
nodes.description: Dowth is a Neolithic passage tomb in the Boyne Valley, County Meath, Ireland.

nodes.title: Alpes Cottiae (late Roman province)
nodes.description: The post-Diocletianic province of Alpes Cottiae according to the Verona List (ca. AD 303-324). It was assigned to the diocese of Italia.

nodes.title: Arabia (late Roman province)
nodes.description: The post-Diocletianic province of Arabia according to the Verona List (ca. AD 303-324). It was assigned to the diocese of Oriens.

nodes.title: Purpurariae (islands)
nodes.description: An island group off the western coast of Morocco.

nodes.title: Pythagoreion
nodes.description: An ancient fortified port on Samos.

nodes.title: House of Julius Polybius
nodes.description: The House of Julius Polybius (IX 13,1.3) sits on the north side of the Via dell'Abbondanza and dates from the second century BC.

nodes.title: Garden of the Fugitives
nodes.description: The so-called "Garden of the Fugitives" (I, 21,1) is an area of the city that was once given over to habitation but that in the final phase of the city was a vineyard with a summer triclinium. Excavation campaigns of the 1960s and 1970s discovered 13 human victims of the AD 79 eruption that destroyed the city.

nodes.title: House of Venus in the shell
nodes.description: Located on the Via dell'Abbondanza, the so-called "House of Venus in the shell" is also known as the House of D. Lucretius Satrius Valens.

nodes.title: House of the geometric mosaics
nodes.description: The House of the Geometric Mosaics (VIII,2,14-16) is a large domus of more than 60 rooms that was achieved by combining two third to second century BC houses.

nodes.title: Castra of Drobeta
nodes.description: A Roman castrum dating to the reign of Trajan located on the Danube, at Turnu-Severin, Romania.

nodes.title: Church of Saint Eusebius (Ronciglione)
nodes.description: A paleochristian sanctuary located along the Via Francigena.

nodes.title: Villa del Cimitero Flaminio
nodes.description: A Roman villa located at the 1.6 km post of the via Tiberina, positioned on a tuff bank, today inside the Prima Porta cemetery.

nodes.title: Peschiera necropolis
nodes.description: An Etruscan necropolis at Tuscania in use from the seventh until the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Temple of Hibis
nodes.description: A large temple located in the Kharga Oasis that is dated to the Saite-Persian period.

nodes.title: Nuragic settlement, Antas
nodes.description: A Nuragic settlement that pre-dates and, in some cases, is re-occupied during the Roman period.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater is located on the opposite bank of the wadi from Bararus.

nodes.title: Fanum Pithiviers-le-Vieil
nodes.description: The Fanum of Pithiviers-le-Vieil.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Coa de Serra
nodes.description: A nuragic complex near Baunei, Sardinia.

nodes.title: Baku
nodes.description: An ancient city located on the Caspian Sea. Baku, now in Azerbaijan, was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000.

nodes.title: Porta Flaminia
nodes.description: A gate in the Aurelian Wall from which the Via Flaminia issued, the Porta Flaminia became known as the Porta del Popolo after the fifteenth century. Sixtus IV is credited with building the gateway that stands today.

nodes.title: Porta Fontinalis
nodes.description: No longer extant, the Porta Fontinalis is only known via textual and epigraphic references. Presumed to be a gate of the Servian Wall, the Porta Fontinalis lay in the Campus Martius, west of the via Lata. It may have been the original point of issuance for the Republican roads known as the Via Flaminia and the Via Salaria.

nodes.title: Osteria del Gladiatore
nodes.description: A Roman tavern in Pompeii.

nodes.title: tribus Maecia
nodes.description: Tribus Maecia (originally Maicia) was a later rural tribe of ancient Rome, established in 332 B.C.

nodes.title: Deir Apa Jeremiah
nodes.description: Late antique monastery at Saqqarah constructed around 470 CE and abandoned by the middle of the 9th century.

nodes.title: Artulu
nodes.description: A city in Tabal mentioned in royal inscriptions of the Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC).

nodes.title: Hubušnu (kingdom)
nodes.description: Hubušnu is a small kingdom in Tabal that is mentioned in Assyrian royal inscriptions of the first millennium BC.

nodes.title: Mulî (mountain)
nodes.description: Mulî is a mountain in Tabal. Inscriptions of the ninth-century-BC Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC) refer to it as "the mountain of alabaster."

nodes.title: Timur (mountain)
nodes.description: Timur is a mountain that is situated between Meliddu and Tabal.

nodes.title: Illubru
nodes.description: Illubru is a city in the western part of Que (kingdom) or in Hilakku that is mentioned in inscriptions of the Assyrian king Sennacherib (r. 704-681 BC). This site is generally connected with classical Lampron, which is likely to be identified with modern Namrun, ca. 20 km northwest of Tarsus.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Orolio
