nodes.description: A nuragic monument near Silanus, Sardinia, constructed primarily of granite and rising to a height of ca. 12 m and dating to the Middle to Late Bronze Age (seventeenth to ninth centuries BC).

nodes.title: Puntone necropolis
nodes.description: An Etruscan necropolis dating to the seventh-fifth centuries B.C. The ancient settlement associated with the site may have been Palmule.

nodes.title: Scoglietto
nodes.description: A Roman sanctuary in use from the first century B.C. through fifth century A.D.

nodes.title: Place near Taparura
nodes.description: Unnamed minor settlement or villa in the territory of the Machounoi

nodes.title: Serreion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 unlocated Serreion

nodes.title: Zereia/Zeira
nodes.description: Diodorus refers to Zereia/Zeira as a fortress and places it near the location of Chalcidice. It was razed by Philip V. It is now unlocated. (cited: BAtlas 51 unlocated Zereia/Zeira)

nodes.title: Apollonia ad Rhyndacum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 D4 Apollonia ad Rhyndacum

nodes.title: Arctonnesos Ins.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B4 Arctonnesos Ins.

nodes.title: Artace
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B4 Artace

nodes.title: Askania L.
nodes.description: Askania L. (Lake Iznik)

nodes.title: Bathys Limen
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B3 Bathys Limen

nodes.title: Berg(o)ule/Arkadioupolis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 A2 Berg(o)ule/Arkadioupolis

nodes.title: Bithynia (region)
nodes.description: Bithynia was an ancient region, kingdom, and Roman province of northwestern Asia Minor.

nodes.title: Bizye
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B1 Bizye

nodes.title: ‘Callum’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 C2 ‘Callum’

nodes.title: Cyzicus
nodes.description: An ancient city of Mysia in Anatolia.

nodes.title: Daphnous
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 D4 Daphnous

nodes.title: Daskylitis Limne
nodes.description: Also called "Aphnitis Limne" in antiquity, according to Strabo. Modern Lake Kuş/Lake Manyas in Turkey.

nodes.title: Daskyleion
nodes.description: Daskyleion (modern Ergili) was the capital of the Persian satrapy of Phrygia from the sixth century BC until the conquests of Alexander the Great.

nodes.title: Didymateiche
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 A4 Didymateiche

nodes.title: Dindymon M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B4 Dindymon M.

nodes.title: Granicus (river)
nodes.description: Granicus fl. (modern Biga Çayı) is a river in Asia Minor that flows from Mount Ida to the Sea of Marmara.

nodes.title: Halone
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B4 Halone

nodes.title: Halone Ins.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B4 Halone Ins.

nodes.title: Helikore/Nicaea
nodes.description: Helikore/Nicaea (modern İznik, Turkey) was a Greek city of northwestern Anatolia. It was the site of the First and Second Councils of Nicaea and was the interim capital city of the Byzantine Empire between 1204 and 1261.

nodes.title: Melanos Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B4 Melanos Pr.

nodes.title: Miletopolitis/Apolloniatis/Artynia L.
nodes.description: A freshwater lake in the vicinity of Bursa, Turkey.

nodes.title: Mygdonia
nodes.description: Mygdonia was a region of northwestern Asia Minor. It takes its name from the Mygdones of Thrace who migrated to the northwestern part of Asia Minor in the Late Bronze Age.

nodes.title: Odryses (river)
nodes.description: Odryses fl. (Nilufer or Niloufer River (Turkish: Nilüfer Çayı)).

nodes.title: Olympus (mountain)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 E4 Olympus M.

nodes.title: Ophiussa (island)
nodes.description: An island located in the southern Sea of Marmara.

nodes.title: Ornoi
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested in written sources. Placed by C. Foss (Barrington Atlas) to the south of modern İnecik, Turkey. According to Hierokles, Ornoi was administratively located in the late province of Europe.

nodes.title: Perinthus/Heraclea
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B3 Perinthus/Heraclea

nodes.title: Phrygia Epiktetos
nodes.description: Phrygia Epiktetos was a region of Phrygia formed by the cities of Aizanoi, Kadoi, Kotiaeion, Nakoleia, and Dorylaeion.

nodes.title: Proconnesus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B3 Proconnesus

nodes.title: Proconnesus (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Sea of Marmara known especially for its high quality, fine-grained marble dubbed Proconnesian marble.

nodes.title: Propontis
nodes.description: The Sea of Marmara.

nodes.title: Prusias ad Mare/Kios
nodes.description: Prusias ad Mare/Kios was an ancient Greek city on the Propontis. The city joined the Aetolian League and was destroyed by Philip V of Macedon. Prusias I of Bithynia rebuilt the site, naming it for himself.

nodes.title: Rhyndakos (river)
nodes.description: Rhyndakos fl. (Mustafakemalpaşa River)

nodes.title: Sangarius (river)
nodes.description: The Sangarius river (modern Sakarya) is the third longest river in Asia Minor and flows through ancient Phrygia.

nodes.title: Sely(m)bria/Eudoxiopolis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 C2 Sely(m)bria/Eudoxiopolis

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 D2 unnamed aqueduct (“Aqueduct of Theodosius”, NNW Constantinopolis)

nodes.title: Unnamed quarry (on Proconnesus Ins.)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B3

nodes.title: Anastasian Wall
nodes.description: Also known as the "Long Wall of Thrace," this fortification line (nearly 60km in length) spanned the Thracian peninsula west of Constantinople. It was built in the 5th century CE and refurbished and modified by the emperor Anastasius in the early 6th century.

nodes.title: [Antigoneia] Ins.
nodes.description: [Antigoneia] Ins. (Burgazada)

nodes.title: Bosphorus
nodes.description: A strait that forms part of the boundary between Europe and Asia.

nodes.title: Byzantium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 53 A2 Byzantium

nodes.title: Chalkitis/Demonnesos (island)
nodes.description: Chalkitis/Demonnesos Ins. (Heybeliada)

nodes.title: Constantinopolis
nodes.description: Capital city of the Eastern Roman Empire, the Latin, and the Ottoman Empires founded by Constantine I in AD 330.

nodes.title: Hieron (Chalkedonion)/Zeus Ourios, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 53 B2 Hieron (Chalkedonion)/Zeus Ourios, T.

nodes.title: Ioulianou/Sophias Limen
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 53 A3 Ioulianou/Sophias Limen

nodes.title: Iuppiter Urius, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 53 B2 Iuppiter Urius, T.

nodes.title: Megale/Pityodes/Prinkipos Ins.
nodes.description: Megale/Pityodes/Prinkipos Ins. (Büyükada)

nodes.title: Prota (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 53 B3 Prota Ins.

nodes.title: Rhodussae (islands)
nodes.description: A group of small islands in the Propontis.

nodes.title: (T)Erebinthodes Ins.
nodes.description: (T)Erebinthodes Ins. (Sedef Island)

nodes.title: Aqua Hadriana
nodes.description: The aqueduct referred to as the “Aqua Hadriana” served the imperial palace in Constantinople.

nodes.title: Neorion
nodes.description: Neorion Harbor was a harbor of Constantinople in use from the fourth century until the late Ottoman period.

nodes.title: Wall of Constantine
nodes.description: The Wall of Constantine (Murus Constantini) was built during the AD 320s as Constantine organized his eponymous city. The course of the Wall of Constantine cannot be determined with precision today.

nodes.title: Theodosian Walls
nodes.description: The Theodosian Walls (Murus Theodosii) were erected during the reign of Emperor Theodosius II (r. 408–450) to defend the landward approach to the city of Constantinople.

nodes.title: Acarnania
nodes.description: Acarnania was a region of west-central Greece.

nodes.title: Achelous (river)
nodes.description: A river of Western Greece. Its floods were noted by Herodotus.

nodes.title: Actium
nodes.description: Site of an ancient temple of Apollo near which Octavian erected a monument to commemorate his naval victory over M. Antonius in 31 BCE.

nodes.title: Actium Pr.
nodes.description: A promontory on the southern side of the entrance to the Ambracian Gulf from the Ionian Sea. It was in the sea off this promontory in 31BC that M. Antonius suffered a famous naval defeat at the hands of Octavian.

nodes.title: Ag. Mina
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C4 Ag. Mina

nodes.title: Aiginion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 D2 Aiginion

nodes.title: Ainos M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C5 Ainos M.

nodes.title: Ambracia
nodes.description: Ambracia (modern Arta) was an ancient city of central Greece, founded as a colony of Corinth in the seventh century BC. It was located near the Ambracian Gulf along the course of the river Arachthos.

nodes.title: Amphilochia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 D3 Amphilochia

nodes.title: Anactorium
nodes.description: A city founded by Corinth in the seventh century B.C. on the gulf of Ambracia.

nodes.title: Arachthos/Araththos/Aratthos/Aracthus (river)
nodes.description: A river in eastern Epirus, Greece that flows from the Pindus Mountains to the Ionian Sea.

nodes.title: Bouthroton
nodes.description: Modern Butrint (Butrinti) in Albania, ancient Bouthroton was an ancient Greek and later Roman city located in Epirus. The city became an important bishopric by the sixth century. The site was enrolled as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1992 because of its archaeological remains, which date from prehistoric times down through the late Middle Ages.

nodes.title: Cephallania (island)
nodes.description: The largest of the Ionian islands.

nodes.title: Corcyra
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 A2 Corcyra

nodes.title: Corcyra (island)
nodes.description: Corcyra Ins. (Kerkyra/Corfu) is an island in the Ionian Sea.

nodes.title: Dodona
nodes.description: An ancient site of northwestern Epirus, Dodona was home to one of the most ancient oracular traditions of the Hellenic world.

nodes.title: Dolicha? Ins.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 D5 Dolicha? Ins.

nodes.title: Echinades (islands)
nodes.description: A group of islands in the Ionian Sea off the coast of Acarnania.

nodes.title: Ephyra/Kichyros
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C3 Ephyra/Kichyros

nodes.title: Epirus
nodes.description: An ancient region that included northwest parts of modern Greece and the southern tip of modern Albania.

nodes.title: Ithaca (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C5 Ithaca Ins.

nodes.title: Ithoria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 D5 Ithoria

nodes.title: Karnos (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C4 Karnos Ins.

nodes.title: Krane
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C5 Krane

nodes.title: Leucas
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C4 Leucas

nodes.title: Leucas (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C4 Leucas Ins.

nodes.title: Molossis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 B2 Molossis

nodes.title: Nekromanteion
nodes.description: An ancient sanctuary of necromancy sacred to Hades and Persephone located on the banks of the Acheron river in Epirus, near the ancient city of Ephyra.

nodes.title: Nicopolis
nodes.description: An ancient city of Epirus founded by Octavian ca. 31 B.C. to commemorate his victory over Marcus Antonius and Cleopatra at the Battle of Actium.

nodes.title: Oiniadai
nodes.description: A city at the former mouth of the Achelous river.

nodes.title: Ormos Vathy 2
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C4 Ormos Vathy 2

nodes.title: Orraon/Horreum
nodes.description: Orraon was a city of the Molossians, founded probably in the early 4th c. BCE and planned on a grid system. It may have been destroyed by the Romans after Pydna in 168, and its inhabitants were removed to Nikopolis in 31 BCE. The site is remarkable for the preservation of its stone-built domestic architecture.

nodes.title: Oxeiai/Thoai (islands)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 D5 Oxeiai/Thoai Inss.

nodes.title: Paianion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 D5 Paianion

nodes.title: Pale
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 B5 Pale

nodes.title: Paxoi (islands)
nodes.description: Paxoi Inss., the smallest group of Ionian islands.

nodes.title: Paxos (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 B3 Paxos Ins.

nodes.title: Phoinike
nodes.description: Phoinike was an ancient Greek city of Epirus and the location of the Treaty of Phoenice which ended the First Macedonian War.

nodes.title: Pronnoi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C5 Pronnoi

nodes.title: Propaxos (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 B3 Propaxos Ins.

nodes.title: Same
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C5 Same

nodes.title: Spelaion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C4 Spelaion

nodes.title: Stratos
nodes.description: Stratos was the chief town of Acarnania. Modern Sourovigli in Greece.

nodes.title: Taphiae? (islands)
nodes.description: A group of small islands in the Ionian Sea located between Leucas and the Acarnanian coast. The main island of this group can probably be identified with the modern island of Meganisi, which in the ancient sources is called Táphos.

nodes.title: Taphos (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C4 Taphos Ins.

nodes.title: Thesprotia
nodes.description: One of the three main ancient tribes of Epirus.

nodes.title: T(o)maros (mountain)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C2 T(o)maros M.

nodes.title: Torybeia?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 D4 Torybeia?

nodes.title: Xylokastro 2
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C4 Xylokastro 2

nodes.title: Zacynthus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 inset Zacynthus

nodes.title: Zacynthus (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Ionian Sea.

nodes.title: Marmarata
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 unlocated Marmarata

nodes.title: Pronathidon
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 unlocated Pronathidon

nodes.title: Ninguaria (island)
nodes.description: Known today as Tenerife, this is the largest of the Canary islands.

nodes.title: Monte Falterona
nodes.description: A peak of the Tuscan-Romagnolo Apennines, rising to 1,654 m. above sea level, Monte Falterona is the source of the Arno river and shows evidence of Etruscan occupation.

nodes.title: Manganello Sanctuary
nodes.description: The Manganello Sanctuary is located at the northern edge Caere's urban plateau.

nodes.title: Tarbiṣu
nodes.description: Tarbiṣu, now modern Sherif Khan, was an Assyrian city located about 5 kilometers north of Nineveh. It was the principal cult center of the god Nergal in Assyria. Starting in the 8th and 7th centuries B.C., Tarbiṣu was a royal city and one of the primary residences of the Assyrian crown prince, who was trained in the art of kingship in the palace built there.

nodes.title: Pol-e Dokhtar
nodes.description: Pol-e Dokhtar (also Romanized as Pol Dokhtar and Pul-i-Dukhtar) is a city in the Lorestan Province of Iran. The ruins of a Sasanian bridge over the Kashkan River are still visible today a few kilometers north of the city; that structure was part of a Sasanian Royal road that connected the Persian capitals Istakhr and Bishapur with towns in central and northern Mesopotamia. In 1992, a horde of ancient objects were found in the nearby Cave Kalmakareh (also referred to as Cave Kalmakarra).

nodes.title: Negub tunnel
nodes.description: The Negub tunnel was part of an irrigation system that supported the Assyrian royal city of Nimrud.

nodes.title: Sur Jureh
nodes.description: Sur Jureh (also Sur Jurʿeh, Sūr Ğurʿa) is a site in the middle Euphrates region in what was part of the ancient kingdom of Suhu. The city, which is probably to be identified with ancient Gabbāri-bānî (or Gabbāri-ibni), was situated on the north bank of the Euphrates, opposite Gleieh (which lies on the southern bank). Like many towns and cities of the ancient kingdom of Suhu, Sur Jureh/Gabbāri-bānî is now underwater; the area was flooded after the construction of the Haditha dam.

nodes.title: Gleieh
nodes.description: Gleieh (also Gleiʾeh, Glaiʿā) is small site in the middle Euphrates region and was part of the kingdom of Suhu. The city, which is probably to be identified with ancient Kār-Apladad, was situated on the south bank of the Euphrates, opposite Sur Jureh (which lies on the northern bank). Like many towns and cities of the ancient kingdom of Suhu, Gleieh/Kār-Apladad is now underwater; the area was flooded after the construction of the Haditha dam.

nodes.title: Largo di Torre Argentina
nodes.description: A square in the Campus Martius of Rome, at the center of which lies an archaeological site that includes the remains of four temples of the Republican period, as well as elements of the first century B.C. theater complex of Cnaeus Pompeius.

nodes.title: So-called West Gate of Apollonia
nodes.description: An unusual structure close to the water edge, on the western side of Apollonia, refurbished in Byzantine times. The presence of Maltese crosses led to its interpretation as a martyrion, but an administrative role has also been suggested.

nodes.title: Tall Bazi
nodes.description: Archaeological site on the eastern bank of the Euphrates in northern Syria. The site contains a town dated to the Early Bronze Age III-IVA (mid-3rd millennium BCE), as well as a Roman sanctuary used only briefly from about the late 1st-late 2nd century CE. The western part of the site was flooded by the construction of the Tischrin Dam in 1999. Tall Bazi and the nearby site of Banat have been tentatively identified as the city of Armi/Armium mentioned in texts from Ebla.

nodes.title: Zominthos
nodes.description: A Minoan settlement dating from ca. 1800 BC onwards, Zominthos is well known for a large Minoan building discovered in 1982.

nodes.title: Sep. Bibuli
nodes.description: The tomb of C. Publicius Bibulus, a plebeian aedile, located at Rome at the foot of the Capitoline hill. It most likely dates to the close of the Republican period.

nodes.title: Azoria
nodes.description: An archaeological site (ancient name unknown) overlooking the Gulf of Mirabello in eastern Crete, not far from the modern town of Kavousi.

nodes.title: Roman Road in Sutton Park
nodes.description: An urban park in Birmingham, England, containing a stretch of preserved Roman road.

nodes.title: Necropoli del Fusco
nodes.description: The Fusco necropolis is the largest and oldest burial area in Greek Syracuse. Located within contrada Canalicchio, the site was excavated by Paolo Orsi in 1893.

nodes.title: Kamyana Mohyla
nodes.description: A stone barrow site near the Molochna River comprising over 50 grottoes and caves, many containing petroglyphs dating from the Mesolithic age through the second millennium BCE, with additional graffiti dated as late as the twelfth century CE.

nodes.title: Tomb of Eumachia
nodes.description: A monumental exedra-type tomb built at the Porta Nocera between ca. A.D 1-30 that served as the tomb for the family of Eumachia.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Sa Jua
nodes.description: A monopteral nuraghe.

nodes.title: Dra' Abu el-Naga'
nodes.description: A necropolis for pharaohs of the Seventeenth Dynasty of ancient Egypt.

nodes.title: So-called House of Hesychios
nodes.description: A Roman peristyle house located in Cyrene.

nodes.title: Baptistry of Neon
nodes.description: An octagonal brick structure erected by Bishop Ursus (late fourth or early fifth century AD) as part of a Basilica (destroyed in 1734). Bishop Neon completed the baptistry at the end of the fifth century AD.

nodes.title: Withdrawn: House of the Tragic Poet
nodes.description: This place resource is a duplicate for http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/912505596 and was erroneously created and published. It has been withdrawn and moved to errata.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Saguntum
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Saguntum occupies the middle terrace in the city's urban layout. It could accommodate ca. 8,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Theater at Saepinum
nodes.description: The intramural theater at Saepinum is one of the best preserved structures at the site. Located in the northern part of the walled area, it is likely built between 2. B.C. and A.D. 4.

nodes.title: The Forum of Corporations
nodes.description: A key commercial center occupying the quadriporticus of the theater of Ostia, the Forum of Corporations dates initially to the Augustan period but is substantially rebuilt in the second century.

nodes.title: Area della Guastuglia
nodes.description: The archaeological site "Area della Guastuglia" at Gubbio is an architectural complex likely connected with civic religion during Gubbio's Roman phase.

nodes.title: Roman temples at Chieti
nodes.description: Structures thought to be temples set within a sacred area that includes a sacred well.

nodes.title: Temple of Juno Caelestis
nodes.description: Juno Caelestis, a successor divinity of the Punic Tanit, is celebrated by a sanctuary built at Dougga ca. 222-235 CE, and sponsored by Q. Gabinius Rufus Felix.

nodes.title: Arch of Alexander Severus
nodes.description: The Arch of Alexander Severus at Thugga was built in 228.

nodes.title: Capitolium at Thugga
nodes.description: The Capitolium at Thugga dates to the middle of the second century and carries epigraphic dedications to Lucius Verus and Marcus Aurelius dating to the late 160s.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Cuicul
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Cuicul was built during the reign of Antoninus Pius.

nodes.title: Tophet de Salammbô
nodes.description: A hybrid sanctuary and necropolis sacred to Tanit and Baal.

nodes.title: Baths of Antoninus at Carthage
nodes.description: The Baths of Antoninus at Carthage date to the middle of the second century and are the largest of the Roman public bath complexes in North Africa.

nodes.title: Greek theater at Alabanda
nodes.description: The Greek theater at Alabanda dates to the Hellenistic period.

nodes.title: Lacus Iuturnae
nodes.description: The Lacus Iuturnae was a pool built near a spring sacred to Iuturna. Legend held that the Dioscuri watered their horses there after the Battle of Lake Regillus in 495 BC.

nodes.title: Palea Kameni
nodes.description: Palea Kameni is the smaller of the two volcanogenic islands in the centre of the Santorini caldera, formed over the last two millennia. It was most likely formed before or during the major period of volcanic activity in A.D. 1866-1870.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Nolza
nodes.description: The Nuraghe Nolza consists of a central, quadri-lobate tower. The tower still stands to ca. 13 m and the complex covers 2.5 ha.

nodes.title: Temple of Apollo at Delphi
nodes.description: The Temple of Apollo situated in the center of the oracular sanctuary of that god at Delphi.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Apollo at Cyrene
nodes.description: A sanctuary at Cyrene dedicated to Apollo Karneios. The sanctuary was in use between the seventh century BC and the second century AD, and included shrines to other gods, including Artemis and Isis.

nodes.title: L-Shaped Palace at Gla
nodes.description: A complex of multifunctional rooms at Gla with two connected wings that extend from a right angle to form two ʺmegaronsʺ that lacked hearths and throne rooms. The palace was built around 1300 BCE.

nodes.title: Roman quarry of Antas
nodes.description: A Roman quarry located approximately 800 meters from the Temple of Antas.

nodes.title: London Wall
nodes.description: London's original Roman wall in stone was built ca. A.D. 190 to 225. The wall originally had a length of ca. 4 km (2.5 miles and enclosed an area of ca. 134 hectares. It once included four city gates.

nodes.title: Abu Sir
nodes.description: An Old Kingdom necropolis serving the ancient Egyptian city of Memphis.

nodes.title: Sepulcretum
nodes.description: A modern appellation of the ancient Iron Age necropolis uncovered along the Sacra Via adjacent to the Temple of Antoninus and Faustina in April 1902. Giacomo Boni and others conducted extensive excavations at the site.

nodes.title: Monte Solaro
nodes.description: Monte Solaro is the tallest mountain on the island of Capri with an elevation of 589 meters.

nodes.title: City wall of Pompeii
nodes.description: The city walls of Pompeii surround the ancient urban center and have several architectural phases.

nodes.title: Dionysopolis
nodes.description: This city was founded by Attalos II and Eumenes II. Although its precise location is unknown today, it was located somewhere on the north bank of the Maeander River, near Çal Dag and the Çal Ova.

nodes.title: Hellenopolis
nodes.description: Likely founded by Attalos II, Hellenopolis was initially populated by an amalgamation of citizens from several nearby Greek cities, and was located somewhere near the Mysia-Bithynia border.

nodes.title: Arnisa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 D3 Arnisa

nodes.title: Byllis
nodes.description: A Hellenistic and Roman site located on the right bank of the Aous river with a defensive circuit of ca. 2 km.

nodes.title: Castra/Parembole
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 D2 Castra/Parembole

nodes.title: Dardania
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 C1 Dardania

nodes.title: Drilon (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 B2 Drilon fl.

nodes.title: Dyrr(h)achium/Epidamnos
nodes.description: A city founded in 627 B.C. by colonists from Corinth and Kerkyra.

nodes.title: (H)Apsos (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 B3 (H)Apsos fl.

nodes.title: Herakleia
nodes.description: Herakleia or Herakleia Lynkestis was an ancient city of Macedonia founded by Philip II of Macedon in the middle of the fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: Illyricum
nodes.description: Illyricum was a Roman province that existed from 167 BC until AD 10.

nodes.title: Lissus
nodes.description: An important Illyrian port located on the river Drin.

nodes.title: Lychnidos
nodes.description: Lychnidos (modern Ohrid, Macedonia) is an ancient city listed as UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1979 and 1980 for both its cultural and natural heritage.

nodes.title: Openica
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 C2 Openica

nodes.title: ‘Scampis’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 C2 ‘Scampis’

nodes.title: Scupi
nodes.description: Scupi (modern Skopje, Macedonia (Macedonian: Скопје)) has been the site of human settlement since ca. 4000 BC.

nodes.title: Ulpiana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 D1 Ulpiana

nodes.title: Damastion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 unlocated Damastion

nodes.title: Aigeai
nodes.description: An ancient settlement most noted for the discovery, in 1977, of Macedonian royal tombs at the site.

nodes.title: Amphax(it)is
nodes.description: The western maritime district of Mygdonia in ancient Macedonia.

nodes.title: Apollonia
nodes.description: An ancient road station and settlement along the Via Egnatia in Mygdonia, between Amphipolis and Thessaoniki. Located near the modern municipality of Nea Apollonia in the Thessaloniki province of Greece. Possibly at a location now called Polina (Papazoglou) or a site between Nea Apollonia and Kokkalou excavated by Hatzopoulos in the early 1990s.

nodes.title: Franks Roman villa
nodes.description: The site of a Roman villa with two parallel ranges of rooms dating from the second half of the first century to the fifth century.

nodes.title: Eastern sanctuary
nodes.description: An extra-mural sanctuary located at the eastern gate of Gabii

nodes.title: Via Ardeatina
nodes.description: The Via Ardeatina connected Rome and Ardea.

nodes.title: Uronarti
nodes.description: An ancient settlement located on an island in the Nile just south of the Second Cataract, now in the north of Sudan. An ancient fortress dating to the reigns of the Middle Kingdom pharaohs (19th century BC) Senusret I and Senusret III is found there.

nodes.title: Uvecik Tepe
nodes.description: Uvecik Tepe or Üvecik Tepe is a tumulus in the Troad built for one Festus, a freedman of the emperor Caracalla.

nodes.title: Kerameikos
nodes.description: A district of ancient Athens located northwest of the Acropolis, the Kerameikos takes its name from the potters' workshops in the area; the portion of the district lying outside the Dipylon Gate served as a necropolis.

nodes.title: So-called House of Jason Magnus
nodes.description: A very large Roman house on the acropolis ridge of Cyrene.

nodes.title: Haut Bécherel
nodes.description: Haut Bécherel is the site of a major Gallo-Roman sanctuary sacred to Mars.

nodes.title: Kom el-Ahmer
nodes.description: Archaeological site in the province of Beheira in the Western Delta, inhabited from the Roman through the Early Islamic periods. Along with the nearby site Kom Wasit, it has been identified as a possible location of Metelis, the capital of the Metelite Nome.

nodes.title: Prytanikon at Athens
nodes.description: The Prytanikon was the seat of the Prytaneis and was located on the west side of the Agora in proximity to the Old Bouleuterion, with which it formed an architectural unit. This structure was supplanted by the later Tholos and its remains are referred to as "Building F". It dates to the later period of the Peisistratids, ca. 550-525 B.C.

nodes.title: Skara Brae
nodes.description: Skara Brae is a stone-built Neolithic settlement located on the west coast of Mainland, the largest island in the Orkney archipelago. Comprised of eight clustered houses, the village was occupied from roughly 3180 to 2500 BC.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Asklepios at Athens
nodes.description: A major sanctuary complex located west of the Theatre of Dionysus Eleuthereus on the south slope of the Athenian acropolis.

nodes.title: Roman Agora of Athens
nodes.description: The Roman agora at Athens is located to the north of the Acropolis and to the east of the ancient Agora.

nodes.title: Crustuminus Ager
nodes.description: The territory of the city of Crustumerium.

nodes.title: Collepardo
nodes.description: A sixth century AD city founded in the time of Theodoric the Great, but that shows traces of first millennium BC habitation in the form of polygonal masonry walls.

nodes.title: Yassı Ada (island)
nodes.description: An island bordering the Chuka Channel in the southeastern Aegean sea; two shipwreck sites (dating to the fourth and seventh centuries A.D.) are located off its southern coast.

nodes.title: Quadriporticus of the theatre
nodes.description: A four-sided portico standing behind the large theater of Pompeii (VIII, 7, 16-17). The complex was constructed ca. 80 BC.

nodes.title: Forte Michelangelo
nodes.description: A fortress at modern Civitavecchia in Italy. It was begun in 1508 and completed 1537 during the reign of Pope Paul III. Antonio Sangallo the Younger designed the fortress.

nodes.title: Castello di Agropoli
nodes.description: A Medieval castle built atop Byzantine foundations. Location based on OpenStreetMap.

nodes.title: Rhion
nodes.description: An ancient harbor and political dependent of Molykreion. Its precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Thermes gallo-romains, Pithiviers-le-Vieil
nodes.description: A Gallo-Roman bath complex at Pithiviers-le-Vieil.

nodes.title: Regio VII, Pompeii
nodes.description: The so-called Regio VII, an archaeological subdivision located in the central western section of Pompeii, contains a mix of residential and commercial structures, as well as the Stabian Baths.

nodes.title: Maiden Castle, Dorset
nodes.description: One of the largest and most complex Iron Age hillforts in Europe, Maiden Castle, in Dorset, was occupied from the Neolithic period through to the fourth century A.D.

nodes.title: Madinat Hamad 3 Burial Mound Field (Dar Kulayb)
nodes.description: A necropolis of the early Dilmun culture, dating to the second millennium B.C.

nodes.title: Via cava del Cavone, Sovana
nodes.description: A hollowed roadway created by cutting the natural tufaceous bedrock. These roads link necropoleis and settlements in the area between Sovana, Sorano, and Pitigliano.

nodes.title: Valle Bona-Monte Rosello necropolis
nodes.description: A Hellenistic necropolis of Suana.

nodes.title: Euphrasian Basilica
nodes.description: An Early Byzantine Christian basilica located in Poreč, Croatia.

nodes.title: Larinum Roman amphitheater
nodes.description: An amphitheater of the first century A.D.

nodes.title: Bearsden Roman bath house
nodes.description: The remains of a stone-built Roman bath at Bearsden on the Antonine Wall.

nodes.title: Roman bridge, Córdoba
nodes.description: A first century Roman bridge over the Guadalquivir river.

nodes.title: Temple of Augustales at Centuripae
nodes.description: An early Imperial (first to third centuries) temple at Centuripae that has been associated with the priestly college of the Augustales.

nodes.title: Roman theater of Saguntum
nodes.description: The Roman theater of Saguntum could accommodate approximately 8,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Amphitheater of Thizica
nodes.description: The small Roman amphitheater of Thizica.

nodes.title: Bouleuterion at Ietas
nodes.description: The Bouleuterion at Ietas dates to the later second century B.C.

nodes.title: Roman siege Camp E'
nodes.description: Remains of a Roman siege camp from the siege of the fortress of Masada in A.D. 72.

nodes.title: Le Sparne archaeological area
nodes.description: An ancient urban area at Poggio Buco in Italy with a defensive wall that included an agger. Also evidence for an elite building of the archaic period.

nodes.title: Theater at Sybaris/Thurii/Copia
nodes.description: The Roman Theater at Sybaris/Thurii/Copia dates originally to the Augustan period.

nodes.title: Saite-Persian cemetery at Abu Sir
nodes.description: At Abu Sir, a cemetery of tombs from the Saite period: is located directly south of the pyramid of Neferefre.

nodes.title: Monte Testaccio
nodes.description: An artificial mountain on the banks of the Tiber river at Rome composed of 580,000 cubic meters of broken amphorae.

nodes.title: Via Praenestina
nodes.description: A consular road running from Rome to Praeneste.

nodes.title: Salemi
nodes.description: The modern town of Salemi, near Trapani, has been associated with the location of the ancient settlement of Halicyae.

nodes.title: San Giovanni de Butris
nodes.description: A church of the eleventh and twelfth century built along the line of the Roman Via Flaminia. The church incorporates Roman remains, including those of a bridge.

nodes.title: Cappuck
nodes.description: Site of a Roman fort occupied during the Flavian and Antonine periods. It lies 4 miles east of Jedburgh in the Scottish Borders, along the line of Dere Street.

nodes.title: Bridgeness Distance Slab
nodes.description: Findspot of the Bridgeness distance slab, near the eastern terminus of the Antonine Wall

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Deva
nodes.description: The second-century A.D. Roman amphitheater at Deva Victrix (modern Chester, England) was the largest military amphitheater in Britain.

nodes.title: Varignano Vecchio
nodes.description: A villa maritima in eastern Liguria, inhabited from ca. 100 BC to the fifth century AD.

nodes.title: So-called Roman Baths in Apollonia
nodes.description: An architectural complex near the sea in Apollonia. It went through different stages and alterations between, roughly, the fourth century B.C. and the seventh century A.D. It was probably used as a private villa, then as public baths and, perhaps, as cisterns in later years.

nodes.title: So-called Residential Insula in Apollonia
nodes.description: An architectural complex located on the West side of the East Church in Apollonia (Cyrenaica). Excavated in 1954-55, it was first thought to be a temple of Isis (Stucchi 1975). According to Kenrick (2013), it is more likely to have been a small production centre, maybe for the fermentation of wine.

nodes.title: Pyramid of Sekhemkhet
nodes.description: The Pyramid of Sekhemkhet, also known as "The Buried Pyramid", is an unfinished step pyramid at Saqqara that was begun ca. 2645 B.C. for Sekhemkhet Djoserty.

nodes.title: Large Theater
nodes.description: The so-called "Large Theater" at Pompeii was built in the Greek style during the second century B.C. Its capacity was approximately 5,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Pyramid of Khendjer
nodes.description: The pyramid of the Pharaoh Khendjer (Thirteenth Dynasty) who ruled Egypt during the Second Intermediate Period (ca. 1760 B.C.)

nodes.title: Mastabet el-Fara'un
nodes.description: The site of the burial of Shepseskaf, the last known pharaoh of the Fourth Dynasty of Ancient Egypt.

nodes.title: Basilica
nodes.description: An important civic building in Pompeii and an early example of the building type, built between ca. 120 and 78 B.C. (VIII, 1, 1).

nodes.title: Badnigalbilukurašušu
nodes.description: Nineveh’s main (or great) inner wall was called Badnigalbilukurašušu ("Wall Whose Brilliance Overwhelms Enemies"). It was constructed by the Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib after he moved the Assyrian capital to Nineveh. Badnigalbilukurašušu’s superstructure was reportedly raised to a height of 200 courses of brick. The visible remains of the twelve-kilometer-long wall and some of its gates are still visible today.

nodes.title: Ezida
nodes.description: One of the temples in the citadel of Nineveh that was dedicated to Nabû, the god of scribes; it is located north of the temple of the goddess Ištar (Emašmaš). The Sumerian ceremonial name Ezida means "True House."

nodes.title: Ešahulezenzagmukam
nodes.description: Around 690 B.C., the Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib started construction on a New Year’s Temple for Nineveh’s tutelary deity Ištar. Ešahulezenzagmukam, whose Sumerian ceremonial name means "House of Joy and Gladness for the Festival of the Beginning of the Year" was never completed and work on it appears to have come to a complete stop ca. 688 B.C., when Sennacherib decided to rebuild the Akītu Temple at Ashur instead.

nodes.title: Step Gate
nodes.description: Most 7th-century B.C. Assyrian inscriptions record that Nineveh had eight south- and east-facing gates: the Step Gate was the sixth of these. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Mušēṣât-šīr-asakki, which means "The One Who Exorcises the 'Flesh' of the Asakku-demon."

nodes.title: Nergal Gate
nodes.description: The northern city wall of Nineveh had three gates: the Nergal Gate was middle gate. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial names Erra-mušamqit-ayyābī ("The God Erra Is the One Who Cuts Down Enemies") and Erra-šāgiš-zāmânīya ("The God Erra Is the One Who Cuts Down My Enemies").

nodes.title: Citadel Gate
nodes.description: The East Gate or Citadel Gate was located on the southeast side of the citadel of Nineveh and it was one of several gates from which the upper town could be accessed from the lower town via a long, stone ramp.

nodes.title: Ager Cosanus survey area
nodes.description: The term "Ager Cosanus" refers to the territorium (territory) of the Latin right colony of Cosa, reportedly established by Rome in south Etruria in 273 B.C. following conflict with the Etruscan city of Vulci. The colonial center of Cosa has been the subject of ongoing archaeological inquiry since the late 1940s. Beginning in the 1970s, the hinterland of the city was subjected to intensive archaeological field survey. The Wesleyan University survey of the rural hinterland of Cosa identified approximately 132 sites.

nodes.title: Roman theater of Acinipo
nodes.description: The Roman theater of Acinipo dates ca. 59-53 B.C.

nodes.title: Pollenzo Roman amphitheater
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at ancient Pollentia (modenr Pollenzo).

nodes.title: Vignale
nodes.description: A Roman villa, mansio, and Late Antique settlement along the Via Aemilia Scauri.

nodes.title: Fort Shalmaneser
nodes.description: The ninth-century-BC Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858–824 BC) constructed an impressive palatial complex in the southeastern corner of the city Kalhu (biblical Calah). This armory, which the seventh-century-BC ruler Esarhaddon (r. 680–669 BC) referred to as an ēkal māšarti (‘review palace’), was completed ca. 846 BC. Fort Shalmaneser, the name of building dubbed by its excavators, remained in use until the very end of the Assyrian Empire (612 BC), although its importance was significantly diminished after the Assyrian court moved away from Kalhu at the end of the eighth century BC, first to Dūr-Šarrukīn and then to Nineveh.

nodes.title: Narekavank
nodes.description: Narekavank, or Narek Monastery, was a tenth-century Armenian monastery near the southern shore of Lake Van. It was a major monastic center, and the mystical poet Grigor Narekatsi (951-1003) studied and resided there. The monastery was abandoned and demolished in the 20th century.

nodes.title: Epirote League
nodes.description: A koinon (league) of Epirote tribes which grew out of the earlier Molossian League, established between 370 and 320 BCE. The league dissolved in the Third Macedonian War (171–168 BCE) due to its constituent cities choosing different sides of the conflict.

nodes.title: Pont du Diable (Céret)
nodes.description: A Medieval bridge spanning the Tech river that dates between 1321 and 1341.

nodes.title: Tech (river)
nodes.description: The Tech river flows some 84 km from its source is the Parcigoule Valley to the Mediterranean Sea.

nodes.title: Baths of Faverges
nodes.description: The Roman Baths of Faverges date to the first century.

nodes.title: Casale Vignale necropolis
nodes.description: An Etruscan rock-cut necropolis of San Giovenale.

nodes.title: Grotte di Catullo
nodes.description: Located on the Sirmione peninsula on the southern shore of Lake Garda, "Grotte di Catullo" is the name given to the ruins of a Roman villa dating to the late first century B.C. and the beginning of the first century A.D.

nodes.title: Casal Bertone necropolis
nodes.description: Casal Bertone is named for the modern Roman neighborhood where it was discovered, about 2 km east of the Porta Maggiore. The site of Casal Bertone covers more than 3,000 square meters. The eastern portion of the site comprised a residential area that was occupied from about the first century B.C. to the fifth to sixth centuries A.D.

nodes.title: Sawtry
nodes.description: Modern day site of a Roman-British settlement dating from the second to fourth centuries AD.

nodes.title: Curia Iulia
nodes.description: The building of the Curia Julia was begun by Julius Caesar and completed by Augustus in 29 BCE. It replaced the former senate house, the Curia Hostilia.

nodes.title: Nuraghe S. Cadrina
nodes.description: A nuragic village of the Middle Bronze Age (ca. 1700-1350 BC), Nuraghe S. Cadrina has a central tower with an original diameter of 11.70 m.

nodes.title: Blakeia
nodes.description: A settlement attested in Aristotle's Kymaion Politeia. Its precise location is unknown today but it was located within Cymian territory.

nodes.title: Via Egnatia
nodes.description: The Via Egnatia was a Roman road begun in the second century BC that crossed the Roman provinces of Illyricum, Macedonia, and Thrace.

nodes.title: Etchmiadzin Cathedral
nodes.description: A fourth century A.D. church located in Ejmiatsin, Armenia. This is the central cathedral of the Mother See of Holy Etchmiadzin of the Armenian Apostolic Church and was enrolled as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000.

nodes.title: Ramla bay villa
nodes.description: A villa maritima discovered in 1910-11.

nodes.title: House of Many Colors
nodes.description: A large and well-appointed house located in the Villa Section of Olynthus, proposed as an Olynthian type-house

nodes.title: Monument near Ghirza
nodes.description: A monument near the modern site of Ghirza

nodes.title: Cresta di Gallo
nodes.description: The hill in the province of Trapani known as Cresta di Gallo has evidence for Bronze Age occupation in the form of a necropolis that is linked with the nearby site of Mokarta.

nodes.title: Odèon/Ekklesiasterion
nodes.description: The Bouleuterion of ancient Region (modern Reggio Calabria).

nodes.title: Temple of Jupiter Heliopolitanus
nodes.description: The Temple of Jupiter Heliopolitanus at Baalbek is considered the largest temple of the Roman world. It served as an oracular shrine.

nodes.title: Temple of Bacchus
nodes.description: Part of the complex of Roman temples at Baalbek, the Temple of Bacchus is one of the best-preserved temples of the Roman world. It is conventionally dated to the second century CE.

nodes.title: Al-'Assāsīf
nodes.description: Necropolis on the West Bank of the Nile near Thebes containing tombs from the 18th, 25th, and 26th dynasties.

nodes.title: Fort at Great Wall of Gorgan
nodes.description: One of the integral forts spaced along the wall

nodes.title: Ptolemaic Kingdom
nodes.description: The Ptolemaic Kingdom was a Hellenistic kingdom founded by Ptolemy I Soter, which was primarily centered on Egypt. It was absorbed into the Roman Empire in 30 BCE following Octavian's victory over Mark Antony and Cleopatra VII Philopator at the battle of Actium in 31 BCE.

nodes.title: Amphitheatrum Castrense
nodes.description: The Amphitheatrum Castrense is a Roman amphitheater built in the third century AD. Its structure was later incorporated into the Aurelianic Walls. Adjacent to the amphitheater is the Christian church of Santa Croce in Gerusalemme.

nodes.title: Nymphaeum divi Alexandri
nodes.description: A monumental nymphaeum on the Esquiline Hill dating to the Severan period; commonly known as "Trofei di Mario". The complex is located at a fork between the Via Tiburtina and the Via Labicana.

nodes.title: Gallicia
nodes.description: A region of northwest Spain that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Galicia.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater of Milan
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater of Milan was built near the Porta Ticinese during the second and third centuries. It was destroyed by the time of the Gothic Wars, most likely during the fifth century.

nodes.title: Mausoleum of Galla Placidia
nodes.description: An ancient funerary chapel, part of the Santa Croce complex in Ravenna, Italy, possibly built as an imperial mausoleum (ca. AD 417 - 425). The empress Galla Placidia (d. AD 450 ) is the presumed, likely patron of the building, though she is very unlikely to have been entombed within one of three sarcophagi found inside.

nodes.title: tribus Clustumina
nodes.description: The tribus Clustumina (or Crustumina) was a rural tribe of Rome which was established in 495 B.C.

nodes.title: House of Marcus Lucretius Fronto
nodes.description: The House of M. Lucretius Fronto (V, 4, a, 11), situated off the north side of the Via di Nola, is an example of a refined domus that is small in size but with opulent Third and Fourth style wall paintings.

nodes.title: Roman siege ramp at Masada
nodes.description: The Roman siege ramp dates to the Roman siege of Masada in A.D. 72.

nodes.title: Necropolis of San Giuseppe
nodes.description: The Necropolis of San Giuseppe is located along a cut tufo road or via cava near Pitigliano.

nodes.title: Abusir South
nodes.description: Abusir South, located north of Saqqara, refers to an archaeological area where a large cemetery of lower-ranking officials of the Old Kingdom has been identified.

nodes.title: Stele of Horemheb at Karnak
nodes.description: Horemheb was the last pharaoh of the 18th Dynasty of Egypt. The deeds of his career were recorded on a stele that was mountaed at the foot of the Tenth Pylon of the Karnak temple.

nodes.title: The House of the Masks
nodes.description: The House of the Masks (also known as the House of the Comedians), built around 150-100 BC, was a luxurious residential complex that may have housed traveling troops of actors performing at the theater in Delos.

nodes.title: The Theater of Larissa
nodes.description: The theater at Larissa was a large stone theater built around the end of the third century BC and used for dramatic performances and as a political meeting place.

nodes.title: Telesterion
nodes.description: The Telesterion (ca. 435 - 421 B.C.) was a sacred hall at Eleusis used for the annual initiation ceremonies for the cult of Demeter and Persephone known as the Eleusinian Mysteries.

nodes.title: Tralles ancient theater
nodes.description: The theater of ancient Tralles.

nodes.title: Ivor / Xion (river)
nodes.description: The modern Oued Ksob of western Morocco.

nodes.title: Azuru
nodes.description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources; the modern site is Azor, Israel.

nodes.title: Dipylon Gate
nodes.description: The Dipylon Gate was the sole double gate in Athens, erected next to the Holy Gate, near the Kerameikos.

nodes.title: Koumasa prepalatial cemetery
nodes.description: A prepalatial cemetery on the island of Crete that includes three tholos tombs and one rectangular tomb.

nodes.title: Pranu Muttedu
nodes.description: Pranu Muttedu is a pre- and protohistoric archaeological site located near Goni, Sardinia. The complex includes standing stones (menhirs) and prehistoric built tombs (domus de janas). The site dates to the Late Neolithic (3200 – 2800 BC) and Early Chalcolithic (2800 – 2600 BC) periods.

nodes.title: Nuraghe S'Ortali 'e su Monti
nodes.description: A nuragic complex dating ca. 1500 BC near Tortolì in Sardinia.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Serbissi
nodes.description: A nuragic complex located near Osini, Sardinia.

nodes.title: Malchittu nuragic temple
nodes.description: A sacred structure with an 'in antis' plan located near Arzachena in Sardinia.

nodes.title: Tell Ischali
nodes.description: Tell Ishchali is an archaeological site in Iraq's Diyala province. Its main floruit in antiquity was from ca. 2700–1800 BC, primarily Dynastic through the Isin–Larsa period. The site was part of the city-state of Eshnunna.

nodes.title: Antro delle Sorti
nodes.description: The "Cave of the Fates" at Praeneste is a sanctuary at the base of the city's terraced sanctuary of Fortuna. It was said to contain wooden oracular tablets.

nodes.title: Arco dei Gavi
nodes.description: A Roman arch built by the gens Gavia.

nodes.title: Byzantine Bath
nodes.description: A thirteenth/fourteenth century Byzantine bath at Thessalonica; listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1988.

nodes.title: Old Town of Ghadamès
nodes.description: The Old Town of Ghadamès was inscribed in 1986 as a UNESCO World Heritage site, but was de-populated throughout the 1990s. It is now listed on the List of World Heritage in Danger (2016).

nodes.title: Palaestra at Olympia
nodes.description: Palaestra in the sanctuary of Zeus at Olympia

nodes.title: The Sassi and the Park of the Rupestrian Churches of Matera
nodes.description: A series of rock-cut dwellings and buildings.

nodes.title: Tall-i Takht (Throne Hill)
nodes.description: The ancient citadel of Pasargadae.

nodes.title: Residential Palace ("P")
nodes.description: Residential Palace ("P") is often regarded as the residence of Cyrus the Great at Pasargadae.

nodes.title: Hellenistic and Roman quarter archaeological area
nodes.description: The Hellenistic and Roman area is orthogonally planned and covers more than 15,000 square meters. It is located near Poggio San Nicola.

nodes.title: Bouleuterion at Akragas/Agrigentum
nodes.description: A bouleuterion complex at Akragas.

nodes.title: Fortifications at Civita di Artena
nodes.description: The polygonal masonry fortifications of the ancient settlement now known as Civita di Artena. These fortifications today measure more than 2.5 km in length.

nodes.title: Sassanid Archaeological Landscape of Fars Region
nodes.description: A cultural landscape located in the southeast of Fars Province, Iran, the Sassanid Archaeological Landscape of Fars Region is the official denomination given by UNESCO to eight Sasanian-era archaeological sites. This landscape was recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site on 30 June 2018.

nodes.title: Arzawa
nodes.description: A kingdom or federation in western Anatolia, whose exact location(s) and extent are matters of scholarly debate. The presence and nature of Arzawa is gleaned primarily from Hittite royal annals and diplomatic texts of the LBA, as well as the two letters from Amarna between Amenhotep III and the king of Arzawa. These texts, however, do not reveal the temporal span of Arzawa, and should be treated as snapshots in time. Arzawa reached its greatest prominence in the middle of the fourteenth century BCE, but had been reduced to a rump state by the end of the century. The remaining territory formed the core of the kingdom of Lydia.

nodes.title: Didi Liakhvi
nodes.description: The Greater Liakhvi River, a tributary of the Kura River in the South Ossetia region of the Republic of Georgia.

nodes.title: Hekateion
nodes.description: The Hekateion is a monumental temple for the goddess Hekate constructed in Lagina ca. 125 BCE.

nodes.title: Circuit wall of Rusellae
nodes.description: The megalithic defensive circuit of Rusellae dates to the seventh and sixth centuries B.C. and represents an important early example of stone-built fortifications in central Italy.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Thuburbo Maius
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Thuburbo Maius is an extramural structure constructed by hollowing out elevated terrain.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Beth Govrin/Eleutheropolis
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater at Beth Govrin/Eleutheropolis dating after the Jewish revolt of the first century A.D.

nodes.title: Gallo-Roman amphitheater-theater of Gennes
nodes.description: A theater / amphitheater dating to the early second century.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Burdigala
nodes.description: The so-called "Palais Gallien" is an early second century A.D. amphitheater.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Carthago Nova/Col. Urbs Iulia
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Cartagena dates to the very end of the first century B.C. and was dedicated to Caius and Lucius Caesar.

nodes.title: Mithraeum at Casa del Mitreo in Emerita Augusta
nodes.description: The well-preserved remains of a second century Mithraeum at Emerita Augusta (mod. Merida, Spain).

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Alalie/Aleria
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater located in eastern Corsica.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Thermae Himeraeae
nodes.description: Roman amphitheater at Termini Imerese was of modest size and is today poorly preserved.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Hydata Hypsitana/Forum Traiani
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Forum Traiani, modern Fordongianus

nodes.title: Roman baths at Hydata Hypsitana/Forum Traiani
nodes.description: The Roman baths Fordongianus dates to the first through third centuries.

nodes.title: Forum of Septimius Severus
nodes.description: The Forum of Septimius Severus at Lepcis Magna

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Calleva Atrebatum
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Calleva Atrebatum began as a timber structure ca. A.D. 55-75. Its remains lie north of the east gate of the third century A.D. town wall and the site was first identified by William Stukeley in 1724. The amphitheater measures approximately 90 by 75 meters.

nodes.title: Via Sublacensis
nodes.description: The Via Sublacensis was built in order to connect the Villa Neronis (Nero's villa at Sublaqueum) to Rome. It split from the Via Valeria near Varia.

nodes.title: Via Herculia
nodes.description: A Roman road known through epigraphic attestations, the Via Herculia connected Aquilonia and Aequum Tuticum.

nodes.title: Forum Romanum
nodes.description: The ancient Roman forum.

nodes.title: City Eleusinion at Athens
nodes.description: The City Eleusinion was one of the most important sanctuaries in the religious life of ancient Athens. It was the urban “branch” of the sanctuary of Demeter and Kore at Eleusis in use during the Archaic and Classical periods.

nodes.title: Domus Confuleius
nodes.description: The domus of the freedman P. Confuleius Sabbio at Capua.

nodes.title: Arch of Augustus (Susa)
nodes.description: An arch dedicated to Augustus at Susa in the late first century BC that records the renewed alliance between the princeps and Marcus Julius Cottius.

nodes.title: Jerash Hippodrome
nodes.description: The Jerash Hippodrome dates after the middle of the second century. While among the smallest of the attested examples of Roman period hippodromes, it numbers among the best preserved.

nodes.title: So-called "Temple of Augustus"
nodes.description: A temple dedicated to Octavian by a Lucius Calpurnius. It replaced a temple of ca. 194 B.C. that had in turn been restored by Sulla.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater of Catania
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater of Catania is the largest known ancient amphitheater in Sicily. Its external dimensions measure ca. 125 x 105 meters. It likely dates to the second century.

nodes.title: Villa urbana
nodes.description: A Roman villa that has now been reconstructed.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Veleia
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater of Roman Veleia.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Spoletium
nodes.description: The remains of the early Imperial amphitheater were discovered within the Caserma Minervio during the early nineteenth century.

nodes.title: Arch of Augustus at Ariminum
nodes.description: The Arch of Augustus at Ariminum was dedicated in 27 B.C. and marked the end of the Via Flaminia.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Verona
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Verona dates to ca. A.D. 30.

nodes.title: San Martino ai Monti
nodes.description: San Martino ai Monti is a minor basilica in Rome. The basilica was founded on a site donated by Equitius during the reign of Pope St. Sylvester I in the fourth century.

nodes.title: Sa Sedda 'e sos Carros
nodes.description: A middle Bronze Age (ca. 1300 B.C.) nuragic settlement.

nodes.title: Forum of Cosa
nodes.description: The forum of Cosa functioned as the administrative center of the town and was the site of key administrative and ritual structures.

nodes.title: François Tomb
nodes.description: An important painted Etruscan tomb dating to the final quarter of the fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: Vagnari
nodes.description: A villa, vicus, and necropolis site in modern Puglia, Italy, located near the modern city of Gravina. The site was active from the first to fourth centuries CE.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Athena Saitis
nodes.description: A sanctuary atop mount Pontinos (near Lerna) mentioned by Pausanias as a ruin in his day. Its precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Theater at the Sanctuary of Asklepios, Epidauros
nodes.description: The Greek theater in the Sanctuary of Asklepios at Epidauros, renowned for its acoustics

nodes.title: Roman theater at Gosbecks
nodes.description: A Roman-British theater was excavated some 125 yards due south of the Gosbecks sanctuary.

nodes.title: Battery at Caer Mote
nodes.description: An earthwork enclosure that is of indeterminate date, although it is possibly Roman.

nodes.title: Roman villa at West Mersea
nodes.description: Remains of a tessellated floor pavement likely indicate the presence of a villa.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Loelle
nodes.description: A nuragic site near Caput Tyrsi.

nodes.title: Roman villa at Maasbracht
nodes.description: A Roman villa near the modern village of Maasbracht, Limburg, Netherlands, famous for its murals. The earliest structures on the site are dated to the second century CE, and the villa was abandoned by the middle of the third century.

nodes.title: Casa dell'Impluvium at Rusellae
nodes.description: The so-called "Casa dell'Impluvium" at Rusellae was excavated in the 1980s. It may present an important, early example of an Italic courtyard house. It dates to the sixth century B.C.

nodes.title: Arènes de Nîmes
nodes.description: The Arènes de Nîmes is a Roman amphitheater built at the end of the first century.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Scythopolis/Nysa
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Scythopolis/Nysa.

nodes.title: Forum of Scylletium/Scolacium
nodes.description: The Roman Forum of Scylletium/Scolacium.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Scylletium/Scolacium
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Scylletium/Scolacium.

nodes.title: Augusteum at Carthago Nova/Col. Urbs Iulia
nodes.description: A temple dedicated to the imperial cult during the reign of Augustus.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Egnatia/Gnathia
nodes.description: The so-called Roman amphitheater at Egnatia/Gnathia dates to the Iulio-Claudian period. It is an elliptical structure with walls in opus Africanum that were revetted with painted plaster.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Rudiae
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Rudiae is part of the complement of Roman buildings dating to the imperial period.

nodes.title: Roman Theater at Mérida
nodes.description: The Roman Theatre of Mérida was sponsored by Marcus Agrippa and dates ca. 16-15 B.C.

nodes.title: Surviving colonnade of the imperial temple at Mérida
nodes.description: The incorrectly so-called "Temple of Diana."

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Lepcis Magna
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Lepcis Magna dates to the first century A.D. and was dedicated to Nero.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Lepcis Magna
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Lepcis Magna was financed in the first century by Annobal Tapapius Rufus.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Ocriculum
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Ocriculum lies outside the city walls.

nodes.title: Roman Town House, Dorchester
nodes.description: A Romano-British house located within Colliton Park, Dorchester, Dorset.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Durno(no)varia
nodes.description: The Neolithic henge known as Maumbury Rings was adapted for use as an amphitheater space during the Roman period.

nodes.title: Sapperton and Cirencester amphitheatre
nodes.description: The Cirencester amphitheater is the second largest known in Britannia. Its earthworks supported tiered seats that could accommodate about 8,000 spectators. The amphitheater was converted to a fortified site in the fifth century during the Saxon invasions.

nodes.title: Roman baths at Fiesole
nodes.description: The Roman baths at Fiesole date to the time of Sulla in the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Drususstein (Drususstone) at Mogontiacum
nodes.description: The remains of a Roman monument at Mainz, perhaps a cenotaph erected in 9 B.C.

nodes.title: Römersteine im Zahlbachtal
nodes.description: Site of the remains of the Roman aqueduct, Römersteine im Zahlbachtal, in the district of Mainz-Bretzenheim.

nodes.title: Ras il-Wardija
nodes.description: A Punic-Roman sanctuary site located on the western coast of Gozo (Gaulos), Malta.

nodes.title: Grutenhäuschen
nodes.description: The Grutenhäuschen is a Roman funereal temple of the third or fourth century A.D. It has been reconstructed on site.

nodes.title: Ninfa
nodes.description: Ninfa is now a garden landscape covering more than 100 hectares in the territory of Cisterna di Latina. In archaeological terms, this landscape includes many remains stretching from protohistory to the Middle Ages.

nodes.title: Praetorian Guard Barracks at Amba Aradam Metro Station
nodes.description: Excavations for Rome's Metro C public transit line at the Amba Aradam Station revealed the remains of a second century A.D. barracks connected with the Praetorian Guard, along with a domus identified as that of a praetorian commandant. Although ruinous, the architectural complex demonstrates good preservation of some features, notably floor mosaics and wall paintings. The second century A.D. stratigraphic horizon was reached at a depth of approximately 12 meters.

nodes.title: Crocifisso del Tufo necropolis
nodes.description: A major necropolis of Volsinii that reaches its maximum extent between 550 and 450 BC. The necropolis is especially noteworthy on account of its orthogonal layout.

nodes.title: Mineral Water Hospital site
nodes.description: Remains of a large building discovered in Aquae Sulis. The site now lies on the grounds of the Royal National Hospital for Rheumatic Diseases.

nodes.title: Casa del pomarius Felix
nodes.description: This house (I.8.2) opens onto the Via dell'Abbondanza and is connected to the taberna at I.8.1 and the shop at I.8.3. It was named the "Casa del pomarius Felix" from electoral programmata painted on its facade. It has a typical atrium-peristyle plan.

nodes.title: Aqueduct west of Djebel Zid
nodes.description: An aqueduct connected to areas of centuriation north of Segermes

nodes.title: Temple of Jupiter Optimus Maximus
nodes.description: The poliadic temple of the city of Rome located on the Capitoline hill.

nodes.title: Corinth Theater
nodes.description: The origins of the theater at Corinth lie in the fifth century B.C. The complex was further expanded during the Hellenistic period. An elaborate renovation during the reign of Hadrian further improved the complex and added a new orchestra and scaenae frons.

nodes.title: Abu Simbel
nodes.description: The site of two temples constructed by Ramesses II, one dedicated to the triad of Amun, Ra-Horakhty, and Ptah, as well as the deified Ramesses, and another dedicated to Hathor and the pharaoh's wife Nefertari. The temple was relocated between 1964 and 1968 to prevent its submersion under Lake Nasser after the construction of the Aswan High Dam.

nodes.title: Pyramid of Menkaure
nodes.description: The Pyramid of Menkaure is the smallest of the three main pyramids located on the Giza plateau. It marks the tomb of the fourth dynasty Egyptian Pharaoh Menkaure.

nodes.title: North Agora
nodes.description: The Agora was the main civic square of the town. It was an enclosed space (ca. 202 x 72 m) surrounded by Ionic porticos on all sides. A fragmentary architrave inscription from the double north colonnade records its dedication by C. Julius Zoilos, the leading figure in the town in the 30s and 20s B.C.

nodes.title: Tomb of Hetepheres I
nodes.description: Hetepheres I was a 4th Dynasty queen of ancient Egypt (ca. 2600 B.C). She may have been a wife of the pharaoh Sneferu and the mother of Khufu.

nodes.title: Tempio della Tosse
nodes.description: The so-called "Tempio della Tosse" is an ancient Roman building along the river Anio. Its dating is problematic, but it is likely a building of late antiquity that is built on the site of an earlier villa. It has been interpreted as a nymphaeum, a temple, and also as a tomb.

nodes.title: Temple of the Sibyl
nodes.description: A second century B.C. Roman temple located on the acropolis of ancient Tibur.

nodes.title: Minor Acropolis, Norba
nodes.description: The so-called Minor Acropolis is located on the hill to the south of the Porta Maggiore. This area is surrounded by the urban enclosure wall and is terraced in polygonal masonry. Two platform temples of unknown assignation are to be found here.

nodes.title: Forum of Norba
nodes.description: The forum of Norba measures ca. 125 x 63 m.

nodes.title: Nesiotic League (First)
nodes.description: The Nesiotic league (the League of the Islanders) was a federal organization of Greek poleis in the Cyclades islands, organized in ca.  314/3 BCE under the direction of Antigonus Monophthalmus. Control passed to the Ptolemies ca. 287 BCE; the league eventually dissolved in the mid-3rd century BCE.

nodes.title: Nesiotic League (Second)
nodes.description: A re-establishment of the first Nesiotic League, the second Nesiotic League was founded by Rhodes in in c.  200 BCE and was dissolved in c. 167 BCE.

nodes.title: Lalibela
nodes.description: Lalibela is an ancient site in in the Amhara Region of Ethiopia known especially for its 11 rock-cut churches.

nodes.title: Spring east of Djebel Zid
nodes.description: Unlabeled feature captured from the Barrington Atlas

nodes.title: Dam over the Simbruina Stagna
nodes.description: Between Sublaqueum and Villa Neronis

nodes.title: Dam over the Simbruina Stagna
nodes.description: East of Sacro Speco

nodes.title: Bridge
nodes.description: Within the Villa Neronis

nodes.title: Unnamed Fort
nodes.description: Unlabeled feature captured from the Barrington Atlas

nodes.title: Kalavasos Ayios Dhimitrios
nodes.description: A Bronze Age site with monumental architecture in ancient Cyprus.

nodes.title: Ring of Brodgar
nodes.description: The Ring of Brodgar (also known as Brogar, or the Ring o' Brodgar) is a Neolithic henge and stone circle monument in Orkney, Scotland.

nodes.title: Torre delle Milizie
nodes.description: A fortified Medieval tower built adjacent to the Forum of Trajan in Rome.

nodes.title: Segustero
nodes.description: A Roman settlement along the Via Domitia.

nodes.title: Stoechades (islands)
nodes.description: A group of four islands off Hyères, France, in the Mediterranean Sea.

nodes.title: Tavia (river)
nodes.description: A river flowing from Alpes Maritimae and emptying in the Ligusticum Mare near Costa Bellene.

nodes.title: Tropaeum Augusti/Alpium Tropaeum/Alpis Summa/Alpis Maritima
nodes.description: A victory monument built by Augustus (5 B.C.) to commemorate the subjugation of the tribes of the western Alps. The Romans considered the spot to be "In Alpe Maritima".

nodes.title: Varus (river)
nodes.description: The Var river.

nodes.title: Vergoanum
nodes.description: An oppidum on Lero island.

nodes.title: Aqueduct supplying Alb(i)um Intimilium
nodes.description: Ancient name, if any, unknown (BAtlas 16 E2 unnamed aqueduct at Alb(i)um Intimilium)

nodes.title: Unnamed monastery
nodes.description: A monastery founded in late antiquity on the island then known as Lerina/Planasia (modern Île Saint-Honorat, France; BAtlas 16 D2 unnamed monastery)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 F1 unnamed monastery (on Gallinaria Ins.)

nodes.title: Merula
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 unlocated Merula fl.

nodes.title: Ad Publicanos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 G2 Ad Publicanos

nodes.title: Allobroges
nodes.description: The Allobroges were an ancient Gallic tribe whose territory lay between the between the Rhodanus fl. (Rhône River) and Lemannus L. (Lake Geneva).

nodes.title: Alpes Cottiae
nodes.description: Alpes Cottiae (Cottian Alps) are a mountain range located the southwestern part of the Alps. They take their name from Marcus Julius Cottius.

nodes.title: Alpes Graiae
nodes.description: A small Alpine province of the Roman Empire, comprising the Val d'Aosta region (Italy) and the Canton Valais (Switzerland). Augustus annexed the territory in 15 B.C.

nodes.title: Anderitum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 A4 Anderitum

nodes.title: Arar (river)
nodes.description: A river of Gaul, the modern Saône.

nodes.title: Arverni
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 B2 Arverni

nodes.title: Brigantio
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 H4 Brigantio

nodes.title: Casuaria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 G2 Casuaria

nodes.title: Caturiges
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 G4 Caturiges

nodes.title: Caturigomagus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 G4 Caturigomagus

nodes.title: Cebenna Mons
nodes.description: An ancient mountain range, attested in Caesar and Strabo, roughly coincident with the modern Cévennes in France, which inherited the name.

nodes.title: Col. Dea Vocontiorum
nodes.description: An Augustan colony in Gallia Narbonensis located in the valley of the Drôme river; an important cultic center of the Vocontii.

nodes.title: Col. Lugdunum
nodes.description: Lugdunum (modern Lyon in France) was a Roman military colony from 43 B.C. and a major center in Gaul. Marcus Agrippa was involved in its expansion and two Roman emperors, Claudius and Caracalla, were born there.

nodes.title: Col. Valentia
nodes.description: A settlement of the Segovellauni in Gallia Narbonensis.

nodes.title: Col. Vienna
nodes.description: A settlement of the Allobroges in Gallia Narbonensis that became a Roman colony in 47 BC.

nodes.title: Cularo/Gratianopolis
nodes.description: Cularo/Gratianopolis was a city of Gallia Narbonensis in the territory of the Allobroges on the Isère river.

nodes.title: Druna (river)
nodes.description: The Drôme river, a tributary of the Rhône.

nodes.title: Eburodunum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 G4 Eburodunum

nodes.title: Etanna
nodes.description: Etanna was a civitas of the Allobroges in Gallia Narbonensis.

nodes.title: Gabali
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 A5 Gabali

nodes.title: Gaesao/Tyrium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 H4 Gaesao/Tyrium

nodes.title: Isara (river)
nodes.description: The Isère river flows into the river Rhône at Pont-de-l'Isère.

nodes.title: Morginnum
nodes.description: Morginnum (Moirans) was a settlement of Gallia Narbonensis, along the road from Vienne to Alpis Cottia.

nodes.title: Octodurus/Forum Claudii Vallensium
nodes.description: Octodurus/Forum Claudii Vallensium (modern Martigny).

nodes.title: Poeninus M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 H2 Poeninus M.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Sa Mandra 'e Sa Giua
nodes.description: A nuraghe and associated village.

nodes.title: Cemetery of the Garamantes
nodes.description: Unnamed cemetery in the el-Agial escarpment

nodes.title: Nuraghe Rumanedda
nodes.description: A nuraghe located near Tottubella in the territory of Sassari.

nodes.title: La Celsa
nodes.description: At La Celsa (12.7 km of the Via Flaminia) are the remains of a cylindrical drum mausoleum that is likely part of a larger funereal complex.

nodes.title: San Gimignano
nodes.description: San Gimignano has origins as an Etruscan settlement but is best known as a Medieval town renowned for its fortified towers.

nodes.title: Salteras
nodes.description: An ancient and medieval Spanish village located north of Sevilla that belonged to the thirteenth-century kingdom of Alfonso X.

nodes.title: Flavian Amphitheater at Puteoli
nodes.description: The Flavian Amphitheater at Puteoli is an amphitheater constructed in the port town of Puteoli under the Flavian dynasty around 80 CE.

nodes.title: Velabrum
nodes.description: The Velabrum is a valley in Rome that connects the Forum Romanum to the Forum Boarium.

nodes.title: Pantheon
nodes.description: A temple in the Campus Martius of Rome that was first built by Marcus Agrippa (ca. 27-25 B.C.) and then re-built by the emperor Hadrian (after A.D. 126). In A.D. 609 the structure was consecrated as a Christian church, S. Maria ad Martyres.

nodes.title: Axios (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 A1 Axios fl.

nodes.title: Bolbe (lake)
nodes.description: Lake Volvi is located on the Chalkidiki peninsula.

nodes.title: Brea
nodes.description: A colony of Athens founded c. 445 BC.

nodes.title: Chalcidice
nodes.description: A peninsula in northern Greece. It was hotly contested between Athens and Sparta during the Peloponnesian War, and was later the site of important gold mines under Philip II of Macedon.

nodes.title: Dion
nodes.description: Dion was a settlement of Pieria located just south of Macedonia and held, traditionally, as the place of Orpheus' death and burial.

nodes.title: Edessa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 B3 Edessa

nodes.title: Erigon (river)
nodes.description: The Erigon is the largest tributary of the Axius river in Macedonia.

nodes.title: ‘Heracleustibus’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 D3 ‘Heracleustibus’

nodes.title: Lete
nodes.description: Lete was a strategically located city of ancient Macedonia.

nodes.title: Loudias (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 B3 Loudias fl.

nodes.title: Loudias L.
nodes.description: A shallow, marshy lake in central Macedonia that was drained in the twentieth century.

nodes.title: Macedonia (region)
nodes.description: The region of ancient Macedonia in the Balkan peninsula. The boundaries of the region have shifted significantly over time, and remain controversial.

nodes.title: Mekyberna
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 D4 Mekyberna

nodes.title: Mygdonia
nodes.description: Mygdonia was a region of ancient Macedonia.

nodes.title: Olympos (mountain in Greece)
nodes.description: Olympus is the highest mountain in Greece, located in the Olympus Range. In Greek mythology, it is the home of the Olympian gods.

nodes.title: Olynthos
nodes.description: Olynthos was an ancient city of the Chalcidice, founded in the seventh century B.C. and destroyed in 348 B.C. by the forces of Philip II of Macedon.

nodes.title: Pallene/Phlegra
nodes.description: Pallene/Phlegra is the westernmost of the three headlands of Chalcidice that project into the Aegean Sea.

nodes.title: Pehčevo
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 C1 Pehčevo

nodes.title: Pella/Diokletianoupolis
nodes.description: Capital of the Kingdom of Macedonia.

nodes.title: Perraibia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 A4 Perraibia

nodes.title: Pieria
nodes.description: Originally the territory of the Pieres, later incoporated into Macedonia

nodes.title: Poteidaia/Kassandreia
nodes.description: Poteidaia/Kassandreia was a Greek colony founded ca. 600 BC by Corinthians on the peninsula of Pallene in western Chalcidice. The site received a Roman colony in 43 B.C. and in 30 B.C. Augustus settled veterans there, renaming it as Colonia Iulia Augusta Cassandrensis.

nodes.title: Pydna
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 C4 Pydna

nodes.title: Stobi
nodes.description: An ancient town of Paeonia that eventually became the capital of the Roman province of Macedonia Salutaris.

nodes.title: Thermaicus Sinus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 C4 Thermaicus Sinus

nodes.title: Thessalonica
nodes.description: A city of northern Greece founded by Cassander of Macedon ca. 315 BC; important center of the Roman and Late Antique.

nodes.title: Zeus Olympios, T.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 B4 Zeus Olympios, T.
