nodes.title: Tiberioi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 unlocated Tiberioi

nodes.title: Tritonos
nodes.description: A town (polichnion) in ancient Macedonia, mentioned by Stephanus. Its precise location is unlocated today.

nodes.title: Andrisimoundou (Akron)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 5 inset Andrisimoundou (Akron)

nodes.title: Anourogrammon/Palaesimundum?
nodes.description: An ancient town of Sri Lanka, an accounting of which was given to the emperor Claudius by Annius Plocamus, who spent six months there.

nodes.title: Banabasi
nodes.description: A settlement in south India that has served as a regional administrative and sacred center since at least the beginning of the first millennium CE.

nodes.title: Barous(s)ai? (islands)

nodes.title: Boreion Pr.

nodes.title: Maniolai (islands)
nodes.description: Islands mentioned in Ptolemy. They may correspond to the modern Andaman islands in the Bay of Bengal.

nodes.title: Mantai
nodes.description: Mantai was an ancient coastal town and harbor of northern Sri Lanka.

nodes.title: Matara
nodes.description: A modern city of Sri Lanka whence a hoard of ancient coins (now in the British museum) that included locally minted, late Roman imitations.

nodes.title: Megisba Stagnum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 5 inset Megisba Stagnum

nodes.title: Abydos
nodes.description: A city of Mysia located on the Hellespont.

nodes.title: Aianteion
nodes.description: Aianteion was a port town in the Troad located near the putative Tomb of Ajax, with which it shared a name.

nodes.title: Amphipolis

nodes.title: Thracia
nodes.description: Thracia refers to a territory occupied by the Thraci (or Thracians), a human population of the northern Balkan Peninsula whose reach stretched from the north Aegean Sea to the Danube river. Parts of Thracia would eventually become incorporated into the Roman provinces of Moesia and Thracia.

nodes.description: The capital city of the parricidal King Kassapa I (A.D. 477–95). The site was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1982.

nodes.title: Monte Amiata

nodes.title: Villa of the Lillies (Amnisos)

nodes.title: Herculaneum Gate

nodes.title: Terrace of Zeus
nodes.description: The so-called "Terrace of Zeus" or "Terrazza di Zeus" at Elea-Velia.

nodes.title: Anubieion at Saqqarah
nodes.description: Late-period district of Saqqara, adjacent to the Teti Pyramid.

nodes.title: So-called Early Christian Basilica
nodes.description: A small basilica located outside the walls of the ancient Greek city of Akragas, at the foot of the so-called Temple of Juno, on the eastern slopes of the Hill of the Temples, in an area previously occupied by the necropolis of the late Roman period.

nodes.title: Necropolis of Porta Ercolano
nodes.description: The Porta Ercolano necropolis, excavated between 1763 and 1838, is the best known of Pompeii's necropoleis, in use from the middle of the first century BC until the first century AD.

nodes.title: Castello di Pieve del Vescovo
nodes.description: The present late fourteenth-century castle on the site is first mentioned in a papal bull of 1206.

nodes.title: House of the Golden Bracelet
nodes.description: The so-called "House of the Golden Bracelet" is a domus at Pompeii located on the Vicolo del Farmacista. It takes its name from the discovery of the remains of a woman wearing a thick gold bracelet.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Theveste → Thelepte

nodes.title: Caprarienses?
nodes.description: A tribe of North Africa, the Caprarianses ("inhabitants of a region full of goats") dwelt in the Montes Caprarienses and were the neighbors of the Abannae.

nodes.title: Caprarienses? M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 34 B3 Caprarienses? M.

nodes.title: Diana Veteranorum
nodes.description: Diana Veteranorum was a vicus in Numidia founded for veterans of Legio III Augusta. It became a municipium in A.D. 162.

nodes.title: Lambaesis
nodes.description: A Roman settlement established in the second century A.D. as the legionary base of Legio III Augusta

nodes.title: Çamlıdere
nodes.description: Modern name for an otherwise unnamed ancient settlement. It may have been a possession of the Ptolemies, Rhodes, and the Attalid kingdom, and was at least peripherally involved with Rome's war against Aristonikos as a Roman ally.

nodes.title: Başkale
nodes.description: Başkale (Turkish "Main Castle") is a town and district located in Van Province in south-eastern Turkey. According to an inscription in the Urartean language of the Urartean king Minua (9th/8th century BCE) on a stone block (A 5-52) the fortress located here was built by Minua and was given the name "City of the God Haldi".

nodes.title: tribus Pollia
nodes.description: The tribus Pollia was one of the older rural tribes of Rome.

nodes.title: Emar
nodes.description: An important Bronze Age trading center in northern Syria. The site is known today as Tell Meskene.

nodes.title: Minorca (island)
nodes.description: Minorca is one of the Balearic Islands of the Mediterranean Sea. Its name likely derives from the Latin 'Insula minor'.

nodes.title: Basilica Hilariana
nodes.description: A basilica erected on the Caelian Hill in Rome under the patronage of Manius Publicus Hilarus and connected to the cult of Cybele and Attis.

nodes.title: Fagutal
nodes.description: Fagutal is the name of the western spur of the Esquiline hill in Rome.

nodes.title: Tempio di Venere, Baiae
nodes.description: The so-called "Tempio di Venere" is likely part of a bathing complex dating to the reign of Hadrian. The surviving structure has an octagonal plan.

nodes.title: Piazza d'Armi
nodes.description: The site of the arx of ancient Veii located on the southern spur of the volcanic plateau on which the city is located. There is archaeological evidence for an initial occupation phase of the ninth century B.C. By the seventh century B.C., the area shows evidence for adoption of rectilinear huts and assumes an orthogonal street grid.

nodes.title: Archaeological area of Piano della Comunità
nodes.description: The archaeological area of Piano (or Quarto) di Comunità is an area of Etrusco-Roman Veii where there is evidence for a Republican domus that is modified during the Augustan period. The area is then used as a necropolis in Late Antiquity (fourth and fifth centuries).

nodes.title: Campetti - Decumano
nodes.description: At Campetti - Decumano, in the southwestern part of Veii near the "Portonaccio" gate, there is evidence for a sacred complex that includes a therapeutic bath dating to the Roman period. Some residential functions emerged in Late Antiquity.

nodes.title: Archaeological area of Villa di Campetti
nodes.description: The site of a Roman villa complex covering ca. 10,000 square meters. The villa was built in the late republican period (second-first centuries B.C.) on the hillside adjacent to the Archaic Portonaccio sanctuary.

nodes.title: Roman baths at Trier
nodes.description: The Imperial Baths at Trier (also referred to as "Kaiserthermen") are a large Roman bath complex in Trier, Germany. The site was designated as part of the "Roman Monuments, Cathedral of St. Peter and Church of Our Lady in Trier", a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The complex dates to the fourth century A.D.

nodes.title: Barbarathermen at Trier
nodes.description: Dating to the second century, the so-called "Barbara Baths" (Barbarathermen in German) are the largest Roman bath complex known north of the Alps. The bath complex was reused first as a Medieval castle and then as a seventeenth century Jesuit college. The ruins were designated as part of the "Roman Monuments, Cathedral of St. Peter and Church of Our Lady in Trier" UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1986.

nodes.title: Aula Palatina
nodes.description: The Aula Palatina is a Roman Imperial Basilica of the emperor Constantine (German: Konstantinbasilika) located at Trier, Germany. It was built ca. A.D. 310 as part of a Roman palace complex.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Augustomagus
nodes.description: A small, first-century amphitheater with an ellipsoidal plan.

nodes.title: Arcadian Gate
nodes.description: The Arcadian Gate is a monumental city gate constructed in the fourth century BCE in Messene.

nodes.title: Hutcheson Hill
nodes.description: Findspot of two Roman distance slabs along the line of the Antonine Wall: RIB 2198 (found in 1865) and 3507 (found in 1969).

nodes.title: Triopium
nodes.description: Sanctuary of Apollo Triopios, known as the Triopion, in the territory of Knidos, was the federal sanctuary of the Dorian hexapolis.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Hercules Victor
nodes.description: The Sanctuary of Hercules Victor in Tivoli is a significant cult place of the second century B.C. The sanctuary is composed of a vaulted, terraced platform that support the temple, its porticoes, and a theater.

nodes.title: Porta Maggiore, Norba
nodes.description: The main gate, defended by a bastion, of the Middle Republican fortifications of the city. The gate still stands to a height of ca. 13 m.

nodes.title: Monte d'Accoddi
nodes.description: A ramped, megalithic structure in Sardinia dated to around 2700-2000 BC.

nodes.title: *Ištunda
nodes.description: *Ištunda is a city(-state) in Tabal. It is mentioned in eighth-century-BC Assyrian sources, especially in royal inscriptions of Tiglath-pileser III (r. 744-727 BC).

nodes.title: *Kulummu
nodes.description: Kulummu is a city (and/or kingdom) in Tabal.

nodes.title: Hurri/Ba'il-hurri
nodes.description: A mountain, probably located on Cyprus, possibly near Larnaka/Kition, perhaps in the vicinity of Stavrovouni Monastery.

nodes.title: Ušnanis
nodes.description: Ušnanis is a Quean fortress located on the Cilician plain. In the eighth century BC, perhaps only for a short time, Phrygia controlled the territory in which Ušnanis was located. The Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705), after his armies defeated the Phrygian king Midas (= Mitâ of Musku), restored Ušnanis to Que, which was then a province of the Assyrian Empire.

nodes.title: Qumasi
nodes.description: Qumasi is a Quean fortress located on the Cilician plain. In the eighth century BC, perhaps only for a short time, Phrygia controlled the territory in which Qumasi was located. The Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705), after his armies defeated the Phrygian king Midas (= Mitâ of Musku), restored Qumasi to Que, which was then a province of the Assyrian Empire.

nodes.title: Abarnani
nodes.description: Abarnani is a fortified city in Que, probably in the eastern part of the Cilician plain. The city is mentioned with Lusanda and Kisuatni in royal inscriptions of the Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC).

nodes.title: Lusanda
nodes.description: Lusanda is a fortified city in Que, probably in the eastern part of the Cilician plain. The city is mentioned with Abarnani and Kisuatni in royal inscriptions of the Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC).

nodes.title: Kisuatni
nodes.description: Kisuatni is a fortified city in Que, probably in the eastern part of the Cilician plain. The city is mentioned with Abarnani and Lusanda in royal inscriptions of the Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC).

nodes.title: Porta Marina
nodes.description: A city gate at the western terminus of the Strada della Marina.

nodes.title: Temple of Venus
nodes.description: The Temple of Venus (VIII,1) is located adjacent to Pompeii's Porta Marina. The site was cleared in the early years of the colony to make way for the temple. Seriously damaged by the AD 62 earthquake, the sanctuary was still being rebuilt at the time of its ultimate destruction.

nodes.title: Luceres
nodes.description: An early Roman tribe from the time of Romulus.

nodes.title: Galatas
nodes.description: A Minoan palatial center on Crete dated ca. 1700-1600 BC that was discovered in the 1990s.

nodes.title: Caesarea Mithraeum
nodes.description: The Mithraeum at Caesarea is only one of two excavated from the eastern half of the Roman empire.

nodes.title: Temple of Poseidon at Taranto
nodes.description: A Doric temple dating to the sixth century B.C.

nodes.title: Son Fornés
nodes.description: A prehistoric, Talaiotic settlement dating from the tenth to mid-seventh centuries B.C. on the island of Majorca.

nodes.title: Sa Caleta
nodes.description: A Phoenician settlement of the eighth and seventh centuries B.C.

nodes.title: Sacred Grove near Mount Pontinos
nodes.description: According to Pausanias, there was a grove of plane trees, with temples and dedications to Aphrodite, Demeter, and Dionysos that stretched from the foot of Mount Pontinus (near Lerna) "to the sea." Its precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Val d'Orcia
nodes.description: A cultural landscape in the agricultural hinterland of Siena, Italy, the Val d'Orcia was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2004.

nodes.title: Mersea Island
nodes.description: An island located in the Blackwater and Colne estuaries to the south-east of Colchester.

nodes.title: Anavarza Kalesi
nodes.description: Anavarza Kalesi is a large fortress of Byzantine and Armenian date on probable Roman foundations. It shares its Turkish name with the 200m high limestone outcrop on which it stands. This outcrop served as the acropolis of ancient Anazarbos, and it also has been suggested as a location for the earlier "Kundu," which is mentioned in Akkadian sources.

nodes.title: Kululu Kalesi
nodes.description: Kululu Kalesi is a proposed location of ancient Artulu.

nodes.title: Bozca
nodes.description: A modern village in the Avanos district of Turkey's Nevşehir province. Bozca is one of the proposed locations of ancient *Atuna.

nodes.title: Ayio Gala
nodes.description: Site in the northwestern corner of the island of Chios consisting of a two caves, both containing pottery and other remains dated to the Neolithic period. The entrance to the upper cave is located inside the Panayia Galactonosera chapel.

nodes.title: Temple to Ramesses II at Abu Simbel
nodes.description: The larger of the two temples at Abu Simbel, dedicated to the triad of Amun, Ra-Horakhty, and Ptah, as well as the deified Ramesses II. The temple was relocated between 1964 and 1968 to prevent its submersion under Lake Nasser after the construction of the Aswan High Dam.

nodes.title: Temple of Victory
nodes.description: A Greek temple of the Doric order (peripteral hexastyle), built in the fifth century BC, possibly to celebrate a victory against the Carthaginians. Its ruins are still visible in the archaeological site of Himera.

nodes.title: Fournou Korifi
nodes.description: An Early Minoan site in south Crete; findspot of the libation vessel known as the 'Goddess of Myrtos'.

nodes.title: Temple of Artemis Azzanathkona
nodes.description: The temple of a syncretized incarnation of Artemis built at Dura-Europos in the Hellenistic period.

nodes.title: Domus dei Coiedii
nodes.description: The so-called Domus dei Coiedii is a domus located at Suasa. It dates to the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Arch of Malborghetto
nodes.description: A fourth century A.D. tetrapylon arch at the intersection of the Via Flaminia and a road linking the Via Tiberina and Veii.

nodes.title: Africa (diocese)
nodes.description: The late Roman diocese of Africa.

nodes.title: Mauretania Caesariensis (late Roman province)
nodes.description: A late Roman province within the diocese of Africa.

nodes.title: Forum Holitorium
nodes.description: The Forum Holitorium was the vegetable market of ancient Rome, situated outside the Porta Carmentalis in the southern Campus Martius. This area was bounded by the Forum Boarium and the Circus Flaminius.

nodes.title: Tomb of Hilarus Fuscus
nodes.description: The Late Republican tomb of the freedman Hilarus Fuscus along the Via Appia (ca. 30 B.C.).

nodes.title: tribus Ramnes
nodes.description: The name of a Roman tribe dating from the earliest period of Roman history.

nodes.title: House of the Vettii
nodes.description: The so-called House of the Vettii (VI, 15, 1) is a luxurious townhouse (domus) located in Pompeii. The house's owners in its final phase were the freedmen brothers Aulus Vettius Conviva, an Augustalis, and Aulus Vettius Restitutus. Among other features the house is important for its Fourth Style wall paintings.

nodes.title: Via Francigena
nodes.description: The Via Francigena is a Medieval pilgrimage route connecting Canterbury, England, and Rome.

nodes.title: Chatal Höyük (Amuq)
nodes.description: Mound site in the Amuq Plain inhabited from the late 4th millennium BCE-mid-1st millennium BCE. In the Late Bronze Age Chatal Höyük was the site of a sizeable town with connections to the Hittite Empire. In the Iron Age the town was within the sphere of the Syro-Hittite state of Unqi, based at Tell Tayinat/Kinaliya. The town gradually declined, but remained inhabited without interruption until at least the fifth century BCE.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Fréjus
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Fréjus dates to the reign of Tiberius.

nodes.title: Tomb of Rekhmire at Thebes
nodes.description: Theban Tomb 100 (TT100), the burial place of Rekhmire, a noble of the 18th dynasty.

nodes.title: Arch of Germanicus
nodes.description: A triumphal arch built by C. Julius Rufus, and dedicated to Tiberius and his adoptive sons, Drusus Caesar and Germanicus.

nodes.title: Porta Capuana
nodes.description: A Roman gate of Aquinum located on the Via Latina.

nodes.title: Mausoleum of C. Ennius Marsus
nodes.description: C. Ennius Marsus was duovir at Saepinum.

nodes.title: Arch of Lucius Neratius Priscus
nodes.description: An arch dedicated to Lucius Neratius Priscus, suffect consul of A.D. 97 and governor of Germania Inferior.

nodes.title: Arch of Trajan
nodes.description: An arch dedicated to Trajan on the Via Flaminia at Carsulae, also known as the Arco di San Damiano.

nodes.title: Porta Bovianum
nodes.description: The western gateway of Saepinum.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Ancona
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Ancona could accommodate 8,000 to 10,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Forum of Conimbriga
nodes.description: The Roman forum of Conímbriga.

nodes.title: Tuna el-Gebel
nodes.description: Tuna el-Gebel was the necropolis serving Schmun/Khmun (Hermopolis Magna).

nodes.title: Theatre of Palmyra
nodes.description: Theatre in the Ancient City of Palmyra. Coordinates determined by eye in Google Earth in November 2012, following description in UNESCO World Heritage List.

nodes.title: Berretta del Prete
nodes.description: A circular Roman mausoleum with a distinctive cupola located at the ninth mile of the Via Appia.

nodes.title: Sepulcrum Statiliorum
nodes.description: A columbarium tomb of the slaves and freedmen of the Statilii, and of M. Statilius Taurus, consul in A.D. 44.

nodes.title: Cypro-Phoenician port hangars of Kition
nodes.description: Covered sheds (neoria) in the ancient harbor of Kition used in the construction and repair of warships by the Phoenician rulers of the city during the fifth century BCE.

nodes.title: Tholos at the Sanctuary of Asklepios, Epidauros
nodes.description: The Tholos, a circular structure in the Sanctuary of Asklepios at Epidaurus, was constructed beginning between 365-360 BCE. The Tholos was designed by Polykleitos the Younger and features Doric architecture as well as a constructed labyrinth beneath the floor of the structure.

nodes.title: Tomb Garden of C. Octabios Eutyches and Munatios Dionysios at Hypaipa
nodes.description: Tomb garden built by C. Octabios (Octavius) Eutyches, Munatius Dionysius, and several others in Hypaipa

nodes.title: Funerary Grove of Epikrates and Tomb Garden of Tertia and Secundus at Nakrason
nodes.description: A funerary grove and tomb garden built by one Epikrates, attested by inscriptions on a stele, in the unlocated Anatolian settlement of Nakrason.

nodes.title: Stadium of Perge
nodes.description: A well-preserved stadium of the Roman period.

nodes.title: Lycian League
nodes.description: Perhaps formed to protest the annexation of Lycia by Rhodes, by 168–7 BCE the league appears to have gained quasi-autonomy under the domination of Rome. Although the league was a party to a treaty with Iulius Caesar in 46 BCE, by 43 CE the region was annexed by Claudius into the province of Lycia; the league survived and had authority over some local customs and legal matters.

nodes.title: Macedonia (Hellenistic kingdom)
nodes.description: A major kingdom in the region of Macedon/Macedonia. In 306 BCE the successors of Alexander III declared themselves as kings, effectively creating independent kingdoms. Lysimachus originally controlled the region of Macedonia with parts of Asia Minor; afterwards, Macedonia was briefly under the control of Seleucus I and Ptolemy Keraunos until the latter's death in 279 BCE. By 277 BCE Antigonus II Gonatas controlled the kingdom. It would remain under the Antigonid dynasty until the Romans defeated Perseus, the final Antigonid king, and dissolved the kingdom following the battle of Pydna in 168 BCE.

nodes.title: Temple of the Storm God at Aleppo
nodes.description: Bronze Age temple dedicated to the weather god Hadad in the citadel of Halab (modern Aleppo).

nodes.title: Roman aqueduct, Spello
nodes.description: An aqueduct carrying water to Spello from the hills below Collepino.

nodes.title: Temple of Mars Ultor
nodes.description: The Temple of Mars Ultor was dedicated in the Forum of Augustus in 2 B.C., fulfilling a vow that Octavian had made to the god in 42 B.C.

nodes.title: Gesher
nodes.description: Site of a pre-pottery Neolithic settlement and a series of Middle Bronze Age tombs, located in the central Jordan Valley.

nodes.title: Almo (river)
nodes.description: A small river of the Ager Romanus that once joined the Tiber just below the walls of Rome. Almo, the eldest son of Tyrrhus, who is one of the heroes in Virgil's Aeneid, shares the river's name.

nodes.title: Lapis Niger
nodes.description: A shrine in the Forum Romanum adjacent to the Republican comitium, recognizable by the distinctive black paving stones that covered it in the later republican period. The shrine has been associated, in tradition, with the tomb of Romulus and/or of Faustulus. Giacomo Boni excavated the site between 1899 and 1905.

nodes.title: Temple Grove of Nikephorion at Pergamum
nodes.description: A temple grove at the Nikephorion in the settlement of Pergamum. Mentioned by Polybius, the precise location of the grove is not known today.

nodes.title: Durolevum
nodes.description: A minor settlement along Watling Street. It may have been located at Ospringe in Kent.

nodes.title: City wall of Ameria
nodes.description: The polygonal masonry circuit wall of ancient Ameria.

nodes.title: Palaikastro, Crete
nodes.description: Palaikastro, located in eastern Crete, was an important trading center in antiquity, from the Bronze Age going forward.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Biunisi
nodes.description: A single-tower nuraghe with a likely associated village.

nodes.title: So-called Area L in Berenike
nodes.description: The ruins of an ancient building with a large peristyle, probably built around the second century AD, in the southwest area of the archaeological site of Sidi Khiribech, in Berenike (modern Banghazi).

nodes.title: So-called Area H in Berenike
nodes.description: The ruins of a house of the early Roman period at the archaeological site of Sidi Khiribech, in Berenike. The house had a courtyard with a peristyle. Some of the internal walls were decorated with frescoes representing the Muses.

nodes.title: Carrowkeel Megalithic Cemetery
nodes.description: A Neolithic cemetery dated to 3400 to 3100 BC. Fourteen passage tombs have been identified.

nodes.title: Tibradden Chambered Cairn
nodes.description: A prehistoric cairn located atop Tibradden Mountain.

nodes.title: Uragh Stone Circle
nodes.description: A stone circle measuring 33 by 26 feet with 11 standing stones located near Gleninchaquin Park, Tuosist, County Kerry, Ireland.

nodes.title: Kizkapanli
nodes.description: A modern village near the Pazarcik dam in Turkey. The Pazarcik Stele, which bears inscriptions of the Assyrian kings Adad-nerari III and Shalmaneser IV, was discovered here.

nodes.title: Agora of Onchestos
nodes.description: Approximate center point of agora of Onchestos sanctuary visible in satellite imagery.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Hispellum
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Hispellum dates to the first century.

nodes.title: Porta Consolare
nodes.description: The Porta Consolare was likely the primary gateway in Hispellum's Roman-era fortification wall.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Béziers
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Béziers dates ca. A.D. 80, during the Flavian period. It measured ca. 110 by 90 meters and could accommodate 15,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Iol Caesarea
nodes.description: An important early example of Roman theatral architecture.

nodes.title: Simitthu Roman theater
nodes.description: The Roman theater at, an ancient Roman-Berber town in northwestern Tunisia.

nodes.title: Capitol Baths
nodes.description: A bath complex dating to the later second century that were subsequently repurposed as a Christian basilica.

nodes.title: Forum of Mactaris
nodes.description: One of two fora at Mactaris. This earlier square is adjacent to the Arch of Trajan.

nodes.title: Vigna Pia necropolis
nodes.description: An imperial necropolis with columbarium tombs and a family tomb connected with the gens Atilia Romana.

nodes.title: Via Gemina
nodes.description: The Via Gemina was a Roman road linking Aquileia and Emona.

nodes.title: Via Domitiana
nodes.description: A Roman road of Campania built during the reign of Domitian.

nodes.title: Theater at Bodrum
nodes.description: The Theater at Bodrum is dedicated to Ares.

nodes.title: Tomb of Nebamun at Thebes
nodes.description: Theban Tomb no. 65 (TT65), the tomb of Nebamun, dated to the reign of Hatshepsut. The tomb was reused in the Twentieth Dynasty for Imiseba, a member of the Theban Clergy. In late antiquity it (along with several of the surrounding tombs) was repurposed as an anchorite dwelling, called in modern times the "Monastery of Cyriacus."

nodes.title: Santa Maria Antiqua
nodes.description: A fifth-century A.D. Christian church built in the Forum Romanum at the foot of the Palatine Hill.

nodes.title: Aquae Regiae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 E1 Aquae Regiae

nodes.title: Bararus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 G2 Bararus

nodes.title: Byzacium
nodes.description: The historical region of coastal Tunisia south of Carthage

nodes.title: Cercina
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 H3 Cercina

nodes.title: Cercina (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 H3 Cercina Ins.

nodes.title: Cillium
nodes.description: Cillium (modern Kasserine, Tunisia) occupies a strategic location in the gap between the Semmama and Chambi mountains, along the road from Gafsa.

nodes.title: Fossatum Africae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 B4 Fossatum Africae

nodes.title: Hadrumetum/Iustinianopolis
nodes.description: Hadrumetum/Iustinianopolis was an important ancient port in North Africa. Founded by Phoenicians, the site pre-dated Carthage. Under Roman administration the site prospered and Trajan assigned it colonial status as Colonia Concordia Ulpia Trajana Augusta Frugifera Hadrumetina.

nodes.title: Lepti Minus
nodes.description: Lepti Minus was an ancient port city in Tunisia.

nodes.title: Libyphoenices
nodes.description: A numerous, loosely affiliated people of the Byzacium and Tripolitana coasts

nodes.title: Machounoi
nodes.description: A small tribe on the coast of the Syrtis Minor

nodes.title: Mactaris
nodes.description: A Numidian site that eventually became a Roman colony in the second century AD.

nodes.title: Masclianae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 E2 Masclianae

nodes.title: Meneg(g)ere?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 B2 Meneg(g)ere?

nodes.title: Sufes
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 D1 Sufes

nodes.title: Sufetula
nodes.description: Sufetula, the modern Sbeitla, was founded in the later first century A.D. and was located at a major road junction.

nodes.title: Sullecthum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 H2 Sullecthum

nodes.title: Thelepte
nodes.description: Thelepte was a Roman city in Africa Byzacena. It achieved municipal status perhaps in the time of Vespasian and became a colonia under Trajan. The city played an important administrative role in fourth century AD north Africa.

nodes.title: Theveste
nodes.description: Theveste (modern Tébessa, Algeria) became a Roman center and, in the Imperial period, the Legio III Augusta was raised there. In later times Theveste is connected with the Donatists.

nodes.title: Thysdrus
nodes.description: Thysdrus (modern El Djem, Tunisia) was a Punic and Roman city of North Africa. It flourished in the second century A.D. and built its massive amphitheater in the third century. After an abortive revolt in A.D. 238, the city was destroyed by soldiers loyal to Maximinus Thrax.

nodes.title: Unnamed Aqueduct at Cillium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 C2 unnamed aqueduct (at Cillium)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Hadrumetum → Vicus Augusti? → Aquae Regiae → Masclianae → Sufetula

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Thysdrus → Aquae Regiae → Masclianae → Sufetula → Cillium → Meneg(g)ere? → Theveste

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Aquae Regiae → Sufes

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Hadrumetum → Lepti Minus → Thysdrus → Usil(l)a → Thaenae

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Taparura → Bararus → Sullecthum

nodes.title: Casacce necropolis
nodes.description: A rock-cut necropolis at Blera with tombs of the Hellenistic period.

nodes.title: Ticis? (river)
nodes.description: The Muga river of Catalonia.

nodes.title: Tolosa
nodes.description: Tolosa (modern Toulouse) was a city of Gallia Narbonensis and the metropolis of the Volcae Tectosages.

nodes.title: Torre de los Escipiones
nodes.description: A first century AD tower tomb built 6 km from Tarraco, the Torre dels Escipions has been listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

nodes.title: Tulcis (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 G4 Tulcis fl.

nodes.title: Uxama (Argaela)
nodes.description: Uxama Argaela was a Celtiberian settlement of the Arevaci. The site was subsequently conquered by the Romans.

nodes.title: Varduli
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 D2 Varduli

nodes.title: Vascones
nodes.description: An ancient, pre-Roman Iberian people that inhabited the regions of Navarre, Lower La Rioja, and northwestern Aragon.

nodes.title: Vindeleia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 B3 Vindeleia

nodes.title: (Volcae) Tectosages
nodes.description: A Gallic people of the Languedoc. Their chief town was Tolosa.

nodes.title: Andelos aqueduct
nodes.description: Unlabeled on the Barrington Atlas, this aqueduct supplied ancient Andelos

nodes.title: Pont del Diable (aqueduct)
nodes.description: A Roman aqueduct built to supply the city of Tarraco.

nodes.title: Bridge of Mantible
nodes.description: The Bridge of Mantible (also known as Puente de Mantible) crosses the Ebro river northwest of Vareia. It is a Roman segmental arch bridge that likely dates to the second century AD.

nodes.title: Iturranduz Dam
nodes.description: Unlabeled on the Barrington Atlas, this dam is popularly known as the "Devil's Bridge."

nodes.title: Pech Maho
nodes.description: Pech Maho was an indigenous oppidum and Greek way station labeled no. 54 on Barrington Atlas map 25.

nodes.title: Centcelles Roman villa
nodes.description: A Roman villa located in the municipality of Constantí, in Catalonia. Among its finds are a dome mosaic with a Christian theme that numbers among the earliest known examples in the Roman world (4th century AD.)

nodes.title: Melem-kurukurra-dulla
nodes.description: According to an inscription of the Neo-Babylonian king Nabonidus, the name of the wall of Kish was Melem-kurukurra-dulla, whose Sumerian ceremonial name means "(Whose) Radiance Spreads over (All) Lands."

nodes.title: Jebel Khalid
nodes.description: Hellenistic settlement constructed in the early 3rd century BCE and abandoned in the 70s BCE. Part of the site seems to have been used later as a Roman camp or fort.

nodes.title: Acropolis palace at Jebel Khalid
nodes.description: Hellenistic palace at the city of Jebel Khalid on the west bank of the Euphrates.

nodes.title: tribus Tromentina
nodes.description: A later rural tribe of ancient Rome, which was established in 387 B.C.

nodes.title: tribus Voturia
nodes.description: The tribus Voturia was an older rural tribe of ancient Rome.

nodes.title: Cursus Barrows (Burial Mounds)
nodes.description: A grouping of burial mounds (named Cursus Barrows) located very close to Stonehenge.

nodes.title: Necropolis near Randazzo, Sicily
nodes.description: A necropolis with remains dating to the fifth century B.C.

nodes.title: Roman city gate, Mainz
nodes.description: A preserved gate of the Roman city wall in the district Mainz-Kästrich.

nodes.title: Villa San Marco
nodes.description: The Villa San Marco originates in the Augustan period and was subsequently expanded during the reign of Claudius. Its owner may have been a freedman of Claudius.

nodes.title: Villa Arianna
nodes.description: The so-called "Villa Arianna" at Stabiae is typically considered one of the earliest villas at the site and is often dated to the second century B.C.

nodes.title: Villa of Publius Fannius Synistor
nodes.description: The Villa of Publius Fannius Synistor was built after the middle of the first century B.C. and was ultimately destroyed by the eruption of Mt. Vesuvius. The villa may have been owned by P. Fannius Synistor and/or L. Herennius Florus.

nodes.title: Villa of Numerius Popidius Florus
nodes.description: The Villa of Numerius Popidius Florus dates to the early first century B.C. It was modified several times before its destruction in A.D. 79.

nodes.title: Villa Regina, Boscoreale
nodes.description: A villa rustica at Boscoreale discovered in 1977. This is the only villa site currently visible and has been subjected to more modern excavation and analysis.

nodes.title: Villa in via Casone Grotta
nodes.description: A Roman villa at Boscoreale discovered in 1986 and only partially excavated.

nodes.title: Villa on the Property of D'Acunzo
nodes.description: A villa rustica excavated and reinterred in 1903 located near the Boscoreale train station.

nodes.title: Ash Altar of Zeus Lykaios
nodes.description: The ash altar of Zeus Lykaios on the southern peak of Mt. Lykaion.

nodes.title: Abbaye Saint-Pierre de Moissac
nodes.description: An important monastery founded probably in the seventh century of the common era.

nodes.title: Via Sebaste: Apollonia ↔ Antiochia ↔ Neapolis
nodes.description: A road network in Pisidia originally built by the governor Cornutus Aquila, beginning ca. 6 BC.

nodes.title: Ekalte
nodes.description: Ekalte, modern Tall Munbāqa, is a medium-sized Bronze Age settlement on the left bank of the Euphrates in northern Syria, ca. 85 kilometres east of Aleppo. Inhabited as early as 2,000 BCE, Ekalte grew to become a significant urban centre in the Late Bronze Age (ca. 1600-1200 BCE). Excavations by the German Oriental Institute since 1969 have unearthed extensive tracts of the urban landscape. Today, the site is partially submerged beneath the waters of the Lake Assad.

nodes.title: Circus of Maxentius
nodes.description: The Circus of Maxentius is part of a complex of buildings built by emperor Maxentius on the Via Appia between A.D. 306 and 312.

nodes.title: Mausoleum at Halicarnassus
nodes.description: The Mausoleum at Halicarnassus is a tomb built between 353 and 350 B.C. for Mausolus, a satrap in the Persian Empire. Antipater of Sidon identified it as one of his Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.

nodes.title: Greek theater of Morgantina
nodes.description: The Greek theater of Morgantina was built during the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Greek theater of Taormina
nodes.description: The Greek theater of Taormina was built originally in the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Roman baths of Taormina
nodes.description: The Roman baths of Taormina are built atop a public building of the Hellenistic period. The Roman baths originally fronted on the forum and were expanded in the second century.

nodes.title: Temple of Amenhotep II
nodes.description: Amenhotep II built a temple at Giza that he dedicated to the god Horemakhet, a sun-god identified with the Great Sphinx. It lies northeast of the Sphinx itself.

nodes.title: La Queyrie
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 F4 La Queyrie

nodes.title: Segusio
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 I3 Segusio

nodes.title: Sequani
nodes.description: The Sequani were a Gallic tribe occupying the river basin of the Arar (Saône), the valley of the Doubs, and the Jura Mountains.

nodes.title: Vesulus M.
nodes.description: Monte Viso is the highest peak of the Cottian Alps and the source of the Po river.

nodes.title: Unnamed Bridge
nodes.description: A bridge near Col. Dea Vocontiorum

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 G2 unnamed bridge (Ad Publicanos)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Col. Vienna → Morginnum → Cularo → Durotincum

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Col. Valentia → Morginnum

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Lucus Augusti → Noiomagos

nodes.title: Untitled

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Octodurus → Summus P(o)eninus

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Cularo → Ad Publicanos

nodes.title: Alesia
nodes.description: A Gallic oppidum, site of Caesar's defeat of Vercingetorix, and afterwards a Gallo-Roman town

nodes.title: Andematunnum
nodes.description: A Gallo-Roman city and capital of the Lingones

nodes.title: Ariorica
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 D3 Ariorica

nodes.title: Augustodunum
nodes.description: Augustodunum was an Augustan foundation located at the point where the river basins of the Loire, Saône, and Rhône rivers meet. Modern Autun.

nodes.title: Bibracte
nodes.description: Bibracte (modern Mont-Beuvray) was an oppidum of the Celtic Aedui, later named Lugdunensis.

nodes.title: Col. Augusta Raurica
nodes.description: Col. Augusta Raurica (modern Augst) was a Roman colony on the south bank of the Rhine established by Iulius Caesar and L. Munatius Plancus in 44 B.C.

nodes.title: Aventicum
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of the Helvetii, located between Aare and Lake Geneva. Modern Avenches in Switzerland.

nodes.title: Col. Iulia Equestris/Noviodunum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 D3 Col. Iulia Equestris/Noviodunum

nodes.title: Dubis (river)
nodes.description: The ancient Dubis is the modern Doubs river.

nodes.title: Eburodunum
nodes.description: Eburodunum, located on the Thièle river, was the site of a Roman vicus and fort at the southern end of Lake Neuchâtel.

nodes.title: Epamanduodurum
nodes.description: Epamanduodurum was a Roman settlement along the road to Vesontio.

nodes.title: Genava
nodes.description: Genava (modern Geneva) was originally an oppidum of the Allobroges that passed into Roman control after the campaigns of Iulius Caesar.

nodes.title: (H)Aedui
nodes.description: A Gallic tribe inhabiting the modern Burgundy region during the La Tène and Roman periods.

nodes.title: Helvetii
nodes.description: The Helvetii were a confederation of Gallic tribes occupying the Swiss plateau and they came into contact with the Roman Republic during the first century BC. Iulius Caesar states that the Helvetti were divided into four pagi.

nodes.title: Iura
nodes.description: The Jura Mountains, a sub-alpine mountain range located to the north of the western Alps, separate the Rhine and Rhone rivers.

nodes.title: Lemannus (lake)
nodes.description: Lemannus Lacus (the modern Lake Geneva).

nodes.title: Lingones
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 B2 Lingones

nodes.title: Lousonna
nodes.description: Lousonna began as a Roman military establishment on the site of a Celtic center.

nodes.title: [Luxovium]
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 D2 [Luxovium]

nodes.title: Mandubii
nodes.description: A conferation of Gallic tribes.

nodes.title: Matisco
nodes.description: A settlement in the territory of the Aedui mentioned by Caesar.

nodes.title: Nantuates
nodes.description: The Nantuates were a Celtic people dwelling in the upper Rhône valley. They formed part of the confederation known as "quattuor civitates Poeninae".

nodes.title: Petinesca
nodes.description: A Roman settlement at Petinesca replaced a Celtic oppidum located on the plateau of the Jensberg. The site was located along the military highway from Aventicum to Salodurum.

nodes.title: Salodurum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 E2 Salodurum

nodes.title: Segobodium?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 C2 Segobodium?

nodes.title: Tarnaias?
nodes.description: The chief settlement of the Nantuates.

nodes.title: *Vertillum?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 B2 *Vertillum?

nodes.title: Vesontio
nodes.description: Vesontion (modern Besançon) is first mentioned by Caesar in his commentaries ca. 58 BC. It is situated on a tributary of the Saône river.

nodes.title: Vindonissa
nodes.description: A Roman legionary base first established ca. AD 15.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Lousonna → Ariorica → Eburodunum → Col. Aventicum → Salodurum → Col. Augusta Raurica

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Segobodium? → Andematunnum → [Luxovium]

nodes.title: Via Salaria
nodes.description: An ancient road that originated at Rome and continued to Castrum Truentinum (Porto d'Ascoli).

nodes.title: Abodiacum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 C2 Abodiacum

nodes.title: Aesontius (river)
nodes.description: The Aesontius, known now as either the Soča or Isonzo river, flows from the Trenta Valley in the Julian Alps to the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Aguntum
nodes.description: Aguntum was an ancient settlement of Noricum that received municipal status under Claudius.

nodes.title: Alpes Carnicae
nodes.description: The Carnic Alps, a part of the Julian Alps.

nodes.title: ‘Apicilia’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 E4 ‘Apicilia’

nodes.title: Aquileia
nodes.description: An ancient Roman city initially founded ca. 181/180 B.C., Aquileia is especially important in Late Antiquity and the Middle Ages.

nodes.title: Avesica
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 F4 Avesica

nodes.title: [Bauzanum]
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 D3 [Bauzanum]

nodes.title: Cambodunum (Raetia)
nodes.description: Cambodunum was a Celtic settlement of Raetia. A Roman presence began under Tiberius (first century AD) when a Roman garrison was stationed at the site.

nodes.title: Carni
nodes.description: The Carni were a people of ancient Histria.

nodes.title: Castellum Pucinum
nodes.description: Castellum Pucinum was a settlement in the territory of the Carni in Histria.

nodes.title: Fons Timavi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 F4 Fons Timavi

nodes.title: Forum Iulii
nodes.description: A settlement founded as a Roman municipium along the line of the Via Iulia Augusta by Julius Caesar ca. 50 BCE (cited: BAtlas 19 F3 Forum Iulii)

nodes.title: [Glemona]
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 F3 [Glemona]

nodes.title: Iulium Carnicum
nodes.description: Iulium Carnicum (modern Zuglio) was a Roman settlement built atop an indigenous settlement after 52 BC. It was a dependency of Aquileia.

nodes.title: Licates
nodes.description: A tribe of the Vindelici, dwelling on the banks of the river Licus.

nodes.title: *Licus? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 F3 *Licus? fl.

nodes.title: Noricum (region)
nodes.description: Region deriving its name from a federated Celtic kingdom that became a province of the Roman empire (q.v.).

nodes.title: Osopus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 F3 Osopus

nodes.title: *Parthanum/*Tartenum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 D2 *Parthanum/*Tartenum

nodes.title: Pons Aeni
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 E2 Pons Aeni

nodes.title: Raetia
nodes.description: An ancient region comprising the central Alps during Roman times, spanning parts of the modern countries of Austria, Germany, Italy, Slovenia, and Switzerland with Liechtenstein. NB the Roman administrative province of Raetia, which has its own place resource in Pleiades.

nodes.title: Reunia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 E3 Reunia

nodes.title: Rostrum Nemaviae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 C1 Rostrum Nemaviae

nodes.title: Santicum
nodes.description: A settlement located at a favorable crossing over the Drau river that was an important road junction.

nodes.title: Tergeste
nodes.description: Tergeste (the modern Trieste) was first a vicus dependent on Aquileia (ca. 100 BC) and later became a colony under Caesar, sometime before 52 B.C. In the Augustan reorganization of Italy, the city was part of the Decima Regio and then of Venetia et Histria. By Late Antiquity, it had become a bishopric.

nodes.title: Teurnia
nodes.description: Teurnia, on the Drau river, was an ancient settlement of Noricum.

nodes.title: Tiliaventum (river)
nodes.description: A river in north-east Italy, flowing from the Alps to the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Timavus (river)
nodes.description: Timavus fl. (the Timavo river).

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 F4 unnamed aqueduct (Tergeste)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 C2 unnamed bridge (Abodiacum, over Licca fl.)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 C2 unnamed bridge (Cambodunum, over Virdo? fl.)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 F4 unnamed bridge (Pons Sonti, over Aesontius fl.)

nodes.title: Reschenpass
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 C3 no. 4 (Reschen Pass)

nodes.title: Fern Pass
nodes.description: Fern Pass (elevation 1212 m) is a mountain pass of the Tyrolean Alps.

nodes.title: Subocrini
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 unlocated Subocrini

nodes.title: Ad Malum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B4 Ad Malum

nodes.title: Albona
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B4 Albona

nodes.title: Alpes Iuliae
nodes.description: The Julian Alps

nodes.title: Andautonia
nodes.description: A Roman settlement and municipium near the Sava river, on the location of modern village of Šćitarjevo, Croatia, south from Zagreb, near Velika Gorica. Cited: BAtlas 20 D4 Andautonia

nodes.title: Ansium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 C5 Ansium

nodes.title: Apsarus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B5 Apsarus

nodes.title: Apsyrta/Crepsa (island)
nodes.description: Apsyrta/Crepsa Ins. (Cres) is an island in the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Apsyrtides (islands)
nodes.description: The Apsyrtides Islands, a group of Liburnian islands located east of Istria.

nodes.title: Aquincum
nodes.description: An ancient city of Pannonia, Aquincum is now located within Budapest, Hungary. The ancient site was first settled by the Eravisci and later served as a Roman castrum along the frontier.

nodes.title: Arba
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B5 Arba

nodes.title: Arba (island)
nodes.description: Rab island in the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Argyruntum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 C5 Argyruntum

nodes.title: Bova Ins.
nodes.description: Bova Ins. (modern Čiovo, Croatia).

nodes.title: Brattia (island)
nodes.description: Brattia Ins. (Brač, Croatia).

nodes.title: Burnum
nodes.description: From ca. 6 B.C. Burnum was the site of a Roman legionary camp (Legio XI; Legio XI Claudia Pia Fidelis - Legio IIII Flavia Felix and Legio VIII Augusta), as well as an auxiliary camp. By the Hadrianic period it had become the civil settlement of Municipium Burnistarum.

nodes.title: Celadussae Inss.
nodes.description: Celadussae Inss., a Dalmatian archipelago in the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Cissa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B5 Cissa

nodes.title: Cissa Ins.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 C5 Cissa Ins.

nodes.title: Colapis (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 C4 Colapis fl.

nodes.title: Contra Florentiam
nodes.description: Contra Florentiam was a late Roman fort located on the Danube frontier.

nodes.title: Corcyra Nigra (island)
nodes.description: The island of Korčula is located in the Adriatic Sea just off the Dalmatian coast.

nodes.title: Crexa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B5 Crexa

nodes.title: Curicta (island)
nodes.description: A large island in the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Curicum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B4 Curicum

nodes.title: Dalmatia
nodes.description: Dalmatia is an historical region of present-day Croatia, located to the east of the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Daorsi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 E7 Daorsi

nodes.title: Delmatae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 D6 Delmatae

nodes.title: Diomedeae (islands)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 D7 Diomedeae Inss.

nodes.title: Dravus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 A3 Dravus fl.

nodes.title: Elaphites (islands)
nodes.description: An island group off the coast of Illyricum.

nodes.title: Emona
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B3 Emona

nodes.title: Flanaticus Sinus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B4 Flanaticus Sinus

nodes.title: Flanona
nodes.description: Flanona (modern Plomin) was an ancient Roman settlement in Istria.

nodes.title: Fulfinium/Fertinium
nodes.description: A Roman municipal center and port.

nodes.title: Iader
nodes.description: The ancient Roman town of Iader (Iadera), given status of a Roman colony in 48 B.C.

nodes.title: Issa (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Adriatic, known today as Vis (Croatian) and Lissa (Italian).

nodes.title: Korkyra Melaina
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 D7 Korkyra Melaina

nodes.title: Ladesta (island)
nodes.description: Ladesta (modern Lastovo) is a part of ancient Liburnia in the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Liburnia (region)
nodes.description: The land of the Liburians on the northeast coast of the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Lissa (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Adriatic, known today as Ugljan/Ugliano.

nodes.title: Lugio/Florentia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 F3 Lugio/Florentia

nodes.title: Magdalensberg
nodes.description: An ancient settlement and emporium of the Celtic Kingdom of Noricum, cited: BAtlas 20 B3 Magdalensberg

nodes.title: Mursa
nodes.description: Mursa was an ancient city on the Drava river and the site of a colonia Aelia Mursa, likely founded by Hadrian in AD 133. Traces of Neolithic and Iron Age cultures have also been discovered at the site.

nodes.title: Neapolis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 A4 Neapolis

nodes.title: Nesactium
nodes.description: Nesactium was an ancient town of Histria.

nodes.title: Neviodunum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 C4 Neviodunum

nodes.title: Ošanići
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 E6 Ošanići

nodes.title: Parentium
nodes.description: A settlement on the western coast of the Istrian peninsula. A Roman castrum was established at the site in the second century BC. Now the site is the modern settlement of Poreč.

nodes.title: Pharus
nodes.description: Pharus (Stari Grad, Croatia) is a fourth century BC Greek colonial foundation on Pharus Ins. in the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Pharus (island)
nodes.description: Pharus Ins. (Hvar, Croatia) is an island in the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Poetovio
nodes.description: Poetovio (Ptuj, Slovenia) was an ancient city in Pannonia that was the base-camp of Legio XIII Gemina.

nodes.title: Pola
nodes.description: A port city on the Adriatic Sea (modern Pula in Croatia).

nodes.title: Pullariae (islands)
nodes.description: Pullariae Inss. (the modern the Brijuni or the Brionian Islands).

nodes.title: Rhizon/Risinium
nodes.description: A city on the Adriatic coast of Dalmatia with a protected harbor.

nodes.title: Rhizonicus Sinus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 F7 Rhizonicus Sinus

nodes.title: Rider
nodes.description: The chief town of the Dalmatae.

nodes.title: Sala (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 D3 Sala fl.

nodes.title: Salona
nodes.description: A coastal city of Dalmatia.

nodes.title: Savaria
nodes.description: Colonia Claudia Savaria (Szombathely) Hungary.

nodes.title: Scarbantia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 D2 Scarbantia

nodes.title: Segestica/Siscia
nodes.description: Segestica/Siscia is an Iron Age settlement recorded by Strabo. It was located at the confluence of three rivers and was used as a staging area for a campaign against the Dacians.

nodes.title: ‘Silvo’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 A4 ‘Silvo’

nodes.title: Spalatum
nodes.description: Spalatum (modern Split, Croatia) is an ancient settlement on the Adriatic coast most noted for the palatial residence of the emperor Diocletian.

nodes.title: Tarsatica
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B4 Tarsatica

nodes.title: Virunum
nodes.description: A Roman city, founded by Claudius, that was the capital of Noricum.

nodes.title: Balline
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 2 B3 Balline

nodes.title: Britannia/Albion (island)
nodes.description: The island of Great Britain is located to the northwest of continental Europe and is the ninth largest island in the world.

nodes.title: Britannicum Mare
nodes.description: Britannicum Mare (The English Channel) is an extension of the Atlantic Ocean that separates England from northern France, and also joins the North Sea to the Atlantic.

nodes.title: Germanicum Mare
nodes.description: The North Sea.

nodes.title: Hibernia
nodes.description: Hibernia is the Classical name for the island of Ireland.

nodes.title: Hyperboreios/Douekaledonios Okeanos
nodes.description: The "northern ocean", referring to the North Atlantic Ocean located to the west of what is now Scotland.

nodes.title: Iouernikos Okeanos
nodes.description: The Irish Sea separates the islands of Ireland and Great Britain.

nodes.title: Roudon (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 2 H2 Roudon fl.

nodes.title: Stoneyford
nodes.description: At Stoneyford in 1852 a burial and associated hoard showing Roman cultural affinity was discovered, although the find and its interpretation are now debated.

nodes.title: Suebicum Mare
nodes.description: The Baltic Sea.

nodes.title: Thule (island)
nodes.description: An island mentioned frequently -- and often metaphorically -- in texts of the Roman period, said by Ptolemy, Strabo, Pliny, and others to lie to the north of Britannia. Some scholars associate it with the island known today as Shetland, but the geographic association even in antiquity (when it was more than just a rhetorical term) varied (see further Todd in New Pauly).

nodes.title: Vistula (river)
nodes.description: Vistula fl. (Vistula River) flows 1,047 km (651 miles) from the south of Poland to the Baltic Sea. Its name is first attested in the Natural History of Pliny the Elder.

nodes.title: Acumincum
nodes.description: Acumincum (Stari Slankamen) was a settlement of the Scordisci that was later conquered by the Romans. During the Flavian period, the cohors I Britannica equitata and II Adjutrix were based there.

nodes.title: *Aureus Mons
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 C5 *Aureus Mons

nodes.title: Burgenae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 C5 Burgenae

nodes.title: Old Winchester Hill
nodes.description: Old Winchester Hill is the site of both Bronze Age barrows and an Iron Age hill fort.

nodes.title: Badbury Rings
nodes.description: Badbury Rings is an Iron Age hill fort in Dorset, England.

nodes.title: Mausoleum of Gallienus
nodes.description: A mausoleum on the Via Appia that has been identified conventionally as that of the emperor Gallienus.

nodes.title: Umma
nodes.description: Umma was an important ancient city of Sumer but has not been scientifically excavated. The mainstream of scholarly opinion associates the ancient site with Tell Jokha, Iraq, located in Iraq's Northwestern Dhi Qar Governorate. This area is remote and is associated with a network of ancient canals. Tell Jokha measures about 1,500 meters in diameter.

nodes.title: Antitaurus M.
nodes.description: Barrington Atlas: BAtlas 89 B1 Antitaurus M.

nodes.title: Constantinian Columbarium
nodes.description: The so-called Constantinian Columbarium is actually a second century AD tomb on the Via Appia.

nodes.title: Tomb of Gaius Rabirius Postumus Libertus and family
nodes.description: A tomb of the Republican period belonging to the freedman family of the Rabirii.

nodes.title: Temple of Janus, Autun
nodes.description: A monumental first-century A.D. Romano-Celtic sanctuary located in Autun, Saône-et-Loire, France, to the northwest of the ancient city of Augustodunum.

nodes.title: House of Pansa
nodes.description: The House of Pansa (VI,6,1) is an atrium house in Pompeii that occupies an entire insula. Architectural elements date the structure ca. 140-120 BC in its original phase. The merchant and duumvir Cn. Alleius Nigidius Maius owned the property.

nodes.title: Seleucid Empire
nodes.description: The Seleucid Empire was a Hellenistic kingdom, founded by Seleucus I Nicator, and ruled by the Seleucid dynasty from 312 to 63 BCE. At its height it stretched from the Aegean Sea to northern India, but it steadily lost territory and prestige. The remnants of the kingdom were eventually incorporated into Roman territory as the province of Syria in 64 BCE.

nodes.title: Naveta des Tudons
nodes.description: A chamber tomb of the late second to early first millennium B.C. located on the island of Minorca.

nodes.title: Unstan Chambered Cairn
nodes.description: A Neolithic chambered cairn dating to the fourth and third millennia BC.

nodes.title: tribus Quirina
nodes.description: The tribus Quirina was one of the last later rural tribes, established in 241 B.C.

nodes.title: House of the Actors
nodes.description: A Roman domus in in Pompeii overlooking the via Stabiana, with shops on both sides of the entrance. The site was excavated in 1872 and bombed in 1943. Located at I,2,6.

nodes.title: tribus Scaptia
nodes.description: A later rural tribe of ancient Rome, which was established in 332 B.C.

nodes.title: Via Aquitania
nodes.description: A Roman road built ca. 118 BC after the Roman defeat of the Allobroges and Arverni tribes in Gaul.

nodes.title: Ab Asturica Burdigalam
nodes.description: A Roman road connecting Asturica Augusta (modern Astorga) and Burdigala (modern Bordeaux).

nodes.title: Gournia
nodes.description: A Minoan palace complex and settlement on Crete, finally abandoned ca. 1200 BCE. The original toponym is unknown and the modern name is derived from stone vessels found at the site.

nodes.title: Lycia et Pamphylia
nodes.description: The Roman province of Lycia and Pamphylia after the Verona List (303-324 AD) (BAtlas 101 M4 Lycia et Pamphylia).

nodes.title: Paphlagonia
nodes.description: The Late Roman province as defined in the Barrington Atlas (BAtlas 101 N3 Paphlagonia)

nodes.title: Baetica
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 E4 Baetica

nodes.title: Sicilia (late Roman province - deprecated)
nodes.description: The Late Roman Province of Sicily as defined by BAtlas 101 J4 Sicilia. Deprecated in favor of place 981549.

nodes.title: Bithynia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 E3 no. 31 (Bithynia)

nodes.title: Porta Romana
nodes.description: The so-called Porta Romana of Saturnia was once part of the Roman wall of the second century B.C.

nodes.title: Savignano sul Rubicone Roman bridge
nodes.description: A Roman bridge on the Rubicon at Savignano sul Rubicone.

nodes.title: Mokarta
nodes.description: A Bronze Age settlement located near Salemi, Sicily. The site has multiple settlement phases, including the Medival ruins referred to as the Castello di Mokarta. A combination of excavation and geophysical prospection has revealed the remains of Bronze Age settlement atop the plateau as well as evidence for outlying necropoleis.

nodes.title: Stone of the Pregnant Woman
nodes.description: The Stone of the Pregnant Woman in Baalbek, Lebanon is one of the largest monoliths ever quarried.

nodes.title: Attalid kingdom
nodes.description: Founded by Philetaerus, who took command of Pergamum in 282 BCE, and declared independent by Attalus I in the 230's BCE, the Attalid kingdom was allied closely to Rome; the kingdom expanded after the Peace of Apamea in 188 BCE. The last king, Attalus III, willed the kingdom to Rome, and after his death in 133, the former kingdom formed the core of the Roman province of Asia.

nodes.title: Yüntdağ
nodes.description: An ancient phrourion in the Attalid Kingdom, which modern scholarship places at Yüntdağ.

nodes.title: Temple of Isis
nodes.description: The Temple of Isis in Pompeii (VIII, 7, 28) is a sanctuary sacred to Isis that dates from the second century BC.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Antigori
nodes.description: A nuragic complex with artifact evidence showing trade linkages between Sardinian peoples and Mycenaean Greeks, along with Cypriots.

nodes.title: Mursia
nodes.description: A modern village on the northwest coast of the Mediterranean island of Pantelleria. Mursia lies atop a settlement of late Bronze Age date that is associated with the cemetery (Sesi) that lies immediately to its south.

nodes.title: Bronze Age Cemetery at Mursia
nodes.description: A cemetery (referred to collectively in Italian as "sesi") consisting of multi-burial stone cairns associated with the Bronze Age settlement at Mursia on Mediterranean island of Pantelleria.

nodes.title: Billingsgate Roman House and Baths
nodes.description: A Roman balneum attached either to a Roman townhouse or mansio.

nodes.title: Temple of Athena Nike
nodes.description: A temple dedicated to Athena Nike constructed on the Athenian Acropolis between 449 and 420 BCE.

nodes.title: Commercial Stoa of Mytilene
nodes.description: This stoa was built against a fourth century BCE seawall sometime in the Hellenistic era. The seawall shows evidence of later Roman repairs.

nodes.title: Reccopolis
nodes.description: Reccopolis is an urban, Visigothic, ex-novo foundation made under king Liuvigild in A.D. 578. The archaeological remains at the site include a palace complex, public area, basilica, walls, and aqueduct. The site is known today by the Spanish version of its Latin name (Recópolis); it is located near the modern village of Zorita de los Canes in the Spanish province of Guadelajara.

nodes.title: Roman bath at Lugdunum Convenarum
nodes.description: The Roman bath at Lugdunum Convenarum is part of the second urban nucleus found at the foot of the Fourvière hill.

nodes.title: Old Palace at Assur
nodes.description: A palace constructed during the reign of Šamši-Adad I (ca. 1836-1776 BCE).

nodes.title: Armaouira
nodes.description: Armaouira (Urartian Argishtikhinili) was a fortified center of ancient Urartu. The site is located close to Armavir, Armenia.

nodes.title: Caucasus (mountain range)
nodes.description: The Caucasus Mountains, located between the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea.

nodes.title: Erebuni
nodes.description: Erebuni was a fortified city of the ancient kingdom of Urartu located in what is now Yerevan, Armenia.

nodes.title: Gorneae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 88 C4 Gorneae

nodes.title: Harmozike
nodes.description: Harmozike was an ancient site in Georgia and the dwelling of the royalty of Caucasian Iberia. The site is located on the Bagineti hill in modern Mccheta. Pompeius Magnus captured the site in 65 BC.

nodes.title: Iberia (ancient region)
nodes.description: Iberia was an ancient region of southern Caucasia.

nodes.title: Kainepolis
nodes.description: Major city of Armenia. Inhabited since the Neolithic Period, the city was capital of the Arsacid Kingdom of Armenia from 120-330 CE, and became a major religious center with the construction of Etchmiadzin Cathedral in the early 4th century.

nodes.title: Karmir-blur
nodes.description: Karmir Blur (or "Red Hill") is the ancient Urartian site of Teishebaini, a fortified city of the seventh century BC built by Rusa II.

nodes.title: Kaspiai Pylai/Albaniai Pylai
nodes.description: Kaspiai Pylai/Albaniai Pylai, also referred to as Portae Caspiae by Pliny, is used to describe both the Sirdara Pass in the Elburs mountains and the road from Darband to the Caspian Sea.

nodes.title: Meschistha
nodes.description: Meschistha (modern Mtskheta (Georgian: მცხეთა)) is an ancient city in Georgia and was the capital of the Hellenistic kingdom of Iberia. Meschistha became a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1994.

nodes.title: Tli
nodes.description: Major burial ground of the late Bronze Age Koban culture, which flourished in the Caucasus from ca. 1400-400 BCE. The Tli necropolis, named after the nearby modern village of Tli, contains 481 graves dated from the Middle Bronze Age through the Iron Age.

nodes.title: Tzon/Tzur
nodes.description: Tzon/Tzur (modern Derbent, Russia) was also known in antiquity as Darband, an ancient city in Dāḡestān on the western shore of the Caspian Sea.

nodes.title: Gangara
nodes.description: An ancient city mentioned by Ptolemy that some have tentatively identified with modern Baku.

nodes.title: Abos M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 D1 Abos M.

nodes.title: Aga Mons
nodes.description: A 3,246 meter mountain at the NE end of the Antitaurus range.

nodes.title: Aghtamar
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 F2 Aghtamar

nodes.title: Altıntepe
nodes.description: A Urartian settlement on a hill overlooking the Euphrates River

nodes.title: Arbela/Arba-ilu
nodes.description: An ancient Mesopotamian city located between the two Zab rivers (modern Erbel/Erbil in Iraq).

nodes.title: Arsanias (river)
nodes.description: Arsanias fl. is a river of eastern Turkey and a major source of the Euphrates fl.

nodes.title: Astaunitis/Asthianene
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 C2 Astaunitis/Asthianene

nodes.title: Bezabde/Zabdaion Chorion
nodes.description: Site of a fortress on the eastern frontier of the Roman empire that was the setting for two famous sieges in 360.

nodes.title: Dur-Sharrukin
nodes.description: Dūr-Šarrukīn (“Fort Sargon”), modern Khorsabad, became the capital of the Assyrian Empire during the reign of the eighth-century-BC ruler Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC). According to the Assyrian Eponym Chronicle, the foundations of the city were laid in 717 BC and the city itself was completed in early 706 BC, one year before Sargon was killed on the battlefield. Sargon’s newly-constructed, rectangular-shaped capital, which he modelled on the general plan on Babylon, was abandoned upon his death in 705 BC; his son and successor Sennacherib (r. 704–681 BC) made Nineveh Assyria’s principal administrative center.

nodes.title: Kentrites/Tigris/Zirmas
nodes.description: The modern Botan river in Turkey. It is a tributary of the Tigris.

nodes.title: Matiane/*Kapauta Limne
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 H3 Matiane/*Kapauta Limne

nodes.title: Mosul/‘Mespila’?
nodes.description: An ancient city located across the Tigris river from the site of Nineveh. Modern Mosul in Iraq.

nodes.title: Mygdonia
nodes.description: A plain in Mesopotamia surrounding Nisibis. Alexander the Great settled Macedonian veterans here.

nodes.title: Nineveh/Ninos
nodes.description: This important Mesopotamian city flanks the eastern edge of the Tigris flood plain, opposite modern Mosul, of which it is now a suburb. From the third millennium B.C. onwards, Nineveh was the most important religious center of the goddess Ištar in the area that would become the Assyrian heartland. Starting in the Middle Assyrian period, the city came under the authority of the kings of Assyria, who often sponsored large-scale building activities there. However, it was not until 704 B.C. that Nineveh became the administrative capital of Assyria, when the Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib moved the royal family and court there and transformed the city into a thriving imperial metropolis. Nineveh remained Assyria’s capital until 612 B.C., when it was captured and destroyed by a Babylonian-Median collation led by Nabopolassar and Cyaxares. The visible remains of the (7th-century) Assyrian city include the citadel mound Kuyunjik, the smaller mound of Nebi Yunus, and the twelve-kilometer-long city wall.

nodes.title: Niphates (mountain)
nodes.description: A mountain range in Armenia, belonging to the eastern Taurus massif.

nodes.title: Nisibis/Antiochia
nodes.description: Nisibis/Antiochia was an ancient city of Mesopotamia that began as part of an Aramaean kingdom that the Assyrian king Adad-Nirari II captured in 896 BC. Following its capture by Alexander the Great, the city became Antiochia Mygdonia under the Seleucids.

nodes.title: Parthenias/Nymphios (river)
nodes.description: A river that originates in the Anti-Taurus Mountains and is a major tributary of the Tigris.

nodes.title: Coemeterium Maius
nodes.description: A major Roman necropolis and catacomb along the Via Nomentana.

nodes.title: So-called Area A in Berenike
nodes.description: Ruins of a Hellenistic courtyard house (possibly connected to the adjacent building, known as Area X) in the archaeological site of Sidi Khiribech in Berenike (modern Benghazi).

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Santa Maria Capua Vetere
nodes.description: Sometimes referred to as the "Anfiteatro Campano", the Roman amphitheater at Santa Maria Capua Vetere is the second largest in the Roman world. Begun under Augustus, it was further renovated under Hadrian and Antoninus Pius.

nodes.title: Tomb of Menidi
nodes.description: A Mycenaean tholos tomb first discovered in 1872. It is one of four such tholoi known in Attica.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Aizanoi
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Aizanoi is part of a theater-stadium complex. The complex is built after A.D. 160 with the patronage of one M. Apuleius Eurycles.

nodes.title: Temple of Zeus
nodes.description: The Temple of Zeus is Aizanoi's main sanctuary. The temple complex was built under Domitian.

nodes.title: City wall, Nicopolis
nodes.description: The Roman period city wall of Nicopolis.

nodes.title: Villa of Manius Antoninus
nodes.description: The Villa of Manius Antoninus at Nicopolis.

nodes.title: Gallic oppidum of Montlaurès
nodes.description: The archaeological remains of a Gallic oppidum lying approximately 4 km NNW of Col. Narbo Martius. Occupied from mid-sixth century BCE until the mid-first century BCE.

nodes.title: Palace of Tupkish
nodes.description: Palace at the Hurrian city Urkesh, constructed by Tupkish in the late third millennium BCE.

nodes.title: A'ali Mound Cemetery
nodes.description: A large complex of burial mounds located near the town of A'ali in central Bahrain. The burials date to the early Dilmun era, ca. 2050-1700 BCE.

nodes.title: Macellum of Puteoli
nodes.description: A macellum of Roman Puteoli. The discovery of a statue of Serapis at the site led to a misidentification of the building as a Serapeum.

nodes.title: Rione Terra
nodes.description: The original urban nucleus of Puteoli, dating from the second century B.C. onwards.

nodes.title: Tarxien (Malta)
nodes.description: A megalithic temple complex (ca. 3150 BC) named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1980.

nodes.title: Blatades Monastery
nodes.description: A fourteenth century monastery.

nodes.title: Theater of Melos
nodes.description: The Theater of Melos likely has Hellenistic origins but the visible phase belongs to the Roman period.

nodes.title: Anazarbos city wall
nodes.description: The Anazarbos city wall visible today was built in the 10th century of the current era.

nodes.title: Ecclesiastical complex, Port of Sanitja
nodes.description: Archaeological excavations in 2008 and 2010 revealed an ecclesiastical complex at the west side of the port of Sanitja on the Spanish island of Menorca. This comples may date to the sixth century A.D.

nodes.title: Areopagus
nodes.description: Named after a mythical trial of the god Ares, the Areopagus is a rocky outcropping in Athens located to the northwest of the acropolis. The hill was used as a meeting place for the Council of the Areopagus which functioned as a council of elders for the city of Athens. The Areopagus is also traditionally identified as the setting for Paul's sermon to Athens.

nodes.title: Cathedral of St. James, Jerusalem
nodes.description: A 12th-century Armenian church in Jerusalem, the principal church of the Armenian Patriarchate of Jerusalem.

nodes.title: Santa Prisca
nodes.description: A titular church on Rome's Aventine Hill dedicated to Saint Prisca. A Mithraeum dating to the late first century A.D. was discovered on the site in 1934.

nodes.title: Via Ostiensis
nodes.description: An ancient road running from Rome to Ostia, exiting the city walls of Rome at the Porta Trigemina.

nodes.title: Via Nomentana
nodes.description: The ancient road connecting Rome and Nomentum.

nodes.title: Civita di Artena
nodes.description: The remains of an ancient fortified center close to the town of Artena, Italy. The original settlement, of uncertain name, may have been established by the Volsci; both Ecetra and Fortinum have been suggested. The modern village was known as Monte Fortino until 1873.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Trebula Mutuesca
nodes.description: The archaeological remains of the Roman amphitheater at Trebula Mutuesca are located at Monteleone Sabino in the Province of Rieti, Italy.

nodes.title: White Pyramid
nodes.description: A pyramid built by Pharaoh Amenemhat II.

nodes.title: Bouros-Kastri peninsula
nodes.description: A peninsula in southeastern Euboea, part of the Karystia region.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Apollo at Halieis
nodes.description: The Sanctuary of Apollo at Halieis is a temple complex dedicated primarily to Apollo, constructed outside of the city of Halieis and dating between the seventh and fourth centuries BCE.

nodes.title: Agora at Malia
nodes.description: The so-called "agora" is a large open courtyard to the northwest of the Middle Minoan palace at Malia.

nodes.title: Unit IV-1 at Nichoria
nodes.description: Unit IV-1 is a large, megaron-style building constructed during the 11th century BCE at the site of Nichoria in Messenia, Greece.

nodes.title: Athenian Treasury at Delphi
nodes.description: The Athenian Treasury at Delphi, built between 510 and 480 BC, is a building intended to house offerings made to Apollo by the citizens of Athens.

nodes.title: Polygonal wall of Roman castrum
nodes.description: The polygonal masonry wall of the Roman castrum at Pyrgi encloses an area of ca. 5.7 ha.

nodes.title: Qalat-i Dinka
nodes.description: Archaeological site in the Peshdar Plain with remains dated to the Neo-Assyrian period. The mound is part of a larger frontier settlement known as the Dinka Settlement Complex.

nodes.title: Castalian spring
nodes.description: A spring in the ravine between the Phaedriades cliffs (on the lower southern slope of Mt. Parnassos) at Delphi.

nodes.title: Hypogeum of via Dino Compagni
nodes.description: A Christian catacomb on the ancient Via Latina used during the fourth century.

nodes.title: Tomb of Puimre at Thebes
nodes.description: Tomb TT39 in the Theban Necropolis, the burial site of Puimre (or Puyemre), an Egyptian official of the 18th Dynasty.

nodes.title: Purṭir
nodes.description: A fortress in the vicinity of Til-garimmu fortified by the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) against Urarṭu.

nodes.title: Temple of Olympian Zeus, Syracuse
nodes.description: The Temple of Olympian Zeus is located approximately 3 km southwest of Syracuse on the Cyane river.

nodes.title: Temple of Olympian Zeus, Athens
nodes.description: The Temple of Olympian Zeus is also known as the Olympieion. A colossal temple dedicated to Zeus, it was built in three stages, beginning in 515 BCE and ending in 131 CE.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater of Carthage
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater built at Carthage.

nodes.title: Villa di Teodorico
nodes.description: A palatial Roman villa and bath complex that has been connected with Theodoric the Great, with twentieth century interpretations labeling it as Theodoric's "hunting lodge". More recent excavations have uncovered evidence for earlier building phases, dating from the first century B.C. through the third century A.D.

nodes.title: Arc de Diane
nodes.description: The ruins of a Roman bath complex at Divona Cadurcorum.

nodes.title: Tall Mūzān
nodes.description: Urkesh or Urkish (the modern Tell Mozan) is a tell located in the foothills of the Taurus Mountains of northeastern Syria. Hurrians founded the site during the fourth millennium B.C.

nodes.title: Arènes de Fréjus
nodes.description: A 12,000 seat Roman amphitheater located in Fréjus, France.

nodes.title: Pathyris (nome)
nodes.description: An administrative division of Egypt at certain periods, centered on the settlement of the same name.

nodes.title: Gallo-Roman Theater of Lillebonne
nodes.description: The Gallo-Roman Theater of Lillebonne was in use from the first to the third century.

nodes.title: Roman siege camp
nodes.description: A siege camp dating to the Roman siege of the fortress of Masada in A.D. 72.

nodes.title: Necropolis of Selva Miccia
nodes.description: The Necropolis of Selva Miccia, located along the road leading to Vulci, contains tombs of the seventh and sixth centuries B.C., corresponding in phase to the elite structure excavated at località Le Sparne.

nodes.title: Doric temple at Kaulonia
nodes.description: The Doric Temple at Caulonia has been dated ca. 420 B.C.

nodes.title: Mount Nebo
nodes.description: A mountain in Jordan rising to ca. 817 meters (2680 feet) above sea level, Mount Nebo is connected with the Hebrew prophet Moses and a Christian site (4th century AD) stands on its summit.

nodes.title: Fortunatae Insulae (Canary Islands)
nodes.description: The "Blessed Islands", equivalent in most ancient literature to the modern Canary Islands (Islas Canarias).

nodes.title: Canaria? (island)
nodes.description: Canaria? (Gran Canaria) is an island of the Canary Islands archipelago.

nodes.title: Via Valeria
nodes.description: An ancient road from Rome to Corfinium.

nodes.title: House of the outdoor triclinium
