nodes.description: A Roman domus in Pompeii facing on to the Via Nocera.

nodes.title: tribus Horatia
nodes.description: The tribus Horatia was a rural tribe of ancient Rome.

nodes.title: tribus Oufentina
nodes.description: The tribus Oufentina was a later rural tribe of Rome, established in 318 B.C.

nodes.title: House of the Tragic Poet
nodes.description: The so-called "House of the Tragic Poet" (VI, 8, 3, 5) was built in the first century BC and has the plan of a classic "Samnite" house. The house was excavated in 1824. It lies at the corner of the Via delle Terme and the Via della Fullonica, across from the Forum Baths.

nodes.title: tribus Poblilia
nodes.description: Tribus Poblilia was a later rural tribe of Rome, which was established in 358 B.C.

nodes.title: Forum of Pompeii
nodes.description: Main forum of the Roman city of Pompeii (VII, 8).

nodes.title: Aurelian Walls
nodes.description: The Aurelian Walls of Rome began as a fortification system built by Aurelian and Probus between 271 and 275. They enclose an area of approximately 1,400 hectares.

nodes.title: Audleystown Court Cairn
nodes.description: A dual court grave near the south shore of Strangford Lough in County Down, Northern Ireland.

nodes.title: Knockeen dolmen
nodes.description: A megalithic dolmen located in Knockeen, County Waterford, Ireland.

nodes.title: Portonaccio sanctuary at Veii
nodes.description: The extraurban sanctuary of Minerva at Portonaccio is an important Etruscan cult center. The temple dates ca. 510 B.C. and was adorned with acroterial sculptures, notably the famous "Apollo of Veii".

nodes.title: Ezida (Kalhu)
nodes.description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the god Nabû. Unlike most of the religious buildings constructed at Kalhu, the Ezida ("True House") was built in the southeast corner of the Citadel.

nodes.title: Burnt Palace at Kalhu
nodes.description: The Burnt Palace, which was destroyed by fire when Kalhu fell to anti-Assyrian Babylonian and Median forces in 612 BC, has the longest building sequence yet identified at Nimrud (biblical Calah). This royal residence, which was constructed in the southeast quarter of the citadel, had at least nine phases of occupation between the Middle Assyrian and Hellenistic Periods. The so-called Burnt Palace was rebuilt/renovated three times during the ninth to seventh centuries BC and it might have temporarily served as a royal residence during the reign of Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC), while that Assyrian king was building his new capital Dūr-Šarrukīn. An immense collection of burnt ivories (the ‘Loftus ivories’) was discovered in and near the throne room in 1954–55; these are now in the British Museum (London).

nodes.title: Sebetti temple (Kalhu)
nodes.description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the divine Sebetti. The location of this building is not known.

nodes.title: Acropolis of Malthi
nodes.description: The acropolis of ancient Dorion.

nodes.title: Santa Costanza
nodes.description: A fourth century AD structure along the Via Nomentana that was built by Constantine I as a mausoleum, originally housing the remains of his daughters Constantina and Helena. It was dedicated as a Christian church in the Middle Ages.

nodes.title: The Great Sphinx
nodes.description: A monumental limestone sphinx situated on the Giza plateau, likely connected with the reign of Pharaoh Khafre.

nodes.title: Valley Temple of Khafre
nodes.description: The Valley Temple associated with the pyramid of Khafre. The Valley Temple is linked to the pyramid and its mortuary temple via a causeway.

nodes.title: Greek theater of Segesta
nodes.description: Remains of a Greek theater at Segesta that was first built in the first half of the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Enirgalana
nodes.description: The cella/shrine of the goddess Ištar in the Eanna temple at Uruk. The Sumerian ceremonial name Enirgalana means "House of the Prince of Heaven."

nodes.title: Ekišibgalekura
nodes.description: The shrine/seat of the goddess Ninimma in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ekišibgalekura may mean "House, Keeper of the Seal of the Ekur."

nodes.title: Eušumgalana
nodes.description: The shrine/seat of the goddess Ninkasi in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eušumgalana means "House of the Dragon of Heaven."

nodes.title: Eešbanda
nodes.description: The shrine/seat of the goddess Šuzianna in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eešbanda means "House, Little Chamber."

nodes.title: Eankikuga
nodes.description: The shrine/seat of the god Kusu in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eankikuga means "House of the Pure Heaven and Underworld."

nodes.title: Dur-Sharrukku/Sippar-Aruru
nodes.description: Dur-Sharrukku is an unlocated city in northern Babylonia that also goes by the name Sippar-Aruru (starting in the 7th century B.C.). In the 8th century B.C., Dur-Sharrukku served as an Assyrian provincial center.

nodes.title: Eedinna
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Ištar (as Bēlet-Sippar) at Sippar. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eedinna means "House of the Steppe."

nodes.title: Ša-Iṣṣur-Adad
nodes.description: An unlocated fortified settlement in the territory of the Chaldean tribe of Bīt-Amukāni.

nodes.title: Emeteursaga
nodes.description: The shrine/cella of the god Zababa in the Edubba temple at Kish. The Sumerian ceremonial name Emeteursaga means "House, Worthy of the Hero."

nodes.title: Egalmah
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Gula (as Ninisinna) at Larsa. The Sumerian ceremonial name Egalmah means "Exalted Palace."

nodes.title: Gurasimmu
nodes.description: The name of a West Semitic tribe living in southern Babylonia, perhaps near Ur.

nodes.title: Parthenon
nodes.description: The poliadic temple of Athena located on the Athenian Acropolis and constructed at the height of Athenian power between 447 and 432 BCE. The Parthenon is the largest Doric temple in mainland Greece.

nodes.title: Achladia
nodes.description: A Minoan site in eastern Crete that was the site of a so-called "large rural villa" covering some 270 square meters and dating to the Middle Minoan and Late Minoan periods.

nodes.title: Ay-ibūr-šabû
nodes.description: The processional road of the god Marduk in Babylon, whose Akkadian ceremonial name means "May the Arrogant Not Flourish." The street runs north-south through the city, from the Ištar Gate to the Esagil temple. The northern stretch of Ay-ibūr-šabû is sometimes referred to as Ištar-lamassi-ummānīšu ("The goddess Ištar is the Guardian Angel of Her Troops").

nodes.title: Enun
nodes.description: The shrine/seat of the goddess Ningal in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Enun means "Princely House."

nodes.title: É.AŠ.AN.AMAR
nodes.description: The shrine/seat of the god Enlil in the Egipar temple at Ur. The exact meaning and reading of the Sumerian ceremonial name are uncertain.

nodes.title: Ešahula
nodes.description: The temple of the god Nergal at Me-Turnat. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ešahula means "House of the Happy Heart."

nodes.title: Edurgina
nodes.description: The temple of the god Bēl-Ṣarbi at Bāṣ. The Sumerian ceremonial name Edurgina means "House, Established Abode."

nodes.title: Larak
nodes.description: A city located near the Tigris River, possibly east or northeast of Nippur.

nodes.title: Dutēti
nodes.description: An unlocated town in Babylonia that is reported to have been located on one of the banks of the Euphrates River.

nodes.title: Baduldua
nodes.description: The city wall of Sippar. Its Sumerian ceremonial name means "Wall Built in Ancient Times." In the 7th century B.C., the wall was also called Badullisâ ("What Named in Ancient Times").

nodes.title: Necropoli di San Placido
nodes.description: A large Roman necropolis in Messina, uncovered in 1914 during the works to build the modern Palazzo della Prefettura.

nodes.title: Circus Maximus
nodes.description: An ancient chariot-racing venue at Rome and a major location for public entertainments (ludi), the Circus Maximus is located between the Aventine and Palatine hills.

nodes.title: Glanum dam
nodes.description: A Roman dam that created the Lac du Peirou and supplied Glanum with water. While the ancient dam was destroyed in the late nineteenth century, the reservoir remains.

nodes.title: Porta Saracena
nodes.description: A gateway in the polygonal masonry circuit wall of Segni.

nodes.title: Castro de Ulaca
nodes.description: Fortified vettonian settlement.

nodes.title: tribus Palatina
nodes.description: An urban tribe of Rome created under the reign of Servius Tullius.

nodes.title: Red Basilica
nodes.description: A Roman temple built above the Selinus river which was originally constructed for the worship of Egyptian gods, most likely Isis and/or Serapis. In the Byzantine era it was converted into a church of St. John. It was subsequently ruined, although the rotunda on the north side is still an active mosque.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Trochesia
nodes.description: A monopteral nuraghe.

nodes.title: Honorific arch
nodes.description: An honorific arch built in Pompeii near the intersection of the streets known by the modern names of the Via della Fortuna and the Via di Mercurio.

nodes.title: House of Iphigeneia
nodes.description: The House of Pinarius Cerialis and Cassia or Casa dell’orefice or Casa di Ifigenia (III, 4, b).

nodes.title: House of Obellius Firmus
nodes.description: The House of M. Obellius Firmus lies south of the Via di Nola and is also known as the House of the Count of Turin. Excavated in 1910, the house's name is derived from electoral graffiti found on the site. (IX, 14, 2, 4, a, b)

nodes.title: tribus Cornelia
nodes.description: A rural tribe of ancient Rome.

nodes.title: tribus Fabia
nodes.description: The tribus Fabia was a rural tribe of Rome.

nodes.title: Gladiators' barracks
nodes.description: A training ground for gladiators in Pompeii noted for the more than 100 inscriptions connected to gladiating. (V, 5, 3)

nodes.title: House of the Prince of Naples
nodes.description: An atrium house with an austere facade located on the west side of the Vicolo dei Vettii (VI 15, 7-8).

nodes.title: House of Publius Casca Longus
nodes.description: The House of Publius Casca Longus (I, 6, 11) is located on the Via dell'Abbondanza and is also known as the Casa dei Quadretti Teatrali.

nodes.title: Piscina Mirabilis
nodes.description: A freshwater cistern at Bacoli on the Gulf of Naples, the Piscina Mirabilis likely provided sailors of the Roman fleet with drinking water. Its capacity is estimated at 12,600 cubic meters.

nodes.title: Kumtepe (Troad)
nodes.description: The oldest permanent settlement in the Troad.

nodes.title: Brú na Bóinne - Archaeological Ensemble of the Bend of the Boyne
nodes.description: Three primary prehistoric sites comprise the Archaeological Ensemble of the Bend of the Boyne located on the north bank of the River Boyne, some 50 km knorth north of Dublin, Ireland. These sites are Newgrange, Knowth, and Dowth.

nodes.title: Italia Annonaria
nodes.description: A Late Roman vicariate established by Constantine I with its administrative capital located at Mediolanum (Milan).

nodes.title: Nuraghe Palmavera
nodes.description: A site near Alghero, Sardinia, belonging to the first nuragic phase (fifteenth and fourteenth centuries BC).

nodes.title: Il Tondo
nodes.description: A first century AD Roman amphitheater located in Latium near Zagorolo, Italy.

nodes.title: Kolymbarion Akron
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B2 Kolymbarion Akron

nodes.title: ‘Luguidunec’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B2 ‘Luguidunec’

nodes.title: Lula
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B2 Lula

nodes.title: Makopsisa
nodes.description: A town known from Ptolemy, Makopsisa (modern Macomer) is located in the Nuoro province of Sardinia.

nodes.title: Maltamonenses
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 Maltamonenses

nodes.title: Martenses
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B3 Martenses

nodes.title: Metalla
nodes.description: A Roman mining center located in the Iglesiente region of Sardinia. The Roman settlement succeeded an earlier nuragic village.

nodes.title: Molaria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A2 Molaria

nodes.title: Molibodes (island)
nodes.description: Molibodes Ins. (Isola di Sant'Antioco)

nodes.title: Monte Sirai
nodes.description: A Phoenician–Punic and later Roman settlement in southwestern Sardinia, Monte Sirai also has evidence for nuragic settlement during the second millennium BC.

nodes.title: Monte Urralidi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 Monte Urralidi

nodes.title: Neapolis
nodes.description: Neapolis was an ancient city of Sardinia, located on the west coast of the island at the southern extremity of the Gulf of Oristano, near the present-day località of Santa Maria di Nabui.

nodes.title: Nemus Sorabense/Sorabile
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B2 Nemus Sorabense/Sorabile

nodes.title: Nora
nodes.description: A pre-Roman and Roman site in southern Sardinia.

nodes.title: Nurac Sessar
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A2 Nurac Sessar

nodes.title: Nure
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A2 Nure

nodes.title: Nymphaios Limen
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A2 Nymphaios Limen

nodes.title: Olbia
nodes.description: A Phoenician, Carthaginian, and Roman center in northeast Sardinia.

nodes.title: Othoca
nodes.description: The site of a Phoenician port on the Gulf of Oristano in western Sardinia.

nodes.title: Oualentia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B3 Oualentia

nodes.title: Pacheia Akra
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 Pacheia Akra

nodes.title: Patulcenses Campani
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B3 Patulcenses Campani

nodes.title: Patulcii
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A2 Patulcii

nodes.title: Pauli Putzu
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 Pauli Putzu

nodes.title: Pheronia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B2 Pheronia

nodes.title: Phintonis (island)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B1 Phintonis Ins.

nodes.title: Porticenses
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B3 Porticenses

nodes.title: Portus Luguidonis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B2 Portus Luguidonis

nodes.title: Quartu S. Elena
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B3 Quartu S. Elena

nodes.title: *Rubrenses
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B3 *Rubrenses

nodes.title: S. Giovanni
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 S. Giovanni

nodes.title: S. Salvatore di Cabras
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 S. Salvatore di Cabras

nodes.title: Saipros (river)
nodes.description: Flumendosa river.

nodes.title: Sarcapos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B3 Sarcapos

nodes.title: Sardinia (island)
nodes.description: The second largest island in the Mediterranean Sea

nodes.title: Temple of Sardus Pater
nodes.description: A Punic-Roman temple dedicated to Sardus Pater Babai located near Fluminimaggiore in southern Sardinia. The original phase of the temple dates ca. 500 BC.

nodes.title: Sestu
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B3 Sestu

nodes.title: Settimo
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B3 Settimo

nodes.title: Sikoulensioi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B3 Sikoulensioi

nodes.title: Sorso
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A2 Sorso

nodes.title: Sulcensis Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 Sulcensis Pr.

nodes.title: Sulci(s)
nodes.description: A site with Phoenician origins (founded ca. 730-700 B.C.) located in southwestern Sardinia.

nodes.title: Sulci(s)
nodes.description: Modern Tortolì, Sardinia.

nodes.title: Sulcis (river)
nodes.description: The Cixerri river.

nodes.title: Tegula
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A4 Tegula

nodes.title: Temos (river)
nodes.description: The Temo river.

nodes.title: Terr'e Frucca
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 Terr'e Frucca

nodes.title: Tharros
nodes.description: An ancient Phoenician settlement located in western Sardinia on a promontory in the Gulf of Oristano. While it originates as a Punic or Carthaginian settlement ca. 700 BC it continued as a major town in Roman times.

nodes.title: Thyrsos (river)
nodes.description: The Tirso river, one of the most important rivers of Sardinia, flows from the Punta Pianedda to the Gulf of Oristano.

nodes.title: Tibula?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B1 Tibula?

nodes.title: Turris Libisonis
nodes.description: A settlement of northwestern Sardinia, located at the mouth of the Mannu River. The site served as a port in Phoenician, Carthaginian, and Roman phases of occupation. The modern Porto Torres stands on the site, about 10 miles distant from Sassari.

nodes.title: Turublum Minus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B1 Turublum Minus

nodes.title: Usel(l)is
nodes.description: A Roman colonia in western Sardinia.

nodes.title: Ussana
nodes.description: A Roman bath structure of the fourth century A.D. whose remains were reused to construct the Medieval church of San Lorenzo.

nodes.title: Villacidro
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 Villacidro

nodes.title: Villaspeciosa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A3 Villaspeciosa

nodes.title: Viniolae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B1 Viniolae

nodes.title: Viniolae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 B2 Viniolae

nodes.title: Agiation
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 C3 Agiation

nodes.title: Alalie/Aleria
nodes.description: A city of Corsica with significant pre-historic, Greek, Etruscan, and Roman phases.

nodes.title: Albiana
nodes.description: A settlement in the interior of southern Corsica

nodes.title: Balatonoi
nodes.description: A pre-Roman people settled in south-eastern Corsica, mentioned by Ptolemy.

nodes.title: Chrysoun Oros
nodes.description: Chrysoun Oros is the highest mountain on the island of Corsica.

nodes.title: Corsica/Kyrnos (island)
nodes.description: The island of Corsica, in the Mediterranean Sea.

nodes.title: Gouola (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 D2 Gouola fl.

nodes.title: Hieron? (river)
nodes.description: A river in eastern Corsica that empties into the Tyrrhenian sea not far from Aleria (modern Fiumorbo).

nodes.title: Lourinon?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 D2 Lourinon?

nodes.title: Makrinoi
nodes.description: A pre-Roman people settled in north-eastern Corsica (modern Casinca), mentioned by Ptolemy.

nodes.title: Mariana
nodes.description: Mariana was a Roman city on the east coast of Corsica founded by Caius Marius ca. 93 BC.

nodes.title: Marianon Akron
nodes.description: A southern promontory of Corsica (modern Capo di Feno).

nodes.title: Temple of Jupiter
nodes.description: A temple dedicated to the Capitoline triad is located on the forum of Saepinum.

nodes.title: Sacriportus
nodes.description: Sacriportus is an ancient site of Latium located between Signia and Praeneste, although its precise location is no longer known. It was the site of a decisive battle between Caius Marius and Lucius Cornelius Sulla.

nodes.title: Clivus Capitolinus
nodes.description: The principal road leading to the Capitolium and the Arx in the city of Rome.

nodes.title: Roman theater of Suasa
nodes.description: The Roman theater of Suasa was discovered in 2003 during excavations near the amphitheater. The semicircular structure measures ca. 55 meters in diameter and dates to the first century A.D.

nodes.title: Thermopolium
nodes.description: A dining establishment that served drinks and hot food in antiquity. There are several well-preserved wall paintings in the interior.

nodes.title: Horti Lucull(i)ani
nodes.description: An elite villa and garden on the Pincian Hill in Rome laid out originally by Lucius Licinius Lucullus ca. 60 BC. The present day Villa Borghese gardens still cover a portion of the Gardens of Lucullus.

nodes.title: Temple/Church
nodes.description: Unknown

nodes.title: South Agora
nodes.description: The so-called South Agora was the city's secondary public square. The complex dedicated by a local aristocrat Diogenes to the emperor Tiberius.

nodes.title: Theater
nodes.description: The Theater of Aphrodisias dates to the second half of the first century B.C. and stands on the eastern slope of the acropolis.

nodes.title: Tetrapylon
nodes.description: The monumental columnar entrance to the sanctuary of Aphrodite

nodes.title: Basilica
nodes.description: Unknown

nodes.title: Arco Felice Vecchio
nodes.description: The so-called "Arco Felice Vecchio" is a city gate of the first century A.D. built under the administration of Domitian.

nodes.title: Via Celle necropolis
nodes.description: A Roman necropolis with 14 tombs constructed during the first and early second centuries A.D.

nodes.title: Tell al-Lahm/Dur-Yakin?/Duru(m)?
nodes.description: Tell al-Lahm/Dur-Yakin?/Duru(m)? is the possible location of an important first millennium B.C. Chaldean settlement. This site appears in first millennium B.C. texts together with Ur, Uruk, Larsa, Eridu, and Kullab (Uruk sanctuary), as well as in Assyrian and Neo-Babylonian texts and inscriptions.

nodes.title: Tigris/Diglitus (river)
nodes.description: The Tigris river, one of the two great rivers that define Mesopotamia, flows 1,850 km from the Taurus Mountains to the Persian Gulf.

nodes.title: Ur(i)
nodes.description: A major Sumerian city-state founded during the Ubaid period, ca. 3800 B.C. In archaeological terms, Ur is particularly well known for the lavish tombs of its Royal Cemetery, its massive Ziggurat. The site served as the capital of the Ur III dynasty.

nodes.title: Uruk/Orchoe/Erech/Orikut
nodes.description: Uruk was an ancient Sumerian (and later Babylonian) city located on the Euphrates river. At its height (ca. 2900 BC), Uruk's population may have topped 50,000 people and its walls enclosed an area of more than six square kilometers, making it the largest city in the world at that point in time.

nodes.title: Antonine Wall
nodes.description: A series of fortifications approximately 63 km in length, spanning the breadth of modern day Scotland between the Firth of Forth and the Firth of Clyde. The Antonine Wall was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2008.

nodes.title: Hadrian's Wall
nodes.description: Hadrian's Wall or Vallum Aelium was the first of two Roman fortifications built across northern Britannia. The project was begun in A.D. 122 and the works eventually stretched from the River Tyne near the North Sea to the Solway Firth on the Irish Sea. The wall represented the northern limit of the Roman Empire.

nodes.title: Kataderbis L.
nodes.description: An ancient lake, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Margastana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 93 unlocated Margastana Ins.

nodes.title: Ardashir-Khurra/Gur/[Firuzabad]
nodes.description: Ardashir-Khurra/Gur/[Firuzabad] was an ancient Persian city. Alexander of Macedonia destroyed the original settlement of Gōr, which was later revived by Ardashir I, founder of the Sassanid dynasty.

nodes.title: Gabr-i Mader-i Soleiman
nodes.description: The Tomb of Cyrus at Pasargadae dates ca. 559-529 B.C.

nodes.title: Gur-i Shapur
nodes.description: The so-called "Shapur cave" in the Zagros Mountains contains a colossal statue of Shapur I, the second ruler of the Sasanid Empire.

nodes.title: Naqsh-i Rustam
nodes.description: An ancient necropolis located northwest of Persepolis.

nodes.title: Pasargadae/Batrakatash
nodes.description: Pasargadae/Batrakatash was an ancient Persian city and the capital of Cyrus the Great (559–530 BC). It remained the capital until Cambyses II moved it to Susa. The site is listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

nodes.title: Qaleh Dukhtar
nodes.description: The so-called "Maiden Castle" is a large fortification built by Ardashir I in the early third century A.D. It is located about 8 kilometers to the north of Firuzabad in modern Iran. Despite the distance involved, it is listed as part of the "cultural landscape of Bam" in the 2004 UNESCO World Heritage List.

nodes.title: Veh Shapur/Bishapur
nodes.description: Veh Shapur/Bishapur was an ancient city in Iran on the ancient road between Persis and Elam. This ancient and medieval town in Fārs was, in the Sasanian period, the administrative center of one of the five districts in the province of Fārs.

nodes.title: Asabon M.
nodes.description: The Al Hajar Mountains of northeastern Oman and the eastern United Arab Emirates are the highest mountain range in the eastern Arabian peninsula.

nodes.title: Janussan
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 95 C3 Janussan

nodes.title: Jazirat al-Ghanam
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 95 inset Jazirat al-Ghanam

nodes.title: Qalat al-Bahrain
nodes.description: An ancient settlement with evidence from occupation stretching from 2300 BC to the sixteenth century AD that was at one time the capital of the Dilmun civilization. Qal’at al-Bahrain was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2005.

nodes.title: Thilouanoi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 95 C3 Thilouanoi

nodes.title: Tylos (island)
nodes.description: Tylos is the ancient name for Bahrain, renowned in antiquity as a center of pearl trading.

nodes.title: Atrek/Sideris?/Sarnios? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 96 C2 Atrek/Sideris?/Sarnios? fl.

nodes.title: Cho(a)rene
nodes.description: Cho(a)rene was a region located east of the Caspian Sea.

nodes.title: Tisia
nodes.description: An ancient place in Bruttium mentioned by Appian. Its precise location is unknown today.

nodes.title: Columbarium of Pomponius Hylas
nodes.description: A Roman columbarium on the Via Appia close to the Porta Latina. The columbarium was excavated in 1831 by Pietro Campana.

nodes.title: Eulmaš
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Anunnītu at Sippar-Anunnītu (=Sippar-Amnanum).

nodes.title: Etemenanki
nodes.description: The ziggurat of the god Marduk at Babylon. The Sumerian ceremonial name Etemenanki means "House, Foundation Platform of Heaven and Underworld."

nodes.title: Emeslam
nodes.description: The temple of the god Nergal at Cutha. The Sumerian ceremonial name Emeslam means "House, Warrior of the Netherworld."

nodes.title: Emašdari
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Ištar of Agade at Babylon. The Sumerian ceremonial name Emašdari means "House of Animal Offerings." The Neo-Babylonian king Nabonidus rebuilt/renovated it.

nodes.title: Ekurra
nodes.description: The temple of the god Bunene at Sippar. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ekurra means "House of the Mountains."

nodes.title: Ekunankuga
nodes.description: The ziggurat of the god Šamaš at Sippar. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ekunankuga means "House, Pure Stairway of Heaven."

nodes.title: Eduranna
nodes.description: The ziggurat of the god Šamaš at Larsa. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eduranna means "House, Bond of Heaven."

nodes.title: Badnigerimhuluha
nodes.description: Nineveh’s outer stone wall was called Badnigerimhuluha ("Wall, Terrorizer of Enemies"). It was constructed by the Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib after he moved the Assyrian capital to Nineveh. The visible remains of the twelve-kilometer-long wall and some of its gates are still visible today.

nodes.title: Sîn-Šamaš Temple
nodes.description: One of the temples in the citadel of Nineveh that was dedicated to the moon-god Sîn and the sun-god Šamaš. Its Sumerian ceremonial name is not preserved in extant cuneiform sources and its exact location remains unknown. The temple is generally believed to have been east of the temples of Ištar (Emašmaš) and Nabû (Ezida) and south of the North Palace (palace of Ashurbanipal).

nodes.title: Emašmaš
nodes.description: The most important temple in the citadel of Nineveh was dedicated to the city's tutelary deity, the goddess Ištar. The temple was located in the center of the citadel and went by the Sumerian ceremonial name Emašmaš (meaning uncertain).

nodes.title: Ekituškuga
nodes.description: A ziggurat dedicated to the goddess Ištar was built near the center of the citadel of Nineveh, not far from the city’s main temple Emašmaš. This structure was given the Sumerian ceremonial names Ekituškuga ("House, Pure Abode") and Ekibikuga ("House whose Site is Pure").

nodes.title: Šibaniba Gate
nodes.description: Most 7th-century B.C. Assyrian inscriptions record that Nineveh had eight south- and east-facing gates: the Šibaniba Gate was the seventh of these. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Dumuq-ašnan-u-lahar-qerebša-kayyān, which means "The Choicest of Grain and Flocks Are Constantly Inside It."

nodes.title: Halahhu Gate
nodes.description: Most 7th-century B.C. Assyrian inscriptions record that Nineveh had eight south- and east-facing gates: the Halahhu Gate was the eighth and last of these. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Bābilat-ḫiṣib-huršānī, which means "The Bearer of the Produce of the Mountains."

nodes.title: Adad Gate
nodes.description: The northern city wall of Nineveh had three gates: the Adad Gate was the easternmost of the three. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Adad-šārik-hegalli-ana-māti, which means "The God Adad Is the Provider of Prosperity to the Land."

nodes.title: Sîn Gate
nodes.description: The northern city wall of Nineveh had three gates: the Sîn Gate was the westernmost of the three. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and called it the Gate of the Garden, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Igisigsig-mušammeh-ṣippāti ("The God Igisigsig Is the One Who Makes Orchards Flourish"). Late in 695 B.C. or early in 694 B.C., the gate was dedicated to the moon-god Sîn and renamed Nannāru-nāṣir-agê-bēlūtīya ("The Divine Nannāru Is the One Who Protects My Lordly Crown").

nodes.title: Step Gate of the Gardens
nodes.description: Nineveh's western wall had seven (or eight) gates: the Step Gate of the Gardens was the third gate from the northern city wall. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it sometime between 694 and 691 B.C. and he gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Igisigsig-mušammeh-ṣippāti, which means "The God Igisigsig Is the One Who Makes Orchards Flourish." The gate is still unlocated, but, based on its everyday name Akkadian name mušlālum ša kirî ("Step Gate of the Gardens"), it must have led up to Sennacherib's Palace on the citadel, perhaps at the foot of the sloping passage Room LI of the South-West Palace.

nodes.title: tribus Pomptina
nodes.description: The tribus Pomptina (or Pontina) was a later rural tribe of Rome, which was established in 358 B.C.

nodes.title: Hospitium of Hermes
nodes.description: A Roman hospitium located near the Porta Stabia in Pompeii (I, 1, 8).

nodes.title: tribus Romilia
nodes.description: An older rural tribe of ancient Rome that was located at the edge of Etruscan territory, across the river Tiber.

nodes.title: Stabian Gate
nodes.description: A Roman city gate at the southern terminus of Strada Stabiana in Pompeii.

nodes.title: tribus Sabatina
nodes.description: The tribus Sabatina (or Sabatia) was a later rural tribe of ancient Rome, which was established in 387 B.C.

nodes.title: Saint-Michel tumulus
nodes.description: The Saint-Michel tumulus is a megalithic funerary mound in Brittany and one of the largest such mounds in Europe.

nodes.title: Brownshill Dolmen
nodes.description: The Brownshill Dolmen is a megalithic portal tomb built between 4000 and 3000 BC near Carlow, Ireland.

nodes.title: Regio II, Pompeii
nodes.description: The so-called Regio II, an archaeological subdivision located in the eastern section of Pompeii, includes the Amphitheater and the Large Palaestra, as well as a number of residences and commercial structures.

nodes.title: Hecatompylos?/Komish/[(Shahr-i) Qumis]
nodes.description: Hecatompylos? was an ancient city in Iran that served as the capital of the Parthian Arsacid dynasty by 200 BC. Alexander passed through in 330 BC and the city eventually became part of the Seleucid empire and later a capital of the Parthian empire.

nodes.title: [Khuvar]/Choara/Apameia (Rhagiane)?
nodes.description: [Khuvar]/Choara/Apameia (Rhagiane)?, a settlement in Parthia called “the most attractive place of Parthia” by Pliny the Elder.

nodes.title: Komisene/Komish
nodes.description: Komisene/Komish was a region bordering Media. Hecatompylos was its chief city.

nodes.title: Padishkhwar(gar)?/Pressouar?/Harborz M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 96 A4 Padishkhwar(gar)?/Pressouar?/Harborz M.

nodes.title: Varkana/Hyrcania/Gurgan
nodes.description: An important region of ancient Iran located between the Caspian Sea and the Harborz Mons.

nodes.title: Great Wall of Gorgan
nodes.description: A linear fortification system, probably built in the Parthian period and used during the Sasanian period, the so-called "Great Wall of Gorgan" stretches almost 200 km from the east coast of the Caspian Sea to near the town of Pishkamar in modern Iran. If the fortification system had a name in antiquity, it has not survived.

nodes.title: Achriane
nodes.description: An ancient region in eastern Hyrkania (in modern Iran).

nodes.title: (A)Parni
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 97 D2 (A)Parni

nodes.title: Daoi/Dahae
nodes.description: An Iranian people of ancient Central Asia, the Daoi/Dahae were composed of a confederation of three tribes – the Parni, Xanthii, and Pissuri. These peoples occupied an area that corresponds with much of modern Turkmenistan.

nodes.title: Nisa(ia)/Parthaunisa/Mithradatkert/Shahr-ram-Peroz
nodes.description: An ancient Parthian fortress containing two settlement mounds, the tells of Old and New Nisa.

nodes.title: Pissouroi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 97 unlocated Pissouroi

nodes.title: Xandioi/Xanthioi/Parioi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 97 unlocated Xandioi/Xanthioi/Parioi

nodes.title: Alexandria/Antiochia/Merv
nodes.description: Alexandria/Antiochia/Merv was a major oasis-city of Central Asia, located along the Silk Road (in modern Turkmenistan). Listed as UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1999.

nodes.title: Ar(e)ia
nodes.description: A region and Persian satrapy located in the area of the modern Afghan province of Herat.

nodes.title: Arius (river)
nodes.description: The Hari River of Afghanistan.

nodes.title: Margiana/Margush/Merv
nodes.description: Margiana/Margush/Merv (Persian: مرو), once the Achaemenid Satrapy of Margiana, is a region of ancient Persia.

nodes.title: Alexandria Oxiana?
nodes.description: Alexandria Oxiana? or Alexandria on Oxus (Ai-Khanoum) was founded in the fourth century B.C. in the wake of the campaigns of Alexander the Great. It was a chief city of the Graeco-Bactrian kingdom.

nodes.title: Pareitakene
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 99 B1 Pareitakene

nodes.title: Takht-i Sangin
nodes.description: Takht-i Sangin is an ancient settlement located near the confluence of the Vakhsh and Panj rivers. It may be the source of the so-called "Oxus Treasure".

nodes.title: Tarmita/Termez
nodes.description: Termez was part of the Graeco-Bactrian kingdom and later the Kushan empire. It eventually became an important center of Buddhism.

nodes.title: Achaia (province)
nodes.description: A Roman province of the early empire, comprising the Peloponnese, central Greece, Euboea, most of the Ionian islands and adjacent areas.

nodes.title: Ancient Egypt (region)
nodes.description: The ancient kingdom(s) and region of Egypt as understood by the Egyptians themselves, their neighbors, and their successors. Individual administrative districts, provinces, nomes, and the like have separate place resources in Pleiades.

nodes.title: Aquitania (Roman province)
nodes.description: A Roman province formed in 27 B.C. by Augustus. According to Strabo, it incorporated the territories of the Aquitani and 14 other peoples whose territories were located between the Garumna and Liger rivers.

nodes.title: Asia
nodes.description: The Roman province of Asia, located on the eastern coast of the Aegean Sea. The region was bequeathed to the Roman Republic by Attalus III of Pergamum in 133 BCE. It was divided into seven smaller provinces by Diocletian in the 4th century CE.

nodes.title: Baetica
nodes.description: Baetica was one of three Roman Imperial provinces in the Iberian peninsula.

nodes.title: Belgica (province)
nodes.description: The Roman province also called Gallia Belgica.

nodes.title: Bithynia et Pontus
nodes.description: A province of the Roman Empire on the Black Sea coast that was formed when the former kingdoms of Bithynia (annexed by Rome in 74 B.C.) and Pontus (annexed in 63 B.C.) were joined together.

nodes.title: Britannia (province)
nodes.description: A province of the Roman Empire at the Death of Trajan (117 CE).

nodes.title: Cyprus (Roman province)
nodes.description: The Roman province.

nodes.title: Creta et Cyrene (Roman province)
nodes.description: A province of the Roman Empire at the death of Trajan (117 CE).

nodes.title: Dalmatia (province)
nodes.description: A province of the Roman Empire at the death of Trajan (117 CE).

nodes.title: Germania Inferior
nodes.description: Germania Inferior was a province of the Roman empire located on the west bank of the Rhine river. It was established as a province ca. AD 80.

nodes.title: Germania Superior
nodes.description: Germania Superior was a province of the Roman empire. Its administrative capital was Mogontiacum (Mainz).

nodes.title: Hellespontus
nodes.description: A Late Roman province included on Hierokles' list.

nodes.title: Iudaea (province)
nodes.description: The Roman province of Iudaea, incorporating the historical regions of Judea, Samaria, and Idumaea, was established in 6 CE, when the former tetrarchy of Herod Archelaus came under direct Roman administration. Following the Bar Kokhba War (132-135), Hadrian changed the province's name to Palaestina, and in the mid- to late 4th century CE the area was divided into three provinces (Palaestina Prima, Secunda, and Tertia or Salutaris).

nodes.title: Lycia et Pamphylia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 100 M4 Lycia et Pamphylia

nodes.title: Mauretania Tingitana (Roman province)
nodes.description: The Roman imperial province of Mauretania Tingitana. Located in northwest Africa, the province stretched from the Mulucha river (modern Oued Moulouia in Morocco) westward to the Atlantic.

nodes.title: Narbonensis
nodes.description: The Roman imperial province of Gallia Narbonensis.

nodes.title: Pannonia Superior (province)
nodes.description: A province of the Roman Empire at the death of Trajan (117 CE).

nodes.title: Sardinia et Corsica (Roman province)
nodes.description: The province of Sardinia et Corsica was the second Roman province and came under Roman control after the First Punic War.

nodes.title: Sicilia (Roman province)
nodes.description: The Roman province of Sicilia (Sicily) was initially organized in 241 BC as a territory with a proconsular governor. The territory fell to the Vandals in AD 440 but was reclaimed by the Byzantines.

nodes.title: Syria (Roman imperial province)
nodes.description: The Roman imperial province of Syria.

nodes.title: Tarraconensis
nodes.description: The Roman imperial province of Hispania Tarraconensis.

nodes.title: Alpes Graiae et Poeninae (Roman province)
nodes.description: Alpes Graiae et Poeninae, a small Alpine province of the Roman Empire. There were three such provinces in the western Alps. Alpes Graiae et Poeninae comprised the Val d'Aosta region and the Canton Valais in Switzerland.

nodes.title: Alpes Cottiae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 100 H3 no. 2 (Alpes Cottiae)

nodes.title: Alpes Maritimae (province)
nodes.description: A Roman province established in the early days of the empire and persisting, with changes, into Late Antiquity.

nodes.title: Albaniana
nodes.description: Albaniana was the site of a castellum that was part of the Roman frontier system (limes) of Germania Inferior.

nodes.title: Albis (river)
nodes.description: The Elbe river flows 1,094 km from the Krkonoše Mountains to the North Sea.

nodes.title: Amisia (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 10 D3 Amisia fl.

nodes.title: Ampsivarii
nodes.description: The Ampsivarii were a Germanic tribe whose homeland was close to the Amisia fl.

nodes.title: Aurelium Cananefatium/Forum Hadriani
nodes.description: Aurelium Cananefatium/Forum Hadriani (modern Voorburg) was the northernmost Roman city on the European continent. It was destroyed ca. AD 270.

nodes.title: Batavodurum/(Ulpia) Noviomagus
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of the Batavi. Modern Nijmegen in the Netherlands.

nodes.title: Burcana (island)
nodes.description: Burcana Ins. (Borkum) is an island in the North Sea. It is mentioned by Strabo and Pliny the Elder as the Burchana fabaria (island of beans).

nodes.title: Carvo?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 10 B5 Carvo?

nodes.title: Castra Herculis?
nodes.description: Castra Herculis? (modern Arnhem)

nodes.title: Chauci
nodes.description: The Chauci were a German tribe occupying the territory between the Ems and Elbe rivers.

nodes.title: Fectio
nodes.description: Fectio was a castellum along the Roman frontier system (limes) of Germania Inferior.

nodes.title: Grinnes
nodes.description: The site of a Roman fort on the river Waal.

nodes.title: Kalkriese
nodes.description: The presumptive archaeological site of the Battle of the Teutoburg Forest (A.D. 9).

nodes.title: Laurum
nodes.description: The Castellum Laurum along the frontier in Germania Inferior was built first in the AD 40s and then destroyed during the Batavian Revolt of AD 69. The rebuilt fort remained in use until the early fifth century.

nodes.title: Levefanum?
nodes.description: A site located along the Roman frontier (limes) in Germania Inferior.

nodes.title: Lugdunum
nodes.description: Lugdunum Batavorum, also referred to as Brittenburg, is the site of Roman ruins near Katwijk aan Zee that emerged in the sixteenth century at the mouth of the Oude Rijn (old river Rhine). The site is connected with the Roman frontier system (limes) of Germania Inferior.

nodes.title: Matilo
nodes.description: Matilo was a castellum along the Roman frontier system (limes) of Germania Inferior. It is located within present-day Leiden.

nodes.title: Suebi
nodes.description: The Suebi were an ancient tribe in Germany, first mentioned by Iulius Caesar ca. 58 BC.

nodes.title: Teutoburgiensis? Saltus
nodes.description: Teutoburgiensis? Saltus (Teutoburger Wald) is a range of low, forested mountains in Lower Saxony and North Rhine-Westphalia.

nodes.title: Traiectum
nodes.description: Traiectum (modern Utrecht) was a fortified site along the Roman frontier (limes) of Germania Inferior. It may have been a crossing point on the Rhine river.

nodes.title: Visurgis (river)
nodes.description: The Weser river in northwestern Germany.

nodes.title: Vleuten-De Meern
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 10 A4 Vleuten-De Meern

nodes.title: Gallaecia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 E3 Gallaecia

nodes.title: Britannia I (province)
nodes.description: Britannia I or Britannia Prima was a province of the Roman empire that was established under the Diocletianic reforms of the third century. The capital of the province remains undetermined but the province was mostly likely centered in the present regions of Wales and Cornwall.

nodes.title: Britannia II?
nodes.description: Britannia II or Britannia Secunda was part of the Diocese of "the Britains" created during the Diocletianic Reforms. It is included in the Verona List of the Roman provinces. Its administrative center may have been located at Eboracum (York).

nodes.title: Aquitania II (province)
nodes.description: The Roman province of Aquitania Secunda was established during the reforms of Diocletian in the late third century and assigned to the diocese of Viennensis. Burdigala was its administrative capital.

nodes.title: Aquitania I (province)
nodes.description: The Roman province of Aquitania Prima was established during the reforms of Diocletian in the late third century and assigned to the diocese of Viennensis. Avaricum Biturigum was its administrative capital.

nodes.title: Mauretania Sitifensis
nodes.description: A late Roman province within the diocese of Africa.

nodes.title: Corsica (Province)
nodes.description: The post-Diocletianic province of Corsica according to the Verona List (ca. AD 303-324); coincident geographically with the island in the Mediterranean.

nodes.title: Viennensis (late Roman province)
nodes.description: The Late Roman province as defined in the Barrington Atlas (BAtlas 101 H3 Viennensis)

nodes.title: Numidia Cirtensis
nodes.description: Late Roman province within the Diocese of Africa.

nodes.title: Numidia Militiana
nodes.description: Late Roman province within the diocese of Africa.

nodes.title: Sardinia (late Roman province)
nodes.description: The Late Roman province of Sardinia was organized under a praeses during the reign of Diocletian. In the fifth century (455) the island was occupied by the Vandals. Justinian I reclaimed the island in 534 and it remained under Byzantine control until the eleventh century.

nodes.title: Byzacena
nodes.description: Byzacena was a late Roman province in the diocese of Africa. It was located in what is now Tunisia.

nodes.title: Flaminia et Picenum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 J3 Flaminia et Picenum

nodes.title: Tuscia et Umbria
nodes.description: A Late Antique region and administrative unit of central Italy that was created during the Diocletianic reforms. It was formed by joining two of the Augustan administrative regions together (Regio VI Umbria and Regio VII Etruria). It was part of the diocese of Italia under Diocletian and, under Constantine I, part of the vicariate of Italia Suburbicaria.

nodes.title: Tripolitana (late Roman province)
nodes.description: A late Roman province within the diocese of Africa.

nodes.title: Apulia et Calabria
nodes.description: Apulia et Calabria was the second Augustan region (regio II) of Italy.

nodes.title: Lucania et Bruttii
nodes.description: Lucania et Bruttii was the third Augustan region (regio III) of Italy.

nodes.title: Epirus Vetus
nodes.description: A province of the Roman Empire that was later incorporated into the province of Macedonia.

nodes.title: Dardania
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 L3 Dardania

nodes.title: Haemimontus
nodes.description: Haemimontus was a late Roman and early Byzantine province located in northeastern Thrace.

nodes.title: Caria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 M4 Caria

nodes.title: Lydia (province)
nodes.description: The Late Roman (post-Diocletianic) province of Lydia.

nodes.title: Palaestina (province)
nodes.description: Following the Bar Kokhba War, Hadrian abolished the name "Iudaea," renaming the province Palaestina. Under Diocletian, the area was divided into three provinces (Palaestina Prima, Secunda, and Tertia).

nodes.title: Hispaniae
nodes.description: A late Roman diocese.

nodes.title: Italia (Diocese)
nodes.description: The post-Diocletianic diocese of Italia according to the Verona List (ca. AD 303-324). Italia was divided between the vicarius Italiae in the north and the vicarius of Rome in the south.

nodes.title: Viennensis (diocese)
nodes.description: The Late Roman diocese as defined in the Barrington Atlas (BAtlas 101 F3 Viennensis)

nodes.title: Galliae
nodes.description: The Diocese of Gaul was a diocese of the later Roman Empire.

nodes.title: Thracia
nodes.description: The Late Roman province as defined in the Barrington Atlas (BAtlas 101 L3 Thracia)

nodes.title: Asiana (diocese)
nodes.description: The late Roman (post-Diocletianic) diocese of Asiana.

nodes.title: Oriens
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 M6 Oriens

nodes.title: Gallia
nodes.description: The ancient region known to the Romans as "Gallia" (Gaul). Famously described by Caesar as the territory of the ancient Celts (Celtae), whom the Romans called Gauls (Galli in Latin).

nodes.title: Corbulonis Fossa
nodes.description: A canal between the Rhine and Mosa rivers constructed by Roman soldiers commanded by Corbulo.

nodes.title: Drusiana Fossa
nodes.description: Drusiana Fossa was a canal constructed by Nero Claudius Drusus ca. 12 BC in order to connect the Rhine delta with Lake Flevo.

nodes.title: Basílica de Son Peretó
nodes.description: A Paleochristian site dating to the fifth century A.D.

nodes.title: Porta Capena
nodes.description: The Porta Capena was a gate in Rome's Republican city walls ("Servian Wall") located on the south-west slope of the Caelian Hill.

nodes.title: Porta Appia
nodes.description: A gate in the Aurelian Wall through which the Via Appia passed. Now known as Porta S. Sebastiano.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Spoletium
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Spoletium dates to the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Ponte delle Torri
nodes.description: A thirteenth century aqueduct at Spoletium.

nodes.title: Pizzone necropolis
nodes.description: A Roman necropolis located at Nocera Superiore which was buried by the volcanic ejecta of the Vesuvian eruption of A.D. 79.

nodes.title: Arco di Riccardo
nodes.description: A surviving gate of the ancient city walls of Tergeste that dates to the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Arènes de Lutèce
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater of Lutetia (modern Paris).

nodes.title: Via Cornelia
nodes.description: The Via Cornelia was an ancient road that ran along the north side of the circus Gai et Neronis. The road diverged from the Via Triumphalis west of the pons Neronianus, near a large tomb known as the Meta Romuli.

nodes.title: Gallo-Roman temple at Nasium
nodes.description: Archaeological remains of the Gallo-Roman temple at ancient Nasium, located at Mazeroie, commune Naix-aux-Forges

nodes.title: Street of Facades, Petra
nodes.description: The so-called "Street of Facades" is a necropolis that is lined with tall, rock-cut tombs that have elaborate facades.

nodes.title: Tell Abu en-Ni'aj
nodes.description: Archaeological site in the Jordan Valley containing the remains of a village dated to the Early Bronze Age IV (ca. 2500-1900 BCE).

nodes.title: Leuctra tropaion
nodes.description: A trophy monument erected by the Thebans following their defeat of the Spartans in 371 BC.

nodes.title: Iri-sagrig
nodes.description: A city of southern Mesopotamia attested from the Fara period (Early Dynastic IIIa) through the Old Babylonian period, located on the Tigris river near Nippur, about 60-80km north of Umma. The exact location of the site is unknown to archaeologists, but known to looters, who have stolen and sold thousands of tablets from the site.

nodes.title: Necropolis of Campo della Fonte
nodes.description: The Campo della Fonte at Rusellae.

nodes.title: Roman theater of Scythopolis
nodes.description: The Roman theater of Scythopolis.

nodes.title: Località De Santis I at Pontecagnano
nodes.description: Necropolis in Pontecagnano containing fifty burials from the Orientalizing Period (725-550 BCE) and an additional six burials from the Lucanian period (4th-3rd centuries BCE).

nodes.title: Serra Orrios
nodes.description: An important nuragic complex that includes remains of a megalithic megaron-type structure.

nodes.title: Drobeta amphitheater
nodes.description: The Drobeta Roman amphitheater.

nodes.title: Mausoleum Augusti
nodes.description: A monumental tomb built in the Campus Martius at Rome by Augustus and dedicated in 28 B.C. The mausoleum served as a family tomb for the Iulio-Claudians.

nodes.title: Poikile Petra
nodes.description: Poikile Petra is the name of a road connecting Seleucia ad Calycadnum and Corycus.

nodes.title: Mura Serviane, Anagni
nodes.description: An ancient opus quadratum wall at Anagni referred to as "Mura Serviane" based on its construction technique.

nodes.title: Santuario di Pyrgi
nodes.description: A sanctuary with twin temples located at the Etruscan port. The Pyrgi sanctuary was initially excavated by Massimo Pallottino in 1957. The so-called Pyrgi Plaques were discovered here in 1964.

nodes.title: Deir Abu Matta
nodes.description: Late antique settlement, possibly monastic, with substantial remains of a church, mud-brick structures, and tombs.

nodes.title: Adonis (river)
nodes.description: The Abraham River of Lebanon.

nodes.title: Amykes Pedion
nodes.description: A large plain located at the east foot of Amanus mountains.

nodes.title: Antilibanus M.
nodes.description: The Anti-Lebanon mountains, also known as the Eastern Lebanon Mountain Range.

nodes.title: Asharne
nodes.description: Tell ‘Acharneh is located 35 km northwest of Hama, on the north bank of the Orontes River, at the crossroads of two main trade routes. This center for the production of oil, wax, and wheat was occupied during the Bronze and Iron Ages, as well as during the First Crusades. Its ancient name, Tunip, is known from second-millennium-BC sources. A stele fragment bearing an inscription of the Neo-Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BCE) found there attests to the city’s occupation during the Iron Age.

nodes.title: Barbalissus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 F2 Barbalissus

nodes.title: Koile Syria/Massyas
nodes.description: Koile Syria/Massyas is a Hellenistic name for a region of Syria.

nodes.title: Larissa/Sizara
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 C3 Larissa/Sizara

nodes.title: Nicephorium/Callinicum/Leontopolis
nodes.description: Nicephorium (modern ar-Raqqa in Syria) was an ancient settlement on the river Euphrates in Syria.

nodes.title: Palmyra
nodes.description: An ancient oasis and trading city with monumental remains, located in modern Syria. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1980.

nodes.title: Pella/Apamea
nodes.description: Pella/Apamea in Syria was an ancient city established by the Seleucids ca. 300 B.C.

nodes.title: Phoenicium Mare
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 A2 Phoenicium Mare

nodes.title: Simyra?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 B4 Simyra?

nodes.title: Thapsacus
nodes.description: The location of the ancient site of Thapsacus is no longer known, but it lay on the western bank of the Euphrates river.

nodes.title: Zenodotion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 unlocated Zenodotion

nodes.title: Abila Dekapoleos/Seleukeia
nodes.description: Abila was a Ptolemaic town located in northern Palestine. Antiochus III conquered it and Pompeius Magnus later freed it in 64 B.C. Becoming autonomous thereafter, Abila became part of the Decapolis.

nodes.title: Abilene
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 C2 Abilene

nodes.title: Ahmadiya
nodes.description: Remains of an ancient village in the Golan that produced Greek and Hebrew Inscriptions probably associated with a synagogue. The site is described by Urman et al. as occupying "two low hills near a group of springs about two kilometers northeast of Qaṣrin."

nodes.title: Ake/Ptolemais
nodes.description: The Phoenician city of Akko was re-founded by Ptolemy II Philadelphos from ca. 285-246 B.C.

nodes.title: Beirut
nodes.description: An ancient Phoenician city, known by various names in antiquity, in what is now Lebanon.

nodes.title: Bostra/Col. Nova Traiana Alexandriana
nodes.description: The ancient city of Bostra (modern Busra in Syria), where extensive ancient Nabataean, Roman, Byzantine and Umayyad structures still visible. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1980.

nodes.title: Chrysoroas/Bardines (river)
nodes.description: Chrysoroas/Bardines fl. (Barada river) flows through Syria from the Anti-Lebanon Mountains to the oasis of Ghouta (الغوطة).

nodes.title: Crocodilon (river)
nodes.description: Crocodilon fl. (Nahal Taninim).

nodes.title: Damascus
nodes.description: The ancient city of Damascus, located in modern Syria, with some 125 monuments dating back to the Roman period. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1979.

nodes.title: Ekdippa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B3 Ekdippa

nodes.title: Gaba Philippi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B4 Gaba Philippi

nodes.title: Gerasa/Antiochia ad Chrysorhoam
nodes.description: Gerasa became a substantial center under Antiochos IV Epiphanes, at which time it became known as Antioch on the Chrysorhoas. It became part of the territory of Iudaea and in 63 B.C. Pompeius Magnus made it part of the Decapolis. It received the status of a Roman colony in the third century.

nodes.title: Heldua
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B2 Heldua

nodes.title: Heliopolis/Col. Iulia Augusta Felix
nodes.description: An ancient settlement in Lebanon's Beqaa Valley, named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site because "with its colossal structures, [it] is one of the finest examples of Imperial Roman architecture at its apogee."

nodes.title: Hermon (mountain)
nodes.description: Hermon M. (Mount Hermon)

nodes.title: Hieromyces (river)
nodes.description: Hieromyces fl. (Yarmouk river) is the largest tributary of the Jordan river.

nodes.title: Iabakchos (river)
nodes.description: Iabakchos fl. (Zarqa River (Arabic: نهر الزرقاء‎, Hebrew: נחל יבוק, Yabok river)) is the second largest tributary of the Jordan River.

nodes.title: Itouraia
nodes.description: Itouraia was a Late Hellenistic and early Roman region north of Palestine extending from from Mount Lebanon to the Anti-Lebanon mountains in Syria.

nodes.title: Kadasa
nodes.description: A multi-period settlement, with Bronze Age to Roman occupation, most notably the site of a large, Persian and Hellenistic administrative building.

nodes.title: Libanus M.
nodes.description: A mountain range of northern Syria that is between the Mediterranean coastline and the Antilibanos mountains of the interior.

nodes.title: Litas (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B3 Litas fl.

nodes.title: Lykos (river)
nodes.description: The ancient Lykos river (modern Nahr al-Kalb) flows from the Libanus mountains to the Mediterranean, passing ca. 10 km north of Beirut.

nodes.title: Aliler Fortress
nodes.description: Aliler Castle is the modern Turkish name of an Urartian fortress situated in the village of Karaağaç, approx. 11 km southeast of Lake Van. Here, the remains of a column base with a fragmentary preserved Urartian inscription of the Urartian king Minua (9th / 8th century BCE) have been found.

nodes.title: Aedes Tensarum
nodes.description: A temple on Rome's Capitoline Hill where the carts that carried the exuviae in festival parades were stored.

nodes.title: Ara del Tufo necropolis
nodes.description: An Etruscan necropolis at Tuscania.

nodes.title: Castle Hill
nodes.description: Castle Hill is located about 350 m south-east of Round Hill and was the site of an Iron Age hill fort.

nodes.title: Domus Romana
nodes.description: West corner of the museum built on the site of a Roman Villa. Time periods following the Barrington Atlas (BAtlas 47 inset Melita).

nodes.title: archaeological area of Monte Bibele
nodes.description: An important later Etruscan and Celtic settlement in the Po Plain with signs of occupation in the Late Bronze Age and then again between the fifth and second centuries BC.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Dionysos
nodes.description: The Sanctuary of Dionysos, which includes a theater, choregic monument, statue bases, and at least one temple, formed part of the civic center of the Attic deme of Ikarion.

nodes.title: Lake Stymphalia
nodes.description: A lake located in the northeastern part of the Peloponnese in Greece.

nodes.title: Temple of Apollo at Syracuse
nodes.description: Temple of Apollo at Syracuse on the island of Ortygia.

nodes.title: Roman theater of Milan
nodes.description: The Roman theater of Milan was built during the Augustan period and could accommodate 7,000 to 9,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Villa Imperiale of Milan
nodes.description: A palatial Roman villa dating to the reign of Maximian.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater of Beneventum
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater of Beneventum dates to the reign of the emperor Nero.

nodes.title: Forum of Beneventum
nodes.description: The forum of the Roman city of Beneventum.

nodes.title: Mausoleum of Theodoric
nodes.description: A monument built in Ravenna, Italy, ca. AD 520 by Theodoric the Great as his future tomb. After Belisarius reconquered Ravenna in 540, the tomb was converted into the church of Sta. Maria della Rotonda.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Perge
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Perge was built ca. 120 AD and renovated ca. 250 AD.

nodes.title: Kaleköy
nodes.description: Kaleköy is a modern village situated ca. 15 km northeast of Mazgirt and ca. 90 km to the north-northeast of Elaziğ in the southeast of Turkey. In the cliff face above the village, lies an Urartian rock-cut tomb. At the left of its entrance is a rock-cut inscription of the Urartian king Rusa, son of Argišti II (seventh century BCE) (CTU I A 12-6). Nowadays the inscription is heavily damaged.

nodes.title: Reginum/Castra Regina
nodes.description: Reginum/Castra Regina was a Roman military installation on the Danube established ca. A.D. 179 for Legio III Italica.

nodes.title: Saltus Sumelocennensis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 B4 Saltus Sumelocennensis

nodes.title: Semnones
nodes.description: The Semnones were a tribe of the Germanic Suebi whose territory lay between the Albis and Viadua rivers.

nodes.title: Sumelocenna
nodes.description: Sumelocenna was a Roman settlement on the Neckar river that was the seat of the procurator of the saltus Sumelocennensis during the late first century AD.

nodes.title: Tragisa(mus) (river)
nodes.description: A tributary of the Danube in lower Austria.

nodes.title: Vicus Alisinensium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 C3 Vicus Alisinensium

nodes.title: Vindelici
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 D4 Vindelici

nodes.title: Virdo? (river)
nodes.description: A river of Bavaria that is a tributary of the Lech.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 B4 unnamed aqueduct (Sumelocenna)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 B2 unnamed bridge (over Moenus fl., near Grosskrotzenburg)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 D4 unnamed bridge (over Licca fl., at Augusta Vindelicum)

nodes.title: Pontus Euxinus
nodes.description: The Black Sea.

nodes.title: Carnuntum
nodes.description: A Roman army camp on the Danube river in Noricum; after the first century AD Carnuntum served as the capital of Upper Pannonia.

nodes.title: Laedavus (river)
nodes.description: The Leitha river is a right tributary of the Danube.

nodes.title: Quadi
nodes.description: The Quadi, mentioned by Tacitus, were an ancient Germanic tribe and a part of the Suebi.

nodes.title: Vindobona
nodes.description: Originally a Celtic settlement of Noricum, Vindobona (now Vienna, Austria) became a Roman military installation by the first half of the first century AD.

nodes.title: Syria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 1 K3 Syria

nodes.title: Thessalia
nodes.description: Thessalia (Thessaly) was a region of ancient Greece.

nodes.title: Tyrrhenum/Inferum Mare
nodes.description: The Tyrrhenian Sea is part of the Mediterranean Sea off the western coast of Italy. It takes its name from the Tyrrhenian people, another name for the Etruscans.

nodes.title: Ustica (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Tyrrhenian Sea occupied since the middle of the second millennium B.C. when Phoenician traders were present there.

nodes.title: Acitodunum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 H2 Acitodunum

nodes.title: Aginnum
nodes.description: Aginnum (modern Agen) was the capital of the Nitiobriges in Gaul.

nodes.title: *Andecamulum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G2 *Andecamulum

nodes.title: Aquitania (region)
nodes.description: A region corresponding generally to modern Aquitaine in France. Its Latin name derives from a tribal confederation incorporated into the Roman empire in the first century BCE. Subsequent Roman provinces used the name.

nodes.title: Aquitanicus Sinus
nodes.description: Aquitanicus Sinus (Bay of Biscay) is a gulf of the northeast Atlantic Ocean located south of the Celtic Sea.

nodes.title: *Argentomagus
nodes.description: *Argentomagus was a pre-Roman and later Roman settlement in the territory of the Bituriges tribe.

nodes.title: Augustonemetum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 I3 Augustonemetum

nodes.title: Augustoritum
nodes.description: Augustoritum (modern Limoges, France) in Gaul was founded as a Roman city ca. 10 B.C.

nodes.title: Aulerci Cenomani
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F1 Aulerci Cenomani

nodes.title: Autessiodurum
nodes.description: Autessiodurum was a town of the Senones in Gallia Celtica.

nodes.title: Avaricum/Biturigae
nodes.description: Avaricum/Biturigae, located at the confluence of Auron and Yèvre river, served as the capital of the Bituriges Cubi.

nodes.title: Avario (river)
nodes.description: Avario fl. (Aveyron river)

nodes.title: Bituriges Cubi
nodes.description: A Gallic tribe.

nodes.title: Bituriges Vivisci
nodes.description: The Bituriges Vivisci were a tribe of Gaul whose capital was at Burdigala.

nodes.title: Blatomagus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G2 Blatomagus

nodes.title: Briva (Curretia)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G3 Briva (Curretia)

nodes.title: Burdigala
nodes.description: Burdigala (modern Bordeaux) was a Celtic center of the Bituriges Vivisci. The Romans lost a battle at the site in 107 BC, with consul Lucius Cassius Longinus being killed in the action. Rome eventually controlled the area ca. 60 BC.

nodes.title: Cadurci
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G4 Cadurci

nodes.title: Caesarodunum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F1 Caesarodunum

nodes.title: Carantomagus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 H4 Carantomagus

nodes.title: Cares (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G1 Cares fl.

nodes.title: Carovicus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G3 Carovicus

nodes.title: Cas(s)inomagus
nodes.description: Located in Transalpine Gaul, Cas(s)inomagus is included on the Peutinger Table. It lies along the road from Mediolanum Santonum (Saintes) to Ausritum, Augustoritum (Lirnmoes), some 25.5 Roman miles from Limoges.

nodes.title: Cenabum
nodes.description: Cenabum was an oppidum of the Carnutes tribe.

nodes.title: Crosa (river)
nodes.description: The river known as the Creuse

nodes.title: Diolindum?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F4 Diolindum?

nodes.title: Divona
nodes.description: Divona (Cahors) was the capital of the civitas of the Cadurci throughout the Roman period. It takes its name from a sacred spring (likely the Fontaine des Chartreux) and a ford on the Lot river.

nodes.title: Duranius (river)
nodes.description: The Duranius or Duranus, the modern Dordogne, is a river of Aquitania that flows into the Atlantic Ocean.

nodes.title: Durotincum?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G3 Durotincum?

nodes.title: Evina
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F1 Evina

nodes.title: Garumna (river)
nodes.description: The Garonne is a river of southwestern Gaul and northern Iberia.

nodes.title: *Geinum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 E1 *Geinum

nodes.title: Herios (river)
nodes.description: Herios fl. (Vilaine river)

nodes.title: Iciodoro
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F2 Iciodoro

nodes.title: Issando
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G3 Issando

nodes.title: Lemovices
nodes.description: The Lemovices were a Gaulish tribe centered around Augustoritum (Limoges).

nodes.title: Liger (river)
nodes.description: The Loire river is the longest river in France. The river runs a course of 1,012 kilometres (629 miles).

nodes.title: Limonum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F2 Limonum

nodes.title: Mediolanum
nodes.description: A town of southwest Gaul founded ca. 20 BC, Mediolanum Santonum was connected with the Roman road network that served Burdigala.

nodes.title: Montbouy
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 H1 Montbouy

nodes.title: Nitiobroges/Nitiobriges
nodes.description: The Nitiobroges were an ancient tribe of southwestern Gaul.

nodes.title: Oltis (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F4 Oltis fl.

nodes.title: Petrocori
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F3 Petrocori

nodes.title: Pictones
nodes.description: The Pictones were a Celtic tribe that inhabited an area along the south bank of the Loire river near the Bay of Biscay.

nodes.title: Pouillé
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G1 Pouillé

nodes.title: *Ratiatum
nodes.description: A site in the Loire estuary that served as a port.

nodes.title: Ruteni
nodes.description: A Gallic tribe whose territory corresponds roughly to the modern region of Aveyron.

nodes.title: Sanxay
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 E2 Sanxay

nodes.title: Segodunum
nodes.description: Segodunum was a Gallic oppidum and later a Gallo-Roman town.

nodes.title: Siata? (island)
nodes.description: Siata? Ins. (modern Houat)

nodes.title: Stadium of Antoninus Pius (Puteoli)
nodes.description: A stadium of ancient Puteoli constructed under Antoninus Pius in the second century A.D. that was revealed by excavation in 2008.

nodes.title: Megaron A at Thermon
nodes.description: Megaron A is an apsidal megaron built sometime between 1400 BC and 1100 BC in the area of the later Sanctuary of Apollo at Thermon.

nodes.title: Stoa of Attalos
nodes.description: The Stoa of Attalos, located on the eastern side of the ancient Athenian agora, is a long, rectangular, two-story building of limestone and marble, with an external and internal colonnade. It was originally constructed around 150 BCE and then reconstructed in the 1950s.

nodes.title: Roman temple of Córdoba
nodes.description: A pseudodipteral, hexastyle, Corinthian order temple begun under Claudius and completed under Domitian. The temple is likely sacred to the imperial cult.

nodes.title: Porta Rosa
nodes.description: An arched gateway built using the Lesbian polygonal masonry technique at Velia.

nodes.title: Aspronisi
nodes.description: A volcanic island that formed on the southwestern edge of the Santorini archipelago following a major volcanic eruption that occurred ca. 1625 BC.

nodes.title: Akripos
nodes.description: An ancient settlement whose precise location can not be determined today

nodes.title: Via Postumia
nodes.description: A Roman road (via publica) of northern Italy begun in 148 B.C. by Spurius Postumius Albinus Magnus.

nodes.title: Uraš Gate
nodes.description: The Uraš Gate is one of Babylon's eight city gates and it is situated on the southeastern side of the inner city, directly south of the Šuanna quarter. King Nebuchadnezzar II built the gate ca. 575 B.C.

nodes.title: Pyramid of Khentkawes
nodes.description: Khentkawes I was a queen of the 4th dynasty of ancient Egypt. She may have been a daughter of the pharaoh Menkaure, and the wife of both kings Shepseskaf and Userkaf. Her tomb at Giza – LG100 – is located close to Menkaure's pyramid complex.

nodes.title: Šamaš Gate
nodes.description: The Šamaš Gate is one of Babylon's eight city gates and it is situated on the southwestern side of the inner city, directly south of the Tuba quarter. King Nebuchadnezzar II built the gate ca. 575 B.C.

nodes.title: Eanšar
nodes.description: The shrine in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eanšar means "House of All Heaven."

nodes.title: Eadgigi
nodes.description: The shrine/seat of the god Nusku in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eadgigi means "House of the Counsellor."

nodes.title: Eganunmah
nodes.description: The treasury of the god Nanna/Suen/Sîn in the Ekišnugal temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eganunmah means "House, Exalted Storehouse."

nodes.title: Etenten
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Ba-KUR at Ša-Iṣṣur-Adad.

nodes.title: Ekurnizu
nodes.description: The sanctuary of the goddess Ninlil at Ḫursagkalama (Tell Ingharra). The Sumerian ceremonial name Ekurnizu means "House, Fearsome Mountain."

nodes.title: E-ibbi-Anum
nodes.description: The temple of the god Uraš at Dilbat. The Akkadian ceremonial name E-ibbi-Anum means "House, Anu Called It into Being."

nodes.title: Edimgalkalama
nodes.description: The temple of the god Ištarān/Anu-rabû at Der. The Sumerian ceremonial name Edimgalkalama means "House, Great Bond of the Land."

nodes.title: Sūrānu
nodes.description: A town probably not far from Uruk.

nodes.title: Amnanum
nodes.description: Name of an Amorite tribe who settled near Sippar-Amnanu (Tell ed-Der) and also near Tuttul (Tell Bi'a) during the Old Babylonian Period.

nodes.title: Suteans
nodes.description: A West Semitic semi-nomadic group attested principally in Babylonia during the first millennium B. C. The Sutû are also attested in cuneiform sources of the second millennium B.C., including several of the Amarna Letters, and these earlier texts provide evidence for the Suteans living in the Levant and Syria, west of the Euphrates River.

nodes.title: Nēmed-Enlil
nodes.description: The outer wall of Babylon was called by the ceremonial Akkadian name Nēmed-Enlil/ Nēmetti-Enlil, which means "Bulwark of the God Enlil." According to the text Tintir = Babylon, Nēmed-Enlil (and the inner wall Imgur-Enlil) had eight city gates, four on the eastern side of the Euphrates and four on the western side of the river. The Assyrian kings Esarhaddon and Ashurbanipal and the Babylonian kings Nabopolassar, Nebuchadnezzar II, and Nebonidus all undertook construction on Babylon’s outer wall.

nodes.title: Imgur-Marduk
nodes.description: The city wall of Nippur according to the so-called "Kuyunjik Ziqqurrat List" (7th century B.C.). Its Akkadian ceremonial name means "The God Marduk Showed Favor."

nodes.title: Nuraghe Lugherras
nodes.description: A nuragic site of the Middle Bronze Age near Oristano, Sardinia.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Ruju
nodes.description: A hilltop nuragic complex with a central tholos tower dating to the Middle and Final Bronze Age (1600-1000 BC).

nodes.title: Bulls of Guisando
nodes.description: A series of Celtiberian sculptures located near El Tiemblo, Ávila, Spain. These statues were perhaps originally created during the second century BC.

nodes.title: Lion Gate at Mycenae
nodes.description: The Lion Gate is the main gate in the Cyclopean walls of the citadel of Mycenae. It takes its name from the sculptural decoration placed in the relieving triangle over the monolithic lintel, which depicts two animals (lions or griffins) in heraldic position on either side of a Minoan-style pillar.

nodes.title: Caimeni
nodes.description: Caimeni is a name ascribed to the geological predecessors of Palea and Nea Kameni. The two later islands were formed by volcanic activity between AD 1620 and 1850.

nodes.title: Ugal-amaru
nodes.description: According to an inscription of the Neo-Babylonian king Nabonidus, the name of the wall of Cutha was Ugal-amaru, whose ceremonial name means "Great Storm, (which is) a Deluge."

nodes.title: Imgur-Enlil
nodes.description: The great, inner wall of Babylon was called by the ceremonial Akkadian name Imgur-Enlil, which means "The God Enlil Showed Favor." According to the text Tintir = Babylon, Imgur-Enlil had eight city gates, four on the eastern side of the Euphrates and four on the western side of the river. The Assyrian kings Esarhaddon and Ashurbanipal and the Babylonian kings Nabopolassar, Nebuchadnezzar II, and Nebonidus all undertook construction on Babylon’s great wall. Imgur-Enlil is one of the seven wonders of the ancient according to some classical sources.

nodes.title: Sumer
nodes.description: Sumer (Akkadian Šumeru; Sumerian Kiengir) is the name of a historical region of southern Mesopotamia, now modern-day southern Iraq. It is home to one of the world’s earliest civilizations and one of the places where writing was first developed. Eridu, Girsu, Lagash, Shuruppak, Umma, Ur, and Uruk are among its most well-known urban centers.

nodes.title: Nuraghe di Sant'Itroxia
nodes.description: A Middle Bronze age nuragic site with evidence of a giant's tomb and a nuragic tower.

nodes.title: Abariltur
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Abariltur

nodes.title: Areikoratikos/Arekorata
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Areikoratikos/Arekorata

nodes.title: Arsaos
nodes.description: A pre-Roman mint located in the territory of the Vascones that is known only by means of numismatic evidence.

nodes.title: Ausesken
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Ausesken

nodes.title: Barskunes/Baskunes
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Ba(r)skunes

nodes.title: Belikiom
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Belikiom (1)

nodes.title: Bentian
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Bentian

nodes.title: Bolskan
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Bolskan

nodes.title: Eustibaikula-Eusti
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Eustibaikula-Eusti

nodes.title: Iltirkesken
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Iltirkesken

nodes.title: Iltukoite
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Iltukoite

nodes.title: Kaiskata
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Kaiskata

nodes.title: Kueliokos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Kueliokos

nodes.title: Lakine
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Lakine

nodes.title: Olkairun
