nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Olkairun

nodes.title: Orosi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Orosi

nodes.title: Sekia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Sekia

nodes.title: Sesars
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Sesars

nodes.title: Seteisken
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Seteisken

nodes.title: Unanbaate
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 unlocated Unanbaate

nodes.title: Acinippo
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 E5 Acinippo

nodes.title: Ad Sorores
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 D2 Ad Sorores

nodes.title: Alcántara
nodes.description: The Roman temple of Alcántara is a well-preserved structure located at one side of the Alcántara Bridge in Extremadura (Spain). The building, dating to A.D. 103, is the work of Caius Iulius Lacer. The lintel inscription indicates the structure was dedicated to Trajan.

nodes.title: Ammaia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 C2 Ammaia

nodes.title: Anas (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 C3 Anas fl.

nodes.title: Anatolikon Stoma
nodes.description: Anatolikon Stoma, the mouth of Baetis/Certis fl.

nodes.title: Augustobriga
nodes.description: Augustobriga was an ancient city located on the left bank of the river Tagus, between Emerita Augusta and Toletum.

nodes.title: B(a)elo
nodes.description: B(a)elo is located on the northern shore of the Strait of Gibraltar. The town was founded by the late second century BC and achieved municipal status under Claudius.

nodes.title: Baetis Aestuaria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 D5 Baetis Aestuaria

nodes.title: Baetis/Certis (river)
nodes.description: The Guadalquivir river is the fifth longest of the Iberian peninsula.

nodes.title: Caepionis Monu.
nodes.description: Caepionis Monumentum (Tower of Caepio) was a tower-cum-lighthouse built by the Roman proconsul Quintus Servilius Caepio in 140 BC. The aim was to make the Salmedina reef at the mouth of the river Baitis (Guadalquivir) navigable. The modern toponym is Chipiona.

nodes.title: Caetobriga
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 B3 Caetobriga

nodes.title: Calpe (mountain)
nodes.description: The Rock of Gibraltar.

nodes.title: Via Cassia
nodes.description: An ancient Roman road branching off from the Via Flaminia and continuing to Luna where it joined the Via Aurelia. The Via Cassia post-dates the Via Amerina and was built after 240 B.C. It combined new construction with re-use of pre-existing roads and tracks.

nodes.title: Via Clodia
nodes.description: An ancient Roman road.

nodes.title: Arch of Gallienus
nodes.description: The Arch of Gallienus marked the Porta Esquilina, a gate in the Servian Wall of Rome. The via Labicana and via Tiburtina issue from Rome at this point. The arch was erected in A.D. 262.

nodes.title: Thermae Antoninianae
nodes.description: The Thermae Antoninianae, commonly known as the Baths of Caracalla, were built in Rome between AD 212 and 216.

nodes.title: Diqdiqah
nodes.description: Diqdiqah is a small satellite of the ancient city of Ur in the present-day Dhi Qar province of southern Iraq ca. 20 kilometres southwest of Nasiriyah. The site has yielded substantial archaeological remains dating to the late third and early second millennium BC, including the remains of a large structure called 'The Treasury of Sîn-iddinam'. Diqdiqah saw brief excavations by British archaeologists Leonard Woolley and Max Mallowan in 1924.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater of Saintes
nodes.description: The Gallo-Roman amphitheater of Mediolanum Santonum.

nodes.title: Capitolium
nodes.description: The so-called Capitolium of Aquinum is found in the northwest part of the site. It may pre-date Roman colonization and it perhaps sacred to Iuno Regina.

nodes.title: Forum of Saepinum
nodes.description: The Forum of Saepinum assumes a trapezoidal shape and is aligned with the decumanus.

nodes.title: Triumphal Arch of Glanum
nodes.description: A Roman triumphal arch built in the early first century A.D.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Suasa
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Suasa dates to the first century A.D.

nodes.title: Amarna
nodes.description: A new capital for Egypt founded by Akhenaten during his reign as pharaoh during Egypt's Eighteenth Dynasty.

nodes.title: Calavon (river)
nodes.description: Tributary of the Druentia fl. (Durance)

nodes.title: Torre Romana, Novaria
nodes.description: A surviving Roman defensive tower.

nodes.title: Basilica of Saint-Pierre-aux-Nonnains
nodes.description: A Christian basilica that incorporates the remains of a fourth century AD Roman gymnasium.

nodes.title: Kastri
nodes.description: The fortified settlement of Kastri near Chalandriani on the Cycladic island of Syros is an important Early Cycladic II site. This fortified hill-top settlement is a very early example of a site in the Aegean with a fortification wall reinforced by means of stone bastions.

nodes.title: Chalandriani
nodes.description: A major Early Bronze Age necropolis on Syros, Chalandriani contains tombs related to the Keros-Syros culture of the Early Cycladic II period.

nodes.title: Theater at Limyra
nodes.description: The Theater at Limyra dates ca. 190 B.C.

nodes.title: Temple of Cybele
nodes.description: This temple at Pessinus was built by the Attalids to honor Cybele.

nodes.title: Acropolis?
nodes.description: The possible location of the acropolis of Makra Kome, according to Stählin (1924, 224) and Béquignon (1937, 316).

nodes.title: Corinth Canal
nodes.description: The Corinth Canal cuts across the Isthmus of Corinth, connecting the Gulf of Corinth to the Saronic Gulf and the Aegean Sea. Several abortive attempts in antiquity were made at creating the canal, although its final (and functional) realization occurred in modernity.

nodes.title: Kato Phournos Tomb
nodes.description: The Kato Phournos Tomb is one of the nine tholos, or "beehive", tombs found around the acropolis of Mycenae. It is thought to have been constructed between 1460 and 1400 BC.

nodes.title: Library of Pergamum
nodes.description: The Library of Pergamum was constructed by the Attalid ruler Eumenes ll on the acropolis of the city of Pergamon between 197 and 159 BCE to house a vast collection of literary and philosophical works.

nodes.title: Temple of Aphrodite Euploia
nodes.description: The temple of Aphrodite Euploia is a tholos constructed in the fourth century BC in Knidos, a coastal city on the Datça Peninsula. It was built to house Praxiteles' famous nude statue of Aphrodite.

nodes.title: Roman cistern
nodes.description: A Roman cistern of the early second century A.D.

nodes.title: Anfiteatro minore
nodes.description: The so-called "Anfiteatro minore" is a small amphitheater at Puteoli dating to the early Imperial period.

nodes.title: Ekklesiasterion
nodes.description: The Ekklesiasterion of Morgantina is located in the center of the ancient city. While its form resembles that of the Greek theater, it is posited that it functioned as a public building akin to the Roman comitium. It likely dates to the later fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Lucus Feroniae
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Lucus Feroniae was financed by one M. Silius Epaphroditus, who in turn received the title patronus. The structure dates to the reign of Tiberius.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Lucera
nodes.description: An amphitheater dating to the time of Augustus.

nodes.title: San Crisogono
nodes.description: San Crisogono (sacred to San Crisogono) is one of the early parish churches (tituli) of Rome. Pope Silvester I (314–335) likely builds the first iteration in the fourth century AD; later reworkings occur in the twelfth and seventeenth centuries, respectively.

nodes.title: Lacus Orphei
nodes.description: A fountain on the Esquiline (Regio V) that was perhaps located just outside the porta Esquilina.

nodes.title: Māri
nodes.description: Mari (Tell Hariri) was an ancient Semitic city that flourished as a trade center and hegemonic state between 2900 BC until 1759 BC. The site was submitted as a tentative candidate for the UNESCO World Heritage list in 1999.

nodes.title: Pyramid of Unas
nodes.description: A pyramid at Saqqara built for Unas, the final ruler of Egypt's Fifth Dynasty.

nodes.title: Nahr al-Kalb monuments
nodes.description: Over twenty rock reliefs (with accompanying inscriptions) are carved into the limestone cliffs around the estuary of the Nahr al-Kalb river.

nodes.title: Acropolis of Athens
nodes.description: The acropolis of the ancient city of Athens in Greece.

nodes.title: Hephaisteion
nodes.description: The temple of Hephaistos located on the northwest side of the Agora of Athens dates to the middle of the fifth century B.C.

nodes.title: Giricano
nodes.description: Modern Giricano, site of the ancient Dunnu-ša-Uzībiis, is located in the Upper Tigris region of south-eastern Turkey, in the province of Diyarbakir, about 11 km southeast of modern Bismil, ca. 5 km northwest of Ziyaret Tepe, on the north bank of the Tigris River.

nodes.title: Tigurini
nodes.description: A sub-tribe of the Helvetii.

nodes.title: Palatinus Mons
nodes.description: The central hill of Rome, Italy. Legend held that Romulus founded the city of Rome on the Palatine.

nodes.title: Aventinus mons
nodes.description: One of the seven hills of Rome. Until the reign of the emperor Claudius, the hill lay outside the pomerium of the city.

nodes.title: Myrtonion
nodes.description: A fortress in Thrace, whose precise location is now unknown.

nodes.title: Villanovaforru, Nuraghe Genna Maria
nodes.description: A multi-period nuragic site that began as a single tower ca. the Middle Bronze Age (1500 BC).

nodes.title: Nuraghe Maiori
nodes.description: A single-tower nuraghe with a central corridor.

nodes.title: Pons Cestius
nodes.description: A Roman stone bridge on the Tiber river, spanning the river channel from the Tiber Island westward to the Transtiberim (Trastevere). The original bridge dates to the first century BC.

nodes.title: Temple of Hera II (Neptune)
nodes.description: A fifth century B.C. Doric temple, the so-called Temple of Hera II is also sometimes referred to as the Temple of Neptune.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Benevento
nodes.description: A Roman theater of the second century A.D. constructed during the reign of Hadrian.

nodes.title: Tomb of Aulus Hirtius
nodes.description: A tomb located in Rome's Campus Martius. Its remains are now submerged in the channelized waters of the Euripus canal beneath the Palazzo della Cancelleria.

nodes.title: Arch of Galerius
nodes.description: The extant remains of a triumphal arch, constructed from 298 to 299 CE and dedicated in 303 CE under the tetrarch Galerius. It commemorates the capture of Ctesiphon from the Sassanids and forms part of a monumental entrance to the palace of Galerius.

nodes.title: Latomos Monastery
nodes.description: A late fifth century AD church, later associated with a small monastery in Thessaloniki, Greece.

nodes.title: Church of Prophet Elijah
nodes.description: A fourteenth century AD church in Thessaloniki.

nodes.title: Roman villa at Artena
nodes.description: A Roman villa built atop the terraced platform of the so-called "Civita di Artena".

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Luca
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Luca dates to the second half of the first century.

nodes.title: Carmine Roman tomb
nodes.description: A Roman tomb of the later second century incorporated into the former Convento del Carmine in Catania, Sicily.

nodes.title: Ekklesiasterion at Akragas
nodes.description: Located in the Upper Agroa, the Ekklesiasterion at Akragas dates to the fourth and third centuries B.C.

nodes.title: El-Qitar
nodes.description: Bronze Age fortified site located on the Euphrates in Syria.

nodes.title: Copper and Gold Mine at Kantanos
nodes.description: Southeast of the ancient settlement of Kantanos on Crete (BAtlas 60 A2)

nodes.title: Tomba della Mula
nodes.description: A tomb near Sesto Fiorentino, that dates to the seventh century B.C.

nodes.title: Tomba della Montagnola
nodes.description: A tholos-type tomb dating to the seventh century B.C.

nodes.title: Bocca di Magra Roman villa
nodes.description: A villa maritima of the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Via Augusta
nodes.description: A Roman road stretching some 1,500 km from Cádiz to the Coll de Panissars.

nodes.title: Via Appia
nodes.description: An early Roman road (via publica) originating at Rome and terminating at Brundisium, the Via Appia was begun in the fourth century B.C. by the censor Appius Claudius Caecus. The Latin author Statius described the Via Appia as "queen of the long roads".

nodes.title: Mount Ararat
nodes.description: The Ararat massif in eastern Asia Minor measures ca. 40 km (25 mi) in diameter and has two peaks, Greater Ararat and Lesser Ararat.

nodes.title: Ehilikalamma
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Ašratu, Ehilikalamma (“House of the Luxuriance of the Land”), was located in the Ka-dingirra district (modern Sahn) of Babylon. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, this was one of four temples in that part of the city, which was located in the northern part of the eastern half of Babylon.

nodes.title: Šuanna
nodes.description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, Šuanna was one of the six city districts of the eastern half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained two temples. Šuanna is also a name of Babylon itself (starting in the twelfth century BC).

nodes.title: nu-x-ù
nodes.description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, nu-x-ù/nu-HAR-UD (name fragmentary and not reconstructable) was one of the four city districts of the western half of the inner city of Babylon.

nodes.title: Kumar
nodes.description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, Kumar was one of the four city districts of the western half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained seven temples.

nodes.title: Bāb-Lugalerra
nodes.description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, Bāb-Lugalerra was one of the four city districts of the western half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained three temples.

nodes.title: Via Labicana
nodes.description: An ancient Roman road connecting Rome and Labicum.

nodes.title: Regio I, Pompeii
nodes.description: The so-called Regio I, an archaeological subdivision located in the southeastern section of Pompeii, contains a mixture of residences and commercial structures.

nodes.title: Regio IV, Pompeii
nodes.description: The so-called Regio IV is a largely unexcavated archaeological subdivision located in the northeastern section of Pompeii.

nodes.title: Regio V, Pompeii
nodes.description: The so-called Regio V, a largely unexcavated archaeological subdivision located in the northern section of Pompeii, contains a mixture of commercial and domestic structures, including a gladiators' barracks.

nodes.title: Regio VI, Pompeii
nodes.description: The so-called Regio VI, an archaeological subdivision located in the northwestern section of Pompeii, contains shops and residential buildings, including the House of the Faun.

nodes.title: Regio IX, Pompeii
nodes.description: The so-called Regio IX, an archaeological subdivision located in the central section of Pompeii, contains a mix of residential and commercial structures.

nodes.title: Corvey
nodes.description: The abbey was first founded in 815 by Charlemagne's cousins, Wala and Adelard.

nodes.title: Old Winteringham
nodes.description: Site of extensive Roman occupation and possible Claudio-Neronian military base where Ermine Street crosses the river Humber, opposite the fort at Petuaria (Brough-on-Humber).

nodes.title: Combley Roman villa
nodes.description: Site of Romano-British villa of winged corridor type, probably late 3rd century CE in date.

nodes.title: Aphrodision at Akrai
nodes.description: Temple dedicated to Aphrodite constructed in the 6th century BCE at the Greek colony of Akrai.

nodes.title: House of the Centenary
nodes.description: A Pompeian domus re-discovered in 1879, the so-called House of the Centenary is among the largest domus in Pompeii.

nodes.title: Pani Loriga
nodes.description: A fortified Phoenico-Punic settlement on Sardinia with two necropoleis.

nodes.title: Staigue stone fort
nodes.description: An Iron Age ring fort, dating perhaps to the fourth century AD.

nodes.title: Ruinas de Tróia
nodes.description: The Tróia peninsula in Portugal is the site of a large facility for the production of Roman fish sauce (garum) and ruins of a large industrial area for the processing has been excacated there.

nodes.title: Theater at Butrint
nodes.description: A Greek and Roman theater at the site of Butrint.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Arretium
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Arretium was built during the late first and early second centuries. It measures 121 by 68 meters.

nodes.title: Roman forum of Luna
nodes.description: The forum of Luna, founded as a colony in 177 B.C.

nodes.title: Arch of Trajan
nodes.description: The Arch of Trajan at Maktar.

nodes.title: Sarmizegetusa Roman amphitheater
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Colonia Ulpia Traiana Augusta Dacica Sarmizegetusa was built in A.D. 108/110 and renovated in 158 under the legio IV Flavia Felix

nodes.title: Cyaneae Theater
nodes.description: The Cyaneae Theater dates to the Roman imperial period.

nodes.title: Bobadela Roman amphitheater
nodes.description: The Bobadela Roman amphitheater dates to the second century.

nodes.title: Porta Tiburtina
nodes.description: The Porta Tiburtina is a gate in the Aurelianic Walls through which the Via Tiburtina passes. It is also known today as the Porta San Larenzo.

nodes.title: Iuktas
nodes.description: A Minoan peak sanctuary on Juktas that served the Minoan palace of Knossos. The site was first excavated in 1909 by Sir Arthur Evans. The site was in use from Early to Late Bronze Age.

nodes.title: Tall-e Bakun B
nodes.description: The second of the two mounds comprising the Tall-e Bakun site.

nodes.title: Catacombe San Marcellino e Pietro
nodes.description: The Catacombs of Marcellinus and Peter lies some 3 km southeast of Rome along the ancient Via Labicana. They date to the fourth century A.D.

nodes.title: Tagliata Etrusca
nodes.description: A rock-cut canal located at the port of ancient Cosa.

nodes.title: Tall-e Bakun A
nodes.description: The larger of the two mounds that make up the Tall-e Bakun site.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Apollo
nodes.description: The Sanctuary of Apollo near Amyklai is a stoa-like building that enclosed a colossal statue of Apollo on three sides and was decorated with reliefs. The tomb of Hyacinthus is used as a statue base, combining the two local deities together.

nodes.title: La Loggia
nodes.description: "La Loggia" refers to a squared tower that is a part of the polygonal masonry curtain wall of Norba.

nodes.title: House of Julia Felix
nodes.description: The so-called House of Iulia Felix (II, 4, 3) is situated on the south side of the Via dell'Abbondanza, near the Palaestra and the Amphitheater. The estate was formed from two complete insulae that were merged. About one-third of the area was occupied by the house, the remainder by a large garden. Following the AD 62 earthquake the proprietress seems to have leased out portions of the property.

nodes.title: Humē
nodes.description: A country mentioned in Neo- and Late-Babylonian texts that roughly corresponds to Que (kingdom and province) and Cilicia Pedias ("Flat Cilicia").

nodes.title: Ištar Gate
nodes.description: The Ištar Gate is the most famous of Babylon's eight city gates and is situated on the northeastern side of the inner city, directly north of the Kadingirra quarter. King Nebuchadnezzar II built the gate ca. 575 B.C.

nodes.title: Sphinx Temple
nodes.description: The Old Kingdom temple associated with the Great Sphinx of Giza and assigned to the reign of Khafre.

nodes.title: The Giza Necropolis
nodes.description: This complex of ancient monuments includes the three pyramid complexes known as the Great Pyramids, the massive sculpture known as the Great Sphinx, several cemeteries, a workers' village and an industrial complex.

nodes.title: Ehiliana
nodes.description: The shrine/cella of the goddess Nanāya in the Eanna temple at Uruk. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ehiliana means "House of the Luxuriance of Heaven."

nodes.title: Ešaduga
nodes.description: The shrine/seat of the god Nanna in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ešaduga means "House which Pleases the Heart."

nodes.title: E(...)gakuga
nodes.description: The shrine/seat of the god Ennugi in the Egipar temple at Ur. The name is damaged and the complete Sumerian ceremonial name of the structure is not known.

nodes.title: Eešerke
nodes.description: The sanctuary of the god Marduk at Sippar-Arūru. The name may be a variant or corruption of the Sumerian ceremonial name Ešeriga ("House which Gleans Barley"); alternatively, it may be part of that temple.

nodes.title: Bāṣ
nodes.description: The unlocated Babylonian city is mentioned in cuneiform documents of the second and first millennia B.C. Information provided the texts seem to indicate that Baṣ, whose name might derive from the Akkadian word for sand, might be located somewhere near Sippar, perhaps close to the Euphrates River.

nodes.title: Zabbān
nodes.description: A city on the Diyālā River, possibly between Kifrī and Qāra.

nodes.title: Kassites
nodes.description: Tribal people living in southwestern Asia, attested principally in Babylonia and western Iran during the second and first millennia B. C. The original homeland of the Kassites has yet to be identified, but it may have been located in the Zagros Mountains.

nodes.title: Withdrawn (duplicate): Creta et Cyrene
nodes.description: A duplicate entry for the Roman Province of Creta et Cyrene (https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/981517).

nodes.title: Nēmed-Marduk
nodes.description: The outer city wall of Nippur according to the so-called "Kuyunjik Ziqqurrat List" (7th century B.C.). Its Akkadian ceremonial name means "Bulwark of the God Marduk".

nodes.title: Monte Bibele
nodes.description: A massif of the middle Bolognese Apennines rising 617 meters above sea level,

nodes.title: Arch of Hadrian at Athens
nodes.description: The Arch of Hadrian is a monument in the form of a Roman triumphal arch, constructed by the citizens of Athens in AD 131 or 132 to honor the Roman emperor Hadrian.

nodes.title: Hiera Oikia at Eleusis
nodes.description: The so-called "Hiera Oikia" is a multi-room structure dating to the 7th century BC in the sanctuary of Demeter of Kore at Eleusis.

nodes.title: Temple of Athena Pronaia
nodes.description: The Temple of Athena Pronaia, located at Delphi, is a peripteral Doric building (6 x 12 columns). It was built ca. 500 BC and is the largest building in the sanctuary of Athena Pronaia.

nodes.title: Southwest Palace at Kalhu
nodes.description: The seventh-century-BC Assyrian king Esarhaddon (r. 680–669 BC) started building a royal residence in the southwest corner of the citadel of Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud). Sculpted and inscribed limestone slabs from the Central Palace (constructed by Tiglath-pileser III [r. 744–727 BC]) and the Northwest Palace (built by Ashurnasirpal II [r. 883–859 BC]) were used as building materials for this royal residence, which very likely remained unfinished at the time of Esarhaddon’s death in 669 BC. Its excavators called it the “Southwest Palace” since it was located in the southwest corner of the citadel.

nodes.title: Central Palace at Kalhu
nodes.description: The eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Tiglath-pileser III (r. 744–727 BC) built himself a grand, ornately-decorated royal residence at Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud). This (large) palatial complex, which included a pillared-portico (a bīt-ḫilāni), was constructed south of the Northwest Palace (built by Ashurnasirpal II [r. 883–859 BC]). The “Cedar Palace” (as it is referred to in at least one contemporary Akkadian inscription) was largely dismantled by the seventh-century-BC ruler Esarhaddon (r. 680–669 BC), who had its (sculpted and inscribed) limestone slabs reused in his own royal residence (the Southwest Palace). The building is now generally referred to as the “Central Palace,” a modern designation given to it by its excavators since the palace was constructed in the central part of the Kalhu citadel.

nodes.title: Enlil temple (Kalhu)
nodes.description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the god Enlil. Although its location is not known, the Enlil temple at Kalhu is thought to have been situated within the Ninurta temple complex, in the northwest corner of the citadel.

nodes.title: Adad-Šala temple (Kalhu)
nodes.description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the god Adad and the goddess Šala. Although its location is not known, the Adad-Šala temple at Kalhu is thought to have been situated within the Ninurta temple complex, in the northwest corner of the citadel.

nodes.title: Sîn temple (Kalhu)
nodes.description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the moon-god Sîn. Although its location is not known, the Sîn temple at Kalhu is thought to have been situated within the Ninurta temple complex, in the northwest corner of the citadel.

nodes.title: Guadaíra (river)
nodes.description: A tributary of the Guadalquivir river that rises in Pozo Amargo in the province of Cadiz.

nodes.title: Amnisos
nodes.description: A Bronze Age site on the north shore of Crete that may have served as a port for Knossos.

nodes.title: S'Arcu 'e is Forros
nodes.description: A significant nuragic complex with major occupational phases during the middle Bronze Age and during the Bronze- to Iron Age transition. A 17 meter long megaron with its temenos is a main feature of the site.

nodes.title: Succoronis
nodes.description: A single-tower nuraghe located near Macomer, Sardinia.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Colombos
nodes.description: Unknown

nodes.title: Tamuli
nodes.description: A Middle Bronze Age nuragic complex near Macomer, Sardinia.

nodes.title: Tiran Island
nodes.description: Tiran (Arabic: جزيرة تيران‎ Jazīrat Tīrān) is an island located in the Straits of Tiran, which separate the Red Sea from the Gulf of Aqaba.

nodes.title: Sanafir Island
nodes.description: An island in the Red Sea to the east of Tiran island.

nodes.title: Sanctuaries of Apollo Deiradiotes and Athena Oxyderkes
nodes.description: At Argos, Pausanias mentions both the sanctuary of Apollo Deiradiotes (Apollo of the ridge) and the sanctuary of Athena Oxyderkes (Athena the clear-sighted).

nodes.title: Tell Um Hammad al-Gharbi
nodes.description: Archaeological site on the banks of the Zerqa River with signs of habitation in the Early Bronze Age I-II and IV. The eastern portion of the larger Tell Um Hammad site is called Um Hammad Sharqiya; the western section is Um Hammad al-Gharbi. The two may have been linked as a single village in the Early Bronze Age IV.

nodes.title: Cuppae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 D5 Cuppae

nodes.title: Cusum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 B4 Cusum

nodes.title: Dierna
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 E5 Dierna

nodes.title: Drobeta
nodes.description: Drobeta is a Dacian settlement that was conquered by the Romans in A.D. 101-2. Trajan's engineer Apollodorus of Damascus built a bridge here that spanned the Danube in 103-5. This bridge, supported by 20 stone pilings and extending 1,135 m connected Drobeta to Pontes (on the right bank of the river).

nodes.title: Horreum Margi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 D6 Horreum Margi

nodes.title: Ložnica
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 B5 Ložnica

nodes.title: Margus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 D5 Margus fl.

nodes.title: Mediana
nodes.description: An extensive late-Roman villa used as a temporary imperial residence in the suburbs of ancient Naissus. Located in the modern village of Brzi brod, within the municipality of Niš, Serbia (BAtlas 21 E6 Mediana).

nodes.title: Naissus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 D6 Naissus

nodes.title: Neresnica
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 D5 Neresnica

nodes.title: Pontes
nodes.description: One of two castra defending the Trajanic bridge across the Danube.

nodes.title: Rakinac
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 D5 Rakinac

nodes.title: Savus (river)
nodes.description: A river of Central Europe and a right tributary of the Danube.

nodes.title: Singidunum
nodes.description: An ancient settlement and Roman fort on the site of modern Belgrade in Serbia.

nodes.title: Tabula Traiana
nodes.description: The Tabula Traiana is a monumental inscription in what is now Serbia commemorating the completion of a Trajanic road along the Danube. The inscription was moved from its original spot to its present location in 1972.

nodes.title: Taurunum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 C5 Taurunum

nodes.title: Trška crkva
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 D5 Trška crkva

nodes.title: Ulpia Traiana Sarmizegetusa
nodes.description: The Roman capital of Dacia established by Trajan and located some 40 km from the indigenous center of Sarmizegetusa Regia (cited: BAtlas 21 E4 Ulpia Traiana Sarmizegetusa)

nodes.title: Viminacium
nodes.description: An ancient city and Roman legionary base along the Danube, near modern Kostolac (Костолац, Caştelu) in Serbia.

nodes.title: "Trajan's Bridge" at Drobeta-Turnu Severin
nodes.description: A Trajanic bridge spanning the Danuba at Drobeta-Turnu Severin.

nodes.title: Argentariae Dalmaticae et Pannonicae
nodes.description: A Dalmatian and Pannonian silver and lead mining region located in the eastern part of what is now Bosnia.

nodes.title: Aurariae Dacicae
nodes.description: A gold mining region in Dacia.

nodes.title: Metalli Ulpiani
nodes.description: The Metalli Ulpiani mining district

nodes.description: *Aureus Mons → Rakinac → Horreum Margi

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Singidunum → *Aureus Mons → Margum→ Viminacium

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Neresnica → Trška crkva

nodes.description: Sapaja → Dierna → Drobeta → Hinova → Basarabi

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Drobeta → Vulcan → Petroşeni → Sîntămăria-Orlea

nodes.title: Anchialus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 E6 Anchialus

nodes.title: Argamum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 F4 Argamum

nodes.title: Plazeira
nodes.description: A hunting base controlled by the Attalid kingdom, with some administrative connection to Apolloniacharax.

nodes.title: Lydia (Kingdom)
nodes.description: Lydia was an Iron Age kingdom of western Asia Minor located east of ancient Ionia.

nodes.title: Village of the Kardakoi
nodes.description: Originally settled by members of the Seleucid military near Telmessos, the town was eventually absorbed into the Attalid Kingdom. It's precise location is not known today.

nodes.title: Castello di Corradino
nodes.description: A mausoleum dating to the Roman Imperial period located at Centuripe in Sicily.

nodes.title: Penkalas Bridge
nodes.description: A second century AD Roman bridge across the Penkalas river ( Kocaçay) in Aezani, Asia Minor.

nodes.title: Grotta della Dragonara
nodes.description: A rock-cut Roman cistern.

nodes.title: Tombs of the Buccii and Melissaei
nodes.description: The Grave enclosure of the Buccii and the Melissaei located on the west side of Pompeii's Herculaneum Gate.

nodes.title: Odeon at Hadrian's Villa
nodes.description: The Odeon at Hadrian's Villa is also referred to as the South Theater. It is located at the southern end of the Villa Adriana.

nodes.title: Ishtar Temple at Mari
nodes.description: Temple dedicated to the goddess Ishtar located in the western section of the city of Mari.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Cubalciada
nodes.description: A Bronze Age nuraghe re-used and re-fortified during the Second World War.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Flumenelongu
nodes.description: Nuraghe Flumenelongu (Alghero-Sassari) is an important archaeological site for considerations of prehistoric maritime commerce in the Mediterranean.

nodes.title: Covili sa Serra su Sipiri nuraghe
nodes.description: Remains of a single tower nuraghe.

nodes.title: Stadium at Nemea
nodes.description: The ancient Greek stadium at the pan-hellenic sanctuary of Nemean Zeus.

nodes.title: House of the Ship Europa
nodes.description: The so-called "House of the Ship Europa" is a large house in the Roman city of Pompeii (I,15,3) that takes its conventional, archaeological name from a large graffito of ship bearing the legend 'Europa'.

nodes.title: Akkad Survey Area
nodes.description: The first archaeological survey of an area of north Babylonia associated with ancient Akkad. The survey was conducted in the 1950s by Robert Adams and Vaughn Crawford and published as an appendix to Gibson 1972. Its extent and methods were influential in the subsequent development of Mesopotamian archaeology.

nodes.title: Cleddans
nodes.description: A Roman fortlet on the Antonine Wall in Scotland.

nodes.title: Summerston
nodes.description: A Roman military installation of 2.4 ha associated with the Antonine Wall that was identified in 1980.

nodes.title: Chassenon Roman baths
nodes.description: The thermal baths of Chassenon are among the best preserved in the Gallo-Roman world. They are part of the ancient city of Cassinomagus.

nodes.title: Ager Veientanus
nodes.description: The territory of the Etruscan, and later Roman, city of Veii in South Etruria.

nodes.title: Molino San Vincenzo
nodes.description: Field survey, geophysical prospection, as well as targeted research and training excavations, have revealed the remains of a mid- to late imperial rural settlement with evidence for agricultural activity. However, the earliest finds (e.g. bucchero) date to the sixth/fifth century B.C., indicating the likelihood of Etruscan settlement activities at this site. The entire site seems to have undergone severe recycling and reuse processes in late antiquity and the remaining structures have broken down systematically in modern times. Ongoing intensive agricultural activities affect the few archaeological structures that remain, resulting in a poor state of preservation.

nodes.title: Ager Venusinus
nodes.description: The Ager Venusinus is the territory of ancient Venosa, located in the Basilicata region of Italy.

nodes.title: Ribaniš
nodes.description: An unlocated city/town in the kingdom of Suhu, probably not far from Alu-eššu, Baqa, and Qaqqar-aradātu.

nodes.title: Ukalāya
nodes.description: An unlocated city in the kingdom of Suhu.

nodes.title: Azlāyyānu
nodes.description: An unlocated town in the kingdom of Suhu that is reported to have been near the Euphrates River, on the bank opposite Kār-Apladad (Gleieh).

nodes.title: Rahi-ilu
nodes.description: An unlocated city/town in the kingdom of Suhu that was situated on an island in the Euphrates River.

nodes.title: Bir Massouda
nodes.description: An archaeological site in Carthage showing signs of continuous habitation from ca. 760 BCE-700 CE.

nodes.title: Pyramid of Djoser
nodes.description: The pyramid of the Third Dynasty pharaoh Djoser was built at Saqqara by architect Imhotep ca. 2267-2648 B.C.

nodes.title: Luristan
nodes.description: Lorestan Province (also written Luristan, Lurestan, or Loristan), is a province of western Iran in the Zagros Mountains.

nodes.title: Kunulua/Tell Tayinat
nodes.description: Tell Tayinat (ancient Kunulua) is a large site (comprising both a sizeable citadel and a sprawling lower town) located at the northern bend of the Orontes River, ca. 30 km southeast of Antakya (ancient Antioch). Strategically located, this fortified city served as a royal capital for various historically-attested Bronze and Iron Age kingdoms (ca. 3200-600 B.C.). In 738 B.C., the Assyrian king Tiglath-pileser III conquered Kunulua (alternately called Kinalua), then the royal city of Syro-Hittite kingdom of Patina, annexed it, and transformed it into an important provincial administrative center. Textual evidence found at the site (e.g., a large tablet inscribed with a copy of Esarhaddon’s Succession Treaty) leaves little doubt that Kunulua should be identified as Tell Tayinat.

nodes.title: Zawiyah
nodes.description: Zāwiyah (also Zawiyeh) is a site in the middle Euphrates region in what was part of the ancient kingdom of Suhu. The city was situated on the north bank of the Euphrates, a few kilometers west of Sur Jureh and Gleieh. Like many towns and cities of the ancient kingdom of Suhu, Zāwiyah is now underwater; the area was flooded after the construction of the Haditha dam. The city's ancient name is not known.

nodes.title: Lydia (Byzantine province)
nodes.description: The Byzantine province of Lydia, succeeding a late Roman province of the same name.

nodes.title: Thileudos
nodes.description: A hunting base controlled by the Attalid kingdom, with some administrative connection to Apolloniacharax.

nodes.title: Walbrook (stream)
nodes.description: Historical water course that ran through the heart of Roman London and flowed into the modern River Thames. Completely built over since the 19th century, it exists only as a subterranean stream and part of the London sewer system.

nodes.title: House of Lucius Cornelius Diadumenus
nodes.description: The House of Lucius Cornelius Diadumenus (VII, 12, 26) is a small domus noted for its wall paintings.

nodes.title: Santa Maria della Libera
nodes.description: An eleventh century church near Aquinum built largely from spolia.

nodes.title: Santa Sabina
nodes.description: A Christian basilica on the Aventine hill in Rome founded in the fourth century AD. The church takes its name from a Christian martyr who was said to have lived on the Aventine. The church is the oldest extant Roman basilica structure that preserves its original plan in the city of Rome.

nodes.title: Alpes Maritimae (late Roman province)
nodes.description: The post-Diocletianic province of Alpes Maritimae according to the Verona List (ca. AD 303-324). It was assigned to the diocese of Viennensis.

nodes.title: Feride Gül Tarla (FGT) excavation sector
nodes.description: The Feride Gül Tarla (FGT) excavation sector at Klazomenai.

nodes.title: Greek Theater
nodes.description: Remains of a mud-brick theater with building inscription in Greek were excavated at Babylon. The structure was substantively rebuilt in modern times.

nodes.title: Medinet Habu
nodes.description: The New Kingdom mortuary temple of Ramesses III at Medinet Habu, on the West bank of the Nile near Luxor.

nodes.title: Harappa
nodes.description: A Bronze Age fortified city located on the Ravi River, inhabited from the fourth through the second millennia BCE, Harappa was one of the most important settlements of the Indus Valley Civilization.

nodes.title: Dawali
nodes.description: Dawali is a site in the middle Euphrates region and was part of the kingdom of Suhu. The city was situated on the east bank of the Euphrates, a few kilometres downstream of Anat (Anatho). The modern city of the same name (Ad Dawālī) is on the west bank of the river. The city's ancient name is not known.

nodes.title: Judeideh
nodes.description: Judeideh (also Jedīdē, Judaide) is a site in the middle Euphrates region in what was part of the ancient kingdom of Suhu. The city was situated on the east bank of the Euphrates, about ten kilometers downstream of Anat (Anatho). Like many towns and cities of the ancient kingdom of Suhu, Judeideh is now underwater; the area was flooded after the construction of the Haditha dam. Its ancient name is not known.

nodes.title: Monte Catria
nodes.description: A mountain of the central Apennine range; the highest peak rises to 1,702 metres (5,584 ft) above sea level.

nodes.title: Kaneš
nodes.description: Kaneš or Kanesh (Hittite: Neša) is located adjacent to modern Kültepe, thus at times the site is referred to as Kültepe Kaneš. The site was one of continuous occupation from the Chalcolithic period to the time of the Roman empire, although its cultural zenith was as a major Hittite site that was the site of a large merchant quarter (kârum) of the Old Assyrian kingdom (ca. twentieth to sixteenth centuries BC).

nodes.title: Seashore Gate
nodes.description: The Neo-Babylonian kings Nabopolassar (r. 625–605 BC) and Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC) constructed an outer wall around the eastern side of Babylon. That mudbrick wall is reported to have had 120 towers and 5 entrances, including the Seashore Gate. This access point to the city was probably located on the southern stretch of the wall.

nodes.title: Tower 1 (Dura-Europos)
nodes.description: A rectangular defensive tower located on the northern end of the defensive circuit walls around the city of Dura-Europos. The fortifications were built ca. 150 BCE. They were breached in 256 CE and went out of use thereafter.

nodes.title: Esabad
nodes.description: The temple of the goddess Gula, Esabad (“House of the Open Ear”), was located in the Tuba district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of three temples in that part of Babylon. Esabad was rebuilt by the Assyrian king Ashurbanipal (r. 668–ca. 631 BC) and Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–652 BC). The temple survived into Arsacid times (247 BC–AD 224).

nodes.title: Enunmah
nodes.description: The temple of the god Nusku, Enunmah (“House of the Exalted Prince”), was located in the Bāb-Lugalerra district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of three temples in that part of Babylon.

nodes.title: Temple de Diane
nodes.description: The so-called "Temple de Diane" is a first century Roman monument on the Gard river dedicated to Augustus.

nodes.title: Tour Magne
nodes.description: Situated atop Mount Cavalier, the so-called "Tour Magne" is a tower on the fortified walls of ancient Nemausus. The tower dates to the time of Augustus.

nodes.title: Stanegate
nodes.description: An important Roman military road built in what is now northern England, linking Corbridge in the east and Carlisle in the west. A later western addition may have linked the fort at Kirkbride.

nodes.title: Temple of Concordia, Agrigento
nodes.description: The Temple of Concord, located in the so-called "Valle dei Templi" of Agrigento, dates ca. 440-430 B.C.

nodes.title: Radicofani
nodes.description: Radicofani, located ca. 60 km southeast of Siena, is the site of the tenth century AD castle of the Carolingian Ghino di Tacco.

nodes.title: Lake Bafa
nodes.description: Lake Bafa (Bafa Gölü) in Ionia formed as a result of the silting of the Latmian Gulf.

nodes.title: Temple of Hercules at Amman/Philadelpheia
nodes.description: The Temple of Hercules is located within the Amman Citadel in Amman, Jordan. The temple was built during the administration of Geminius Marcianus, ca. 162-166.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Nuceria (Alfaterna)
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Nuceria (Alfaterna) likely dates to the Augustan period.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Caralis
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Cagliari dates to the first and second centuries.

nodes.title: Sacellum of the Augustales
nodes.description: The so-called "Sacellum of the Augustales" at Misenum is an architectural complex located near the theater that was first built during the Iulio-Claudian period and dedicated to the Imperial cult. The complex was renovated during the second century, at which time one Cassia Victoria re-dedicated the shrine in honor of her husband, L. Laecanius Primitivus, who was a priest of the Augustales during the reign of Marcus Aurelius.

nodes.title: Roman forum at Tergeste
nodes.description: The Roman forum of Tergeste.

nodes.title: Roman amphitheater at Tolosa
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Purpan-Ancely dates ca. A.D. 40 and is the only significant Roman architecture to survive from ancient Tolosa.

nodes.title: Ġgantija
nodes.description: Megalithic temple on the island of Gozo; named a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1980

nodes.title: Arles Amphitheatre
nodes.description: The Arles Roman amphitheater or Arènes d'Arles was built ca. A.D. 90 and could seat over 20,000 spectators.

nodes.title: Domvs Romana
nodes.description: A ruined Roman townhouse located on the boundary between Mdina and Rabat, Malta that was discovered in 1881. It dates to the first century B.C.

nodes.title: House A VII 4
nodes.description: Olynthian "type house" for the orthogonally planned urban area on the North Hill

nodes.title: Nea Moni
nodes.description: An eleventh century monastery on Chios built by Constantine IX Monomachos. The site was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1990.

nodes.title: Tarnis (river)
nodes.description: The Tarn river.

nodes.title: Triobris (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 H4 Triobris fl.

nodes.title: Turoni
nodes.description: An ancient people who lived in western France just south of Caesarodunum, modern Tours.

nodes.title: Uliarios/*Olario (island)
nodes.description: The island of Oléron located in the Bay of Biscay.

nodes.title: Ussel
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 H3 Ussel

nodes.title: Uxellodunum
nodes.description: Uxellodunum was an oppidum on the Dordogne river in the territory of the Cardurci tribe.

nodes.title: Veneticae (islands)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 B1 Veneticae Inss.

nodes.title: Vesunna
nodes.description: Vesunna (Périgueux) was an oppidum of the Petrucorii that became part of Roman Aquitania.

nodes.title: Vi(n)genna? (river)
nodes.description: Vi(n)genna? fl. (Vienne river) is a major river of France and a tributary of the Liger fl. (Loire river).

nodes.title: Vindilis Ins.
nodes.description: Vindilis Ins. (modern Belle Île)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F1 unnamed aqueduct (E Caesarodunum)

nodes.title: Cornillé, Cm. Chambourg-sur-Indre
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F1 no. 18 (Cornillé, Cm. Chambourg-sur-Indre)

nodes.title: Ermine Street
nodes.description: The Ermine Street was a major Roman road of Britain, running from Londinium to Colonia Lindum and Eburacum.

nodes.title: Temple of Khnum at Esna
nodes.description: A temple dedicated to the god Khnum constructed during the Ptolemaic and Roman period in the city of Esna (Latopolis).

nodes.title: Shrine of Strenia
nodes.description: The Shrine of Strenia was located in the valley of the Colosseum and is mentioned as the starting point of the Sacra Via.

nodes.title: Arco Romano de Dona Isabel
nodes.description: The so-called "Arco Romano de Dona Isabel" is a second or third century A.D. city gate of Évora, the ancient site of Ebora Liberalitas Iulia.

nodes.title: Temple of Artemis Agrotera
nodes.description: A temple of Artemis on the Ilissos that marks the spot where the goddess first hunted after arriving from Delos. The archaeological remains of the site are found on the modern Ardettou Street in Athens.

nodes.title: Balochistan (region)
nodes.description: A desert and mountainous region located between the Plateau of Iran and the Indian subcontinent, comprising the modern regions of southeastern Iran (Sistan and Baluchestan province), western Pakistan (Balochistan province), and southern Afghanistan (Nimruz, Helmand and Kandahar provinces). The region's name is derived from the Baloch people, who have inhabited the region since at least the ninth century CE. In antiquity, the southern part of the region, along the coast of the Arabian Sea, was known as Maka in the Achaemenid period and Gedrosia in the Hellenistic period.

nodes.title: 'Ir David/Wadi Hilweh
nodes.description: The City of David is the name given in the 20th century to an archaeological site located in the Arab neighborhood of Wadi Hilweh, located south of the Temple Mount and the Ophel in East Jerusalem. The site contains pottery from as early as the Chalcolithic Age, and has been proposed as a possible original core of the city of Jerusalem. The Silwa necropolis, a burial site dated to the 9th-7th centuries BCE, is located within this area.

nodes.title: Via Caecilia
nodes.description: The Via Caecilia left the Via Salaria at the 35th mile and continued to the Adriatic coast.

nodes.title: Vigna Randanini
nodes.description: A Jewish catacomb along the Via Appia discovered in 1859.

nodes.title: Auditorium Maecenatis
nodes.description: An early Imperial building on the Esquiline Hill in Rome, the Auditorium Maecenatis has been connected with Maecenas as it stands in the area of his gardens (horti). While its precise function is unknown, the building may have served as a conservatory.

nodes.title: Porte des Gaules
nodes.description: The point of entry of the Via Aurelia.

nodes.title: Villa romana delle Grotte
nodes.description: A villa dating to the final quarter of the first century BC located on a headland overlooking Portoferraio on the island of Elba.

nodes.title: Thermae Agrippae
nodes.description: The Thermae Agrippae, built by M. Vipsanius Agrippa in the Campus Martius, were the earliest of Rome's great public baths.

nodes.title: tribus Galeria
nodes.description: The tribus Galeria was one of the older rural tribes of ancient Rome

nodes.title: Forum Boarium (at Pompeii)
nodes.description: The so-called "Forum Boarium" in Pompeii was erroneously named by its 1755 excavators who discovered the bones of large bovids and assigned the name that still is used to describe this insula in Pompeii's Regio II (II, 5).

nodes.title: House and caupona of Epagatus
nodes.description: Roman villa and caupona in Pompeii.

nodes.title: Temple of Apollo
nodes.description: The Temple of Apollo (VII,7,32) in Pompeii is one of the city's oldest cults, dating to the sixth century BC. The sanctuary assumed its present appearance in the second century BC.

nodes.title: Porta Ostiensis
nodes.description: The Porta Ostiensis, now known as the Porta San Paolo, is a gate in Rome's Aurelian Wall from which the Via Ostiensis issues.

nodes.title: Apollo, Aedes
nodes.description: The likely site of the original sanctuary to Apollo at Rome. The visible remains belong to the Augustan phase.

nodes.title: San Teodoro al Palatino
nodes.description: A church on the Palatine Hill in Rome sacred to Saint Theodore of Amasea dating originally to the sixth century AD.

nodes.title: Arcus Dolabellae et Silani
nodes.description: Situated on the Caelian Hill, the Arcus Dolabellae et Silani sits at the northern corner of the Castra Peregrina.

nodes.title: Sant'Agata di Militello
nodes.description: A modern town in Sicily that has been associated with the location of the ancient settlement of Agathyrnum.

nodes.title: Limen to Kaisareiou
nodes.description: A harbor constructed in Constantinople during the reign of Theodosius I; 37 Byzantine-era shipwrecks have been excavated from the harbor site.

nodes.title: Cilbian Plain
nodes.description: A plain that abuts the plain of the Cayster river. Strabo remarks that it is fertile.

nodes.title: Roman Baths (Bath)
nodes.description: Bathhouse complex in Aquae Sulis, modern-day Bath. This well-preserved site is now a museum and the bathing complex itself is below modern street-level.

nodes.title: Crystal Palace Pub, Bath
nodes.description: Remains of sequence of Romano-British deposits found in the cellar of a pub in modern-day Bath.

nodes.title: Yaylakale (mountain)
nodes.description: Mountain peak in modern Turkey

nodes.title: House of the Moralist
nodes.description: The so-called House of the Moralist, also known as the House of M. Epidius Hymenaeus, is located on the Via dell'Abbondanza. The house was formed from two connecting properties that belonged to two related wine-merchants, T. Arrius Polites and M. Epidius Hymenaeus ( III, 4, 2-3).

nodes.title: Castronuovo di Sicilia
nodes.description: A modern location in Sicily that has been associated with the location of the ancient settlement of Krastos.

nodes.title: Unnamed villa
nodes.description: An unnamed villa of Tripolitana

nodes.title: Roman baths of Acinipo
nodes.description: The Roman baths of Acinipo date to the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Luxeuil Abbey
nodes.description: Located in France's Burgundy region, the Luxeuil Abbey was founded ca. 585–590 by the Irish missionary Saint Columbanus.

nodes.title: Dhaskalio (settlement)
nodes.description: An Early Cycladic settlement identified on the island of Daskalio in the Cyclades. This settlement is the most substantial yet known for the Early Bronze Age in the Cyclades.

nodes.title: Tomb (heroon) of King Perikles of Lycia
nodes.description: The monumental tomb of Perikles was erected in Limyra. The tomb takes the form of an Ionic Greek temple.

nodes.title: Graeco-Roman theater at Oinoanda
nodes.description: The theater at Oinoanda is believed to date from the second century B.C. It sits on the northern fringe of the city.

nodes.title: Kastos (island)
nodes.description: An Ionian island.

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 C4 unnamed bridge (over Sapis fl., near Caesena)

nodes.title: Centuriation near Vicetia
nodes.description: Roman centuriation to the northwest of Vicetia (modern Vicenza in Italy)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 A2 unnamed centuriation (N Castello del Tartaro (Verona))

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 A3 unnamed centuriation (near Forum Gallorum (Mutina))

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 C4 unnamed centuriation (Forum Popilii)

nodes.title: Centuriation at Opitergium
nodes.description: Roman centuriation in the area of Opitergium (modern Oderzo in Italy)

nodes.title: Antibacchias
nodes.description: Now unlocated, Antibacchias was an island in the Red Sea.

nodes.title: Apuani
nodes.description: The Apuani were a Ligurian tribe of northwest Italy.

nodes.title: Argentarius M.
nodes.description: A promontory stretching towards the Tyrrhenian Sea in correspondence of the two southernmost islands of the Tuscan Archipelago.

nodes.title: ‘Argoos Limen’
nodes.description: A port on the island of Ilva (modern Elba), so named based on the resting place of the Argonauts, according to Strabo.

nodes.title: Arnus (river)
nodes.description: The Arno river flows from its origin at Mount Falterona to the Marina di Pisa where it empties into the Tyrrhenian Sea.

nodes.title: Artemisia/Dianium (island)
nodes.description: A small island of the Tuscan Archipelago.

nodes.title: Auser (river)
nodes.description: The Serchio river.

nodes.title: Caecina (river)
nodes.description: The Cecina river flows through Etruria and empties into the Tyrrhenian Sea near Vada Volaterrana. The river course passed through the ancient territory of the Etruscan city of Volterra.

nodes.title: Cala Maestra
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 E5 Cala Maestra

nodes.title: Caprasia (island)
nodes.description: The north-westernmost of the seven islands of the Tuscan Archipelago.

nodes.title: Domitiana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 E5 Domitiana

nodes.title: Falesia
nodes.description: A Tyrrhenian coastal port opposite Elba, some 12 miles south of Populonia.

nodes.title: Fossae Papirianae
nodes.description: Fossae Papirianae refers to a navigable coastal canal and road station location along the Via Aemilia Scauri between Luna and Pisae.

nodes.title: Fufluna/Populonium
nodes.description: Populonia likely derives its name from the Etruscan god 'Fufluns' and was an important maritime and commercial center of Etruria located in the Colline Metallifere.

nodes.title: Igilium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 D5 Igilium

nodes.title: Igilium (island)
nodes.description: An island in the Tyrrhenian Sea with Etruscan and Roman occupation.

nodes.title: Ilva/Aethalia (island)
nodes.description: The largest island of the Tuscan Archipelago, Ilva (modern Elba) is located in the Tyrrhenian Sea 50 km east of Corsica. It is the third largest Italian island.

nodes.title: Incitaria?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 E5 Incitaria?

nodes.title: Isola del Tinetto
nodes.description: An island in the Ligurian Sea.

nodes.title: Luca
nodes.description: Luca (the modern Lucca) was originally an Etruscan settlement that became a Roman colony ca. 180 B.C.

nodes.title: Luna
nodes.description: Luna (the modern Luni) is an ancient settlement of Liguria. It was re-founded by the Romans as a colonial settlement in 177 BC.

nodes.title: Macra (river)
nodes.description: The Magra river of northern Italy.

nodes.title: Marciana Marina
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 C4 Marciana Marina

nodes.title: Monte Castello
nodes.description: A fortified Etruscan settlement on Ilva.

nodes.title: Monte Serra
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 C4 Monte Serra

nodes.title: Oglasa (island)
nodes.description: Oglasa (Montecristo) is an island in the Tyrrhenian Sea and part of the Tuscan Archipelago.

nodes.title: Orbetello
nodes.description: A city of Tyrrhenian Etruria that came under Roman control in 280 B.C.; the Latin colony of Cosa was established nearby in 273 B.C.

nodes.title: Pisae
nodes.description: A city situated on the Tyrrhenian seaboard and likely of Etruscan origin. Its early nature was that of a mercantile center. The city became a Roman colony in 89 B.C.

nodes.title: Pistoriae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 D2 Pistoriae

nodes.title: Planasia (island)
nodes.description: Planasia (modern Pianosa) is an island of the Tuscan archipelago to which Agrippa Postumus was exiled by Augustus in A.D. 6 or 7.

nodes.title: Portus Herculis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 E5 Portus Herculis

nodes.title: Portus Pisanus?
nodes.description: The port city of Roman Pisa.

nodes.title: Prile (river)
nodes.description: The Bruna river flows some 70 km from the Colline Metallifere to the Tyrrhenian Sea, passing to the south of Massa Marittima. Its mouth is located at Castiglione della Pescaia.

nodes.title: Salebro?
nodes.description: An ancient coastal town with Etruscan origins near Lacus Prelius.

nodes.title: S. Gaetano di Vada
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 C3 S. Gaetano di Vada

nodes.title: S. Giovanni
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 C4 S. Giovanni

nodes.title: S. Liberata
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 E5 S. Liberata

nodes.title: Taberna Frigida
nodes.description: Taberna Frigida was a road station on the Via Aemilia Scauri at the crossing of the Frigidus river, located between Pisae and Luna.

nodes.title: Telamon
nodes.description: An ancient city of coastal Etruria, Telamon was eventually razed by L. Cornelius Sulla.

nodes.title: Umbro (river)
nodes.description: A river of Etruria that flows from Castelnuovo Berardenga to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

nodes.title: Urgo/Gorgon (island)
nodes.description: The northernmost island in the Tuscan Archipelago.

nodes.title: Vada Volaterrana
nodes.description: Vada Volaterrana was an Etruscan port city located north of the mouth of the Cecina river.

nodes.title: Valvata
nodes.description: Valvata was a statio on the Via Quinctia between Faesulae and Pisae.

nodes.title: Vatl/Vetulonia
nodes.description: The Etruscan Vatluna resisted Rome's influence in the seventh century, although the city may have been the source of Rome's adoption of the curule chair and the fasces.

nodes.title: Velathri/Volaterrae
nodes.description: A major Etruscan city of North Etruria.

nodes.title: Caldaccoli aqueduct
nodes.description: A first century A.D. Roman aqueduct that carried water from the locality known as "Caldaccoli" to baths in Pisa.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 D2 unnamed centuriation (Luca)

nodes.title: An unnamed quarry on Ilva
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 C4 unnamed quarry (Ilva)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 B3 unnamed monastery (Caprasia)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 B3 unnamed monastery (Urgo)

nodes.title: Monastero di San Mamiliano
nodes.description: The monastery of San Mamiliano located on the island of Montecristo.

nodes.title: Untitled Villa on the island of Igilium.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 D5 unnamed villa (Igilium Ins.)

nodes.title: Aquae Populoniae
nodes.description: Remains of an Etrusco-Roman thermal complex, dating from the third century B.C. to late antiquity, were documented between 2000 and 2003.

nodes.title: Hasta
nodes.description: An unlocated road station in coastal Etruria.

nodes.title: Triturrita
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Triturrita

nodes.title: Velinae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Velinae

nodes.title: Acquarossa
nodes.description: Acquarossa was an Etruscan settlement that was abandoned in the sixth century BC. The settlement occupied a steep-sided plateau and had an area of approximately 32 ha. Its ancient name is unknown.

nodes.title: Ad Aesim
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D2 Ad Aesim

nodes.title: Ad Aesim
nodes.description: A statio located at the mouth of Aesis fl. on the Adriatic coast; the Antonine Itinerary places it between Ancona and Sena Gallica.

nodes.title: Ad Centesimum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E3 Ad Centesimum

nodes.title: Ad Octavum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Ad Octavum

nodes.title: Aesis
nodes.description: An Umbrian town that became a colonia civium Romanorum under the name of Aesis in 247 B.C.

nodes.title: Aesis (river)
nodes.description: Aesis fl. (modern Esino river) is a river of the Marche region of Italy and flows into the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Ager Gallicus (region)
nodes.description: A region of Italy in which Gallic settlement had taken place after 400 BC. This territory was captured by Rome following the battle of Sentinum in 295 BC.

nodes.title: Alba Fucens
nodes.description: A town of the Aequi along the Marsic frontier where the Romans established a Latin colony in 304/3 B.C. Alba Fucens was a significant center of the middle republican period and became a place where Rome kept state prisoners, including Syphax of Numidia, Perseus of Macedonia, and Bituitus, king of the Arverni.

nodes.title: Albinia (river)
nodes.description: The Albegna is a river of southern Tuscany and flows from Monte Amiata to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

nodes.title: Alsietinus lacus
nodes.description: The Alsietinus lacus, modern Lago di Martignano, is a small volcanic crater-lake in southern Etruria. The lake was the source of the Augustan aqueduct aqua Augusta Alsietina that served non-potable water to the Transtiberim and Ianiculum.

nodes.title: Ameria
nodes.description: Ameria, claimed by Cato the Elder as the oldest town in Umbria, was an important center that may have gained Roman municipal status as early as 338 B.C., following the Latin War.

nodes.title: Amiternum
nodes.description: Amiternum was an ancient settlement of the Sabines that Rome captured in 293 BC. The settlement was situated at the intersection of four Roman roads: the Via Caecilia, the Via Claudia Nova, and the two branches of the Via Salaria. The historian Sallust was born at Amiternum in 86 B.C.

nodes.title: Ancon(a)
nodes.description: A port city founded by colonists from Syracuse in 387 BC.

nodes.title: Anguillara
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Anguillara

nodes.title: Anxanum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 G4 Anxanum

nodes.title: *Aprutium
nodes.description: An ancient region of eastern Italy (modern Abruzzo).

nodes.title: Aquae Cutiliae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Aquae Cutiliae

nodes.title: Aquae Passeris
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Aquae Passeris

nodes.title: Armenta (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 Armenta fl.

nodes.title: Arretium
nodes.description: Arretium (the Etruscan Aritim) was one of the duodecim populi Etruriae and described by Livy as one of the "Capitae Etruriae". The Romans captured the city in 311 B.C. and it became a station on the via Cassia.

nodes.title: Asculum
nodes.description: Asculum (modern Ascoli Piceno) was the principal city of the Piceni.

nodes.title: Asisium
nodes.description: A Roman settlement built over an Umbrian one on a western foothill of the Apennines, Asisium received municipal status and was assigned to the Tribus Sergia. Totila destroyed most of the city in A.D. 545.

nodes.title: Aternum
nodes.description: Aternum (modern Pescara) was a settlement at the mouth of the Aternus river.

nodes.title: Aternus (river)
nodes.description: The Aterno-Pescara river.

nodes.title: Aufinum
nodes.description: Aufinum (modern Ofena) was an ancient center of the Abruzzo. Pliny lists the Aufinates Cismontani among the communities of the Vestini.

nodes.title: *Aurinia/Saturnia
nodes.description: An Etruscan town that Dionysius of Halicarnassus claimed had been founded by the Pelasgians, Saturnia received a Roman colony in 183 BC.

nodes.title: Auximum
nodes.description: Auximum (modern Osimo) is an ancient settlement of Picenum. The original foundation was likely carried out by Greeks from Ancona. The Romans made it a base for military operations from 174 B.C.

nodes.title: Aveia
nodes.description: Aveia was a settlement of the Vestini in the valley of the Aterno river.

nodes.title: Avens (river)
nodes.description: A river of the Sabine territory.

nodes.title: Baccanae
nodes.description: Baccanae was a road station along the Via Cassia.

nodes.title: Badies
nodes.description: Badies is a site (vicus) along the Via Salaria mentioned in the Antonine Itinerary. Its location is no longer certain.

nodes.title: Blera
nodes.description: An Etruscan town located on the Via Clodia.

nodes.title: Cales
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Cales

nodes.title: Caletranus Ager
nodes.description: The Caletranus Ager was the territory surrounding the Etruscan city of Caletra.

nodes.title: Campovalano
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Campovalano

nodes.title: Capena
nodes.description: An ancient urban center in Faliscan territory adjacent to Etruria, Capena was sacked by the Romans in 390 BC.

nodes.title: Capestrano
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Capestrano

nodes.title: Carsulae
nodes.description: An ancient settlement originating the late fourth or third centuries BC and lying along the route of the Roman Via Flaminia.

nodes.title: Castellina
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A2 Castellina

nodes.title: Castellum Firmanorum
nodes.description: Castellum Firmanorum was the ancient port of Firmum Picenum.

nodes.title: Castiglione del Lago
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C2 Castiglione del Lago

nodes.title: Castrum Novum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Castrum Novum

nodes.title: Castrum Truentinum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Castrum Truentinum

nodes.title: Centum Cellae
nodes.description: Centum Cellae (modern Civitavecchia) was an ancient coastal settlement in Tyrrhenian Etruria. The emperor Trajan re-builds the harbor at the site in 106/7 and Pliny the Younger mentions its name, Centum Cellae. Saracens destroyed the city in A.D. 812.

nodes.title: Le Ciliegeta
nodes.description: The site of Le Ciliegeta, near the source of the river Arno, served as a rich stips votiva. The site was discovered in 1836. The finds included over 600 bronzes, more than 1,000 pieces of aes rude, 2,000 weapons and other artifacts.

nodes.title: Cingulum
nodes.description: Cingulum was a town in Picenum.

nodes.title: La Cività di Spedino
nodes.description: La Cività di Spedino was a fortified upland center (951 m ASL) in the territory of the Aequi.

nodes.title: Clanis (river)
nodes.description: Clanis fl. (Chiana river) is a river of central Italy that flows into the Tiber river.

nodes.title: Clasius? (river)
nodes.description: Clasius? fl., a river of Umbria and part of the Tiber river's basin.

nodes.title: Clitumnus (river)
nodes.description: A small river of Umbria.

nodes.title: Cluana
nodes.description: Cluana was an ancient settlement in Picenum.

nodes.title: Clusium
nodes.description: Clusium, the Etruscan Clevsin (modern Chiusi), was a major city of Etruria. Lars Porsena was a sixth century B.C. king of Clusium.

nodes.title: Cluviae
nodes.description: A city of the Carricini Samnites.

nodes.title: Contrada Altavilla
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Contrada Altavilla

nodes.title: Contrada S. Rustico
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Contrada S. Rustico

nodes.title: Corciano
nodes.description: The environs of Corciano were inhabited by Etruscans and, later, there is evidence for Roman villas. In 1812, a series of bronze panels from an Etruscan parade chariot was discovered at Castel San Mariano di Corciano.

nodes.title: Corfinium
nodes.description: Corfinium was the principal city of the Paeligni in the valley of the Aternus river. The site becomes the capital of the breakaway Italic groups that oppose Rome during the Social War.

nodes.title: Cortona
nodes.description: An Umbrian city that, under Etruscan influence, expanded and came to be called 'Curtun'. Later it became the Roman colony of Cortino.

nodes.title: Cosa
nodes.description: A Latin colony in south Etruria founded ca. 273 B.C.

nodes.title: Crustumius (river)
nodes.description: Crustumius fl. (Conca river)

nodes.title: Cumara? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Cumara? fl.

nodes.title: Cupra Maritima
nodes.description: Cupra Maritima was a coastal city of Picenum (regio V) assigned to the tribus Velina.

nodes.title: Cures
nodes.description: Cures (also Cures Sabini) was a Sabine city located in the Tiber river valley along the Via Salaria. The Romans conquered Cures in 290 B.C. under M'. Curius Dentatus and granted it status as a municipium in the tribus Sergia.

nodes.title: Cutiliensis L.
nodes.description: A lake located near ancient Reate.

nodes.title: Eretum
nodes.description: Eretum was a settlement of the Sabines and is involved in legendary accounts of early Rome.

nodes.title: Etruria/Tuscia (region)
nodes.description: Etruria/Tuscia was an ancient region of Central Italy inhabited by the Etruscans.

nodes.title: Faesulae
nodes.description: Faesulae (modern Fiesole) was an Etruscan foundation called Viesul, Viśl, or Vipsul. The city was conquered by Romans in 283 B.C. Sulla would settle Roman veterans there. Citizens of the town supported the conspiracy of Catiline.

nodes.title: Falerii
nodes.description: A fortified town located some 6 km from Falerii Veteres and established by the ancient Romans ca. 241 B.C.

nodes.title: Falerii Veteres
nodes.description: Falerii Veteres was the principal city of the Faliscans. It is located on a tuff outcropping at the point where several tributaries of the Treia join to flow into the Tiber. After rebelling against Rome in 241 B.C., Falerii suffered serious reversals of fortune.

nodes.title: Falerio
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Falerio

nodes.title: Falisci
nodes.description: The name for a group of Italic people who occupied the Ager Faliscus within Etruria.

nodes.title: Fanum Fortunae
nodes.description: Fanum Fortunae, the site of a shrine to Fortuna, is first mentioned in the ancient sources in 49 B.C. when Iulius Caesar held the town. An Augustan colony was established at the site and the Romans prevailed in the Battle of Fano in A.D. 271. The town was eventually destroyed by the Ostrogoths.

nodes.title: Fanum Fugitivi
nodes.description: A road station on the Via Flaminia, located between Interamna and Spoletium.

nodes.title: Ferentium
nodes.description: Ferentium (modern Ferento) was a city of Etruria first mentioned in the Liber Coloniarum ca. 123 BC that became a Roman municipium after the Social War. Substantial remains of the city remain; the site was the birthplace of Otho and noted for its fine stone monuments and statues.

nodes.title: Fescennium
nodes.description: Fescennium (modern Narce) was a Faliscan settlement located ca. 5 km south of Falerii Veteres.

nodes.title: Firmum Picenum
nodes.description: Firmum Picenum was founded as a Latin colony in 264 B.C. with 6,000 colonists. It received municipal status after 48 B.C.

nodes.title: Florentia
nodes.description: Florentia (modern Florence / Firenze) was founded as a colony for military veterans ca. 80 B.C. by Lucius Cornelius Sulla.

nodes.title: Flusor (river)
nodes.description: The Potenza river.

nodes.title: Fons Clitumni
nodes.description: Originally the site of a shrine dedicated to the river god Clitumnus and later a paleochristian shrine. The temple was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011.

nodes.title: Foruli
nodes.description: Foruli was a Sabine town located between Amiternum and Interocrea.

nodes.title: Forum Aurelii
nodes.description: A settlement in Etruria situated on the Via Aurelia between Centumcellae and Cosa according to the Antonine Itinerary.

nodes.title: Forum Cassii
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Forum Cassii

nodes.title: Forum Clodii
nodes.description: An ancient road station on the Via Clodia.

nodes.title: Forum Decii
nodes.description: A town of the Sabines mentioned by Pliny the Elder.

nodes.title: Forum Flaminii
nodes.description: A town founded in 220 B.C. by Caius Flaminius during the construction of the Via Flaminia.

nodes.title: Forum Sempronii
nodes.description: An ancient Roman colony, founded in the time of Gaius Sempronius Gracchus.

nodes.title: Fulginiae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Fulginiae

nodes.title: Furfo
nodes.description: A vicus of the Vestini.

nodes.title: Galeata
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 Galeata

nodes.title: Graviscae
nodes.description: The port of the Etruscan city of Tarquinia.

nodes.title: Hatria
nodes.description: An ancient city of Picenum that may have originated as colony established by Etruscans from Adria in the Veneto region. An alternate narrative suggests that the city's origins may be as a late sixth century B.C. colony founded by Aegina.

nodes.title: *Hercules Curinus
nodes.description: A sanctuary dedicated to Hercules Curinus located near Sulmo.

nodes.title: Helvia Ricina
nodes.description: An ancient settlement in Picenum at modern Villa Potenza in Marche, Comune di Macerata, Italy.

nodes.title: Helvillum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D2 Helvillum

nodes.title: Helvinus? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F2 Helvinus? fl.

nodes.title: Hispellum
nodes.description: Hispellum (modern Spello) is an ancient settlement of Umbria that became a Roman colony in the first century BC.

nodes.title: Histonium
nodes.description: Histonium, on the Adriatic coast, was a chief town of the Frentani.

nodes.title: Horta
nodes.description: The Etruscan settlement of *Hurta (the modern Orte) was close to the Vadimonis Lacus where the Romans fought, and won, two engagements against Etruscan armies.

nodes.title: Iguvium
nodes.description: An Umbrian hilltown, Iguvium is best known as the find-spot of the Iguvine Tables.

nodes.title: *Incerulae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 *Incerulae

nodes.title: Interamna Nahars
nodes.description: An Umbrian center founded in the seventh century B.C. that became an important Roman municipality along the Via Flaminia.

nodes.title: Interamnia Praetuttiorum
nodes.description: Originally a settlement of the Praetuttii located at the confluence of the rivers Tordino and Vezzola (modern Teramo).

nodes.title: Intercisa/Petra Pertusa
nodes.description: Intercisa/Petra Pertusa was a road station on the Via Flaminia. The toponym derives from the rock-cut tunnel or galleria that dates to the reign of Vespasian.

nodes.title: Interocrium
nodes.description: A Sabine town that was later known as a mansio on the course of the Via Salaria.

nodes.title: Interpromium
nodes.description: A village of the Marrucini, forming a station on the Via Claudia Valeria between Corfinium and Teate.

nodes.title: Lucus Feroniae
nodes.description: A sanctuary and grove of Feronia and an associated settlement located along the Via Tiberina in the territory of Capena.

nodes.title: Lugnano
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C3 Lugnano

nodes.title: Luni sul Mignone
nodes.description: Luni sul Mignone is a site with archaeological evidence for habitation in the later second millennium BC, continuing into the Italian Iron Age. Excavations conducted by the Swedish Institute in Rome (1960-1963) exposed three phases of settlement activity.

nodes.title: Marrucini
nodes.description: The Marrucini were an Italic tribe centered around Teate in the Abruzzo. In conflict with Rome through the end of the Second Samnite War, the Marrucini became allied with Rome thereafter. Their language was likely in the Sabellic family.

nodes.title: Marsi
nodes.description: The Marsi were an ancient Italic tribe. Their chief center was located at Marruvium.

nodes.title: Marsiliana d’Albegna
nodes.description: An ancient settlement located near the confluence of the rivers Albegna and Elsa.

nodes.title: Marta (river)
nodes.description: The Marta river flows from Lake Bolsena to the Tyrrhenian Sea. Its course flows past both Tuscania and Tarquinia and enters the Tyrrhenian Sea near Lido di Tarquinia.

nodes.title: Martanum
nodes.description: An ancient harbor of the city of Tarquinia.

nodes.title: Maternum
nodes.description: Maternum was a settlement of ancient Etruria that is known from the Peutinger Table. It is located along the Via Clodia between Saturnia and Tuscana.

nodes.title: Metaurus (river)
nodes.description: Metaurus fl. (Metauro river) flows from near Monte dei Frati in the Apennine Mountains to the Adriatic Sea. The Metaurus was the site of two key battles in antiquity.
