The first, in 207 B.C., saw the defeat of Hasdrubal Barca by the consuls Marcus Livius Salinator and Gaius Claudius Nero. The second, the Battle of Fano, saw Aurelian defeat the Alamanni in A.D. 271.

nodes.title: Mevania
nodes.description: Mevania (modern Bevagna) was a Roman municipium in Umbria located on the Via Flaminia. The town was enrolled in the tribus Aemilia.

nodes.title: Mevaniola
nodes.description: Mevaniola was a Roman city located in the Bidente valley. Its inhabitants were of Umbrian extraction, connected with the settlement of Mevania (Bevagna).

nodes.title: Minio (river)
nodes.description: A river that flows some 62 km from the Monti Sabatini to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

nodes.title: Misus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E1 Misus fl.

nodes.title: Nar (river)
nodes.description: The Nera river, a tributary of the Tiber.

nodes.title: Nemora Vacunae
nodes.description: Shrine dedicated to a rural divinity of the Sabina.

nodes.title: Nepet
nodes.description: Nepet had become a Roman town before 396 B.C. when Livy dubs it, along with Sutrium, as one of the "keys" to Etruria. It became a Roman colony in 383 B.C. and a municipium after the Social War.

nodes.title: Nequinum/Narnia
nodes.description: Nequinum/Narnia (modern Narni) was an ancient settlement in Umbria. It became a Latin colony in 299 BC.

nodes.title: Nuceria
nodes.description: Nuceria (modern Nocera Umbra) is an ancient town in Umbria, perhaps founded in the seventh century B.C. by Camerinum.

nodes.title: Ocriculum
nodes.description: An ancient Umbrian city that became allied with Rome in 308 B.C.

nodes.title: [Orcla]
nodes.description: [Orcla] or Norchia is an ancient Etruscan settlement located near Tarquinia and along the line of the Roman Via Clodia.

nodes.title: Ortona
nodes.description: An ancient site in Italy that most likely originates with the Frentani.

nodes.title: Osa (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A3 Osa fl.

nodes.title: Ostia Aterni
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 G4 Ostia Aterni

nodes.title: Paeligni
nodes.description: An ancient Oscan tribe of eastern Italy, the Paeligni are mentioned in the historical sources first in the fourth century BC when they oppose Rome during the Second Samnite War. The Paeligni came into alliance with Rome at the end of the fourth century BC but again took sides against Rome in the Social War.

nodes.title: Pallia (river)
nodes.description: The Pallia is a tributary of the Tiber river.

nodes.title: Palmensis Ager
nodes.description: Pliny the Elder discusses the Palmensis Ager in connection with his description of the Praetutii.

nodes.title: Passo Corese
nodes.description: Passo Corese is located near Cures (Fara in Sabina). The site is often connected with Titus Tatius' march on Rome in 747 B.C.

nodes.title: Pausulae
nodes.description: Pausulae was a town of Picenum mentioned by Pliny the Elder. It was a Municipium of Regio V.

nodes.title: Peltuinum
nodes.description: Peltuinum was a settlement of the Vestini located along the Via Claudia Nova. The town is notable as the birthplace of the Roman general Gnaeus Domitius Corbulo.

nodes.title: Perusia
nodes.description: A city of ancient Umbrian and Etruscan origin, Perusia aided Rome during the Second Punic War but was sieged and reduced by Octavian in the first century B.C. during campaigns against Lucius Antonius. It was rebuilt by Augustus and became Colonia Vibia Augusta Perusia quite late, in A.D. 251-3, under Trebonianus Gallus.

nodes.title: Phalacrinae
nodes.description: A Roman town in which the emperor Vespasian was born in A.D. 9.

nodes.title: Picenum (region)
nodes.description: Picenum was a region of Central Italy, extending along the coast of the Adriatic Sea from the mouth of the Aesis to that of the Matrinus, and inland as far as the central Apennines.

nodes.title: Pinna
nodes.description: Pinna (modern Penne) was a center of the Vestini. The site came under Roman control after the Social War (89 BC).

nodes.title: Pitigliano
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Pitigliano

nodes.title: Pitinum
nodes.description: An ancient center of the Vestini.

nodes.title: Plestia
nodes.description: Plestia was a municipium of the tribus Ufentina.

nodes.title: Poggio Buco
nodes.description: Poggio Buco was a pre-Roman site located in the valley of the Fiora river. Its archaeological remains include those of a circuit wall and a necropolis. The archaeological site is located ca. 9 km west of Pitigliano.

nodes.title: Ponte a Buriano
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 Ponte a Buriano

nodes.title: Potentia
nodes.description: A city settled in an area subjugated by Rome during the fourth century B.C. The local populace rebelled against Rome after the defeat at Cannae (216 B.C.), however the defeat of the Carthaginians eventually led to Potentia's reincorporation into the Roman sphere.

nodes.title: Praetuttii
nodes.description: The Praetuttii were an ancient tribe of central Italy.

nodes.title: Quinto Fiorentino
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A1 Quinto Fiorentino

nodes.title: Reate
nodes.description: Reate (modern Rieti) was a major Sabine center that came to be captured by Manius Curius Dentatus in late third century B.C.

nodes.title: Rusellae
nodes.description: An Etruscan city captured by Rome in 294 B.C., Rusellae's >2 mile circuit of megalithic walls represent an important early instance of stone fortification walling in the Italian peninsula.

nodes.title: Sabatinus lacus
nodes.description: A volcanic lake in Latium north of Rome (modern Lago di Bracciano).

nodes.title: Sacraria
nodes.description: A station on the Via Flaminia near Le Vene.

nodes.title: Saena
nodes.description: Saena was an Etruscan city that received a Roman colony (Saena Iulia) in the time of Augustus.

nodes.title: Sagrus (river)
nodes.description: A river of eastern Italy (modern Sangro).

nodes.title: San Giovenale
nodes.description: The archaeological remains of an Etruscan settlement were discovered at San Giovenale, close to Blera, Italy, by the Swedish Institute at Rome in the 1950s and 1960s. The ancient name of the site is unknown.

nodes.title: San Giuliano
nodes.description: An Etruscan settlement evidenced by its extensive, surviving necropolis, which now lies within the Parco Naturale Regionale Marturanum in the administrative territory of Barbarano Romano, Italy. Its modern name is transferred from a nearby medieval church.

nodes.title: Sarteano
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Sarteano

nodes.title: Sena (river)
nodes.description: The Nevola river.

nodes.title: Sena Gallica
nodes.description: Located at the mouth of the river Misa, Sena Gallica was founded by the Senonian Gauls in the fourth century B.C. and became the site of Rome's earliest Adriatic colony before 280 B.C. Pompeius Magnus destroyed the city in 82 B.C.

nodes.title: Senones
nodes.description: An ancient Gallic tribe that entered Italy after 400 BC and settled on the Adriatic coast from Forlì to Ancona, marking the so-called Ager Gallicus.

nodes.title: Sentinum
nodes.description: An ancient town in the region of Italy now known as Le Marche, Sentinum is perhaps best known for the pivotal Battle of Sentinum of the Third Samnite War that took place nearby in 295 BC.

nodes.title: Sepernates?
nodes.description: An ancient people of Etruria inhabiting the area around Nazzano Romano.

nodes.title: Septempeda
nodes.description: Septempeda was an ancient settlement of Picenum. Its Roman phase began as a conciliabulum in the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Settefinestre
nodes.description: A Late Republican Roman slave-run villa owned by the senatorial family of the Volusii.

nodes.title: Spoletium
nodes.description: An ancient city along the route of the Via Flaminia; an initial colony was established there in 241 BC.

nodes.title: Statonia
nodes.description: An ancient city of south Etruria.

nodes.title: Suana
nodes.description: Suana (Sovana) has Etruscan origins but later became a Roman municipium. In the fifth century A.D. it became an episcopal see.

nodes.title: Suasa
nodes.description: Suasa was the site of a Roman municipium in Umbria. It lies in the Piano Volpello along a road from Cales to Sena Gallica. Alaric razed the settlement in 409.

nodes.title: Succosa
nodes.description: Succosa was located between the Portus Cosanus and the Via Aurelia Antica to the north. It is mentioned in the Itineraries and located on the Tabula Peutingeriana. F.E. Brown suggests that Succosa, derived from "sub-Cosa", emerges in the first century B.C. following the decline of the hill-top colony. It may also be the "Respublica Cosanorum" that is mentioned in Severan inscriptions known from the hill-top town.

nodes.title: Superaequum
nodes.description: One of three towns of the Paeligni which possessed municipal rights.

nodes.title: Sutrium
nodes.description: An ancient settlement along the line of what would become the Roman Via Cassia and described by Livy, together with Nepet, as one of the keys to Etruria. A Latin colony was founded at the site after the fall of Veii.

nodes.title: Tadinae
nodes.description: Tadinae (Sant'Antonio della Rasina to the west of Gualdo Tadino) is an ancient municipium of Umbria and was a road station on the Via Flaminia.

nodes.title: Tarchna/Tarquinii
nodes.description: An ancient city of Etruria and the leading city of the doudecim populi Etruriae, Tarquinia (called Tarch(u)na or Tarchna in Etruscan) was a major urban center of ancient Italy.

nodes.title: Teate
nodes.description: Originally named Teate Marrucinorum, Teate (modern Chieti) was the principal settlement of the Marrucini. Strabo attributes its origins to Arcadian Greeks.

nodes.title: Tetricus M.
nodes.description: Tetricus M., a mountain group in Italy, part of the central Apennines.

nodes.title: Tifernum Tiberinum
nodes.description: An Umbrian hilltown in the floodplain of the Tiber river north of Perusia.

nodes.title: Tinea (river)
nodes.description: The Topino river in Umbria.

nodes.title: Tinna (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F2 Tinna fl.

nodes.title: Tolentinum
nodes.description: Tolentinum was a town of Picenum that is listed as having municipal status in the Liber Coloniarum.

nodes.title: Tolenus (river)
nodes.description: A river of Lazio and Abruzzo that is a tributary of the Velino.

nodes.title: Traianus?
nodes.description: A Roman villa that is typically associated with the emperor Trajan.

nodes.title: Trasumennus L.
nodes.description: Trasumennus L. (Lake Trasimeno) is the largest lake of the Italian peninsula and the site of a major engagement of the Second Punic War on June 21, 217 B.C.

nodes.title: Trebiae
nodes.description: Trebiae was an ancient city of Umbria (regio IV) located near the line of the Via Flaminia.

nodes.title: Trebula Mutuesca
nodes.description: Trebula Mutuesca or Trebula Mutusca was one of two Sabine cities bearing the name Trebula.

nodes.title: Tres Tabernae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Tres Tabernae

nodes.title: Trevignano
nodes.description: Trevignano Romano, located on the shores of Lake Bracciano, lies some 47 km from Rome. Archaeological evidence for Etruscan occupation, in the form of tombs dating to the eighth - sixth centuries B.C., has been discovered to the north of the modern town. A medieval castle was built there under Innocent III ca. 1200.

nodes.title: Truentus (river)
nodes.description: A river of Picenum that flows from its source on the Gran Sasso d'Italia to the Adriatic Sea at Porto d'Ascoli.

nodes.title: Tuder
nodes.description: Tuder, modern Todi, is an ancient city of Umbria. Its foundation likely occurred during the eighth/seventh centuries BC, although legendary traditions associate the site with the activities of Herakles.

nodes.title: Tuficum
nodes.description: Tuficum was an ancient city of Umbria located on the Aesis river. It became a municipium of the tribus Oufentina.

nodes.title: Tuscana
nodes.description: An ancient city that traced its legendary origins to Ascanius, son of Aeneas. The site became an important Etruscan mercantile center and eventually achieved Roman municipal status in 88 B.C.

nodes.title: Umbria (region)
nodes.description: The eponymous region of the Umbri, an ancient Italic people who spoke the Umbrian language. The physical geography of the landlocked region is hilly and dominated by the Appennine Mountains.

nodes.title: *Umbro (river)
nodes.description: The Ambra flows from the foot of Monte Luco to the Arno river.

nodes.title: Urbs Salvia
nodes.description: An ancient city of Regio V (Picenum) where a Roman colony was founded in the second century B.C.

nodes.title: Urvinum Mataurense
nodes.description: Urvinum Mataurense (modern Urbino).

nodes.title: Vadimonis (lake)
nodes.description: A partially dry lake of ancient Etruria near Orte. The Romans were victorious in two battles fought against the Etruscans there (310 and 283 BC).

nodes.title: Velzna/*Volsinii Veteres/Urbiventus
nodes.description: Volsinii Veteres was one of the most powerful and important cities of Etruria, as it was the location of the important federal sanctuary located at the Fanum Voltumnae.

nodes.title: Vestini
nodes.description: The Vestini were an ancient tribe of Italy and lived in the southern part of the modern Abruzzo, between the Gran Sasso and the northern bank of the Aterno river. A major center was located at Pitinum.

nodes.title: Vettona
nodes.description: Vettona (modern Bettona) is an ancient settlement of Umbria located between Perusia and Mevania. Pliny the Elder lists it among the municipalities of Umbria, and it also numbered as one of the “xv Populi Umbriae".

nodes.title: Vicarello
nodes.description: A large, Roman imperial estate covering ca. 2,000 ha on the shores of Lake Bracciano. The name may derive from Vicus Aurelius, suggesting a connection with Marcus Aurelius.

nodes.title: Vicus Martis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Vicus Martis

nodes.title: Vicus Matrini
nodes.description: Vicus Matrini was a mansio along the Via Cassia, located between Sutri and Forum Cassi. The site's name is attested on the Peutinger Table.

nodes.title: Vicus Novus/Ad Novas
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Vicus Novus/Ad Novas

nodes.title: Visentium
nodes.description: Visentium (Bisenzio) was an Etruscan settlement located on the shores of Lago di Bolsena. The site has yielded especially important evidence for Iron Age and Etruscan period burials.

nodes.title: Volsiniensis L.
nodes.description: A volcanic lake of northern Latium formed by the collapse of the Vulsini volcano. Roman sources record volcanic activity at the site as late as the second century B.C.

nodes.title: Volsinii
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Volsinii

nodes.title: Volusii
nodes.description: A villa associated with the Volusii Saturnini built ca. 50 B.C.

nodes.title: Vomanus (river)
nodes.description: The Vomano river in Abruzzo flows into the Adriatic Sea.

nodes.title: Vulci
nodes.description: Vulci (originally Velch or Velx in Etruscan) was an Etruscan city 80 km northwest of Rome. Vulci was one of the duodecim populi Etruriae.

nodes.title: Roman aqueduct at Arretium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 unnamed aqueduct (Arretium)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An aqueduct located near the sulphurous springs at Aquae Tauri, northeast of Centumcellae.

nodes.title: Unnamed aqueduct near Amiternum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 unnamed aqueduct (near Amiternum)

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge
nodes.description: An unnamed ancient bridge located on the Via Aurelia over the Osa river at Telamon.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 unnamed bridge (W Ponte a Buriano, over R. Arno)

nodes.title: Ponte di Pogi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 unnamed bridge (over *Umbro fl., W Arretium at Pogi)

nodes.title: Ponte dell'Abbadia
nodes.description: An ancient bridge over the Fiora river (the ancient Armenta) near Vulci. Ancient name unknown.

nodes.title: Bridge on Via Cassia near *Volsinii Veteres
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C3

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 unnamed bridge group (on Via Cassia, near Sorrina)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Clodia, at Blera)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 unnamed bridge group (on Via Amerina, near Nepet)

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge over the Nar river near Terni
nodes.description: An ancient bridge near the *Via Curia.

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1-C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Flaminia (20))

nodes.title: Ponte di Quintodecimo
nodes.description: The Ponte di Quintodecimo is located near Acquasanta Terme.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A1 unnamed centuriation (Florentia)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A4 unnamed centuriation (Cosa)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E1 unnamed centuriation (Fanum Fortunae)

nodes.title: Unnamed centuriation near Potentia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F2 unnamed centuriation (Potentia)

nodes.title: Acerrae Vafriae
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Umbria that is attested in Pliny the Elder but is recorded as a place that had vanished by his own day.

nodes.title: Ad Martis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Ad Martis

nodes.title: Ad Nonas
nodes.description: Ad Nonas is the name of a now unlocated road station near Cosa; the name is attested in the Peutinger Table.

nodes.title: Ad Novas
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Ad Novas

nodes.title: Aequum Faliscum
nodes.description: A settlement along the Via Flaminia, now unlocated. Strabo places it between Otricoli and Rome; the possibility must be allowed that it is taken to the identical with Falerii.

nodes.title: Caelestini
nodes.description: An ancient people of Italy whose territory is unlocated.

nodes.title: Castellum Amerinum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Castellum Amerinum

nodes.title: Ceios
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Ceios

nodes.title: Cingilia
nodes.description: A settlement of the Vestini, now unlocated, that, according to Livy, Iunius Brutus captured in 325 B.C.

nodes.title: Clusiolum
nodes.description: Clusiolum is an unlocated site in Umbria. Pliny the Elder discusses it in connection with the Felginates who at one point held Clusiolum. Its location is described as being above Interamna.

nodes.title: Crinivolum
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Cutina
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Dolates Sallentini
nodes.description: An ancient people of Umbria whose territory is now unlocated.

nodes.title: Falinates
nodes.description: An ancient people of Umbria whose territory is now unlocated.

nodes.title: Fanum Voltumnae
nodes.description: A shrine of Voltumna that served as the chief religious center of Etruria. The Etruscan League (duodecim populi Etruriae) was said to meet annually at the shrine.

nodes.title: Fiscellus M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Fiscellus M.

nodes.title: Flosis (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Flosis fl.

nodes.title: Forum Brentani/Brentanorum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Forum Brentani/Brentanorum

nodes.title: Forum Iulii Concupiensium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Forum Iulii Concupiensium

nodes.title: Frusteniae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Frusteniae

nodes.title: Iabuscer
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated.

nodes.title: Larolon
nodes.description: A toponym attested in Strabo but not elsewhere - perhaps the name of a stream emptying into the Tiber near Ocriculum.

nodes.title: Novana
nodes.description: Novana, now unlocated, was a town of Picenum that is only known via Pliny's Natural History. The textual description places the site near Asculum and Cupra.

nodes.title: Novem Pagi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Novem Pagi

nodes.title: Paesinates
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

nodes.title: Plangenses
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

nodes.title: Sabate
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

nodes.title: Sacrata
nodes.description: Attested on the Peutinger Map, this road station near the Adriatic coast in Italy cannot be located with certainty today.

nodes.title: Salinae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Salinae

nodes.title: Sarranates
nodes.description: An ancient people of Umbria whose territory is unlocated.

nodes.title: Severus M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Severus M.

nodes.title: Solinates
nodes.description: An ancient Umbrian people whose territory is now unlocated.

nodes.title: Suillates
nodes.description: The Suillates were an ancient people of Umbria. Their territory is now unlocated.

nodes.title: Suriates
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

nodes.title: Surpicanum
nodes.description: An ancient settlement along the Via Salaria, the exact position of which remains unknown.

nodes.title: Tabellaria
nodes.description: A road station located on the via Aurelia between Centumcellae and Graviscae in Etruria, now unlocated.

nodes.title: Taresuni
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

nodes.title: Testruna
nodes.description: Testruna is now unlocated, although it may have been located near Amiternum. Dionysius of Halicarnassus names it as the original settlement of the Sabines.

nodes.title: Traiana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Traiana

nodes.title: Turocaelum Vettiolum
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Usidicani
nodes.description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

nodes.title: Veregra/Beregra
nodes.description: Veregra/Beregra was an ancient settlement of Picenum that is attested in the texts of Pliny and Ptolemy, although its precise location cannot be determined today.

nodes.title: Vesinicates
nodes.description: An ancient people of Umbria whose territory is now unlocated.

nodes.title: Via Quinctia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Via Quinctia

nodes.title: Vindenates
nodes.description: An ancient Umbrian people whose territory is unlocated.

nodes.title: Visuentani
nodes.description: An ancient people of Umbria whose territory is unlocated.

nodes.title: Acqua Acetosa
nodes.description: A settlement along the Via Laurentina that has yielded significant evidence for protohistoric occupation, including funereal evidence of the eighth and seventh centuries B.C.

nodes.title: Ad Bivium
nodes.description: A statio in Latium located at the intersection of the Via Latina and the Via Labicana, near the modern Valmontone.

nodes.title: Ad Duas Lauros
nodes.description: The toponym 'Ad Duas Lauros' refers to a large imperial property at the third mile of the Via Labicana and today comprised of the archaeological park of Centocelle. The site is mentioned in the Liber Pontificalis as that of a large imperial villa in which Helena, mother of Constantine I, lived. Archaeological work conducted in the late 1990s identified the remains of substantial Republican period villas in the same area, with evidence of both elite dwellings and viticulture. The villas identified are the Villa della Piscina and the Villa Ad Duas Lauros.

nodes.title: Ad Gallinas Albas
nodes.description: Ad Gallinas Albas refers to a location along the Via Flaminia.

nodes.title: Ad Nonum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Ad Nonum

nodes.title: Ad Pictas
nodes.description: Ad Pictas is a road station east of Rome, known mostly for its role in Sulla's march on Rome in 88 B.C. The precise location of the statio continues to be debated.

nodes.title: Ad Quintanas
nodes.description: Ad Quintanas is the name of a road station on the Via Labicana.

nodes.title: Ad Sextum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Ad Sextum

nodes.title: Ad Sponsas
nodes.description: Ad Sponsas was a road station on the Via Appia.

nodes.title: Ad Statuas
nodes.description: Ad Statuas was a road station on the Via Labicana located east of Rome.

nodes.title: Ad Turres
nodes.description: Ad Turres was located on the Via Aurelia some 10 miles from Lorium and 12 miles from Pyrgi.

nodes.title: Aeflanus M.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Aeflanus M.

nodes.title: Aefula
nodes.description: Aefula was an ancient settlement of Latium that had disappeared by the time of Pliny the Elder, although the cult of Bona Dea there continued to flourish.

nodes.title: Aequi
nodes.description: The Aequi were an ancient Italic tribe of northeast Latium in the first millennium BC.

nodes.title: Afilae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 E2 Afilae

nodes.title: Alba Longa?
nodes.description: Alba Longa, located in the Alban Hills southeast of Rome, was the chief city and founder of the Latin League. Conflict with Rome caused Alba's destruction in the seventh century B.C. The legendary history of Romulus and Remus connects them to the royal lineage of the city.

nodes.title: Albanus L.
nodes.description: A volcanic lake in ancient Latium at the foot of Albanus Mons, Albanus Lacus (Alban Lake) is connected with the site of the city of Alba Longa and, later, with imperial properties of the Flavian house.

nodes.title: Albanus M.
nodes.description: The second highest summit of the Alban Hills, Mons Albanus is an extinct volcano with an elevation of 950 m (3,117 ft). In the middle of the first millennium B.C. there may have been volcanic activity as noted by the historian Livy. The mountain was sacred for Latin peoples who held important festivals there and a major shrine to Iuppiter Latiaris stands on the mountain top.

nodes.title: Algidus
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of Latium located in the territory of the Aequi.

nodes.title: Algidus (mountain)
nodes.description: Algidus (mons) refers to the eastern rim of the dormant Alban volcano in the Alban Hills of central Italy, known today as  Monte Artemisio.

nodes.title: Alsium
nodes.description: Alsium served as a port for Caere, together with Fregenae.

nodes.title: Anagnia
nodes.description: Anagnia was a Hernican town that sided with Rome against the Volscians and later became civitas sine suffragio.

nodes.title: Anio (river)
nodes.description: The Anio river (modern Aniene) is a river of northern Latium.

nodes.title: Annunziatella
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Annunziatella

nodes.title: Antium
nodes.description: Antium ranked as one of the most important and most powerful centers of Latium and was captured by Rome at the close of the Latin War in the fourth century B.C. Imperial Antium was well known for a number of coastal villas.

nodes.title: Villa degli Antonini
nodes.description: The so-called 'Villa of the Antonines', located near Genzano di Roma in the Alban Hills, lies just south of the Via Appia between the road's 18th and 19th milestones.

nodes.title: Aquae Albulae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Aquae Albulae

nodes.title: Ardea
nodes.description: Ardea was an ancient settlement of the Rutuli in Latium.

nodes.title: Aricia
nodes.description: Aricia is an ancient Latin settlement and a member of the Latin League.

nodes.title: Artena
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Artena

nodes.title: Astura (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D4 Astura fl.

nodes.title: Baebiana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 A2 Baebiana

nodes.title: Bovillae
nodes.description: A town of ancient Latium along the line of the Via Appia, Bovillae is traditionally considered to be a colony of Alba Longa and was one of the thirty cities of the Latin League.

nodes.title: Cabum?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Cabum?

nodes.title: Caere
nodes.description: Caere (also known as Cisra or Cerveteri) was a major Etruscan polis located ca. 50 km north-northwest of Rome in southern Etruria.

nodes.title: Calepodius
nodes.description: A Christian catacomb originally containing the tombs of Pope Callixtus I and Pope Julius I, along with that of the eponymous Saint Calepodius.

nodes.title: Campus Martius
nodes.description: The Campus Martius or "field of Mars" is the name given to the level ground between the slopes of the Capitoline, the Quirinal, and Pincian hills, and the Tiber river.

nodes.title: Careiae
nodes.description: An ancient town on the Via Clodia.

nodes.title: Casal Rotondo
nodes.description: A Roman tomb that supports a Medieval farmhouse (casale) at the sixth mile of the Via Appia. The tomb originally dates ca. 30 BC; it was a large, circular tomb with a diameter of approximately 35 m.

nodes.title: Casale di Gregna
nodes.description: A villa at the seventh mile of the Via Latina.

nodes.title: Casale Morena
nodes.description: A villa located at the eighth mile of the ancient Via Latina. The villa was first built in the first century B.C. and continued in use until the fourth century. During its life span there were several phases of architectural modification and expansion.

nodes.title: Cassio
nodes.description: A villa in Tibur that has been incorrectly linked to Gaius Cassius Longinus. In the eighteenth century, the site produced a cache of Egyptianizing sculpture that likely dates to the reign of Hadrian and is now held in the Vatican Museums.

nodes.title: Le Castella
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Le Castella

nodes.title: Castelporziano
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 Castelporziano

nodes.title: Castra Albana
nodes.description: Castra Albana was a permanent, fortified camp of the Legio II Parthica constructed during the Severan period.

nodes.title: La Cecchina
nodes.description: The so-called "Torraccio della Cecchina" is a Roman funereal monument dating to the second century A.D. It is located at the ninth kilometer of the modern Via Nomentana.

nodes.title: Centroni
nodes.description: The Villa dei Centroni, located on the modern via Anagnina, lay at the ninth mile of the ancient via Latina. It dates from the first century B.C. onward.

nodes.title: Ceres et Faustina, T.
nodes.description: The Roman temple dedicated to Ceres and Faustina received patronage from Herodes Atticus. Its remains were eventually repurposed in the construction of the church of Sant'Urbano.

nodes.title: Cervara 2
nodes.description: In the vicinity of Tor Cervara are anio tuff (tufo d'Aniene) quarries.

nodes.title: Cessati Spiriti
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Cessati Spiriti

nodes.title: Cimitero Maggiore
nodes.description: A major Roman necropolis and catacomb along the Via Nomentana.

nodes.title: Civitana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Civitana

nodes.title: Clodio
nodes.description: Cicero describes the villa of Publius Clodius Pulcher as being located at the thirteenth mile of the Via Appia near Bovillae.

nodes.title: Collatia
nodes.description: Collatia was an ancient city of Latium located between Gabii and the Anio fl. A colony of Alba Longa, Collatia was one of the most ancient cities of Latium. Subjugated by Rome under the Tarquins, Collatia would decline during the Republican period and numbers among the lost Latin cities by the accounting of Pliny the Elder.

nodes.title: Compitum
nodes.description: A multi-period sanctuary near Anagnia.

nodes.title: Cora
nodes.description: A Latin center in the Monti Lepini that was already a Roman municipium by 211 B.C.

nodes.title: Corniculum
nodes.description: An ancient town of Latium connected with the origins of Serivus Tullius.

nodes.title: Cremera (river)
nodes.description: The Cremera is a small stream in Lazio that played a role in the fourth century BC war between Rome and the Etruscan city-state of Veii.

nodes.title: Crepaddosso
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Crepaddosso

nodes.title: Crustumerium
nodes.description: An ancient town of Latium located at the headwaters of the Allia river, very close to the territory of the Sabines, Crustumerium figures in Rome's early history. The Romans conquered the site in 500 B.C. and formed the tribus Crustumina or Clustumina in 471 B.C.

nodes.title: Diana, T.
nodes.description: A site sacred to Diana near Lake Nemi, comprised of a Tuscan-style sanctuary and a sacred grove.

nodes.title: Ficana
nodes.description: An ancient city of Latium that was said to have been conquered by Ancus Marcius, Ficana was located near the eleventh mile of the Via Ostiensis. Excavation at the site has produced important evidence for the urban center beginning from the eighth century BC. Pliny the Elder mentions Ficana as one of the lost cities of Latium.

nodes.title: Ficulea
nodes.description: Ficulea was an ancient city of Latium situated between Rome and Nomentum.

nodes.title: Fidenae
nodes.description: Fidenae was an ancient city of Latium.

nodes.title: Fortis Fortuna, T.
nodes.description: A sanctuary of Fors Fortuna in Trastevere. Varro ascribes its foundation to Servius Tullius.

nodes.title: Fortuna Muliebris, T.
nodes.description: A sanctuary dedicated to Fortuna Muliebris along the Via Latina. Tradition holds that it was dedicated in 487 B.C.

nodes.title: Forum Appii
nodes.description: An ancient road station on the Via Appia located 69 km southeast of Rome.

nodes.title: Gabii
nodes.description: An ancient Latin city located on the line of the Republican Via Praenestina connecting Rome to Praeneste. Gabii is allied to Rome from an early date and flourished during the archaic period, declining by the time of Augustus.

nodes.title: Giordani
nodes.description: A fourth century A.D. catacomb along the via Salaria at Rome.

nodes.title: La Giostra
nodes.description: A fortified site on the Via Appia dating to the Republican period.

nodes.title: Villa Gordiani
nodes.description: A third century A.D. villa complex along the Via Praenestina connected with Gordian I, Gordian II, and Gordian III.

nodes.title: Grottaferrata
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Grottaferrata

nodes.title: Grottarossa
nodes.description: Grottarossa is located at the intersection of key roadways in northern suburbium of Rome, lying along the Via Flaminia as well as at the point where the Via Veientana separated from the Via Cassia and thereby connected Rome with Veii. There is archaeological evidence for tombs, both built tombs and rock-cut tombs in the exposed tuff escarpments, as well as villas.

nodes.title: Grotta Oscura
nodes.description: The quarries at Grotta Oscura were an important source of high quality tuff located in the territory of Veii.

nodes.title: Hernici
nodes.description: The Hernici (Hernicans) were an Italic tribe of first millennium B.C. Latium. Their territory was bounded by the Trerus fl. (Sacco) and the Lacus Fucinus (Fucine Lake).

nodes.title: Isola Sacra
nodes.description: An extensive second and third century A.D. necropolis located between the city of Ostia and Portus.

nodes.title: Iuppiter Latiaris, T.
nodes.description: An important Latial sanctuary of Iuppiter located on Mons Albanus (modern Monte Cavo).

nodes.title: Labicum
nodes.description: Originally a member of the Latin League, the city of Labicum was taken by the Romans ca. 418 B.C. By the time of Augustus, the site was almost certainly deserted and its precise location remains debated today.

nodes.title: Lanuvium
nodes.description: Lanuvium was an important city of Latium located south of the Alban Hills. After opposing Rome at the battle of Aricia (504 B.C.) and Lake Regillus (496 B.C.), Lanuvium was captured by the Romans in 338 B.C.

nodes.title: Latium Vetus (region)
nodes.description: Latium Vetus is an historical region of Italy. Latium Vetus begins south of the Tiber river and extends as far as Circeo, at which point the boundary of Latium Adiectum is reached.

nodes.title: Laurentes
nodes.description: Laurentum was an ancient city of Latium located some 16 miles from Rome, between Ostia and Lavinium. Its precise location can no longer be determined. In Rome's legendary history Laurentum is the site of king Latinus' dwelling.

nodes.title: Lavinium
nodes.description: An ancient city of Latium on the Numicus river that was founded, according to Virgil, by Aeneas.

nodes.title: Lepinus M.
nodes.description: Lepinus M., a mountain range of central Italy that belongs to the Anti-Apennines.

nodes.title: Lorium
nodes.description: An ancient town on the Via Aurelia.

nodes.title: Lucio Vero
nodes.description: A Roman villa located at Acquatraversa on the Via Cassia that is frequently attributed to Lucius Verus.

nodes.title: Magliana Vecchia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Magliana Vecchia

nodes.title: Marmenia
nodes.description: The Domus Marmeniae is a villa located on the Via Appia near the fourth milestone. The villa grounds hosted a pagan necropolis and tradition holds that the matrona, Marmenia, relocated the body of St. Urban to a mausoleum built on the grounds.

nodes.title: Mondragone
nodes.description: A Renaissance villa (Villa Mondragone) was built atop the platform of a Roman villa dating to the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Monte del Grano
nodes.description: Monte del Grano is a popular name that was assigned to a mausoleum once thought to belong to Alexander Severus, although that assignation is no longer supported. The archaeological remains are now part of the Parco XVII Aprile 1944.

nodes.title: Monteverde
nodes.description: The hill of Monteverde, a part of the Ianiculum hill to the west of the Tiber river, was a source of a brown, lithoid tuff (tufo di Monteverde) that was quarried for use as a building material from the second century BC.

nodes.title: Naumachia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Naumachia

nodes.title: Nemorensis (lake)
nodes.description: Nemorensis Lacus (modern Lake Nemi) is a small, volcanic lake in Latium located south of Rome. The lake is known for its adjacent sanctuary of the goddess Diana and for a number of sunken Roman ships of the first century AD that were recovered from it.

nodes.title: Nomentum
nodes.description: The Latin town of Nomentum and Rome were linked by means of the Via Nomentana. In Livy's history the town, a member of the Latin League, is captured by Lucius Tarquinius Priscus. Nomentum was one of a number of towns captured by Tarquinius. The Romans granted the town civitas sine suffragio after 338 B.C.

nodes.title: Norba
nodes.description: Norba, located in the Monti Lepini, was a member of the Latin League (ca. 499 B.C.) and became a Latin colony ca. 492 B.C. The city was destroyed in the early first century B.C.

nodes.title: Numicus (river)
nodes.description: The Numicus flumen was a river of Latium connected with the legendary history of Aeneas. Modern Fosso di Pratica in Italy.

nodes.title: Villa of the Octavii
nodes.description: The archaeological remains of a Roman villa on the hill of San Cesareo are speculatively identified as belonging to the gens Octavia, according to Della Portella 2004 op. cit.

nodes.title: Opimiano
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Opimiano

nodes.title: Osteria dell’Osa
nodes.description: The site of a major Iron Age necropolis (Latial chronology) composed of over 600 burials.

nodes.title: Ostia
nodes.description: The port city of ancient Rome located at the mouth of the river Tiber.

nodes.title: Pianabella
nodes.description: A large Christian basilica discovered in 1976 several hundred meters southeast of the Porta Laurentina of Ostia. The original phase dates to the end of the fourth century A.D.

nodes.title: Plinio
nodes.description: The so-called villa of Pliny the Younger, also known as the Villa delle Palombara. The villa's first phases date to the Iulio-Claudian period. It continues in use, and continues to undergo modifications, through the second century A.D.

nodes.title: Pometia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Pometia

nodes.title: Pons Mulvius
nodes.description: Pons Mulvius (the Milvian Bridge) is a Roman bridge over the Tiber river. The original phase of the bridge dates to the consulship of Gaius Claudius Nero in 206 B.C. The bridge is most famous as the site of a decisive battle between Maxentius and Constantine I fought in A.D. 312.

nodes.title: Ponte Mammolo
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Ponte Mammolo

nodes.title: Portus
nodes.description: The great ancient maritime port of Rome, located on the right-hand bank of the Tiber river.

nodes.title: Praeneste
nodes.description: An ancient city of central Italy, the eighth and seventh century B.C. origins of which demonstrate high-level trade contact with the Eastern Mediterranean world. The city withdrew from the Latin League (499 B.C.) and opposed Rome in the Latin war; Cincinnatus eventually subdued Praeneste. Sulla founded a new colony there in the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Prati Fiscali
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Prati Fiscali

nodes.title: Prima Porta
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B1 Prima Porta

nodes.title: Priscilla
nodes.description: A Christian catacomb within an ancient quarry on the Via Salaria that was in use from the second until the fourth centuries AD. The Catacomb of Priscilla was likely named for Priscilla, a member of the gens Acilia, and contains the oldest known Marian painting (third century AD).

nodes.title: Quintilii
nodes.description: A suburban villa built by Sextus Quintilius Maximus and Sextus Quintilius Condianus (consuls in A.D. 151).

nodes.title: Quintilio Varo
nodes.description: A villa located near the sanctuary of Madonna di Quintiliolo (Tivoli) that is traditionally associated with Quintilius Varus. The remains of the basis villae may date as early as the third century B.C.

nodes.title: Robigo?, T.
nodes.description: The sanctuary of the god Robigus, located at the sixth mile of the Via Cassia. The Romans celebrated the festival of Robigalia on 25 April.

nodes.title: Roma
nodes.description: The capital of the Roman Republic and Empire.

nodes.title: La Rustica
nodes.description: La Rustica was a Latin site located along the Via Collatina.

nodes.title: Sacer Mons
nodes.description: Sacer Mons is a hill on the banks of the Anio river and is connected, traditionally, with the episode of the secession of the Roman plebs of 494 BC.

nodes.title: Salinae
nodes.description: Salt pans located to the east of Ostia and to the north-east of Portus around the Tiber river estuary.

nodes.title: S. Agnese
nodes.description: A titular church on the Via Nomentana, S. Agnese houses the remains of the eponymous saint. The present church was built by Pope Honorius I in the seventh century AD, on the site of a fourth century basilica built by Constantine I.

nodes.title: S. Alessandro
nodes.description: The basilica and catacombs of S. Alessandro are located at the seventh milestone of the Via Nomentana.

nodes.title: S. Callisto
nodes.description: A large catacomb on the Via Appia south of Rome notable especially for its so-called 'Crypt of the Popes'. The catacomb covers approximately 15 hectares.

nodes.title: S. Ermete
nodes.description: S. Ermete is the site of a Paleochristian basilica and catacomb; the catacombs are also referred to as the Catacombs of Bassilla, and both names occur in the documentary sources.

nodes.title: S. Laurentius
nodes.description: The Papal Basilica of Saint Lawrence outside the Walls (Basilica Papale di San Lorenzo fuori le Mura) is one of the Seven Pilgrim Churches of Rome. The basilica serves as the shrine and tomb dedicated to Saint Lawrence and its earliest phases likely belong to the fourth century AD.

nodes.title: S. Lidano
nodes.description: The so-called "Archi di San Lidano" are the remains of a Roman stone bridge in the Pontine plain, near the modern locality of Sezze Scalo. The bridge likely dates originally to the second century B.C.

nodes.title: SS. Marcellino e Pietro
nodes.description: The church of Saints Marcellinus and Peter is a Roman Catholic church located on the Via Merulana in Rome. Pope Siricius built the original church in the fourth century A.D., close to the catacombs of Marcellinus and Peter. The relics of the saints were deposited in the church in 1256.

nodes.title: S. Maria di Galeria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B1 S. Maria di Galeria

nodes.title: S. Passera
nodes.description: S. Passera is a Christian church on the Tiber river in Rome, opposite the Basilica of Saint Paul Outside the Walls. The current church dates to the ninth century and incorporated the remains of a Roman tomb. The church is traditionally connected to a community of local miners.

nodes.title: S. Paulus
nodes.description: One of Rome's four major papal basilicae, S. Paulus was founded by Constantine I in the early fourth century A.D. and expanded by Valentinian I in the 370s.

nodes.title: S. Petrus
nodes.description: The Basilica of St. Peter in Vatican City; currently a Renaissance edifice standing on the site of Old St. Peter's Basilica, a church built by Constantine I between AD 319 and 333. The holy site is located on the Mons Vaticanus in connection with the purported site of the burial of the Christian Saint Peter. (cited: BAtlas 43 B2 S. Petrus)

nodes.title: S. Scholastica
nodes.description: A convent founded within the area of the Villa Neronis (BAtlas 43 E2 S. Scholastica)

nodes.title: S. Sebastianus
nodes.description: S. Sebastianus (San Sebastiano fuori le mura) is a Christian basilica outside the walls of Rome; the earliest phase belongs to the fourth century AD.

nodes.title: S. Sinforosa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 S. Sinforosa

nodes.title: S. Valentino
nodes.description: A Christian catacomb along the Via Flaminia dedicated to S. Valentino.

nodes.title: Satricum
nodes.description: An ancient settlement on the right bank of the river Astura, Satricum has a mixed heritage of Latins and Volscians. In 499 B.C. Satricum was a member of the Latin League, but was under Volscian control in 488 B.C. The site is noted for its sanctuary of Mater Matuta.

nodes.title: Saxa Rubra
nodes.description: Saxa Rubra (modern Grottarossa) is the name of a road station on the Via Flaminia nine Roman miles from the center of ancient Rome. It was at Saxa Rubra that Constantine I defeated Maxentius in A.D. 312.

nodes.title: Mausoleum of Caecilia Metella
nodes.description: A tomb on the Via Appia south of Rome belonging to Caecilia Metella, a daughter of Metellus Creticus. She was born ca. 100 BC. In 1303 the tomb was incorporated into the Castrum Caetani, serving as the main tower of the fortification.

nodes.title: Sep. Geta
nodes.description: A Roman tomb along the Via Appia that is traditionally believed to be that of Publius Septimius Geta, the younger son of Septimius Severus.

nodes.title: Serrone di Bove
nodes.description: The small hill known as "Il Poggio di Serrone di Bove" is located in the hinterland of ancient Norba and was the site of settlement activity. Architectural remains on the site include those of a polygonal masonry substruction or platform as well as an ancient roadway.

nodes.title: Setia
nodes.description: A Volscian settlement of the fifth century B.C. that became a Latin colony in 382 B.C.

nodes.title: Sette Bassi
nodes.description: A large, suburban villa complex on the Via Tuscolana. The villa was in use from the reign of Antoninus Pius until the fourth century A.D.

nodes.title: Settebagni
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Settebagni

nodes.title: Settecamini
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Settecamini

nodes.title: Signia
nodes.description: A city of Latium Adjectum established as a Latin colony ca. 494 B.C.

nodes.title: Simbruina Stagna
nodes.description: A series of three artificial lakes created along the river Anio.

nodes.title: Solforata
nodes.description: At Solforata along the Via Ardeatina activity related to the extraction of sulfur has been identified.

nodes.title: La Storta
nodes.description: A station on the Via Cassia attested in an inscription dated to A.D. 379-383.

nodes.title: Sublanuvio
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 Sublanuvio

nodes.title: Sublaqueum
nodes.description: An ancient settlement, located at modern Subiaco in Italy, Sublaqueum was located in the territory of the Aequi that was annexed by Rome in 304 B.C.

nodes.title: Tiberis (river)
nodes.description: The Tiber river is the third-longest river of the Italian peninsula, flowing 406 km (252 mi) from the Apennine Mountains to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

nodes.title: Tibur
nodes.description: A Sabine town, 30 km east-north-east of Rome, Tibur was the seat of the Tiburtine Sibyl.

nodes.title: Tomba degli Orazi e Curiazi
nodes.description: A Roman tomb near Albano Laziale connected in tradition with the story of the contest between the Horatii and Curiatii.

nodes.title: Tomb of Vibius Marianus
nodes.description: An imperial Roman tomb of Publius Vibius Marianus, erroneously identified as the Tomba di Nerone (Tomb of Nero) by G. B. Piranesi.

nodes.title: Tor Angela
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Tor Angela

nodes.title: Tor Marancia
nodes.description: The modern toponym Tor Marancia is claimed to derive from the Praedium Amaranthianus, a villa belonging to the second-century A.D. freedman Amaranthus.

nodes.title: Il Torraccio
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Il Torraccio

nodes.title: Il Torraccio
nodes.description: A circular mausoleum dating to the Late Republican period along the Via Praenestina.

nodes.title: Il Torraccio
nodes.description: The so-called "Il Torraccio (1)" is the cement core of a Roman tomb located at the twelfth milestone of the Via Appia Nuova, on the left side.

nodes.title: Torre Pascolaro (settlement)
nodes.description: A Final Bronze Age settlement of four to five hectares in South Etruria.

nodes.title: Tredici Altari
nodes.description: A Latin federal sanctuary at Lavinium, consisting of a series of altars that range in date from the sixth to the second century BC and a sacred site (or heroon) connected with the hero Aeneas.

nodes.title: Trerus/Tolerus (river)
nodes.description: A river of central Italy and a right tributary of the Liris.

nodes.title: Tres Tabernae
nodes.description: A statio at the point where the Via Appia crosses the Via Ninfina.

nodes.title: Tusculum
nodes.description: Tusculum was a Latin city of the Alban Hills in central Italy. After 381 BC Tusculum became the first "municipium cum suffragio".

nodes.title: Valvisciolo
nodes.description: An Iron Age settlement and necropolis located in the Monti Lepini near the abbey of Valvisciolo, characterized by polygonal masonry terrace walls. While the ancient name of the site is unknown, various proposals have been raised, including Sulmo (Savignoni, Mengarelli) and Pometia (Ogilvie). The settlement corresponds to the Latial II B phase and occupation ends ca. the late sixth century B.C.

nodes.title: Varia
nodes.description: Varia (modern Vicovaro) was a settlement of the Sabines.

nodes.title: Veii
nodes.description: An important city of South Etruria located north-northwest of Rome, Veii was eventually sacked by the Romans in 396 B.C. The ancient city covered some 180 ha.

nodes.title: Velitrae
nodes.description: Velitrae (modern Velletri) was an ancient Volscian settlement. In the Roman Republican period, Velitrae was attacked by Marcus Furius Camillus (379 B.C.) and again by Cincinnatus (377 B.C.); the Romans controlled the site by 365 B.C. The gens Octavia hailed from the city and a youthful Octavian spent time there.

nodes.title: Agora of Athens
nodes.description: The marketplace of the ancient city of Athens in Greece.

nodes.title: Stoa of Zeus (Eleutherios)
nodes.description: The Stoa of Zeus Eleutherios was built on the west side of the Agora of Athens between 430-425 BC, in honor of Zeus "of Freedom"; the stoa, Doric in its external order, housed the shields of Athenians who had died fighting for the city.

nodes.title: Theater of Dionysus Eleuthereus
nodes.description: Theatre on the south slope of the Acropolis in Athens.

nodes.title: Caerleon Roman amphitheatre
nodes.description: Amphitheatre of the legionary fortress at Caerleon

nodes.title: Altar of Hieron II
nodes.description: A monumental altar built around the third century B.C. that was probably dedicated to Zeus Eleutherios. Remains of the altar are located in the archaeological area of Neapolis in Syracuse, Sicily.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Monte Sant'Angelo
nodes.description: A Catholic sanctuary on Mount Gargano, in northern Apulia, Italy. Listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011.

nodes.title: Santa Sofia
nodes.description: A Longobard church in Benevento, Italy, listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011.

nodes.title: House of Meleager
nodes.description: The so-called "House of Meleager" (VI.9.2) is a domus in Pompeii of the "Samnite" type that was excavated first in 1829, then again in 1836 and 1966. The interior boasts rich painted decoration corresponding to Mau's first, third, and fourth styles.

nodes.title: Thodasa
nodes.description: An unlocated community which was close to, and eventually entered into sympolitiea with, Kildara.

nodes.title: Great Dam of Ma'rib
nodes.description: The Great Dam of Ma'rib dates originally to the eighth century BC and was connected with the Sabaean and Himyarite kingdoms around Ma'rib.

nodes.title: Temple of Zeus Lepsinos at Euromus
nodes.description: The Temple of Zeus Lepsinos at Euromus is located southeast of the ancient settlement. The well-preserved Corinthian temple dates to the reign of Hadrian.

nodes.title: Via Triumphalis necropolis
nodes.description: A segment of an imperial necropolis preserved along a portion of a consular road on the Vatican Hill. The Via Triumphalis necropolis was uncovered during the construction of a parking structure in the Via del Pellegrino.

nodes.title: Libraries' Courtyard at Hadrian's Villa
nodes.description: The Libraries' Courtyard belongs to the republican period and is one of the most ancient gardens at Hadrian's Villa. It is enclosed in a large peristyle 48 m wide, 72 m long, and is located at the northern end of Villa Adriana.

nodes.title: Ionian League
nodes.description: An Ancient Greek confederation originally formed in the sixth century BCE by twelve Ionian cities, with religious festivals celebrated at Panionia.

nodes.title: Porte de France, Nemausus
nodes.description: A first century B.C. city gate of ancient Nemausus.

nodes.title: Scarborough Castle
nodes.description: The ruins of a medieval castle built ca. A.D. 1135 by William le Gros, Earl of Albemarle. Now an English Heritage site.

nodes.title: Roman signal station at Scarborough
nodes.description: A Roman signal station dating from ca. A.D. 370. Comprising a ditch, an inner wall with bastions, and a signal tower, it was used until the early fifth century.

nodes.title: Byrsa
nodes.description: Walled citadel in Carthage built in the early first millennium BCE. The site was destroyed during the Third Punic War in 146 BCE by the forces of Scipio Aemilianus. The hill became the site of the city's forum in the Roman period.

nodes.title: Theater at Telmessos
nodes.description: The ancient theater at Telmessos (Fethiye) dates to the reign of Augustus.

nodes.title: Büyükkale
nodes.description: The royal citadel of Hattusa.

nodes.title: So-called Temple 1 at Hattusa
nodes.description: Temple 1, also referred to as the "Great Temple", is located in the lower city of Hattusa. It dates to the thirteenth century B.C.

nodes.title: Temple of the Severan family
nodes.description: Near a complex of baths built under Commodus a Severan complex that included a plaza, porticoes, and a temple dedicated to the Severan family was added.

nodes.title: Macellum of Sagalassos
nodes.description: The Roman Macellum of Sagalassos.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Italica
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Italica could accommodate 3,000 spectators. It predates the Hadrianic rebuilding of the city.

nodes.title: Maiden Tower (Baku)
nodes.description: A twelfth-century monument in the Old City, Baku, Azerbaijan.

nodes.title: Lyceum
nodes.description: The seat of Aristotle's Peripatetic school of philosophy at Athens founded in 335/4 B.C. The Lyceum was destroyed by Sulla in 86 B.C.

nodes.title: Walls of Caerwent (Venta Silurum)
nodes.description: The city walls of Venta Silurum (modern Caerwent) are among the best-preserved Roman period city walls in Britain. The walls were constructed around the 3rd century CE, augmenting an earlier earthwork defense system, with external towers added in the mid 4th century.

nodes.title: Porte Noire (Besançon)
nodes.description: A Gallo-Roman triumphal arch dedicated to Marcus Aurelius.

nodes.title: Jewry Wall
nodes.description: The so-called "Jewry Wall" is a substantial segment of surviving Roman masonry at Ratae.

nodes.title: Aldborough Studforth Hill
nodes.description: Archaeological remains at 'Aldborough Studforth Hill' site may be the location of possible Roman amphitheater.

nodes.title: Cardiff Castle
nodes.description: Cardiff Castle incorporates remains of the antecedent Roman fort.

nodes.title: Roman temple of Vic
nodes.description: The Roman temple of Vic dates to the second century A.D.

nodes.title: Teatro Romano de Regina
nodes.description: The Roman theater at Regina, now Badajoz, Spain.

nodes.title: Eastern theater at Laodicea ad Lycum
nodes.description: Digitized by hand in Google Earth in July 2012 at an eye altitude of 683m. Dates are general for the settlement, following Foss and Mitchell in BAtlas 65.

nodes.title: Verulamium Roman theater
nodes.description: The Roman Theatre at Verulamium, St. Albans was begun around the middle of the second century and continues in use until the fourth century.

nodes.title: Briteiros
nodes.description: The Citânia de Briteiros is an archaeological site of the Castro culture located in the northwestern part of the Iberian Peninsula.

nodes.title: Burbida/Bonisana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 C2 Burbida/Bonisana

nodes.title: Caelionicco/Coloricum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F4 Caelionicco/Coloricum

nodes.title: Cale
nodes.description: Cale was the site of an ancient city located at the mouth of the Durius fl. The Roman colony Portus Cale was established there in 136 BC.

nodes.title: Callaeci Bracari
nodes.description: The Callaeci Bracari formed part of a large Celtic tribal federation that inhabited Gallaecia, a region roughly corresponding to what is now Galicia (Spain).

nodes.title: Callaeci Lucenses
nodes.description: The Callaeci Lucenses formed part of a large Celtic tribal federation that inhabited Gallaecia, a region roughly corresponding to what is now Galicia (Spain).

nodes.title: Callaecia
nodes.description: Callaecia was a Roman province and an early Medieval kingdom in north-west Hispania.

nodes.title: Capera
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 E4 Capera

nodes.title: Conimbriga
nodes.description: Conimbriga was a Celtic and Roman settlement in Portugal that was inhabited between the ninth century BC and the seventh century AD.

nodes.title: Durius (river)
nodes.description: The Douro (or Duero) river is the third longest river of the Iberian Peninsula behind the Tagus and Ebro.

nodes.title: Elbocoris
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 D4 Elbocoris

nodes.title: Gigia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F1 Gigia

nodes.title: Glandimirum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 C2 Glandimirum

nodes.title: Intercatia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F3 Intercatia

nodes.title: Langobriga
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 C4 Langobriga

nodes.title: Legio VII Gemina
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F2 Legio VII Gemina

nodes.title: Lucus Augusti
nodes.description: Lucus Augusti (Lugo, Spain). The Roman walls of the city were listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000.

nodes.title: Minius (river)
nodes.description: Minius fl. (modern Minho River) is a river of Galicia in the Iberian peninsula. Its ancient name likely derives from minius, the Latin term for cinnabar, and thus its name is, essentially, 'red river'.

nodes.title: Monte Mozinho
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 C3 Monte Mozinho

nodes.title: Nelo/Nabios (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 D1 Nelo/Nabios fl.

nodes.title: Nemetobriga
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 D2 Nemetobriga

nodes.title: Neri
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 B2 Neri

nodes.title: Nerion/Artabrum/Celticum/Magnum Pr.
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 B1 Nerion/Artabrum/Celticum/Magnum Pr.

nodes.title: Ocelum Duri
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F3 Ocelum Duri

nodes.title: Palantia
nodes.description: The chief town of the Vaccaei in the northern part of Hispania Tarraconensis.

nodes.title: Preterion
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F3 Preterion

nodes.title: El Raso
nodes.description: A fortified settlement of the Vettones located in the municipality of Candeleda (Ávila, Spain) near the hamlet of El Raso. Archaeological remains at the site consist of several walled enclosures distributed in at least three areas covering some 20 ha.

nodes.title: Salmantica
nodes.description: Salmantica (modern Salamanca) was an indigenous Celtic center before falling to the Carthaginians and, later, the Romans.

nodes.title: S. Chuís
nodes.description: A Pre-Roman hillfort in the Asturias region, near the northern coast of the Iberian peninsula. The fort was constructed around 1000 BCE and remained in use throughout the Iron Age and shows signs of occupation during the Roman period through the third century CE.

nodes.title: Segovia
nodes.description: Segovia, originally of Celtiberian origin, became a Roman settlement. It is perhaps the site where Metellus defeated Hirtuleius, the general of Sertorius, in 75 B.C.

nodes.title: Sentice
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F4 Sentice

nodes.title: Sibaris/Sabaria/Sarabis
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F3 Sibaris/Sabaria/Sarabis

nodes.title: Siccae (islands)
nodes.description: Siccae Inss. (the Cíes Islands) an archipelago off the coast of Pontevedra, Spain.

nodes.title: Talabriga
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 C4 Talabriga

nodes.title: Turduli Veteres
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 C3 Turduli Veteres

nodes.title: Vaccaei
nodes.description: The Vaccaei were a Celtic tribe of the Durius river valley.

nodes.title: Vettonia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 E4 Vettonia

nodes.title: Vicus Aquarius
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F3 Vicus Aquarius

nodes.title: Segovia aqueduct
nodes.description: Supplied Segovia with water from mountains to the southeast

nodes.title: Roman Bridge (Chaves)
nodes.description: A Roman bridge over the river Tâmega at Aquae Flaviae (modern Chaves, Portugal).

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 unlocated Kambaiton

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 unlocated Oktodouron

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 unlocated Phoros Narbason
