nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 unlocated Pinetum

nodes.title: Valabriga
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 unlocated *Valabriga

nodes.title: Andelos
nodes.description: A Roman settlement in Spain

nodes.title: Aquae Terebellicae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 D2 Aquae Terebellicae

nodes.title: Aquae Voconiae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H4 Aquae Voconiae

nodes.title: Aquitani
nodes.description: A confederation of a number (?20) of Iberian tribes initially subjugated by P. Licinius Crassus in 56 BC.

nodes.title: Arevaci
nodes.description: The Arevaci were a pre-Roman Celtic tribe of northern Hispania who dominated most of Celtiberia from the fourth to late second centuries BC.

nodes.title: Atur(r)us (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 D2 Atur(r)us fl.

nodes.title: Auscii
nodes.description: The Auscii were an ancient tribe of Aquitania and submitted to Caesar's legate in 56 BC.

nodes.title: Ausetani
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H4 Ausetani

nodes.title: Auso
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H4 Auso

nodes.title: Baetulo
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H4 Baetulo

nodes.title: Bele(g)ia/Veleia
nodes.description: Bele(g)ia/Veleia (Iruña-Veleia) was a Roman town along the ab Asturica Burdigalam road.

nodes.title: Berà
nodes.description: A Roman triumphal arch dedicated ca. 13 BC by Lucius Licinius Sura and perhaps dedicated to Augustus.

nodes.title: Birra (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H2 Birra fl.

nodes.title: Blanda(e)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H4 Blanda(e)

nodes.title: Calagurris (Nassica) Iulia
nodes.description: Calagurris (Nassica) Iulia (modern Calahorra, Spain) was conquered by Rome in 187 BC and later supported Quintus Sertorius in his war against Cn. Pompeius Magnus.

nodes.title: Celtiberia
nodes.description: Celtiberia was inhabited by Celtic-speaking tribes of the Hallstatt culture in the latter first millennium BC. Some attested tribal names include the Arevaci, Belli, Titti, Lusones, and Berones.

nodes.title: Cervaria
nodes.description: A promontory on the Mediterranean coast of modern France, at the Spanish border. It was described by Pomponius Mela as marking "the boundary of Gallia" in Roman times. Modern Cap Cerbère.

nodes.title: Clodianus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H3 Clodianus fl.

nodes.title: Cocosates (Sexsignani)
nodes.description: A pre-Roman tribe that settled in what today is southwestern France, to the north of the river Adour. They were bounded by the Tarbelli to the south and the Boiates to the north.

nodes.title: Col. Barcino
nodes.description: Colonia Iulia Augusta Paterna Faventia Barcino (Barcelona) was a Roman settlement in Tarraconensis founded by Augustus.

nodes.title: Col. Caesaraugusta
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 E4 Col. Caesaraugusta

nodes.title: Col. Clunia (Sulpicia)
nodes.description: Col. Clunia (Sulpicia) was a Roman city of Hispania Tarraconensis. The site was besieged by Cn. Pompeius Magnus during the war against Sertorius.

nodes.title: Col. Narbo Martius
nodes.description: Col. Narbo Martius (modern Narbonne) was established in Gaul in 118 B.C. as a Roman colony.

nodes.title: Col. Ruscino
nodes.description: Col. Ruscino was an Iberian oppidum and town of Narbonese Gaul.

nodes.title: Col. Tarraco
nodes.description: An Iberian site in contact with Greek and Phoenician merchants that became a major Roman center from the third century BC onward.

nodes.title: Complutum
nodes.description: Complutum was an ancient oppidum founded in the first century A.D. and largely re-fashioned in the third century A.D.

nodes.title: Condatomagus?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 I1 Condatomagus?

nodes.title: Deciana
nodes.description: Deciana is an important pass through the Pyrenees. The ancient Roman Via Augusta passes through Deciana.

nodes.title: Egara
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H4 Egara

nodes.title: Egir(i)cius (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 F2 Egir(i)cius fl.

nodes.title: Elimberrum
nodes.description: Elimberrum was the capital of the civitas of the Auscii.

nodes.title: Elusa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 F2 Elusa

nodes.title: Gerunda
nodes.description: A settlement of Tarraconensis located at the confluence of the Ter and the Onyar rivers, Gerunda was the chief town of the Gerundenses.

nodes.title: La Graufesenque
nodes.description: La Graufesenque is the name of an archaeological site located in southern France at the point of the confluence of the Tarn and Dourbie rivers. The archaeological site is across the river valley from Millau, known in antiquity at Condatomagus. The site was famous for its large-scale production of high quality red terra sigillata pottery. This was produced in enormous quantities and exported across the western Roman world. Production of this type began in the reign of Augustus.

nodes.title: (H)Iberus (river)
nodes.description: The Ebro river in Spain.

nodes.title: Hispanum/(H)Ibericum Mare
nodes.description: Hispanum/(H)Ibericum Mare (The Balearic Sea)

nodes.title: Iac(c)a
nodes.description: Iac(c)a was a town of the Vascones in Hispania Tarraconensis.

nodes.title: Imus Pyreneus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 D2 Imus Pyreneus

nodes.title: Indigetes
nodes.description: A pre-Roman, Iberian people known primarily through their coinage, which bears the inscription "UNTIKESKEN" (q.v.). They seem to have occupied an area in the northeast of the Iberian peninsula, included the coastal area between the Muga and Fluvià rivers.

nodes.title: It(o)uris(s)a/Turissa
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 D3 It(o)uris(s)a/Turissa

nodes.title: Laeetania
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H4 Laeetania

nodes.title: Lugdunum Convenarum
nodes.description: Lugdunum Convenarum (modern Saint-Bertrand-de-Comminges) was founded by Cnaeus Pompeius as a Roman colony in 72 BC. The site defended the Aran valley and the approaches to Iberia.

nodes.title: El Mèdol
nodes.description: A Roman limestone quarry that served Tarraco and is now included in the UNESCO World Heritage listing.

nodes.title: Moysiacum
nodes.description: A place mentioned in passing in the Vita of Saint Desiderius. Modern scholars have identified it with modern Moissac in southern France where there are significant Merovingian and later medieval remains, some of which overlie structures of late Roman date.

nodes.title: Neroua (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 C2 Neroua fl.

nodes.title: Pompei Tropaea
nodes.description: In 71 BC as Pompey returned to Italy from Iberia he set up a monument in the Pyrenees (near the Col de Panissars) known as the Pompei Tropaea. This monument commemorated the 876 cities Pompey had conquered.

nodes.title: Pompelo
nodes.description: Cn. Pompeius Magnus is considered to have been the founder of Pompelo (modern Pamplona) while on campaign against Sertorius in 75 BC.

nodes.title: Pyrenaei (mountains)
nodes.description: The Pyrenees Mountains separate the Iberian Peninsula from the rest of continental Europe. The mountain ranges extends from the Bay of Biscay to Cap de Creus, for an extent of 491 km (305 miles).

nodes.title: (S)Edetani
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 E4 (S)Edetani

nodes.title: Sotiates
nodes.description: A pre-Roman tribe of the Aquitani.

nodes.title: Suessetani
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 E3 Suessetani

nodes.title: Summus Pyreneus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 D2 Summus Pyreneus

nodes.title: Pian di Mola necropolis
nodes.description: A monumental rock-cut necropolis at Tuscania.

nodes.title: Terme della Regina
nodes.description: Terme della Regina, Tuscania (Italy).

nodes.title: Necropolis of Madonna d'olivo
nodes.description: An Etruscan necropolis located about 2 km south-west of Tuscania that overlooks valley of the Marta river. The necropolis takes its name from the adjacent Church of the Madonna dell’Olivo.

nodes.title: Forum of Lucus Feroniae
nodes.description: The forum of the Roman colony, Colonia Iulia felix Lucoferensis.

nodes.title: Temple of Divus Iulius
nodes.description: The temple on the Sacra Via dedicated to the deified Iulius Caesar, authorized in 42 B.C. and built by Augustus, with its dedication occurring on 18th August, 29 B.C.

nodes.title: Çatalhöyük west mound
nodes.description: Human settlement on the West Mound of Ҫatalhöyük began later than its eastern counterpart and continued longer. The mound is commonly associated with the Early Chalcolithic period, ca. 5,900-5,600 B.C.

nodes.title: Necropoli delle Pianacce
nodes.description: An Etruscan necropolis with tombs ranging in date from the sixth to the second centuries B.C. In 2003 the fourth-century painted tomb of the 'infernal quadriga' was discovered.

nodes.title: Tanakun
nodes.description: Tanakun is a fortified city in or bordering the northeastern part of Que. It is mentioned in royal inscriptions of the Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC).

nodes.title: Kasku (region)
nodes.description: A region in northeastern Anatolia mentioned in second- and first-millennium-BC Assyrian and Hittite sources.

nodes.title: Til-karme
nodes.description: Til-karme is a city in Gurgum that is mentioned in an inscription of the Assyrian king Tiglath-pileser III (r. 744-727 BC).

nodes.title: Paqarhubuni (settlement)
nodes.description: Paqarhubuni is a city that was part of Bīt-Adini during the reign of the Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC); it might have been part of Bīt-Agūsi while Adad-nērārī (r. 809-782 BC) was king of Assyria. The city and its surrounding region were between the kingdoms of Gurgum and Kummuhu.

nodes.title: Usian
nodes.description: A fortress in the vicinity of Til-garimmu fortified by the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) against Musku (Phrygia).

nodes.title: Lambaesis amphitheater
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater at Lambaesis.

nodes.title: Teleboas? (river)
nodes.description: Teleboas? fl. (the modern Karasu (Euphrates)) is a river of eastern Turkey and one of the sources of the Euphrates.

nodes.title: Thospia/Bouana/‘Ospa’
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 F2 Thospia/Bouana/‘Ospa’

nodes.title: Thospitis Limne
nodes.description: Lake Van, the largest lake in Asia Minor, is a saline soda lake.

nodes.title: Tili
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 D3 Tili

nodes.title: Zabdicene
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 D3 Zabdicene

nodes.title: Alexandria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 unlocated Alexandria

nodes.title: Amardos (river)
nodes.description: The Sefīd-Rūd river flows into the Caspian Sea at Rasht.

nodes.title: Caspium/Hyrcanium Mare
nodes.description: The Caspian Sea is a remnant of a larger, inland sea and is now the world's largest enclosed body of water. It has been classified as both a lake and as a sea.

nodes.title: Kyros (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 90 D1 Kyros fl.

nodes.title: Straton (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 90 G4 Straton fl.

nodes.title: Aballava
nodes.description: Roman fort, cited: BAtlas 9 D6 Aballava

nodes.title: (A)Esica
nodes.description: (A)Esica, also known as Great Chesters, was a fort on the line of Hadrian's Wall.

nodes.title: Alauna/Alione
nodes.description: A Roman fort at present-day Maryport. Part of Cumbrian coastal defenses.

nodes.title: Auchendavy
nodes.description: Site of Roman fort on the Antonine Wall.

nodes.title: Balmuildy Roman Fort
nodes.description: Balmuildy was the site of a Roman fort on the Antonine Wall in Scotland. This is one of only two Antonine Wall forts found to have stone ramparts.

nodes.title: Banna
nodes.description: The Roman fort at Banna, now known as Birdoswald Roman fort.

nodes.title: Bar Hill
nodes.description: The site of a Roman fort on the Antonine Wall.

nodes.title: Bearsden
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 9 C5 Bearsden

nodes.title: Bremenium
nodes.description: A Roman fort at present-day High Rochester.

nodes.title: B(r)ibra?
nodes.description: Roman fort at present-day Beckfoot. Part of the Cumbrian coastal defenses.

nodes.title: Brigantes
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 9 E6 Brigantes

nodes.title: *Brocolitia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 9 E5 *Brocolitia

nodes.title: Cadder
nodes.description: A fort on the Antonine Wall at Cadder.

nodes.title: *Camboglanna
nodes.description: A Roman fort of Hadrian's Wall, located between Banna (Birdoswald) to the east and Uxelodunum (Stanwix) to the west. It lies approximately 11 km west of Birdoswald and commands the Cambeck Valley.

nodes.title: Castlecary
nodes.description: Site of Roman fort on Antonine Wall.

nodes.title: Castlehill
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 9 C5 Castlehill

nodes.title: Cataractonium
nodes.description: The remains of a Roman fort and settlement located at Catterick, North Yorkshire.

nodes.title: Cilurnum
nodes.description: Cilurnum is the site of a fort dating to A.D. 123 on Hadrian's Wall that guarded a military bridge along the Roman road. It is now known as Chester's Roman Fort.

nodes.title: Clota (river)
nodes.description: The River Clyde, the eighth-longest river in the United Kingdom, flows into the Firth of Clyde.

nodes.title: Colani(c)a?
nodes.description: Probably to be associated with a complex of Roman forts at modern day Camelon, just to the north of the Antonine Wall.

nodes.title: Condercum
nodes.description: A fort on Hadrian's Wall.

nodes.title: Congavata
nodes.description: A Roman fort on Hadrian's Wall, cited: BAtlas 9 D6 ‘Congavata’

nodes.title: *Coriosopitum/Coria
nodes.description: A Roman town and fort at present-day Corbridge.

nodes.title: Crawford
nodes.description: Site of a small Roman fort between Castledykes and Tassiesholm. The fort was discovered in 1938 and excavated in 1961-66.

nodes.title: Croy Hill
nodes.description: The site of a Roman fort and fortlet on the Antonine Wall.

nodes.title: Duntocher
nodes.description: Roman fort on the Antonine Wall in West Dunbartonshire, Scotland.

nodes.title: Eburacum
nodes.description: The site of a Roman legionary fortress, municipium, and colonia at modern day York

nodes.title: Falkirk
nodes.description: The site of a Roman fort on the Antonine Wall.

nodes.title: Gabrosentum
nodes.description: A Roman fort at present-day Moresby that was a part of the Cumbrian coastal defenses.

nodes.title: Habitancum
nodes.description: A Roman fort at present-day Risingham.

nodes.title: (H)Ebudes (islands)
nodes.description: (H)Ebudes Inss. (Inner Hebrides), an archipelago off the west coast of Scotland.

nodes.title: Onnum
nodes.description: A fort on Hadrian's Wall known today as Halton Chesters.

nodes.title: Isurium
nodes.description: Isurium (modern Aldborough) was a Roman settlement - and likely fort - along Dere Street.

nodes.title: Kirkintilloch
nodes.description: Roman fort on the Antonine Wall, in East Dunbartonshire, Scotland

nodes.title: Longovicium
nodes.description: A Roman fort at present-day Lanchester.

nodes.title: Luguvalium
nodes.description: Luguvalium was a fortified Roman settlement in Britannia.

nodes.title: Magis?
nodes.description: A Roman fort at modern-day Burrow Walls, probably to be identified with the ancient toponym "Magis".

nodes.title: Magnis
nodes.description: Magnae Carvetiorum was a Roman fort on Hadrian's Wall. It lies to the south of the Roman vallum near the line of the Stanegate.

nodes.title: Maia
nodes.description: A Roman fort on Hadrian's Wall, cited: BAtlas 9 D6 Maia

nodes.title: *Manavia (island)
nodes.description: *Manavia Ins. (The Isle of Man) is an island in the Irish Sea between Britain and Ireland.

nodes.title: Mumrills
nodes.description: Mumrills was the site of the largest Roman fort on the Antonine Wall.

nodes.title: Navan
nodes.description: A ceremonial site of pre-Christian Gaelic Ireland and the capital of the Ulaid. The site consists of a fortified settlement with a ceremonial building.

nodes.title: Newton Kyme
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 9 F7 Newton Kyme

nodes.title: Old Kilpatrick
nodes.description: Old Kilpatrick is the site of the western terminal fort of the Antonine Wall.

nodes.title: Orcades (islands)
nodes.description: Orcades Inss. (The Orkney Islands), an archipelago of northern Scotland comprised of ca. 70 islands.

nodes.title: Ouedra/Adron (river)
nodes.description: Ouedra/Adron fl. flows eastward from the Pennines to the North Sea.

nodes.title: Piercebridge
nodes.description: A Roman fort, cited: BAtlas 9 F6 Piercebridge

nodes.title: Pons Aeli
nodes.description: The site of a Roman fort at Newcastle dating between the second and fourth centuries. The fort was perhaps designed to protect a bridge over the river Tyne.

nodes.title: Robogdion? Akron
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 9 A5 Robogdion? Akron

nodes.title: Rough Castle
nodes.description: A Roman fort on the Antonine Wall.

nodes.title: Scarborough
nodes.description: On Castle Hill, Scarborough, a Roman signal station was established ca. A.D. 370 that remained in use until the early fifth century. A medieval castle was established ca. A.D. 1135.

nodes.title: *Scitis
nodes.description: *Scitis (Isle of Skye) is the largest and northernmost large island in the Inner Hebrides of Scotland.

nodes.title: Seabegs Wood
nodes.description: Site of a Roman fortlet on the Antonine Wall

nodes.title: Segedunum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 9 F6 Segedunum

nodes.title: Tinea (river)
nodes.description: Tinea fl. (the River Tyne)

nodes.title: Trimontium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 9 E5 Trimontium

nodes.title: Uxelodu(nu)m
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 9 E6 Uxelodu(nu)m

nodes.title: Velunia(te)
nodes.description: A Roman fort associated with the Antonine Wall at modern day Carriden House. It does not lie on the Wall itself, but rather is 1.3 km to the south east of the Wall's eastern terminus at Bridgeness.

nodes.title: Verbeia (river)
nodes.description: The River Wharfe, located in northern England, flows from the Yorkshire Dales to join the River Ouse near Cawood.

nodes.title: *Vercovicium
nodes.description: A fort on Hadrian's Wall.

nodes.title: Vindolanda
nodes.description: A fort south of Hadrian's Wall and findspot of the Vindolanda Tablets.

nodes.title: Vindomora
nodes.description: A Roman fort at present-day Ebchester.

nodes.title: Vindovala
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 9 F6 Vindovala

nodes.title: Vinovia
nodes.description: Vinovia was a Roman fort, now known as Binchester Roman fort, established ca. A.D. 79 to guard the crossing of Dere Street on the River Wear.

nodes.title: Westerwood
nodes.description: The site of a Roman fort on the Antonine Wall.

nodes.title: Aborras/Chaboras (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 91 B2 Aborras/Chaboras fl.

nodes.title: Adiabene
nodes.description: Adiabene was an ancient kingdom in Assyria situated between the Upper Zab (Lycus) and the Lower Zab (Caprus) rivers. Its capital was at Arbela.

nodes.title: Anatho
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 91 C3 Anatho

nodes.title: Ashur/‘Lamban’?/‘Liba(nai)’?
nodes.description: Aššur, modern Qal'at Sherqat, is an Assyrian city on the western bank of the Tigris River. Named after its enigmatic tutelary deity, it was the original capital, ancestral home, and burial place of the Assyrian royal family. From the late third millennium B.C. until 614 B.C., when the city was captured and destroyed by the Medes, Aššur was Assyria's most important religious center. It was also Assyria's principal administrative center until the beginning of the ninth century, when Ashurnasirpal II (883-859) moved the capital to the newly constructed Calah.

nodes.title: Babylon
nodes.description: The ancient city of Babylon began as an Akkadian city-state founded by Amorites in 1894 B.C. The city was also the seat of the Neo-Babylonian Empire from 608 to 539 B.C.

nodes.title: Borsippa/Burs
nodes.description: An ancient city of Sumer southwest of Babylon on the east bank of the Euphrates.

nodes.title: Cutha
nodes.description: Kutha or Cutha (modern Tell Ibrahim) is located on the Upper Euphrates, north of Nippur and northeast of Babylon. The archaeological site consists of two tells. Archaeological evidence of the Neo-Babylonian period has been revealed by excavation.

nodes.title: ‘Diabas’/Turnat (river)
nodes.description: The Diyala River is a major tributary of the Tigris.

nodes.title: Dilbat
nodes.description: Ancient Dilbat was a minor Sumerian city southeast of Babylon on the eastern bank of the Western Euphrates river in modern-day Al-Qādisiyyah, Iraq.

nodes.title: D(o)ura/Europos
nodes.description: An ancient settlement on the Euphrates river in modern Syria.

nodes.title: Hindanu/Eddana
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 91 C3 Hindanu/Eddana

nodes.title: Nimrud
nodes.description: In the ninth century BC, Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883-859 BC) built himself a new administrative center. Kalhu (biblical Calah) — modern Nimrud, a site identified as Larissa, a city mentioned in Xenophon’s Anabasis — became the capital of the Assyrian Empire, replacing Ashur, which had served as Assyria’s capital since the third millennium BC. The city — which is located twenty miles south of the modern Mosul and which occupied a strategic position six miles north of the point where the Tigris River meets the Greater/Upper Zab — served as Assyria’s capital until the reign of Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC). Although Kalhu never again became the primary residence of Assyria’s kings, that city remained a vital administrative, military, and religious center until the fall of the Assyrian Empire.

nodes.title: Kish
nodes.description: Kish was an ancient city of Sumer located east of Babylon in Mesopotamia. Kish was occupied from the Jemdet Nasr period (ca. 3100 BC) until its abandonment under the Seleucids.

nodes.title: Me-Turnat
nodes.description: Me-Turnat was a Bronze Age and Iron Age settlement located on the Diyala river.

nodes.title: Opis
nodes.description: Opis was an ancient city of Babylonia located on the Tigris river close to the site of modern Baghdad.

nodes.title: Radani (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 91 F3 Radani fl.

nodes.title: Seleucia/Sliq Kharawta
nodes.description: Seleucia/Sliq Kharawta was a city founded on the Tigris river by Seleukos I Nikator.

nodes.title: Sippar
nodes.description: Sippar (or Zimbir) was an ancient city located on the east bank of the Euphrates river at the site of modern Tell Abu Habbah. In order to avoid confusing this site with its sister city of Sippar-Amnanum (Tell ed-Der), it is sometimes labeled as Sippar-Yahrurum.

nodes.title: Tell Babil
nodes.description: The so-called "Summer Palace of Nebuchadnezzar," located at ancient Babylon in modern Iraq.

nodes.title: Tell Mahuz
nodes.description: The site of Tell Mahuz site in northern Iraq was occupied from the fourth millennium B.C. to the Early Islamic Period.

nodes.title: Zabas Megas (river)
nodes.description: The Great Zab river originates near Lake Van and flows some 400 km until it joins the Tigris river.

nodes.title: Zabas Mikros/Kapros?/Zerbis? (river)
nodes.description: Zabas Mikros/Kapros?/Zerbis? fl. (Little Zab River) flows from the Zagros Mountains to the Tigris river.

nodes.title: Shams el-Din
nodes.description: The ancient settlement of Shams el-Din in Egypt's Kharga Oasis, which contains a necropolis and 4th century AD church.

nodes.title: Arderikka
nodes.description: A now unlocated site in Assyria located on the Euphrates river upstream from Babylon.

nodes.title: Gyndes (river)
nodes.description: The Gyndes was a river of Assyria and Susiana that is discussed by Herodotus. Its precise location can not be determined with certainty, but some scholars have identified it with the modern Diyala river in Iraq.

nodes.title: Korsote
nodes.description: Xenophon describes Korsote as a large city located in the desert to the south of the confluence of the Chaboras (Habur) and the Euphrates rivers. It is now unlocated.

nodes.title: Maskas (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 91 unlocated Maskas fl.

nodes.title: Phrygia
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 91 unlocated Phrygia

nodes.title: Deru/Beth Daraya/[Badra]
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 92 A3 Deru/Beth Daraya/[Badra]

nodes.title: Dezful/[Qantara al-Rum]
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 92 D4 Dezful/[Qantara al-Rum]

nodes.title: Iasonius (mountain)
nodes.description: A mountain mentioned by Strabo, Ptolemy, and Ammianus. It is probably to be identified with Mount Damāvand in modern Iran.

nodes.title: Tiber Island
nodes.description: An island in the Tiber River at the site of Rome.

nodes.title: Balikh River
nodes.description: The Balikh River that flows from 'Ayn al-'Arus in Syria to the Euphrates river.

nodes.title: Sa Femina Nuraghe
nodes.description: A poorly preserved, single-tower nuraghe located near Olmedo, Sardinia.

nodes.title: San Vitale
nodes.description: The basilica of Saints Vitalis, Valeris, Gervase and Protase, commonly known as the Basilica di San Vitale, is a titular minor basilica church in Rome. The church was built ca. AD 400 by Pope Innocent I.

nodes.title: Van Fortress
nodes.description: Van Fortress is an ancient citadel of Urartu built during the ninth through seventh centuries BC.

nodes.title: Stadium at Epidaurus
nodes.description: This stadium, constructed in a natural depression near Epidaurus, was part of the sanctuary of Asclepius, the god of medicine and healing, and housed athletic contests in honor of the god. It dates to the fourth century B.C.

nodes.title: Bizye Roman amphitheater
nodes.description: A Roman amphitheater in eastern Thrace.

nodes.title: Southwark
nodes.description: An extensive Roman settlement located on the south bank of the river Thames opposite Londinium.

nodes.title: Bronze Age Barrow at Old Winchester Hill
nodes.description: A number of Bronze Age barrow tombs are found within the general area of the Iron Age hill fort.

nodes.title: Civitavecchia di Arpino
nodes.description: The fortified acropolis of the ancient city of Arpinum.

nodes.title: Beaumont-sur-Oise amphitheater
nodes.description: The Beaumont-sur-Oise Gallo-Roman amphitheater.

nodes.title: Baths of Caracalla (Albano Laziale)
nodes.description: Public baths generally dated to the reign of Caracalla.

nodes.title: Tell el-Borg
nodes.description: Fortified site dated to the New Kingdom located on the eastern frontier of Egypt, just into the Sinai Peninsula.

nodes.title: Qasr al-Lebekha
nodes.description: A late-Roman fort at Ain Labakha/Lebekha in Egypt's Kharga Oasis

nodes.title: Alpes Graiae et Poeninae (late Roman province)
nodes.description: The post-Diocletianic province of Alpes Graiae et Poeninae according to the Verona List (ca. AD 303-324). It was assigned to the diocese of Galliae.

nodes.title: Germania Superior
nodes.description: Germania Superior was a province of the Roman empire.

nodes.title: Asiane (Byzantine diocese)
nodes.description: Byzantine diocese

nodes.title: Pontike
nodes.description: The Diocese of Pontus was a diocese of the later Roman Empire. It was established in 314. Justinian would abolish the diocese in 535/6, only to re-establish it in 548. This diocese would continue to function until it was replaced by the themata of Armeniakon and Opsikion in the seventh century.

nodes.title: Anatolike
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 F5 Anatolike

nodes.title: Europe

nodes.title: Haimimontos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 E3 no. 4 (Haimimontos)

nodes.title: Palaia Epeiros
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 D4 no. 12 (Palaia Epeiros)

nodes.title: Lykia
nodes.description: The Late antique province of Lykia (BAtlas 102 E4 no. 28)

nodes.title: Karia (late Roman province)
nodes.description: Karia was a geographic region of the Roman Empire whose territory belonged to the province of Asia. As a part of the Diocletianic reforms, Karia was subdivided into smaller units. It again became a separate province as part of the Diocese of Asia.

nodes.title: Honorias
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 F3 no. 32 (Honorias)

nodes.title: Galatia I
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 F3 no. 34 (Galatia I)

nodes.title: Galatia Saloutaria
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 F4 no. 35 (Galatia Saloutaria)

nodes.title: Kappadokia I
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 F4 no. 36 (Kappadokia I)

nodes.title: Kappadokia II
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 F4 no. 37 (Kappadokia II)

nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 G3 no. 38 (Helenopontos)

nodes.title: Pontos Polemoniakos
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 G3 no. 39 (Pontos Polemoniakos)

nodes.title: Armenia I
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 G4 no. 40 (Armenia I)

nodes.title: Armenia II
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 G4 no. 41 (Armenia II)

nodes.title: Euphratesia
nodes.description: Euphratesia was as a Roman province of Greater Syria and a part of the late Roman Diocese of the East. Around AD 341 the province was created from the territory of Syria Coele.

nodes.title: Palaestina I (late Roman province)
nodes.description: The late Roman province of Palaestina Prima, established during the 4th century, incorporated the region of central Palestine. Its capital was Caesarea.

nodes.title: Palaestina II (late Roman province)
nodes.description: The late Roman province of Palaestina Secunda, established during the 4th century, comprised the region of northern Palestine, including Galilee and the southern Golan Plateau. Its capital was Skythopolis.

nodes.title: Palaestina III (late Roman province)
nodes.description: The late Roman province of Palaestina Tertia, or Palaestina Salutaris, was founded during the 4th century CE. The province comprised Southern Transjordan and the Negev. Its capital was Petra.

nodes.title: (H)Adriaticum/Superum Mare
nodes.description: A body of water separating the Apennine Peninsula of Italy from the Balkan Peninsula.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Lugdunum → Castra Herculis? → (Ulpia) Noviomagus

nodes.title: Cimbri
nodes.description: A Germanic tribe that made war against the Roman Republic between 113 and 101 BC.

nodes.title: Flevum Ostium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 10 unlocated Flevum Ostium

nodes.title: Hispania
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 1 B2 Hispania

nodes.title: Ibericum Mare
nodes.description: The westernmost portion of the Mediterranean Sea, lying between the Iberian Peninsula and North Africa.

nodes.title: Internum Mare
nodes.description: The Mediterranean Sea or Mare Nostrum is a sea connected to the Atlantic Ocean that is surrounded almost completely by land.

nodes.title: Ionium Mare
nodes.description: The Ionian Sea, located south of the Adriatic Sea, is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea.

nodes.title: Italia
nodes.description: The Italian peninsula extending northward to the Alps as recognized by the Romans.

nodes.title: Agedincum
nodes.description: A settlement located at the Yonne-Vanne confluence in the territory of the Senones.

nodes.title: Ambiani
nodes.description: The Ambiani were an ancient Belgic people.

nodes.title: Andethanna
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of the Treveri. Modern Niederanven in Luxembourg.

nodes.title: Aquae Mattiacorum
nodes.description: Aquae Mattiacorum (modern Wiesbaden) was the capital of the Civitas Mattiacorum.

nodes.title: Ara Ubiorum/Col. Claudia Ara Agrippinensium
nodes.description: Ara Ubiorum/Col. Claudia Ara Agrippinensium (Cologne, Germany) was a key site of the Germanic Ubii that became a Roman colony in the first century AD. The city served as the capital of Germania Inferior.

nodes.title: Argentorate
nodes.description: Argentorate (modern Strasbourg, France) was established perhaps ca. 12 BC by Nero Claudius Drusus as a Roman outpost in Germania Superior.

nodes.title: Asciburgium
nodes.description: An auxiliary outpost in Germania Inferior where the Ala Primae Tungrorum was based until the site was destroyed by the Batavi ca. AD 70.

nodes.title: Atrebates
nodes.description: The Atrebates were a Belgic tribe of Gaul and Britain prior to the Roman conquest. In Gallia Belgica, they inhabited the Artois region.

nodes.title: Atuatuca
nodes.description: Atuatuca (modern Tongeren, Belgium) was also known as Aduatuca Tungrorum or Atuatuca Tongrorum and served as the capital of the Civitas Tungrorum.

nodes.title: [Augusta] Ambianorum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 B2 [Augusta] Ambianorum

nodes.title: Augusta Suessionum
nodes.description: Augusta Suessionum (modern Soissons) was a Gallic site captured by Iulius Caesar and re-established as a Roman city.

nodes.title: Augustobona
nodes.description: Augustobona Tricassium stood at a key highway hub on the Via Agrippa.

nodes.title: Augustomagus
nodes.description: Augustomagus (modern Senlis) was located along the road between between Caesaromagus and Suessona.

nodes.title: Autricum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 B4 Autricum

nodes.title: Axona (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D3 Axona fl.

nodes.title: Bagacum
nodes.description: Bagacum was an ancient city located in Gallia Belgica and a capital of the Nervii.

nodes.title: Beaumont-sur-Oise
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C3 Beaumont-sur-Oise

nodes.title: Beda
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of the Treveri. Modern Bitburg in Germany.

nodes.title: Belginum
nodes.description: An ancient settlement (vicus) of the Treveri. Located near modern Wederath (Bernkastel-Wittlich district) in Germany.

nodes.title: Bellovaci
nodes.description: The Bellovaci were a tribe of Gallia Belgica.

nodes.title: Bingium
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 H3 Bingium

nodes.title: Bonna
nodes.description: Bonna (modern Bonn, Germany) began as a Roman military outpost in Germania Inferior ca. 11 BC.

nodes.title: Caesaromagus
nodes.description: Caesaromagus was the civitas capital of the Bellovaci.

nodes.title: Caletes
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 A3 Caletes

nodes.title: Camaracum
nodes.description: Camaracum was the capital of the civitas of the Nervii.

nodes.title: Carnutes
nodes.description: The Carnutes were a powerful Celtic tribe occupying a territory between the Sequana (Seine) and the Liger (Loire) rivers.

nodes.title: Castellum Mattiacorum
nodes.description: A fort constructed ca. 11 BC to protect a wooden bridge built to span the Rhine river.

nodes.title: Castellum Menapiorum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C2 Castellum Menapiorum

nodes.title: Castra Vetera
nodes.description: Castra Vetera was established as a Roman fort ca. 15 B.C.

nodes.title: Catalauni
nodes.description: The Catalauni were a tribe of Gallia Belgica.

nodes.title: Ceuclum
nodes.description: Vicus on the Meuse river along the road from Noviomagus to Atua(tu)ca.

nodes.title: Col. Augusta Treverorum
nodes.description: The chief ancient city (civitas) of the Treveri. Modern Trier in Germany.

nodes.title: Col. Ulpia Traiana/Tricensimae
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 G1 Col. Ulpia Traiana/Tricensimae

nodes.title: Condrusi
nodes.description: The Condrusi were a Germanic tribe of ancient Belgium.

nodes.title: Contionacum
nodes.description: A palatial Roman villa, built in the 4th century CE and subsequently used as an imperial summer residence by the emperor Valentinianus I. Located at modern Konz bei Trier in Germany.

nodes.title: Coriovallum
nodes.description: Coriovallum (modern Heerlen) was a Roman military settlement along the frontier (limes) in Germania Inferior.

nodes.title: Divodurum/Mettis
nodes.description: Divodurum/Mettis was a Celtic capital oppidum of the Mediomatrici tribe and was captured by Iulius Caesar in 52 BC.

nodes.title: Durnomagus
nodes.description: Durnomagus (modern Dormagen) was a Roman settlement along the frontier (limes) in Germania Inferior. It was first occupied by Legio I Germanica.

nodes.title: Durocasses
nodes.description: Durocasses (Dreux) was the capital of the Celtic tribe of the Durocasses.

nodes.title: Durocatalaunum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E4 Durocatalaunum

nodes.title: Durocortorum
nodes.description: The capital of the Remi in Gallia Belgica, now Reims.

nodes.title: Eburones
nodes.description: The Eburones were an ancient people of Gallia Belgica.

nodes.title: Römische Villa Otrang
nodes.description: This extensive rural villa of the Roman imperial period (ancient name unknown) was built in the territory of the Treveri. Located at modern Fliessem-Otrang in Germany.

nodes.title: Les Vaux de la Celle
nodes.description: An ancient Gallo-Roman sanctuary near modern Genainville (France), with excavated remains of a temple, nymphaeum, and theater: BAtlas 11 B3 Génainville (sic)

nodes.title: Unnamed religious complex
nodes.description: Referred to today as "Gisacum", this vast Gallo-Roman religious complex (with major spa), is located largely in the French commune of Le Vieil Evreux.

nodes.title: Iatinon/Fixtuinum
nodes.description: Iatinon/Fixtuinum was a city of the the city of the Meldi, a people of Gallia Lugdunensis.

nodes.title: Icauna (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D4 Icauna fl.

nodes.title: Icorigium
nodes.description: An ancient settlement of the Treveri. Modern Jünkerath in Germany.

nodes.title: Igel
nodes.description: The village of Igel is known for its funerary monument of the Secundinii dating ca. A.D. 250.

nodes.title: Isara (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C3 Isara fl.

nodes.title: Iuliobona
nodes.description: A settlement of the Caletes in Gallia Belgica

nodes.title: Lesura (river)
nodes.description: Lesura fl., a lefthand tributary of the Moselle river.

nodes.title: Lexovii
nodes.description: The Lexovii were a Celtic people on the western banks of the lower Sequana river.

nodes.title: Lupia (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 H1 Lupia fl.

nodes.title: Lutetia
nodes.description: Lutetia (modern Paris) was the capital of the Parisii, a tribe of ancient Gaul.

nodes.title: Sanctuary of Isis and Magna Mater
nodes.description: The Sanctuary of Isis and Magna Mater at Roman Mogontiacum (modern Mainz, Germany) was active between the first century and the third century A.D.

nodes.title: Gallo-Roman Settlement at Mamer
nodes.description: A settlement of the Treveri (ancient name unknown) at modern Mamer in Luxembourg.

nodes.title: Mediomatrici
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 G3 Mediomatrici

nodes.title: Meldi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D4 Meldi

nodes.title: Minariacum?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C2 Minariacum?

nodes.title: Moenus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 I2 Moenus fl.

nodes.title: Mogontiacum
nodes.description: The original Roman settlement at Mogontiacum (modern Mainz) was established by Drusus ca. 13/12 BC. The settlement became an important military center throughout Roman times and was the base of operations for numerous Roman legions.

nodes.title: Monheim-Haus Bürgel
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 G1 Monheim-Haus Bürgel

nodes.title: Mosa (river)
nodes.description: The Meuse or Maas river.

nodes.title: Mosella (river)
nodes.description: Mosella fl. (Moselle river)

nodes.title: Nasium
nodes.description: A large ancient settlement located in the vicinity of modern Naix-aux-Forges and Saint-Armand-sur-Ornain in France. Excavations began in the 19th century and continued in the 20th.

nodes.title: Nava? (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 H3 Nava? fl.

nodes.title: Nemetacum
nodes.description: Nemetacum was the principal center of the Atrebates.

nodes.title: Nennig
nodes.description: The site of a Roman villa some 40 km upstream on the Moselle from Trier. The site was discovered in 1852 and was excavated between 1866 and 1876.

nodes.title: Nervii
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D2 Nervii

nodes.title: Nicer (river)
nodes.description: Nicer fl. (Neckar river)

nodes.title: Nida
nodes.description: A Roman vicus, corresponding to the modern Frankfurt am Main-Heddernheim in Germany.

nodes.title: Nida (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 G3 Nida fl.

nodes.title: Novaesium
nodes.description: Novaesium (modern Neuss) was a Roman castrum along the German frontier (limes) founded ca. 16 B.C.

nodes.title: Noviodunum?
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D3 Noviodunum?

nodes.title: Noviomagus Treverorum
nodes.description: This settlement of the Treveri (modern Neumagen in Germany) served for a time as market and road station and was later the site of a late Roman fortification. Extensive funerary remains also survive.

nodes.title: Oberaden
nodes.description: Oberaden was the site of a Roman fort used during the Germanic Wars of Drusus.

nodes.title: Orolaunum
nodes.description: A large settlement (vicus) of the Treveri, located at modern Arlon in Belgium.

nodes.title: Ouindinon/Subdinnum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 A4 Ouindinon/Subdinnum

nodes.title: Parisii
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C4 Parisii

nodes.title: Pithiviers-le-Vieil
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C4 Pithiviers-le-Vieil

nodes.title: Remi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E3 Remi

nodes.title: Rhenus (river)
nodes.description: The Rhine River is the twelfth longest river in Europe, flowing 1,233 km (766 mi) from Switzerland to the North Sea.

nodes.title: Ricciacum (or Ricciacus)
nodes.description: An ancient settlement and road station of the Treveri, located at modern Dalheim in Luxembourg.

nodes.title: Rotomagus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 B3 Rotomagus

nodes.title: Saarbrücken
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 H3 Saarbrücken

nodes.title: St-André-sur-Cailly
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 B3 St-André-sur-Cailly

nodes.title: St-Dié
nodes.description: St-Dié was the site of a Gallo-Roman settlement located on the Meurthe river.

nodes.title: Settlement at St-Mard
nodes.description: This modern site in Belgium was once home to a settlement of the Treveri (it was dubbed "Vertunum" in earlier modern literature).

nodes.title: Samara (river)
nodes.description: The River Somme flows some 245 km (152 mi) from Fonsommes near Saint-Quentin to the Bay of the Somme in the English Channel.

nodes.title: Samarobriva Ambianorum
nodes.description: A city of Gallia Belgica located on the Somme that is mentioned in Caesar's commentaries.

nodes.title: Saravus (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 G3 Saravus fl.

nodes.title: Scarponna
nodes.description: Scarponna was a station along the road from Langres to Trier, located at a crossing on the Moselle river.

nodes.title: Senones
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C4 Senones

nodes.title: Sequana (river)
nodes.description: Sequana fl. (the Seine river) flows from the plateau of Langres to the English Channel.

nodes.title: Silvanectes
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C3 Silvanectes

nodes.title: Tabernae
nodes.description: Remains of a Roman vicus and hilltop temple complex excavated at modern Tawern in Germany.

nodes.title: Tarvenna
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C2 Tarvenna

nodes.title: Settlement at Titelberg, Luxembourg
nodes.description: A Celtic and Roman settlement of the Treveri (ancient name unknown) with prehistoric antecedents.

nodes.title: Treveri
nodes.description: An ancient Gallic people, later part of the Roman Empire. Their chief city was Augusta Treverorum.

nodes.title: Tricasses
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D4 Tricasses

nodes.title: Tullum
nodes.description: Tullum was the capital of the civitas Leucorum.

nodes.title: Lopadusa (island)
nodes.description: The largest of the Pelagie Islands in the Mediterranean Sea, Lopadusa has long served as a maritime base beginning with Punic occupation in the first millennium BC.

nodes.title: Ubii
nodes.description: The Ubii were a Germanic tribe settled on the right bank of the Rhine river. Iulius Caesar encountered them during his campaigns. Their capital was Ara Ubiorum.

nodes.title: Vangiones
nodes.description: The Vangiones were a Germanic tribe. They allied themselves with Ariovistus (58 BC) as he invaded Gaul and was defeated by Julius Caesar near Belfort. Drusus established two forts among the Vangiones, castrum Mogontiacum (13 BC, later Mainz) and another (14 BC) at Worms.

nodes.title: Veliocasses
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 A3 Veliocasses

nodes.title: Vendeuil-Caply
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C3 Vendeuil-Caply

nodes.title: Verbinum/Vironum
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D3 Verbinum/Vironum

nodes.title: Vicus Contiomagus
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 G3 Vicus Contiomagus

nodes.title: [Vicus Cruciniacum]
nodes.description: A Roman vicus on the Nahe river.

nodes.title: Roman Villa at Welschbillig
nodes.description: This extensive villa (ancient name unknown) was located at modern Welschbillig in Germany (in the ancient territory of the Treveri).

nodes.title: Lusitania
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 1 B3 Lusitania

nodes.title: Unnamed Roman bridge at Trier
nodes.description: BAtlas 11 G3 unnamed bridge (Col. Augusta Treverorum)

nodes.title: Unnamed bridge
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 H3 unnamed bridge (over *Nava fl., at Bingium)

nodes.title: Unnamed Roman bridge at Mainz
nodes.description: Over the Rhenus fl. (Rhine) at Mogontiacum (BAtlas 11 I2 unnamed bridge)

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 I2 unnamed bridge (over Moenus fl., at Castellum Mattiacorum)

nodes.title: Magna Graecia
nodes.description: Magna Graecia refers to the coastal areas of Southern Italy on the Tarentine Gulf that were extensively colonized by Greek colonists beginning in the eighth century BC.

nodes.description: Durocortorum → Noviomagus → Basbellain → Ara Ubiorum

nodes.title: Chaussée Jules César
nodes.description: A Roman road linking Lutetia and Rotomagus, the construction of which was begun by Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa. The modern French Route nationale 14 follows the course of the ancient road.

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Bingium → Divodurum

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: N→ Ara Ubiorum → Wesseling → Col. Augusta Treverorum → Scarponna→ S

nodes.title: Untitled
nodes.description: Batavodurum → Forum Hadriani

nodes.title: Ad Fines
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 unlocated Ad Fines

nodes.title: Bratuspantium
nodes.description: Bratuspantium, now unlocated, was an oppidum of the Bellovaci.

nodes.title: Petromantulum?/Petromantalum?/Petrum Viaco
nodes.description: An ancient settlement or road station, attested by the Antonine Itineraries and the Peutinger Map, whose precise location is uncertain (BAtlas 11 unlocated Petromantulum/Petrum Viaco).

nodes.title: Vellaunodunum
nodes.description: Vellaunodunum, now unlocated, was a Gallic oppidum of the Senones tribe two days' march from Agedincum.

nodes.title: Vicus Helena
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 unlocated Vicus Helena

nodes.title: Aenus (river)
nodes.description: The Inn river is a right tributary of the Danube.

nodes.title: Arae Flaviae
nodes.description: Arae Flaviae (Rottweil) was founded as a Roman municipium in A.D. 73. by Cn. Pinarius Clemens.

nodes.title: Augusta Vindelicum/Aelia Augusta
nodes.description: Augusta Vindelicum/Aelia Augusta (modern Augsburg, Germany) was the capital of Raetia. The city was established in 15 BC by Drusus and Tiberius.

nodes.title: Bac (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 F3 Bac fl.

nodes.title: Batavi
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 G4 Batavi

nodes.title: Grosskrotzenburg
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 B2 Grosskrotzenburg

nodes.title: Hochdorf
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 B4 Hochdorf

nodes.title: Licca (river)
nodes.description: The Licca river (modern Lech) is a right tributary of the Danube.

nodes.title: *Murra (river)
nodes.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 C3 *Murra fl.

nodes.title: Temple of Athena Skiras at Phaleron
nodes.description: This sanctuary, reported in Phaleron by Pausanias, is thought to have been located near the modern "old town" of Phaleron in Attica. It is not to be confused with the Temple of Athena Skiras on the island of Salamis, reported by Herodotus.

nodes.title: Tower of Seneca
nodes.description: The Tower of Seneca is a sixteenth century castle in Corsica built atop the remains of a Roman watchtower.

nodes.title: Roman Forum at Syracuse
nodes.description: The area, roughly situated between the island of Ortygia and the district of Acradina, was used as an agora and, in later years, as the forum of the city of Syracuse. It is now a public park where ancient ruins are still visible.

nodes.title: So-called Roman Gymnasium at Syracuse
nodes.description: A monumental complex in the ancient city of Syracuse, probably built around the first century AD. It was initially identified as a gymnasium or a thermal bath; it includes the ruins of a theatre, a quadriporticus, and a temple.

nodes.title: Salvatoretto
nodes.description: The remains of a Roman villa and cistern.

nodes.title: Qalaat al-Madiq
nodes.description: A town and medieval fortress in northwestern Syria adjacent to the site of ancient Apamea.

nodes.title: Gard (river)
nodes.description: Tributary of the Rhodanus (Rhone)

nodes.title: Maa
nodes.description: A fortified settlement on Cyprus dating to the thirteenth and twelfth centuries B.C.

nodes.title: Porte d'Auguste of Nemausus
nodes.description: A first century gate of Nemausus, also known as the "Porte d'Arles".

nodes.title: Sissû
nodes.description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources. It is identified with modern Kozan (formerly Sis) and classical Sision.

nodes.title: Basilica of Sant'Apollinare in Classe
nodes.description: A basilica begun in the sixth century AD by Bishop Ursicinus with financial support from the Greek banker Iulianus Argentarius.

nodes.title: Temple of Amphiaraus
nodes.description: The Temple of Amphiaraus is an oracular temple dedicated to the hero/god Amphiaraus, located within the sanctuary of the Amphiareion. The site was believed to have healing powers and was particularly important in the Late Classical and Hellenistic periods (fifth to third centuries BCE).

nodes.title: Bryn Celli Ddu
nodes.description: A Neolithic mound site on the island of Anglesey.

nodes.title: Via Claudia Augusta
nodes.description: The Via Claudia Augusta was a Roman road that traversed the Alps, connecting the Po river valley to Rhaetia. It was begun by Claudius in AD 46/7.

nodes.title: Nuraghe Goni
nodes.description: Nuraghe Goni is located atop a plateau overlooking Lake Mulargia.

nodes.title: Porta Aurelia
nodes.description: A gate in the Aurelian Wall at the summit of the Ianiculum through which the Via Aurelia passes.

nodes.title: Forum granary
nodes.description: Roman granaries of the forum in Pompeii. (VII,7,29).

nodes.title: tribus Lemonia
nodes.description: An older rural tribe of ancient Rome.

nodes.title: tribus Menenia
nodes.description: The gens Menenia was an ancient patrician line that lent its name to the tribus Menenia.

nodes.title: tribus Papiria
nodes.description: The tribus Papiria is one of the earliest rural tribes of Rome.

nodes.title: Stabian Baths
nodes.description: The Stabian Baths (VII, 1, 8) and (VII,2) are located at the intersection of the Via Stabiana and the Via dell'Abbondanza. They are the oldest baths in Pompeii.

nodes.title: Porta Latina
nodes.description: A city gate in the Aurelian Wall that was substantially modified under Honorius in the fifth century A.D.

nodes.title: Santa Venera al Pozzo
nodes.description: An archaeological area in Sicily, near Acireale, possibly related to the ancient settlement of Acium.

nodes.title: Urartu
nodes.description: An eastern Anatolian kingdom on the eastern shore of Lake Van. Originating from a regional collection of principalities first mentioned in the 13th century BCE, it had become a single political entity by the 9th century BCE. Urartu was a powerful rival to the Neo-Assyrian Empire. It ceased to exist sometime in the late 7th or early 6th century BCE.

nodes.title: Lepti Minus Roman amphitheater
nodes.description: The Roman amphitheater of Lepti Minus.

nodes.title: Porticus Pompei
nodes.description: A porticus built in 55 B.C. in connection with the Theater of Pompey. The Curia Pompei, site of Iulius Caesar's assassination in 44 B.C., was likely located within the portico.

nodes.title: Arrone (river)
nodes.description: The Arrone flows from Lake Bracciano to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

nodes.title: Etruscan altar of Grotta Porcina
nodes.description: A rock-cut altar dating to the first half of the sixth century B.C.

nodes.title: Vetralla
nodes.description: The origins of Vetralla proper, located some two kilometers from Forum Cassii, lie in the early Middle Ages, but Etruscan and Roman remains are abundant in its territory.

nodes.title: Ponte Camillario
nodes.description: A Roman bridge on the Via Cassia.

nodes.title: Ploutonion at Hierapolis
nodes.description: The Ploutonion at Hierapolis is a walled sanctuary dedicated to Pluto and Kore.

nodes.title: Viminal Hill
nodes.description: The Viminal Hill, located between the Quirinal and Esquiline hills, is the smallest of the so-called seven hills of Rome.

nodes.title: Via Taranto columbaria
nodes.description: Two early imperial columbaria were discovered in 1932 along the Via Taranto.

nodes.title: Enkomi
nodes.description: Enkomi is the site of an important Middle Bronze Age settlement in eastern Cyprus.

nodes.title: Šuruppak
nodes.description: An ancient Sumerian city located about 35 miles south of Nippur on the banks of the Euphrates river. A place from the TAVO index.

nodes.title: Kissonerga-Skalia
nodes.description: Kissonerga-Skalia is an archaeological site dating to the Early Middle Cypriot Bronze Age (EM-MC ca. 2400-1650 B.C.) located north of Paphos, Cyprus.

nodes.title: Unnamed settlement
nodes.description: An unnamed settlement on Cercina or Cercinits islands

nodes.title: Mine on Euboea
nodes.description: One of a group of mines on Euboea Ins.

nodes.title: Forum Boarium (at Rome)
nodes.description: Rome's so-called "cattle market", the Forum Boarium is a key area of commercial and ritual activity on the east bank of the river Tiber. It is flanked by the Capitoline, Palatine, and Aventine hills.

nodes.title: Ara Maxima Herculis
nodes.description: An early cult center connected with Herakles located in Rome's Forum Boarium.

nodes.title: Aedes Herculis Pompeiani
nodes.description: A temple of Hercules located near the Circus Maximus.

nodes.title: Aedes Hercules Custos
nodes.description: The temple of Hercules Custos was located near the Circus Flaminius in Rome.

nodes.title: Roman theater at Salona
nodes.description: The Roman theater of Salona.

nodes.title: Shara Temple at Umma
nodes.description: Large temple at Tell Jokha/Umma dedicated to the Sumerian god Shara. The temple was constructed by king Šu-Suen of the Third Dynasty of Ur (2035-2027 BCE), and was used during the Ur III-Old Babylonian periods.

nodes.title: Villa of Manlius Vopiscus
nodes.description: A villa site near Tivoli that has long been associated Manlius Vopiscus, who is mentioned by Statius. Excavations were begun in 1825. In 1835 Pope Gregory XVI began construction of his eponymous Villa Gregoriana on the grounds of the Roman villa.

nodes.title: Tomb of Cossinia
nodes.description: A Roman tomb on the right bank of the Anio discovered in 1929. The tomb dates to the first century A.D. and is associated with Cossinia, a priestess of the cult of Vesta.

nodes.title: Amphitheater of Alba Fucens
nodes.description: A first century A.D. amphitheater at Alba Fucens built during the reign of Tiberius.

nodes.title: Corinth Roman Amphitheater
nodes.description: The small Roman amphitheater at Corinth was located northeast of the Temple of Apollo. It has been suggested that it dates to the early days of the Roman colony, perhaps placing its construction in the first century B.C.

nodes.title: Domus, M. Tullius Cicero
nodes.description: The house of the Roman statesman and orator M. Tullius Cicero was located on the north-eastern corner of the Palatine Hill in Rome.
